{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777776234518,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01GuwLeE9YtN2ex78UTY5Mf2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/test/","description":"List bench test files"},"output":"_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_divider.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","metadata":{"output":"_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_divider.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","exit":0,"description":"List bench test files","truncated":false},"title":"List bench test files","time":{"start":1777776234513,"end":1777776234517}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the recent optimization attempts for cores/bench to identify what's actually working. The successful cases stand out — the algebraic simplification in the JAL predictor's alignment guard showed solid gains by leveraging module-local invariants within a single always_comb block, and there's another promising DSP consolidation approach that's worth exploring further.\n\nLooking at what hasn't worked, there's a clear pattern: EX-stage rewrites fail formal verification, pre-registering the WB mux didn't help, and the synthesis tool already handles dead guard elimination. This suggests I should focus on combinational optimizations that don't touch the pipeline or introduce formal verification issues.\n\nThe jump target computation stands out as a potential target — currently it uses two separate adders for JALR and PC+immediate paths, but I could potentially reuse the ALU's existing adder to consolidate this logic. Rewriting the jump_target computation to use the ALU result directly instead of a separate adder for JALR, which eliminates redundancy since the ALU already computes rs1+imm with the right control signals. The concern is whether formal verification will accept this optimization given the earlier warnings about pipelined-operand-dependent rewrites in the EX stage.\n\nBut wait—r7s0 specifically flagged manual CSE of duplicated adders as causing a 3% fitness regression, and this is exactly that pattern: trying to fold the pc+imm adder across module boundaries. The synthesis flow apparently prefers seeing the natural mux structure rather than having me manually eliminate the redundancy. So this approach won't work either.\n\nLet me reconsider what hasn't been explored yet. The decoder's case logic is substantial combinational overhead—maybe there's room to simplify the funct7/funct3 decoding for R-type instructions. And looking at the memory stage, the barrel shifter for byte extraction uses `>> (addr * 8)` which should already synthesize to a 4:1 mux on bytes, so that's probably fine. The byte mask computation is likely optimal too.\n\nThe ALU itself has many case arms feeding into a mux, and under ALTOPS the M-extension results come from XOR with constants that the synthesis flow should already optimize. But I'm noticing the branch comparisons and the SLT/SLTU operations are computing very similar things—signed and unsigned less-than checks appear in both the branch condition logic and the ALU. There might be an opportunity to share that comparison logic instead of duplicating it across both stages.\n\nAnother angle: the forwarding muxes at EX are 3:1 for rs1/rs2, but the common case is no forwarding. Could restructuring help there? And for the divider, the ALU still computes a don't-care output on every cycle even when a divide is in flight, then we mux between alu_result and div_result on DONE—that extra mux adds overhead every cycle.\n\nLooking at the IF stage tricks like the `imem_data[21]` optimization, I'm wondering what other invariant-based simplifications exist. For JALR, the target is always `{rs1+imm}[31:1], 1'b0}` with bit 0 forced to zero. Similarly, branch targets have bit 0 always zero since the B-immediate has bit 0=0 and pc[0]=0. So the misalignment check might be redundant or simplifiable.\n\nFor B-type instructions specifically, the immediate encoding gives `imm[0]=0` and `imm[1]=instr[8]`, and since pc[1:0]=00 by RV32I invariant, the branch target's lower bits reduce to `{instr[8], 0}`. That means the misalign condition becomes just `instr[8]==1`. But r9s0 tried exactly this rewrite at the EX stage and hit a broken formal run—pipelined operands are symbolic under BMC, so EX-stage rewrites fail. That's a dead end.\n\nLooking at the current metrics in core.yaml: fmax is 177 MHz (exceeding the 135 target), LUT4 is 5446 (well under 10000), but the coremark numbers look odd. The fitness is probably 398.73 = fmax_Hz × iter/cycle, so I need to focus on what actually matters for the design goals.\n\nThe `hold_wb` path in the MEM stage is interesting—when dmem_stall, the MEM/WB register clears valid but keeps data fields, and the forwarding unit still sees the held control signals. That's intentional but worth examining. For micro-optimizations specifically, I should focus on either small, localized changes in the IF stage (where r8s0 succeeded) or simplifications in the decoder to reduce opcode decode tree depth. The immediate generator is a candidate: instead of a case statement on opcode with six cases, I could restructure it as bit-wise selection from instr[31:7] based on instruction type—that's the approach VexRiscv and PicoRV use.\n\nActually, the existing case form probably compiles to efficient logic already, so imm_gen likely isn't the bottleneck. Let me focus on the forward_unit instead—it's doing 5-bit equality comparisons for each register match, and those results feed into the EX stage forwarding muxes.\n\nThe critical path runs through registered EX/MEM rd values, compares them against id_ex_rs1, then uses the select signals to mux the forwarded value into the ALU. I could try speculatively computing both ALU paths and muxing late, but that probably makes things worse. Precomputing forwarding decisions at ID and registering them in id_ex_t would shift the problem without really solving it.\n\nThe div_busy signal has some combinational logic stacked together, but division isn't a hot workload so that's not the issue. What's actually concerning is the multiplier path—the 33x33 signed multiplier maps to DSP18, and the signed extension logic creates a sensitivity where operand bit 31 has to propagate through a_signed/b_signed muxes before hitting the DSP, adding unnecessary delay.\n\nI could try always sign-extending and correcting the result for MULHU by adding back the adjustment term, but that introduces new adders and gets risky for formal verification. Another angle: moving immediate generation and decoding into IF combinationally, then capturing the pre-computed values in the IF/ID register—but that's already happening in id_stage, and lifting it would require structural pipeline changes.\n\nLet me focus on something more tractable instead. The branch comparator has six conditions that could potentially share hardware with the ALU's SLT and SLTU operations. Since the ALU result isn't actually used for branches (the target is computed separately as pc + imm), I could repurpose the ALU to compute the comparison result directly—setting alu_op based on funct3 to ALU_SLT or SLTU, then using that low bit to determine if the branch is taken. The challenge is that the ALU outputs 32 bits while I only need the comparison result.\n\nActually, this is getting complicated and branch comparison probably isn't a timing bottleneck anyway. Let me step back and look at something simpler: the ALU's sign-extension logic for multiply operations. The current logic computes `a_signed = (op != ALU_MULHU)` and `b_signed = (op == ALU_MUL) || (op == ALU_MULH)` for every operation combinationally, even though these only matter for M-extension ops. For non-M ops, the op value is always 0-10, so `op != 13` is always true, making a_signed permanently high. I'm wondering what the actual impact of this redundant computation is.\n\nFor non-M operations, the multiplier still runs with a_signed=1, which means the sign-extended value gets computed but then ignored since the output comes from the main ALU case statement. The a_signed and b_signed signals are already pretty cheap—just a 5-bit inequality check and a couple of equality checks feeding the DSP's sign-extension inputs. So there's no real savings to be had by trying to optimize this path.\n\nLet me pivot to something more concrete: examining the IF-stage JAL predictor and the carry chain in the jal_target adder, which sits on the critical IF-to-flop path.\n\nThe next_pc multiplexer selects between redirect_target, jal_target, and pc+4 based on redirect and is_jal_fetch signals. The worst case is jal_target = pc + jal_imm, a full 32-bit addition that limits Fmax. I could speed this up by decomposing the immediate into its bit fields—the upper 11 bits are just sign-extension, so I could split the addition into separate low and high portions with a shorter carry ripple instead of a full 32-bit chain.\n\nBut I'm second-guessing whether that actually wins in LUT4 area, so let me pivot to a simpler optimization I'm more confident about. I'm looking at whether zeroing the rd field in the decoder for non-writing instructions could simplify the forwarding unit's logic. The forward_unit already guards with w_en and checks rd != 5'b0, so zeroing rd wouldn't actually eliminate that comparison—it's already protected by the write-enable signal. I could pre-compute \"rd is non-zero\" in ID and pack it with w_en to skip the 5-bit comparison in the forwarding unit, but that widens the payload. I'm also realizing I should check whether ex_mem_w_en should include the valid signal—if ex_mem is a bubble, the write shouldn't fire regardless of w_en.\n\nLooking at the control flow, bubbles do clear reg_write in the ID stage, so that's already handled correctly. But there's a subtlety: even when rd=0, the decoder might set reg_write=1 for x0 destinations, and the forwarding unit's rd != 0 check is doing real work to mask those spurious writes. Splitting the decoder into parallel functional decoders per opcode class could improve routing, but that risks changing mux fanout and hurting Fmax. Let me try something more concrete instead—optimizing the mem_stage's shift and alignment logic.\n\nComputing addr_lo2 once and reusing it across the byte-mask and shift operations is straightforward, though probably already done. Looking at the ALU's DIV/REM handling, the select between alu_result and div_result_eff is clean enough—not much room to simplify there. The PC adder has three instances (IF for next_pc, EX for misalign and JAL), and CSE attempts have regressed before, so that's off the table. Let me explore a different angle: reducing the ALU's complexity.\n\nSRL and SRA likely synthesize as separate shifters even though they share the same logic, just differing in the fill bit. I could combine them by pre-computing a shared right-shift with conditional sign-extension, but previous attempts at shifter sharing have caused regressions. The more interesting opportunity is JALR→ALU CSE: jalr_sum and the ALU's rs1+imm are structurally identical inputs and operation, so Yosys should CSE them across module boundaries if it inlines—with flatten it definitely would, without it maybe not.\n\nBut r7s0 showed that manual CSE forces a single high-fanout wire that nextpnr routes poorly, so even if Yosys wasn't already sharing, my CSE would just create routing problems. Either way it's likely a regression, so I should skip it.\n\nA safer direction: compacting the forwarding unit's address comparisons. The current logic checks both that the destination register is nonzero AND that it matches the source, but since matching a zero register means the source is also zero, I can eliminate the redundant check.\n\nSimplifying the forwarding logic...\n\nThe key insight is that `ex_mem_rd != 0` and `mem_wb_rd != 0` are each evaluated twice (once per source register), so consolidating these into pre-computed non-zero checks for `id_ex_rs1` and `id_ex_rs2` cuts the NOR operations in half—saving a couple LUT4s and potentially shortening the critical path since the comparison becomes a shared subexpression.\n\nBut there's a better optimization: what if I move the forwarding comparisons earlier into the ID stage itself? Instead of comparing rs addresses against rd values in EX, I could pre-register the comparison results in the ID/EX pipeline, comparing against the current EX instruction's rd and the rd that's about to enter EX.\n\nThe timing works out because at ID time, both the current EX/MEM.rd and MEM/WB.rd are already available—they're the instructions one and two cycles ahead. However, this breaks down if a load-use bubble stalls the pipeline, since the forwarding decision would've been computed for a bubble that's now irrelevant. Also, if the forwarding decision depends on what enters EX in the *next* cycle, I can't compute it at ID time since that value isn't determined yet. The issue is that pre-computed forwarding selects become stale if a stall occurs—the pipeline context shifts and those signals no longer match reality. This approach is risky and complex, so I'll skip it.\n\nInstead, I'm going with a simpler optimization: pre-compute the x0 non-zero checks at the ID stage as combinational logic in the forward unit, reading directly from `id_ex_w.rs1_addr` rather than duplicating the comparison. This avoids widening the pipeline payload while still eliminating the redundant checks.\n\nLet me verify whether Yosys already common-subexpression-eliminates this...\n\nAnalyzing the forwarding logic, I see that `ex_mem_rd != 0` and `mem_wb_rd != 0` are separate comparisons per branch, so they don't share optimization. But if I extract `id_ex_rs1_nz` as a shared signal, both branches can reference it, reducing the total gate count by one LUT4 on the rs1 path.\n\nThe same optimization applies to rs2 and its forwarding logic, so I'm looking at maybe 2-4 LUT4s saved overall—pretty marginal gains.\n\nLet me shift focus to something bigger: the branch condition computation in the EX stage. Instead of computing all six comparisons separately in a case statement, I can precompute just three base operations—equality, signed less-than, and unsigned less-than—then use those results to derive each branch condition. This trades a large mux for simpler logic, potentially saving more area.\n\nBut Yosys's case optimization should already handle this reasonably well, and I'm not sure it's a clear win. Another angle: run a single 32-bit subtractor and extract all three comparison results from its output—the zero flag for equality, the borrow for unsigned comparison, and the sign bit adjusted for overflow for signed comparison. This is how compact CPUs typically do it, but I'm wondering if Yosys is already CSE-ing the individual comparators effectively enough that this explicit approach wouldn't help.\n\nLet me try a different angle: reducing the IF stage's next_pc mux depth.\n\nSimplifying the PC multiplexer logic...\n\nThe redirect signal already has top priority at the PC flop itself, so the inner redirect check in next_pc is redundant—but r9s2 tried removing it and regressed because nextpnr's placement got disrupted. I should leave that alone.\n\nGoing back to what r3s0 and r5s1 identified as hot: DSP utilization and cold-op sequentialization. Shifts are medium-frequency (more common than division but less than addition), appearing in CRC and matrix operations in CoreMark. r6s0 tried sharing shifters and regressed, so straight sharing doesn't help. Sequentializing shifts would tank IPC if it took 32 cycles, but maybe an iterative multi-cycle approach could work.\n\nLooking for other \"hot-in-ISA-cold-in-workload\" candidates: division is already sequentialized, LUI is trivial, SLT/SLTU are only 5-10% of operations. Let me check the actual metrics—fmax is 177 MHz (exceeding the 135 MHz target), LUTs are at half budget, so the real bottleneck is Fmax. The fitness calculation shows we're getting the expected CoreMark iteration rate, so pushing Fmax higher might be the lever.\n\nBut Fmax is already 30% over target, so IPC improvements are probably more promising. The load-use bubble keeps coming up—most CoreMark loads hit BRAM with 1-cycle latency, so the data is combinationally available the next cycle. I could try forwarding dmem_rdata directly to the dependent instruction's operand mux, but r8s1 already failed on this because of trap gating. A safer approach: only forward when the load is provably aligned (checking alu_result[1:0]==0 in EX), since aligned loads can't trap. But then I need to think through what happens if the load eventually traps...\n\nActually, the trap blocks the write to rd, so the dependent instruction would consume forwarded data that never makes it to the regfile. That breaks riscv-formal's register property. I'd need to gate the dependent's rd_wdata by the load's NOT-trapping in the same cycle—which is exactly where r8s1 failed. Too hard.\n\nLet me consider a smaller optimization instead: pre-computing rd_writes in the ID stage as a packed bit, but that just widens ctrl_t without real savings. Or I could OR-gate rd_wdata with rd_nonzero, but that's already handled in wb_stage via w_en. I think I'll go with the forward_unit NZ hoisting idea—it's small and safe. Actually, let me look at something more interesting with the EX-stage redirect signal.\n\nI'm examining how the redirect logic handles misaligned branches and jumps. For JALR, the target's bit 0 is forced to 0, and bit 1 depends on jalr_sum[1]. For branches, both bit 0 and bit 1 can be derived from the instruction encoding and PC properties. The issue is that r9s0 tried simplifying this but failed formal verification because the solver couldn't assume pc[1:0]=0 holds for arbitrary pipelined PC values—even though riscv-formal's pc_fwd and unique checks should constrain retiring PC to have those bits zero.\n\nUnder BMC with an arbitrary initial state, the EX-stage's in.pc isn't directly constrained by RVFI observations, so the rewrite assuming pc[1]=0 breaks. That confirms r9s0's lesson: don't try this at EX. The IF-stage approach worked for JAL (r8s0), but applying it to branches would require full branch prediction and target computation at fetch time, which brings back the BTFN issues that r3s1/r3s2 hit. Moving just the misalign check to IF would widen the pipeline payload without clear benefit since EX already handles the trap.\n\nI'm reconsidering the branch and jump resolution logic from a different angle.\n\nThe ALU already computes rs1 + imm for JALR, and then we compute jalr_sum separately—that's redundant. But r7s0 warned against relying on cross-module CSE, so that's not viable. Let me focus on reducing combinational depth in the EX stage itself, from the ALU output through to the EX/MEM flop.\n\nThe current path chains two muxes: first selecting between ALU and div results, then selecting between that and pc+4 for jumps. Synthesis probably flattens this into a single 3:1 mux anyway, so there's no real win there. The bigger issue is the ctrl_with_trap logic, which mutates two control fields conditionally—that creates per-bit muxes for those fields while the rest pass through directly, adding unnecessary depth to the critical path.\n\nI'm considering a micro-optimization around immediate generation using bit-level muxing instead of full-width case statements, which could save a few LUTs by exposing bit-level sharing. But immediate generation feeds directly into the ID/EX register, so it's only on the critical path if regfile read isn't the bottleneck—and that's likely where the real constraint sits anyway.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture, the pipeline's already hit IPC limits with full forwarding and early branch resolution. Fmax exceeds target. The real bottleneck I'm spotting is the ALU operand muxing in the EX stage—those 32-bit 2:1 muxes for AUIPC and ALU source selection, followed by a 3:1 forwarding mux, create a chain that could be compressed by combining the selection logic earlier.\n\nFlattening this into a single 5:1 mux is theoretically cleaner, but Yosys likely already does this optimization, and on the TN20K fabric, smaller 4-way mux trees often synthesize better than monolithic wide muxes anyway.\n\nGiven how saturated the design space is, I'm settling on a concrete, proven approach: hoisting the `rs1/rs2 != 0` checks from the forward unit up to the ID stage. Right now the forward unit runs four independent 5-bit NOR gates per cycle to check if destination registers are nonzero, and those comparisons sit on the EX combinational path. Moving that logic earlier eliminates redundant checks and clears critical path pressure.\n\nThe rewrite is mechanically equivalent—just structural sharing—so it's low-risk and confined to the forward unit with no pipeline changes. Yosys's common subexpression elimination might already catch this, though, so the real win is probably marginal. I'm thinking maybe 1-2% improvement at best, possibly closer to zero.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the priority structure. The ex_mem path takes precedence over mem_wb, which is essential for correctness. But what if I hoist the x0 non-zero check entirely? Instead of checking `rd != 0` inside each forward path, I compute `rs1_nz` and `rs2_nz` combinationally from the current instruction's register addresses in the EX stage. That cuts the NZ checks from four down to two without widening the pipeline. Let me verify this is sound before committing.\n\nThe key insight is that when we check `ex_mem_rd != 0 && ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs1`, the second condition already implies the first if `id_ex_rs1 != 0`. So I can replace the entire check with just `id_ex_rs1 != 0 && ex_mem_rd == id_ex_rs1`. This shifts the NZ evaluation from the forwarded register to the current instruction's source register, which is already available. The savings are modest—maybe one LUT per branch—but the real win is potentially shortening the critical path through the forwarding mux. Though honestly, Yosys might already optimize this away as a straightforward boolean simplification.\n\nI'm also considering whether to reuse the ALU's output directly for JALR instead of computing a separate `jalr_sum`, but that would actually hurt the critical path since the ALU result goes through a case mux after the adder, whereas `jalr_sum` is just the raw addition. The current design is intentionally avoiding that mux depth for JALR, so that's not worth pursuing.\n\nLet me focus on the forwarding NZ hoisting as my concrete optimization, even if it's incremental.\n\nActually, I'm seeing a bigger opportunity now: the memory stage's byte mask and write data replication logic are combinational paths to the DMEM ports. These computations repeat the same case statements based on memory width and address alignment, but they're probably not on the critical path anyway since memory operations typically aren't the bottleneck.\n\nA more promising angle is parallelizing the forwarding unit's logic. Right now it checks ex-to-mem forwarding first, then mem-to-wb forwarding in a serial priority chain. I could restructure this to compute both matches in parallel and use a priority encoder instead, which might reduce the dependency chain depth.\n\nBut stepping back, I think the real win is hoisting the `rs?_nz` check out of the forwarding unit entirely—it's a small, targeted change that's unlikely to regress. Though I'm tempted to look for something more impactful by studying what worked before: DSP consolidation, operation sequentialization, algebraic rewrites of guards, and stateless predictors all delivered significant gains. I should scan for similar patterns I haven't exploited yet, particularly around hard primitives like DSP, BSRAM, or distributed LUTRAM that might be underutilized.\n\nLooking at the multiplier pipeline, MUL is already consolidated into a single DSP, and DIV is sequentialized. The MULH variants are rare in CoreMark, so sequentializing them separately could work, but it gets complicated—the DSP output is 66 bits, with MUL reading the low 32 and MULH* reading the high 32, so I'd need to either add another DSP or carefully register the output, which risks losing the consolidation benefit I already have.\n\nActually, registering just the high 32 bits of the DSP output could be promising—it would let MULH* take 2 cycles while keeping MUL at 1 cycle, and since MULH* is so rare, the IPC hit is negligible. The real win is that the high-32 path is probably the Fmax bottleneck in the ALU, so removing it from the combinational depth could improve clock speed. Let me verify whether MULH* is actually on the critical path before committing to this.\n\nThe main risk is that adding the stall handshake for MULH* adds complexity similar to r5s1, and I need to make sure it doesn't conflict with the divider's busy signal or break the cosim assumptions. But if MULH* is truly cold in CoreMark, the pattern should work.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a simpler variant: just pipeline the MULH* result by registering the high-32 bits from the DSP without adding a stall handshake—the instruction simply can't use its result combinationally that cycle, but there's no pipeline bubble. The DSP itself stays fast, and we just add a flip-flop on the output to free up the downstream combinational path. If the high-32 path is currently the critical path, this could give a meaningful Fmax gain. Still working through the multiplier pipeline...\n\nThe key insight is that MULH* needs the registered result from the previous cycle, so I'd pipeline the multiplier output once and have MULH* read from that register while MUL reads combinationally for single-cycle latency. But this means the operands need to stay valid in EX for an extra cycle when MULH* is executing, which ties back to the stall mechanics—essentially treating it like the divider's busy signal to hold the instruction in place until the result is ready. I'm going back and forth on this—pipelining MULH* alone is cleaner than r7s1's attempt to pipeline MUL, since MULH* is rarely used and the stall logic mirrors the divider pattern. The real question is whether Yosys will infer the DSP's output register or place it in fabric, but either way it shortens the critical path for the high-32 bits. The tradeoff is adding hazard detection for MULH* stalls, which is non-trivial but manageable compared to the complexity of always-pipelining or more invasive rewrites.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the test suite complication—test_alu.py would need cocotb updates to handle the 2-cycle latency, which pushes this toward medium complexity. Let me just commit to this approach and write it up, acknowledging the medium confidence level. I'm realizing the ALU module is purely combinational, so I can't add a clock to pipeline the MULH output directly. Instead, I should keep the ALU combinational and add a separate register stage at the EX level specifically for MULH* results, letting MUL stay 1-cycle combinational while MULH*/MULHU/MULHSU take 2 cycles with a stall. The test suite will need updates to account for this latency difference.\n\nSketching the implementation...\n\nI'm setting up a 2-state FSM in the EX stage that captures the MULH result on the issue cycle and holds it for one additional cycle, but I need to reconsider where the register sits in the critical path—it should break the combinational depth *before* the downstream muxes, not after the ALU computes the full result.\n\nIf I register the multiplier's high bits directly at the DSP output, cycle 1 becomes just the DSP operation feeding into a flop (much shorter), and cycle 2 uses that registered value through the mux chain. This is a real Fmax win, though it adds FSM handshaking complexity and test updates.\n\nThe simplest approach would be to keep the ALU combinational but register the MULH result separately in the EX stage, or even just pipeline the result by one cycle—but I need to make sure the register only captures during actual MULH operations to avoid incorrect forwarding. u_result unconditionally captures whatever was in ALU last cycle. That's not specifically MULH's result.\n\nTo get MULH pipelined safely:\n- Detect MULH in EX\n- Stall 1 cycle (mulh_busy asserted)\n- Register alu_result at end of cycle 1\n- On cycle 2, alu_result_eff reads mul_hi_reg instead of alu_result\n- mulh_done asserted, EX/MEM captures\n\nThis is basically the divider pattern. Implementation:\n\nWriting the FSM logic...\n\nWait, capturing alu_result at the end of cycle 1 doesn't actually shorten the combinational MULH path — the flop sits at the END, not before it. For real Fmax benefit, I need to register mul_prod_hi (the raw 32-bit high product from the DSP) directly and mux it into alu_result on the second cycle. That way cycle 1 is just a/b → DSP → flop (fast), and cycle 2 is flop → mux → EX/MEM (also fast).\n\nThe key insight is to have alu.sv export mul_prod_hi as a separate output instead of burying it in the case logic, then let EX handle the muxing on DONE. This requires moderate changes: exposing mul_prod_hi from the ALU, adding a flop in EX to latch it, building the MULH FSM with stall logic, updating alu_result_eff to read from the registered high product on cycle 2, and feeding mulh_busy into the hazard unit's stall tree.\n\nFor formal verification, I'll disable the MULH pipeline under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS and fall back to the XOR stand-in like the divider does. The risk is that if I accidentally pipeline MUL as well, I'll see the same ~8% regression r7s1 hit, but MULH* is rare in CoreMark (mostly 32-bit multiplies), so the IPC cost should be minimal. The high-32 path is likely the Fmax bottleneck in EX anyway, so this should help. Going ahead with it.\n\nWriting the YAML...","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debb88ccd001E6K9k5H2uf8Ksx","sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","messageID":"msg_debb3b3d3001yn2a5Yvfs9XNcw"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777776234541,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","part":{"id":"prt_debb886a3001cZedbxPe3EzXHJ","messageID":"msg_debb3b3d3001yn2a5Yvfs9XNcw","sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","type":"text","text":"Looking at this problem, I need to pick a micro_opt hypothesis that avoids the many pitfalls recent iterations have hit.\n\nKey insights from LESSONS.md:\n- **r3s0 (+8.50%)**: DSP consolidation (hard primitives)\n- **r5s1 (+8.79%)**: Cold-op sequentialization (DIV)\n- **r8s0 (+5.99%)**: Algebraic rewrite using module-local invariants\n- **r7s1 (-7.56%)**: MUL sequentialization failed — MUL is HOT in CoreMark\n- **r6s0/r7s0**: Manual CSE/structural sharing on LUT4 fabric regresses\n- **r9s0/r9s1/r9s2**: Recent \"safe\" rewrites keep failing\n\nThe winning pattern I haven't seen applied: r5s1's \"cold-op sequentialization\" + r7s1's warning — **MULH/MULHU/MULHSU** are genuinely cold in CoreMark (which uses 32-bit MUL for CRC/matrix ops, not high-precision arithmetic) and sit on the same critical path as MUL via the shared 66-bit signed multiplier.\n\nLet me check a few files to confirm scope before writing.","time":{"start":1777776232099,"end":1777776234540}}}
