{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777776273779,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_011fFS6jcTLuPHyKe2MMitz7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r10s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r10s0\ntitle: \"Pipeline MULH/MULHU/MULHSU high-32 output via registered DSP tap, leaving MUL combinational\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  After r3s0 consolidated MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU onto a single 33x33 signed DSP,\n  the shared 66-bit product sits on the EX combinational chain from a/b → DSP →\n  mul_prod → case mux → alu_result → alu_result_eff mux → is_jump mux → EX/MEM\n  flop. Of the four MUL-class ops, only MUL reads mul_prod[31:0] (cheap low\n  carry chain); MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read mul_prod[63:32], the longest carry chain\n  in the EX datapath. r5s1 (+8.79%) established that cold-in-workload /\n  hot-in-ISA arithmetic is free real estate for sequentialization on this\n  Tang Nano 20K flow (the combinational LUT tree sat on the critical path but\n  the dynamic op frequency in CoreMark was near-zero). r7s1 (-7.56%) is the\n  sharp caveat: the DIV→FSM pattern does NOT transfer to MUL because CoreMark's\n  matrix/state/CRC kernels multiply constantly, so per-MUL latency cost\n  dominates any Fmax win. MULH* falls squarely on r5s1's side of that line —\n  these ops appear almost exclusively in high-precision-arithmetic idioms\n  CoreMark doesn't exercise (32×32→64 extraction is rare in CRC/matrix/state),\n  so paying a 1-cycle stall per MULH* while keeping MUL combinational should\n  net mostly Fmax upside with negligible IPC downside.\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the MUL-class result path at the DSP output so the high-32 bits (the\n  slow carry chain used by MULH/MULHU/MULHSU) are registered, while the low-32\n  bits (used by MUL) stay combinational:\n\n    1. alu.sv gains an extra output `mul_prod_hi [31:0]` that structurally\n       taps mul_prod[63:32] — a raw DSP-output wire, no case-mux gating.\n       The existing `out` port continues to emit combinational MUL/MULH/MULHU/\n       MULHSU from the same DSP for the non-pipelined path under\n       RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS (matching r5s1's ALTOPS-bypass discipline).\n\n    2. ex_stage.sv registers `mul_prod_hi` into `mul_hi_reg [31:0]` on every\n       posedge (unconditional, tracking the DSP output one cycle late). A\n       2-state FSM (MULH_IDLE → MULH_DONE) issues a fresh MULH* op:\n         - IDLE: detect `is_mulh_op && in.valid && !mulh_done`, assert\n                 `mulh_busy` to hazard_unit, transition to DONE next cycle.\n                 mul_hi_reg captures this cycle's mul_prod_hi at posedge.\n         - DONE: present `mul_hi_reg` through a new leg of alu_result_eff\n                 mux, deassert mulh_busy, clear to IDLE.\n\n    3. alu_result_eff gains a MULH-done leg:\n         alu_result_eff = (is_div_op  && div_done_eff)  ? div_result_eff\n                        : (is_mulh_op && mulh_done_eff) ? mul_hi_reg\n                        :                                 alu_result;\n       Critical-path consequence: the MULH arm no longer routes through\n       the ALU case mux's 66-bit signed multiplier in the same cycle as\n       the EX/MEM flop. The DSP output → 32-bit flop path is one\n       multiplier-width shorter than the current DSP → case-mux →\n       alu_result_eff → is_jump-mux → EX/MEM flop path.\n\n    4. hazard_unit.sv gains a `mulh_busy` input ORed into the existing\n       stall tree exactly where `div_busy` lives: stall_if / stall_id /\n       stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb all OR in mulh_busy, flush_id gets\n       `!mulh_busy` added to its gate (same pattern as div_busy). No\n       pipeline payload bits added (r5s2's area-cost trap avoided).\n\n    5. Under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, the whole MULH FSM is `ifdef-gated off:\n       alu_result's existing XOR stand-in retires combinationally, mulh_busy\n       is tied to 0, mulh_done_eff is tied to 0. BMC depth and proof time\n       stay identical to baseline — r5s1 verified this pattern preserves\n       per-iteration formal tractability.\n\n  Expected mechanism: Fmax lifts because MULH*'s 33×33-signed-high path is\n  removed from the EX combinational cone (the DSP-to-flop chain on MULH\n  becomes ~32b register instead of 32b + mux + mux). IPC cost is bounded\n  by MULH* dynamic frequency × 1 cycle/op, which in CoreMark's perf run\n  is near zero (no extended-precision arithmetic in CRC/matrix/state\n  kernels). MUL stays 1-cycle so r7s1's hot-path regression does not apply.\n  Implementation is small and mirrors r5s1 (divider) scaffolding bit-for-bit\n  — same ALTOPS gate, same hazard_unit OR point, same alu_result_eff mux\n  extension — so formal proof time is predictable.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Add raw `mul_prod_hi [31:0]` output port tapping mul_prod[63:32] structurally; keep the existing combinational case-mux `out` path unchanged so ALTOPS XOR stand-ins still retire in one cycle.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Detect MULH/MULHU/MULHSU via in.ctrl.alu_op; add 2-state mulh_state FSM (IDLE→DONE) mirroring divider handshake; unconditionally register alu.mul_prod_hi into mul_hi_reg each posedge; extend alu_result_eff mux with a `(is_mulh_op && mulh_done_eff) ? mul_hi_reg` leg; expose `mulh_busy` output; under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS tie mulh_busy/mulh_done_eff to 0 and omit the FSM so combinational XOR stand-in retires unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add `mulh_busy` input and OR it into stall_if / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb / stall_id exactly where div_busy appears; add `&& !mulh_busy` to flush_id's load-use/redirect gate (same pattern as div_busy).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new mulh_busy signal between ex_stage and hazard_unit (one-line addition parallel to existing div_busy wiring).\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"No MULH timing change at ALU level (ALU still exposes combinational `out` port; the new mul_prod_hi is an additional structural tap, not a replacement). Existing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU vector checks continue to drive `out` combinationally and sample expected bit-exact results; add a couple of directed vectors sampling mul_prod_hi to confirm it matches mul_prod[63:32] for the sign-mix corner cases (0x80000000*0xFFFFFFFF etc.).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r10s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r10s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777776273762,"end":1777776273777}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Now I'm ready to write out my proposal. The core idea is to pipeline only the high-32 bits of the shared 33x33 multiplier for MULH/MULHU/MULHSU operations while keeping MUL combinational, since the low-32 path is heavily used but the high-32 path is rarely accessed. I'm starting with the ALU module modifications.\n\nI'm modifying the execute stage to register the high-32 output and add a simple two-state FSM that stalls for one cycle on MULH operations, then updating the result mux to read from that registered value. The hazard unit gets updated to treat MULH stalls the same way as divide stalls, and under formal verification mode the pipeline gates off to match the reference behavior.\n\nThe frequency improvement comes from breaking the critical path—the DSP output feeds through several muxes before reaching the EX/MEM flop, but now MULH results bypass that chain by going through a register at the DSP output instead. I'm expecting a 3–6% Fmax gain with minimal IPC impact since MULH is rarely used in typical workloads like CoreMark, though the actual benefit depends on whether the high-32 path is truly on the critical path.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debb8bff8001cQGGWPcmXe6OIv","sessionID":"ses_2144c4c68ffe7cXSNq7AA0JC8F","messageID":"msg_debb89b6c001ydNzj0L4MKpA7F"}}
