{"type":"text","timestamp":1777777239277,"sessionID":"ses_2143b044dffeQynofhidL0JK7r","part":{"id":"prt_debc778500013LcBw0m9j5imNA","messageID":"msg_debc4fc0a0013d34k1sK6qahpV","sessionID":"ses_2143b044dffeQynofhidL0JK7r","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent outcomes, especially r8s0 (+5.99% from an algebraic pre-adder simplification confined to a module-local invariant), and the cautionary lessons:\n- r9s0: EX-stage rewrites using `in.pc` invariants break BMC (pipelined operands are symbolic)\n- r9s2: Removing boolean guards that synth absorbs into priority-mux flattening regresses\n- r10s1/r9s1/r8s1: MEM↔EX forwarding leg is Fmax-hostile\n- r10s2/r8s2: IF next_pc widening is Fmax-fatal\n- r7s0/r7s1: Manual CSE and MUL sequentialization regress\n\nLet me examine `ex_stage.sv`'s divider handshake signals feeding into `hazard_unit`:\n\n```\ndiv_start_pulse = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_busy_int && !div_done_int;\ndiv_busy        = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse);\n```\n\nLet `X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int`. Then:\n`div_busy = X && (div_busy_int || (X && !div_busy_int))`\n- X=0 → 0\n- X=1 → `div_busy_int || !div_busy_int` = 1\n\nSo **`div_busy` is provably identical to `X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int`**, with the `|| div_start_pulse` term algebraically redundant. This is not a priority-mux absorbed guard (the r9s2 trap); it's a genuine redundant AND/OR chain feeding four hazard_unit stall outputs that gate the pipeline registers' clock enables.\n\nThis matches the r8s0 pattern (algebraic simplification confined to a module-local subexpression, no pipeline payload widening, no IF-side mux touching, no MEM↔EX forwarding change, no formal coupling risk).","time":{"start":1777777211472,"end":1777777239276}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777777239284,"sessionID":"ses_2143b044dffeQynofhidL0JK7r","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015ics9sa54RQYqJczSjhcCU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r11s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r11s0\ntitle: \"Algebraically collapse div_busy to is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The ex_stage.sv divider handshake feeds the hazard_unit's stall_if /\n  stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb outputs, which drive the clock\n  enables of every pipeline register in the core. Any LUT4 depth on\n  that fanout path translates directly into Fmax pressure on Tang Nano\n  20K, where r5s1's +8.79% win already confirmed that touching the\n  divider-to-hazard path moves the fitness needle.\n\n  Currently:\n    div_start_pulse = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_busy_int && !div_done_int;\n    div_busy        = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\n                      && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse);\n\n  Let X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int. Substituting:\n    div_busy = X && (div_busy_int || (X && !div_busy_int))\n  - X=0: div_busy=0.\n  - X=1: div_busy = (div_busy_int || !div_busy_int) = 1.\n  So div_busy is bit-exact equivalent to X — the ORed div_start_pulse\n  term is algebraically redundant against the outer AND gate. This is\n  exactly the r8s0 pattern: a module-local algebraic simplification\n  using only signals already driven in ex_stage (no pipelined-operand\n  invariants like r9s0's doomed EX-side pc/rs1 rewrite, which is the\n  trap that breaks BMC reachability).\n\n  Critically, this is NOT the r9s2 failure mode: r9s2 removed boolean\n  guards (!flush, !redirect) that were already being absorbed into the\n  upstream priority-mux flattening for the PC flop, so the claimed\n  LUT4 reduction was imaginary and the removal only perturbed placement\n  for the worse. The div_busy rewrite attacks a genuine redundant AND/OR\n  chain that feeds a NON-priority-mux consumer (hazard_unit's stall\n  outputs are simple OR-reductions across stall reasons, not priority\n  muxes), so Yosys's priority-mux absorption does not already cover it.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the `div_busy` expression in ex_stage.sv from\n\n    assign div_busy = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\n                      && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse);\n\n  with the algebraically-equivalent, strictly shorter form\n\n    assign div_busy = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int;\n\n  Keep `div_start_pulse` unchanged — it is still consumed by the\n  divider's `start` input and its !div_busy_int gate is legitimately\n  needed there to prevent re-capturing an in-flight divide.\n\n  Expected mechanism:\n  - div_busy's logical depth drops from ~3 LUT4 levels\n    (AND4 of {is_div_op, in.valid, !div_done_int, (div_busy_int |\n    (is_div_op & in.valid & !div_busy_int & !div_done_int))}) to\n    ~2 LUT4 levels (AND3).\n  - div_busy fans out to all four hazard_unit stall/hold outputs,\n    each of which is ORed into clock-enable logic for if/id/ex/mem\n    pipeline registers. Shortening this path shortens the\n    EX→hazard→clock-enable fanout that lands near the Fmax limiter on\n    the Tang Nano 20K flow post-r3s0 / r5s1 consolidation.\n  - No pipeline-payload widening, no new ctrl bit, no RVFI provenance\n    shuffle (the r2s0 / r9s1 trap), no IF-side next_pc mux touch\n    (the r4s2 / r8s2 / r10s2 trap), no MEM↔EX forwarding widening\n    (the r8s1 / r10s1 trap). The change is confined to one assign\n    inside ex_stage.sv.\n  - The non-ALTOPS (cocotb / cosim / fpga) and ALTOPS (formal) paths\n    diverge identically before and after — under ALTOPS, div_busy is\n    already hardwired to 1'b0 via the existing `ifdef, and that leg\n    is untouched.\n\n  Risk model: same class as r8s0 (algebraic, module-local, no\n  invariant assumptions about pipelined operands). Worst case:\n  Yosys's opt_expr already found this simplification and the edit is\n  a no-op at gate level (fitness delta ~0). Best case: the saved\n  LUT4 level propagates through the stall-enable fanout and lifts\n  Fmax a few MHz (2-4% fitness).\n\n  Formal tractability is unaffected — div_busy under ALTOPS is 1'b0\n  unconditionally (guarded by the existing `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS\n  branch in ex_stage.sv), so SBY's BMC sees identical state-space\n  shape pre- and post-edit.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the div_busy assignment in the non-ALTOPS branch with the algebraically-reduced form `assign div_busy = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int;`. Leave div_start_pulse and all other divider handshake signals untouched. The ALTOPS branch (`assign div_busy = 1'b0;`) is not modified.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r11s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r11s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777777239269,"end":1777777239281}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the optimization wins from previous attempts, particularly that algebraic simplification in r8s0 which gave us nearly 6% improvement by recognizing RV32I invariants and rewriting the condition check. Now I need to identify what pattern the micro_opt slot should target next in the cores/bench/ directory.\n\nLooking at what hasn't worked — extending optimizations to the EX stage fails because pipelined operands become symbolic under BMC, removing boolean guards actually hurts performance, and anything touching the IF-stage mux or MEM→EX forwarding creates Fmax problems. The real opportunity seems to be in the EX stage's critical path, where the branch condition logic uses a 6-way mux over multiple comparators that could potentially share structure with the ALU's comparison operations. I'm also noticing the immediate generation has a lot of redundancy — all immediates source their MSB from the same instruction bit and share many other bit positions, which might be worth consolidating. Looking at the forwarding unit logic, each forward decision checks if the destination register matches the source, but there's a subtle issue with the rd != 0 guard. The register file already gates writes to x0, so forwarding a zero result would be correct anyway — but if we forward when rd=0 and rs1=0, we'd incorrectly forward the ALU result instead of keeping zero. So the rd != 0 check is actually necessary to prevent forwarding stale values to the x0 path.\n\nNow examining the redirect logic in the execute stage more carefully. The branch_taken signal only fires when it's actually a branch instruction with the condition met, and the redirect target is either the branch destination (pc + B_imm) or the jump target depending on instruction type. Since B-type immediates always have bit 0 = 0 by ISA encoding, and the PC is always 4-byte aligned, I'm checking whether branch_target[1:0] can ever be non-zero...\n\nit turns out this depends only on instruction bit 8, so theoretically I could simplify the misalignment check to just `is_branch && branch_taken && instr[8]`. But r9s0's experience shows this kind of rewrite fails under BMC because even though in.pc is pipelined and constrained to be 4-byte aligned, the formal tool treats it as symbolic during per-stage reset, making such assumptions unsafe. So that avenue is closed. Looking at other potential optimizations, the forward unit comparators are already efficient 5-bit equality checks, and I'm now considering whether pipelining could help elsewhere.\n\nThe hazard unit has some redundant logic — `stall_ex_mem` and `hold_mem_wb` both compute `dmem_stall || div_busy`, which synthesis will merge anyway. For CoreMark's typical workload of loads, stores, adds, shifts, and comparisons, the register file read latency after loads is the real bottleneck. The ALU's 33×33 multiplier runs every cycle but only gets used for MUL operations, though gating it would save power rather than area. The shift operations already share a barrel shifter efficiently. The real opportunity might be in the EX stage's result mux that selects between the ALU and divider outputs — `is_div_op` is derived from a case statement on the ALU opcode, so there's potential to optimize that decode path.\n\nActually, the division opcodes (15–18) are consecutive but don't follow a clean bit pattern that would make a faster check. Given that IF-side widening and MEM→EX paths are already Fmax-hostile, and previous optimizations shifted the critical path, I should focus on the remaining suspects: the PC+immediate adder in IF, the ALU result mux in EX, and the regfile read timing into ID/EX. Let me examine the IF stage more closely.\n\nFor the EX stage's jump target, I'm noticing that JALR redundantly computes `rs1 + imm` in a separate adder when the ALU is already computing the same sum—I could reuse the ALU result directly instead. But I need to verify the decoder actually routes rs1 and imm to the ALU for JALR operations before committing to this optimization. The branch comparator does the same signed/unsigned comparison work as the ALU's SLT/SLTU operations, but we'd need a second ALU operation per cycle to reuse it — probably not worth it. Let me look at this from the r8s0 optimization angle instead: finding mux selects derived from adder outputs and rewriting them using ISA invariants to eliminate logic. In the fetch stage, `is_jal_fetch` was already optimized this way. Looking at the execute stage, the misalignment checks gate the redirect — `branch_target = pc + imm` and `jump_target` both need alignment checks, but since the ISA guarantees imm[0]=0 and pc[0]=0, I can derive the alignment directly from the input signals rather than waiting for the adder result.\n\nFor branches, `branch_target[1] = pc[1] ^ imm[1]`, which under the pc[1:0]=0 invariant becomes just `imm[1]` — essentially `instr[8]`. But r9s0 already tried this exact rewrite at the EX stage and it failed because the formal setup doesn't enforce pc[1:0]=0 across stage boundaries under per-stage BMC semantics; the solver can arbitrarily initialize `in.pc` independently. So that path is blocked. The IF stage's `jal_target` still relies on the adder itself, though we're already using the imem_data shortcut for the select.\n\nLooking at the div_busy signal, I can simplify it significantly. Currently it's `is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse)`, but expanding `div_start_pulse` shows the `div_busy_int || !div_busy_int` term always evaluates to true, so the whole thing reduces to just `is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int` — eliminating the disjunction entirely.\n\nThis matters because `div_busy` feeds into the hazard unit which stalls all pipeline stages, so shortening this critical path from EX back to IF/ID/EX/MEM could help timing. Yosys might not catch this optimization automatically, so it's worth simplifying manually.\n\nBut realistically this is a micro-optimization worth maybe 0-2%. Let me think about what's actually on the critical path in EX — probably the regfile read through the forwarding mux into the ALU, or the MEM/WB forwarded data through a mux into the ALU. The `fwd_mem_wb` signal comes from the MEM/WB flop output, so it's already fast.\n\nLooking at other bottlenecks: the IF stage's `is_jal_fetch` gate uses `!flush && !redirect`, but r9s2 showed these can't be removed. The flush signal itself comes from the hazard unit, which would only fire on redirect if memory stalls were zero — not a general win.\n\nThe hazard unit's load-use detection is already pretty tight with its three 5-bit comparisons. And the regfile's write-first bypass for each read port is standard. Let me focus on something more concrete — maybe specializing how the regfile handles the write-first bypass path, since that equality check and mux run on both read ports.\n\nActually, moving that bypass logic into the ID stage instead might be cleaner, but it's probably not a clear performance gain. The immediate generator's case statement could theoretically be restructured using muxes based on which source bits feed each output bit, but r7s0 showed that manual CSE regressions, so restructuring is risky. There's also the MEM/WB register's `ctrl.reg_write` signal — when hold_wb stalls the pipeline, it clears valid but keeps the control bits for forwarding. The write enable becomes `ctrl.reg_write && valid`, which is zero during a hold, so that's already correct. But I'm seeing the signal passed through multiple stages...\n\nactually, that's intentional for forwarding during stalls, so it's fine as-is.\n\nFor branch conditions, all six branch operations compare rs1 to rs2, and I could theoretically share a single subtraction across them — `a == b` becomes `(a - b) == 0` and `a < b` (signed) becomes `(a - b)[31] ^ overflow`. But on LUT4 fabric, a shared subtractor plus extractors might not beat parallel comparators, and Yosys probably already optimizes this intelligently anyway.\n\nLet me focus on something more targeted instead. The `div_busy` expression in the EX stage can be simplified algebraically — it reduces to just `is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int`, which is a small, localized change that shortens the hazard unit input path without touching branch prediction or forwarding logic. This should give a modest 1-3% improvement with low risk, and might even let downstream synthesis fold the div stall signal tree further.\n\nLet me verify the algebra here. Substituting the definition of `div_start_pulse` into the `div_busy` expression and factoring out the common subexpression `X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int`, I can show that `div_busy` simplifies to just `X` in both cases — when X is false and when it's true. So the simplification is correct.\n\nThe real question is whether Yosys's optimizer already catches this. The `opt` pass does basic algebraic simplifications, but recognizing the shared subexpression across two separate terms might require `opt -share`, which isn't always enabled by default. If Yosys misses it, this manual simplification could shorten a timing-critical path that feeds the pipeline register clock enables.\n\nBut there's a catch — even a \"clean\" rewrite like this can perturb synthesis and placement, potentially costing a percent or two of performance. Given that risk, I should look for something more impactful instead.\n\nI'm considering a few alternatives: pre-computing `is_div_op` and `div_op_code` in the decoder to avoid a case statement in EX, but that widens the ID/EX pipeline by 3 bits, which r5s2 warns against. Gating multiplier operands to zero saves switching power but not area or Fmax. The more promising angle is simplifying the memory misalign detection logic...\n\nExamining misalign detection...\n\nActually, I'm noticing something about the divider's start signal. The divider only accepts `start` when its state is IDLE, so the caller's `!div_busy_int && !div_done_int` check in EX is technically redundant — the divider ignores start in any other state. Removing that external gating would simplify EX, but I need to think through the stalling semantics to make sure it doesn't break anything.\n\nLooking at the PC computation in EX, I see a 4-way mux where both the misalign fault path and the default path produce pc+4. That's redundant — I can fold those together and simplify the logic.\n\nFor the ALU result mux, there's a 3-way selection between pc+4 for jumps, the divider result when done, and the regular ALU output. I'm wondering if I could route pc+4 through the ALU itself for JAL/JALR by setting the operands appropriately, but that would require decoder changes and the ALU result is already overridden anyway, so it's not a clean win.\n\nFor JALR specifically, the ALU already computes rs1+imm for the jump target, and I need that same value for the register write data. I could explicitly reuse the ALU result instead of computing it separately, which would eliminate a redundant adder. But this manual common subexpression elimination might cause regressions with high-fanout nets, and the ALU result already feeds downstream anyway, so the benefit is unclear.\n\nLet me step back and focus on something with clearer impact. Pre-computing an `is_div_op` flag in the decoder would let the EX stage read it directly instead of decoding it from the opcode, saving a few LUT levels. But that flag feeds into the critical path through div_busy to the hazard unit, so I need to think through whether this actually helps or just shifts the bottleneck.\n\nThe payload widening concern from earlier applies here too—even a single bit added to id_ex_t has synthesis costs. The div_busy algebraic simplification feels safer and more straightforward.\n\nLet me explore other angles. Combining mem_read and mem_write into a single mem_op bit seems promising since they're mutually exclusive, but the distinguishing information is already encoded elsewhere (mem_to_reg for loads, regfile write for stores), so I'd just be moving the decode around rather than eliminating it. And mem_op itself is already derived combinationally in the hazard unit anyway.\n\nAnother thought: mem_addr is stored in mem_wb_t but it's recomputable from alu_result, so maybe I can eliminate that redundancy. I'm realizing the bypass logic needs to gate on `w_addr != 5'b0` to prevent incorrectly forwarding writes to x0, since the regfile write itself is gated but the bypass isn't. So I can simplify by making the bypass condition explicit: `bypass_rs1 = w_en && w_addr != 0 && w_addr == rs1_addr`, which naturally excludes x0 reads and eliminates the need for the separate priority check.\n\nThis trades one complexity for another—the bit-width checks are similar—but it removes a priority level in the mux chain, which is a cleaner structural approach that relies on the invariant that regs[0] stays zero after reset.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether the savings are worth it. The 32:1 mux for regs[rs1_addr] dominates the path anyway, so adding a 2:1 versus 3:1 priority mux on top might only save a single LUT4, which probably won't move the critical path. This feels marginal.\n\nI'm leaning toward committing to the div_busy simplification instead—it's a cleaner win that follows the proven r8s0 pattern without falling into the r9s2 trap of removing guards that get absorbed by priority muxes. The div_busy case is different because the redundant computation isn't being folded upstream; it's a genuine simplification. Confidence is low-medium, maybe a 1–3% delta.\n\nBut I want to push for something more substantial. Let me revisit the ex_stage misalign_fault logic...\n\nI'm analyzing the misalign detection for branches, jumps, and JALR. For branches and JAL in RV32I, the lower bits of the target address can be derived directly from instruction bits under the assumption that pc[1:0]=0, which means I can replace the full address computation with a simple check on the instruction encoding. JALR is different—there's no invariant to exploit since the target depends on a runtime register value.\n\nI tried implementing this optimization but it broke formal verification because the program counter is symbolic during execution, so I'm abandoning that approach and moving forward with the div_busy simplification instead.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debc78df4001HabSN3ufDc1rVs","sessionID":"ses_2143b044dffeQynofhidL0JK7r","messageID":"msg_debc4fc0a0013d34k1sK6qahpV"}}
