{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763528772,"sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01GKiMNZQbdh7P2hDXwnJMCR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/core.yaml"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/core.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: name: bench\n2: description: Frozen LLM-benchmark fixture core. Identical RTL to baseline at the bench-fixture-v1\n3:   freeze point. The benchmark matrix clones from the bench-fixture-v1 orphan branch\n4:   and operates only on this directory.\n5: isa: rv32im\n6: target_fpga: tang-nano-20k\n7: targets:\n8:   fmax_mhz: 135\n9:   lut4: 10000\n10:   coremark_iter_s: 300\n11:   coremark_per_mhz: 2.2\n12: current:\n13:   fmax_mhz: 135.21\n14:   lut4: 9880\n15:   ff: 1858\n16:   coremark_iter_s: 2.0e-06\n17:   coremark_per_mhz: 0.0\n18:   source_id: baseline-bench-2d376e0\n19:   updated: '2026-05-02T23:11:23.254832Z'\n\n(End of file - total 19 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"name: bench\ndescription: Frozen LLM-benchmark fixture core. Identical RTL to baseline at the bench-fixture-v1\n  freeze point. The benchmark matrix clones from the bench-fixture-v1 orphan branch\n  and operates only on this directory.\nisa: rv32im\ntarget_fpga: tang-nano-20k\ntargets:\n  fmax_mhz: 135\n  lut4: 10000\n  coremark_iter_s: 300\n  coremark_per_mhz: 2.2\ncurrent:\n  fmax_mhz: 135.21\n  lut4: 9880\n  ff: 1858\n  coremark_iter_s: 2.0e-06\n  coremark_per_mhz: 0.0\n  source_id: baseline-bench-2d376e0\n  updated: '2026-05-02T23:11:23.254832Z'","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/core.yaml","time":{"start":1777763528758,"end":1777763528770}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Starting fresh with a baseline for this 5-stage in-order RV32IM core running at 135.21 MHz with a fitness score of 301.04. The main performance bottleneck for CoreMark appears to be branch prediction, which currently handles all branches the same way.\n\nThe real Fmax killer though is likely the combinational ALU path—it's trying to do everything at once, including a full 32x32 multiplier and a 32-bit divider. Both of these are probably creating massive logic depths. The divider especially is almost certainly the worst offender, since a single-cycle 32-bit divider requires dozens of LUT4 levels just for the carry-save network. Registering the multiplier to take a cycle or two would free up the critical path significantly, and that's probably the highest-impact micro-optimization I can make for Fmax on this platform. K (GOWIN LUT4 fabric) is likely to make DIV/REM iterative and keep MUL registered. But making MUL iterative could hurt CoreMark IPC since CoreMark uses quite a bit of multiplication (matrix operations).\n\nActually wait - micro_opt. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nLooking at the ALU:\n- All three 64-bit products computed combinationally  \n- Divider is also combinational\n- `always_comb` case selects the result\n\nFor Fmax at 135 MHz on GOWIN LUT4, the divider is almost certainly the critical path. Register the divider to take multiple cycles.\n\nBut actually — the simpler micro_opt that should definitely help:\n\n**Share one multiplier tree instead of three.** Currently `mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, `mul_su` are all computed in parallel. Yosys might or might not merge these. By computing a single unsigned 33x33 multiplier with sign-extended operands based on op, we save multiplier logic and potentially reduce critical path.\n\nActually, let me look more carefully. In GOWIN, DSP blocks can do signed/unsigned 18x18 multiplication. A 32x32 multiplier uses multiple DSP blocks. Three separate multipliers would burn DSP resources. Sharing them → less logic → potentially better routing → higher Fmax.\n\nHmm but fitness = iter/s × Fmax. \n\nAnother angle: **Registered ALU output / pipeline the ALU result path into MEM**. But this adds latency and IPC loss.\n\nLet me consider **decoder-stage pre-computation**. The decoder is 5 `if-else if` chains deep. Could be flattened to a ROM/LUT-style table.\n\nActually looking at critical path possibilities on this FPGA:\n1. IF stage: PC update + IMEM address (short, no issue)\n2. ID stage: decoder + imm_gen, regfile read combinational (medium)\n3. EX stage: forward muxes + ALU (DIV/MUL heavy) + branch resolve + misalign check (LONG)\n4. MEM stage: dmem shifting (medium)\n5. WB stage: simple mux\n\nThe EX stage is almost certainly the critical path, with divider being the worst.\n\n**Hypothesis: Separate the multi-cycle divider from the combinational ALU, making DIV/REM iterative (32-cycle shift/subtract). MUL stays combinational (DSP-backed). This shortens the EX critical path dramatically, improving Fmax. IPC hit for DIV/REM is minimal since CoreMark rarely uses them in hot loops.**\n\nActually, this might hurt CoreMark - CoreMark's state_main (crcstate test) uses quite a few modular operations... but let me just count. CoreMark's hot loops are mostly matrix (MUL heavy) and list (pointer chasing). DIV/REM is rarely critical. Registering the divider separately and keeping multiplication combinational should improve Fmax without significantly hurting CoreMark performance, since division operations aren't in the critical hot paths. I'm verifying the fitness calculation — iter/s equals iteration count divided by elapsed time, which confirms fitness is directly proportional to both Fmax and IPC, so a 10% boost in either gives 10% fitness gain. The iterative divider is the cleanest micro-optimization since CoreMark barely uses DIV/REM, making it essentially free for IPC while dropping the critical path and raising Fmax.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deaf6afde001U3uOfqokvZB59X","sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","messageID":"msg_deaf627fd001Q4mKvHOu5fpAo1"}}
