{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777763532231,"sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","part":{"id":"prt_deaf6bdc2001xAb4gf7v95OaGJ","messageID":"msg_deaf6b08d001aYLDnha5KC1390","sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","snapshot":"97242038ebafea4a2baaaab32280042d085440b4","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763572109,"sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EpWyBR3uxCeFcCgPb2WSYw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\ntitle: \"Iterative shift-subtract divider to shorten EX-stage critical path\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\n  Fitness = Fmax × CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\n  one-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\n  combinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\n  to SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\n  fabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\n  LUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\n  of the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\n  the other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier path (which lands on\n  DSP blocks) and the adder/shift paths, and is almost certainly what\n  caps Fmax at 135 MHz — well below the 150–170 MHz that a well-floor-\n  planned 5-stage core reaches on Tang Nano 20K when divide is iterative.\n  CoreMark itself issues essentially zero divide ops in its hot loops\n  (matrix, list, state machines use MUL/shifts/compares, not DIV/REM),\n  so the IPC cost of making divide multi-cycle is negligible — a few\n  dozen cycles per 449,148-cycle iteration at most, i.e. <0.01% IPC\n  regression against an 8–15% Fmax gain.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extract the four divide operations (DIV, DIVU, REM, REMU) from alu.sv's\n  combinational case and implement them in a new `div_unit.sv` module as\n  an iterative 33-cycle non-restoring / shift-subtract divider:\n\n  - div_unit owns a small FSM: IDLE -> BUSY (32 iterations) -> DONE.\n  - On a DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU reaching EX with !busy, ex_stage asserts\n    `div_start` with the op and operands; div_unit latches them, masks\n    the sign for DIV/REM, and iterates shift-subtract on a 32-bit\n    partial remainder. On the 33rd cycle it re-applies the sign to\n    produce quotient/remainder and asserts `div_done` for one cycle.\n  - RV32M edge cases (divide-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1 signed overflow) are\n    handled as single-cycle early-exits from IDLE before starting the\n    iteration, matching the current ALU semantics bit-for-bit.\n  - ex_stage drives a new `div_busy` output that the hazard unit ORs\n    into `stall_if`, `stall_id`, and `stall_ex_mem` — the LOAD/STORE\n    stall path is identical structurally, so the existing forwarding\n    logic, EX/MEM hold, and MEM/WB clear-valid behaviour are reused\n    verbatim.\n  - alu.sv loses the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU arms of its real (non-ALTOPS)\n    case; the ALU.output for a divide op is now driven by div_unit's\n    result register, muxed in ex_stage before the EX/MEM register.\n  - The ALTOPS branch in alu.sv (XOR-of-add/sub stand-ins) stays\n    unchanged so `make formal` continues to prove the M-ext contract\n    at PREUNSAT depth. The CLAUDE.md caveat about `make formal-deep`\n    is what covers bit-accurate divide — and the cocotb `test_alu.py`\n    vectors plus cosim against reference.py already exercise every\n    edge case end-to-end.\n\n  Expected effect on Fmax: removing a ~30-level combinational LUT4\n  cascade from EX should lift the critical path enough for nextpnr\n  to route at 145–155 MHz (median across 3 seeds), a +8 to +14% gain.\n  Expected effect on IPC: CoreMark stall budget from DIV/REM is under\n  100 cycles per iteration (far under 0.1% of 449k cycles), so IPC is\n  effectively flat. Net fitness delta: +5 to +10%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 7\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/div_unit.sv\n    description: \"New module. 33-cycle shift-subtract divider FSM producing DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU results. Single-cycle early-exit for div-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 overflow matching current alu.sv semantics. Exposes start/busy/done/result ports.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU arms from the non-ALTOPS case (divider now external). Keep ALTOPS branch untouched so `make formal` still proves via XOR stand-ins. ALU remains combinational for all other ops.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate div_unit. On divide ops, assert div_start, mux div_unit.result into the EX/MEM register's alu_result field when div_done, and expose div_busy to the hazard unit.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add div_busy input. OR it into stall_if/stall_id/stall_ex_mem (same shape as dmem_stall path), and clear MEM/WB valid while busy so rvfi_order doesn't tick during the iteration.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new div_busy signal from ex_stage to hazard_unit. No change to RVFI port set — divide instructions simply retire N cycles later through channel 0.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Verify existing 30+ M-ext bit-vector cases still pass bit-for-bit against the iterative divider (cocotb waits div_busy to deassert before sampling result). Add explicit vectors for div-by-zero and INT_MIN/-1 early-exit paths.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add regression: back-to-back DIV/REM with RAW dependency on the quotient; LOAD followed immediately by DIV consuming the loaded value; branch that consumes DIV's result — all must retire in-order with correct rvfi_order and no channel-1 retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777763572088,"end":1777763572106}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" So the fitness metric comes out to around 301 iterations per second, which is the product of maximum frequency and instructions per cycle. The bottleneck is clearly the combinational ALU running at 135 MHz on this GOWIN platform—I've got three parallel 64-bit multipliers and a 32-bit divider all competing in the execute stage with multiplexing overhead. The optimization path forward is to convert that divider into an iterative design to free up the critical path.\n\nBut actually, there's a more focused angle: consolidating the three multipliers into a single unit that handles all the signed/unsigned variants by using sign-extended 33-bit operands and extracting the result based on the operation type. This avoids the routing contention from three parallel DSP blocks, reduces LUT4 usage, and keeps the combinational path intact—no IPC loss. It's lower risk, narrower scope, and should give a direct Fmax improvement. I'm leaning toward this over the divider change to keep the scope manageable.\n\nWait, though—the real bottleneck is probably the divider itself, not the multiplier. Division maps to a 30+ level LUT cascade in Yosys with no DSP support on GOWIN, which is likely the actual critical path. Making it iterative would have a higher ceiling, but that's a bigger architectural change. Let me go with the iterative divider as the primary optimization: a 32-cycle shift-subtract FSM in a new module, removing the combinational division path entirely. I'll modify the execute stage to detect DIV/REM operations, start the divider unit, and assert a busy signal, then update the hazard unit to stall on that signal.\n\nThe tradeoff is that division now takes 33 cycles instead of 1, but CoreMark barely uses division, so the IPC hit is negligible—well under 1%. Removing the slowest combinational operation from the execute stage should push Fmax up by 8-12% realistically, even accounting for muxing and forwarding overhead. Overall fitness should improve by 5-10%.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deaf6f672001WTvaKdfCzYYR62","sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","messageID":"msg_deaf6b08d001aYLDnha5KC1390"}}
