{"type":"text","timestamp":1777763580663,"sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","part":{"id":"prt_deaf76af30010iwyZKPpBFQjIM","messageID":"msg_deaf759cc001O5fV4V5leMbz1O","sessionID":"ses_21509fe4cffew1148S6vq4uZWs","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Iterative shift-subtract divider to lift Fmax.\n\nThe combinational `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands in `alu.sv` synthesize to ~30-level LUT4 cascades on Tang Nano 20K (no HW divide primitive in GOWIN fabric), almost certainly capping Fmax at 135 MHz. CoreMark issues essentially zero DIV/REM in its hot loops, so the IPC cost of making divide 33-cycle iterative is negligible (<0.1%) against an expected 8–14% Fmax gain.\n\n**Scope:** new `rtl/div_unit.sv` FSM, remove DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU arms from `alu.sv` (non-ALTOPS branch only — ALTOPS stays untouched so `make formal` still proves M-ext via XOR stand-ins), wire `div_busy` through `ex_stage.sv`, `hazard_unit.sv`, `core.sv`. Cocotb regressions cover bit-accuracy and RAW-through-divide hazards. Target: +7% fitness, medium confidence.","time":{"start":1777763576563,"end":1777763580660}}}
