{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777766363458,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"id":"prt_deb21f13e001M6npS76A67BMD9","messageID":"msg_deb21de4e001KoqndG1Xt11TXF","sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","snapshot":"60cedac05be08812b8ecf39c78f7e7d32cdb92f0","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766386884,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01VcTPuWZs3VeCwii6NeQgdw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/ 2>/dev/null && head -c 200 cores/bench/LESSONS.md 2>/dev/null","description":"Check experiments directory"},"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (broken, n/a): Adding a BTB with speculative IF-stage redirect and a new `predicted`/`pred_target` field threaded through if_id_t and id_ex_t expands the formal stat","metadata":{"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (broken, n/a): Adding a BTB with speculative IF-stage redirect and a new `predicted`/`pred_target` field threaded through if_id_t and id_ex_t expands the formal stat","exit":0,"description":"Check experiments directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check experiments directory","time":{"start":1777766386878,"end":1777766386882}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the recent optimization attempts in the micro_opt category—the iterative shift-subtract divider, the split M-extension multi-cycle unit, and the BTB all resulted in regressions or formal verification issues. The baseline fitness sits at 301.04 with an Fmax of 135.21 MHz, though the coremark_iter_s metric of 2.0e-06 looks suspicious and worth double-checking.\n\nFor improving CoreMark performance, I need to either raise Fmax by reducing the critical path or lower cycles per instruction. The current design has a 5-stage single-issue pipeline with a combinational ALU that includes both multiplier and divider—that divider is almost certainly the bottleneck, synthesizing into a massive combinational tree on the Gowin GW2A. The previous attempts to pipeline the divider regressed, likely because while shortening the critical path, they added too many cycles without enough Fmax gain to compensate, especially since CoreMark doesn't rely heavily on division anyway.\n\nI'm considering other micro-optimization angles: the write-first bypass in the register file creates a data-dependency path that might be critical, the decoder could be simplified, and the ALU's large case statement forces the synthesizer to create muxes after all operations. An interesting approach would be pipelining the multiplier through Gowin's DSP blocks with registered stages—this could reduce the critical path without hurting throughput since CoreMark's main loop is dominated by bit operations and memory access rather than multiply operations.\n\nThe real bottleneck is likely the branch resolution path: forwarded operands feed into the ALU comparator, which determines the branch condition and redirect target, then feeds back to the PC mux in IF. This is a long combinational chain, especially since the forwarding includes the WB-stage mux. I could reduce this by pre-computing branch conditions earlier or registering the redirect, though that adds latency.\n\nLooking at the EX/MEM to data memory path, the address comes directly from the ALU result stored in the EX/MEM register, which is good. The actual critical path in FPGA synthesis depends on the timing report, but typically it's either the register file read through forwarding and ALU to the EX/MEM flop, or the ALU output feeding branch resolution and PC redirection. Since the ALU is the largest combinational block—especially with division and multiplication—the best optimization would be to extract the divider into a separate multi-cycle unit that only stalls on DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operations, letting the main ALU shrink and Fmax improve significantly. That's actually what hyp-002 attempted, so I need to figure out why it regressed.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb224c63001vojughV9tbAsnK","sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","messageID":"msg_deb21de4e001KoqndG1