{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766392324,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015Hv21NvBWm8VT6QARPhLqz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-2d376e0\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T23:11:18.053225Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative shift-subtract divider to shorten EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier path (which lands on\\nDSP blocks) and the adder/shift paths, and is almost certainly what\\ncaps Fmax at 135 MHz \\u2014 well below the 150\\u2013170 MHz that a well-floor-\\nplanned 5-stage core reaches on Tang Nano 20K when divide is iterative.\\nCoreMark itself issues essentially zero divide ops in its hot loops\\n(matrix, list, state machines use MUL/shifts/compares, not DIV/REM),\\nso the IPC cost of making divide multi-cycle is negligible \\u2014 a few\\ndozen cycles per 449,148-cycle iteration at most, i.e. <0.01% IPC\\nregression against an 8\\u201315% Fmax gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier pa... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split M-extension into multi-cycle unit off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX critical\\npath and lower LUT count is strictly fitness-positive for this workload.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"BTB with 1-bit hysteresis for taken branches and unconditional jumps\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX,\\nproducing a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch and every\\nJAL/JALR (IF/ID is flushed to NOP and ID/EX is flushed to a bubble\\nbefore the redirected instruction reaches IF). CoreMark is dominated\\nby tight loops (core_list_find, crcu8/crcu16, core_bench_matrix inner\\nloops) \\u2014 10-20% of dynamic instructions are control-flow, and the\\nvast majority of those are backward loop-closing branches that are\\nalmost always taken. Assuming ~15% branches+jumps at ~60% taken rate\\nand 2 cycles of penalty each, the lost IPC is on the order of 18%\\nof total CoreMark cycles. Removing even 70% of those bubbles is the\\nsingle biggest IPC lever this core has short of going superscalar,\\nand it does not touch the RVFI contract, the memory interface, or\\nthe ALU path. No prior iteration has attempted this \\u2014 the baseline\\ncore has zero prediction, PC always fetches pc+4 until EX redirects.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX,\\nproducing a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch and every\\nJAL/JALR (IF/ID is flushed to NOP and ID/EX is flushed to a bubble\\nbefore the redirected instruction reaches IF). CoreMark is dominated\\nby tight loops (core_list_find, crcu8/crcu16, core_bench_matrix inner\\nloops) \\u2014 10-20% of dynamic instructions are control-flow, and the\\nvast majority of those are backward loop-closing branches that are\\nalmost always taken. Assuming ~15% branches+jumps at ~60% taken rate\\nand 2 cycles of penalty each, the lost IPC is on the order of 18%\\nof total CoreMark cycles. Removing even 70% of those bubbles is the\\nsingle biggest IPC lever this core has short of going superscalar,\\nand it does not touch the RVFI contract, the memory interface, or\\nthe... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 4 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-2d376e0\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 301.04, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 135.21, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9880, \"ff\": 1858, \"seeds\": [121.29, 135.21, 136.07], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-02T23:11:18.053225Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative shift-subtract divider to shorten EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier path (which lands on\\nDSP blocks) and the adder/shift paths, and is almost certainly what\\ncaps Fmax at 135 MHz \\u2014 well below the 150\\u2013170 MHz that a well-floor-\\nplanned 5-stage core reaches on Tang Nano 20K when divide is iterative.\\nCoreMark itself issues essentially zero divide ops in its hot loops\\n(matrix, list, state machines use MUL/shifts/compares, not DIV/REM),\\nso the IPC cost of making divide multi-cycle is negligible \\u2014 a few\\ndozen cycles per 449,148-cycle iteration at most, i.e. <0.01% IPC\\nregression against an 8\\u201315% Fmax gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier pa... (line truncated to 2000