{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766464935,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BsGhYm94nb2j1VTfLsMGJ7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\ntitle: \"Pre-register rd_wdata at MEM/WB boundary to shorten forward + regfile read paths\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\n  M-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\n  divider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path — Yosys\n  was already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\n  attempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\n\n  Re-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\n  `w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\n  is purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\n  consumers:\n\n    1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\n       the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\n       (MEM/WB flop) → wb_stage mux → fwd_rs?_sel mux → is_auipc mux →\n       ALU → EX/MEM flop — four mux levels before ALU input.\n    2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\n       ID-stage's regfile read path is\n       (MEM/WB flop) → wb_stage mux → regfile bypass mux → ID/EX flop\n       — two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\n       rd matches.\n\n  That extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\n  plausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\n  1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\n  transformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\nhypothesis: |\n  Consolidate the WB-stage write-data mux into the MEM stage so the\n  selected rd_wdata is clocked into the MEM/WB register directly,\n  turning wb_stage into a trivial `w_data = in.rd_wdata` pass-through.\n\n  Concretely:\n   - Extend `mem_wb_t` in core_pkg.sv with a new field\n     `logic [31:0] rd_wdata;`  (can replace `read_data` since\n     read_data is only consumed by wb_stage's mux anyway; keep\n     read_data for the RVFI-accurate rmask path if needed).\n   - In mem_stage.sv, compute\n     `rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result;`\n     and assign it to `reg_q.rd_wdata`. This is a 32-bit 2:1 mux on\n     already-combinational outputs of the same stage — zero added\n     delay in MEM (it fits behind the existing `load_data` combo\n     without deepening that cone).\n   - In wb_stage.sv, set `w_data = in.rd_wdata;`\n     — one LUT level of mux gone from the forwarding + regfile\n     read-bypass critical paths.\n\n  This is an IPC-neutral transformation (same retirement semantics,\n  same forwarded values, same regfile writes) that purely shortens two\n  combinational cones by one mux level each. It must stay IPC-neutral\n  because `load_data` was already computed combinationally in mem_stage\n  every cycle; we just route its mux result through the existing\n  MEM/WB flop instead of re-doing the mux combinationally in WB.\n\n  Expected Fmax lift: 3–8% (one LUT-mux level out of a typical 7–10\n  level path on GW2A). Zero IPC change. Zero formal-state expansion\n  (no new pipeline payload, same retirement sequence). RVFI contract\n  preserved: wb_stage still drives w_en/w_addr/w_data identically at\n  the interface; only the internal provenance of w_data changes.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add rd_wdata field to mem_wb_t (pre-muxed write-back value).\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute rd_wdata = mem_to_reg ? load_data : alu_result and register it into MEM/WB.\"\n  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    description: \"Simplify w_data to pass mem_wb.rd_wdata straight through; remove the combinational mem_to_reg mux.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Ensure fwd_mem_wb input to ex_stage remains wired to wb_stage's w_data output (now a pass-through of the registered rd_wdata) so the forwarding critical path shortens by one mux level.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777766464918,"end":1777766464934}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Both M-ext improvements registered as regressions with zero delta, which means the orchestrator detected no actual change—the divider modification might've been neutral since Yosys was already inferring DSPs, or the critical path doesn't run through that component. Looking at the baseline numbers, I see fmax_mhz at 135.21 and coremark_iter_s at 2.0e-06 with a successful fit.\n\nWait, let me verify the fitness calculation: 135.21 MHz times 2.0e-06 gives 2.70e-04, but the fitness shows 301.04. That doesn't match. Let me reconsider—if fitness is Fmax times iterations per cycle instead, then 10 iterations divided by 4,491,485 cycles is about 2.226e-6, and multiplying that by 135.21e6 gives 301.05. That's it. So the coremark_iter_s field is actually iterations per cycle, not iterations per second.\n\nSince both divider rework attempts came back unchanged, the critical path clearly isn't in the divider or multiplier—it's somewhere else. I'm thinking through the likely bottlenecks: the register file write-first bypass logic where the read mux checks write enable and address on every read, feeding into the ID stage's rs1 and rs2 values; branch resolution in the execute stage with its forwarding muxes, comparator, and the redirect signal that has high fanout back to the instruction fetch PC mux; or possibly something else I haven't fully considered yet.\n\nThe ALU itself has 19 operations with a deep mux tree, and the 32-bit variable shifter creates a barrel shifter that's also a deep LUT structure. But the forwarding path from memory-writeback through the execute stage is interesting—the mem_to_reg mux output chains through the forwarding selection logic to reach the ALU inputs, which is a long combinational path. A promising optimization would be to register the final write data at the MEM/WB boundary instead of computing it combinationally, so both the register file write and the forwarding path see a single registered output rather than a mux chain.\n\nLooking at the actual implementation though, wb_stage is purely combinational—it just picks between the already-registered ALU result and read data with a single 32-bit mux. The EX/MEM forwarding path uses the registered ALU result directly, and the MEM/WB path goes through that 2-to-1 mux, so neither is particularly bad. The real bottleneck on GW2A is likely the ALU's 32-bit carry chain for addition or the barrel shifter, since the platform has slower LUT-based carry logic than Xilinx or Intel. I notice the branch comparator and the SLT/SLTU comparator are duplicated in the ALU—moving the branch comparison earlier into the ID stage after register read could shorten the EX path significantly. The register file's write-first bypass is actually necessary because it handles the case where an instruction in WB is writing to a register that an instruction still in IF/ID needs to read—the forwarding unit can't help there since the dependent instruction hasn't reached EX yet. I could use a negedge-write approach to let reads see the new value on the same cycle, but that violates the single-clock-edge constraint for FPGAs. Stalling dependent instructions until WB completes would work but adds unnecessary latency. Let me explore what other optimizations haven't been attempted yet.\n\nLooking at the actual critical path in EX, the forwarding unit's inputs come from registered EX/MEM signals so the mux selection is fast, and then rs1 flows through the ALU to produce the result that gets registered into EX/MEM. The bottleneck isn't obviously in the forwarding itself—I need to trace through where the actual delay is accumulating.\n\nThe ALU is the real concern here since it's packed with a 64-bit multiplier using three DSP blocks, a 32-bit divider, a shifter, adders, and a 19-way mux all in series. The divider removal in hyp-002 showed no improvement despite the 0% delta result, which suggests either the implementation had issues or the critical path shifted to something equally deep. Let me try a different surgical optimization instead—maybe simplifying the branch comparator by using a single 32-bit subtractor to drive all six branch conditions, or rethinking how the forwarded write-back data flows through the pipeline to reduce that critical path.\n\nActually, the more promising angle is consolidating the writeback mux. Right now the wb_stage mux sits between registered inputs and feeds into the forward path, adding an extra LUT level. If I compute rd_wdata at the end of MEM and register it directly in the MEM/WB pipeline register, then fwd_mem_wb becomes just a flop output instead of going through that combinational mux. That's a clean micro-optimization that should save roughly one LUT level—maybe 5% Fmax gain. But let me look at the register file logic to see if there's something even more impactful there.\n\nExamining register file implementation...","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb2333fd001P1S0rTpixXZU2c","sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","messageID":"msg_deb22627e001uOGm83zhZrfJ01"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777766464937,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"id":"prt_deb23282a001vgHdWlrTV6HUuD","messageID":"msg_deb22627e001uOGm83zhZrfJ01","sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and prior attempts:\n- hyp-001 (iterative divider) and hyp-002 (multi-cycle M-ext) both regressed — dividers weren't the Fmax bottleneck after all\n- hyp-003 (BTB) blew up formal state space — predictors must keep state off RVFI payload\n\nFor a fresh micro_opt angle: looking at the design, `wb_stage` is a combinational mux (`mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result`) that drives BOTH (a) `fwd_mem_wb` into EX's forwarding muxes AND (b) `w_data` into the regfile's write-first bypass. That's a `mux → mux → ID/EX flop` and `mux → mux → EX/MEM flop` path that hasn't been addressed. Consolidating rd_wdata at the MEM/WB register boundary turns those paths into flop outputs.","time":{"start":1777766443050,"end":1777766464936}}}
