{"type":"text","timestamp":1777766469974,"sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","part":{"id":"prt_deb2386d0001vjebkxVcR3bNWU","messageID":"msg_deb237e1d001OqTYB2jMtWEFVy","sessionID":"ses_214de2249ffe6E5u96KapWHWT2","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Since both prior divider-rework attempts returned 0.00% delta (divider wasn't actually the Fmax bottleneck), this micro_opt targets a different, previously-ignored combinational path: the `wb_stage` mux (`mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result`) feeds both the EX-stage forwarding path AND the regfile write-first read bypass, adding one LUT-mux level to two critical cones. Pulling that mux back one pipe stage so `rd_wdata` lands registered at the MEM/WB boundary makes `wb_stage` a trivial pass-through, shortening both cones without touching IPC, the RVFI payload, or formal state (so no BTB-style proof blowup).","time":{"start":1777766467280,"end":1777766469973}}}
