{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768215430,"sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","part":{"id":"prt_deb3e32f1001Pjck2hFjJB6pV1","messageID":"msg_deb3db263001Wpr3crnlzk30yB","sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","type":"text","text":"Looking at this, I need to find a micro_opt for Fmax improvement. Let me check history and examine the critical path.","time":{"start":1777768215281,"end":1777768215430}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768215469,"sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Fi6YAXd2aC5MnRqtxrLLvn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check existing hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypotheses","time":{"start":1777768215451,"end":1777768215466}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the current best result with the static JAL predictor and need to find a micro-optimization in the micro_opt category. The critical path seems to be in the ALU where multiplication and division operations are combined in a single stage, so I should focus on optimizing that area rather than the smaller hazard and forward units.\n\nThe main bottleneck is the EX stage where the forwarding multiplexer feeds into the ALU operand mux and then the ALU itself, with branch target computation adding to the delay. I notice that branch targets for JAL and regular branches only need pc+imm, which are both available in the ID stage—so I could pre-compute this value there and pass it through the pipeline instead of computing it in EX, removing an adder from the critical path. I'm reconsidering the forward mux and ALU chain as the real bottleneck—the combinational path from forwarded operands through the ALU is likely what's limiting Fmax at 141 MHz. While pre-computing the branch target in the ID stage is a clean optimization, I think the simpler and more impactful approach is to focus on shortening that critical EX-stage path, so I'll go with pre-computing branch_target = pc + imm in ID and propagating it through the pipeline to avoid the extra adder in the redirect logic.\n\nBut I need to be careful about expanding id_ex_t—the formal proof lessons showed that adding fields like BTB predictions blew the budget, and renaming fields broke RVFI taps. A single 32-bit field for pre-computed branch_target shouldn't be as problematic since the behavior is unchanged, but I should verify this won't significantly impact proof time before committing to it.\n\nActually, I'm noticing the ALU computes M-extension products unconditionally...\n\nExamining M-extension logic... Finishing the multiplier control logic...\n\nThis approach consolidates all four operations into a single 33-bit signed multiplier by controlling the sign-extension bits per operation—MUL and MULH sign-extend both operands, MULHU zero-extends both, and MULHSU mixes them. It's a cleaner optimization that should reduce DSP usage and improve timing by eliminating the fan-out from three parallel multipliers, plus it simplifies the ALU's non-multiply paths. The divider can wait; let me document this multiplier approach.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3e32fa001R4RQGpnsBGr4T7","sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","messageID":"msg_deb3db263001Wpr3crnlzk30yB"}}
