{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768276797,"sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","part":{"id":"prt_deb3ed6e00016LgRrvBbXTKLY5","messageID":"msg_deb3e6cc8001Khu3N4UL0vSrBG","sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","type":"text","text":"Looking at the critical path, I see the ALU computes three separate 64-bit multipliers (`mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, `mul_su`) unconditionally. On Tang Nano 20K, each maps to a separate DSP block. Three DSPs running in parallel creates routing congestion and LUT overhead. A single 33×33 signed multiplier with operand sign-extension muxes handles all four MUL variants cleanly.\n\nKey insight from lessons:\n- r1s2 (BTB): adding pipeline payload blows formal budget → **avoid** touching `id_ex_t`\n- r2s0 (rd_wdata): renaming mem_wb_t fields breaks RVFI taps → **avoid** MEM/WB changes\n- r2s2 success: change was purely local (ALU/IF) with no payload expansion\n\nMy hypothesis stays local to `alu.sv` — no pipeline payload changes, no RVFI tap changes, ALTOPS branch untouched, cocotb `test_alu.py` vectors unchanged.","time":{"start":1777768257248,"end":1777768276796}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768276808,"sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_013WbYzz354f11r4Ve85Dd6E","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Fold MUL variants into single 33x33 signed multiplier with sign-ext mux\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\n  on every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\n  mul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\n  multiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\n  dedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\n  every EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\n  routing channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\n  \"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\n  moving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax —\n  evidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\n  but has free area/routing headroom to give up.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su with a single 33-bit signed multiplier\n  whose operand sign bits are muxed from op: MUL / MULH use signed*signed\n  (sign-extend both), MULHU uses unsigned*unsigned (zero-extend both),\n  MULHSU uses signed*unsigned (sign-extend a, zero-extend b). MUL only\n  reads the low 32 bits of the 66-bit product, so the \"signed vs unsigned\n  a\" sign bit is a don't-care for MUL and we alias it to MULH (signed).\n  The substitution is confined to alu.sv and only affects the\n  !RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch; the ALTOPS XOR stand-ins and the\n  divider logic stay byte-for-byte identical. Expected wins:\n    * DSP block count drops 3 -> 1 (frees two DSPs, reduces routing\n      pressure around the EX critical path).\n    * LUT4 / FF footprint of the ALU shrinks because operand\n      sign-extension wires collapse into a single 33-bit pair.\n    * Fmax ceiling may lift 2-5% if the three-DSP routing was the\n      binding path; IPC is identical (single-cycle semantics preserved).\n  Correctness is covered by test/test_alu.py's existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/\n  MULHSU vectors and cosim's field-by-field diff against reference.py.\n  Formal runs under ALTOPS so formal time is unchanged. No pipeline\n  payload bits change; no RVFI tap repoints; no formal state expansion.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Replace the three parallel mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su 64-bit products with one 33x33 signed multiplier. Mux the operand sign-extension bits from the ALU op code: signed-extend rs1 for MUL/MULH/MULHSU (zero for MULHU); signed-extend rs2 for MUL/MULH (zero for MULHU/MULHSU). Keep the 66-bit product; select low-32 for MUL, high-32 for MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. Leave the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS branch untouched. Leave DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU untouched.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Extend the existing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU coverage with a corner-case sweep (INT_MIN*INT_MIN, INT_MIN*-1, 0xFFFFFFFF*0xFFFFFFFF, 0x80000000*0x00000001) to prove the muxed-sign multiplier matches the three-multiplier reference bit-for-bit under both signed and unsigned interpretations; add a directed test that MUL's low-32 output is independent of the chosen sign-ext path (since low bits are invariant under sign-extension).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777768276793,"end":1777768276807}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The M-extension changes turned out to be regressions rather than fundamental issues, which means the single-cycle ALU is probably adequate since multipliers are handled by DSPs anyway. Now I'm trying to identify what's actually constraining performance at 141.58 MHz on the Tang Nano—the forwarding mux feeding into the ALU operands during the execute stage looks like the prime suspect for the critical path.\n\nI'm considering several micro-optimizations: registering the forwarding mux won't work since it needs data that isn't available until later stages, but pre-computing branch targets and AUIPC results in the decode stage could help by moving those 32-bit additions earlier. I could also compute PC+4 ahead of time, though that's probably not expensive enough to matter much.\n\nThe more interesting angle is consolidating the three simultaneous multipliers into a single signed multiplier with sign-extension control, since the routing overhead from three DSP blocks might be hurting Fmax more than the actual computation. But the regression from the multi-cycle M-extension attempt suggests the multiplier isn't even on the critical path at 141.58 MHz, so I need to look elsewhere—probably at the load path in the memory stage or some other long combinational chain I haven't identified yet. I'm weighing whether to pre-compute the branch target in the ID stage and store it instead of the immediate in the id_ex_t register, but that risks formal verification issues since r2s2 succeeded by avoiding payload changes. The multiplier consolidation approach is safer—it doesn't touch the pipeline state, keeps IPC identical, and should help with routing congestion on the Tang Nano 20K without the formal verification risk of adding new fields.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3ee3e300169HgwDZz5BlhZJ","sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","messageID":"msg_deb3e6cc8001Khu3N4UL0vSrBG"}}
