{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768282792,"sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","part":{"id":"prt_deb3f2920001AkD5JInT4gGCe2","messageID":"msg_deb3f23b60017p3dRUnygxXjbg","sessionID":"ses_214c24e41ffeOiI2kB73OyuQJU","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260502-001-r3s0` at `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis:** Consolidate the three parallel 64-bit multipliers in `alu.sv` (`mul_ss`, `mul_uu`, `mul_su`) into a single 33×33 signed multiplier with operand sign-extension muxed from the ALU op code.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- On Tang Nano 20K (GW2A), each 33×33 multiplier grabs a separate DSP18 block. Three parallel DSPs per EX cycle creates routing/congestion pressure near the 141.58 MHz Fmax ceiling.\n- Prior r1s1 (multi-cycle M-ext) proved the multiplier is *timing-tolerable* single-cycle — IPC hit from moving it off critical path outweighed Fmax gain — so this frees area without touching IPC.\n- Change is **confined to `alu.sv`**: no pipeline payload changes (heeds r1s2 lesson), no RVFI tap repoints (heeds r2s0 lesson), ALTOPS branch and divider untouched.\n- Formal proof time unchanged (ALTOPS path intact); `test_alu.py` extended with corner cases (INT_MIN², all-ones², sign-boundary) to prove bit-equivalence.\n\nExpected: +3% fitness via reduced DSP count → lower LUT4, reduced routing congestion around EX, modest Fmax headroom. Confidence low because the multiplier may not be the binding Fmax path.","time":{"start":1777768278304,"end":1777768282791}}}
