{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777769608026,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","part":{"id":"prt_deb5373560014tByzQ2YMxK0pV","messageID":"msg_deb5362a1001fJ8d6fTrpMEED2","sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","snapshot":"c0fc73655d84913c6c860a503c24846ae00274d4","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769712075,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","part":{"id":"prt_deb55001c001sbVwN06a7HwhaL","messageID":"msg_deb5362a1001fJ8d6fTrpMEED2","sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent successful patterns:\n- r3s0 (+8.50%): DSP consolidation — collapsed 3 mul paths to 1\n- r2s2 (+5.87%): Stateless static prediction\n\nPattern: structural consolidation of redundant EX-stage arithmetic pays off on Tang Nano 20K. Branch predictor hypotheses in this slot have all regressed formal (r3s1/r3s2 cascade).\n\nLet me look at what parallel comparator hardware still exists in EX stage.","time":{"start":1777769709596,"end":1777769712074}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769712112,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01CjW6b1FeqBdPBQej271x4H","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -20","description":"Check existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777769712097,"end":1777769712110}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the current fitness of 345.80 for micro_opt, I'm reviewing what's worked recently—the DSP folding and JAL predictor improvements—and now focusing on the remaining bottlenecks like ALU critical path delays in division and multiplication, forwarding mux contention in the EX stage, and register file constraints.\n\nExamining the write-first bypass in the register file, I notice it creates a combinational path from the WB stage through to the regfile read mux, but this gets registered into ID/EX so it's not directly on the critical path. The real issue is the ALU's 33x33 multiplier and combinational division logic, plus the complex forwarding mux chain in EX that feeds into the ALU. I'm wondering if there's redundancy between the write-first regfile bypass handling same-cycle writes and the MEM/WB forwarding mux—if the regfile already resolves write-read conflicts, maybe the forwarding path is unnecessary and could be removed to simplify timing.\n\nLet me trace through the pipeline timing more carefully. When an instruction is in WB at cycle N and a dependent instruction is in EX at the same cycle, the dependent needs the WB data immediately via MEM/WB forwarding. But if the dependent is in ID at cycle N, it reads the regfile with write-first bypass and gets the WB data, which then registers into ID/EX for use in EX at cycle N+1. So the forwarding mux is only needed for instructions that are already in EX when their source is in WB—instructions that are 2 cycles behind rather than 3. At cycle N when I'm executing, the instruction two steps ahead is writing to the regfile, but I already captured stale data from the regfile read back in cycle N-1 when that instruction was still in the memory stage—so MEM/WB forwarding is essential to get the correct value. All three forwarding paths are genuinely needed.\n\nLooking at the EX stage critical path, the ALU feeds into the EX/MEM register along with branch and jump target calculations, though those don't depend on the ALU output itself. The real bottleneck is likely the combinational division logic, which is typically very deep. The current design already hits 153.61 MHz, which exceeds the 135 MHz target, so division might not actually be the limiting factor here.\n\nThe coremark metrics look suspicious—the iteration time is absurdly low and the per-MHz score is zero, suggesting either a stale or failed configuration. But the fitness score of 345.80 versus the baseline of 301.04 shows real improvement, so I should focus on what's actually working. The recent successful optimization (r3s0) consolidated DSP blocks, so I'm looking for similar structural consolidation opportunities—maybe combining the three shifter variants into a single barrel shifter, or optimizing the regfile write-forward bypass path where the write data comes from the MEM/WB stage.\n\nThe most promising angle is merging the ALU's subtract/comparison logic with the branch comparator—both need subtraction and comparison operations, so a single 33-bit signed subtractor could drive both paths and save area on the Tang Nano 20K. I'm also considering whether the multiplier generates unnecessary 66-bit products on non-multiply instructions that Yosys might not eliminate, though that's more of a power optimization than a timing win. The unified subtractor approach is a well-known optimization that could share a single 32-bit subtractor across all comparison operations, potentially gaining 2-5% with medium confidence. The divider is likely the real bottleneck—converting DIV/REM to multi-cycle would dramatically cut LUTs and improve Fmax, but that's a structural change requiring a state machine and pipeline stalling, so I'll focus on the branch comparator unification as the cleaner micro-optimization.\n\nLooking at the actual ALU and branch logic, both stages run in parallel and Yosys should theoretically share comparators already, but explicit unification via a common subtractor would guarantee it. I'm also considering the shifter consolidation—SLL, SRL, and SRA could theoretically use a single barrel shifter with bit-reversal tricks, though Yosys's map_shift pass probably handles this optimally already. The real opportunity might be in the pc_next mux in the EX stage, which is currently quite deep.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the cleanest micro-opt is precomputing `pc+4` in the IF stage and carrying it through the pipeline—that way EX doesn't have to compute it separately for jump return addresses, which would reduce critical path pressure.\n\nBut thinking about it more, the real bottleneck on the FPGA is probably the combinational divider in the ALU. A 32-bit divide is hundreds of LUT levels deep, and since branch resolution doesn't depend on ALU output anyway (it uses rs1/rs2 directly), making the divider multicycle could significantly improve Fmax without hurting IPC much, since CoreMark barely uses division.\n\nLooking at the forwarding logic more carefully, I notice the 3-way mux for rs1 happens at the start of EX stage. The forwarding decision could actually be made in ID since all the dependencies are known there, but the data still has to come from the later pipeline stages anyway, so moving it wouldn't help much.\n\nI think the cleanest optimization is still the unified subtract-based comparator for branches and ALU operations. The unified subtractor for SUB, SLT, SLTU, and branch comparisons could save 2-4% of EX-stage LUTs, though I'm skeptical modern synthesis tools don't already optimize this away. Looking at the actual bottlenecks, the critical path likely runs through the forwarding mux into the ALU, or through the branch condition logic from the register file. The `mem_wb_t` struct carries 64 FFs just for RVFI tracing, which is unavoidable overhead. Let me focus on the actual timing-critical paths instead of speculative LUT savings.\n\nThe divider is the real suspect here—32-bit combinational division should be catastrophically deep, easily 160+ LUT4 levels on a Tang Nano 20K, yet the reported Fmax is 153 MHz. Either Yosys is somehow using DSP blocks for division (unlikely), the divider is marked as multi-cycle, or it's isolated enough that it's not actually on the critical path. I need to understand whether the combinational divide is truly the bottleneck or if something else is limiting frequency.\n\nLet me focus on a concrete optimization: unifying the EX-stage subtractor for both the ALU (ADD, SUB, SLT, SLTU) and the branch comparator (BEQ, BNE, BLT, BGE, BLTU, BGEU). I can use a single 33-bit signed subtractor that computes `{sign_bit, operand1} - {sign_bit, operand2}`, where the sign bit of the result gives the less-than condition and a zero result gives equality. This consolidates multiple comparison paths into one fast path, though I need to verify that the ALU operands and branch operands are actually the same after forwarding. me document this as a potential optimization. The write-first bypass in the register file creates a long combinational path from the writeback stage output through the bypass mux and into the ID/EX register, all within a single cycle. I could eliminate this path by removing the bypass and relying on MEM/WB forwarding instead, though I need to verify the timing works out since the regfile write completes at the end of the WB cycle.\n\nActually, the bypass is necessary—without it, I'd need an extra forwarding level at the EX stage which gets messy. I'll keep the current design and focus on the unified compare/subtract optimization instead. The forward unit's equality checks are already efficient with the parallel structure, so that's not worth pursuing. Let me commit to writing up the subtractor micro-optimization in YAML format now.\n\nWait, I should also check the misalignment detection for branches and jumps—the comparison is just checking if the lower bits aren't zero, but for JAL the immediate generator already zeros out bit 0, so misalignment only happens if bit 1 is set. That's a tiny optimization though.\n\nSo my final focus: a unified 33-bit subtractor at the EX stage that both the ALU and branch unit can share, eliminating redundant comparator logic and reducing fanout on the operand nets.\n\nThe key is making sure Yosys actually synthesizes this as a single physical subtractor rather than two separate ones—I'll need to structure it so the hardware sharing is explicit and unavoidable, then expose the zero, sign, and borrow flags for both the ALU's SUB/SLT/SLTU operations and the branch condition logic.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb5506a60014TV6FPTIz4xoxi","sessionID":"ses_214ac9d96ffe0M9pTsTF9eWR2u","messageID":"msg_deb5362a1001fJ8d6fTrpMEED2"}}
