{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777770470456,"sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","part":{"id":"prt_deb609c33001KGfoci416gLNv6","messageID":"msg_deb608a3d001Z7m1i1mdwbvLuF","sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","snapshot":"c72ef0fe98d3688f4f17201ff4f94f18805d2f42","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770493949,"sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","part":{"id":"prt_deb60f18e001QAws0JoMtk1xU9","messageID":"msg_deb608a3d001Z7m1i1mdwbvLuF","sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation:\n- Current best fitness: 345.80 (from DSP consolidation win)\n- Fmax 153.61 MHz, LUT4 9865, FF 1867\n- Recent predictor attempts keep failing formal\n- M-ext consolidation worked great — look for similar structural wins\n\nThe reg_file's synchronous reset loop (`for i in 0..32: regs[i] <= 0`) prevents Yosys from inferring LUTRAM on GW2A. With 32×32=1024 bits of state currently synthesized as resettable flops (roughly half the 1867 FF count), this is a huge area sink. Converting to distributed LUTRAM is a classic, formal-safe micro_opt — riscv-formal accepts arbitrary initial register state under BMC, and CoreMark's crt0 writes before reading.","time":{"start":1777770492302,"end":1777770493948}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777770493984,"sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01FtF7wUZXhc7Ytk4Y2fmXuq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check hypotheses directory"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777770493971,"end":1777770493982}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the current core's fitness of 345.80 from the DSP consolidation approach, and I need to figure out what micro-optimization hypothesis could work next. The recent predictor attempts didn't pan out, but the DSP consolidation did succeed. Checking the critical path on Tang Nano 20K, the Fmax is already at 153.61 MHz, which beats the 135 MHz target, so I'm trying to understand what constraints remain to optimize.\n\nLooking at potential micro-optimizations, the register file reset logic stands out—currently it's synthesizing 32 flops with reset signals, but if I remove that reset, the synthesizer could infer LUTRAM instead, which would be much more efficient on the GW2A. Since the register file is 32x32 (1024 bits of state) and likely accounts for a significant chunk of the current 1867 total flip-flops, moving it to distributed RAM could free up resources and potentially improve Fmax. The divider and shifter are also candidates, but they're riskier structural changes, and the branch comparator optimization already failed in a previous attempt.\n\nThe main concern with removing reset is whether it breaks formal verification or simulation semantics. In formal verification with SBY, the initial state is typically symbolic anyway, so uninitialized registers aren't a problem. For simulation, well-formed code shouldn't read uninitialized registers before writing to them, and the crt0 initialization handles the calling convention. A safer middle ground might be to keep the reset but use synthesis attributes to hint that LUTRAM is acceptable, or to structure the code so Yosys can infer it despite the reset logic. The bypass mux will still be needed even with distributed RAM, but it becomes a simple LUT mux rather than a critical path bottleneck. I'm going to make the reset a no-op for the register file contents—this keeps the semantics identical for real programs since uninitialized registers are never read before being written anyway. The concrete plan is to add the `(* syn_ramstyle = \"distributed\" *)` attribute and remove the reset logic, which should let Yosys infer SSRAM or LUTRAM, saving around 1024 FFs and 300+ LUTs in reset overhead while likely improving Fmax and overall area.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb60f632001ithFx5eHB0uD3P","sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","messageID":"msg_deb608a3d001Z7m1i1mdwbvLuF"}}
