{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777770523116,"sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01VnAWFPY5gwxQg1iqDWQN5N","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r5s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r5s0\ntitle: \"Infer 32x32 register file as GW2A distributed LUTRAM by dropping synchronous reset\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current reg_file synthesizes as 32 resettable 32-bit flops (~1024 FFs,\n  over half the core's 1867 FF count) because the explicit reset loop\n  `for (i=0; i<32; i++) regs[i] <= 0` forces every entry into a flop with\n  a set/reset pin. On the Gowin GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) this blocks\n  inference of distributed LUTRAM (SSRAM / LUTR-style shadow RAM), which\n  is the natural fit for a small dual-read single-write RAM with\n  combinational reads. The previous fitness win (hyp-001-r3s0, DSP\n  consolidation, +8.50%) confirmed that on this device area/routing\n  pressure in the datapath — not worst-case logic depth — is what caps\n  Fmax. Freeing ~1000 FFs plus the reset-distribution fanout and\n  collapsing the per-register reset net should both reduce global\n  routing congestion and pull the regfile-read-to-ALU path shorter, so\n  the win is simultaneously area (LUT4/FF) and Fmax.\nhypothesis: |\n  Rewrite reg_file.sv so the 32x32 array is declared with a Gowin-style\n  synthesis hint `(* syn_ramstyle = \"distributed\" *)` (and a yosys-\n  compatible `(* ram_style = \"distributed\" *)` twin) and dropped from\n  the synchronous reset block. The write-first bypass mux on both read\n  ports is already in place, so formal/cosim semantics for same-cycle\n  RAW are unchanged. Initial contents become arbitrary — this is\n  already the convention riscv-formal's BMC assumes (the regfile is\n  free at induction start), and CoreMark/selftest crt0 writes every\n  architectural register before any read, so no real program observes\n  the change. x0 stays synthesized as a constant-0 read mux and is\n  never written; the write enable still gates on `w_addr != 0`.\n\n  Concretely:\n    - Remove the `for (int i=0; i<32; i++) regs[i] <= 0;` reset arm.\n      Keep the `w_en && w_addr != 0` write path unchanged.\n    - Add `(* syn_ramstyle = \"distributed\", ram_style = \"distributed\" *)`\n      on the `regs` declaration. Both attributes are harmless to tools\n      that don't recognize them (Verilator ignores unknown attributes);\n      Yosys-himbaechel for GW2A picks up `syn_ramstyle`.\n    - Keep the combinational read ports and write-first bypass as-is.\n    - Add a cocotb smoke test in test_regfile.py (new) that exercises\n      write-then-read, write-first-bypass on rs1 and rs2, x0-read-zero\n      after a write to x0, and x0-write-is-silently-dropped. Reset is\n      still applied by the test harness; the DUT simply won't zero the\n      array on reset, which is fine because the test writes before\n      reading every non-x0 register.\n\n  Formal impact: zero. `regs_ch0`/`regs_ch1` riscv-formal checks\n  already treat the initial regfile as symbolic; removing the explicit\n  `<= 0` reset matches that assumption more literally, not less. SBY\n  proof depth is unchanged.\n\n  Fitness arithmetic: if Yosys maps the 1024 bits to 16 GW2A SSRAM16\n  cells (typical distributed-LUTRAM tile), we recover ~1000 FFs and\n  ~300-500 LUT4s that were the reset-distribution mux fabric. Fmax\n  should rise 3-8% from the reduced fanout on the reset net and\n  shorter regfile-read-to-ALU routing. IPC is untouched — this is a\n  pure synthesis-level area/Fmax play, the same flavor of win as r3s0.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n    description: \"Drop the synchronous reset loop on regs[]; add syn_ramstyle=distributed and ram_style=distributed synthesis attributes on the 32x32 register array to let Yosys/nextpnr-himbaechel infer GW2A distributed LUTRAM. Keep the write-first bypass and x0-as-zero combinational mux exactly as today; no functional change.\"\n  - file: test/test_regfile.py\n    description: \"New cocotb smoke test: reset the DUT, write each of x1..x31 with a distinct pattern, read back on both ports; verify write-first same-cycle bypass on rs1 and rs2; verify x0 reads as 0 after a write to x0; verify writing w_addr=0 does not corrupt x0. Covers the LUTRAM-inferred regfile's functional behavior without relying on initial contents.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r5s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r5s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777770523100,"end":1777770523114}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Since there's no prior work on LUTRAM inference for regfiles, I'm starting fresh with this approach. Now I'll draft the hypothesis file to formalize my thinking.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb61153a001MwmuVKaQ6Ks5EU","sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","messageID":"msg_deb610cdf0010DFr7ziw9P246H"}}
