{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770526765,"sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","part":{"id":"prt_deb616e5d001P5Hvpk47Wkh4Wn","messageID":"msg_deb616a32001zvH8Fmpww639Sa","sessionID":"ses_2149f75faffeAIt05srg7nZfUC","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written: `hyp-20260502-001-r5s0` — infer the 32×32 register file as GW2A distributed LUTRAM by dropping the synchronous reset loop and adding `syn_ramstyle=distributed` / `ram_style=distributed` attributes.\n\n**Rationale in one line:** The reset loop forces ~1024 resettable flops (over half the core's 1867 FF count); on Tang Nano 20K the prior DSP-consolidation win (+8.50%) proved area/routing — not logic depth — caps Fmax here, so converting the regfile to LUTRAM frees FFs and collapses the reset-distribution net for both an area win and an Fmax bump, with zero formal or IPC change (write-first bypass already handles same-cycle RAW; riscv-formal treats initial regfile state as symbolic).","time":{"start":1777770524253,"end":1777770526762}}}
