\\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\\non every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\\nmul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\\nmultiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\\ndedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su with a single 33-bit signed multiplier\\nwhose operand sign bits are muxed from op: MUL / MULH use signed*signed\\n(sign-extend both), MULHU uses unsigned*unsig...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Unified EX-stage subtractor: share ALU SUB/SLT/SLTU and branch comparator\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage currently contains two parallel comparator networks that\\nconsume the same post-forward rs1/rs2 operands:\\n\\n  1. ALU ops SUB / SLT / SLTU \\u2014 each compiled separately via `a - b`,\\n     `$signed(a) < $signed(b)`, and `a < b` in alu.sv's case arms.\\n  2. Branch resolve in ex_stage.sv \\u2014 six funct3-indexed compares\\n     (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU), structurally independent of the\\n     ALU.\\n\\nThat is two full-width adder/subtractor trees plus two equality trees\\ncompeting for LUT4s and fanout on the forward-mux outputs. Yosys CSE\\ndoes fold some of this, but the compares live in two different\\n`always_comb` blocks in two different modules with different output\\npolarities (signed/unsigned/equal/not-equal) so the sharing is far\\nfrom guaranteed on GW2A.\\n\\nThe r3s0 win (+8.50%) proved that on Tang Nano 20K the EX path is\\narea/routing-bound rather than timing-bound: explicitly collapsing\\nthree redundant DSP multipliers into one paid off even though each\\nsub-expression was already single-cycle. The same structural\\nconsolidation opportunity exists here for the 32-bit sub/compare\\nlogic \\u2014 a fifth of EX-stage LUTs in a typical textbook 5-stage go\\nto these parallel comparators.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage currently contains two parallel comparator networks that\\nconsume the same post-forward rs1/rs2 operands:\\n\\n  1. ALU ops SUB / SLT / SLTU \\u2014 each compiled separately via `a - b`,\\n     `$signed(a) < $signed(b)`, and `a < b` in alu.sv's case arms.\\n  2. Branch resolve in ex_stage.sv \\u2014 six funct3-indexed compares\\n     (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU), structurally independent of the\\n     ALU.\\n\\nThat is two full-width adder/subtractor trees plus two equality trees\\ncompeting for LUT4s and fanout on the forward-mux outputs. Yosys CSE\\ndoes fold some of this, but t...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Infer 32x32 register file as GW2A distributed LUTRAM by dropping synchronous reset\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current reg_file synthesizes as 32 resettable 32-bit flops (~1024 FFs,\\nover half the core's 1867 FF count) because the explicit reset loop\\n`for (i=0; i<32; i++) regs[i] <= 0` forces every entry into a flop with\\na set/reset pin. On the Gowin GW2A (Tang Nano 20K) this blocks\\ninference of distributed LUTRAM (SSRAM / LUTR-style shadow RAM), which\\nis the natural fit for a small dual-read single-write RAM with\\ncombinational reads. The previous fitness win (hyp-001-r3s0, DSP\\nconsolidation, +8.50%) confirme