{"type":"text","timestamp":1777771823604,"sessionID":"ses_2148d60e7ffeY8NESW3ewx766W","part":{"id":"prt_deb74f612001obeNUO4JjOKW8W","messageID":"msg_deb74a082001gtfsDnzf0CZKuK","sessionID":"ses_2148d60e7ffeY8NESW3ewx766W","type":"text","text":"Looking at the prior attempts in micro_opt, I see:\n- r3s0 (+8.50%): DSP consolidation for MUL variants — structural sharing win\n- r4s0 (broken): Unified subtractor for SUB/SLT/SLTU+branch — failed formal (insn_xori_ch1 PREUNSAT)\n- r5s0 (-0.73%): Regfile LUTRAM attempt\n\nThe r3s0 pattern (consolidate redundant datapath structure into shared hardware) is the proven micro_opt play. The ALU still has three independent 32-bit shifters (SLL/SRL/SRA). Let me propose sharing these via bit-reversal onto a single right-shifter — structurally analogous to the r3s0 MUL consolidation, purely combinational, zero IPC impact.","time":{"start":1777771804179,"end":1777771823603}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777771823613,"sessionID":"ses_2148d60e7ffeY8NESW3ewx766W","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016JZaravGto9G2jnZGC3Tzd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r6s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r6s0\ntitle: \"Consolidate SLL/SRL/SRA onto a single shared right-barrel-shifter via bit-reversal\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The ALU currently synthesises three independent 32-bit barrel shifters\n  in alu.sv's case arms:\n    ALU_SLL: a << shamt\n    ALU_SRL: a >> shamt\n    ALU_SRA: $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)\n  Each 32-bit variable barrel shifter is a 5-level 32-wide mux cascade\n  (~80 LUT4 on GW2A). Three of them consume ~240 LUT4 even though at\n  most one result is selected per cycle. Yosys CSE does NOT fold these\n  because the shift directions differ and the `>>>` arithmetic variant\n  has a different fill-bit discipline than `>>`.\n\n  The prior big micro_opt win (r3s0, +8.50%) established the dominant\n  pattern on Tang Nano 20K: the EX path is area/routing-bound, not\n  logic-depth-bound, so explicitly collapsing redundant datapath trees\n  into shared hardware pays off even when every sub-expression was\n  already single-cycle. Folding three MUL variants onto one 33x33\n  multiplier freed DSP routing; folding three 32-bit barrel shifters\n  onto one right-shifter with bit-reversal should free the analogous\n  LUT4 routing channel around the ALU output mux.\n\n  Zero IPC impact (purely combinational restructuring with identical\n  bit-level semantics), formal-invariant (SLL/SRL/SRA are base I ops\n  fully proven by the per-instruction BMC), and the saving is a pure\n  area/routing gain that tends to translate into Fmax uplift on this\n  device.\nhypothesis: |\n  Rewrite the SLL/SRL/SRA arms of alu.sv to share a single 32-bit\n  right-barrel-shifter, using the standard bit-reversal trick so a left\n  shift is computed as reverse(reverse(a) >> shamt). Concretely:\n\n    1. Generate `a_rev[i] = a[31-i]` combinationally (free — just wiring).\n    2. Pick shifter input: `sh_in = is_sll ? a_rev : a`.\n    3. Pick arithmetic fill bit: `fill = is_sra ? a[31] : 1'b0`.\n    4. Compute right shift with fill: replicate fill into the MSBs\n       being shifted in. Cleanest form is\n         sh_out = $signed({fill, sh_in}) >>> shamt  (then drop hi bit)\n       or equivalently a manual 5-stage barrel shifter that muxes in\n       the fill bit at each stage. Yosys collapses both to the same\n       GW2A LUT4 tree.\n    5. For SLL: re-reverse the output bits.\n    6. Route `sh_out_final` into the ALU_SLL/ALU_SRL/ALU_SRA arms of\n       the case statement. All three arms now read from the same\n       shared structural shifter.\n\n  Additionally, identify the shift-op selection lines by adding three\n  1-bit flags derived from `op` (is_sll / is_srl / is_sra) rather than\n  re-reading `op` inside the shared shifter datapath — this gives Yosys\n  a cleaner netlist to share.\n\n  Side-effects the hypothesis does NOT change:\n    - ALU I/O ports, operand widths, or shamt derivation.\n    - Any case arm other than SLL/SRL/SRA.\n    - M-extension ALTOPS vs non-ALTOPS discipline.\n    - pipeline timing: retirement remains single-cycle for shifts.\n\n  Expected outcome: ~100-150 LUT4 reduction in EX, freeing routing\n  around the ALU output mux and lifting Fmax ~3-8%. CoreMark IPC\n  unchanged (identical bit results). Formal proof time unchanged\n  (SBY already verifies shift semantics under BMC regardless of how\n  they're structurally emitted).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Replace three independent shift expressions in the case arms for ALU_SLL / ALU_SRL / ALU_SRA with a single shared right-barrel-shifter fed by optional input bit-reversal (for SLL) and a fill-bit mux (0 for SRL, a[31] for SRA), followed by optional output bit-reversal for SLL. All three shift arms then read from the same shared combinational shifter.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r6s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r6s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777771823599,"end":1777771823611}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The unified subtractor approach in r4s0 broke the formal verification for the XOR instruction, so I need to explore other micro-optimization strategies that haven't been tested yet. Looking back at what's already been attempted, the iterative divider in the ALU initially caused regressions but was eventually extracted into a separate module where it worked.\n\nNow I'm considering several untried optimizations: consolidating the three separate shifter operations into a single right-shifter using bit-reversal for left shifts, simplifying the memory stage load shifter with an explicit multiplexer instead of dynamic shifting, moving branch resolution earlier to the ID stage, flattening the ALU output multiplexer that currently has around twenty cases, and reducing the forwarding multiplexer complexity in the EX/MEM feedback path.\n\nFor the shifter consolidation specifically, I'm calculating that on the Tang Nano 20K, three separate 32-bit barrel shifters consume roughly 240 LUT4s total. By sharing a single right-shifter and using bit-reversal for left shifts, I could significantly reduce that footprint—reversing the input for SLL operations, then reversing the output after the right-shift operation.\n\nLooking at the current ALU implementation, the three shift operations are written as separate cases. I'm thinking about consolidating them into a unified shifter that selects the direction and uses conditional sign-extension for arithmetic shifts, similar to how the DSP consolidation worked in the r3s0 revision.\n\nImplementing the unified shifter...\n\nThe key insight is that bit-reversal lets me convert left shifts into right shifts—reverse the input, shift right, then reverse the output. For arithmetic right shift, I just need to parameterize the fill bit based on whether it's SRA or SRL. This should collapse to a single barrel shifter tree and save around 80 LUTs with no IPC impact. The semantics are preserved because the bit-reversal transformation is mathematically sound, and I can verify it with the existing cocotb tests.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb74fb96001sB1D3L7DQJEcMe","sessionID":"ses_2148d60e7ffeY8NESW3ewx766W","messageID":"msg_deb74a082001gtfsDnzf0CZKuK"}}
