{"type":"text","timestamp":1777772797886,"sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","part":{"id":"prt_deb841f75001Z03Y8rJaCyT50s","messageID":"msg_deb80b84a001SBBsffSM62SBCx","sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","type":"text","text":"Looking at this challenge, let me analyze the lessons and recent outcomes to identify a promising micro_opt angle.","time":{"start":1777772797813,"end":1777772797885}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772797929,"sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_019DJtyZJxkeAHHCtWg5RR48","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | tail -20","description":"Check existing hypotheses directory"},"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml\nhyp-20260502-003-r7s2.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml\nhyp-20260502-003-r7s2.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777772797923,"end":1777772797927}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent optimization attempts, I'm seeing a pattern where extracting hot operations and consolidating them onto specific hardware resources yields meaningful gains. The last few iterations focused on sequentializing DIV operations and consolidating MUL onto DSP18, so I should explore what other bottlenecks might exist in the workload that could benefit from similar targeted extraction and consolidation strategies.\n\nExamining the EX stage's critical path, I notice the branch comparator is duplicating comparison logic that already exists in the ALU for SLT/SLTU operations. The branch conditions like BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU are essentially performing the same signed and unsigned comparisons, so there's potential to consolidate this redundant logic. Though I need to be careful here—Yosys might already be sharing these operations, similar to what happened with the barrel shifter attempt.\n\nThe challenge is that the ALU and branch comparator operate on different operands: the ALU uses forwarded values (alu_a/alu_b which can include immediates), while the branch comparator works directly on rs1/rs2. This makes them harder to share without adding muxing overhead that could hurt the critical path.\n\nLooking at the operand forwarding and the full adder in the ALU, those 3:1 muxes feeding into the arithmetic operations are likely contributors to the timing pressure at 167 MHz. I should trace through what's actually on the critical path: forwarding muxes feeding into the ALU, then the ALU result mux, then the pc_next computation and branch resolution logic.\n\nThe divider stalls are a non-issue for CoreMark since it has almost no divisions, but I'm noticing the write_data field in the EX/MEM register is redundant with rs2_val—both get set to the same forwarded rs2 value. Removing it would save 32 bits of flops, though it's probably already optimized away by synthesis. The bigger opportunity might be pulling BEQ/BNE resolution into the ID stage like r6s2 attempted, but that approach only yielded 0% improvement before.\n\nThe real constraint is that ID-stage forwarding muxes and the comparator compete for path pressure, and load-use hazards would force bubbles anyway. A pipelined multiplier is more promising—the current 33x33 combinational multiplier likely spans multiple DSP slices on the GW2A, so pipelining it could reduce critical path pressure.\n\nBut adding a pipeline stage to the multiplier means the hazard unit needs another handshake and MUL stalls increase, which matters since CoreMark's matrix multiply kernel uses them. The GW2A DSP18 has an optional output register that Yosys might map to for \"free\" pipelining, though that still requires pipeline coordination.\n\nLet me trace what's actually on the critical path in the execute stage: the forward muxes, ALU operand selection, and the ALU itself with its adder, shifter, multiplier, and comparators.\n\nThen after the ALU there's the division result mux, followed by a final 32-bit mux that selects between pc+4 for jumps and the ALU result. That's a lot of muxing stacked together.\n\nI could optimize this by routing pc+4 through the ALU itself as a dedicated operation, eliminating that final output mux. For JAL/JALR instructions, I'd set the ALU to compute pc+4 directly instead of doing it outside the ALU, which removes one 32-bit mux from the critical path. This would require updating the decoder to set the ALU operation accordingly and removing the conditional mux in the register write logic.\n\nBut looking at the decoder more carefully, I'm realizing the jump target computation is already duplicated in multiple places. For JALR, there's a separate adder computing rs1 + imm outside the ALU, even though the ALU could be doing this same addition when alu_src=1. For JAL, there's another separate adder for pc + imm. So I have redundant adders all over the place—the ALU has one, and then there are dedicated adders for jump target calculation that duplicate this work.\n\nThe real issue is that for JAL and JALR, the ALU's result isn't actually used for the write-back data anyway—we always write pc+4 instead. So the ALU is computing something that gets thrown away. What if I flip this around: make JAL and JALR use the ALU to compute pc+4 directly by routing pc to alu_a and setting alu_b to 4? Then the ALU result becomes the rd_wdata, and I can eliminate the mux that selects between jump results and ALU results. The jump target itself can still be computed separately in the redirect logic, but at least I'm not wasting the ALU and I'm removing a mux from the critical path.\n\nThe downside is this requires decoder changes to route pc to alu_a for jump instructions and somehow get 4 into alu_b, which is getting complicated. There's also another mux in the pipeline—the one that selects between div_result and alu_result—that I should consider while I'm thinking about this.\n\nActually, Yosys probably merges those muxes together anyway, so it's probably not the bottleneck. Let me consider a different optimization instead. The regfile-to-BRAM idea is tempting since the Tang Nano has BSRAM blocks available, but the r5s0 experience showed that Yosys didn't actually infer LUTRAM. BRAM would be even trickier because it's synchronous-read, which would break the combinational read path and require shifting the read address earlier in the pipeline. That cascades into forwarding complications.\n\nI'm thinking about consolidating the M-extension muxing in the ALU...\n\nCollapsing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into one case since they all pull from mul_prod[63:32], but Yosys already does that via case-collapsing. The real candidate is narrowing the ID-stage branch resolution to just BEQ/BNE. The r6s2 regression explicitly flagged this—I can add a simple 32-bit XOR equality check in ID, detect BEQ/BNE by checking opcode 0x63 with funct3[2:1]==0, and resolve taken branches early without needing the full signed/unsigned compare tree. That saves a cycle on taken branches if forwarding isn't blocking.\n\nNow I'm working through the forwarding constraint: if a BEQ in ID needs to compare rs1 against rs2, and rs1 was just written by the instruction currently in EX, the ALU result isn't combinationally available yet—it's still mid-computation. But for non-load ALU ops, the result latches into EX/MEM at the end of the cycle, so I can forward from that registered value one cycle later. The tricky case is when the branch immediately follows an ALU op and needs that result right now; that forces a stall.\n\nComparing the timing: baseline BEQ takes 2 cycles of bubbles (IF and ID both flush after EX resolves), but early ID-stage resolution saves a cycle when there's no dependency. With a dependency on an in-EX ALU op, I stall one cycle then resolve early—same total as baseline. The real win is branches whose operands come from the register file or MEM/WB forwarding, which is probably common in loops but hard to quantify without profiling. The concern is whether adding ID-stage forwarding muxes and equality logic hurts Fmax, though the XOR-based equality check for BEQ/BNE is actually quite cheap compared to a full comparator.\n\nThe forwarding path itself is tractable: I need 3:1 muxes in ID for rs1/rs2 (pulling from the regfile, EX/MEM.alu_result, and MEM/WB), but since the regfile already has write-first bypass, MEM/WB forwarding is essentially free. For EX/MEM forwarding, I'd just multiplex the registered ex_mem_q.alu_result onto the ID path for branch operands only. But I'm realizing r6s2's analysis warned that adding these muxes and a 6-way comparator to the ID combinational path could compete with the regfile-read and decode chain, which previously had slack relative to EX.\n\nThere's also the load-use stall case: if a branch depends on an in-flight load, I can't forward the result to ID since it doesn't exist yet—I'd have to stall. So even with ID-stage forwarding, I still need hazard detection for loads.\n\nA cheaper approach might be to skip ID-stage forwarding entirely and just stall whenever a branch's source register matches an in-flight instruction that hasn't written back yet. But that loses performance wins for most cases. The real question is whether I can narrow the stall condition to only the expensive cases—loads and divides—and forward from EX/MEM for everything else.\n\nThe catch is that the ALU result isn't available until the end of the cycle when it gets captured into the EX/MEM register, so during ID I can't use it combinationally. I'd need to stall anyway. So the proposal is to add early resolution for BEQ/BNE in ID, stall only when the source register matches an instruction currently in EX, and otherwise resolve the branch immediately to save a bubble cycle on taken branches. The earlier attempt with all six comparison types showed no improvement, so narrowing to just BEQ/BNE might be the key—it's a simpler comparator and avoids unnecessary forwarding complexity.\n\nThe tricky part is handling the dual redirect paths without flushing extra cycles. When ID resolves a branch and redirects, the same instruction will eventually reach EX and resolve again. The simplest fix is to convert the branch into a NOP in the ID/EX register once ID has already resolved it, so EX sees a NOP and doesn't trigger a redundant redirect.\n\nBut that breaks RVFI reporting — the instruction needs to retire with its original opcode. So instead I need to let the branch flow through the pipeline normally while signaling EX to skip its redirect logic since ID already handled it. That requires adding a payload bit to id_ex_t, which feels costly, but it might be the only way to avoid losing a cycle when EX redundantly redirects to the same target.\n\nActually, reconsidering the cost: I just need a single bit flag to gate the redirect output in EX, plus the equality check in ID. The synthesis overhead should be minimal compared to what r5s2 did with a full target path and mux.\n\nSo the refined approach is adding an `id_resolved_taken` bit to id_ex_t, performing the BEQ/BNE equality check in ID with a redirect, gating EX's redirect output when that flag is set, and adding a stall condition in the hazard unit for operand dependencies. It's more complex than I'd like, especially around ID-stage timing, but it avoids the redundant redirect penalty.\n\nI'm also noticing some potential micro-optimizations like eliminating the duplicate rs2_val and write_data fields in the pipeline registers, but those are probably not worth the effort for minimal area savings.\n\nLooking at other possibilities: the divider's dividend_orig_q storage for REM-by-zero handling, narrowing the counter to 5 bits instead of 6, and whether the immediate generator could be more efficient — but none of these seem critical. The imm_gen already carries 32 bits for both branch and ALU use cases, which Yosys should handle reasonably well.\n\nNow I'm considering the multiply path as a potential bottleneck. The 33×33 multiply in the ALU is a large combinational tree, and registering its output would break that critical path, but at the cost of adding a cycle of latency that could hurt CoreMark's matrix multiply performance. Using a DSP18 with pipelined output is tempting but feels like scope creep.\n\nI think I'll stick with the BEQ/BNE early resolution approach since the lesson highlighted it as a concrete path forward — keeping the payload addition minimal with just 1 extra bit. Beyond that, I'm noticing the ALU's adder and comparator could theoretically share hardware for signed/unsigned operations, though Yosys likely already optimizes this. There's also potential to share the pc+imm computation between branch target calculation and other uses...\n\nActually, I'm realizing pc+imm gets computed in multiple places: the ALU handles it for AUIPC, then branch_target and jump_target both calculate it separately. I can consolidate these into a single shared adder result and reuse it across all three paths, which should save some LUT4s even if it's a small area win. I'm seeing that there could be up to three parallel adders computing pc+imm in different paths (ALU for AUIPC, branch resolution, and jump resolution), and while I could consolidate the branch and jump paths into a single adder with output muxing, the AUIPC path is harder to share without adding complexity. The synthesis tool might not catch this anyway given the different enable conditions and consumers, so it's probably not worth the effort—I'll stick with the simpler approach of just doing early BEQ/BNE resolution and be careful about timing.\n\nLooking at the lesson again, it's pointing out that the IPC gains from moving branch resolution earlier are fundamentally limited by how fast the operands can arrive from the EX stage, so I should either narrow the comparator to just the two most common cases or shift focus to non-branch optimizations instead. Let me explore that second path—maybe I can save area or improve timing elsewhere. One option is to compute pc+4 once in the EX stage and reuse it for both the misalign fault path and the default next-pc, rather than computing it multiple times. Another idea is to precompute pc+4 in the IF stage and carry it through the pipeline so the EX stage doesn't need a separate adder for JAL writeback, though that adds 32 bits of pipeline state which might not be worth the tradeoff.\n\nThe MUL aliasing logic is already optimal—the output mux correctly selects the low or high 32 bits depending on the operation. And for RVFI, I can't really remove rs1_val and rs2_val from the MEM/WB register because they're mandatory RVFI fields and have to be captured at instruction retirement time; reading them from the regfile later would give stale values after subsequent writes.\n\nLet me focus on something concrete: consolidating the `pc + imm` adder in the EX stage. I could merge the separate branch_target and jump_target computations into one shared adder, leaving the ALU's AUIPC path untouched. It's low-risk—doesn't touch RVFI semantics or pipeline payloads—but the area savings would probably be minimal, maybe 1-2% if the synthesizer wasn't already doing common subexpression elimination.\n\nFor something with more potential impact, I'm looking at the regfile's write-first bypass logic. Currently it uses combinational forwarding to let writes bypass directly back to reads in the same cycle, but I could eliminate that by using explicit forwarding from the EX/MEM/WB stages to the ID stage instead.\n\nActually, the most promising angle is pipelining the multiplier output using the DSP18's internal register. If I can leverage the DSP primitive's built-in register with a synthesis directive, I'd get a 1-cycle pipeline for free without burning extra LUT4s, which would significantly shorten the EX critical path.\n\nThe tradeoff is that MUL becomes 2-cycle, requiring a mul_busy stall like we did for DIV. CoreMark's matrix multiply loop is heavy on multiplies, so the IPC hit from ~10% of instructions taking an extra cycle could be substantial—maybe 9% IPC drop. But if Fmax jumps from 167 MHz to 200+ MHz, that's a >10% frequency gain, which could net positive overall. The risk is whether the frequency win actually materializes and whether it's worth the added complexity.\n\nLet me step back and go with something safer. I'll propose narrow BEQ/BNE early resolution in the ID stage instead—just a 32-bit XOR plus OR-reduction for equality checking, which is cheap. I'll add a 1-bit flag to id_ex_t to signal when the branch is already resolved, gate off the EX-stage redirect when that flag is set, and stall BEQ/BNE if their source registers are being written by in-flight instructions. This follows the r6s2 hint more directly and avoids the multiplier pipelining complexity.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether the stall cost is actually worth it. A taken branch normally costs 2 cycles (flush IF and ID), but with early resolution and no dependency it's just 1 cycle (flush IF only). If there's a dependency and we stall for 1 cycle to wait for the result, then resolve, we end up with 2 cycles anyway—potentially no better than baseline. Let me trace through the timing to see if there's a real win here.\n\nFor branches without dependencies, we save a cycle by resolving in ID instead of EX. For branches with dependencies, the stall plus resolution equals the baseline cost. Not-taken branches are unaffected. Assuming about 25% of branches are taken without immediate dependencies, and branches make up 15% of instructions, this could yield roughly 3-4% CPI improvement. The added logic for the resolved-taken flag is minimal—just one extra bit in the pipeline state. This seems worth pursuing.\n\nThe implementation would require changes across several modules: adding the resolved-taken bit to the pipeline register, computing equality and branch condition in ID, stalling on hazards, and gating the EX redirect when ID already resolved it. But this is getting complicated. Let me step back and consider a simpler optimization instead.\n\nI could consolidate the `pc + imm` computation that appears in multiple places—branch targets, jump targets, and AUIPC. Rather than computing it separately in each path, I'd create a single `pc_plus_imm` wire in the EX stage and reuse it across all three cases.\n\nDefining helper wires for `pc_plus_imm` and `pc_plus_4`...\n\nThis is a straightforward refactoring that might help Yosys share logic, though the impact is probably marginal—maybe 0-2% improvement at best.\n\nLooking at the current metrics of 167 MHz and 5469 LUTs, there's actually decent headroom in area. The real bottleneck is likely the critical path through the ALU and muxes in EX. I should explore parallelizing the AUIPC and LUI paths instead, since both currently funnel through the ALU.\n\nActually, LUI and AUIPC are already pretty cheap operations—the ALU should already be optimizing them away. That's probably not worth the complexity.\n\nLet me step back. The concrete win I'm going to pursue is the shared `pc + imm` adder in the EX stage—it's low-risk and should give a solid 1-3% improvement.\n\nWait, I keep second-guessing myself. What about moving the load data extraction logic earlier in the MEM stage? Looking at how `dmem_rdata` flows through shift-and-extend operations before registering into the MEM/WB boundary... actually, that's already in the MEM stage, not EX, so it's not a critical-path problem.\n\nAlright, I'm going to commit to the early BEQ/BNE resolution in the ID stage—it's the approach the lesson suggested and has clear upside if I'm careful about it.\n\nActually, no. Let me try fusing the forwarding paths—combining `fwd_ex_mem` and `fwd_mem_wb` into a single \"freshest writer\" path. But wait, those represent different pipeline stages, so I can't actually fuse them.\n\nOK, I'm going with the consolidated `pc+imm` and `pc+4` adders in the EX stage. It's a clear, safe micro-optimization with no risk to the invariants, probably 1-3% improvement, medium confidence.\n\nBut looking back at what actually moved the needle—the big wins were 5-9% from substantial changes like the sequential divider, MUL consolidation, and the JAL predictor. Small refactors might just disappear in the noise.\n\nLet me think bigger. What about a pipelined multiplier that uses the DSP's internal pipeline register? The 33×33 signed multiplier is currently combinational, and registering it would break the EX critical path. I'd need to detect MUL in EX, assert a busy signal, then capture the registered product on the next cycle—similar to the divider FSM but just one cycle. Or I could try making MUL a 2-stage pipeline using the existing EX/MEM register as a buffer, but that doesn't really help. Adding an EX2 stage would be structural and would break the test pipeline. So pipelining MUL would require...\n\nDesigning a stall mechanism similar to `div_busy` but for just one cycle. I'm sketching out the logic: detect when MUL enters EX, register the result, then retrieve it the next cycle while stalling the pipeline. But this is getting complex—when MUL stalls in EX, IF/ID stall too, so the MUL stays put. Next cycle, I don't re-capture, just retrieve. I'm overcomplicating this. For a simple 1-cycle pipeline, I could just use a simpler formulation...\n\nDesigning the MUL stall logic...\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to extract the multiplier into its own module with a handshake interface (start/busy/done/result), just like the divider. That's a 1-cycle latency design. But I'm worried Yosys might already be mapping the multiplier to pipelined DSP18 blocks with internal attributes, which would duplicate work. I could skip adding a pipeline register and instead rely on Yosys pragmas to use the DSP18's internal one, but that's uncertain.\n\nI need to stop spinning and commit to something. The safest, clearest win is consolidating the `pc + imm` adder in ex_stage.sv—it's a structural optimization that Yosys isn't guaranteed to perform, even if the gain is only 1-3%. The multiplier is the critical path bottleneck in the ALU anyway, so optimizing the adder won't move the needle much.\n\nActually, wait—the multiplier output feeds through the ALU's output mux, then the alu_result_eff mux, then the jump pc+4 mux. All those cascaded muxes after the multiply add significant delay. Repositioning to capture pre-muxed versions in the EX/MEM register and doing the final mux post-register would help, but that just widens the register without solving the core issue.\n\nLet me go with sequentializing the 32-bit multiplier into 2 cycles like the divider did—add a mul_busy stall and register the output to shorten the EX combinational path. CoreMark's matrix_mult has MULs in tight loops though, so I risk a 5-10% IPC hit for a 15-20% Fmax gain. The r5s1 lesson says hot-in-ISA-cold-in-workload arithmetic is free real estate, but MUL isn't cold in CoreMark. I need to actually check the instruction mix in matrix_mult to see if MULs dominate enough to make this trade-off worthwhile.\n\nLooking at the actual CoreMark kernels, CRC and list operations dominate over matrix_mult, so MULs are probably only 2-5% of overall cycles. If sequentializing costs 2-5% IPC but Fmax rises 10%+, that's net positive. I'll go with a pipelined multiplier following the divider pattern—extract it to rtl/multiplier.sv with 1-cycle latency and handshake. But I'm wrestling with whether to register the 33x33 product internally using the DSP18 register, which would make MUL take 2 cycles in EX and stall the pipeline 1 extra cycle per multiply. Forwarding the result directly to EX/MEM via a mux might work, but the timing is tight—the mul_prod needs to be captured at the same clock edge that EX/MEM latches, so it'll miss the deadline.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing this whole approach. MULs are more common than DIVs, so if IPC drops 5-10% from a 2-cycle MUL but Fmax only rises 5-8%, we net negative. The Tang Nano 20K is already at 167 MHz, well above the 135 MHz target, so the multiplier might not even be the critical path—it could be the forwarding muxes or memory access instead. Too much uncertainty here.\n\nI'm going to play it safer: consolidate the redundant adders in ex_stage.sv (branch_target, jump_target, pc+4 in pc_next default). It's a low-risk micro-optimization with expected 1-3% improvement, and I'll write this up as the hypothesis.\n\nWait, one more thing just occurred to me. I could move misalign_fault detection to a separate early path to cut the EX critical path. The misalign_branch check is deep in the combinational logic since branch_taken comes from the comparator after forwarding. Since misalign_fault rarely triggers anyway, delaying detection to MEM stage wouldn't hurt common cases, and riscv-formal allows this since traps report at retirement in WB. But the trap gating logic that prevents register writes might itself be EX-critical, so I need to think through whether this actually helps.\n\nActually, the register write gating happens in WB anyway, so if MEM sets is_illegal and clears reg_write, we're still safe. But this is a bigger refactor than it's worth right now.\n\nLet me just go with the consolidation idea. I'm going to unify the three PC+imm additions scattered across the EX stage — branch_target, jump_target for JAL, and the fallback pc_next — into explicit shared signals fed by single adders. This guarantees Yosys won't miss the CSE opportunity, cuts LUT4 usage, and should trim the EX critical path. Medium confidence, expecting around 2% fitness gain.\n\nI'm also noticing the ALU computes pc+imm for AUIPC, which follows the same pattern, but it feeds a different consumer so I'll leave that alone for now. Focusing on the jump and branch consolidation.\n\nWriting the YAML now with hypothesis ID hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb841f7a001Zj16haniptgkVW","sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","messageID":"msg_deb80b84a001SBBsffSM62SBCx"}}
