{"type":"text","timestamp":1777772837589,"sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","part":{"id":"prt_deb84559f001QSF6VWOeGz3f62","messageID":"msg_deb842a22001lMQ1yavmdoj9xE","sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","type":"text","text":"Based on my analysis of the lessons and recent outcomes, I'll propose a targeted micro-optimization. Key observations:\n\n1. **r2s2 / r5s1 / r3s0** pattern: wins come from structural consolidation (DSP/divider) or stateless reconstruction\n2. **r6s0 lesson**: Yosys LUT-sharing is *not* reliable across distinct always_comb blocks — explicit structural sharing does pay off for hard primitives AND for adders when split across combinational islands\n3. **r6s2 lesson**: control-flow IPC is near-saturated; \"pursue non-branch optimizations\"\n\nLooking at `ex_stage.sv`, I see **multiple redundant 32-bit adders** computing identical operand patterns across separate `always_comb` blocks:\n- `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm` (one adder)\n- `jump_target` non-JALR path: `(in.pc + in.imm)` (second adder)\n- `reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4) : ... : (in.pc + 4)` (two pc+4 adders)\n- ALU's ADD arm also computes `pc + imm` for AUIPC\n\nThese each feed different downstream consumers (alu_result vs pc_next), sit in different combinational blocks, and Yosys CSE is not guaranteed across them. Unlike r6s0's shifter attempt (where Yosys DOES share within a single ALU case), these adders are in structurally disjoint islands — this is exactly the \"hard primitive that synth can't share on its own\" pattern that worked for r3s0's DSP consolidation.","time":{"start":1777772811679,"end":1777772837587}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772837604,"sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01P9YWJSaM9psNSCbHVLeRRK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\ntitle: \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\n  computing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\n  always_comb blocks:\n\n    (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\n    (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\n    (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\n                       : is_jump   ? jump_target\n                       : taken     ? branch_target\n                                   : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\n\n  Yosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\n  downstream consumers is unreliable — each `+` expression typically\n  lowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\n  identical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\n  opportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\n  but the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\n  duplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\n  be collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\n  costs ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\n  such adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\n  branch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\n  EX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux→ALU chain.\n\n  This fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\"pursue\n  non-branch optimizations\") and follows the successful structural\n  consolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\n  without touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\n  payload struct widths.\nhypothesis: |\n  Refactor ex_stage.sv to compute two shared combinational signals\n  once and reference them from every consumer:\n\n    logic [31:0] pc_plus_imm;   // single adder for branch/jump target\n    logic [31:0] pc_plus_4;     // single adder for linear-advance paths\n    assign pc_plus_imm = in.pc + in.imm;\n    assign pc_plus_4   = in.pc + 32'd4;\n\n  Then rewrite:\n    branch_target = pc_plus_imm;\n    jump_target   = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : pc_plus_imm;\n\n    reg_q.pc_next <= misalign_fault ? pc_plus_4\n                   : in.ctrl.is_jump  ? jump_target\n                   : branch_taken     ? branch_target\n                                      : pc_plus_4;\n\n  This is a pure structural refactor with zero functional change —\n  every output bit is bit-identical to the current implementation for\n  every input vector. Consequently:\n\n    - RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps are unchanged (same value, same\n      cycle, same register).\n    - No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t payload bits added or removed\n      (avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening synthesis penalty).\n    - No new formal state; SBY BMC depth unchanged (per the r1s2 and\n      r3s1 lessons on symbolic-fetch coupling — this change doesn't\n      touch fetch or predictor state at all).\n    - No change to the EX→MEM handshake, div_busy, or the JAL\n      predictor in if_stage.sv.\n\n  Expected effect on Tang Nano 20K synthesis:\n    - 1 adder collapsed for pc+imm (branch_target + jump_target\n      sharing), saving ~32 LUT4 of carry chain duplication.\n    - 1 adder collapsed for pc+4 (misalign-fault path + default\n      pc_next sharing), saving another ~32 LUT4.\n    - The pc_plus_imm wire is a single-source fanout to two mux legs\n      (branch_target-select and jump_target-select) instead of two\n      parallel adders racing to the same register input, shortening\n      the critical-path slack on reg_q.pc_next.\n\n  Risk profile:\n    - Zero IPC impact (identical functional semantics).\n    - Zero formal impact (same combinational output per input).\n    - Zero invariant-1 (RVFI 2-channel) impact.\n    - Only risk is that Yosys was already sharing these adders, in\n      which case the RTL becomes cleaner but fitness is a wash. Even\n      in that case the hypothesis strictly doesn't regress anything\n      and documents the intent for future code readers. The LESSONS.md\n      r6s0 note explicitly flags that Yosys sharing is NOT reliable\n      for LUT-based datapaths across islands, which is the exact\n      pattern here.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\n      pc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\n      and `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\n      duplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\n      / jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\n      next-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\n      references to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\n      jalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\n      different adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\n      for the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\n      pc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\n      running the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\n      test_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\n      unique / liveness / insn_* checks — no trace should change.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777772837578,"end":1777772837602}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm committing to my approach and examining the ex_stage.sv implementation to understand how branch and jump targets are calculated, along with how misalignment faults are handled in the pipeline.\n\nNow I'm seeing there are actually six adders being used across the design: the ALU handles rs1+imm for loads, stores, and JALR operations; separate adders compute pc+imm for both branch and jump targets; another adder calculates the JALR sum; and two more handle pc+4 for the misalignment path and default next PC. The key insight is that pc+imm gets computed twice (for branch and non-JALR jump), and rs1+imm is being calculated redundantly in both the ALU and the JALR path, which suggests I could consolidate these by sharing a single pc+imm adder and reusing the ALU's result for JALR instead of computing it separately.\n\nI'm going to focus on consolidating the pc+imm and pc+4 adders within the execute stage since that's contained and lower-risk, while leaving the ALU changes for later since they'd require more invasive modifications. Yosys might already be sharing the pc+4 constant, but I should make the pc+imm sharing explicit. This refactoring should be straightforward—just reorganizing the execute stage logic—and while the gains are modest, I'm fairly confident it'll help with area.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb8465fe001PfEcHYgZxqRJ0D","sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","messageID":"msg_deb842a22001lMQ1yavmdoj9xE"}}
