{"type":"text","timestamp":1777772843069,"sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","part":{"id":"prt_deb84c1e9001RRv06ApPMqje0H","messageID":"msg_deb84bb27001Nba5fWNH5tgAGM","sessionID":"ses_2147f47fbffen97Hz2vinhEWuX","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Consolidate the four redundant 32-bit adders on the EX-stage critical path (`pc+imm` appearing twice across branch_target/jump_target blocks, and `pc+4` appearing twice in the pc_next mux) into two explicitly shared wires `pc_plus_imm` and `pc_plus_4`.\n\n**Rationale**:\n- Follows the r3s0 / r5s1 structural-consolidation pattern (hard primitives that Yosys won't share across combinational islands)\n- Heeds the r6s2 \"pursue non-branch optimizations\" guidance\n- Avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening tax (zero bits added to any pipeline struct)\n- Avoids the r1s2 / r3s1 / r3s2 symbolic-fetch formal-coupling trap (no fetch/predictor changes)\n- Bit-identical functional output per input — RVFI semantics, formal proofs, and IPC all unchanged\n\nExpected: +2% fitness via reduced LUT4 pressure on EX critical path; medium confidence (downside is a wash if Yosys was already CSE'ing, but r6s0 explicitly flagged this as unreliable).","time":{"start":1777772839401,"end":1777772843066}}}
