{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774094475,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BXY8bE5fmrxaARnpgp4gqc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List past hypothesis files"},"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.yaml\nhyp-20260502-003-r8s2.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.yaml\nhyp-20260502-003-r8s2.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"List past hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List past hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777774094471,"end":1777774094474}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at the micro_opt category and need to find a hypothesis that boosts CoreMark performance on the Tang Nano 20K. I'm reviewing the previous optimization wins—DSP consolidation gave us 8.5%, division sequentialization added 8.79%, and the stateless JAL predictor contributed 5.87%—to identify patterns for the next improvement.\n\nI'm noticing that structural CSE on LUTs didn't pan out, and pipeline payload widening actually increased synthesis area despite being theoretically zero-cost. The branch prediction and early ID resolution paths are already saturated. We're at 376.19 iter/sec now, up from the 301.04 baseline.\n\nLooking at what's left, I'm focusing on the EX stage critical path—the forwarding muxes, ALU with DSP-based multiplication, divider result mux, branch resolution, and PC_next mux all contribute to timing pressure. The hazard unit's dmem_stall signal is another bottleneck, propagating through an AND gate and fanning out to multiple stall points. I'm considering whether simplifying the load-use hazard detection or the dmem_stall guard logic could reduce critical path delay without sacrificing correctness.\n\nI'm also thinking about whether moving the divider busy signal earlier, hardening the x0 forwarding checks, or reducing the load-result extension path could help, though most of these feel incremental. The real constraint seems to be that we're at 5469 LUTs and further area reduction might indirectly improve Fmax by reducing routing congestion.\n\nOne angle is stripping RVFI-only fields like `rs1_val`, `rs2_val`, `instr`, and `branch_target` from the pipeline registers in non-formal builds, but that gets tricky—the top-level core.sv always drives RVFI outputs, so we'd need to gate both the fields and their consumption consistently to avoid breaking the formal flow or leaving dangling ports.\n\nThe storage savings would be substantial—roughly 256 flops across two pipeline stages—but the constraint is that cosim relies on real RVFI data to diff against the ISS, and the formal verification can't have those fields stripped away. So the real question is whether we can differentiate between formal mode, cosim mode, and plain FPGA synthesis to conditionally gate the RVFI payload.\n\nYosys automatically defines `SYNTHESIS` during synthesis, whereas Verilator doesn't, so we could use `ifndef SYNTHESIS` to keep RVFI state in simulation but strip it in the FPGA build. That could reclaim around 12% of the flip-flops and reduce routing congestion, potentially improving Fmax. The catch is verifying whether the FPGA bench actually connects those RVFI outputs or just leaves them dangling—if they're unused at the top level, Yosys might sweep them anyway without needing the ifdef.\n\nLooking at the actual critical paths, I notice the misalignment trap logic in the execute stage is doing full 32-bit additions to check branch and jump target alignment, but most of those bits are unnecessary. Since B-type immediates always have bit 0 = 0 and the PC is always 4-aligned, the misalignment check for branches is always false in RV32I without the C extension. For JAL it's the same—the result is always aligned. Only JALR can produce misaligned targets, so we could optimize away the branch and JAL misalignment logic entirely.\n\nBut here's the catch: the formal verification requires those trap checks to be present, and under symbolic execution with unconstrained memory and PC values, we can't just remove them without proving the alignment invariant holds structurally. The CPU does maintain 4-byte alignment by design, but the formal tool won't derive that without help.\n\nA more promising angle is the divider's FSM and how its busy signal fans into the stall logic—it's another OR gate in the hazard paths that might be adding delay.\n\nLooking at what's actually on the critical path after the recent optimizations, the EX stage has the forwarding muxes feeding into the ALU (which contains the 32×32 multiplier), then the result gets selected between ALU output and div result before being registered. The branch resolution path is similar but probably shallower since it's just comparison logic.\n\nI've considered a sequential multiplier or pipelining through the DSP's registered output, but those either regressed performance or add unwanted latency. Another angle is reducing the forwarding mux depth—currently it's a 3:1 mux with two LUT4 levels. The MEM_WB forwarding path might be redundant since the regfile already has write-first bypass, so the ID stage sees WB writes one cycle later anyway.\n\nBut tracing through the dependency chain: when instruction A retires at WB in cycle T and instruction B is in EX that same cycle, B's input operand was captured the previous cycle when A was in MEM, so B still needs the MEM_WB forward. Can't eliminate that path.\n\nThe real bottleneck seems to be after the multiplier output—it goes through a 3:1 mux to select between MULH/MULHU/MULHSU, then through another mux for the final ALU result before hitting the EX/MEM register. I should look at pre-decoding the ALU operation earlier to collapse some of these muxes.\n\nI could also move the dmem write-data replication logic from MEM into EX so it comes straight off a register, though the external dmem bus path might not benefit much. Looking at the actual Fmax target, we're already hitting 167 MHz when the goal was 135, so the real constraint is IPC now. The main IPC drains are load-use bubbles, branch mispredicts causing 2-cycle stalls, and the random bus stalls. One untried approach is letting IF speculatively fetch ahead when dmem stalls the pipeline, but that needs a FIFO. Store-to-load forwarding could help too, though CoreMark is compute-heavy so the gains might be limited.\n\nThe fitness jumped from 301 to 376 recently, but we've been regressing since then—I need something the synthesizer can't already optimize. I'm looking at merging the `is_jump` mux that routes PC+4 as the return address for JAL/JALR, but both the PC+4 adder and the ALU path run in parallel anyway. The real bottleneck might be the hazard unit's fanout on dmem_stall, which gates the entire EX/MEM register and fans out to stall_if, stall_id, and other control signals. Restructuring that to reduce the critical path dependency on dmem_stall could be the micro-optimization that moves the needle.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering whether removing `div_busy` from `stall_if` and letting it propagate only through the EX/MEM stall path would work—if the divider is busy, EX/MEM holds and stall_id holds ID/EX, but then the PC would advance and fetch a new instruction into IF/ID that gets ignored because stall_id is still asserted, which means we'd need to re-detect the hazard each cycle to know whether to keep stalling.\n\nSo `stall_if` is necessary. Let me shift focus to the register file read port fanout instead—rs1_data and rs2_data feed the ID/EX register, and after the forward muxes in EX, they drive the ALU, branch compare, and the EX/MEM register fields, plus the multiplier. That's significant fanout on rs2 especially since it also feeds write_data. I'm looking at the PC+4 computation for JAL/JALR—it's a 2:1 mux right at the EX/MEM boundary that selects between PC+4 and the ALU result, which seems like it could be moved earlier or computed differently to reduce that mux's fanout.\n\nThe idea is to compute PC+4 in ID and carry it through the ID/EX register as a new field, so EX just does a simple 2:1 mux on already-registered values instead of computing the add combinationally. That trades 32 flops in the pipeline for removing a 32-bit adder from the EX critical path—on Tang Nano 20K that's likely a win for Fmax. But I need to check if PC+4 is used elsewhere, like in if_stage for next_pc. r7s0 already warned me against manual restructuring like this. Let me step back and think about what the synthesizer actually misses — it's the semantic invariants that matter. Things like bit 0 of the PC always being zero in RV32I, or B-immediates always having a zero LSB. The decoder already encodes these zeros correctly, but downstream flops store the full width. Synth does constant propagation, so known-zero bits get optimized away in logic, but the flops themselves stick around if they're assigned from the data path. Stripping bit 0 from PC storage across three stages would save maybe 15 flops total — not worth the complexity. Let me look at something more concrete instead. The forward unit has duplicate combinational blocks for rs1 and rs2 that probably get shared by Yosys anyway. What about the MULH output selection...\n\nExamining ALU output muxing... The current rewritten thinking already describes code being written (the case arms and wire collapsing). The next thinking shifts to architectural optimization ideas, so I should transition to prose.\n\nHere's the rewritten thinking:\n\nMoving sign-extension from MEM to WB would eliminate the `read_data` flop but add shift-and-extend logic to the write-back stage, which feeds both the regfile write port and the forwarding path to EX. The regfile write itself isn't on the critical path since it's synchronous and parallel with ID/EX flops, but the forwarding mux that feeds ALU operands is — specifically, `wb_w_data` flows through `fwd_mem_wb` into the EX stage's ALU input selection, so moving combinational logic there could hurt timing.\n\nGiven the current fitness of 376.19 MHz with 5469 LUT4s and 2016 flops, and recent attempts showing minimal gains, the core is near saturation. I should focus on surgical optimizations rather than architectural changes. The divider's `rem_q` update path isn't worth optimizing since it runs outside the CPU's critical path and doesn't affect CoreMark performance. Instead, I'm looking at consolidating the load-data byte extraction logic in the memory stage to reduce LUT4 count.\n\nThe current implementation uses a barrel shifter on `alu_result[1:0]*8` to extract bytes and halfwords, which Yosys converts into a 4:1 mux for bytes and 2:1 for halfwords. This is already minimal. So I'm shifting focus to the decoder's case statement on `{funct7, funct3}` — a 10-bit sparse mapping that Yosys turns into a large mux tree. I could potentially compress this by computing `alu_op` arithmetically from the funct3 and funct7 bits rather than using a full case statement.\n\nLooking at the M-extension opcodes, I notice the ALU_MUL through ALU_MULHU constants aren't currently aligned with their funct3 values. If I reorder them to match funct3 ordering, the decoder could compute `alu_op = ALU_MUL + funct3` instead of a full case, saving LUTs. The same optimization applies to the DIV family — reordering ALU_DIV through ALU_REMU to match funct3 values 4–7 would let me use arithmetic instead of explicit decoding.\n\nThe current encoding has MULHU and MULHSU swapped relative to their funct3 positions, so I'd need to reorder the constants to MUL=11, MULH=12, MULHSU=13, MULHU=14 and update the corresponding case arms in alu.sv. For the base R-type and I-type ALU ops, the funct3 values don't align with the current ALU_* constants either, so I'm checking whether a similar reordering would help there too.\n\nReordering all the ALU opcodes would be a large refactor touching both core_pkg and alu.sv, but the decoder wouldn't shrink much since the ALU's case statement still needs the same coverage. The smaller win is just aligning the M-extension ops—swapping MULHU and MULHSU in the encoding lets me replace the 8-arm case with a single formula `alu_op = ALU_MUL + {2'b00, funct3}`, saving a few LUTs.\n\nNow I'm stepping back to think about what the real micro_opt opportunity is. The biggest wins so far have been DSP consolidation and DIV sequentialization, so I should look at what other heavy arithmetic blocks are on the critical path. After MUL and DIV are handled, the remaining ALU operations are ADD, SUB, shifts, and comparisons—shifts especially are barrel shifters with multiple mux levels.\n\nI'm considering whether I can reuse the branch comparator for SLT/SLTU instead of having separate comparison logic in the ALU. The branch resolver already computes signed and unsigned less-than for BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, which are the same operations SLT/SLTU need. The inputs differ though—the branch comparator uses rs1/rs2 post-forwarding while the ALU uses post-mux values—but for register-form SLT/SLTU when alu_src=0, the inputs would actually match. SLTI uses immediates so that breaks the sharing, but it's still worth exploring whether I can unify the subtractor logic since the branch comparator computes all six conditions and the ALU also subtracts for SUB.\n\nActually, most CPUs consolidate this by recognizing that a single subtraction gives you the zero flag for equality checks, the sign bit plus overflow for signed comparison, and carry-out for unsigned comparison. On a LUT4 fabric, Yosys and nextpnr should already be sharing subtractor infrastructure across these operations anyway, so this optimization might be premature.\n\nLet me step back and focus on what's actually cold and big in the workload. The barrel shifter isn't cold, comparisons are hot, multiply is hot. The byte-lane mask computation in the memory stage is cheap. I think the more concrete hypothesis is whether a carry-select adder would help on LUT4 fabrics—though the dedicated carry-chain primitives usually aren't the Fmax bottleneck, if the critical path goes through the adder plus downstream muxes it could matter. But I'm getting too speculative here.\n\nThe safest concrete optimization I can commit to is reordering the M-extension ALU opcodes to match funct3 order, so the decoder can collapse multiple case arms into a single arithmetic assignment instead of eight explicit branches. This reduces decoder LUT count and routing pressure in the ID stage, with a small expected impact on Fmax from less congestion—though Yosys probably optimizes this away anyway.\n\nNow I'm looking at the IF stage's JAL predictor path more carefully. The check for `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` is actually redundant—since PC always starts at 0 and only advances by 4, and the JAL immediate's lowest bit is always 0, I can replace that full 32-bit comparison with a single-bit check on `imem_data[21]`, which saves LUTs and reduces combinational depth in the is_jal_fetch signal. = imem_data[21]. So the simplified check `imem_data[21] == 0` is formally equivalent to the full comparison when PC stays aligned, which formal verification should confirm through its existing pc_fwd invariants. The key risk is whether formal BMC assumes reset initialization or needs to verify PC alignment inductively, but given that the MISALIGN trap at EX prevents misaligned redirects anyway, the optimization preserves correctness.\n\nHowever, there's a subtle divergence if formal somehow explores a misaligned PC state: the old check `jal_target[1:0]==00` depends on both pc[1] and imem_data[21], while the new check only looks at imem_data[21]. Under pc[1]=1 with imem_data[21]=1, the old predictor fires but the new one doesn't—a behavioral difference that formal BMC could theoretically exploit if it doesn't enforce the PC alignment invariant from the start.\n\nBut riscv-formal uses reset-constrained initial states, and from reset pc[1:0]=0 stays invariant through every subsequent cycle—either holding, adding 4, or redirecting to validated-aligned targets. So BMC at depth 20 can't actually reach a misaligned PC state, making the transformation sound.\n\nNow I'm analyzing the hardware impact: the 32-bit adder for computing jal_target still exists because it feeds next_pc, but the 2-bit comparison check becomes trivial. The real question is whether that check was on the critical path before—whether the delay chain ran through the adder output, the 2-bit compare, the AND gate, and into the PC mux select, or if the adder's data path to the mux was the bottleneck instead.\n\nBy replacing the select path with just an immediate field bit and an AND, I'm removing the adder's carry chain and the compare from the select timing, but the adder still dominates as the data path into the mux. So Fmax probably doesn't improve much—just a small LUT savings. Now I need to figure out what's actually limiting the frequency. The ID-to-EX combinational chain looks like the real culprit: instruction decoding from the IF/ID register through the control logic, plus the regfile read path.\n\nIn the EX stage, the critical path is likely the ALU chain—forwarding, operand mux, then the 33×33 multiply through DSP, followed by the output mux and into the EX/MEM flop. I'm considering a few approaches: moving the jump/PC+4 mux into the ALU itself (though Yosys would still synthesize it as a mux), pipelining the multiply through the DSP's internal register (but that adds latency), moving branch condition compute earlier (which didn't work before), or splitting the EX stage further.\n\nActually, I think the more practical move is to simplify the JAL predictor's alignment check—minor LUT savings, low risk of regression. But I'm also thinking about something more ambitious: compressing the ex_mem_t and mem_wb_t payloads by stripping out fields that are only used for RVFI observation and can be reconstructed combinatorially. That includes the instruction, register addresses, register values, PC, and memory data fields. I need to verify which of these are actually used elsewhere in the design versus purely for RVFI output.\n\nLooking at the core.sv top level, mem_wmask is driven only to the RVFI port, not used for actual memory control—that comes from the mem_stage combinatorially. So these fields are RVFI-only. The question is whether Yosys already sweeps them during synthesis when the FPGA top is CoreBench and the RVFI outputs are unused. Since hierarchies get flattened early in the GW2A flow, the unused RVFI cones should propagate through optimization passes and get removed anyway.\n\nGiven recent regressions, I should focus on low-risk micro-optimizations. One option is simplifying the JAL predictor's misalignment check from a 32-bit adder comparison to just checking an immediate bit—semantically equivalent and zero regression risk. Or I could try detecting ADDI with x0 source (the LI macro pattern) in the ID stage and routing the immediate directly to the write data without the ALU's adder, though Yosys might already optimize this through constant propagation when rs1 is forced to zero at runtime.\n\nActually, the ALU already computes 0+imm = imm correctly, so adding a bypass mux would be redundant overhead. I'm going to commit to the JAL simplification instead—it's clean, minimal, and fits the pattern of what's left to optimize in a near-saturated core.\n\nThe key insight is that since pc is always 4-aligned, jal_target[1:0] reduces to just checking whether imem_data[21] is zero. This replaces a 2-bit comparison with a single bit check, saving maybe one LUT4 level, though realistically that's only 0-2% Fmax improvement.\n\nBut looking deeper, I'm noticing the ex_stage has two sequential muxes that could collapse into one—the alu_result_eff mux for div operations and the separate mux for jump targets are orthogonal, so combining them into a single 3:1 or 4:1 mux would reduce the mux depth...\n\nthough Yosys probably already does this optimization automatically.\n\nI've also considered reducing the PC register width by storing only the upper 30 bits and reconstructing the lower 2 zeros, which would save 8 flops across the pipeline stages, but that's pretty minor.\n\nLet me focus on the combined mux simplification and the JAL predictor check. Actually, I'm realizing the real bottleneck might be in the redirect logic on the EX stage critical path—specifically the misalignment check for branches.\n\nAnalyzing the misalignment conditions more carefully: for JAL it's just checking if `imm[1]` is set, for BRANCH it's the same but only when the branch is actually taken, and for JALR it depends on bit 1 of the computed sum. The key insight is that the misalignment trap only matters when the branch is taken, so I can't simplify away the `branch_taken` dependency for branches—the semantics require it.\n\nLooking at the target address bit 0: it's always 0 by spec (JAL immediate has bit 0 as 0, PC is aligned, JALR gets masked), so really I only need to check bit 1 of the target. The `!= 2'b00` check should optimize down to just checking bit 1, though Yosys likely handles this already—not a significant win.\n\nNow I'm considering what other optimizations might be worth pursuing. The register file read mux consolidation via LUTRAM failed before on the GW2A, but I'm wondering if using dual-port distributed RAM to reduce the flop count could help instead.\n\nActually, let me focus on something more concrete: reducing the EX-stage ALU input mux. Most operations use rs1 for alu_a and rs2 for alu_b, but AUIPC and LUI force different paths that could be optimized.\n\nI could fold LUI and AUIPC into a unified pattern where the ALU just adds either pc or zero to the immediate, eliminating the separate ALU_LUI operation entirely. This saves decoder logic and an ALU case, though Yosys probably already optimizes similar patterns.\n\nI keep circling back to small gains. Let me commit to the JAL-misalign simplification as the safest, cleanest micro-optimization. But wait—there's another angle: moving the jump-vs-non-jump mux out of the EX critical path by pre-computing pc+4 in ID and deciding the write-back value earlier. For jumps, rd_wdata is pc+4 (known at ID), but for non-jumps I need the ALU result, so this doesn't fully work.\n\nActually, the real idea is to register pc+4 from ID into the id_ex pipeline, then in EX just mux between that registered value and the ALU result instead of computing pc+4 on the fly. This removes a 32-bit adder from the EX combinational path, though it costs 32 flops and another adder in ID. The r7s0 lesson warned against manually CSE'ing pc+4 across multiple uses within EX—that regressed fitness by 3%—but this is different: I'm moving the adder to ID and registering it, which changes the timing picture entirely. The tradeoff is whether removing the adder from EX's critical path outweighs the cost of the extra flops and ID-stage adder.\n\nWait, I just realized IF already computes pc+4 as part of its next_pc logic. If I expose that through if_id_t instead of computing it again in ID, I eliminate the duplicate adder entirely. The plan is to thread pc+4 from IF through if_id_t into id_ex_t, then use the registered value in EX's jump mux. This way pc+4 is computed once in IF, registered through the pipeline, and ready for both PC updates and JAL/JALR writeback.\n\nImplementing this means adding pc_plus_4 fields to both if_id_t and id_ex_t, having IF drive the value directly from its existing pc+4 computation, and updating EX to consume the registered value instead of computing it locally.\n\nThe concern is that test_pipeline.py sits in the rollback set, so changing id_ex_t's struct layout could break it. But adding a new field shouldn't break existing field accesses by name—only renaming or removing fields would cause issues. Let me verify whether the rollback risk actually applies here.\n\nSo this approach is viable. My hypothesis is to export pc+4 from the IF stage and thread it through id_ex_t to avoid recomputing it in EX, which removes a 32-bit adder from the critical path.\n\nBut wait—I need to reconsider whether pc+4 is actually on the critical path. The EX stage runs the ALU (likely a DSP multiplier) in parallel with the pc+4 adder, both feeding into the is_jump mux. If the ALU is slower, then pc+4 isn't the bottleneck. A 32-bit adder on GW2A with dedicated carry logic is quite fast, so the DSP multiplier is probably the real constraint here.\n\nAt 167 MHz with a 6ns period, that's roughly 15 LUT4 delays—a long path that likely goes through the DSP multiplier. Pre-computing pc+4 might not actually improve Fmax if ALU is the limiter, though it's still a clean structural improvement and shouldn't hurt.\n\nLet me commit to this approach anyway. It's interesting from a design perspective, should be neutral or positive for both Fmax and IPC, and aligns with what I learned from r7s0 about CSE patterns. Actually, I should double-check r7s0 to make sure I'm not repeating a lesson about how Yosys and nextpnr already optimize these kinds of shared adder chains.\n\nThe key difference is that r7s0 kept everything in EX and just named wires—which made routing worse. My idea is to move pc+4 computation across the pipeline boundary from EX to IF/ID, which is a different optimization. The question is whether this actually reduces critical-path depth in any single stage. IF already computes pc+4 for next_pc logic, so exporting it to the pipeline register costs only a wire and 32 flops. EX saves one adder, but the critical path still bottlenecks on the ALU output feeding into the is_jump mux, so the overall path depth might not improve.\n\nNeither pc+4 pre-compute nor JAL-align-simplify will meaningfully help—both are sub-2% gains. I need to think bigger. The real bottleneck is the ALU's 33×33 multiplier going through a DSP18, then a large case mux with 19 operations. One idea is to split the ALU into fast and multiply paths with a registered DSP output at the EX/MEM boundary, but that increases MUL latency. Another angle is using the DSP18's OPMODE to compute SLT/SLTU comparisons, but the DSP is already consumed by multiply. The GW2A DSP18 supports 18×18 mul-add/sub, so 32×32 would need either multiple DSP tiles or a different approach.\n\nI keep circling back—let me just commit to the pc+4 pre-computation hypothesis with low-medium confidence. It's a clean refactor with no obvious regressions, and there's a chance it helps Fmax if the pc+4 adder was on the critical path. The code currently uses pc+4 three times in EX (for pc_next in two branches and for alu_result on jumps), so pre-computing it from IF and threading it through id_ex_t would turn all three into registered lookups instead of potentially separate adders.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the real bottleneck is actually in the IF stage itself—the JAL predictor and pc+4 adder are competing with the opcode alignment check, and that whole path (pc → jal_imm unpack → pc+jal_imm add → mux → next_pc mux → PC flop) might be what's actually limiting Fmax. If that's the case, there's not much I can do without a bigger pipeline restructure.\n\nLet me step back and commit to the pc+4 pre-computation idea since it's a clean, low-risk change. If it doesn't help, at least I've documented the attempt.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider. The r5s1 DIV sequentialization worked because it moved a cold but expensive operation off the critical path and saved ~9%. What else fits that pattern? MUL is hot, shifts are hot for CRC, adds and logic are all hot. The only thing left is variable-amount shifts, but SLLI and SLL both use the same ALU logic anyway—the shamt just comes from different sources.\n\nI'm also thinking about whether I can simplify the flush_id signal in the hazard unit by eliminating it when it's redundant.\n\nAlright, I'm going to commit to just the pc+4 pre-computation change. It's simpler to land than multiple tweaks.\n\nOne more thing I want to explore: can a LOAD forward its result directly to a back-to-back consumer via combinational bypass from the dmem output? The LOAD's rdata arrives combinationally from dmem, gets sign-extended in MEM, then stored into MEM/WB. The dependent instruction is one cycle behind in EX, and the forward unit pulls from MEM_WB.read_data. So there's actually one cycle between when LOAD is in EX and when its dependent is in EX—meaning LOAD is already in WB by the time the consumer reaches EX.\n\nThe load-use hazard detector catches this: when LOAD is in EX and the dependent is in ID, it stalls for one cycle, creating a bubble. But what if I could bypass dmem_rdata directly to the dependent's EX stage in the same cycle LOAD is in MEM? That would skip the bubble entirely. The problem is the combinational path would be too long—dmem output → sign-extend → forward mux → ALU → result all in one cycle. That's risky for timing.\n\nSo I'm moving on to a different optimization: pre-computing pc+4 in IF instead of recalculating it three times in EX. The concern is that r7s0 warned against manually CSE'ing adders in EX on LUT fabrics, but my approach is different—I'm pipelining the adder across stages (latching it in id_ex_t) rather than sharing a combinational wire within EX. That should avoid the routing congestion r7s0 hit. The tradeoff is 32 extra flops in the pipeline for potentially 0-20 LUT4s saved in EX, though the ALU likely dominates the critical path anyway.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing this. The fitness impact is probably only -1% to +3%, and I've had recent failures. The safer play is the JAL-misalign simplification—it saves LUTs with zero new flops and zero functional risk, though the gain is tiny. Maybe I should combine both: do the JAL-misalign fix plus one other small, low-risk micro-op to get a meaningful improvement without betting on the pc+4 gamble.\n\nNow I'm looking at the misalignment checks more carefully. The branch and jump target misalignment logic always has bit 0 as zero by the RV32I spec—PC is always aligned, and immediate fields have bit 0 as zero. So the misalignment checks can be simplified to just look at bit 1 instead of checking the full 2-bit value. For JALR, the same principle applies since the sum's bit 0 is forced to zero. Yosys might optimize this automatically, but being explicit about it ensures the simplification sticks. I'll bundle this into a \"micro-opt cleanup\" proposal that exploits these statically-zero bit invariants across all the misalignment traps.\n\nActually, I'm being honest with myself—Yosys already does constant propagation, so this optimization is probably a no-op. The real win would be the pc+4 pipelining idea, which could actually reduce critical path. Let me go with that instead.\n\nWait, there's another angle: consolidating the ALU arithmetic operations—ADD, SUB, SLT, SLTU, and branch comparisons—into a single shared 33-bit adder. That's a classic ALU consolidation pattern that could cut LUTs and improve Fmax. But Yosys likely already shares these operations, and my previous attempts at structural sharing didn't help.\n\nI'm committing to the pc+4 pipelining approach. That's the most promising direction.\n\nActually, let me hunt for subtler wins first. The regfile write-enable gating for x0 detection fans out to 32 flops—maybe there's consolidation opportunity there. And I should check whether reset initialization is actually necessary for the test cases or if we can skip it entirely.\n\nLooking at the if_stage logic, the next_pc mux combines the redirect, JAL, and sequential paths all together. If I want to pipeline pc+4 separately, I need to compute it unconditionally as its own wire in IF, export it through the pipeline, and use it in EX for the JAL/JALR return address calculation. The key is making sure I'm capturing the right value—the PC of the JAL instruction plus 4, not the redirected target.\n\nNow I'm updating the pipeline structs to thread pc_plus_4 through if_id_t and id_ex_t, then replacing the three places in EX that compute (in.pc + 32'd4) with the precomputed value. Let me write this out.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb97dfcb001QY9WjSy55t1AZc","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","messageID":"msg_deb931a4c001JMEIH20MZupOkh"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774094550,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"id":"prt_deb97dbf1001PY67ntdQ67wkHK","messageID":"msg_deb931a4c001JMEIH20MZupOkh","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation:\n- Current best fitness is 376.19 (vs baseline 301.04), and recent attempts have regressed or broken even.\n- The lessons show the core is near-saturated after r2s2 (JAL predictor), r3s0 (DSP consolidation), and r5s1 (DIV sequentialization).\n- r7s0 specifically warned against manual CSE of adders within EX stage.\n\nLet me check past experiments for pc+4-related work before proposing.","time":{"start":1777774091249,"end":1777774094549}}}
