{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774104893,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_014zrHK4LMFZtwBnTCmAQRZ9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep \"pc_plus\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -2","description":"Find pc_plus references"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor ex_stage.sv to compute two shared combinational signals\\nonce and reference them from every consumer:\\n\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_imm;   // single adder for branch/jump target\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_4;     // single adder for linear-advance paths\\n  assign pc_plus_imm = in.pc + in.imm;\\n  assign pc_plus_4   = in.pc + 32'd4;\\n\\nThen rewrite:\\n  branch_target = pc_plus_imm;\\n  jump_target   = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : pc_plus_imm;\\n\\n  reg_q.pc_next <= misalign_fault ? pc_plus_4\\n                 : in.ctrl.is_jump  ? jump_target\\n                 : branch_taken     ? branch_target\\n                                    : pc_plus_4;\\n\\nThis is a pure structural refactor with zero functional change \\u2014\\nevery output bit is bit-identical to the current implementation for\\nevery input vector. Consequently:\\n\\n  - RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps are unchanged (same value, same\\n    cycle, same register).\\n  - No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t payload bits added or removed\\n    (avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening synthesis penalty).\\n  - No new formal state; SBY BMC depth unchanged (per the r1s2 and\\n    r3s1 lessons on symbolic-fetch coupling \\u2014 this change doesn't\\n    touch fetch or predictor state at all).\\n  - No change to the EX\\u2192MEM handshake, div_busy, or the JAL\\n    predictor in if_stage.sv.\\n\\nExpected effect on Tang Nano 20K synthesis:\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+imm (branch_target + jump_target\\n    sharing), saving ~32 LUT4 of carry chain duplication.\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+4 (misalign-fault path + default\\n    pc_next sharing), saving another ~32 LUT4.\\n  - The pc_plus_imm wire is a single-source fanout to two mux legs\\n    (branch_target-select and jump_target-select) instead of two\\n    parallel adders racing to the same register input, shortening\\n    the critical-path slack on reg_q.pc_next.\\n\\nRisk profile:\\n  - Zero IPC impact (identical functional semantics).\\n  - Zero formal impact (same combinational output per input).\\n  - Zero invariant-1 (RVFI 2-channel) impact.\\n  - Only risk is that Yosys was already sharing these adders, in\\n    which case the RTL becomes cleaner but fitness is a wash. Even\\n    in that case the hypothesis strictly doesn't regress anything\\n    and documents the intent for future code readers. The LESSONS.md\\n    r6s0 note explicitly flags that Yosys sharing is NOT reliable\\n    for LUT-based datapaths across islands, which is the exact\\n    pattern here.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 364.26, \"delta_pct\": -3.17, \"vs_baseline\": 21.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 161.81, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5440, \"ff\": 1994, \"seeds\": [168.52, 158.33, 161.81], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:52:26.936440Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r7s0 (regression, -3.17%): Manually CSE'ing structurally-duplicated 32-bit adders (pc+imm across branch_target/jump_target; pc+4 across misalign-fault/default-pc_next/JAL-rd_wdata) in ex_stage.sv regressed fitness ~3% \\u2014 confirming that the r6s0 pattern generalizes beyond barrel shifters to ordinary adders on LUT4 fabrics: Yosys/nextpnr already share ripple-carry chains feeding a common mux cascade (the pc_next 4-way select was already collapsing in synthesis), so the hand-lifted `pc_plus_imm`/`pc_plus_4` wires introduce no new sharing but DO force a single-source high-fanout net feeding multiple mux legs across different always_comb blocks, which nextpnr routes with extra buffering/detour on Tang Nano 20K and lands worse on the EX critical path; the r3s0 DSP-consolidation heuristic is STRICTLY for hard primitives (DSP18, BSRAM, multipliers), and for LUT-only datapaths the empirical rule is \\\"don't manually CSE \\u2014 let the synth flow see the natural mux structure,\\\" with synth-report area diffs required before committing any structural-sharing refactor.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical op