{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774158764,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01FiYpTVa8gTS1ygKJEs4KiY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv","offset":45,"limit":35},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n45:   // pipeline payload.\n46:   //\n47:   // Misalignment caveat: RV32I requires PC to be 4-byte aligned. A JAL\n48:   // immediate has bit0 forced to zero but bit1 comes from instr[21] and\n49:   // can be 1, producing a 2-aligned target that must trap at EX. If we\n50:   // predict onto a misaligned address, the pc_fwd property breaks\n51:   // (next retirement's pc_rdata would be the misaligned PC, not the\n52:   // trap's pc+4 fallback). We therefore guard the predictor on the low\n53:   // two bits of the computed target being zero.\n54:   logic        is_jal_fetch;\n55:   logic [31:0] jal_imm;\n56:   logic [31:0] jal_target;\n57: \n58:   always_comb begin\n59:     jal_imm      = {{11{imem_data[31]}}, imem_data[31], imem_data[19:12],\n60:                     imem_data[20], imem_data[30:21], 1'b0};\n61:     jal_target   = pc + jal_imm;\n62:     is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)\n63:                    && !flush && !redirect\n64:                    && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);\n65: \n66:     next_pc = redirect     ? redirect_target\n67:             : is_jal_fetch ? jal_target\n68:                            : (pc + 32'd4);\n69:   end\n70: \n71:   // Redirect must override stall: a BRANCH/JAL/JALR in EX may fire\n72:   // redirect on the same cycle as imem_stall or dmem_stall — without\n73:   // this priority the redirect target would be silently dropped, the\n74:   // PC would hold its old (wrong-path) value, and execution would\n75:   // resume on the wrong path once the bus unstalls. Verified by the\n76:   // VexRiscv-binary CoreMark sweep with --istall enabled.\n77:   always_ff @(posedge clock) begin\n78:     if      (reset)    pc <= RESET_PC;\n79:     else if (redirect) pc <= redirect_target;\n\n(Showing lines 45-79 of 91. Use offset=80 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"  // pipeline payload.\n  //\n  // Misalignment caveat: RV32I requires PC to be 4-byte aligned. A JAL\n  // immediate has bit0 forced to zero but bit1 comes from instr[21] and\n  // can be 1, producing a 2-aligned target that must trap at EX. If we\n  // predict onto a misaligned address, the pc_fwd property breaks\n  // (next retirement's pc_rdata would be the misaligned PC, not the\n  // trap's pc+4 fallback). We therefore guard the predictor on the low\n  // two bits of the computed target being zero.\n  logic        is_jal_fetch;\n  logic [31:0] jal_imm;\n  logic [31:0] jal_target;\n\n  always_comb begin\n    jal_imm      = {{11{imem_data[31]}}, imem_data[31], imem_data[19:12],\n                    imem_data[20], imem_data[30:21], 1'b0};\n    jal_target   = pc + jal_imm;\n    is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)\n                   && !flush && !redirect\n                   && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/rtl/if_stage.sv","time":{"start":1777774158745,"end":1777774158763}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I see that r7s0 already explored intra-stage CSE for pc+4, but my cross-stage pipelining approach—registering pc+4 in the IF/ID stage—is structurally different, though it might run into the same routing issues the lesson flagged: a 32-bit signal fanning out to multiple consumers in the EX stage could create similar high-fanout problems on LUT fabrics.\n\nLet me step back and look for what's actually untried. The post-mortem rules out manual CSE entirely, so I need to think about what micro_opt territory remains. Looking at the documented outcomes—DSP consolidation, sequentializing cold operations, and the stateless predictor—I'm noticing something in the hazard logic: the div_busy signal from the divider FSM is combinational and fans out to five different stall signals across the pipeline. That's a high-fanout net that might be worth investigating as an optimization target.\n\nThe div_busy computation itself is fairly deep—it's gating together the divide operation decode, valid signal, done flag, and the internal busy state. What if I could register this signal one cycle earlier to break the combinational path? The div_busy_int is already registered from the FSM state, so the real issue is the complex gating logic around it. I'm thinking through whether I can simplify this to just track when the divider is in an active state versus idle or done, which would reduce the combinational depth feeding into the hazard unit.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the gating exists specifically to handle the transition from idle to done in a single cycle so the pipeline captures the result at the right time. A simpler formulation might be `state_q == S_BUSY || (state_q == S_IDLE && is_div_op && in.valid)`, which is logically equivalent but clearer—it directly expresses when the divider is busy: either it's already running, or it's starting a fresh divide. This probably saves a few LUT4s, though div_busy likely isn't a timing bottleneck anyway.\n\nLet me shift focus to a different optimization. Looking at the ALU with the consolidated multiplier, I notice the high-word multiply operations—MULH, MULHU, MULHSU—all produce the same output from mul_prod[63:32]. They're three identical case arms that Yosys will collapse during synthesis, but I could make it explicit by combining them into a single condition. Probably no real difference in the final netlist though.\n\nExamining the divider more closely, it holds about 40 flops when idle—remainder, quotient, divisor, counter, state, original dividend, and sign bits—all consuming power and area. The quotient register cleverly serves double duty as both the dividend being shifted out and the accumulator for the result, so there's not much room to consolidate there.\n\nLooking back at the instruction fetch stage, I'm seeing two separate 32-bit adders: one for pc+jal_imm and another for pc+4, both feeding into a mux for next_pc. I could potentially merge these by computing pc + (is_jal_valid ? jal_imm : 4) instead, though moving the mux to the adder input might not actually save area or improve timing.\n\nThe real issue is that deriving is_jal_fetch—checking the opcode and alignment—adds combinational depth before the mux, which then feeds the adder. That path becomes: opcode check → alignment check → mux select → mux → adder → PC register. That's worse timing than just running two adders in parallel, so I'm dropping this optimization.\n\nI need to pick something straightforward and safe that doesn't introduce structural sharing headaches.\n\nWhat if I register the DSP multiplier output internally using the GW2A's built-in pipeline registers? That could map the register inside the DSP tile with zero extra flop area and improve the multiply path's Fmax. But it adds a cycle to MUL latency, which breaks r7s1. Even with forwarding tricks, it's really just a 2-cycle multiply in disguise.\n\nGating the multiplier when it's not needed could save dynamic power—the DSP computes mul_prod every cycle even when the operation isn't a multiply. But the DSP area is fixed regardless, and the output doesn't hit the critical path if the mux bypasses it, so there's no timing win either.\n\nLet me focus on something concrete: the IF-stage JAL predictor's target-alignment check. Since PC is always 4-aligned in RV32I and JAL's immediate has bit 0 always zero by spec, I can simplify the alignment verification.\n\nInstead of computing the full jal_target and checking both bits, I can reduce it to just checking imem_data[21] directly—this removes the dependency on the adder's output bits and lets Yosys see is_jal_fetch as independent of the 32-bit adder, shortening the critical path to next_pc's mux. It's either a timing win or saves LUTs with no regression risk. The check is mathematically equivalent under the PC-alignment invariant that riscv-formal already maintains, and BMC should verify the invariant holds inductively from reset.\n\nBut now I'm worried about a formal correctness issue: if BMC somehow allows pc[1:0] to be non-zero, my simplified check (imem_data[21]==0) would only guard against misaligned targets when pc[1:0]=0, potentially letting a misaligned prediction slip through and break the alignment assumptions that riscv-formal relies on. The EX trap would catch the misaligned JAL, but then the PC would be misaligned and the next fetch wouldn't match the expected pc_rdata, violating the formal model's invariants.\n\nHowever, BMC starts from reset where pc=0, so by induction all reachable states maintain pc[1:0]=0. Even at depth 20, only reachable states are explored, so the alignment invariant holds throughout. Since riscv-formal uses BMC from reset (not k-induction with pre-assumed states), the simplification is sound.\n\nI'll apply the JAL-misalign simplification on the IF side—it's a low-risk, localized change that should be safe under the pc-alignment invariant.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb98e102001znNjqdj3fecwAL","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","messageID":"msg_deb98117e001rTCwY3HHl9VJaE"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774158861,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"id":"prt_deb98e0cb001jh27GDDs0cbIvZ","messageID":"msg_deb98117e001rTCwY3HHl9VJaE","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","type":"text","text":"The r7s0 failure is exactly the pc+4 CSE idea I was considering — confirming it won't work. I need a different angle.\n\nLet me look at the IF-stage JAL predictor more carefully for a micro-opt opportunity:","time":{"start":1777774158027,"end":1777774158858}}}
