{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774205231,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"id":"prt_deb991114001xpYUF9015u2vJ0","messageID":"msg_deb98e463001vwX9nlDMR6BgWC","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear target. The JAL predictor's `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` check depends on the 32-bit adder output and sits on the mux-select path feeding the PC register. Under RV32I's PC-alignment invariant (pc[1:0]=0 at reset, maintained by spec-compliant updates), and given `jal_imm[0]=0` (JAL J-immediate spec), the check simplifies to `imem_data[21]==0`.\n\nThis takes the 32-bit adder OFF the is_jal_fetch combinational path entirely — the predictor's mux-select becomes a single-bit decode of the raw instruction, independent of the adder. The adder still feeds the mux-data leg (jal_target), but that was always the timing-dominant path. Removing the adder from the select path is a pure Fmax win with no IPC/formal impact.","time":{"start":1777774170388,"end":1777774205230}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774205240,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_015NGApZ8V3qBRwHhYsJyRiM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r8s0\ntitle: \"IF-stage JAL predictor: decouple misalign-guard from 32-bit adder output\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The r2s2 stateless JAL predictor in if_stage.sv (the +5.87% win) gates\n  its fire signal `is_jal_fetch` on `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00`, where\n  `jal_target = pc + jal_imm`. That 2-bit equality is a post-adder\n  consumer, so the is_jal_fetch signal waits on the full 32-bit\n  `pc + jal_imm` carry chain before the next_pc mux-SELECT can resolve.\n  The mux-DATA leg (jal_target itself) obviously also waits on the\n  same adder, but mux-data and mux-select races both feed a single\n  LUT4 mux cell: whichever arrives last sets the arrival at the PC\n  flop. Today select = adder -> 2-bit compare -> AND-reduce is STRICTLY\n  LONGER than data = adder alone, so select is on the IF-stage\n  critical path.\n\n  This is NOT the r7s0/r6s0 \"manually CSE combinational wires\" pattern\n  that failed — no signals are shared across always_comb islands, no\n  pipeline-payload struct widens, no new registers appear, and no new\n  fanout nets are created. It's a local algebraic simplification\n  confined to one expression inside a single always_comb block, using\n  invariants RV32I already guarantees.\n\n  The RV32I invariants used:\n    (a) pc[1:0] == 2'b00 always (RV32I without C-ext: reset pc=0,\n        all redirects are EX-validated-aligned-or-trapped, pc+4\n        preserves alignment). Riscv-formal's pc_fwd/unique checks\n        inductively enforce this across all reachable states.\n    (b) jal_imm[0] == 0 always (JAL J-immediate encoding per ISA\n        spec: bit 0 is hardwired zero in the immediate-generator).\n\n  Given (a) and (b):\n    jal_target[0] = pc[0] XOR jal_imm[0] XOR 0 = 0 XOR 0 = 0\n    jal_target[1] = pc[1] XOR jal_imm[1] XOR carry_from_bit0\n                  = 0 XOR imem_data[21] XOR 0\n                  = imem_data[21]\n\n  Therefore `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` is algebraically equivalent\n  to `imem_data[21] == 1'b0` — a single-bit check directly off the\n  fetched instruction word, with zero dependence on the 32-bit adder.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the post-adder align guard in if_stage.sv's always_comb\n  block:\n\n      is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)\n                     && !flush && !redirect\n                     && (jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00);\n\n  with the pre-adder algebraic equivalent:\n\n      is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)\n                     && !flush && !redirect\n                     && (imem_data[21] == 1'b0);\n\n  No other RTL changes. The `jal_target = pc + jal_imm` wire and\n  the next_pc mux remain exactly as-is; only the align-guard leg of\n  the `is_jal_fetch` AND-reduction is re-sourced.\n\n  Why this helps Fmax on Tang Nano 20K:\n    - Before: `is_jal_fetch` waits on `pc + jal_imm` (32-bit CARRY\n      chain, ~6-10 LUT4-equivalent delays on GW2A) + a 2-bit OR\n      reduction + an AND with opcode/flush/redirect. Arrives LATE.\n    - After: `is_jal_fetch` depends only on imem_data[6:0],\n      imem_data[21], flush, and redirect — all available at cycle\n      start (imem_data is a module input, flush/redirect arrive\n      early). Arrives in ~2 LUT4 delays.\n    - The next_pc mux has `is_jal_fetch` as select and jal_target\n      (adder output) as data. Previously both waited on the adder\n      so the mux's \"worst input\" was bounded by the select chain\n      which was STRICTLY SLOWER than the data chain. After the\n      change, select is fast and data (jal_target) becomes the\n      worst input — but data is STRICTLY FASTER than the old\n      select because it skips the 2-bit compare + AND.\n    - Net: next_pc's arrival at the PC flop is shortened by the\n      2-bit compare + AND-reduction stages. On a path currently\n      limiting Fmax to ~167 MHz, this is a ~1-2 LUT4 depth\n      reduction.\n\n  Why this is safe:\n    - IPC unchanged: the predictor fires on the same set of\n      {valid JAL instructions with aligned targets} as before.\n      Every input pattern that used to fire still fires; every\n      pattern that used to NOT fire still doesn't. Proof: under\n      invariants (a)+(b), old condition <=> new condition, bit-exact.\n    - RVFI unchanged: same PC trajectory, same retirement order,\n      same pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps.\n    - Formal proof: riscv-formal pc_fwd/unique/liveness/insn_*\n      checks all pass under BMC from reset; pc[1:0]=0 holds\n      inductively in every reachable state explored by BMC, so the\n      algebraic equivalence holds throughout the proof window.\n    - No pipeline payload widening (no new id_ex_t / ex_mem_t\n      fields — avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 / r7s2 synthesis-penalty\n      trap).\n    - No cross-islands CSE (avoids the r6s0 / r7s0 high-fanout\n      routing regression). The adder's output wire loses ONE\n      consumer (the 2-bit compare); it still has its one primary\n      consumer (jal_target in the mux-data leg). Fanout actually\n      DECREASES by 2 fanout points.\n    - No stage-register probe changes — test_pipeline.py\n      (rollback-protected per r4s1) is untouched.\n    - No formal-wrapper changes — formal/wrapper.sv (don't-touch)\n      is untouched.\n\n  Expected fitness: small but real. The r2s2 retrospective noted\n  the JAL predictor is live on the IF critical path; shaving 2 LUT4\n  depths off is a clean ~1-3% Fmax win on Tang Nano 20K. IPC\n  unchanged (CoreMark's dynamic JAL mix is identical). LUT count\n  drops by the 2-bit compare + AND gate cells, a minor LUT4 savings\n  of ~2-4 cells. Low downside: worst case is Yosys was already\n  constant-folding `{0,0,0,imem_data[21],0}[1:0] == 00` to\n  `!imem_data[21]` via bit-level propagation on the adder-sum sliced\n  low-2, in which case fitness is a wash but the RTL is cleaner\n  and correctness-documented.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      In the single always_comb block that drives is_jal_fetch and\n      next_pc, replace the `(jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00)` term of the\n      `is_jal_fetch` AND-reduction with `(imem_data[21] == 1'b0)`.\n      Keep jal_imm, jal_target, and the next_pc mux exactly as they\n      are — jal_target still feeds the mux-data leg of next_pc.\n      Update the adjacent block comment (the \"Misalignment caveat:\"\n      paragraph on lines ~47-53) to note the algebraic\n      simplification: under RV32I pc-alignment and jal_imm[0]=0,\n      jal_target[1:0]==2'b00 reduces to imem_data[21]==0, so the\n      guard no longer needs the 32-bit adder output. Verify by\n      running the full cocotb suite (test_pipeline, test_rvfi,\n      test_decoder) — no retirement trace should change, since the\n      predictor fires on exactly the same input set. Verify formal\n      by running `make formal` — all insn_*_ch0, pc_fwd, unique,\n      liveness, causal checks should pass with the same outcome\n      (DONE/PREUNSAT) as the r7s2 baseline.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777774205227,"end":1777774205238}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm realizing the condition can be simplified significantly—since the program counter is always 4-aligned and the JAL immediate's lowest bit is always zero by specification, the check really just depends on whether bit 21 of the instruction is zero. Now I need to formulate a focused hypothesis that makes one minimal change to fix this.\n\nLooking at the full IF critical path, the 32-bit adder feeds both the mux data and the select signal through a 2-bit alignment check. If I move the alignment check to depend directly on the instruction bits instead, the select signal becomes independent of the adder, splitting the critical path into two branches that reconverge at the mux. The adder-to-mux path would then dominate, eliminating those extra logic levels from the critical path and saving roughly 600 picoseconds on this architecture.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb991880001fc5PsoWbyYiU40","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","messageID":"msg_deb98e463001vwX9nlDMR6BgWC"}}
