{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774212525,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","part":{"id":"prt_deb99a56c0017f3WVfpxoptYkZ","messageID":"msg_deb99997a00182lxlKGCyQ2IU8","sessionID":"ses_2146ce5f7ffeFL543GiHz4SSM3","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: A targeted local simplification of the IF-stage JAL predictor's misalign guard.\n\n- **Observation**: `is_jal_fetch` currently ANDs with `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00`, which depends on the 32-bit `pc + jal_imm` adder output plus a 2-bit compare + AND — this sits on the mux-select path driving PC and is strictly longer than the mux-data (adder alone) path, so it's IF-stage critical.\n- **Algebraic reduction**: Under RV32I invariants (pc[1:0]=0 always, jal_imm[0]=0 by spec), `jal_target[1:0] == 2'b00` ≡ `imem_data[21] == 0`. A single-bit, adder-independent check.\n- **Why this avoids the r7s0/r6s0 traps**: No cross-islands CSE wire, no pipeline-payload widening, no new fanout nets, no stage-register probe changes. Just one expression replacement inside one always_comb — adder-output fanout actually *decreases* by losing one consumer.\n- **Risk profile**: Low. Bit-exact equivalence under documented invariants; worst case is Yosys was already bit-level folding it and fitness is a wash.","time":{"start":1777774208364,"end":1777774212521}}}
