{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777775177355,"sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_017R9gp6DPuvFuM4HVaAtVJ8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses</path>\n<type>directory</type>\n<entries>\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r4s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r5s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r6s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r4s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r6s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r9s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r4s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r5s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r6s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r7s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r8s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r9s2.log\n\n(27 entries)\n</entries>","metadata":{"preview":".agent.hyp-20260502-001-r1s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r2s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r3s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r4s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r5s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r6s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r7s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r8s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r4s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r6s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-002-r9s1.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.log\n.agent.hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.log","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses","time":{"start":1777775177340,"end":1777775177354}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the optimization opportunities for the cores/bench directory. The key wins come from architectural simplifications: decoupling the multiplexer select from the adder's carry chain using ISA invariants gained us nearly 6%, consolidating DSP operations into a single multiplier added another 8.5%, and there's a partial third optimization I'm still evaluating.\n\nThe manual CSE attempts and wider RAS/BTB paths actually regressed performance, and the load-use forwarding broke formal verification, so those are dead ends. The ID-stage branch resolution is now the bottleneck.\n\nLooking at what's left to optimize, the current fitness is really constrained by Fmax times IPC. The execute stage is critical—the ALU result feeds both the EX/MEM register and the forwarding path back to execute, and it's multiplexed with the jump PC calculation and division result. The memory stage has its own path through the load shifter and byte masking logic, while the fetch stage already benefited from the r8s0 optimization.\n\nI'm thinking about whether that r8s0 pattern—where a post-adder guard that controls the mux select can be rewritten as a slice of an input signal using architectural invariants—applies elsewhere. Let me check the memory stage misalignment logic...\n\nExamining misalignment detection... The jump mux selects between `pc+4` and the ALU output based on `is_jump`, which is already a registered control signal from the ID/EX stage, so that's not a bottleneck. I'm looking for other optimization opportunities across the pipeline. The ALU itself computes all operations through a full 32-bit priority mux, which creates significant fanout. For the workload CoreMark runs—memory access, arithmetic, shifts, multiplies, and branches—I should examine whether the register file write-port logic or ALU operations can be consolidated. The `x0` guard and read bypass in the register file don't seem critical, but I'm wondering if there's more sharing possible in the ALU's ADD, SUB, and shift operations.\n\nYosys likely handles resource-sharing automatically, so manual optimization there won't help. The sign-extension muxes for the multiplier use narrow comparisons on the 5-bit opcode, which should be fine. The load data path is interesting though—the dynamic shifter followed by width-based selection and sign-extension could potentially be restructured to reduce the critical path by combining those stages more efficiently. The redirect signal path from EX to IF is critical — branch resolution has to propagate through the forwarding muxes, comparator, and target computation all the way to the PC mux in the same cycle. I'm wondering if the misalign_fault check is adding unnecessary delay; since branch targets from PC + immediate should naturally have bit 0 = 0 by encoding, maybe I can simplify that logic path.\n\nFor JALR specifically, the jump target gets forced to an even address anyway, so I need to figure out whether bit 1 of the result depends on a carry from the lower bits or if it's just a direct XOR of the source operands.\n\nNow I'm working through the JAL case more carefully. The IF-stage predictor only redirects on JAL when bit 21 of the instruction is 0, meaning the target is guaranteed aligned. So a misaligned-target JAL (where bit 21 is 1) doesn't get predicted in IF—it flows through the pipeline linearly. When it reaches EX, the redirect signal only fires for branches or JALR instructions, not for JAL. So a mispredicted misaligned JAL would keep executing sequentially unless the misalignment fault itself triggers a trap, which sets the illegal flag and prevents writeback.\n\nFor the branch target misalignment check, I can optimize by recognizing that `branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00` is equivalent to checking `instr[8]` directly. The low bits of the adder result don't involve carry-in from higher bits—`branch_target[0]` is just `pc[0] XOR imm[0]`, and `branch_target[1]` depends only on `pc[1]`, `imm[1]`, and a carry that's zero since both `pc[0]` and `imm[0]` are zero. So I can replace the misalignment check with a direct reference to the instruction bit, saving logic on the critical path.\n\nFor JALR, the misalignment depends on `rs1[1] XOR imm[1] XOR (rs1[0] AND imm[0])`, which is simpler than a full comparison but still tied to the register value. For JAL, the target's bit 1 comes directly from the instruction encoding at position 21, so that's also a direct lookup rather than an adder result.\n\nBy extracting these conditions separately—branch misalignment from `instr[8]`, JALR misalignment from the XOR chain on rs1 and imm, and JAL misalignment from `instr[21]`—I can break the critical path dependency on the full adder outputs. The original code had to compute the complete branch and jump targets just to check if bits [1:0] were nonzero, but now the misalignment fault can be determined much earlier without waiting for those wide adders to settle. The core idea is to replace post-adder low-bit checks with direct instruction-bit lookups, leveraging architectural invariants like PC always being 4-byte aligned and immediate encodings being fixed. I need to verify the algebraic equivalence carefully: B-immediate bit 1 maps to `instr[8]`, J-immediate bit 1 to `instr[21]`, and for JALR the low bit is forced to zero while bit 1 comes from the adder's bit 1 output. Formal verification should confirm this preserves bit-exact semantics since we're just rerouting the same information through a faster path. I'm extracting the immediate bits directly from the instruction encoding—imm[0] comes from instr[20] and imm[1] from instr[21]—so the misalignment check stays mathematically identical while bypassing the full adder on the critical path. This cuts down gate delays for the redirect suppression and reduces LUT usage, with medium confidence in a 3-5% performance gain.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deba8698300186Q6rZz2c6a1yP","sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","messageID":"msg_deba746b1001w0U6bfN517A5ja"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777775177358,"sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","part":{"id":"prt_deba866a7001Fcl1R37SyW060b","messageID":"msg_deba746b1001w0U6bfN517A5ja","sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent successful improvements, particularly r8s0 (+5.99% — algebraic pre-adder simplification for JAL predictor's alignment guard), and noting the meta-rule \"look for post-adder guards that gate the mux SELECT feeding the same adder's mux DATA,\" I see a direct application in ex_stage.sv's misalign-trap detection.","time":{"start":1777775175335,"end":1777775177357}}}
