{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777775200128,"sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EmrsvdW757SCAhKjJoeKQc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-001-r9s0\ntitle: \"Algebraic pre-adder simplification of EX-stage misalign-trap guards\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  r8s0 (+5.99%) proved that replacing post-adder low-bit alignment guards\n  with direct instruction-bit checks using RV32I architectural invariants\n  shortens the mux SELECT path, decouples fanout from the 32-bit adder\n  carry chain, and passes formal cleanly. The IF-stage JAL predictor was\n  the first consumer of that trick. An identical pattern lives at the\n  EX-stage redirect path: `misalign_branch = is_branch && branch_taken &&\n  (branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` and `misalign_jump = is_jump &&\n  (jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` both gate `redirect` (which drives the\n  PC-load signal to IF, a Fmax-critical cross-stage net) with post-adder\n  low-bit checks. On Tang Nano 20K the EX→IF redirect path is where\n  branch-resolution timing closes or fails, so cutting adder dependence\n  from the misalign guard is high-leverage. Meta-rule audit: r6s0/r7s0\n  showed manual CSE regresses, but r8s0's algebraic rewrite (confined to\n  one always_comb expression, no new cross-island wires, no payload\n  widening, adder fanout *decreases*) is the exception — this proposal\n  replicates that exception in a different stage.\nhypothesis: |\n  In ex_stage.sv, rewrite `misalign_branch` and `misalign_jump` using the\n  following RV32I-invariant derivations (bit-exact preserving):\n\n    pc[1:0] = 2'b00 always (inductively enforced by riscv-formal pc_fwd).\n    B-imm[0] = 0 (hardwired in imm_gen for B-type).\n    B-imm[1] = instr[8] (from B-type encoding).\n    J-imm[0] = 0 (hardwired in imm_gen for J-type).\n    J-imm[1] = instr[21] (from J-type encoding).\n    I-imm[0] = instr[20] (for JALR).\n    I-imm[1] = instr[21] (for JALR).\n    JALR's jump_target forces bit 0 to zero; bit 1 = jalr_sum[1].\n\n  Therefore:\n    branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00\n      == branch_target[1]\n      == pc[1] ^ B-imm[1] ^ (pc[0] & B-imm[0])\n      == 0    ^ instr[8]  ^ (0 & 0)\n      == instr[8]\n\n    For JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr):\n      jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00 == instr[21]\n\n    For JALR (is_jalr):\n      jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00 == jalr_sum[1]\n        == rs1[1] ^ I-imm[1] ^ (rs1[0] & I-imm[0])\n        == rs1[1] ^ instr[21] ^ (rs1[0] & instr[20])\n      (rs1 here is the post-forward value already feeding the adder.)\n\n  The resulting expressions use only `in.instr[8]`, `in.instr[21]`,\n  `in.instr[20]`, and rs1[1:0] (2-bit AND + 3-way XOR for JALR) — no\n  32-bit adder dependence. The misalign check becomes ~3-4 LUT4s instead\n  of a 2-bit-compare driven by the adder output's low bits. `redirect`\n  is still `(branch_taken || is_jalr) && !misalign_fault`, and\n  `redirect_target = is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target` is unchanged\n  (the adder result still feeds PC DATA, just not the SELECT guard).\n  `reg_q.pc_next`'s trap-fallback mux SELECT also narrows to the\n  shortened guard, paying dividends on the RVFI pc_wdata path.\n\n  This is a pure algebraic rewrite — every trap decision is bit-exact\n  equivalent to the original for every legal rs1/imm/pc combination.\n  Formal should pass unchanged (SBY's BMC state space is unaffected,\n  cone of influence actually shrinks for the misalign checks). Expected\n  win: 3-5% fitness from Fmax-bound Tang Nano 20K where the EX-to-IF\n  redirect path is tight, following r8s0's ~+6% trajectory for the\n  structurally analogous IF-stage rewrite.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Rewrite misalign_branch and misalign_jump using algebraic identities from RV32I encoding invariants: branch_target[1]==instr[8]; JAL jump_target[1]==instr[21]; JALR jump_target[1]==rs1[1]^instr[21]^(rs1[0]&instr[20]). This decouples the misalign_fault gate (which feeds redirect and pc_next's trap-fallback mux SELECT) from the branch_target/jump_target 32-bit adder carry chain. Preserves bit-exact trap semantics for every input combination. Uses post-forward rs1 (already local in always_comb) and id_ex.instr bits (already clocked into ID/EX register). No pipeline payload changes, no new cross-island wires, no formal state-space expansion.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777775200120,"end":1777775200127}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deba8754e001i4CwN1nfHLcXSd","sessionID":"ses_21458b986fferCNcvh1YBI4kP0","messageID":"msg_deba86ed0001F0OIqHI4CmoJUy"}}
