{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777775920737,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","part":{"id":"prt_debb3c65d001ldsPayrFGbPH3r","messageID":"msg_debb3b369001gULIrw9Ebm3pGC","sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","snapshot":"093a020381749dcfb40067bf68ad8c15a40af4c6","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777776087958,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","part":{"id":"prt_debb64517001IR8Od7HyN0Fdyn","messageID":"msg_debb3b369001gULIrw9Ebm3pGC","sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent history and lessons, let me analyze what structural angles remain viable:\n\n1. **Load-use bubble elimination (r8s1)** — broken formally due to incomplete trap-surface replication at the forwarding point. The lesson explicitly prescribes the fix: \"replicate mem_stage's COMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic (misalign + OoB + any other fault) at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\"\n\n2. **IF-stage next_pc mux widening** — saturated, any new leg costs Fmax (r8s2).\n\n3. **ID-stage early branch resolution** — saturated in both wide (r6s2) and narrow (r7s2) forms.\n\n4. **DSP/adder CSE** — r3s0 DSP already consolidated; manual adder CSE regresses (r7s0).\n\nThe cleanest structural opportunity remaining is the r8s1 retry with explicit mem_misalign replication at the forward site. The trap surface in mem_stage is precisely `mem_op && ((width==2 && addr[1:0]!=0) || (width==1 && addr[0]!=0))` — a compact, fully-replicable formula. OoB is sim-level, not RTL, so there's no additional fault to replicate.","time":{"start":1777776084247,"end":1777776087956}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777776087993,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_013hXjoTZqCNPK9jiqDnHBWq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypotheses directory exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses directory exists","time":{"start":1777776087978,"end":1777776087991}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent attempts, I'm seeing a pattern of failures across different optimization strategies—the combinational load forwarding broke formal verification, the RAS addition caused significant regression, the algebraic pre-adder also broke formal, and the pre-register WB mux attempt was cut short. I need to figure out what structural changes might actually work without introducing these kinds of regressions.\n\nThe successful optimizations point toward a clear direction: hard primitive consolidation like DSP18 and sequentializing operations that aren't hot in the workload like division. The divider's 34-cycle latency doesn't matter for CoreMark since it barely uses division, so the real question is whether there's area savings to be had there. The register file is another angle—I tried LUTRAM inference before and it failed, but I'm wondering if splitting it into separate banks per read port could help timing, though that would double the flops. The IF stage's PC+4 adder and the 3-way next_pc mux are also potential targets, especially since the mux width has been a binding constraint before.\n\nLooking at the EX stage's critical path—forwarding mux feeding into the ALU with its 33×33 multiplier, then branch resolution and the PC mux before the flop—this seems like where the real bottleneck is. The ALU itself is one massive combinational block with many parallel operations feeding into a single mux, which Yosys might resource-share but that's not helping timing. I already know from r7s1 that pipelining the multiplier failed because CoreMark actually hits MUL heavily, so that's not the move. The MEM stage's load path is also sequential—byte-lane masking, misalignment checks, data shifting and sign-extension all depend on the dmem read result, so there's inherent latency there that's hard to optimize around. → EX/MEM flop.\n\nLet me consider other structural optimizations. I could dedicate a single-direction shifter with input reversal, but that already regressed in r6s0. Pipelining the ALU across two cycles is essentially what r7s1 tried for multiplication and it hurt performance. A sequential multiplier would also regress CoreMark since MUL is frequently used. I'm thinking about reducing the fanout from alu_result since it drives so many consumers, or precomputing the dmem address to shorten the address-to-memory path. Another angle is splitting the register file into two separate banks to halve the fanout per array, though that doubles the flip-flop count. I could also try registering pc+4 ahead of time rather than computing it combinationally in the IF stage, but that adds latency. Similarly, pre-registering the hazard and forwarding unit outputs would help but costs a cycle.\n\nLooking at the hard primitives available on the Tang Nano 20K—DSP18 for multiplication is already consolidated to one, and the BSRAM is external to the core. The SSRAM attempt in r5s0 failed. The divider uses a carry-chain for its 33-bit subtractor, which isn't huge in area. Since frequency improvements are plateauing across multiple attempts, I need to focus on IPC gains instead. The real question is what instruction-level parallelism wins are still available beyond the branch prediction and resolution attempts that already failed.\n\nThe load-use bubble from r8s1 is a 1-cycle penalty that matters in pointer-chasing workloads like CoreMark, but fixing it requires replicating the entire trap surface at the forwarding point—doable but complex. Another angle is whether we can flatten the decoder's case statement into a lookup-table style routing, though that's more of a micro-optimization. The more structural idea would be merging the ID and EX stages into a combined ID/EX stage to eliminate the pipeline register between them.\n\nRemoving the EX/MEM register entirely could allow same-cycle LOAD-to-use, but the combinational path through ALU output to memory byte masking and address generation would likely violate timing. The branch comparators are already running in parallel to the ALU in the EX stage, so that's not a bottleneck. Precomputing the branch target in the IF stage by carrying pc + B-imm through the pipeline could help reduce branch latency.\n\nI'm exploring whether I can compute branch_target earlier in the ID stage where I have both the PC and decoded immediate, then register it into the ID/EX pipeline stage as a dedicated field instead of the general immediate field—though this widens the payload and costs area. Pre-decoding simple opcode classes like is_branch, is_mem, is_jump at the IF stage could help hazard and forwarding logic react faster, but again payload widening is a concern. The divider is cold code, so optimizing it with a radix-2 non-restoring algorithm won't yield much. Looking at the MEM/WB register, many fields like rs1_val, rs2_val, and pc are only needed for RVFI compliance, but they have to stay for formal verification.\n\nThe RVFI-only fields could theoretically be gated under ifdef for synthesis, but the top-level core.sv can't change its IO shape, and the FPGA flow through CoreBench.sv probably doesn't even connect those RVFI outputs—they're dead code that synthesis tools should already be pruning anyway. So that's not a real win. I'm thinking about restructuring the decoder's massive case statement into something more like a PLA lookup to reduce area.\n\nActually, a cleaner structural approach might be duplicating the register file into two separate arrays—one for each read port. Instead of a single 32-entry array with two combinational readers, I'd have regs_a and regs_b both written identically but each serving its own read path. This could shorten the decode tree on each port and potentially reduce LUT usage, though it doubles the flip-flop count. The tradeoff is whether synthesis is already doing this optimization implicitly or if making it explicit helps. It's a bit speculative, but worth considering against other options.\n\nNow looking at the MEM stage, there's a combinational chain where misalignment detection gates the memory write and read enables. Pre-computing misalignment in EX and registering it into the pipeline would clean up that path, but it costs a payload bit. The real question is whether we're still chasing Fmax or if IPC is the limiting factor now—we're already at 177 MHz versus a 135 MHz target, so maybe the load-use bubble is where the real gains are.\n\nThe key is to eliminate that bubble through combinational forwarding from MEM back to EX, but only if we replicate the trap surface correctly. I need to compute the effective register write signal in MEM (gating out misaligned loads) and expose both the loaded data and that write-enable combinationally to the forwarding logic. Then in EX, I route this as a fourth forwarding source through the existing mux, which means the hazard unit can stop stalling on load-use dependencies. The tricky part is making sure the trap conditions—misalignment based on address alignment and memory width—are faithfully reproduced at the forwarding point so we never forward invalid data. Out-of-bounds checking isn't actually enforced by the core itself; it's a simulation harness constraint, so I only need to worry about misalignment. So the core doesn't trap on OoB, meaning the only trap in mem_stage is mem_misalign. Replicating that at the forwarding point should be tractable, but r8s1 broke formal even with careful replication — the issue is that the forwarded value's provenance diverges from what eventually gets written to the regfile, making the formal equality check unsatisfiable.\n\nThe fix is to compute the exact same trap predicate at the forwarding point and gate the forward identically. If a LOAD traps, reg_write gets cleared and no write happens, so a dependent shouldn't forward from it — it should read the old regfile value instead. I'm working through the forwarding logic: only forward from an EX/MEM load if it's not trapped and reg_write is valid, but this adds a combinational path from memory through shifting, sign-extension, the forward mux, and into the ALU that could kill Fmax. The tradeoff is whether eliminating the load-use bubble (maybe 5-15% of cycles in pointer-walk code) justifies the timing risk, especially given that r8s1 already failed formally. I'm considering a safer structural approach instead: duplicating the register file into dedicated read banks for rs1 and rs2. Looking at the EX stage critical path more carefully, the multiplier feeding into the EX/MEM flop is likely the bottleneck. The DSP18 primitive has internal pipeline registers that might not be getting inferred, so I could try explicitly registering the multiplier output to let the DSP18's built-in registers do the heavy lifting instead of relying on synthesis to figure it out.\n\nBut r7s1 already experimented with a 2-cycle multiplier and it regressed performance, so that's probably not the answer.\n\nThe divider's shift-subtract logic is another candidate—converting from restoring to non-restoring division could reduce LUT usage in the subtractor, though the gains would be marginal since the divider runs for 32 cycles and stalls the pipeline anyway.\n\nThe real insight is about the load-use bubble. The current forwarding path routes through the post-trap-gated MEM/WB payload, which means the bubble exists because the LOAD instruction hasn't completed its trap/fault checking yet when the dependent instruction needs the result.\n\nI could try forwarding earlier from the combinational load data, but that requires replicating all of mem_stage's trap logic at the forwarding point—a risky approach. A cleaner alternative might be to leverage the DSP block's built-in output register for the multiplier: instead of an explicit FSM, just instruct Yosys to use the DSP's registered output, making MUL 2-cycle with no extra LUT cost. The tradeoff is a 1-cycle stall for multiply operations, but the register is already there in the hardware.\n\nHowever, r7s1 already tried this with a manual FSM and saw significant IPC regression despite potential Fmax gains—the multiply stall cost outweighs the frequency benefit. I'm also considering a 2-stage sequential shifter to split the barrel shifter path, but shifts are common in CoreMark workloads, so the IPC hit would likely be worse than any Fmax improvement. That leaves me thinking about register file duplication as a structural option, though I'm not highly confident. Actually, I should examine the hazard_unit path more carefully—all the stall signals fan out to IF, ID, EX, and MEM stages, and the stall_if signal gates the instruction fetch.\n\nLooking at the EX/MEM register logic, I notice both pc_next and alu_result consume pc + 4, and jump/branch targets also reuse pc + imm calculations. But r7s0 showed that manual CSE of adders causes regressions, so I shouldn't try to optimize that. Pre-computing pc + 4 in the decode stage and registering it separately would reduce EX pressure, but the payload widening cost would likely negate any benefit.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the ID/EX register already carries many fields that just pass through to MEM/WB for RVFI, so adding one more field might not increase flops if synthesis prunes unused logic. But that's different from r7s0's issue, which was CSE within EX itself.\n\nThe real question is whether pc + 4 is even on the critical path. The 32-bit adder is relatively small, and without synthesis logs I'm just guessing—the actual bottleneck is probably the multiplier chain. Pipelining the DSP18 multiplier output through Yosys's DSP inference to use the built-in register would convert MUL into a 2-cycle operation, but r7s1 already showed that 2-cycle MUL regresses due to IPC cost, so that's a dead end.\n\nI'm going to go with register file duplication—it's structurally sound, low-risk formally since it doesn't change pipeline semantics, and could give a moderate area or Fmax win if synthesis isn't already doing it. Even if it's neutral, it's unlikely to hurt. I considered splitting imm_gen into stages or pre-computing immediates in the decoder, but that would require duplicating the case statement and isn't clearly better. I also looked at folding the divider's DONE state into the last BUSY cycle to save one cycle per divide, but DIV is cold enough that it won't move CoreMark, so it's not worth the complexity. Registering the shift amount won't actually help since the BRAM output still needs to feed the barrel shifter combinationally. Let me go back to load-use bubble elimination with proper trap replication — that's where the real win is. I'll expose the combinational load result and a valid signal from mem_stage, then add a fourth forwarding source in the forward unit that prioritizes the load data over the M/WB path, carefully replicating the misalignment fault at the forward point to avoid the formal verification issues I hit before.\n\nNow I'm realizing the key issue: when there's a LOAD in EX/MEM, I can't just forward ex_mem.alu_result because that contains the address, not the loaded value. The actual data only appears in mem_wb after the memory stage completes. So I need to distinguish between LOAD and non-LOAD instructions in the forwarding logic — for LOADs, forward the combinational load_data_comb directly from mem_stage; for everything else, forward the ALU result as before. This means updating the forward unit to check if the instruction in EX/MEM is a memory read and handle it separately.\n\nUpdating the forward unit logic... The key insight is that by gating the forward on `!ex_mem_misalign`, I'm matching mem_stage's gating of reg_write bit-for-bit, which cleanly avoids the r8s1 failure mode. For non-misaligned LOADs, I forward the combinational load data; for misaligned LOADs, the dependent reads the old regfile value since the LOAD doesn't write rd. The tradeoff is a potential Fmax hit: dmem_rdata now flows combinationally through load_data_comb extraction, the forward mux, and into the ALU in a single cycle instead of being split across two. However, since BRAM reads are typically registered and the extraction logic (4:1 mux plus sign-extend) is relatively cheap at around 3 LUT4 levels, this should be manageable on the Tang Nano 20K. els. Forward mux is ~2 LUT4 levels. ALU is variable — worst case MUL's DSP which has its own delay.\n\nSo the added combinational depth is ~5 LUT4 levels. On a 5.6ns period, is this sustainable? Hard to say without measurement.\n\nGiven r8s1 broke formal (not Fmax), the formal fix might actually open up this IPC win if Fmax holds.\n\nOK I'll propose this. The key differentiator from r8s1 is the CORRECT trap-surface replication at the forward point: `ex_mem_misalign` computed from ex_mem_w.alu_result[1:0] and ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_width, matching mem_stage's `mem_misalign` bit-for-bit.\n\nWait, I realize there's another subtlety. ex_stage computes `misalign_fault` for branches/jumps and gates ctrl_with_trap.reg_write. mem_stage computes `mem_misalign` and gates ctrl_with_trap.reg_write again. So the EX/MEM register's ctrl.reg_write already has misalign_fault for branches/jumps gated out. The remaining gating happens in mem_stage for loads/stores misalign.\n\nSo at the forward point, we need:\n- ex_mem.ctrl.reg_write (already gated for branch/jump misalign)\n- AND for LOADs: also !mem_misalign(ex_mem.alu_result, ex_mem.ctrl.mem_width)\n\nThat's what we need.\n\nBut I also need to gate on valid — if EX/MEM has a LOAD with valid=0 (a stalled bubble), load_data_comb is garbage. The core lesson from r8s1 is that any zero-bubble load-use scheme must replicate mem_stage's complete trap and reg_write gating logic bit-for-bit at the forwarding point, or else accept the existing 1-cycle stall and chase IPC elsewhere. I'm committing to the replication path and need to enumerate the full trap surface: memory operations, misalignment checks based on width and address, and any other faults that gate reg_write in mem_stage. I'm working through whether the combinational forwarding actually creates a feedback loop—it doesn't, since the address bits come from a registered signal in the prior cycle. The r8s1 failure was probably something else entirely, like incomplete valid gating or wrong register forwarding. I'm confident enough in the approach to move forward: replicate the trap gating at the forward point, add combinational load forwarding, and remove the load-use stall, expecting a modest performance gain.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debb64fe2001z5x0AvQIzjh69J","sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","messageID":"msg_debb3b369001gULIrw9Ebm3pGC"}}
