{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777776129886,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01G7GLncFU3vkF8Nhx7shh2f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r10s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r10s1\ntitle: \"Zero-bubble load-use via MEM->EX combinational forward with bit-exact misalign-trap replication\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The load-use bubble remains the largest untapped structural IPC opportunity\n  on this microarchitecture. CoreMark's pointer-walk, matrix, and CRC kernels\n  all execute dependent LW->ALU/BRANCH sequences where the consumer must wait\n  one cycle for the LOAD to clear MEM/WB before MEM/WB->EX forwarding can\n  fire. Branch-prediction IPC is saturated (r2s2 JAL predictor + r6s2/r7s2\n  proved ID-resolution is a dead end), and Fmax is 177 MHz vs a 135 MHz target\n  so there's also headroom to trade a little combinational depth for an IPC\n  win. The r8s1 post-mortem prescribed the exact fix: \"replicate mem_stage's\n  COMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\"\n  r8s1 went broken (not regression) - formal broke due to a trap-surface\n  mismatch between the forward-mux gate and mem_stage's actual reg_write\n  suppression, NOT due to any inherent incompatibility with the microarch.\n  OoB is sim-enforced, not RTL - so the complete trap surface on the load-\n  result path is just the compact mem_misalign predicate.\nhypothesis: |\n  Eliminate the load-use pipeline bubble by adding a fourth combinational\n  forwarding source in forward_unit sourced from mem_stage's pre-flop\n  load_data path, and remove the load-use stall from hazard_unit.\n\n  Concretely:\n\n  (1) mem_stage exposes two new module outputs:\n      - load_data_comb (32b): the sign/zero-extended load result, identical\n        formula to the one that currently flops into mem_wb.read_data.\n      - load_fwd_ok (1b): asserts when the LOAD in EX/MEM will actually\n        write its rd this cycle's next edge. Bit-exact to the mem_stage\n        reg_write gate:\n          load_fwd_ok = in.valid\n                     && in.ctrl.mem_read\n                     && in.ctrl.reg_write\n                     && (in.rd != 5'b0)\n                     && !mem_misalign\n        where mem_misalign uses the identical expression already in\n        mem_stage (mem_op && width/addr combinations).\n\n  (2) forward_unit gains a new select encoding 2'd3 = LOAD_COMB. Priority\n      (younger wins, x0 never forwards):\n        LOAD in EX/MEM (load_fwd_ok && rd==rs?) -> 2'd3\n        non-LOAD in EX/MEM (reg_write && rd==rs? && !mem_read) -> 2'd1\n        MEM/WB (reg_write && rd==rs?) -> 2'd2\n        else -> 2'd0\n      The \"non-LOAD in EX/MEM\" arm gains an explicit `!mem_read` guard so\n      we never forward the LOAD's effective-address as if it were an ALU\n      result (that's the class of bug the current scheme avoids by stalling).\n\n  (3) ex_stage's fwd mux adds the 2'd3 case sourcing the new\n      mem_stage.load_data_comb wire.\n\n  (4) hazard_unit's load_use_hazard term is DELETED (set to 1'b0). Every\n      other stall source (imem_stall / dmem_stall / div_busy / redirect)\n      stays intact. This means id_ex_mem_read and id_ex_rd become unused;\n      drop those ports from hazard_unit or tie them with lint-off.\n\n  (5) Trap-path guarantee: on a misaligned LOAD, load_fwd_ok is low\n      (identical mem_misalign formula as mem_stage's reg_write gate), so\n      the forward never fires, the dependent reads the stale regfile\n      value (the correct pre-LOAD value since the LOAD won't write), and\n      mem_stage propagates ctrl.reg_write=0 to MEM/WB the next cycle -\n      matching exactly what the non-forwarded path would have produced\n      one cycle later after the now-removed load-use stall. The RVFI\n      reg_check's rd_wdata vs regfile-write equality holds on both\n      trap and non-trap LOADs.\n\n  Fmax cost analysis: the new combinational chain is\n    dmem_rdata (BRAM-registered, fast at cycle start)\n     -> shift-extract (2 LUT4 levels, 4:1 mux + halfword/byte slice)\n     -> sign-extend (1 LUT4 level)\n     -> forward mux (1 LUT4 level, now 4:1 instead of 3:1)\n     -> ALU a/b input\n     -> ALU (existing path)\n     -> EX/MEM flop\n  vs the old chain which stopped at the MEM/WB flop after sign-extend.\n  Net added depth: ~3-4 LUT4 levels upstream of the existing ALU cone.\n  On Tang Nano 20K at 5.6ns period and 177 MHz current Fmax, expect\n  Fmax to drop ~10-20 MHz worst case. CoreMark IPC uplift from removing\n  load-use bubble is estimated 4-8% on pointer-heavy kernels (load-use\n  hazard rate ~5-10% of instructions in CoreMark's list/matrix workload),\n  net fitness expected positive but not certain.\n\n  Divergence from r8s1: r8s1's post-mortem blamed incomplete trap-gating.\n  This hypothesis makes the trap-gate predicate LITERALLY the same\n  SystemVerilog expression in both mem_stage (driving ctrl_with_trap.\n  reg_write) and the forward-unit input (driving load_fwd_ok) by\n  instantiating mem_misalign once inside mem_stage and exposing the\n  result, rather than recomputing it. This removes any chance of a\n  subtle formula mismatch that could have caused r8s1's reg_ch0 to\n  PREUNSAT.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Expose load_data_comb and load_fwd_ok as new module outputs. load_data_comb is the existing sign/zero-extended load path factored out of the flop input. load_fwd_ok is in.valid && in.ctrl.mem_read && in.ctrl.reg_write && (in.rd != 0) && !mem_misalign - using the SAME mem_misalign signal that already gates ctrl_with_trap.reg_write into the MEM/WB register. No behavioral change to existing flopped outputs.\"\n  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add new select encoding 2'd3 = LOAD_COMB. Add two new inputs: ex_mem_mem_read (to distinguish LOAD-in-EX/MEM from ALU-op-in-EX/MEM) and ex_mem_load_fwd_ok (from mem_stage). Priority updated: LOAD-in-EX/MEM (load_fwd_ok && rd match) wins first, then non-LOAD-in-EX/MEM with !mem_read guard, then MEM/WB, then none. Applies symmetrically to rs1 and rs2.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a fourth fwd mux case (2'd3) sourcing a new input fwd_load_comb (the new mem_stage.load_data_comb). Both rs1 and rs2 mux tables updated.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new mem_stage outputs (load_data_comb, load_fwd_ok) to forward_unit and ex_stage. Pass ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read and load_fwd_ok into forward_unit's new inputs.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Delete the load_use_hazard term entirely (set to 1'b0 and drop id_ex_mem_read/id_ex_rd/if_id_rs1/if_id_rs2 ports or tie-off). stall_id now only asserts on dmem_stall or div_busy; flush_id only on redirect. All other stall sources unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Update the load-use stall test (if present) to expect zero-bubble behavior: a LOAD followed by a dependent ALU op should retire back-to-back (rvfi_order increments in consecutive cycles, not with a 1-cycle gap). Add a targeted test: LW x1,(x2); ADD x3,x1,x1 -> assert the ADD retires the cycle immediately after the LW. Add a misaligned-LOAD followed by a dependent test: LW x1,1(x2); ADD x3,x1,x1 -> assert the LW traps (rvfi_trap_0=1 on the LW retirement), the ADD's x1 source is the stale pre-LW x1 (post-forward mux must see 2'd0=ID/EX value or 2'd2=MEM/WB prior), and no regfile write for x1 happens.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r10s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r10s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777776129868,"end":1777776129884}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_debb664b30018zcJlAgyjWHOJW","sessionID":"ses_2144c4cddffeIMXcJtvP00ok4P","messageID":"msg_debb65ee9001fygvKuX1DsHBdk"}}
