{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777777166417,"sessionID":"ses_2143b0324ffeLcDQEIrw0wTJDT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01XDm897aX61oKS38fiD9FnX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r11s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r11s1\ntitle: \"Retime load-extract from pre-MEM-flop to post-MEM-flop (WB-stage combinational)\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  Lesson r10s1 established that BRAM synchronous read data (dmem_rdata)\n  arrives LATE in the cycle on Tang Nano 20K, and any combinational\n  consumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\n  remaining slack. The current mem_stage does exactly that competition\n  *before* the MEM/WB flop: dmem_rdata -> byte-shift by alu_result[1:0]\n  -> sign/zero-extend per (mem_width, mem_sext) -> flop into\n  mem_wb.read_data. That is ~4 LUT4 levels of extract logic sitting on\n  the binding late-arriving dmem_rdata path, eating MEM-stage slack\n  that then reports up as the global Fmax ceiling.\n\n  Meanwhile wb_stage is currently a trivial 2:1 mux (mem_to_reg ?\n  read_data : alu_result) feeding the regfile write port and the RVFI\n  rd_wdata tap. It has substantial combinational slack — both\n  mem_wb.read_data and mem_wb.alu_result arrive at the start of the\n  cycle (clean flop outputs), and the fanout is shallow.\n\n  This is the exact retiming pattern the \"move combinational logic\n  from a tight stage to a loose stage, across an existing flop\n  boundary\" heuristic applies to. It is NOT the r10s1 pattern (which\n  crossed a stage boundary the wrong way — late BRAM data into an EX\n  forwarding path that then had to feed the ALU cone); this retimes\n  FORWARD by zero stages (same flop boundary, logic just moves from\n  before to after it).\nhypothesis: |\n  Retime the load-extract logic from mem_stage (pre-flop) to wb_stage\n  (post-flop), so the MEM/WB register captures the raw dmem word\n  directly and WB does shift/sign-extend combinationally before the\n  regfile write.\n\n  Concrete edits:\n  1. rtl/core_pkg.sv — delete mem_wb_t.read_data (redundant once WB\n     does the extract; mem_rdata already carries the raw BRAM word\n     for the RVFI tap). Keep mem_rdata, alu_result, ctrl, mem_rmask,\n     mem_wmask unchanged.\n  2. rtl/mem_stage.sv — delete the shifted/byte_val/hword_val/load_data\n     combinational block. MEM/WB register now captures:\n       - dmem_rdata directly into mem_rdata (unchanged)\n       - alu_result unchanged (already stored)\n       - no read_data field to populate\n     Net effect: the dmem_rdata->flop critical path loses its\n     shift-extend cone, so the binding MEM-stage arc becomes the\n     same dmem_rdata->flop arc the BRAM was designed to deliver.\n  3. rtl/wb_stage.sv — compute load_data combinationally from\n     (mem_rdata, ctrl.mem_width, ctrl.mem_sext, alu_result[1:0]):\n       shifted  = mem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0] * 8);\n       byte_v   = shifted[7:0]; hword_v = shifted[15:0];\n       load_data = (mem_width==0) ? (sext ? sx8(byte_v)   : zx8(byte_v))\n                 : (mem_width==1) ? (sext ? sx16(hword_v) : zx16(hword_v))\n                 :                   mem_rdata;\n       w_data = ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : alu_result;\n     The new combinational depth in WB is ~4 LUT4 levels — well within\n     the slack the bare 2:1 mux had, and the inputs (mem_rdata,\n     alu_result, ctrl) are all clean flop outputs arriving at t=0 of\n     the cycle.\n\n  RVFI correctness:\n   - io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 is still driven by wb_w_data (wb_stage output).\n     wb_w_data is bit-exactly identical to the old implementation\n     for every retiring instruction — the extract function is the\n     same function of the same inputs (mem_rdata was already\n     registered from the same dmem_rdata the old mem_stage shifted\n     pre-flop, and alu_result[1:0] was already stored in mem_wb).\n   - io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0 still taps mem_wb_w.mem_rdata, unchanged.\n   - mem_wb.read_data field disappears — no RVFI tap references it\n     (it only fed wb_stage's w_data mux), so the r2s0 field-rename\n     lockstep hazard does not apply. Still, I will grep core.sv\n     top-level for any stray reference before committing.\n\n  Forwarding correctness:\n   - fwd_mem_wb = wb_w_data (unchanged wire; core.sv wires u_wb.w_data\n     to ex_stage.fwd_mem_wb). wb_w_data is bit-exact per above, so\n     MEM/WB -> EX forwarding for LOAD-consumers two-behind is\n     preserved value-wise.\n   - Timing of fwd_mem_wb: the new wb_stage adds ~4 LUT4 between\n     mem_wb_w.mem_rdata (flop out) and wb_w_data. fwd_mem_wb then\n     feeds the EX-stage forwarding 3:1 mux. Current EX-side forward\n     path is (fwd_mem_wb | fwd_ex_mem | in.rs*_val) -> ALU. We need\n     the new WB extract + EX forwarding mux + ALU cone to still fit\n     the cycle. The ALU cone is the existing EX critical path; the\n     old fwd_mem_wb arrived in ~0 LUT4 from mem_wb.read_data-flop.\n     Net EX-side delta: +4 LUT4 combinational between mem_wb_w flop\n     and fwd_mem_wb. This is the main timing risk.\n\n     Mitigation analysis: the EX-stage critical path is dominated by\n     the ALU (specifically the DSP18 multiplier + final output mux\n     per r3s0/r10s0's lessons); the forwarding mux input for\n     fwd_mem_wb is NOT on that critical path — fwd_ex_mem (the EX/MEM\n     flop output, two-cycle-ahead ALU result) is the more common\n     forward case and has no new delay. The MEM/WB->EX forward case\n     is only invoked for a specific LOAD-consumer pattern where the\n     LOAD's data has already been captured at MEM/WB, and the cycle\n     where this forward is live is the cycle AFTER the LOAD's MEM\n     stage, so the dmem_rdata late-arrival problem no longer applies\n     (mem_rdata is a clean flop output by this point).\n\n     In other words: r10s1's regression was because dmem_rdata\n     arrived late AND had to feed the ALU same-cycle. This retiming\n     makes mem_rdata a flop output (arrives early) AND the extract\n     happens one cycle later when nothing else is competing for the\n     WB slack. The two scenarios are fabric-topologically opposite.\n\n  Formal tractability:\n   - Pipeline stage count unchanged (5). test_pipeline.py stage probes\n     unaffected (per r4s1's lesson on pipeline-depth-changes).\n   - No new state (no new flops, no new id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t\n     widening — mem_wb_t actually shrinks by 32 bits).\n   - No new redirect or prediction logic (none of the r3s1/r3s2/r9s0\n     symbolic-fetch-coupling failure modes apply).\n   - The `reg` check (which r9s1 tripped on a seemingly-equivalent\n     WB-mux refactor) compares rvfi_rd_wdata to the regfile write.\n     Both are driven by wb_w_data, which is bit-exactly unchanged.\n     The subtle r9s1 failure was losing alu_result as a sidecar in\n     the trap/no-write case — here alu_result is STILL in mem_wb_t\n     (unchanged), only read_data is removed, so the solver still\n     has alu_result as a distinct regfile-state degree of freedom.\n     The cover(rvfi_valid_0 && rvfi_trap_0) sanity check r9s1's\n     lesson prescribes should pass without issue because a trapped\n     LOAD still has its alu_result captured and reg_write=0 clears\n     the rd write regardless of the extract path.\n\n  Expected Fmax delta: moving ~4 LUT4 levels off the binding\n  dmem_rdata late-arrival path should recover 5-12 MHz on the\n  Tang Nano 20K GW2A flow. With Fmax currently 177 MHz, that's\n  ~3-7% Fmax. IPC is unchanged (bit-exact retirements, same\n  load-use stall discipline). Fitness = IPC * Fmax, so net\n  fitness gain ~3-7%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Remove mem_wb_t.read_data field. Keep mem_rdata (raw BRAM word for RVFI tap and WB extract), alu_result, ctrl, mem_rmask/wmask all unchanged. No new fields added — mem_wb_t shrinks by 32 bits.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Delete the shifted/byte_val/hword_val/load_data combinational extract block. MEM/WB register drops the read_data <= load_data assignment. dmem_rdata now flows straight into mem_wb_w.mem_rdata flop without pre-flop shift/extend, shortening the BRAM-read-to-flop critical path by ~4 LUT4 levels.\"\n  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add combinational load-extract: shift mem_rdata right by alu_result[1:0]*8, then sign/zero-extend low 8 or 16 bits per ctrl.mem_width and ctrl.mem_sext. w_data mux becomes (mem_to_reg ? load_data : alu_result). Input signal list expands to include mem_rdata, ctrl.mem_width, ctrl.mem_sext, alu_result[1:0]; all of these are already in the mem_wb_t input bundle and are clean flop outputs at t=0 of the WB cycle.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Audit for any stray references to mem_wb_w.read_data at top-level (per r2s0 lesson's lockstep requirement). Expected: none — read_data only fed wb_stage's w_data mux, not any RVFI tap. RVFI taps for rd_wdata (via wb_w_data) and mem_rdata (via mem_wb_w.mem_rdata) are unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Audit probe signals for any reference to mem_wb_reg.read_data or equivalent. If present, retarget to reconstruct via the wb_stage extract or use mem_wb_reg.mem_rdata + control. Stage probe names (if_id_reg, id_ex_reg, ex_mem_reg, mem_wb_reg) are unchanged since pipeline depth is unchanged — per r4s1 the orchestrator rollback hazard does not apply here.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r11s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r11s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777777166397,"end":1777777166415}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_debc618c1001ZxcmD7GHkh6flt","sessionID":"ses_2143b0324ffeLcDQEIrw0wTJDT","messageID":"msg_debc61393001fpaMOGUiSTcnzy"}}
