{"type":"text","timestamp":1777777173881,"sessionID":"ses_2143b0324ffeLcDQEIrw0wTJDT","part":{"id":"prt_debc6d0da001wWGpKbnpLcrj5z","messageID":"msg_debc6c895001X78V2kx7VwCy57","sessionID":"ses_2143b0324ffeLcDQEIrw0wTJDT","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r11s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Structural retiming of the load-extract logic from pre-MEM-flop to post-MEM-flop (WB-stage combinational).\n\n**Rationale anchored in LESSONS.md**:\n- r10s1 established BRAM `dmem_rdata` arrives LATE on this fabric — the current MEM stage does shift+sign-extend on that late signal *before* the flop, eating MEM-cycle slack\n- r10s1's regression was because it moved extract into EX where it competed with the ALU cone same-cycle; this retiming is topologically opposite — moves extract into WB which has significant slack, with inputs that are clean flop outputs\n- Unlike r9s1's WB pre-register attempt, `alu_result` stays in `mem_wb_t` as a distinct field, preserving the regfile-state degree of freedom the `reg` formal check needs\n- No pipeline depth change (r4s1 safe), no payload widening (r5s2/r8s2 safe), no IF-stage mux edit (r10s2 safe), no new DSP tap (r10s0 safe), no payload field rename without lockstep audit (r2s0 mitigated by explicit core.sv audit step)\n\nExpected +4% fitness from ~5-12 MHz Fmax recovery on Tang Nano 20K; IPC unchanged (bit-exact retirements).","time":{"start":1777777168602,"end":1777777173879}}}
