{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763522485,"sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BHGWTgH3T9BUHuypHJ4rcy","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/rtl/ && echo \"---\" && ls cores/bench/test/ 2>/dev/null","description":"Check RTL and test layout"},"output":"alu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n---\n_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","metadata":{"output":"alu.sv\ncore_pkg.sv\ncore.sv\ndecoder.sv\nex_stage.sv\nforward_unit.sv\nhazard_unit.sv\nid_stage.sv\nif_stage.sv\nimm_gen.sv\nmem_stage.sv\nreg_file.sv\nwb_stage.sv\n---\n_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","exit":0,"description":"Check RTL and test layout","truncated":false},"title":"Check RTL and test layout","time":{"start":1777763522481,"end":1777763522483}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm working through the performance calculations — with 4491485 cycles across 10 iterations, that gives me an IPC of about 2.23e-6, and using the Fmax seeds (121, 135, 136) with a median of 135.21, I get a fitness of roughly 301 iterations per second. Now I'm moving on to analyze the structural component.\n\nThe CPU is a 5-stage in-order pipeline running at 135 MHz on the Tang Nano 20K, and the critical path is likely through the multiplier in the execute stage. With 22% of cycles lost to instruction and data stalls, I'm looking at several structural improvements: splitting the multiplier into a multi-cycle unit to free up the critical path and boost Fmax, adding an instruction buffer to hide fetch stalls, or implementing a dual-issue superscalar. The highest-leverage option seems to be decoupling the multiplier into its own iterative unit, which would both raise the clock frequency and potentially improve IPC by removing the bottleneck from the main ALU. ies in a single combinational path — Verilator synthesizes with `*` which becomes a large combinational multiplier. This is likely the critical path on Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18 has DSP but the 32-bit multiply is probably multi-LUT).\n- Moving to a multi-cycle sequential multiplier would dramatically shorten the ALU critical path → much higher Fmax.\n- The IPC hit is small: CoreMark does very few MUL/DIV operations per iteration.\n\n**Option 2: Instruction prefetch buffer (FIFO between imem and decode)**\n- The 22% imem stall causes direct pipeline bubbles. A 4-entry FIFO between IF and ID could absorb stall bursts.\n- But when the average stall rate is 22%, you can't fully hide it — the bus isn't delivering faster. But you can hide variance, so worst-case sequences don't cost all 22%. Actually, if stalls are random 22% per cycle, a FIFO only helps bursts, not the aggregate. Still some improvement.\n- More importantly: a prefetch buffer enables the IF stage's imem_addr to advance speculatively while the FIFO has room, which does NOT help if every stall is visible. Hmm.\n\n**Option 3: Move multiplier out of ALU into a separate 2-cycle pipelined unit with result held in EX/MEM**\n- Best overall: Fmax up, minimal IPC cost.\n\nActually thinking about this more carefully: the ALU computes three separate 64-bit multipliers in parallel combinationally — mul_ss, mul_uu, mul_su — then selects one. That's three 32x32 multipliers every cycle, which is massive logic and definitely the Fmax bottleneck. I should pipeline the multiplier into a separate multi-cycle unit to dramatically reduce the EX-stage critical path, save 1500-2000 LUTs, and add only minimal stalls since CoreMark barely uses MUL/DIV. The divider is probably even worse — a 32-bit divider combinationally is huge. So the real win is a structural change: move both MUL and DIV out of the critical path into a dedicated execution unit that takes multiple cycles. The FPGA synthesis determines Fmax, so removing `*` and `/` from the critical path pays off significantly.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deaf6978200130namIKjI3C7gE","sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","messageID":"msg_deaf62d1a0018ghwxqsDbBsS1U"}}
