{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763556850,"sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01WoTJsiH6TWhPz39pisSbNd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\ntitle: \"Split M-extension into multi-cycle unit off EX critical path\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\n  (mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\n  and a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\n  via the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\n  certainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\n  budget (target 10000 — only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\n  seeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive — exactly\n  the signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\n\n  CoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\n  MUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\n  uses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\n  small IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX critical\n  path and lower LUT count is strictly fitness-positive for this workload.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Split the ALU into two execution units and route ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*,\n  ALU_REM* to a new multi-cycle M-unit:\n\n    1. `alu.sv` keeps only single-cycle ops (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/\n       SLL/SRL/SRA/LUI). The three 64-bit multipliers and the divider are\n       deleted from its combinational body. The M-extension op decodes\n       remain legal in decoder.sv (invariants #2, #10 preserved).\n\n    2. A new `m_unit.sv` implements MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU as a 2-cycle\n       pipelined unsigned 32x32 multiplier with sign-fixup at the output\n       stage (Booth-style via sign-extension registers). DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\n       run as a 32-cycle iterative restoring divider. The unit has a\n       `start` / `busy` / `done` handshake and an internal result register.\n\n    3. `ex_stage.sv` gains a stall-output `m_busy`. When an id_ex_t enters\n       EX with an M-extension op, the stage starts the M-unit, holds the\n       ID/EX register via `stall_ex_mem` (wired through hazard_unit), and\n       only advances into EX/MEM when the M-unit reports `done`. The ALTOPS\n       path still does the algebraic stand-in in a single cycle so the\n       formal gate's 20-step budget is unaffected.\n\n    4. `hazard_unit.sv` widens `stall_ex_mem` to OR in `m_busy`. Because\n       id_ex_t is held during a multi-cycle M-op, rvfi_order's +1 invariant\n       (#4) is naturally preserved — the retirement happens exactly once\n       when the M-unit finishes and MEM/WB captures the result.\n\n  Expected effect: removing four parallel 32-bit arithmetic units from the\n  EX critical path should raise median Fmax from ~135 MHz to ~155-170 MHz\n  (+15-25%), and free ~1500-2500 LUTs (the three combinational multipliers\n  are the largest single block; the divider is similarly expensive because\n  the GW2AR lacks dedicated div hardware). The IPC hit is bounded: at\n  ~10 MUL/iter * 1 extra cycle + ~2 DIV/iter * 31 extra cycles ≈ 70-80\n  added cycles per CoreMark iteration on a baseline of ~449k cycles/iter —\n  well under 0.1% slowdown. Net: +10-20% fitness.\n\n  Implementation notes: keep the ALTOPS branch of alu.sv exactly as-is\n  (single-cycle, formal-tractable) and only the `else` branch changes. The\n  M-unit always reports done in 1 cycle under ALTOPS so formal stays\n  bounded. test/test_alu.py vectors for M-ext move to test/test_m_unit.py\n  with the same 30+ vectors per op; test/test_pipeline.py gets a multi-\n  cycle-stall smoke test (a MUL immediately followed by a dependent ADD).\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 15\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove the three combinational 64-bit multipliers and the combinational 32-bit divider from the non-ALTOPS branch. Keep only RV32I single-cycle ops. ALTOPS branch stays byte-identical so formal-gate bounds are unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/m_unit.sv\n    description: \"New module: multi-cycle M-extension execution unit. 2-cycle pipelined 32x32 multiplier with sign fix-up for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. 32-cycle iterative restoring divider for DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU. Handshake: start/busy/done/result. ALTOPS branch collapses to 1-cycle algebraic stand-in.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate m_unit alongside alu. When id_ex_t carries an M-ext opcode, start the m_unit, hold the EX/MEM register until m_unit.done, and route m_unit.result into reg_q.alu_result when done fires. Emit m_busy upward to hazard_unit.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add m_busy input; OR it into stall_ex_mem and stall_id so the pipeline freezes while an M-ext op is in flight. Forwarding correctness preserved because ID/EX is held with its original operands.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new m_busy signal between ex_stage and hazard_unit. No change to top-level IO, RVFI port set, or memory contract.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Remove M-extension vectors (they move to test_m_unit.py). Keep base RV32I coverage intact.\"\n  - file: test/test_m_unit.py\n    description: \"New cocotb suite: 30+ vectors per MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU/DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU covering all RV32M corner cases (div-by-zero, INT_MIN/-1, negative operands). Verifies the start/busy/done handshake completes in 2 cycles for MUL and 32 cycles for DIV.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a multi-cycle-stall regression: MUL rs,a,b followed immediately by ADD rd,rs,... asserts rd sees the MUL result on the correct cycle and rvfi_order increments only once per retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777763556837,"end":1777763556849}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm formulating the core architectural hypothesis: moving multiplication and division operations into a separate multi-cycle execution unit would eliminate the three parallel 64-bit multipliers and the combinational divider from the critical path, significantly reducing timing pressure on the main ALU.\n\nThis approach trades a small cycle penalty on multiply/divide operations for a substantial frequency gain—potentially 15-20% improvement from ~135 MHz to 150-170 MHz—which should more than compensate in overall performance since CoreMark's workload is dominated by simpler operations like addition, shifting, loads, stores, and branches. The LUT savings also help us stay within the 10,000 gate budget we're approaching.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deaf6b8820014Trc8UefJoiEQ8","sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","messageID":"msg_deaf697f4001cHZDnzelkT0k68"}}
