{"type":"text","timestamp":1777763562313,"sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","part":{"id":"prt_deaf724c8001l16F0cZPNan75o","messageID":"msg_deaf71e32001PgljZq2xg3HYkQ","sessionID":"ses_21509fec2ffeSwWO2IJ0EK1Rsm","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r1s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Structural angle — split M-extension (MUL/MULH*/DIV*/REM*) out of the single-cycle combinational ALU into a dedicated multi-cycle `m_unit.sv` (2-cycle pipelined mul, 32-cycle iterative div). \n\n**Why:** The current `alu.sv` instantiates three parallel combinational 64-bit multipliers plus a combinational 32-bit divider every cycle, almost certainly the Fmax bottleneck on GW2AR-18C and a big chunk of the 9880/10000 LUT budget. CoreMark's timed loop rarely hits M-ext, so a multi-cycle M-unit trades negligible IPC for ~15-25% Fmax headroom and frees substantial LUTs.\n\n**Invariants preserved:** ALTOPS branch unchanged (formal bounds intact), rvfi_order +1 via pipeline hold during M-busy, decoder illegality defaults unchanged, top-level IO untouched.","time":{"start":1777763558600,"end":1777763562311}}}
