{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777766362444,"sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","part":{"id":"prt_deb21ed4a001UKlVcNWoxhvxdN","messageID":"msg_deb21dd8f001wXkXuG3ui0ghfM","sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","snapshot":"60cedac05be08812b8ecf39c78f7e7d32cdb92f0","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766413130,"sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01TvH9yX2uRFYP1di3dV9aQX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5; echo \"---\"; ls cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null","description":"Check experiments dir structure"},"output":"---\ncores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","metadata":{"output":"---\ncores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","exit":0,"description":"Check experiments dir structure","truncated":false},"title":"Check experiments dir structure","time":{"start":1777766413124,"end":1777766413127}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing what structural changes could boost performance on this 5-stage RV32IM core—previous attempts at iterative dividers, multi-cycle extensions, and branch prediction all regressed or timed out, so I need to reconsider the approach and look at how core frequency and instructions-per-cycle interact to improve overall fitness. CoreMark has many branches, so reducing branch mispredict penalties is key. I could resolve branches earlier in the ID stage with forwarding from later pipeline stages, cutting the penalty from 2 cycles to 1, but that adds logic that might hurt Fmax. Merging IF and ID into a single stage would reduce pipeline depth and flushes, though decoding and register reads in one cycle could be risky for timing. Let me focus on what's actually limiting the critical path in the EX stage.\n\nThe multiplier in the ALU is likely the bottleneck for Fmax, and pipelining it has regressed before. But I think there's a simpler win: implementing zero-cycle JAL resolution. Since JAL has a constant target and PC+4 is deterministic, I can decode it in the IF stage, redirect the PC immediately, and compute the register write in ID normally—no hazards, no speculation, just a clean structural improvement that eliminates the 2-cycle bubble for function calls.\n\nThe implementation adds JAL detection in the IF stage to decode the opcode and compute the J-type immediate combinationally, then overrides next_pc with the target. The tricky part is managing the pipeline state: when JAL is detected in IF, the next cycle has already fetched from PC+4 (the wrong path), so I need to trace through the exact cycle-by-cycle behavior to ensure the IF/ID payload stays valid and the wrong-path fetch gets flushed cleanly without breaking the rd=PC+4 writeback that flows down the pipeline.\n\nLooking at the detailed cycle trace, JAL incurs a 2-cycle penalty: the redirect signal from EX flushes the IF/ID stage (which holds the wrong-path instruction from PC+4), and the hazard unit's flush_id logic converts that to a NOP in the ID/EX stage. By cycle N+3, the target instruction is fetched and begins flowing through the pipeline normally.\n\nWith early JAL detection in IF, I can compute the target address and redirect the fetch immediately, so the target instruction enters ID just one cycle after JAL—essentially back-to-back with zero bubbles. This saves roughly 2 cycles per JAL, which matters significantly for CoreMark since it has many function calls. The tradeoff is adding combinational logic in IF: J-immediate extraction, a PC+immediate adder, and opcode comparison to detect the JAL instruction.\n\nI need to be careful about stalls and flushes—the early JAL redirect should only fire when IF is producing a valid instruction, not when it's stalled or flushed by EX. JALR won't work here since it needs regfile reads, so I'm focusing on JAL only. The change is localized to the IF stage module and can be tested by checking JAL latency in the pipeline tests. I don't expect this to break RVFI correctness since the JAL instruction still retires normally through the full pipeline; I'm just optimizing when the next fetch happens. The risk is a slight Fmax drop from the longer combinational path, but the IPC improvement should outweigh that.\n\nNow I'm realizing a conflict: when IF early-redirects on JAL, the EX stage will still compute its own redirect signal based on the jump instruction, which would flush the target instruction that IF already fetched. I need to suppress the EX redirect when the JAL was already handled by IF. The cleanest approach is to pass a bit through the pipeline stages indicating this JAL was early-redirected, so EX knows to skip its redirect logic for that instruction. Now I'm ready to implement this. I need to modify the IF stage to decode JAL and redirect early, add an `early_jumped` flag to track when that happens, propagate it through the pipeline, and suppress the EX redirect when it's already been done—plus add a test to verify the latency improvement. I'm estimating this gets us about 8% better performance with medium confidence.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb22b2da001pTg4rkiYFOCO6Y","sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","messageID":"msg_deb21dd8f001wXkXuG3ui0ghfM"}}
