{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777766423484,"sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","part":{"id":"prt_deb22dbba001r0iO3IH1C2cn5u","messageID":"msg_deb22cf09001T73SrjcDzS5FaZ","sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","snapshot":"60cedac05be08812b8ecf39c78f7e7d32cdb92f0","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766451456,"sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01QsWV1pme2gCGrDgG162tRv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\ntitle: \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\n  set reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\n  signal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\n  is purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\n  J-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\n  penalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\n  when EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\n  until pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\n  function-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\n  their per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\n  JALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\n  rs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\n\n  Prior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\n  the M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\n  the divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\n  count grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\n  (`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\n  blew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\n  both failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\n  introduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\nhypothesis: |\n  Decode JAL (opcode 0x6F) combinationally in if_stage.sv. When the\n  fetched word is JAL and the IF output is valid (not flushed by an EX\n  redirect, imem_stall, or reset), compute the J-type immediate and\n  override next_pc with pc + imm_J instead of pc + 4. The JAL instruction\n  itself still flows normally through ID/EX/MEM/WB so its PC+4 writeback\n  retires and RVFI sees the canonical pc_wdata = target. EX must NOT\n  re-redirect for a JAL that IF already jumped, so a single-bit\n  `early_jumped` flag is added to `if_id_t` (propagated into `id_ex_t`\n  as a field separate from ctrl_t). `ex_stage` ANDs its redirect\n  condition with `!in.early_jumped` for the JAL case (is_jump &&\n  !is_jalr). JALR is untouched (it needs rs1 + forwarding and has no\n  purely-IF-visible target).\n\n  Cost in logic:\n    - A 32-bit J-imm extractor (existing pattern from imm_gen.sv) and\n      a 2:1 mux on next_pc gated by `imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111`.\n    - 1-bit `early_jumped` through 2 pipeline registers.\n  Expected Fmax impact: the added IF-stage adder is 32-bit pc + 32-bit\n  sign-extended imm, parallel with the existing pc+4 incrementer — it\n  is unlikely to become the new critical path given EX currently owns\n  Fmax via the ALU/multiplier mux. Worst case Fmax gives up ~2-3%;\n  IPC gain from eliminating ~2 bubbles on every dynamically-retired\n  JAL (CoreMark has thousands per iteration) should dominate.\n\n  Correctness hooks:\n    - RVFI: pc_wdata of the JAL is always `pc + imm_J` whether IF\n      early-jumped or EX did. rd_wdata stays PC+4. No change to any\n      RVFI field → riscv-formal `pc_fwd` / `unique` / `causal` checks\n      remain closed with zero added state-space work.\n    - Formal: the `early_jumped` flag is a pure function of decoded\n      opcode + IF stall/flush signals — not speculative, not predicted\n      — so SBY's BMC depth is unchanged.\n    - Traps: a misaligned JAL target still traps in EX (its\n      misalign_fault path fires there as before; we gate the EX redirect\n      but not the misalign_fault computation, which also suppresses\n      reg_write and leaves pc_next = pc + 4).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a single-bit `early_jumped` field to if_id_t and id_ex_t (outside ctrl_t so decoder default-illegal semantics are unaffected).\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Detect JAL (opcode 7'b1101111) on imem_data, extract the J-imm, and override next_pc = pc + imm_J when the IF output would otherwise be a valid instruction. Set out.early_jumped accordingly. Preserve reset/flush/stall priority so imem_stall and EX redirects still win over the early-jump.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Propagate in.early_jumped into the ID/EX register as a standalone field (zero when reset/flush).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Gate the redirect output for unconditional JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr) with !in.early_jumped so IF's in-flight target fetch is not flushed. Misalign_fault still asserts and still overrides via the existing trap path.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a JAL-latency cocotb test: two JALs back-to-back to verify zero bubble cycles in rvfi_order deltas, plus a branch-then-JAL interleaving test to confirm EX redirects still win when IF's JAL-prediction would race an older redirect, plus a misaligned-JAL test (imm with bit[1] set) to confirm trap semantics are preserved.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777766451445,"end":1777766451454}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the previous attempts and their outcomes, I'm considering a different approach: implementing an early JAL redirect mechanism in the instruction fetch stage. This is a structural modification that reshapes the IF stage and adds an early redirect path, distinct from the prior approaches that focused on optimization, multi-cycle units, and branch prediction.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb22df58001ypmMzSaJIXQ2w8","sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","messageID":"msg_deb22cf09001T73SrjcDzS5FaZ"}}
