{"type":"text","timestamp":1777766457470,"sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","part":{"id":"prt_deb234f420012LMCKiO17Q2kr4","messageID":"msg_deb23498a001lLLM3LoMqr0Ab2","sessionID":"ses_214de2307ffecRkmyYmljUhVtX","type":"text","text":"Written hypothesis `hyp-20260502-002-r2s1`: **Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect** (structural).\n\nCore idea: decode JAL combinationally in `if_stage.sv`, compute `pc + imm_J`, and redirect PC immediately on the next cycle — eliminating the 2 bubbles that currently follow every JAL while it traverses to EX. JAL still flows the pipeline normally so its rd=PC+4 writeback and RVFI fields remain canonical; a new `early_jumped` flag on the `if_id_t`/`id_ex_t` registers tells EX to suppress its redundant redirect.\n\nWhy this avoids the failure modes of the three prior attempts:\n- Not an M-extension datapath change (r1s0/r1s1 regressed there).\n- Not speculative — `early_jumped` is a deterministic function of the decoded opcode, so no branch-predictor state joins the RVFI-observed payload (the blow-up mode of r1s2's BTB).\n- RVFI/formal contract is unchanged: `pc_wdata` of the JAL is `pc + imm_J` either way; `pc_fwd`/`unique`/`causal` checks don't see new state.\n\nExpected: +5% fitness (conservative) — CoreMark's hot path has many function-call JALs, and dropping 2 bubbles per JAL compounds across iterations. Confidence medium.","time":{"start":1777766453058,"end":1777766457468}}}
