{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768263171,"sessionID":"ses_214c24ef8ffeYfbPZyhmOieHEy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01K4ZpY1kWXCKAbuLr51ak5B","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r3s1\ntitle: \"Stateless IF-stage backward-taken branch prediction (BTFNT)\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The successful r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) eliminated the 2-cycle redirect\n  bubble for unconditional jumps. The next structural lever on the same\n  axis is conditional branches — still paying a 2-cycle EX-redirect penalty\n  every time a branch is taken. In CoreMark's hot loops (core_list_find,\n  crcu8/crcu16 bit loops, core_bench_matrix nested loops, core_state state\n  machines) the dominant control flow is loop-closing backward branches\n  that are taken on every iteration except the last. A 5-iteration loop\n  pays 2 bubbles × 4 = 8 cycles of taken-branch redirect and 0 cycles on\n  the exit-fallthrough; a 50-iteration loop pays 98 cycles of bubbles.\n\n  Static backwards-taken / forwards-not-taken (BTFNT) is the classic\n  prediction heuristic that captures this without any history: a BRANCH\n  instruction whose sign-extended B-immediate is negative is almost\n  certainly a loop edge. The r1s2 BTB lesson (broken, formal timeout)\n  was that threading speculative state through the RVFI-observed payload\n  blows the per-insn BMC budget. The r2s2 lesson was the exact opposite\n  pattern succeeds: a *stateless* predictor whose decision is a pure\n  function of the already-observed (PC, instr) pair costs zero formal\n  state because EX can re-derive the IF-side decision from the same bits\n  it already has in ID/EX.\n\n  On CoreMark (~15% branch frequency, ~70% backward-taken), eliminating\n  the 2-cycle bubble on backward-taken branches while paying a 2-cycle\n  bubble on the ~30% of backward branches that fall through (loop\n  exits, rare) is net-positive IPC. Rough estimate: 0.15 × 0.70 × 2 =\n  0.21 cycle savings per dynamic instr, offset by 0.15 × 0.30 × 2 = 0.09\n  new mispredict cost ≈ 0.12 cycle/instr net, i.e. ~8–10% IPC win on\n  top of the JAL baseline. Fmax impact is expected to be minimal:\n  the IF-stage critical path grows by one 32-bit adder + alignment\n  check (same incremental work the JAL predictor already added), and\n  EX-stage redirect logic gains a single XOR comparing predicted vs.\n  actual branch-taken — far below the current Fmax-limiting ALU/divider\n  mux reported by r1s0/r1s1.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a stateless BTFNT predictor at IF that mirrors the JAL-predictor\n  pattern already in `if_stage.sv`:\n\n  1. IF stage (rtl/if_stage.sv):\n     - Combinationally decode the fetched word. When it is a BRANCH\n       opcode (0x63), funct3 is a valid branch (not 2/3), the\n       sign-extended B-immediate is negative (imm[31]==1, i.e. backward),\n       AND the computed target `pc + imm` is 4-byte aligned (target[1:0]\n       == 0), redirect the PC register to the branch target this same\n       cycle — exactly like the existing JAL predictor. No pipeline\n       payload bits are added; no \"predicted\" flag threaded anywhere.\n     - The fetched branch instruction itself still flows into ID/EX/MEM\n       as a normal branch. The next fetched word comes from the\n       predicted target (not pc+4).\n     - Guards: same as JAL — skip prediction on flush/redirect in the\n       same cycle; skip on misaligned target; skip on `funct3 ∈ {2,3}`\n       (reserved / illegal branch).\n\n  2. EX stage (rtl/ex_stage.sv):\n     - Re-derive the IF-side prediction from the same (pc, instr, imm)\n       bits already in id_ex_t. Call it `predicted_taken`:\n         predicted_taken = in.ctrl.is_branch\n                        && (in.imm[31] == 1'b1)\n                        && (branch_target[1:0] == 2'b00)\n                        && (in.ctrl.branch_op != 3'd2)   // guarded\n                        && (in.ctrl.branch_op != 3'd3);\n       This is pure combinational of bits already present in EX's input,\n       exactly mirroring IF's decision — no new pipeline payload.\n     - Redirect becomes:\n         redirect = (branch_actual != branch_predicted_nextpc)\n                 || in.ctrl.is_jalr;\n         redirect_target = branch_taken ? branch_target : (pc + 4);\n       where `branch_actual` = resolved next PC and\n       `branch_predicted_nextpc` = predicted_taken ? branch_target : pc+4.\n       In other words: redirect only when IF's prediction disagrees with\n       EX's resolution. Matches today's JAL behavior (no redirect on\n       correctly-predicted JAL).\n     - The misalign-trap path is unchanged; misaligned branch targets\n       already trap in EX, and IF's predictor guard ensures misaligned\n       backward branches fall through IF's normal pc+4 path so EX's\n       misalign trap fires exactly as today.\n\n  3. pc_next bookkeeping for RVFI (learned from r2s1 failure):\n     - The retiring branch's rvfi_pc_wdata MUST be the architecturally\n       resolved next PC (branch_target on taken, pc+4 on not-taken),\n       regardless of whether IF predicted. This is already what the\n       current EX-stage reg_q.pc_next mux computes — leave it alone.\n       Only the redirect *gate* is narrowed, not the pc_next\n       computation. This was the exact bug that killed r2s1: gating\n       pc_next's target path on `!predicted` instead of on\n       `branch_taken` desynced rvfi_pc_wdata from rvfi_pc_rdata of the\n       next retirement.\n\n  No state lives in the RVFI-observed pipeline payload. No new\n  recovery FSM. SBY re-derives the predictor's decision from the same\n  bits it already proves over. The additional constraint on the\n  formal state space is zero.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 8\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add BTFNT predictor alongside the existing JAL predictor: decode BRANCH opcode 0x63, check backward immediate (imm[31]==1), check target alignment, check branch_op != {2,3}; when all hold and no flush/redirect, set next_pc to branch_target instead of pc+4. Priority: redirect > JAL > BTFNT > pc+4.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Re-derive IF's prediction combinationally (predicted_taken = is_branch && imm[31] && aligned && !reserved_funct3); narrow redirect to fire only on mismatch between predicted next-PC and resolved next-PC (branch_taken ? target : pc+4). Keep reg_q.pc_next unchanged — it still reports the architectural next PC for RVFI. Misalign-trap path unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_branch_predictor.py\n    description: \"New cocotb suite exercising BTFNT correctness: (a) backward-taken branch hits zero-bubble path; (b) backward-not-taken branch triggers EX redirect to pc+4; (c) forward-taken branch still costs 2 cycles (no prediction); (d) misaligned backward branch target traps exactly as today; (e) reserved branch_op (funct3=2/3) is never predicted; (f) rvfi_pc_wdata matches resolved next-PC on every retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777768263163,"end":1777768263170}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" With JAL handled, I'm moving on to conditional branches using a stateless static predictor at the IF stage—taking backward branches with negative immediates, following the same pattern that worked for JAL and keeping the RVFI payload clean.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3e7a25001SXovg5Ka1R4ep1","sessionID":"ses_214c24ef8ffeYfbPZyhmOieHEy","messageID":"msg_deb3e662c001n6HhFhrlwtGbnz"}}
