{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768269443,"sessionID":"ses_214c24ef8ffeYfbPZyhmOieHEy","part":{"id":"prt_deb3ef2f9001svfB1LEXw4FIXL","messageID":"msg_deb3eee6a001ehlhFF6ZWIoXj7","sessionID":"ses_214c24ef8ffeYfbPZyhmOieHEy","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r3s1.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary**: Stateless BTFNT (backward-taken / forward-not-taken) branch predictor at IF stage — the natural extension of the successful r2s2 JAL predictor pattern (+5.87%) applied to conditional branches.\n\n**Key design choices driven by prior lessons**:\n- r1s2 lesson (BTB broke formal): no `predicted` / `pred_target` bits threaded through `if_id_t` / `id_ex_t`. EX re-derives the prediction as a pure function of bits already in `id_ex_t`.\n- r2s1 lesson (JAL early-redirect broke RVFI): the EX-stage `pc_next` mux stays exactly as today — it always computes the architectural next PC for `rvfi_pc_wdata`. Only the redirect *gate* is narrowed.\n- r2s2 success pattern: guard IF prediction on target alignment (`target[1:0]==0`) so misalign-trap semantics remain intact.\n\n**Expected impact**: +8% fitness. Covers the loop-closing backward branch path that dominates CoreMark's hot kernels (core_list_find, crcu8, core_bench_matrix, core_state). Fmax risk minimal — same incremental IF-side work as the existing JAL predictor plus one XOR in EX.","time":{"start":1777768264441,"end":1777768269441}}}
