{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769666774,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"id":"prt_deb54575d0015ugoSSb33E0vvt","messageID":"msg_deb5361ea001jXGqemD5Rdma1f","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","type":"text","text":"Let me check the experiments log for prior structural attempts, especially anything around dividers or pipeline restructuring.","time":{"start":1777769666397,"end":1777769666773}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769666802,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01TsUREJvLiUmv7ThEsXM8vd","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -i \"divid|div.sv|iterative|multi-cycle|pipelin.*mult|critical path\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -30","description":"Search log for divider/pipelining hypotheses"},"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","metadata":{"output":"zsh:1: command not found: rg\n","exit":0,"description":"Search log for divider/pipelining hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Search log for divider/pipelining hypotheses","time":{"start":1777769666799,"end":1777769666801}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm analyzing what structural changes could boost the RV32IM CPU's CoreMark performance—the current best fitness is 345.80 compared to a baseline of 301.04, with recent improvements from the JAL predictor showing promise, though I notice the coremark_iter_s metric looks like a placeholder that needs investigation.\n\nLooking at the pipeline architecture, I see several promising directions: merging pipeline stages to reduce latency, implementing two-read-port single-cycle loads to eliminate load-use hazards, or moving branch resolution earlier into the ID stage so mispredicted branches only cost one bubble instead of two. The most compelling option seems to be early branch resolution in ID—if I can compute the branch comparison there instead of in EX, I'd reduce the branch penalty significantly while also lowering the EX stage's critical path, which should help with fmax.\n\nThe main challenge is handling data hazards when operands aren't ready yet, which would require forwarding paths back to ID. That complicates the design, but it's a structural technique that avoids the formal verification issues that plagued the speculative predictor approaches. The load-use hazard remains the biggest performance bottleneck though, so I should also explore whether making loads resolve in a single cycle through the EX stage is feasible.\n\nLooking at the memory interface contract, `dmem_rdata` arrives combinationally and feeds directly into the load data path before being registered in the next cycle. This means the data is technically available in the same cycle the request goes out, so theoretically combining EX and MEM stages could eliminate the load-use bubble entirely—but only if the synchronous BRAM actually supports zero-wait access as the handshake signals suggest.\n\nThe tradeoff is critical path: merging EX and MEM would force the ALU result, memory access, and load extraction all into one stage, which would likely tank Fmax. I need to figure out whether the performance gain from eliminating load-use stalls outweighs the clock frequency penalty.\n\nActually, pipelining the multiplier itself might be the better move — DSP blocks on Gowin are designed to work with registered inputs and outputs anyway, so making MUL a 2-cycle operation with pipeline registers at the DSP boundaries could push Fmax higher without the complexity of merging stages. The tradeoff is that back-to-back multiplies would need stalls, but CoreMark doesn't hit that case often enough to matter. the multiplication in the DSP block, then selects the registered output, which means a 1-cycle stall when a MUL is followed by a dependent instruction. The Fmax gain should be significant since we're freeing up the EX critical path, and CoreMark barely uses multiplication so the IPC hit is negligible. The tricky part is handling the mul_busy signal and forwarding logic, though an easier route might be letting the synthesis tool balance the ALU timing itself. Actually, I think merging EX and MEM into a single stage is more promising — it eliminates load-use stalls entirely and cuts the branch misprediction penalty by a cycle, but the risk is that combining the ALU and memory read into one stage could blow up the critical path.\n\nWait, the memory access is external with handshake signals, and in the FPGA the BRAM has a 1-cycle read latency, so the load address goes out in EX and the data comes back in MEM — I can't actually combine those stages. Let me reconsider. Predecoding in the IF stage could reduce the ID critical path by moving decode earlier, but that gets messy with the JAL predictor. Given that the DSP folding won the +8.50% gain, I should look for a similar structural win. The divider is almost certainly the real bottleneck — it's a massive combinational chain for 32-bit signed division, so pipelining it into multiple cycles would free up Fmax significantly. We're actually already above the target Fmax at 153.61 MHz, so the issue might be LUT capacity rather than timing — we're at 9865 out of 10000 LUTs. Converting to an iterative divider would free up significant LUT resources, which could improve routing flexibility and potentially help Fmax even if the combinational divider wasn't the direct critical path. The tradeoff is that this makes the ALU stateful, which means the cocotb tests would need to handle multi-cycle division, so I'd need to either update those tests or keep the divider separate in the EX stage with its own busy signal.\n\nI'm settling on a cleaner approach: create a standalone iterative divider module that lives in the EX stage, detect DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU operations there, stall the pipeline until the divider finishes, and use its output instead of the ALU's combinational result. The ALU keeps its combinational DIV path only for ALTOPS mode (where it's replaced with XOR anyway), and removes it for the real synthesis path. This should save 400-800 LUTs historically on Gowin while keeping the test surface minimal.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb545771001VX5s4RmN24FTOa","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","messageID":"msg_deb5361ea001jXGqemD5Rdma1f"}}
