{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769670729,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01BGLEAXZLgPVcffgjWhLxog","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"divid|iterative|multi-cycle|critical path|pipelin.*mul","path":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 7 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative shift-subtract divider to shorten EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier path (which lands on\\nDSP blocks) and the adder/shift paths, and is almost certainly what\\ncaps Fmax at 135 MHz \\u2014 well below the 150\\u2013170 MHz that a well-floor-\\nplanned 5-stage core reaches on Tang Nano 20K when divide is iterative.\\nCoreMark itself issues essentially zero divide ops in its hot loops\\n(matrix, list, state machines use MUL/shifts/compares, not DIV/REM),\\nso the IPC cost of making divide multi-cycle is negligible \\u2014 a few\\ndozen cycles per 449,148-cycle iteration at most, i.e. <0.01% IPC\\nregression against an 8\\u201315% Fmax gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier pa...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split M-extension into multi-cycle unit off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX critical\\npath and lower LUT count is strictly fitness-positive for this workload.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX c...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Pre-register rd_wdata at MEM/WB boundary to shorten forward + regfile read paths\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\\nconsumers:\\n\\n  1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\\n     the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 fwd_rs?_sel mux \\u2192 is_auipc mux \\u2192\\n     ALU \\u2192 EX/MEM flop \\u2014 four mux levels before ALU input.\\n  2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\\n     ID-stage's regfile read path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 regfile bypass mux \\u2192 ID/EX flop\\n     \\u2014 two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\\n     rd matches.\\n\\nThat extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\\nplausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\\n1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\\ntransformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Fold MUL variants into single 33x33 signed multiplier with sign-ext mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\\non every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\\nmul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\\nmultiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\\ndedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\\non every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\\nmul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\\nmultiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\\ndedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su with a single 33-bit signed multiplier\\nwhose operand sign bits are muxed from op: MUL / MULH use signed*signed\\n(sign-extend both), MULHU uses unsigned*unsig...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Stateless IF-stage backward-taken branch prediction (BTFNT)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) eliminated the 2-cycle redirect\\nbubble for unconditional jumps. The next structural lever on the same\\naxis is conditional branches \\u2014 still paying a 2-cycle EX-redirect penalty\\nevery time a branch is taken. In CoreMark's hot loops (core_list_find,\\ncrcu8/crcu16 bit loops, core_bench_matrix nested loops, core_state state\\nmachines) the dominant control flow is loop-closing backward branches\\nthat are taken on every iteration except the last. A 5-iteration loop\\npays 2 bubbles \\u00d7 4 = 8 cycles of taken-branch redirect and 0 cycles on\\nthe exit-fallthrough; a 50-iteration loop pays 98 cycles of bubbles.\\n\\nStatic backwards-taken / forwards-not-taken (BTFNT) is the classic\\nprediction heuristic that captures this without any history: a BRANCH\\ninstruction whose sign-extended B-immediate is negative is almost\\ncertainly a loop edge. The r1s2 BTB lesson (broken, formal timeout)\\nwas that threading speculative state through the RVFI-observed payload\\nblows the per-insn BMC budget. The r2s2 lesson was the exact opposite\\npattern succeeds: a *stateless* predictor whose decision is a pure\\nfunction of the already-observed (PC, instr) pair costs zero formal\\nstate because EX can re-derive the IF-side decision from the same bits\\nit already has in ID/EX.\\n\\nOn CoreMark (~15% branch frequency, ~70% backward-taken), eliminating\\nthe 2-cycle bubble on backward-taken branches while paying a 2-cycle\\nbubble on the ~30% of backward branches that fall through (loop\\nexits, rare) is net-positive IPC. Rough estimate: 0.15 \\u00d7 0.70 \\u00d7 2 =\\n0.21 cycle savings per dynamic instr, offset by 0.15 \\u00d7 0.30 \\u00d7 2 = 0.09\\nnew mispredict cost \\u2248 0.12 cycle/instr net, i.e. ~8\\u201310% IPC win on\\ntop of the JAL baseline. Fmax impact is expected to be minimal:\\nthe IF-stage critical path...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"Stateless IF-stage BTFN conditional-branch predictor (reconstruct at EX)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous round's JAL predictor (hyp-20260502-003-r2s2, +5.87%)\\nconfirmed the \\\"provably correct by construction\\\" pattern: decode the\\ninstruction word at IF, redirect PC the same cycle, reconstruct the\\nprediction decision at EX from the same instruction bits, and narrow\\nthe EX-stage redirect signal to mispredicts. Zero new pipeline\\npayload bits, zero new formal state \\u2014 SBY proof time unchanged.\\n\\nJAL is now zero-bubble, but conditional branches (opcode 0x63) still\\npay the full 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch. In\\nCoreMark the inner hot loops (crcu8 loop, core_list_find reverse\\nwalk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k, core_state_transition's\\nbig switch) are dominated by backward loop-closing conditional\\nbranches that are taken ~90% of the time. Forward branches in\\nif/else-error paths are taken <20% of the time. Static BTFN\\n(Backward-Taken-Forward-Not-taken) captures both biases perfectly\\nand needs zero bits of history \\u2014 the prediction is a pure function\\nof the B-immediate's sign bit (instr[31]).\\n\\nPrior attempts and their lessons inform this design:\\n  - r1s2 (BTB): blew formal budget by threading `predicted`+`pred_target`\\n    through if_id_t/id_ex_t. AVOID payload fields.\\n  - r2s1 (JAL early-redirect with `early_jumped` flag): broke\\n    pc_fwd because gating EX `redirect` silenced the pc_wdata tap.\\n    AVOID: keep pc_next computation independent of the redirect\\n    assertion gate.\\n  - r2s2 (stateless JAL predictor): succeeded because IF's decision\\n    is a pure function of instruction bits, and EX reconstructs the\\n    exact same decision to decide whether to redirect. ADOPT this\\n    pattern verbatim, extended to branches.\\n\\nWith the JAL predictor already deployed, conditional branches are\\nthe next-biggest source of control-flow bubbles. Estimated\\ndensit...","metadata":{"matches":7,"truncated":false},"title":"divid|iterative|multi-cycle|critical path|pipelin.*mul","time":{"start":1777769670690,"end":1777769670728}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deb54666c001oYw1J3FGnJ1L2b","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","messageID":"msg_deb545920001ni3zIhjiqnL6ff"}}
