{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769804579,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Cq9QisGk78AqxdmYRAifyv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nwith open('cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl') as f:\n    for line in f:\n        try:\n            e = json.loads(line)\n            fm = e.get('fmax_mhz','?')\n            cm = e.get('coremark_iter_s','?')\n            fit = e.get('fitness','?')\n            print(f\\\"{e.get('id','?'):35s} {e.get('outcome','?'):12s} fit={fit} fmax={fm}\\\")\n        except: pass\n\"","description":"List fitness/fmax per experiment"},"output":"baseline-bench-2d376e0              improvement  fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-001-r1s0               regression   fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-002-r1s1               regression   fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-003-r1s2               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-001-r2s0               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-002-r2s1               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-003-r2s2               improvement  fit=318.71 fmax=141.58\nhyp-20260502-001-r3s0               improvement  fit=345.8 fmax=153.61\nhyp-20260502-002-r3s1               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-003-r3s2               broken       fit=? fmax=?\n","metadata":{"output":"baseline-bench-2d376e0              improvement  fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-001-r1s0               regression   fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-002-r1s1               regression   fit=301.04 fmax=135.21\nhyp-20260502-003-r1s2               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-001-r2s0               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-002-r2s1               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-003-r2s2               improvement  fit=318.71 fmax=141.58\nhyp-20260502-001-r3s0               improvement  fit=345.8 fmax=153.61\nhyp-20260502-002-r3s1               broken       fit=? fmax=?\nhyp-20260502-003-r3s2               broken       fit=? fmax=?\n","exit":0,"description":"List fitness/fmax per experiment","truncated":false},"title":"List fitness/fmax per experiment","time":{"start":1777769804576,"end":1777769804578}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the experimental results, I'm seeing a clear pattern emerge: the divider and multi-cycle approaches both regressed because the performance cost outweighed any benefits, while the stateless JAL and single DSP multiplication folding both showed solid improvements. The formal verification broke with the branch target predictor changes, so that's a separate issue to investigate.\n\nFor structural optimization, I'm reconsidering what actually matters. The multi-cycle M-unit hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax, and the branch prediction speculation broke formal verification. I'm thinking about a few non-speculative approaches instead: moving branch comparison to the ID stage to resolve branches earlier and reduce bubbles from 2 cycles to 1, computing PC+4 in the IF stage to eliminate that adder from the critical path in EX, or adding a proper IF/ID register to pipeline the combinational path between stages—though that last one trades deeper pipeline depth for higher Fmax, which could backfire with more hazards.\n\nLooking at the actual critical path now, I suspect it's not the ALU but the regfile read with write-first bypass logic. The current design has no IF/ID flop, so imem_data flows combinationally through decode, regfile read, and into the ID/EX register—that's a long chain. Adding an IF/ID register would break that path and likely boost Fmax significantly, but it adds a cycle to branch penalties. Alternatively, I could move the decoder to the IF stage as a pre-decode step, letting ID focus just on regfile reads and immediate generation, though both operations already happen in parallel in the current design.\n\nThe real bottleneck might be LUT saturation causing routing congestion at 10k LUTs. Converting the 32x32 regfile from distributed LUTs to BRAM blocks could save 400–500 LUTs and ease routing pressure. Gowin BRAMs don't natively support 2 asynchronous read ports, so I'd likely need to mirror the BRAM across two blocks to get dual reads while keeping the write-first bypass behavior.\n\nNow I'm weighing whether adding an IF/ID pipeline stage could break the critical path and gain 20–30% in Fmax. The trade-off is a deeper branch penalty: going from 2 cycles to 3 cycles when a branch is taken. I'm calculating whether the Fmax gain outweighs the extra branch misprediction cost in CoreMark—roughly 0.09 additional cycles per instruction, which might be offset by the frequency improvement.\n\nBut I'm uncertain whether IF→ID is actually the bottleneck. The real critical path could be in the MEM stage, where load data gets shifted and sign-extended, or in the register file with its dual read ports and write-first bypass logic. I'm leaning toward a safer approach: optimizing the load data alignment in the MEM stage by simplifying the barrel shifter and sign-extension logic, rather than restructuring the entire pipeline.\n\nActually, let me step back and consider something more concrete. I could move branch condition evaluation into the ID stage to resolve branches earlier, reducing the penalty of mispredicts and potentially freeing up the EX stage for other work. This is a different structural change that hasn't been explored yet and could yield real gains without the risk of adding a full pipeline stage.\n\nThe idea is to compute branch conditions in ID using the regfile reads, with forwarding from downstream stages to handle data dependencies. This would cut the taken-branch bubble from 2 cycles down to 1. The tradeoff is adding forwarding muxes to ID and more complex hazard detection—if a LOAD writes to one of the branch's source registers, we'd have to stall until the data arrives. It's non-speculative, so it shouldn't break formal verification the way the earlier speculative attempts did. The JAL predictor already handles unconditional jumps cleanly, so this would clean up the remaining conditional branch stalls.\n\nBut I'm realizing the forwarding-to-ID path gets messy: if the previous instruction is a LOAD, its result isn't ready until MEM, so we'd actually stall longer than we do now. And looking at the current pipeline, branch comparison and the branch-target adder already run in parallel with the ALU in EX, so they're not even on the critical path. Maybe there's a different structural change worth exploring instead—something like splitting the MEM stage's load alignment logic to reduce latency elsewhere. Moving the load data alignment and sign-extension into the writeback stage could trim the MEM critical path, though it's risky if MEM isn't actually the bottleneck. I'm reconsidering whether this is worth the effort given the M-extension timing issues we've already hit. Let me explore other structural improvements that haven't been attempted yet.\n\nCombining the hazard and forwarding units wouldn't help Fmax. Replacing the write-first bypass in the regfile with explicit WB-to-ID forwarding wouldn't be an improvement either—the current bypass already avoids needing an extra mux at the ID/EX boundary. Looking at the actual critical path on Tang Nano 20K at 153 MHz, the bottleneck could be anywhere from instruction decode and regfile reads, through the forwarding and ALU stages, to load data processing and writeback. I need to identify which of these five candidate paths is actually limiting frequency before making changes.\n\nThe decoder's nested case statement synthesizes into a large priority mux with 20-30 LUT4 levels, which could easily be the culprit. I could flatten it into a ROM-style lookup table indexed by opcode and function bits for potentially faster single-stage decoding, though that makes maintaining the illegal instruction default trickier. Alternatively, I could pipeline the decoder output earlier with an IF-to-IFD register, but that adds a stage which isn't ideal. Given that the successful hypotheses so far have involved structural reductions in the EX stage and JAL predictor, I should focus on something similarly concrete and area-reducing rather than just speculating about the decoder.\n\nThe multiplier pipelining idea won't work—r1s1 already tried it and regressed because the single-cycle mul is timing-tolerable and pipelining loses more IPC than it gains in Fmax. Sharing the ALU's variable shifter with the MEM stage's load-alignment shifter would save LUTs, but they're in different pipeline stages so literal sharing would break the pipeline. However, I can move the PC+4 adder computation from EX (where it's used for JAL/JALR return addresses) to IF where it's already being calculated for next_pc, removing an extra 32-bit adder from the EX critical path—a small rebalancing that should help Fmax slightly.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering early branch resolution in the ID stage with forwarding to cut the taken-branch penalty from 2 cycles to 1. This isn't speculation—it's a concrete calculation in ID that determines the actual branch outcome, which IF then uses to redirect. The real constraint is handling data hazards: if an instruction in EX or MEM writes to the branch's source registers, I'd need to either forward the result or stall. For a load-to-branch case, the load's result isn't ready until MEM, so the branch would need to stall 2 cycles waiting for it—worse than the current 1-cycle load-use stall, which makes this approach problematic.\n\nLooking at the cycle-by-cycle timing, when a load immediately precedes a branch, both designs end up with roughly 3 cycles of overhead: the current design takes 1 stall plus 2 redirect bubbles, while the proposed design takes 2 stalls plus 1 bubble. Since about half of CoreMark's branches follow loads, the actual gain shrinks to maybe 0.045 cycles per instruction—around 2% IPC improvement—which isn't compelling enough to justify the added complexity and potential formal verification issues.\n\nLet me reconsider the approach entirely. What if instead I remove the write-first bypass from the regfile and rely on the existing forwarding unit to handle all MEM/WB cases? The regfile read would become a simple lookup without the combinational mux from the write data, shortening the critical path and reducing area. The forward_unit already catches same-cycle writes via its MEM/WB forwarding case, so nothing should break—though I'd need to verify that no existing paths depend on the bypass and ensure the forwarding logic covers all scenarios. The issue is that without write-first bypass in the regfile, an instruction in the ID stage reading a register that's being written by WB will get stale data, and by the time it reaches EX, the forwarding unit won't catch it since WB has already moved past. I'd need to add forwarding logic elsewhere—either on the ID/EX write path or ID output path—which defeats the purpose of removing bypass.\n\nI'm going in circles here. Let me settle on something concrete: moving the PC+4 return address computation from EX to IF stage. It's a small optimization that reuses the next-PC calculation already happening in IF, reducing adder pressure in EX for JAL/JALR instructions. Probably gains 1-3% on Fmax, but honestly that's marginal.\n\nActually, the bigger idea is worth pursuing: eliminate the rs1_val and rs2_val latches in the ID/EX register by making them combinational pass-throughs directly from the regfile to the EX operand muxes. But that's standard practice anyway—keeping those latches is fine and expected.\n\nI'll go with the load-extend-to-WB approach instead.\n\nMoving load data alignment and sign/zero extension from MEM to WB stage is a classic pipeline rebalancing. MEM just captures the raw word from memory along with the address bits and control signals, then WB handles the shift, extend, and mux logic. This shortens MEM's critical path while WB was mostly idle anyway, so the pipeline becomes better balanced and Fmax should improve. The functional behavior stays the same—RVFI observations are unaffected since mem_rdata remains raw and rd_wdata is still the final written value.\n\nI need to update the MEM stage to remove shift/extend logic and capture raw data plus metadata, modify the mem_wb_t struct to carry the low address bits and control signals, and add the shift/extend logic to WB before the final mux.\n\nBut wait—there's a forwarding issue. The forward path from MEM/WB to EX now includes the shift logic, which adds delay to the forwarding mux and actually lengthens the EX critical path instead of helping. That defeats the purpose.\n\nLet me reconsider. A cleaner structural win would be moving branch resolution earlier to the ID stage with proper load-use stall handling—that's a well-established optimization that actually reduces the taken-branch bubble without creating new critical path problems.\n\nThe approach: branches resolve in ID using real forwarded data (no speculation), JAL stays in IF, JALR stays in EX since it needs rs1. ID gets a comparator and target adder, then asserts an early redirect to IF. Formally this should be cleaner than the r3s2 issues since we're not coupling branch_taken to imem_data—just using real data in ID to drive a sequential redirect.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the RVFI semantics: pc_wdata for branches moves from EX to ID, and the MEM/WB register just carries pc_next through. Same semantics, just resolved earlier. The IF stage's next_pc logic currently takes redirect from EX, but with early branch resolution in ID, that redirect signal would come from ID instead. This is the key structural change—moving where the redirect originates—and it should reduce the taken-branch penalty from 2 cycles to 1.\n\nThe implementation is concrete: add a branch comparator in ID that combinationally computes branch_taken from the regfile reads, then assert early_redirect back to IF to flush the wrong-path instruction. The existing load-use hazard detection already covers the case where a LOAD is in EX and a branch is entering ID, so that stall mechanism carries over. I'm ready to commit this and start modifying the id_stage module.\n\nBut now I'm realizing the critical path concern—adding an ALU comparator and forwarding paths into ID could hurt Fmax significantly, which might offset the 3-5% IPC gain from reducing branch bubbles. The tradeoff isn't obvious. Let me step back and explore a different angle instead of pushing through with the branch resolution move.\n\nI considered using a shared barrel shifter or DSP blocks for shift operations, but those don't work—the shifter stages are separate, and DSPs are already committed to the multiplier. A dedicated half-word multiplier would just undo prior optimization work.\n\nGiven all the constraints, I'm going to commit to the ID-stage early branch resolution. It's a clean, classical approach that targets the biggest remaining opportunity, and since it's non-speculative, the formal verification should hold up. Time to write the YAML spec.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb566f54001X8Xf4UpeEZKboe","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","messageID":"msg_deb548c08001nj4bimnTpzXghZ"}}
