{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769969591,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01LkdELoniw4Qu8DipqznC7n","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r4s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r4s1\ntitle: \"Pre-decode in IF + insert IF/ID register: 6-stage pipeline to break imem_data->decode->id_ex_reg critical path\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  Fitness history shows Fmax is the dominant lever: JAL predictor (r2s2)\n  and DSP fold (r3s0) both won primarily via Fmax (135.21 -> 141.58 ->\n  153.61 MHz, tracking 1:1 with fitness). Conversely r1s0/r1s1 (divider,\n  multi-cycle M-unit) regressed despite targeting EX-stage arithmetic,\n  proving the EX LUT path (now DSP-consolidated) is NOT the current\n  ceiling. The remaining deepest combinational window is the IF->ID\n  path: in today's 5-stage the only register between the FPGA BRAM's\n  output flop (imem_data) and id_ex_reg is a full cycle containing\n  (a) the decoder's ~20-arm case statement producing 15 control bits,\n  (b) the 32-bit imm_gen, (c) the 32x32 regfile distributed-LUT read\n  with write-first bypass mux, and (d) the ctrl_t packing into\n  id_ex_reg. That is easily 10-15 LUT4 levels on Gowin GW2A, which at\n  ~0.35 ns/LUT plus routing is right at the 6.5 ns period of 153 MHz.\n  Until this path is split, neither JAL-nor-DSP-class optimizations\n  can unlock the next Fmax tier; both r3s1 and r3s2 already confirmed\n  that speculative branch prediction cannot close under SBY, so the\n  remaining structural move is pipeline-depth rebalance.\n\n  At LUT4=9865/target 10000 we also have routing-pressure evidence\n  (seed-to-seed Fmax variance was ~15 MHz before r3s0 settled it),\n  which a shallower per-stage logic depth directly relieves.\nhypothesis: |\n  Convert the 5-stage IF->ID->EX->MEM->WB pipeline to a 6-stage\n  IF->IFD->ID->EX->MEM->WB by inserting a new IFD pipeline register\n  whose payload is ALREADY-DECODED control. Specifically:\n\n  1. Move the decoder, imm_gen, and the JAL-target pre-computation into\n     the IF stage. IF now outputs combinationally {pc, instr, ctrl, imm,\n     rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rd, valid} — all pure functions of imem_data +\n     pc that today happen in ID. The JAL static predictor stays exactly\n     where it is (it was never on the IF->ID critical path, it's on the\n     pc-reg-self-feedback path).\n  2. Add a new `if_id_t` as a REGISTERED struct (flipped from its current\n     combinational-bundle role in core_pkg.sv) holding the IF-stage\n     combinational outputs. Latched at the IF->IFD edge.\n  3. Shrink id_stage to a single job: regfile read (using the registered\n     rs1_addr / rs2_addr from IFD) + build id_ex_reg. No decode work.\n     The regfile's write-first bypass stays as-is for WB-to-ID RAW.\n  4. hazard_unit's load-use check now compares `ifd_reg.rs?_addr` vs\n     `id_ex_reg.rd` (one cycle later in wall-time but same relative\n     distance in pipeline slots — semantics preserved).\n  5. EX-resolved redirect must flush one additional stage (IFD in\n     addition to IF-comb and ID). flush_ifd asserted on the same\n     condition as flush_id today.\n  6. The JAL predictor's redirect latency vs instruction flow is\n     unchanged: JAL is still decoded in IF on the cycle its word\n     returns from imem; IF still redirects PC same cycle. The JAL\n     itself just rides through one extra register (IFD) before ID.\n     Zero-bubble JAL is preserved.\n  7. RVFI semantics are identical: retirement still observed at\n     MEM/WB, rvfi_order +1 per retirement, pc_wdata computed in EX\n     exactly as today. Only wall-clock latency of a single instruction\n     grows by 1 cycle; steady-state IPC in a hazard-free stream is\n     unchanged.\n\n  Expected trade-off (back-of-envelope):\n  - Fmax: the per-cycle logic depth on the (imem_data -> id_ex_reg)\n    path is halved (IF cycle: decode + imm_gen; IFD->ID cycle: regfile\n    read + ctrl pack), target +15-25% Fmax (153 -> ~180-190 MHz).\n  - IPC: taken-branch penalty rises from 2 to 3 cycles (flush\n    IF-comb + IFD + ID on EX redirect). CoreMark has ~9% dynamic\n    taken conditional branches post-JAL-predictor, so +0.09\n    cycles/instr on a baseline of ~2.5 cycles/instr = ~3.6% IPC loss.\n    JAL (~3%) stays zero-bubble via the existing IF predictor.\n    JALR (~0.3%) stays at 2-cycle EX redirect (now 3-cycle), small.\n    Load-use stall: unchanged at 1 cycle (the stall is between ID/EX\n    and IFD now; same slot count, just one cycle later in wall-time).\n  - Net fitness: +10 to +20% if Fmax hits +15%.\n\n  Formal risk (learned from prior rounds):\n  - r1s2/r3s1/r3s2's failure mode was SPECULATIVE state or\n    branch-direction-correlated redirect breaking BMC induction.\n    THIS hypothesis adds zero speculation: IFD just registers\n    already-committed decode output. rvfi_valid_0 reachability\n    through symbolic fetch streams is identical — the pipe is one\n    stage deeper but every stage is deterministic.\n  - r2s0's failure was a specific RVFI-tap plumbing bug (rd_wdata\n    field renamed without re-pointing io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0). THIS\n    hypothesis doesn't rename any RVFI-observed mem_wb_t field.\n  - The only new SBY concern is symbolic liveness across the added\n    stage — riscv-formal's liveness check is parameterized by a\n    bound; 1 extra stage is absorbed trivially within the existing\n    20-step BMC depth.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 12\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend if_id_t into a REGISTERED payload: add fields ctrl (ctrl_t), imm ([31:0]), rs1_addr/rs2_addr/rd ([4:0]). These were previously decoded inside id_stage from the combinational instr.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate decoder + imm_gen in IF stage. Output the full if_id_t struct combinationally (pc, instr, ctrl, imm, rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rd, valid). Retain existing JAL static predictor on the pc-update path. Adapt flush/redirect handling so the new IFD register captures NOP ctrl on flush (decoder on NOP yields reg_write=0, is_illegal=0).\"\n  - file: rtl/ifd_stage.sv\n    description: \"New module: single pipeline register that captures if_id_t on posedge clock. Inputs: stall (hold), flush (load '0). Drives registered outputs to id_stage and hazard_unit. Under 40 LOC.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Strip decoder + imm_gen instances. Now only drives regfile read addresses (from registered rs1_addr/rs2_addr) and builds id_ex_reg from the registered ctrl + regfile-read data + passed-through pc/imm/rd/rs?_addr/instr/valid.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Load-use check uses ifd_reg.rs?_addr (replaces if_id_w.instr[19:15/24:20]). Add flush_ifd output asserted on redirect. Branch-redirect flush now covers 3 slots: IF-comb (flush_if), IFD (flush_ifd), ID (flush_id).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Re-wire top-level: if_stage -> ifd_stage -> id_stage -> ex_stage -> mem_stage -> wb_stage. Route flush_ifd/stall_ifd signals. RVFI taps remain at mem_wb_w (unchanged — every io_rvfi_*_0 observation point is identical to today).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Update cycle-timing probes: retirement of instruction N now occurs at cycle N+5 in a hazard-free stream (was N+4). Existing cocotb assertions on rvfi_order and per-channel _0 suffix are semantically unchanged; only wall-clock offsets shift.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r4s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r4s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777769969578,"end":1777769969589}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" So r2s0 was exactly what I had in mind, but it failed—the lesson was clear about needing to re-point the top-level RVFI taps. I need to try a different structural approach instead of repeating that same solution. Since the MEM/WB pre-register attempt in r2s0 broke things, and the forward/bypass logic might have been the underlying issue, I should explore whether that's actually the right direction.\n\nLooking at what's worked before, the successful optimizations all targeted the EX stage—the DSP folding for area, the JAL predictor to eliminate bubbles. So what else can I optimize there? I'm considering splitting the shifter into its own 2-cycle pipeline since barrel shifting is LUT-heavy on Gowin, but that would hurt IPC on every shift operation, and shifts are frequent in CoreMark. Merging the hazard and forward units wouldn't help Fmax either. But adding an IF/ID pipeline register to break up the long combinational path from instruction memory through decode to the ID/EX register—that hasn't been tried yet. It would deepen the pipeline to 6 stages, increase branch penalty from 2 to 3 cycles, but potentially gain 20-30% on Fmax. The IPC hit would be around 3-6%, but the net fitness gain could be 15-24%, which is significant. The new IFR register would hold the instruction and PC, ready to feed into decode.\n\nFor JAL to stay 0-bubble, the decode happens in IF as it does now with the same-cycle PC redirect, then the JAL flows through IFR, ID, and EX normally—just one stage later. Conditional branches would see a 3-cycle bubble instead of 2 when resolved in EX. The RVFI formal semantics should remain unchanged since those fields still come from MEM/WB. The main risks are implementation complexity and test surface area, but this directly addresses the likely Fmax bottleneck. However, I'm second-guessing whether adding flops and control logic for the multiplexing will actually help when LUT saturation might already be the limiting factor at 9865 LUTs against a 10000 target. A lower-risk alternative would be inserting a pipeline register just for the decoder output rather than splitting the entire IF/ID boundary.\n\nActually, the real insight is that the BRAM latency is already external—the PC drives the address in cycle N and data returns in cycle N+1, so by the time imem_data reaches id_ex_reg, one clock has already passed. The critical path is really just the combinational logic from BRAM output through decoder and regfile into id_ex_reg. Adding an if_id_reg would register imem_data and PC before the decoder, stretching decode across two cycles but halving the logic per cycle and breaking that critical path. Since imem_data and PC don't need preprocessing, I can just register them directly—this adds a flop but gives the decoder and regfile read a full cycle to complete.\n\nBetter yet, I'll pre-decode the instruction in the IF stage itself, latching the control signals into if_id_reg rather than the raw instruction. That way the first cycle handles the combinational decode, and the ID stage only needs to do regfile read and immediate generation, balancing the workload across both stages.\n\nDefining the if_id_reg structure...\n\nActually, the immediate can be extracted combinationally from the instruction too, so IF effectively becomes fetch + decode + immediate generation, with ID reduced to just regfile read before passing to EX. The hazard detection shifts by a cycle since it now reads from the registered instruction fields instead of combinational ones, which complicates things.\n\nThis is getting unwieldy. Let me step back and propose something more focused: pipelining the ALU's barrel shifter into two stages. The 32-bit variable shifter is a resource hog and likely a critical path bottleneck. Breaking it into two stages—first shifting by the high bits of the shift amount, then the low bits—would ease timing, though it'd stall dependent shifts by one cycle. For CoreMark, shifts are maybe 5-10% of instructions, so the IPC penalty would be minimal.\n\nBut actually, Gowin handles shifts reasonably well with DSP blocks, and the r3s0 changes already consolidate DSP usage for multiplication. The shifter stays on LUTs anyway, so this might not be worth the complexity.\n\nLet me commit to something concrete: moving branch resolution earlier into the ID stage. This is a classic MIPS optimization—the comparator and target adder move to ID, using forwarded data from EX and MEM/WB stages. Taken-branch penalty drops from 2 cycles to 1, gaining 3-5% IPC, though the new forwarding path to ID might cost 5% in Fmax, netting around neutral or slightly positive overall.\n\nThe Fmax risk is concerning though. Let me go with the safer option: adding an IF/ID pipeline register to create a 6-stage pipeline. This scales Fmax better without the forwarding complexity. RVFI observations stay at MEM/WB, so no formal semantics change. Branch redirects flush three stages, load-use detection shifts one stage later but works the same way, and the JAL predictor continues operating in IF unchanged. This feels like the right move—committing to the YAML now.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb585e44001WEt53rJxtT4s94","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","messageID":"msg_deb57a983001XXcz1TP2RcjEmV"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769969595,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","part":{"id":"prt_deb585863001k3d3B8A8okw1Wu","messageID":"msg_deb57a983001XXcz1TP2RcjEmV","sessionID":"ses_214ac9e5cffeU2A2fUH6dUGm1x","type":"text","text":"I have a clear picture now. Key insights:\n- Fmax is the dominant fitness lever (both winning hypotheses moved Fmax: JAL=+4.7% Fmax, DSP-fold=+8.5% Fmax)\n- r2s0 already tried pre-register rd_wdata and broke it (avoid rehash)\n- r1s0/r1s1 showed the divider is NOT the critical path\n- r3s1/r3s2 broke formal via speculative prediction\n- Current critical path likely runs: BRAM out → `imem_data` → decoder case (wide) + regfile read → `id_ex_reg` — this is a ~full cycle of combinational logic through deep case statements\n\nLet me propose a structural pipeline-depth change: insert an IF/ID register with pre-decode in IF, turning the 5-stage into a 6-stage pipeline. This is a legitimately fresh structural angle that targets the most likely Fmax bottleneck.","time":{"start":1777769928803,"end":1777769969593}}}
