{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770508083,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"id":"prt_deb612ab7001fu8zDvn9Xata6u","messageID":"msg_deb60899f0019SAFHHDv2PkHh0","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation:\n- Current fitness 345.80 came from a structural DSP-consolidation win (r3s0, +8.5%)\n- Recent failures: branch predictors (formal coupling), pipeline-depth changes (test_pipeline rollback), unified subtractor (broken), always-taken branches (didn't occur dynamically)\n- Category is `structural`\n\nLet me check what's in alu.sv around the divider more carefully — and scan log.jsonl for prior divider attempts.","time":{"start":1777770506935,"end":1777770508082}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777770508119,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01JUc9AK4xAVKUQ95ZNDNuSc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -l \"divider|sequential.div|iterative.div|multi.cycle.div\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Search for prior divider hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Search for prior divider hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"Search for prior divider hypotheses","time":{"start":1777770508107,"end":1777770508117}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent failures and successes, I can see that branch predictor changes with symbolic fetch coupling caused formal verification issues, while pipeline depth modifications broke the test suite. The MUL consolidation was a clear win with an 8.50% improvement, and the fitness metric has already jumped significantly from 301 to 345, so I need to build on what's working and avoid the pitfalls that derailed previous attempts.\n\nThe structural opportunities I'm considering are consolidating redundant adders across the ALU, branch target, and JAL paths, optimizing the critical path through the EX stage, simplifying register file bypass logic, and potentially combining the shifters for SLL/SRL/SRA operations into a single barrel shifter. The r4s0 attempt at unifying the EX-stage subtractor failed, so I need to be more careful about what I merge.\n\nI'm noticing that the load data path has a variable shift operation that likely synthesizes inefficiently—replacing that with a direct 4:1 mux to select the appropriate byte or halfword could help. Another angle is separating the M-extension operations into their own module so the base ALU stays lean and can potentially reach higher clock frequencies, though I'm realizing the DIV operation is combinational and that might complicate things.\n\nLooking at the combinational division more carefully—Yosys does support `/` through structural cells, and while the baseline hit 153 MHz, division could still be a bottleneck. Making DIV multi-cycle with a restoring divider would free up the critical path significantly, though it adds pipeline complexity and a new stall condition. The tradeoff seems worth it since CoreMark has very few DIV instructions anyway.\n\nNow I'm considering a different angle: replacing the variable byte-lane shifter with an explicit 4:1 mux on the address bits—that should synthesize cleaner than the dynamic shift operation. I'm also thinking about folding the branch comparator into the ALU's SUB path since they're doing redundant work, though that was attempted before and caused issues.\n\nThe real structural win I'm seeing is consolidating all the 32-bit adders scattered across the EX stage—there's ALU ADD/SUB, AUIPC, JAL target computation, branch target, JALR target, and PC+4. That's a lot of redundant adder logic that could be unified into a single adder with a mux on the operands.\n\nBut the strongest candidate for a real improvement is moving to a sequential divider instead of keeping the combinational one in the ALU. The combinational divider is probably killing the critical path and eating up area on the Gowin GW2A, especially since it's just one of 19 ALU operations. A multi-cycle iterative divider would drop area significantly and improve Fmax, and CoreMark barely uses division anyway so the IPC hit is minimal. The tradeoff is needing to wire up stall signaling through the hazard unit, but that's manageable and touches multiple files in a way that counts as a real structural change. I'm settling on the cleanest approach: create a separate `divider.sv` module that operates iteratively, instantiate it in the EX stage alongside the ALU, and when a divide operation is decoded, assert the divider's start signal and stall the pipeline until the result is ready—this keeps the ALU combinational and avoids cascading interface changes throughout the design.\n\nFor ALTOPS mode, the divider stays unused since the ALU's synthetic XOR output handles it; in normal operation, the divider produces the real result and overrides the ALU output.\n\nI expect this to significantly improve Fmax since divide is a long combinational path on FPGA, and CoreMark has minimal divide instructions, so the IPC hit should be negligible—estimating around +8% fitness gain overall.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb612bd7001djglpdqIHNl8CO","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","messageID":"msg_deb60899f0019SAFHHDv2PkHh0"}}
