{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777770513935,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"id":"prt_deb61460a001JLB3XMUg7346ux","messageID":"msg_deb6137dc001bVyR8Ea4Gt7HVL","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","snapshot":"c72ef0fe98d3688f4f17201ff4f94f18805d2f42","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770551127,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"id":"prt_deb614dcc001DnAe1XzHiYAEcn","messageID":"msg_deb6137dc001bVyR8Ea4Gt7HVL","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","type":"text","text":"No prior divider attempts. The combinational `a / b` and `a % b` in alu.sv are almost certainly the longest path in EX and a major LUT4 consumer on GW2A — while CoreMark has essentially zero dynamic divides. This mirrors the r3s0 win (consolidating DSP-heavy arithmetic) and is a clean structural play.","time":{"start":1777770515916,"end":1777770551126}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777770551141,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016onN4r4t8GDNm7pxmawpp6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r5s1\ntitle: \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative 32-cycle sequential divider module\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\n  SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\n  these to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\n  deep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A — both a large LUT4\n  consumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in\n  the EX stage (32-bit restoring division fanning into the ALU\n  output mux, which then feeds EX/MEM's alu_result register plus\n  the forwarding path to the next cycle's EX operand muxes).\n\n  Meanwhile CoreMark is an integer benchmark dominated by list\n  traversal, matrix multiply, and CRC/state transitions; its\n  dynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM ops.\n  So whatever Fmax and LUT budget is being spent on the\n  combinational divider is pure waste for this fitness function.\n\n  The successful r3s0 hypothesis (+8.50% from folding 3 DSP18\n  multipliers into 1) established the pattern: identify EX-stage\n  arithmetic structures whose current implementation over-spends\n  FPGA resources, and consolidate/sequentialize them. The divider\n  is the most egregious remaining instance — a single 32-bit\n  combinational divide is worth more LUT4s than the rest of the\n  ALU combined and sits on the EX critical path.\n\n  Current fitness 345.80 at 153.61 MHz; Fmax target is 135 MHz\n  (we're already over) but Gowin timing closure on GW2A tightens\n  sharply above 150 MHz — removing the combinational divider\n  should push Fmax materially further.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of alu.sv's combinational case\n  arms and into a new `divider.sv` module — a 32-cycle iterative\n  restoring divider that stalls the pipeline while it works.\n\n  Microarchitecture:\n    - `divider.sv`: inputs (start, a, b, op[1:0] selecting\n      DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), outputs (busy, done, result[31:0]).\n      Classic shift-subtract state machine with one 33-bit\n      subtract per cycle; handles RV32M corner cases (divide-by-0,\n      INT_MIN/-1 overflow) at result-mux time so the iterative\n      core is pure unsigned restoring division. ~32 cycles per\n      operation.\n    - `ex_stage.sv`: instantiate divider alongside the existing\n      ALU. Detect divide ops from ctrl.alu_op. On decode of a\n      DIV/REM, assert divider.start for one cycle; raise a new\n      `div_stall` output while divider.busy is high; when\n      divider.done fires, override alu_result with divider.result\n      for the cycle of capture into EX/MEM.\n    - `hazard_unit.sv`: accept `div_busy` as a new stall input;\n      assert `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem` for the\n      duration (same pattern as dmem_stall — hold all upstream\n      stages, hold EX/MEM register, clear MEM/WB valid).\n    - `core.sv`: wire `div_busy` from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\n    - `alu.sv`: in the non-ALTOPS branch, replace the four\n      DIV*/REM* case arms with `out = 32'b0` (don't care — EX\n      stage will override from divider output). Keep the ALTOPS\n      branch bit-identical (XOR stand-ins stay combinational) so\n      the formal proof path is unchanged and SBY still completes\n      inside its 1800s budget.\n    - Preserve the ALU's combinational MUL path verbatim (r3s0's\n      shared DSP18 stays) — only DIV/REM become sequential.\n\n  Why this keeps formal tractable:\n    - ALTOPS mode (what `make formal` actually runs) keeps\n      DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as simple XOR stand-ins in both alu.sv\n      and riscv-formal's spec, so no iterative state machine\n      enters the BMC depth — formal sees the same\n      single-cycle-retirement pattern it sees today.\n    - The stall integration mirrors the existing dmem_stall\n      pattern exactly, which is already proven under formal.\n    - No new RVFI-observable pipeline payload bits — div_busy is\n      a purely internal handshake. Avoids the r1s2 class of\n      state-space blowup failures.\n    - RVFI retirement still happens at MEM/WB; the divide just\n      takes multiple cycles where rvfi_valid_0 stays low (same\n      as any other stall), then retires normally.\n\n  Why this keeps cosim/CoreMark correct:\n    - `test/test_alu.py` has 30+ vectors per M-ext op. Divider\n      result-mux handles all RV32M corner cases identically to\n      the current combinational path.\n    - Real arithmetic mode (cosim against reference.py) diffs\n      each retired DIV/REM field-by-field — unchanged.\n    - CoreMark's 6 KB run executes the divider maybe a handful\n      of times at most (certainly not inside the hot loops),\n      so IPC impact on the bracketed-region cycle count is\n      negligible (~dozens of extra cycles against millions).\n\n  Expected cost/benefit:\n    - Fmax: +5-10 MHz from removing the biggest EX-stage\n      combinational tree. On a 153 MHz baseline, +5 MHz is\n      ~+3%; +10 MHz is ~+6.5%.\n    - LUT4: 32-cycle iterative divider is ~200-300 LUT4s vs\n      ~800-1200 LUT4s for the combinational `$div`, so a net\n      LUT4 reduction that may open further P&R freedom.\n    - IPC: near-zero impact (CoreMark has near-zero DIVs).\n    - Net fitness: projected +5 to +8%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/divider.sv\n    description: \"New module. 32-cycle iterative restoring divider with one 33-bit subtractor per cycle. Inputs: clock, reset, start, a[31:0], b[31:0], op[1:0] (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU). Outputs: busy, done (1-cycle pulse), result[31:0]. Handles divide-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow at the result-mux stage. Unsigned core with sign-fixup wrappers for DIV/REM.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"In the non-ALTOPS branch, replace the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case arms with `out = 32'b0` (result is overridden by ex_stage from the divider module). Keep ALTOPS branch bit-identical. Keep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU's shared-DSP18 path exactly as r3s0 left it. Preserve combinational interface.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate divider. Detect divide ops from ctrl.alu_op. Pulse divider.start for one cycle on initial decode of DIV/REM; drive `div_stall` output while divider.busy is high. Mux divider.result into reg_q.alu_result on the cycle divider.done fires (otherwise use ALU's combinational output). Handle the stall-triggered re-entry of the same EX instruction: start only fires on the rising edge of a new divide.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add `div_busy` input. Raise stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb while div_busy is asserted (same pattern as dmem_stall). Ensure dmem_stall and div_stall compose correctly (either triggers the same set of holds).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire div_busy from ex_stage into hazard_unit. No changes to RVFI port set or top-level IO.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Update ALU test harness if the DIV/REM tests still probe `out` directly from alu.sv — retarget those vectors to exercise the new divider module standalone, or exercise DIV/REM through the full EX stage via test_pipeline.py-style stimulus. Preserve all 30+ RV32M corner-case vectors (divide-by-0, INT_MIN/-1, signed/unsigned discipline).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777770551121,"end":1777770551139}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" The division and modulo operations in the ALU are likely creating the critical path in the execute stage since 32-bit division involves a long chain of subtract-compare operations, but CoreMark doesn't actually use dynamic divides much—it's mostly bitwise manipulation, matrix operations, and list processing—so the performance impact is minimal. The FPGA synthesis timing is being cut off here, but this seems to be analyzing whether the divider is actually a bottleneck.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb615090001AlRXxrXs88mC85","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","messageID":"msg_deb6137dc001bVyR8Ea4Gt7HVL"}}
