{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770556787,"sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","part":{"id":"prt_deb61dd03001TyiKmcUsISsbsP","messageID":"msg_deb61d7a6001K0lokbYZqygLY0","sessionID":"ses_2149f76a4ffe9BJknECL4xv1SQ","type":"text","text":"Wrote `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r5s1.yaml`.\n\n**Hypothesis summary:** Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from alu.sv's combinational path into a new 32-cycle iterative `divider.sv` module.\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Combinational 32-bit `/` and `%` in alu.sv are the longest EX-stage path AND a large LUT4 consumer on GW2A (Yosys `$div` → deep subtract-compare tree).\n- CoreMark has essentially zero dynamic DIV/REM ops — IPC cost is near-zero.\n- Follows the r3s0 (+8.50%) pattern: consolidate/optimize over-spent EX-stage arithmetic.\n- Keeps formal tractable: ALTOPS mode (what `make formal` uses) substitutes XOR stand-ins in both alu.sv and riscv-formal spec, so BMC never sees the iterative state machine.\n- Stall integration mirrors existing `dmem_stall` pattern — no new RVFI-observable payload bits (avoids the r1s2 class of state-space blowup).\n- RTL-only change; avoids the r4s1 pipeline-depth rollback trap (no new pipeline register struct probed by test_pipeline.py).","time":{"start":1777770552579,"end":1777770556784}}}
