{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777771655914,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","part":{"id":"prt_deb72b2e8001C5w1d9wvfv2VOC","messageID":"msg_deb729f0b001NncaZcRDKPmhJC","sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","snapshot":"127c54179551782ef9984e30ee038035adb2e21a","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777771755789,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","part":{"id":"prt_deb7430b3001yAakjlcC56cFTQ","messageID":"msg_deb729f0b001NncaZcRDKPmhJC","sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation:\n- Current best: 376.19, baseline: 301.04\n- Category: structural (diversity slot)\n- Recent successful structural moves: r3s0 (mul DSP consolidation +8.5%), r5s1 (iterative divider +8.79%) — both removed redundant EX-stage combinational arithmetic\n- Recent failures: predictors (symbolic-fetch traps), RAS (payload widening cost Fmax), pipeline depth changes (break test_pipeline.py probes)\n\nThe pattern that consistently wins is **consolidating redundant combinational arithmetic in EX** without touching the pipeline payload or formal state.\n\nLet me check the ALU shifter implementation:","time":{"start":1777771753651,"end":1777771755788}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777771755795,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01NqKEXpBDQkBwGMWXJ4mLFV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"ALU_SLL|ALU_SRL|ALU_SRA|shamt","path":"cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv"},"output":"Found 5 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/rtl/alu.sv:\n  Line 24:   logic        [4:0]  shamt;\n\n  Line 50:     shamt = b[4:0];\n\n  Line 70:       ALU_SLL:    out = a << shamt;\n\n  Line 71:       ALU_SRL:    out = a >> shamt;\n\n  Line 72:       ALU_SRA:    out = $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt);\n","metadata":{"matches":5,"truncated":false},"title":"ALU_SLL|ALU_SRL|ALU_SRA|shamt","time":{"start":1777771755769,"end":1777771755792}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the structural category outcomes, the DIV extraction showed solid gains at nearly 9%, while the RAS change tanked performance by 60% and the branch predictor hurt by almost 8%. The regfile LUTRAM was essentially neutral. Current best fitness sits at 376.19 with a core frequency of 167.11 MHz, so I'm starting to see which structural modifications actually help versus which ones degrade the design.\n\nFrom what's working, SP/arithmetic consolidation proved effective, and I need to avoid touching the RVFI payload and pipeline depth since those are being probed. The EX-stage critical path is clearly a constraint. Now I'm examining the remaining structural inefficiencies: the regfile LUTRAM attempt failed before due to sync reset issues, the shifter could be optimized, the branch comparator might be simplified, and most importantly, the load data extraction is using a barrel shifter for what should really be a simple 4-to-1 byte multiplexer based on address bits. The byte-lane mask follows the same wasteful pattern. The ALU itself is a bottleneck with multiple operations—multiply, shift, add, compare—all competing through a single output mux, and the load address path feeds directly to memory combinationally, which could be hitting Fmax limits.\n\nLooking at the branch comparator specifically, I could potentially reuse the ALU's existing subtractor and SLT logic instead of building separate 32-bit comparators for each branch type. The key insight is that BEQ/BNE can be handled by checking if the subtraction result is zero, and BLT/BGE can use the SLT output directly. This would mean decoding branch operations to drive the ALU's operation select, letting the ALU do the comparison work rather than duplicating that logic—though I'd need to handle the branch target calculation separately since that still needs PC+immediate.\n\nA more practical win is replacing the variable shifter in the memory stage's load-data extraction with an explicit 4:1 byte multiplexer. The current approach of `dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0] * 8)` should theoretically fold down to a mux, but in practice Yosys sometimes infers it as a barrel shifter, which wastes area and adds delay. An explicit mux would be cleaner and faster.\n\nThe real question is whether this shift is even on the critical path. Since the BRAM is zero-wait, the bottleneck is actually the shift and sign-extension logic running combinationally between the memory read and the MEM/WB register. Moving the load-data extension into the WB stage could help — the MEM/WB register would just hold the raw BRAM output plus control bits, then WB expands it. This would clean up the MEM stage's combinational path, though it does require adjusting the mem_wb_t layout and verifying RVFI observability still works correctly.\n\nBut there's a forwarding problem: if WB does the shift and sign-extend, then fwd_mem_wb includes that work, which means the EX stage's forwarding mux gets fed by a longer combinational chain (MEM/WB register → WB shift+sext → EX mux → ALU → EX/MEM register). That's a pretty long path and might not be worth it.\n\nLet me explore a different angle — maybe consolidating the branch comparator with the ALU could help. The branch logic needs six comparison variants, and while the ALU already has SLT/SLTU, adding BEQ/BNE as a simple XOR-reduce is cheap, but the ALU already has XOR available.\n\nActually, I could use the ALU's subtractor output directly: route the SUB result through branch condition logic to extract zero and sign flags for BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE. But modifying the ALU is risky. The simpler approach is just computing equality, signed less-than, and unsigned less-than, then muxing based on branch_op — which is what the code already does, and the synthesizer should optimize it well enough.\n\nI should focus on what actually moved the needle before. The DSP consolidation and sequential divider both removed wide combinational logic from EX. Looking at what else is wide there: the shifter has three separate 32-bit barrel shifters for SLL, SRL, and SRA. Yosys might share them, but consolidating to a single bidirectional shifter could help.\n\nI'm thinking about a unified shifter that reverses bits for left shifts, computes right/arithmetic shifts uniformly, then reverses the output back for SLL — this would share one 32-bit shifter across all three operations and probably save around 400 LUT4s. The cocotb tests already validate ALU correctness, so refactoring shouldn't break anything.\n\nActually, looking at the current implementation more carefully, Yosys typically does share these shift operations into `$shift` or `$shl/$shr/$sshr` cells, though the GW2A synthesizer might not. But there's a more impactful angle: fast-path branch resolution. If I could resolve branches in the ID stage by adding comparators and a target adder there, the misprediction penalty drops from 2 cycles to 1. The tradeoff is that ID-stage resolution requires operand availability, which conflicts with forwarding from later stages.\n\nBranches are typically backward-taken and forward-not-taken, so a static predictor would help, but the formal verification lesson from earlier work shows that speculation beyond tautological cases breaks correctness. The real win might be fusing the ALU and branch units — mapping branch operations to ALU SUB and deriving branch conditions from ALU flags (zero, negative, overflow, carry) instead of maintaining separate comparators. This shares one large adder across both ALU and branch logic, though I still need to compute branch_target separately and handle the redirect decision.\n\nLooking at what actually consumes area in the EX stage, the 33×33 multiplier dominates (one DSP block), barrel shifters take a decent chunk, and the branch comparator's 32-bit compares are probably minor. I'm considering a few angles: register-file read port consolidation, eliminating the MEM stage for ALU instructions to shorten the pipeline, or unifying the shifter logic. But eliminating MEM would change pipeline depth and break the test expectations from earlier lessons. A cleaner bounded improvement might be a unified bidirectional shifter or better ALU result latching to improve the critical path through the EX stage.\n\nActually, looking at the EX critical path more carefully: regfile read feeds into the forwarding mux, which feeds ALU operands, which go through shift/multiply/add operations, then into the jump target mux that selects between PC+4 and the ALU result. The multiply is already single-cycle via DSP, so the real bottleneck is probably all these muxes chained together. If I pre-compute PC+4 in the ID stage instead of doing it in EX, I can remove a 32-bit adder from the critical path — EX would just mux between the pre-computed value and alu_result_eff. This shifts the add to ID where regfile read dominates anyway, so it won't hurt timing. Adding a field to the id_ex_t struct shouldn't break test_pipeline.py since that probes pipeline depth, not individual struct fields.\n\nBut I'm also noticing that PC+imm for branches is another add in EX. I could pre-compute that too, though imm is already available in ID and JALR still needs rs1+imm so I can't fully avoid the computation. Let me focus on something simpler: maybe I can restructure how the misalign-trap detection and jump-target mux are organized to get them off the critical path entirely.\n\nActually, looking at what's currently happening in EX — there's the ALU result, the jump_target computation with its mux, misalign fault detection, the PC_next 4-way mux, the alu_result override for jumps, and the trap control mux. That's a lot of combinational logic stacked after the ALU finishes. I could move some of this to MEM where there's more breathing room, but that would delay the redirect signal by a cycle and add bubbles, which defeats the purpose.\n\nHere's what I'll actually do: pre-compute PC+4 in the IF stage and pass it through the pipeline as part of the register transfers. Then in EX, instead of adding PC+4 for jump instructions, I just use the pre-computed value, cutting out one 32-bit adder from the critical path.\n\nThe nice part is PC+4 is already being calculated in IF for the default next_pc, so it's essentially free to expose. I'd add a `pc_plus_4` field to the if_id and id_ex registers — minor payload widening but no logic changes. This should give a small Fmax improvement, maybe 2-4%, without affecting pipeline depth or formal verification.\n\nOne thing to watch: if test_pipeline.py checks struct field offsets, adding this field might shift things, though it probably uses field names anyway. Also, I'm noticing that branch_target (pc+imm for non-JALR) and the JAL case both compute pc+imm — those could potentially be unified, but that's a separate optimization.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to consolidate the EX-stage adders: share a single pc+imm computation between branch_target and jump_target instead of computing them separately, then use the pre-computed pc+4 from IF instead of regenerating it in EX. This removes redundant arithmetic without changing the pipeline structure.\n\nLooking at the actual LUT4 budget and considering what worked in previous attempts, the register-file LUTRAM approach (r5s0) proved to be a hard negative despite the proper GW2A synthesis attributes, so I should skip that direction. Let me focus on a different structural win that's actually feasible.\n\nThe cleanest move is to extract the load byte-muxing logic out of the combinational path in the MEM stage. Currently the data memory read result gets shifted, sign-extended, and captured all combinationally, which creates a critical path bottleneck. I could either write it explicitly as a 4:1 byte multiplexer instead of relying on synthesis to infer it from the barrel shifter, or better yet, push the entire load-extension work into the WB stage—capturing just the raw data and address bits in MEM, then doing the byte selection and sign extension in WB where there's more timing slack. This would free up the MEM stage's critical path while the WB stage is currently trivial anyway.\n\nBut that creates a problem: the regfile write-forward bypass path would lengthen since ID needs to see WB's extended output, and the EX stage's forwarding from WB would also have to wait for that extra combinational work. That's too risky for the timing gain.\n\nSo I'm settling on the simpler structural fix: replace the variable right-shift with an explicit 4:1 byte multiplexer in the MEM stage. Same idea for the write-data replication and byte-mask shifting—use explicit muxes instead of variable shifts. This gives the synthesizer a clear hint about what I'm trying to do and should reduce LUT usage in that stage without moving logic around.\n\nI also considered folding the divider output directly into the result register on its DONE cycle to bypass the ALU's output mux, and consolidating the ALU's multiple shifters into a single bidirectional unit...\n\nConsolidating the shifters into one...\n\nActually, let me reconsider whether this really helps with Fmax. A unified shifter using bit-reversal for left shifts adds extra depth compared to a direct shifter, so left shifts would actually get slower. And the LUT4 savings of ~350 only translates to Fmax if shifters are on the critical path, which they might not be. The ALU output mux is already huge with 19 operations, so that's probably the real bottleneck. Let me focus on something more concrete instead.\n\nI'll go with consolidating the three barrel shifters into a single bidirectional right-shifter with bit-reversal for left shifts. It's a straightforward optimization that mirrors the multiplier consolidation from r3s0, targets LUT4 reduction in the execute stage, and should drop area by 300-400 LUT4s. If the execute stage is area-constrained like we saw before, this could improve both area and timing through reduced routing congestion—I'm estimating around 3-4% improvement overall.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb743637001leL9CwWYLoXBkP","sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","messageID":"msg_deb729f0b001NncaZcRDKPmhJC"}}
