{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777771791208,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01NfBdeQnPmLfiXpk16c1m3R","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r6s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r6s1\ntitle: \"Unified bidirectional barrel shifter in ALU via bit-reversal for SLL\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The ALU currently instantiates three independent 32-bit variable shifters\n  for SLL, SRL, and SRA (alu.sv:70-72). On GW2A fabric this is the same\n  kind of structural duplication that r3s0 eliminated for the MUL/MULH/\n  MULHU/MULHSU triplet (3 DSP18 -> 1 DSP18, +8.5% fitness) and r5s1\n  eliminated by sequentializing DIV/REM. Each 32-bit barrel shifter costs\n  roughly 150-200 LUT4 plus routing, and three separate shifters feed a\n  19-way case-mux at the ALU output — a known EX-stage area/routing hot\n  spot on the Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's dynamic instruction mix makes\n  heavy use of SLL/SRL/SRA (array indexing, bit-packing in\n  core_matrix/core_list), so the shifters are definitely touched, but\n  three parallel copies are never simultaneously required: op is\n  one-hot among SLL/SRL/SRA at any cycle. This is the textbook\n  consolidate-on-demand pattern that lessons r3s0 and r5s1 endorse for\n  EX-stage arithmetic.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the three separate shift operations in rtl/alu.sv with a single\n  unified bidirectional shifter built on one 33-bit arithmetic right-\n  shifter, using the standard bit-reversal trick for SLL:\n\n    1. For SLL: reverse the input bits (streaming-operator `{<<{a}}`),\n       right-shift by `shamt`, then reverse the output bits. This\n       produces the same result as `a << shamt` but shares the\n       physical shifter with SRL/SRA.\n    2. For SRL: drive a zero fill bit into the 33-bit arithmetic\n       right-shift.\n    3. For SRA: drive `a[31]` into the 33-bit fill bit, letting the\n       signed right-shift sign-extend naturally.\n\n  Concretely: one `logic signed [32:0] shift_ext` feeding one\n  `shift_ext >>> shamt` expression, with upstream input-reverse mux\n  and downstream output-reverse mux gated on `op == ALU_SLL`. The\n  ALU's output case-mux folds SLL/SRL/SRA into a single `shift_result`\n  entry, reducing the output-mux width and halving the combinational\n  routing footprint feeding it.\n\n  Expected wins, matching the r3s0/r5s1 pattern:\n    - EX-stage LUT4 drops by roughly 250-400 cells (two 32-bit barrel\n      shifters removed).\n    - Reduced routing pressure around the ALU output mux improves\n      place-and-route Fmax, which is the dominant fitness driver\n      (167.11 MHz currently, target 135 but headroom still helps).\n    - No change to IPC — shift ops remain single-cycle combinational.\n    - No pipeline payload change: alu.sv's port set (op/a/b/out) is\n      unchanged.\n    - No formal-state expansion: the ALU's functional behavior on\n      SLL/SRL/SRA is bit-identical, and test_alu.py's existing vectors\n      plus riscv-formal's insn_sll/srl/sra checks validate the new\n      path end-to-end.\n    - ALTOPS branch is untouched (shifts aren't M-extension ops) so\n      formal BMC depth stays identical.\n\n  Risks and mitigations:\n    - Bit-reversal adds a couple of LUT4 levels on the SLL path. The\n      unified right-shifter itself is typically 4-5 LUT4 levels deep\n      on GW2A LUT4 fabric, plus one level each for input/output\n      reverse on SLL only. This is still shorter than the original\n      SLL path's dedicated 32-bit left-shifter (5-6 LUT4 levels) in\n      practice, because bit-reverse is pure routing (zero-delay in\n      many tools) or one LUT4 level; the main cost is routing, not\n      logic depth.\n    - If Yosys's streaming-operator support is shaky on GW2A, fall\n      back to an explicit 32-bit for-loop reverse in an always_comb\n      block — semantically identical, slightly more verbose.\n    - The cocotb test_alu.py suite already contains SLL/SRL/SRA\n      vectors across shift amounts 0..31 and edge cases (MSB set\n      for SRA) — any semantic drift gets caught there before formal.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: |\n      Replace the three separate shift operations (ALU_SLL/SRL/SRA\n      arms of the output case) with a single unified bidirectional\n      shifter. Add upstream bit-reverse on `a` for SLL, a 33-bit\n      arithmetic right-shift driven by op-dependent fill bit, and\n      a downstream bit-reverse on the output for SLL. The ALU's\n      output case-mux collapses three entries to one shared\n      `shift_result` entry, shrinking both the shifter logic and\n      the output mux. No port or parameter changes; behaviour on\n      all other ALU ops (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SLT/SLTU/LUI/MUL*/DIV*)\n      is untouched.\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: |\n      Extend (do not replace) the existing SLL/SRL/SRA test vectors\n      with extra edge cases specifically stressing the new unified\n      path: shamt=0 (identity), shamt=31 (maximum shift), shamt=\n      {1,7,15,16,24} across a mix of all-ones, alternating, MSB-set,\n      and sign-bit-toggling inputs, to catch any off-by-one from\n      bit-reversal or fill-bit wiring. Ensures regressions are\n      caught at the cocotb gate before formal/fpga stages burn time.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r6s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r6s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777771791195,"end":1777771791207}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm checking whether the ALU's shifters are already consolidated or if they're candidates for optimization. Rather than getting bogged down in the synthesis path analysis, I can propose a structural consolidation and let the implementation team validate it against timing constraints. My approach is to merge the three shift operations—logical left, logical right, and arithmetic right—into a single unified right-shifter that handles left shifts through bit reversal, fills in sign extension bits for arithmetic right shifts, and operates as a 33-bit signed unit.\n\nWriting hypothesis YAML...","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb74644f001OjAlfGZU2glLCq","sessionID":"ses_2148d6144ffedWsXEFRGMrtAUF","messageID":"msg_deb7452fb001TIhjFLsAKUmtVe"}}
