{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772594605,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4787ffeae1bMmbW3taIGK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01SH9X5WohR15jhFPoh9y8rX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List prior hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List prior hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List prior hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777772594594,"end":1777772594604}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the structural changes from previous experiments to identify what worked. DSP consolidation gave a solid boost, the stateless JAL predictor helped, and the iterative divider showed promise, but the RAS modification caused a regression because threading fields through the payload hurt the maximum frequency.\n\nThe current bottleneck is clear: the 33x33 combinational multiplier is still sitting on the critical path in the EX stage, and pipelining it to 2 cycles like we did with the divider could recover Fmax without much performance cost since multiplication is rare in CoreMark workloads. can be pipelined for higher Fmax. CoreMark's dynamic mix rarely exercises MUL, so the stall penalty should be minimal. I'll implement a 1-cycle FSM that captures operands in EX, registers the 66-bit product, and delivers the result the next cycle—mirroring the DIV pattern from r5s1. The hazard unit gets `mul_busy` and `mul_done` signals, and I'll gate the whole thing under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS to keep the combinational XOR path for formal verification. This should yield around +3-6% fitness.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb81057c001cBpv60wqr6d9vc","sessionID":"ses_2147f4787ffeae1bMmbW3taIGK","messageID":"msg_deb80b8af001116nnYvkkcB8GQ"}}
