{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772640080,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4787ffeae1bMmbW3taIGK","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01H2AkoJX1StzVBhdiWDfFsT","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r7s1\ntitle: \"Sequentialize MUL/MULH* into a 2-cycle pipelined DSP multiplier (r5s1 pattern for multiply)\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  r5s1 netted +8.79% by extracting DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU into a\n  32-cycle iterative FSM — rare-in-workload but LUT-hungry arithmetic was\n  sitting on the EX critical path and paying Fmax for every cycle. The same\n  argument applies verbatim to MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU: CoreMark's dynamic\n  instruction mix contains very few multiplies (the core loops are list/matrix\n  pointer chase + ALU ops, not MAC-dense), but the 33x33 signed multiplier\n  consolidated in r3s0 is still a COMBINATIONAL path that feeds mul_prod[63:0]\n  into the EX-stage alu_result mux every cycle. On GW2A the DSP18 block\n  supports an internal pipeline register that Yosys/himbaechel will only\n  infer if we register the product — leaving it combinational forces a\n  same-cycle 33x33 multiply + sign-ext mux + 2:1 alu_result mux all before\n  the EX/MEM flop, which is almost certainly the current Fmax-limiting\n  chain after r5s1 removed the divider from it.\n\n  Current core: Fmax 167.11 MHz, LUT4 5469, fitness 376.19. The EX ALU's\n  mul_prod is the tallest remaining combinational tree (r6s0 confirmed the\n  barrel shifter is already opportunistically shared and not a fat tree).\n  One-cycle multiply sequentialization is the lowest-risk Fmax play left.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Apply the r5s1 divider pattern to MUL: stall the pipeline for exactly one\n  extra cycle on MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU so the 33x33 multiplier output can\n  be registered (letting Yosys map it into the DSP18's pipeline flop),\n  removing the 66-bit signed product path from the EX combinational\n  critical path.\n\n  Concretely:\n  (1) Add `rtl/multiplier.sv` — a 2-cycle FSM (S_IDLE -> S_MUL1 -> S_DONE).\n      In S_IDLE, when `start` is asserted it captures a/b/op and transitions\n      to S_MUL1. In S_MUL1 it drives mul_prod = a_ext * b_ext into a\n      registered 64-bit `prod_q` and transitions to S_DONE. In S_DONE the\n      result (low-32 for MUL, high-32 for MULH*) is stable on the output\n      and the FSM returns to S_IDLE on the next clock.\n  (2) Drop the combinational MUL arms out of `alu.sv` (they become\n      don't-care 32'b0 in non-ALTOPS mode, mirroring the DIV treatment\n      r5s1 already introduced). Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the ALU\n      keeps its XOR stand-ins verbatim so formal proof depth does not\n      change. Remove the 33-bit mul_a_ext / mul_b_ext / mul_prod from the\n      combinational path entirely in non-ALTOPS mode.\n  (3) Instantiate the multiplier in `ex_stage.sv` alongside the divider.\n      Add `mul_busy` / `mul_done` outputs, gate start with\n      `!RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`, and fold `mul_busy` into the existing\n      `div_busy` hazard signal (OR them and rename the hazard input\n      `mdu_busy` to reflect both). The alu_result_eff mux in EX grows\n      from 2-way (ALU vs divider) to 3-way (ALU vs divider vs multiplier\n      DONE result) — trivial LUT cost for the kind of Fmax win registering\n      a 66-bit multiplier enables.\n  (4) Update `hazard_unit.sv` to accept the unified `mdu_busy` in place\n      of `div_busy`. stall_if / stall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb\n      semantics are unchanged — the multiplier uses the exact same\n      bus-stall mirror discipline the divider already established.\n\n  Why this should work (risk ledger):\n  - Formal: ALTOPS path is untouched (ALU's XOR stand-in fires\n    combinationally as today) so SBY BMC depth = baseline; r5s1 proved\n    this pattern threads through the RVFI wrapper without order/unique\n    regressions. No RVFI payload bits are added (multiplier state stays\n    inside ex_stage; EX/MEM captures the done cycle's result the same\n    way it does for the divider).\n  - IPC: 2-cycle multiply vs today's 1-cycle means every MUL costs an\n    extra stall. CoreMark's dynamic MUL count is tiny (core.list_reverse\n    + matrix row/col scaling; portmes use * sparingly), so even a 100%\n    multiply-op slowdown translates to well under 0.5% IPC loss at the\n    CoreMark level. The DIV sequentialization (32 cycles, same workload\n    MUL-adjacency) netted +8.79% because Fmax dominated.\n  - Fmax: removing a 33x33 signed multiplier + high/low product select\n    mux from the pre-EX/MEM combinational path frees DSP18 pipeline\n    slack that neighbour logic (branch compare + misalign + alu_result\n    mux) can then spread into. Expected Fmax lift ~5-8 MHz on Tang Nano\n    20K (consistent with r5s1's divider extraction delta).\n  - Area: multiplier FSM adds ~10 flops (state + 66-bit prod_q) and\n    ~a handful of LUT4s for the 3-way alu_result_eff mux, offset by\n    removing the combinational a_ext/b_ext replication logic from\n    alu.sv. Net likely small negative area, well inside the 10000 LUT4\n    budget.\n  - Lessons-check vs r5s2: no pipeline payload widening — multiplier\n    state is localized to ex_stage, same containment discipline as the\n    divider. Vs r6s0: DSP18 is a hard primitive like DIV's wide\n    subtractor, not a LUT4 tree synth can auto-share — so consolidation\n    argument holds (not the barrel-shifter false analogy). Vs r4s1:\n    no new pipeline stage register is added, so test_pipeline.py's\n    stage-name probes stay valid.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/multiplier.sv\n    description: \"New file. 2-cycle FSM (IDLE -> MUL1 -> DONE) wrapping a registered 33x33 signed multiplier with muxed sign-extension bits for MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU. op encoding matches ALU_MUL..ALU_MULHSU. Exposes start/busy/done/result handshake identical to divider.sv.\"\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: \"Remove combinational MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU arms in the non-ALTOPS branch (replace with out = 32'b0, mirroring the existing DIV treatment). Drop mul_a_ext / mul_b_ext / mul_prod / a_signed / b_signed declarations from non-ALTOPS mode. ALTOPS XOR stand-ins stay byte-for-byte identical so formal is unaffected.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate multiplier u_mul alongside u_div. Generate mul_start_pulse analogously to div_start_pulse. Extend alu_result_eff mux to 3-way (ALU vs divider-done vs multiplier-done). Combine mul_busy | div_busy into a new mdu_busy output to hazard_unit (renaming div_busy port).\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Rename the div_busy input port to mdu_busy; stall logic is identical (mdu_busy now covers both divider and multiplier multi-cycle occupancy).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Rename the div_busy wire to mdu_busy at the ex_stage <-> hazard_unit hookup. No RVFI port changes.\"\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: \"Adjust any MUL vector tests that probed alu.out combinationally in a single cycle — MUL now takes 2 cycles end-to-end in the EX stage. Keep the 30+ bit-exact RV32M vectors but gate them through the new mul_busy handshake (or probe the registered result one cycle later).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777772640069,"end":1777772640079}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm considering a structural optimization where I'd apply the divider extraction pattern to the multiplier—converting the 33x33 multiplier from a combinational operation in the EX stage to a 2-cycle operation that captures and registers the DSP output, which would remove the 66-bit path from the critical path and free up timing headroom.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb812890001IG5yww77bndEnc","sessionID":"ses_2147f4787ffeae1bMmbW3taIGK","messageID":"msg_deb811ac6001qh0eqAzNHPVLDU"}}
