{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777773810200,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01UxzTLzaYe2qsAzGoBNmQab","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777773810188,"end":1777773810198}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent wins, I'm noticing a pattern—the JAL predictor, DSP consolidation, and DIV sequentialization all delivered solid gains, while most branch prediction tweaks haven't panned out. I should focus on structural changes to the core rather than incremental predictor improvements.\n\nI'm exploring several angles: moving divider muxing to shorten the critical path, pipelining the instruction memory fetch, pushing immediate generation earlier into IF to lighten ID's load, or restructuring the register file to handle write-back muxing differently. Some options like splitting EX into two stages or moving load data extraction out of MEM could reduce bottlenecks, though they risk changing pipeline depth. The most promising direction seems to be reducing critical path pressure in IF and EX without disrupting the existing pipeline structure.\n\nNow I'm looking at the actual EX stage logic—it's computing PC+4 for jumps, branch targets, and jump targets, with the divider result override happening inside EX. The issue is that both jump and branch paths share PC+4 computation, and manual CSE didn't help in r7s0. I'm considering moving the divider result mux to the output side of the EX/MEM register instead, or handling JALR's jump target and write data in parallel with branch resolution to reduce the critical path pressure in EX itself.\n\nActually, I think there's a better structural fix: moving the WB mux earlier. Right now the MEM/WB register holds both `read_data` and `alu_result` separately, then WB combinationally muxes them based on `mem_to_reg` to produce `w_data`, which then feeds the forwarding path back to EX. If I pre-compute the muxed result at the MEM stage instead—capturing `rd_wdata` directly in the MEM/WB register—the forwarding path becomes just a direct register read with no mux delay. This saves a combinational level in the EX forwarding critical path. The tradeoff is that I need to be careful with RVFI observation, since it currently tracks the muxed output. Moving the WB mux into the MEM stage would shorten the critical path for EX forwarding by eliminating one combinational level, and RVFI semantics stay intact since `rd_wdata` gets computed earlier but carries the same value through the pipeline. This is a clean structural optimization worth implementing.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb9391b2001p5L6Y3YxnHgbPG","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","messageID":"msg_deb931b14001a35cUwJqAlP1F0"}}
