_0 did not produce any traces\\nmake[1]: *** [reg_ch0/status] Error 1\\nmake[1]: Target `all' not remade because of errors.\\n\\nFormal: 0 passed, 1 failed\\nFailed: no_checks_generated\\n\\nFull run log: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1/formal/last_run.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (broken, n/a): IF-stage early-redirect for JAL must still drive the EX-stage RVFI `pc_wdata` tap to the jump target \\u2014 gating `redirect` with `!early_jumped` silences the only signal that steers the EX rvfi_pc_wdata mux to `jump_target`, so the retiring JAL reports `pc_wdata = pc + 4` while the next fetched instruction's `pc_rdata` is the real target, breaking `pc_fwd` / `causal` transitively; any IF-side redirect optimization must either (a) compute pc_wdata from the decoded JAL target independently of the EX redirect gate, or (b) keep the EX redirect asserted (even if IF ignores it) purely for RVFI observability.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Fitness history shows Fmax is the dominant lever: JAL predictor (r2s2)\\nand DSP fold (r3s0) both won primarily via Fmax (135.21 -> 141.58 ->\\n153.61 MHz, tracking 1:1 with fitness). Conversely r1s0/r1s1 (divider,\\nmulti-cycle M-unit) regressed despite targeting EX-stage arithmetic,\\nproving the EX LUT path (now DSP-consolidated) is NOT the current\\nceiling. The remaining deepest combinational window is the IF->ID\\npath: in today's 5-stage the only register between the FPGA BRAM's\\noutput flop (imem_data) and id_ex_reg is a full cycle containing\\n(a) the decoder's ~20-arm case statement producing 15 control bits,\\n(b) the 32-bit imm_gen, (c) the 32x32 regfile distributed-LUT read\\nwith write-first bypass mux, and (d) the ctrl_t packing into\\nid_ex_reg. That is easily 10-15 LUT4 levels on Gowin GW2A, which at\\n~0.35 ns/LUT plus routing is right at the 6.5 ns period of 153 MHz.\\nUntil this path is split, neither JAL-nor-DSP-class optimizations\\ncan unlock the next Fmax tier; both r3s1 and r3s2 already confirmed\\nthat speculative branch prediction cannot close under SBY, so the\\nremaining structural move is pipeline-depth rebalance.\\n\\nAt LUT4=9865/target 10000 we also have routing-pressure evidence\\n(seed-to-seed Fmax variance was ~15 MHz before r3s0 settled it),\\nwhich a shallower per-stage logic depth directly relieves.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the 5-stage IF->ID->EX->MEM->WB pipeline to a 6-stage\\nIF->IFD->ID->EX->MEM->WB by inserting a new IFD pipeline register\\nwhose payload is ALREADY-DECODED control. Specifically:\\n\\n1. Move the decoder, imm_gen, and the JAL-target pre-computation into\\n   the IF stage. IF now outputs combinationally {pc, instr, ctrl, imm,\\n   rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rd, valid} \\u2014 all pure functions of imem_data +\\n   pc that today happen in ID. The JAL static predictor stays exactly\\n   where it is (it was never on the IF->ID critical path, it's on the\\n   pc-reg-self-feedback path).\\n2. Add a new `if_id_t` as a REGISTERED struct (flipped from its current\\n   combinational-bundle role in core_pkg.sv) holding the IF-stage\\n   combinational outputs. Latched at the IF->IFD edge.\\n3. Shrink id_stage to a single job: regfile read (using the registered\\n   rs1_addr / rs2_addr from IFD) + build id_ex_reg. No decode work.\\n   The regfile's write-first bypass stays as-is for WB-to-ID RAW.\\n4. hazard_unit's load-use check now compares `ifd_reg.rs?_addr` vs\\n   `id_ex_reg.rd` (one cycle later in wall-time but same relative\\n   distance in pipeline slots \\u2014 semantics preserved).\\n5. EX-resolved redirect must flush one additional stage (IFD in\\n   addition to IF-comb and ID). flush_ifd asserted on the same\\n   condition as flush_id today.\\n6. The JAL predictor's redirect latency vs instruction flow is\\n   unchanged: JAL is still decoded in IF on the cycle its word\\n   returns from imem; IF still redirects PC same cycle. The JAL\\n   itself just rides through one extra register (IFD) before ID.\\n   Zero-bubble JAL is preserved.\\n7. RVFI semantics are identical: retirement still observed at\\n   MEM/WB, rvfi_order +1 per retirement, pc_wdata computed in EX\\n   exactly as today. Only wall-clock latency of a single instruction\\n   grows by 1 cycle; steady-state IPC in a hazard-free stream is\\n   unchanged.\\n\\nExpected trade-off (back-of-envelope):\\n- Fmax: the per-cycle logic depth on the (imem_data -> id_ex_reg)\\n  path is halved (IF cycle: decode + imm_gen; IFD->ID cycle: regfile\\n  read + ctrl pack), target +15-25% Fmax (153 -> ~180-190 MHz).\\n- IPC: taken-branch penalty rises from 2 to 3 cycles (flush\\n  IF-comb + IFD + ID on EX redirect). CoreMark has ~9% dynamic\\n  taken conditional branches post-JAL-predictor, so +0.09\\n  cycles/instr on a baseline of ~2.5 cycles/instr = ~3.6% IPC loss.\\n  JAL (~3%) stays zero-bubble via the existing IF predictor.\\n  JALR (~0.3%) stays at 2-cycle EX redirect (now 3-cycle), small.\\n  Load-use stall: unchanged at 1 cycle (the stall is between ID/EX\\n  and IFD now; same slot count, just one cycle later in wall-time).\\n- Net fitness: +10 to +20% if Fmax hits +15%.\\n\\nFormal risk (learned from prior rounds):\\n- r1s2/r3s1/r3s2's failure mode was SPECULATIVE state or\\n  branch-direction-correlated redirect breaking BMC induction.\\n  THIS hypothesis adds zero speculation: IFD just registers\\n  already-committed decode output. rvfi_valid_0 reachability\\n  through symbolic fetch streams is identical \\u2014 the pipe is one\\n  stage deeper but every stage is deterministic.\\n- r2s0's failure was a specific RVFI-tap plumbing bug (rd_wdata\\n  field renamed without re-pointing io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0). THIS\\n  hypothesis doesn't rename any RVFI-observed mem_wb_t field.\\n- The only new SBY concern is symbolic liveness across the added\\n  stage \\u2014 riscv-formal's liveness check is parameterized by a\\n  bound; 1 extra stage is absorbed trivially within the existing\\n  20-step BMC depth.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend if_id_t into a REGISTERED payload: add fields ctrl (ctrl_t), imm ([31:0]), rs1_addr/rs2_addr/rd ([4:0]). These were previously decoded inside id_stage from the combinational instr.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate decoder + imm_gen in IF stage. Output the full if_id_t struct combinationally (pc, instr, ctrl, imm, rs1_addr, rs2_addr, rd, valid). Retain existing JAL static predictor on the pc-update path. Adapt flush/redirect handling so the new IFD register captures NOP ctrl on flush (decoder on NOP yields reg_write=0, is_illegal=0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ifd_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"New module: single pipeline register that captures if_id_t on posedge clock. Inputs: stall (hold), flush (load '0). Drives registered outputs to id_stage and hazard_unit. Under 40 LOC.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Strip decoder + imm_gen instances. Now only drives regfile read addresses (from registered rs1_addr/rs2_addr) and builds id_ex_reg from the registered ctrl + regfile-read data + passed-through pc/imm/rd/rs?_addr/instr/valid.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Load-use check uses ifd_reg.rs?_addr (replaces if_id_w.instr[19:15/24:20]). Add flush_ifd output asserted on redirect. Branch-redirect flush now covers 3 slots: IF-comb (flush_if), IFD (flush_ifd), ID (flush_id).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Re-wire top-level: if_stage -> ifd_stage -> id_stage -> ex_stage -> mem_stage -> wb_stage. Route flush_ifd/stall_ifd signals. RVFI taps remain at mem_wb_w (unchanged \\u2014 every io_rvfi_*_0 observation point is identical to today).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Update cycle-timing probes: retirement of instruction N now occurs at cycle N+5 in a hazard-free stream (was N+4). Existing cocotb assertions on rvfi_order and per-channel _0 suffix are semantically unchanged; only wall-clock offsets shift.\"}]}, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r4s1 (broken, n/a): Pipeline-depth rebalance (5->6 stages via an IFD register between IF and ID) is a structural change that inevitably touches `test/test_pipeline.py` \\u2014 the cocotb probe signals (e.g. `dut.if_id_reg.*`, stage-latched opcodes) shift by one stage and tests assert against specific stage names \\u2014 but `test/test_pipeline.py` sits in the orchestrator's rollback set even though generic `test/test_*.py` is nominally hypothesis-editable, so stage-count-changing hypotheses fail at the guardrail before any RTL is evaluated; future Fmax-via-deeper-pipeline moves must either (a) keep the existing stage register names and only add combinational lifts within a stage, or (b) split the decode work across two cycles without adding a new named pipeline register struct that test_pipeline.py probes.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor ex_stage.sv to compute two shared combinational signals\\nonce and reference them from every consumer:\\n\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_imm;   // single adder for branch/jump target\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_4;     // single adder for linear-advance paths\\n  assign pc_plus_imm = in.pc + in.imm;\\n  assign pc_plus_4   = in.pc + 32'd4;\\n\\nThen rewrite:\\n  branch_target = pc_plus_imm;\\n  jump_target   = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : pc_plus_imm;\\n\\n  reg_q.pc_next <= misalign_fault ? pc_plus_4\\n                 : in.ctrl.is_jump  ? jump_target\\n                 : branch_taken     ? branch_target\\n                                    : pc_plus_4;\\n\\nThis is a pure structural refactor with zero functional change \\u2014\\nevery output bit is bit-identical to the current implementation for\\nevery input vector. Consequently:\\n\\n  - RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps are unchanged (same value, same\\n    cycle, same register).\\n  - No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t payload bits added or removed\\n    (avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening synthesis penalty).\\n  - No new formal state; SBY BMC depth unchanged (per the r1s2 and\\n    r3s1 lessons on symbolic-fetch coupling \\u2014 this change doesn't\\n    touch fetch or predictor state at all).\\n  - No change to the EX\\u2192MEM handshake, div_busy, or the JAL\\n    predictor in if_stage.sv.\\n\\nExpected effect on Tang Nano 20K synthesis:\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+imm (branch_target + jump_target\\n    sharing), saving ~32 LUT4 of carry chain duplication.\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+4 (misalign-fault path + default\\n    pc_next sharing), saving another ~32 LUT4.\\n  - The pc_plus_imm wire is a single-source fanout to two mux legs\\n    (branch_target-select and jump_target-select) instead of two\\n    parallel adders racing to the same register input, shortening\\n    the critical-path slack on reg_q.pc_next.\\n\\nRisk profile:\\n  - Zero IPC impact (identical functional semantics).\\n  - Zero formal impact (same combinational output per input).\\n  - Zero invariant-1 (RVFI 2-channel) impact.\\n  - Only risk is that Yosys was already sharing these adders, in\\n    which case the RTL becomes cleaner but fitness is a wash. Even\\n    in that case the hypothesis strictly doesn't regress anything\\n    and documents the intent for future code readers. The LESSONS.md\\n    r6s0 note explicitly flags that Yosys sharing is NOT reliable\\n    for LUT-based datapaths across islands, which is the exact\\n    pattern here.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 364.26, \"delta_pct\": -3.17, \"vs_baseline\": 21.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 161.81, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5440, \"ff\": 1994, \"seeds\": [168.52, 158.33, 161.81], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:52:26.936440Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r7s0 (regression, -3.17%): Manually CSE'ing structurally-duplicated 32-bit adders (pc+imm across branch_target/jump_target; pc+4 across misalign-fault/default-pc_next/JAL-rd_wdata) in ex_stage.sv regressed fitness ~3% \\u2014 confirming that the r6s0 pattern generalizes beyond barrel shifters to ordinary adders on LUT4 fabrics: Yosys/nextpnr already share ripple-carry chains feeding a common mux cascade (the pc_next 4-way select was already collapsing in synthesis), so the hand-lifted `pc_plus_imm`/`pc_plus_4` wires introduce no new sharing but DO force a single-source high-fanout net feeding multiple mux legs across different always_comb blocks, which nextpnr routes with extra buffering/detour on Tang Nano 20K and lands worse on the EX critical path; the r3s0 DSP-consolidation heuristic is STRICTLY for hard primitives (DSP18, BSRAM, multipliers), and for LUT-only datapaths the empirical rule is \\\"don't manually CSE \\u2014 let the synth flow see the natural mux structure,\\\" with synth-report area diffs required before committing any structural-sharing refactor.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Search log.jsonl for r2s0 context","truncated":false},"title":"Search log.jsonl for r2s0 context","time":{"start":1777773834183,"end":1777773834186}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent wins, I'm noticing a clear pattern: the successful optimizations either map to hardware primitives, eliminate structural redundancy, or reduce the critical path depth. The three standouts—the JAL predictor, DSP consolidation, and DIV sequentialization—all follow this principle. I'm also tracking which approaches have hit diminishing returns, like branch prediction, so I can focus energy elsewhere.\n\nNow I'm exploring what structural changes might still be available. The main candidates are moving the writeback mux earlier to shorten the forwarding path, registering the branch target separately to speed up PC updates, pre-computing shift amounts in the memory stage using address bits that arrive early, and potentially reorganizing how the ALU result and division result are muxed to avoid redundant logic in the execute stage. I'm also reconsidering what's actually needed downstream from the EX/MEM register—some signals like branch_taken might be carrying unnecessary overhead.\n\nLooking more carefully at the register transfer, I notice that branch_taken and branch_target are stored in EX/MEM but never actually used downstream; they're dead bits that could be removed for a small area savings. But the more promising structural move is collapsing the writeback mux into the memory stage itself—instead of having the memory-to-register control signal live in mem_wb_t and doing the mux combinationally in the writeback stage, I'd pre-compute the final rd_wdata at the end of MEM and register that single value, eliminating the mux from the forwarding path and simplifying the writeback stage.\n\nThe catch is that r2s0 already attempted this exact optimization and failed because the RVFI taps weren't updated in lockstep when the mem_wb_t fields changed, so I'd need to be very careful to re-point io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 and io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0 correctly to avoid the same regression.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb93ecf1001H2SQ4MbExiNLY2","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","messageID":"msg_deb939af6001tp0lZdROe4pz9c"}}
