{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777773923427,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01AF4qwAzkGXRvcfySvsFNDw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -E \"load.use|load_use|load-use|zero.bubble|MEM.*forward|forward.*MEM\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"Check if load-use forwarding was tried"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_deb954c5b001dh7e6xNxrZtU2M\n\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative 32-cycle sequential divider module\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in\\nthe EX stage (32-bit restoring division fanning into the ALU\\noutput mux, which then feeds EX/MEM's alu_result register plus\\nthe forwarding path to the next cycle's EX operand muxes).\\n\\nMeanwhile CoreMark is an integer benchmark dominated by list\\ntraversal, matrix multiply, and CRC/state transitions; its\\ndynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM ops.\\nSo whatever Fmax and LUT budget is being spent on the\\ncombinational divider is pure waste for this fitness function.\\n\\nThe successful r3s0 hypothesis (+8.50% from folding 3 DSP18\\nmultipliers into 1) established the pattern: identify EX-stage\\narithmetic structures whose current implementation over-spends\\nFPGA resources, and consolidate/sequentialize them. The divider\\nis the most egregious remaining instance \\u2014 a single 32-bit\\ncombinational divide is worth more LUT4s than the rest of the\\nALU combined and sits on the EX critical path.\\n\\nCurrent fitness 345.80 at 153.61 MHz; Fmax target is 135 MHz\\n(we're already over) but Gowin timing closure on GW2A tightens\\nsharply above 150 MHz \\u2014 removing the combinational divider\\nshould push Fmax materially further.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in\\nthe EX stage (32-bit restoring division fanning into the ALU\\noutput mux, which then feeds EX/MEM's alu_result register plus\\nthe forwarding path to the next cycle's EX operand muxes).\\n\\nMeanwhile CoreMark is an integer benchmark dominated by list\\ntraversal, matrix multiply, and CRC/state transitions; its\\ndynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM ops.\\nSo whatever Fmax and LUT budget is being spent on the\\ncombinational divider is pure waste for this fitness function.\\n\\nThe successful r3s0 hypothesis (+8.50% from folding 3 DSP18\\nmultipliers into 1) established the pattern: identify EX-stage\\narithmetic structures whose current implementation over-spends\\nFPGA resources, and consolidate/sequentialize them. The divider\\nis the most egregious remaining instance \\u2014 a single 32-bit\\ncombinational divide is worth more LUT4s than the rest of the\\nALU combined and sits on the EX critical path.\\n\\nCurrent fitness 345.80 at 153.61 MHz; Fmax target is 135 MHz\\n(we're already over) but Gowin timing closure on GW2A tightens\\nsharply above 150 MHz \\u2014 removing the combinational divider\\nshould push Fmax materially further.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Extract DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of alu.sv's combinational case\\narms and into a new `divider.sv` module \\u2014 a 32-cycle iterative\\nrestoring divider that stalls the pipeline while it works.\\n\\nMicroarchitecture:\\n  - `divider.sv`: inputs (start, a, b, op[1:0] selecting\\n    DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU), outputs (busy, done, result[31:0]).\\n    Classic shift-subtract state machine with one 33-bit\\n    subtract per cycle; handles RV32M corner cases (divide-by-0,\\n    INT_MIN/-1 overflow) at result-mux time so the iterative\\n    core is pure unsigned restoring division. ~32 cycles per\\n    operation.\\n  - `ex_stage.sv`: instantiate divider alongside the existing\\n    ALU. Detect divide ops from ctrl.alu_op. On decode of a\\n    DIV/REM, assert divider.start for one cycle; raise a new\\n    `div_stall` output while divider.busy is high; when\\n    divider.done fires, override alu_result with divider.result\\n    for the cycle of capture into EX/MEM.\\n  - `hazard_unit.sv`: accept `div_busy` as a new stall input;\\n    assert `stall_if`, `stall_id`, `stall_ex_mem` for the\\n    duration (same pattern as dmem_stall \\u2014 hold all upstream\\n    stages, hold EX/MEM register, clear MEM/WB valid).\\n  - `core.sv`: wire `div_busy` from ex_stage into hazard_unit.\\n  - `alu.sv`: in the non-ALTOPS branch, replace the four\\n    DIV*/REM* case arms with `out = 32'b0` (don't care \\u2014 EX\\n    stage will override from divider output). Keep the ALTOPS\\n    branch bit-identical (XOR stand-ins stay combinational) so\\n    the formal proof path is unchanged and SBY still completes\\n    inside its 1800s budget.\\n  - Preserve the ALU's combinational MUL path verbatim (r3s0's\\n    shared DSP18 stays) \\u2014 only DIV/REM become sequential.\\n\\nWhy this keeps formal tractable:\\n  - ALTOPS mode (what `make formal` actually runs) keeps\\n    DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU as simple XOR stand-ins in both alu.sv\\n    and riscv-formal's spec, so no iterative state machine\\n    enters the BMC depth \\u2014 formal sees the same\\n    single-cycle-retirement pattern it sees today.\\n  - The stall integration mirrors the existing dmem_stall\\n    pattern exactly, which is already proven under formal.\\n  - No new RVFI-observable pipeline payload bits \\u2014 div_busy is\\n    a purely internal handshake. Avoids the r1s2 class of\\n    state-space blowup failures.\\n  - RVFI retirement still happens at MEM/WB; the divide just\\n    takes multiple cycles where rvfi_valid_0 stays low (same\\n    as any other stall), then retires normally.\\n\\nWhy this keeps cosim/CoreMark correct:\\n  - `test/test_alu.py` has 30+ vectors per M-ext op. Divider\\n    result-mux handles all RV32M corner cases identically to\\n    the current combinational path.\\n  - Real arithmetic mode (cosim against reference.py) diffs\\n    each retired DIV/REM field-by-field \\u2014 unchanged.\\n  - CoreMark's 6 KB run executes the divider maybe a handful\\n    of times at most (certainly not inside the hot loops),\\n    so IPC impact on the bracketed-region cycle count is\\n    negligible (~dozens of extra cycles against millions).\\n\\nExpected cost/benefit:\\n  - Fmax: +5-10 MHz from removing the biggest EX-stage\\n    combinational tree. On a 153 MHz baseline, +5 MHz is\\n    ~+3%; +10 MHz is ~+6.5%.\\n  - LUT4: 32-cycle iterative divider is ~200-300 LUT4s vs\\n    ~800-1200 LUT4s for the combinational `$div`, so a net\\n    LUT4 reduction that may open further P&R freedom.\\n  - IPC: near-zero impact (CoreMark has near-zero DIVs).\\n  - Net fitness: projected +5 to +8%.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-cycle iterative restoring divider with one 33-bit subtractor per cycle. Inputs: clock, reset, start, a[31:0], b[31:0], op[1:0] (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU). Outputs: busy, done (1-cycle pulse), result[31:0]. Handles divide-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow at the result-mux stage. Unsigned core with sign-fixup wrappers for DIV/REM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"In the non-ALTOPS branch, replace the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case arms with `out = 32'b0` (result is overridden by ex_stage from the divider module). Keep ALTOPS branch bit-identical. Keep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU's shared-DSP18 path exactly as r3s0 left it. Preserve combinational interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider. Detect divide ops from ctrl.alu_op. Pulse divider.start for one cycle on initial decode of DIV/REM; drive `div_stall` output while divider.busy is high. Mux divider.result into reg_q.alu_result on the cycle divider.done fires (otherwise use ALU's combinational output). Handle the stall-triggered re-entry of the same EX instruction: start only fires on the rising edge of a new divide.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Raise stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb while div_busy is asserted (same pattern as dmem_stall). Ensure dmem_stall and div_stall compose correctly (either triggers the same set of holds).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire div_busy from ex_stage into hazard_unit. No changes to RVFI port set or top-level IO.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update ALU test harness if the DIV/REM tests still probe `out` directly from alu.sv \\u2014 retarget those vectors to exercise the new divider module standalone, or exercise DIV/REM through the full EX stage via test_pipeline.py-style stimulus. Preserve all 30+ RV32M corner-case vectors (divide-by-0, INT_MIN/-1, signed/unsigned discipline).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/divider.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-cycle iterative restoring divider with one 33-bit subtractor per cycle. Inputs: clock, reset, start, a[31:0], b[31:0], op[1:0] (DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU). Outputs: busy, done (1-cycle pulse), result[31:0]. Handles divide-by-0 and INT_MIN/-1 overflow at the result-mux stage. Unsigned core with sign-fixup wrappers for DIV/REM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"In the non-ALTOPS branch, replace the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case arms with `out = 32'b0` (result is overridden by ex_stage from the divider module). Keep ALTOPS branch bit-identical. Keep MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU's shared-DSP18 path exactly as r3s0 left it. Preserve combinational interface.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate divider. Detect divide ops from ctrl.alu_op. Pulse divider.start for one cycle on initial decode of DIV/REM; drive `div_stall` output while divider.busy is high. Mux divider.result into reg_q.alu_result on the cycle divider.done fires (otherwise use ALU's combinational output). Handle the stall-triggered re-entry of the same EX instruction: start only fires on the rising edge of a new divide.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `div_busy` input. Raise stall_if, stall_id, stall_ex_mem, and hold_mem_wb while div_busy is asserted (same pattern as dmem_stall). Ensure dmem_stall and div_stall compose correctly (either triggers the same set of holds).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire div_busy from ex_stage into hazard_unit. No changes to RVFI port set or top-level IO.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Update ALU test harness if the DIV/REM tests still probe `out` directly from alu.sv \\u2014 retarget those vectors to exercise the new divider module standalone, or exercise DIV/REM through the full EX stage via test_pipeline.py-style stimulus. Preserve all 30+ RV32M corner-case vectors (divide-by-0, INT_MIN/-1, signed/unsigned discipline).\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 376.19, \"delta_pct\": 8.79, \"vs_baseline\": 24.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 167.11, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5469, \"ff\": 2016, \"seeds\": [169.98, 160.9, 167.11], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:21:24.709863Z\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 5, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r5s1 (improvement, +8.79%): Extracting DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU from alu.sv's combinational `$div`/`$mod` arms into a 32-cycle iterative restoring divider (gated off under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` so formal sees the ALTOPS XOR stand-in unchanged, and stalling the pipeline via a new `div_busy` hazard input mirroring `dmem_stall`) netted ~+9% fitness because CoreMark's dynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM but the combinational divider was the widest LUT4 tree in EX and sat on the critical path feeding `alu_result` \\u2014 the general pattern (following r3s0's DSP-consolidation): hot-in-ISA-cold-in-workload EX arithmetic is free real estate for sequentialization, and gating the FSM behind ALTOPS keeps SBY's BMC depth identical so formal stays tractable.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution (halve taken-branch bubble to 1 cycle)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"After r2s2's JAL predictor (+5.87%), the dominant remaining control-flow\\npenalty is the 2-cycle redirect bubble on every taken conditional branch\\n(opcode 0x63). Five prior IF-stage *speculative* attempts to attack this\\nbubble all failed:\\n  - r1s2 (BTB) blew the formal budget by threading predicted/pred_target\\n    through if_id_t/id_ex_t.\\n  - r3s1 (BTFNT) / r3s2 (BTFN) triggered the symbolic-fetch coupling\\n    trap: narrowing EX `redirect` to `mispredict` correlates the gate\\n    with `branch_taken`, and SBY's induction for the `reg` property\\n    cannot close the loop where IF redirects onto an address whose\\n    `imem_data` is itself a free symbolic variable AND the branch's\\n    resolved direction is also free.\\n  - r4s2 (tautological rs1==rs2) passed formal but the idiom is ~zero\\n    in compiler-emitted code, and the extra B-imm adder / 3-way mux\\n    cost Fmax. Net -7.92%.\\n  - r5s2 (RAS for JALR returns, formal-gated) passed formal but the\\n    4-way next_pc mux and EX ret_pred_hit comparator blew Fmax on the\\n    Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths. Net -60.03%.\\n\\nThe r3s2 lesson distills the explicit mitigation direction:\\n  \\\"future branch-prediction hypotheses should either target the\\n   EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear)\\n   or accept that a formal wrapper-level assume ... is required\\\"\\n\\nThis hypothesis takes the non-speculative path. It has NOT been tried.\\nAll five prior predictor attempts were IF-stage speculation \\u2014 none\\nmoved the resolution itself earlier in the pipeline.\\n\\nCoreMark's dynamic trace is dominated by tight loops (crcu8 inner,\\ncore_list_find reverse walk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k,\\ncore_state_transition dispatch). Assuming ~12% of dynamic instructions\\nare conditional branches with ~55% taken rate, cutting the taken-branch\\npenalty from 2 cycles to 1 cycle is ~6.6% of total cycles reclaimed\\nbefore any Fmax adjustment. JALR stays at EX (needs register-computed\\ntarget \\u2014 unchanged, as r5s2 proved the IF-side JALR predictor is\\nsynthesis-toxic on this FPGA).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After r2s2's JAL predictor (+5.87%), the dominant remaining control-flow\\npenalty is the 2-cycle redirect bubble on every taken conditional branch\\n(opcode 0x63). Five prior IF-stage *speculative* attempts to attack this\\nbubble all failed:\\n  - r1s2 (BTB) blew the formal budget by threading predicted/pred_target\\n    through if_id_t/id_ex_t.\\n  - r3s1 (BTFNT) / r3s2 (BTFN) triggered the symbolic-fetch coupling\\n    trap: narrowing EX `redirect` to `mispredict` correlates the gate\\n    with `branch_taken`, and SBY's induction for the `reg` property\\n    cannot close the loop where IF redirects onto an address whose\\n    `imem_data` is itself a free symbolic variable AND the branch's\\n    resolved direction is also free.\\n  - r4s2 (tautological rs1==rs2) passed formal but the idiom is ~zero\\n    in compiler-emitted code, and the extra B-imm adder / 3-way mux\\n    cost Fmax. Net -7.92%.\\n  - r5s2 (RAS for JALR returns, formal-gated) passed formal but the\\n    4-way next_pc mux and EX ret_pred_hit comparator blew Fmax on the\\n    Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths. Net -60.03%.\\n\\nThe r3s2 lesson distills the explicit mitigation direction:\\n  \\\"future branch-prediction hypotheses should either target the\\n   EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear)\\n   or accept that a formal wrapper-level assume ... is required\\\"\\n\\nThis hypothesis takes the non-speculative path. It has NOT been tried.\\nAll five prior predictor attempts were IF-stage speculation \\u2014 none\\nmoved the resolution itself earlier in the pipeline.\\n\\nCoreMark's dynamic trace is dominated by tight loops (crcu8 inner,\\ncore_list_find reverse walk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k,\\ncore_state_transition dispatch). Assuming ~12% of dynamic instructions\\nare conditional branches with ~55% taken rate, cutting the taken-branch\\npenalty from 2 cycles to 1 cycle is ~6.6% of total cycles reclaimed\\nbefore any Fmax adjustment. JALR stays at EX (needs register-computed\\ntarget \\u2014 unchanged, as r5s2 proved the IF-side JALR predictor is\\nsynthesis-toxic on this FPGA).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move conditional-branch resolution from EX to ID (non-speculative).\\nID reads rs1_data/rs2_data combinationally from the regfile and can\\nevaluate BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU one cycle earlier than EX. On a\\nresolved taken branch, ID asserts `id_redirect` with target =\\nid.pc + id.imm, redirecting IF the same cycle the BRANCH is in ID.\\n\\nBubble accounting:\\n  baseline: BRANCH in EX fires redirect \\u2192 IF and ID squashed \\u2192 2 bubbles\\n  new:      BRANCH in ID fires redirect \\u2192 IF squashed, BRANCH moves to\\n            EX \\u2192 1 bubble (the squashed IF)\\n\\nTo keep RVFI pc_wdata and the `reg` / `pc_fwd` formal properties intact,\\nEX still computes branch_taken / branch_target / pc_next as before, and\\nstores them in ex_mem_t. The only change at EX is that its `redirect`\\noutput is gated off for conditional BRANCH when ID already redirected.\\nThis is tracked via a single new 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` in\\nid_ex_t (so ex_stage knows which instruction ID already took care of).\\n\\nFormal tractability \\u2014 why this is safe:\\n  - No speculation. ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2 values.\\n    When ID says \\\"taken\\\", it's the SAME answer EX would compute next\\n    cycle (subject to forwarding equality, which is a pipeline\\n    invariant), not a guess.\\n  - No symbolic-fetch coupling. The r3s1/r3s2 failure mode was a\\n    feedback loop between free imem_data at the redirect target and a\\n    free branch direction. Here ID's redirect target and direction are\\n    both determined by already-fetched concrete values (instr bits +\\n    forwarded register values), exactly like the JAL predictor's\\n    `pc+imm` \\u2014 provably-correct-by-construction.\\n  - pc_wdata tap unchanged: RVFI still reads mem_wb.pc_next, which still\\n    comes from ex_mem.pc_next, which EX still computes from its own\\n    (redundant) branch_taken path. The r2s1 \\\"gate silences the\\n    pc_wdata tap\\\" trap is avoided because pc_next computation is\\n    decoupled from the redirect-assertion gate.\\n  - riscv-formal's `causal` / `pc_fwd` checks see the same retirement\\n    sequence as baseline \\u2014 only the IF PC trajectory shifts earlier\\n    on taken branches.\\n\\nID-stage forwarding (new, scoped to branch comparator only):\\n  Two 3:1 muxes select rs1_cmp / rs2_cmp from:\\n    - in.rs1_data / rs2_data (regfile, default)\\n    - ex_mem_w.alu_result (when ex_mem_w.rd matches and ex_mem_w is a\\n      register-write, non-LOAD)\\n    - wb w_data (when mem_wb_w.rd matches)\\n  LOAD-in-EX cannot forward to ID (its rdata doesn't exist yet), so\\n  hazard_unit grows one case: if BRANCH in IF/ID has rs1/rs2 matching\\n  a LOAD's rd in ID/EX, stall ID one extra cycle (in addition to the\\n  existing load-use stall). The BRANCH falls back to the standard\\n  EX-stage resolution in that case \\u2014 no speculation, just no IPC win\\n  for LOAD\\u2192BRANCH adjacency (rare; compilers schedule around it).\\n\\nLoad-use handling:\\n  The existing load-use hazard (LOAD in EX with dep in IF/ID) already\\n  stalls 1 cycle. With compare-in-ID active, a BRANCH immediately\\n  after a LOAD still gets the 1-cycle stall; after the stall, LOAD is\\n  in MEM/WB, BRANCH is in ID, and the WB-result forward path lets ID\\n  resolve normally. No new hazard interactions; just an additional\\n  forward source at ID.\\n\\nFmax risk mitigation:\\n  ID stage currently only drives decoder + imm_gen + regfile read \\u2014\\n  significant slack vs. the EX critical path (ALU + divider + fwd mux).\\n  Adding a 6-way funct3-driven comparator and two 3:1 forwarding muxes\\n  at ID should land well under the EX path's delay. If Fmax regresses\\n  materially, the comparator scope can be narrowed to BEQ/BNE only\\n  (the two fastest / most common) via a subsequent micro-opt iteration.\\n\\nScope exclusions (keep the change bounded):\\n  - JALR resolution stays at EX (needs rs1+imm; r5s2 showed IF-side\\n    JALR prediction is synthesis-toxic).\\n  - JAL handling unchanged (r2s2's static IF predictor).\\n  - Misalign-branch trap stays at EX (it must be a synchronous\\n    rvfi_trap with the exact retiring insn; ID lacks the retirement\\n    context and the 2-cycle EX path already catches it).\\n  - test/test_pipeline.py probes access named struct fields\\n    (dut.u_id.reg_q.ctrl.*, etc.); adding id_ex_t.id_branch_resolved\\n    is an append-only field change, not a stage rename, so the r4s1\\n    test_pipeline.py trap does not apply.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` to id_ex_t, indicating the ID stage already asserted redirect for this instruction's conditional branch. No other payload changes; zero new RVFI-visible bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a conditional-branch comparator at ID: funct3-driven BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU on rs1_cmp/rs2_cmp (post ID-stage forwarding). Drive id_redirect and id_redirect_target outputs. Set id_branch_resolved=1 in the ID/EX register when a conditional BRANCH is resolved at ID with no forwarding hazard. When ID cannot resolve (LOAD producer in ID/EX), fall back to baseline (EX-stage resolves as before, id_branch_resolved=0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new ID-stage forwarding sources (ex_mem_w.alu_result + ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write + ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to skip LOAD; wb w_data + wb w_en). Wire id_redirect/id_redirect_target into if_stage. Add load-use-at-ID detection to hazard_unit inputs (LOAD in ID/EX with BRANCH in IF/ID whose rs1/rs2 matches).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend PC update priority: redirect_ex > id_redirect > jal_pred > pc+4. Both redirects flush IF; id_redirect does not flush ID because the BRANCH itself is what's moving from ID to EX (not being squashed). Keep the existing misalign guard on jal_pred; ID-side conditional branches cannot produce misaligned targets under RV32I (B-imm bit0 is implicit 0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the BRANCH portion of the `redirect` output on `!in.id_branch_resolved`. JALR and misalign-trap redirect paths are unchanged. pc_next computation in the EX/MEM register is unchanged (still branch_taken ? target : pc+4) so RVFI pc_wdata is byte-for-byte identical to baseline on all retirements.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_needs_load` input from top-level (BRANCH in IF/ID with rs matching a LOAD's rd in ID/EX). When asserted, force stall_id / stall_if for one extra cycle so the LOAD advances to MEM/WB and its result becomes forwardable to ID; otherwise ID's forward muxes would select stale data for the BRANCH compare.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a directed test for the compare-in-ID path: program a sequence `ADDI x5,x0,3 ; ADDI x5,x5,-1 ; BNE x5,x0,-4 ; ADDI x6,x0,42` and verify (a) rvfi_order increments by exactly the expected number of retirements, (b) only 1 bubble per taken BNE (vs. 2 in baseline) by counting cycles between PC=BNE and PC=BNE-target across the loop, and (c) the load-use-BRANCH fallback path still resolves correctly with an extra stall. Also add a regression probe that id_ex.id_branch_resolved is 0 whenever the instr is not a conditional BRANCH.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` to id_ex_t, indicating the ID stage already asserted redirect for this instruction's conditional branch. No other payload changes; zero new RVFI-visible bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a conditional-branch comparator at ID: funct3-driven BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU on rs1_cmp/rs2_cmp (post ID-stage forwarding). Drive id_redirect and id_redirect_target outputs. Set id_branch_resolved=1 in the ID/EX register when a conditional BRANCH is resolved at ID with no forwarding hazard. When ID cannot resolve (LOAD producer in ID/EX), fall back to baseline (EX-stage resolves as before, id_branch_resolved=0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new ID-stage forwarding sources (ex_mem_w.alu_result + ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write + ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to skip LOAD; wb w_data + wb w_en). Wire id_redirect/id_redirect_target into if_stage. Add load-use-at-ID detection to hazard_unit inputs (LOAD in ID/EX with BRANCH in IF/ID whose rs1/rs2 matches).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend PC update priority: redirect_ex > id_redirect > jal_pred > pc+4. Both redirects flush IF; id_redirect does not flush ID because the BRANCH itself is what's moving from ID to EX (not being squashed). Keep the existing misalign guard on jal_pred; ID-side conditional branches cannot produce misaligned targets under RV32I (B-imm bit0 is implicit 0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the BRANCH portion of the `redirect` output on `!in.id_branch_resolved`. JALR and misalign-trap redirect paths are unchanged. pc_next computation in the EX/MEM register is unchanged (still branch_taken ? target : pc+4) so RVFI pc_wdata is byte-for-byte identical to baseline on all retirements.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_needs_load` input from top-level (BRANCH in IF/ID with rs matching a LOAD's rd in ID/EX). When asserted, force stall_id / stall_if for one extra cycle so the LOAD advances to MEM/WB and its result becomes forwardable to ID; otherwise ID's forward muxes would select stale data for the BRANCH compare.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a directed test for the compare-in-ID path: program a sequence `ADDI x5,x0,3 ; ADDI x5,x5,-1 ; BNE x5,x0,-4 ; ADDI x6,x0,42` and verify (a) rvfi_order increments by exactly the expected number of retirements, (b) only 1 bubble per taken BNE (vs. 2 in baseline) by counting cycles between PC=BNE and PC=BNE-target across the loop, and (c) the load-use-BRANCH fallback path still resolves correctly with an extra stall. Also add a regression probe that id_ex.id_branch_resolved is 0 whenever the instr is not a conditional BRANCH.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 376.19, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 24.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 167.11, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5469, \"ff\": 2016, \"seeds\": [169.98, 160.9, 167.11], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:39:16.255365Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r6s2 (regression, +0.00%): Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution \\u2014 the r3s2-mitigation \\\"move resolution earlier at EX/ID, keep IF linear\\\" path \\u2014 is formal-tractable (no symbolic-fetch coupling, ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2) but nets ~0% CoreMark fitness because the theoretical ~6.6% IPC win from halving the taken-branch bubble (2\\u21921) is fully cancelled on Tang Nano 20K by (a) a new 6-way funct3 comparator + two 3:1 ID-stage forwarding muxes landing on the ID combinational path (which previously had slack vs EX but now competes with the regfile-read+decode+imm_gen chain), (b) an extra load-use stall case when a BRANCH depends on an in-flight LOAD (forward-to-ID is impossible since the LOAD's rdata doesn't exist yet at ID), and (c) id_ex_t widening by a `id_branch_resolved` bit that, like r5s2's RAS payload, costs synthesis area even when proof cost is zero; IPC wins from moving resolution earlier are structurally bounded by the slowest ID-side operand source (forwarded ex_mem.alu_result from a full-width ALU+divider mux), so future non-speculative branch-bubble plays should either (i) narrow the ID comparator to BEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping the signed/unsigned compare tree) or (ii) accept that this pipeline's IPC-Fmax tradeoff curve for control-flow is near-saturated after r2s2's JAL predictor and pursue non-branch optimizations.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor ex_stage.sv to compute two shared combinational signals\\nonce and reference them from every consumer:\\n\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_imm;   // single adder for branch/jump target\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_4;     // single adder for linear-advance paths\\n  assign pc_plus_imm = in.pc + in.imm;\\n  assign pc_plus_4   = in.pc + 32'd4;\\n\\nThen rewrite:\\n  branch_target = pc_plus_imm;\\n  jump_target   = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : pc_plus_imm;\\n\\n  reg_q.pc_next <= misalign_fault ? pc_plus_4\\n                 : in.ctrl.is_jump  ? jump_target\\n                 : branch_taken     ? branch_target\\n                                    : pc_plus_4;\\n\\nThis is a pure structural refactor with zero functional change \\u2014\\nevery output bit is bit-identical to the current implementation for\\nevery input vector. Consequently:\\n\\n  - RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps are unchanged (same value, same\\n    cycle, same register).\\n  - No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t payload bits added or removed\\n    (avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening synthesis penalty).\\n  - No new formal state; SBY BMC depth unchanged (per the r1s2 and\\n    r3s1 lessons on symbolic-fetch coupling \\u2014 this change doesn't\\n    touch fetch or predictor state at all).\\n  - No change to the EX\\u2192MEM handshake, div_busy, or the JAL\\n    predictor in if_stage.sv.\\n\\nExpected effect on Tang Nano 20K synthesis:\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+imm (branch_target + jump_target\\n    sharing), saving ~32 LUT4 of carry chain duplication.\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+4 (misalign-fault path + default\\n    pc_next sharing), saving another ~32 LUT4.\\n  - The pc_plus_imm wire is a single-source fanout to two mux legs\\n    (branch_target-select and jump_target-select) instead of two\\n    parallel adders racing to the same register input, shortening\\n    the critical-path slack on reg_q.pc_next.\\n\\nRisk profile:\\n  - Zero IPC impact (identical functional semantics).\\n  - Zero formal impact (same combinational output per input).\\n  - Zero invariant-1 (RVFI 2-channel) impact.\\n  - Only risk is that Yosys was already sharing these adders, in\\n    which case the RTL becomes cleaner but fitness is a wash. Even\\n    in that case the hypothesis strictly doesn't regress anything\\n    and documents the intent for future code readers. The LESSONS.md\\n    r6s0 note explicitly flags that Yosys sharing is NOT reliable\\n    for LUT-based datapaths across islands, which is the exact\\n    pattern here.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 364.26, \"delta_pct\": -3.17, \"vs_baseline\": 21.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 161.81, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5440, \"ff\": 1994, \"seeds\": [168.52, 158.33, 161.81], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:52:26.936440Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r7s0 (regression, -3.17%): Manually CSE'ing structurally-duplicated 32-bit adders (pc+imm across branch_target/jump_target; pc+4 across misalign-fault/default-pc_next/JAL-rd_wdata) in ex_stage.sv regressed fitness ~3% \\u2014 confirming that the r6s0 pattern generalizes beyond barrel shifters to ordinary adders on LUT4 fabrics: Yosys/nextpnr already share ripple-carry chains feeding a common mux cascade (the pc_next 4-way select was already collapsing in synthesis), so the hand-lifted `pc_plus_imm`/`pc_plus_4` wires introduce no new sharing but DO force a single-source high-fanout net feeding multiple mux legs across different always_comb blocks, which nextpnr routes with extra buffering/detour on Tang Nano 20K and lands worse on the EX critical path; the r3s0 DSP-consolidation heuristic is STRICTLY for hard primitives (DSP18, BSRAM, multipliers), and for LUT-only datapaths the empirical rule is \\\"don't manually CSE \\u2014 let the synth flow see the natural mux structure,\\\" with synth-report area diffs required before committing any structural-sharing refactor.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage BEQ/BNE-only early branch resolution (non-speculative, cheap comparator)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \\\"future\\nnon-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\\nBEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\\nthe signed/unsigned compare tree)\\\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\\ndominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\\nBEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture \\u224870-80% of conditional-branch cycles\\nat a fraction of the comparator cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \\\"future\\nnon-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\\nBEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\\nthe signed/unsigned compare tree)\\\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\\ndominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\\nBEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture \\u224870-80% of conditional-branch cycles\\nat a fraction of the comparator cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage early-resolution path restricted to BEQ and BNE (funct3\\n\\u2208 {000, 001}), non-speculative: resolve the branch using forwarded rs1/rs2\\noperands at ID. The comparator is a single 32-bit equality (XOR-tree +\\nreduction-OR), dramatically cheaper than r6s2's 6-way signed/unsigned\\ncompare. When both operands are available at ID (not blocked behind an\\nin-flight LOAD in EX/MEM), compute taken = (rs1==rs2)^funct3[0], redirect\\nIF from ID to branch_target/pc+4, and mark the branch as already-resolved\\nin id_ex_t via a single 1-bit flag. At EX, a BEQ/BNE carrying\\nid_branch_resolved=1 bypasses the EX redirect (pc_next already correct,\\nRVFI pc_wdata wired from the pre-resolved target). Fallback: any BEQ/BNE\\nthat cannot be resolved at ID (operand behind an in-flight LOAD, or not\\nyet valid) falls through to the existing EX resolution path unchanged.\\nBLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU continue to resolve at EX (skipped by ID \\u2014 their\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree is what blew the timing budget in r6s2).\\n\\nFormal-tractability argument (addresses the r3s1/r3s2 trap): this change\\nis NON-speculative. ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2 values;\\nthere is no symbolic-fetch feedback loop where the predictor's redirect\\ntarget and the branch's resolved direction are both free variables.\\nrvfi_pc_wdata is always the resolved branch_target (whether resolved at\\nID or EX); rvfi_order / rvfi_trap are untouched. id_ex_t widens by 1 bit\\n(id_branch_resolved) plus a 32-bit pc_next field carried from ID \\u2014 BUT\\npc_next is already a 32-bit payload in ex_mem_t/mem_wb_t, so the extra\\nregister state is just 33 bits in id_ex_t, and the ID comparator is a\\nsingle narrow XOR-tree.\\n\\nWhy this is different from r6s2: r6s2 widened the ID comparator to cover\\nall 6 branch variants, which put a signed<, unsigned<, and == tree in\\nparallel on the ID combinational path. ID previously had slack vs EX but\\nnot enough for three wide comparators. BEQ/BNE alone is just a 32-bit XOR\\nreduction (\\u22485 LUT4 levels, same depth as a single operand-forward mux),\\nwhich should fit comfortably inside the existing ID slack. We explicitly\\nskip BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU to preserve ID-path timing.\\n\\nWhy this is different from r5s2: no 32-bit predicted_target threaded\\nthrough the pipeline, no new 4-way next_pc mux at IF. The 1-bit\\nid_branch_resolved flag and the 32-bit pc_next (already a downstream\\npayload field) are the only new id_ex_t state; EX muxes pc_next straight\\nthrough instead of recomputing it on resolved branches.\\n\\nExpected IPC win: CoreMark ~12-15% branch density, of which BEQ/BNE are\\n\\u224870-80%, taken rate ~60%. Saving 1 bubble cycle per taken BEQ/BNE where\\noperands are ID-available gives approx 0.12 \\u00d7 0.75 \\u00d7 0.60 = ~5.4% IPC\\nuplift. Fmax impact: neutral-to-slightly-negative (single narrow XOR tree\\n+ two 3:1 forwarding muxes on ID path). Net fitness: targeting +3-5%.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_resolved` (1-bit) and `pc_next` (32-bit) fields to id_ex_t so EX can bypass its redirect/target-mux for ID-resolved BEQ/BNE. pc_next defaults to pc+4 at ID for non-branches and non-resolved branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID-stage early-resolution logic restricted to funct3 \\u2208 {000 BEQ, 001 BNE}. Wire in rs1_val / rs2_val forwarding from EX/MEM.alu_result and MEM/WB write-mux data (drive via new input ports). Use a single 32-bit equality comparator (rs1_eff == rs2_eff), compute taken = eq ^ funct3[0]. Gate early resolution on: (a) instr is BEQ/BNE, (b) operand not waiting on an in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM, (c) if_id_w.valid. When resolved, set id_branch_resolved=1, set pc_next = taken ? (pc + B-imm) : (pc + 4), and drive an id_redirect pulse + id_redirect_target to if_stage via a new module output. Pass pc_next through id_ex_t.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_stage inputs (fwd_ex_mem, fwd_mem_wb, load_in_flight) from ex_mem_w and wb_stage outputs. Wire id_stage's new outputs (id_redirect, id_redirect_target) into if_stage alongside the existing EX redirect with ID having higher priority (the in-flight EX redirect cannot conflict since only one branch is in the resolution cone at a time). Add id_flush input to flush the branch shadow in IF/ID when ID redirects.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept new id_redirect / id_redirect_target inputs. PC reg update priority: reset > ex_redirect > id_redirect > static JAL predictor > pc+4. When id_redirect fires, emit NOP into the IF/ID combinational payload this cycle (same pattern as the existing flush logic) so the mis-speculated next sequential fetch is squashed.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"When id_ex_w.ctrl carries a BEQ/BNE AND id_branch_resolved=1, skip EX redirect (redirect output stays low for this instruction), and use id_ex_w.pc_next directly as the EX/MEM pc_next payload (don't recompute branch_target + branch_taken for RVFI). For non-resolved branches and BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, existing EX resolution path runs unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an id_redirect input mirroring the existing EX redirect's flush semantics: flush_if on id_redirect (so IF/ID next-cycle payload becomes NOP), and ensure the branch itself continues to ID/EX normally (the branch must retire with rvfi_valid=1 at WB \\u2014 only the wrong-path instruction behind it is squashed).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that exercises ID-stage early-resolution: a BEQ with rs1==rs2 and both operands ID-available should produce a taken redirect 1 cycle earlier than the current EX-resolution baseline (observe via fetch-PC sequence). A BEQ with operand blocked behind a LOAD falls through to EX resolution (baseline timing). Validate rvfi_pc_wdata matches the branch target on both paths.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_resolved` (1-bit) and `pc_next` (32-bit) fields to id_ex_t so EX can bypass its redirect/target-mux for ID-resolved BEQ/BNE. pc_next defaults to pc+4 at ID for non-branches and non-resolved branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID-stage early-resolution logic restricted to funct3 \\u2208 {000 BEQ, 001 BNE}. Wire in rs1_val / rs2_val forwarding from EX/MEM.alu_result and MEM/WB write-mux data (drive via new input ports). Use a single 32-bit equality comparator (rs1_eff == rs2_eff), compute taken = eq ^ funct3[0]. Gate early resolution on: (a) instr is BEQ/BNE, (b) operand not waiting on an in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM, (c) if_id_w.valid. When resolved, set id_branch_resolved=1, set pc_next = taken ? (pc + B-imm) : (pc + 4), and drive an id_redirect pulse + id_redirect_target to if_stage via a new module output. Pass pc_next through id_ex_t.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_stage inputs (fwd_ex_mem, fwd_mem_wb, load_in_flight) from ex_mem_w and wb_stage outputs. Wire id_stage's new outputs (id_redirect, id_redirect_target) into if_stage alongside the existing EX redirect with ID having higher priority (the in-flight EX redirect cannot conflict since only one branch is in the resolution cone at a time). Add id_flush input to flush the branch shadow in IF/ID when ID redirects.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept new id_redirect / id_redirect_target inputs. PC reg update priority: reset > ex_redirect > id_redirect > static JAL predictor > pc+4. When id_redirect fires, emit NOP into the IF/ID combinational payload this cycle (same pattern as the existing flush logic) so the mis-speculated next sequential fetch is squashed.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"When id_ex_w.ctrl carries a BEQ/BNE AND id_branch_resolved=1, skip EX redirect (redirect output stays low for this instruction), and use id_ex_w.pc_next directly as the EX/MEM pc_next payload (don't recompute branch_target + branch_taken for RVFI). For non-resolved branches and BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, existing EX resolution path runs unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an id_redirect input mirroring the existing EX redirect's flush semantics: flush_if on id_redirect (so IF/ID next-cycle payload becomes NOP), and ensure the branch itself continues to ID/EX normally (the branch must retire with rvfi_valid=1 at WB \\u2014 only the wrong-path instruction behind it is squashed).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that exercises ID-stage early-resolution: a BEQ with rs1==rs2 and both operands ID-available should produce a taken redirect 1 cycle earlier than the current EX-resolution baseline (observe via fetch-PC sequence). A BEQ with operand blocked behind a LOAD falls through to EX resolution (baseline timing). Validate rvfi_pc_wdata matches the branch target on both paths.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 376.19, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 24.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 167.11, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5469, \"ff\": 2016, \"seeds\": [169.98, 160.9, 167.11], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:54:21.381056Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r7s2 (regression, +0.00%): Following r6s2's post-mortem prescription to narrow ID-stage early branch resolution to BEQ/BNE-only (single 32-bit XOR-reduction equality, skipping the signed/unsigned compare tree) still lands at ~0% net fitness \\u2014 disproving the \\\"narrower comparator will fit in ID slack\\\" escape hatch and confirming the alternative branch of r6s2's dilemma: this pipeline's control-flow IPC-Fmax curve is structurally saturated after r2s2's JAL predictor because (a) BEQ/BNE-dependent-on-in-flight-LOAD cases cannot forward to ID (the LOAD's rdata doesn't exist yet at ID, forcing a new load-use stall that didn't exist when resolution was at EX) and those cases are common in CoreMark's pointer-walk / null-check idioms, (b) the 1-bit `id_branch_resolved` flag widening id_ex_t costs synthesis area on Tang Nano 20K regardless of comparator width (same mechanism as r5s2's RAS payload and r6s2's full-width variant), and (c) the BEQ/BNE \\u224870-80%-of-conditional-branches estimate ignores that the remaining BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU still pay the full 2-cycle bubble, capping the achievable IPC uplift below the fixed structural cost; future branch-bubble hypotheses on this microarchitecture should pivot away from ID-resolution entirely (the slot is now proven saturated across both wide-r6s2 and narrow-r7s2 variants) toward non-control-flow optimizations or accept the saturation.\"}\n","metadata":{"output":"...\n\nRVFI-visible bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a conditional-branch comparator at ID: funct3-driven BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU on rs1_cmp/rs2_cmp (post ID-stage forwarding). Drive id_redirect and id_redirect_target outputs. Set id_branch_resolved=1 in the ID/EX register when a conditional BRANCH is resolved at ID with no forwarding hazard. When ID cannot resolve (LOAD producer in ID/EX), fall back to baseline (EX-stage resolves as before, id_branch_resolved=0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new ID-stage forwarding sources (ex_mem_w.alu_result + ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write + ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to skip LOAD; wb w_data + wb w_en). Wire id_redirect/id_redirect_target into if_stage. Add load-use-at-ID detection to hazard_unit inputs (LOAD in ID/EX with BRANCH in IF/ID whose rs1/rs2 matches).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend PC update priority: redirect_ex > id_redirect > jal_pred > pc+4. Both redirects flush IF; id_redirect does not flush ID because the BRANCH itself is what's moving from ID to EX (not being squashed). Keep the existing misalign guard on jal_pred; ID-side conditional branches cannot produce misaligned targets under RV32I (B-imm bit0 is implicit 0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the BRANCH portion of the `redirect` output on `!in.id_branch_resolved`. JALR and misalign-trap redirect paths are unchanged. pc_next computation in the EX/MEM register is unchanged (still branch_taken ? target : pc+4) so RVFI pc_wdata is byte-for-byte identical to baseline on all retirements.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_needs_load` input from top-level (BRANCH in IF/ID with rs matching a LOAD's rd in ID/EX). When asserted, force stall_id / stall_if for one extra cycle so the LOAD advances to MEM/WB and its result becomes forwardable to ID; otherwise ID's forward muxes would select stale data for the BRANCH compare.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a directed test for the compare-in-ID path: program a sequence `ADDI x5,x0,3 ; ADDI x5,x5,-1 ; BNE x5,x0,-4 ; ADDI x6,x0,42` and verify (a) rvfi_order increments by exactly the expected number of retirements, (b) only 1 bubble per taken BNE (vs. 2 in baseline) by counting cycles between PC=BNE and PC=BNE-target across the loop, and (c) the load-use-BRANCH fallback path still resolves correctly with an extra stall. Also add a regression probe that id_ex.id_branch_resolved is 0 whenever the instr is not a conditional BRANCH.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` to id_ex_t, indicating the ID stage already asserted redirect for this instruction's conditional branch. No other payload changes; zero new RVFI-visible bits.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a conditional-branch comparator at ID: funct3-driven BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU on rs1_cmp/rs2_cmp (post ID-stage forwarding). Drive id_redirect and id_redirect_target outputs. Set id_branch_resolved=1 in the ID/EX register when a conditional BRANCH is resolved at ID with no forwarding hazard. When ID cannot resolve (LOAD producer in ID/EX), fall back to baseline (EX-stage resolves as before, id_branch_resolved=0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new ID-stage forwarding sources (ex_mem_w.alu_result + ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write + ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to skip LOAD; wb w_data + wb w_en). Wire id_redirect/id_redirect_target into if_stage. Add load-use-at-ID detection to hazard_unit inputs (LOAD in ID/EX with BRANCH in IF/ID whose rs1/rs2 matches).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend PC update priority: redirect_ex > id_redirect > jal_pred > pc+4. Both redirects flush IF; id_redirect does not flush ID because the BRANCH itself is what's moving from ID to EX (not being squashed). Keep the existing misalign guard on jal_pred; ID-side conditional branches cannot produce misaligned targets under RV32I (B-imm bit0 is implicit 0).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the BRANCH portion of the `redirect` output on `!in.id_branch_resolved`. JALR and misalign-trap redirect paths are unchanged. pc_next computation in the EX/MEM register is unchanged (still branch_taken ? target : pc+4) so RVFI pc_wdata is byte-for-byte identical to baseline on all retirements.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_needs_load` input from top-level (BRANCH in IF/ID with rs matching a LOAD's rd in ID/EX). When asserted, force stall_id / stall_if for one extra cycle so the LOAD advances to MEM/WB and its result becomes forwardable to ID; otherwise ID's forward muxes would select stale data for the BRANCH compare.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a directed test for the compare-in-ID path: program a sequence `ADDI x5,x0,3 ; ADDI x5,x5,-1 ; BNE x5,x0,-4 ; ADDI x6,x0,42` and verify (a) rvfi_order increments by exactly the expected number of retirements, (b) only 1 bubble per taken BNE (vs. 2 in baseline) by counting cycles between PC=BNE and PC=BNE-target across the loop, and (c) the load-use-BRANCH fallback path still resolves correctly with an extra stall. Also add a regression probe that id_ex.id_branch_resolved is 0 whenever the instr is not a conditional BRANCH.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 376.19, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 24.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 167.11, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5469, \"ff\": 2016, \"seeds\": [169.98, 160.9, 167.11], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:39:16.255365Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 6, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r6s2 (regression, +0.00%): Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution \\u2014 the r3s2-mitigation \\\"move resolution earlier at EX/ID, keep IF linear\\\" path \\u2014 is formal-tractable (no symbolic-fetch coupling, ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2) but nets ~0% CoreMark fitness because the theoretical ~6.6% IPC win from halving the taken-branch bubble (2\\u21921) is fully cancelled on Tang Nano 20K by (a) a new 6-way funct3 comparator + two 3:1 ID-stage forwarding muxes landing on the ID combinational path (which previously had slack vs EX but now competes with the regfile-read+decode+imm_gen chain), (b) an extra load-use stall case when a BRANCH depends on an in-flight LOAD (forward-to-ID is impossible since the LOAD's rdata doesn't exist yet at ID), and (c) id_ex_t widening by a `id_branch_resolved` bit that, like r5s2's RAS payload, costs synthesis area even when proof cost is zero; IPC wins from moving resolution earlier are structurally bounded by the slowest ID-side operand source (forwarded ex_mem.alu_result from a full-width ALU+divider mux), so future non-speculative branch-bubble plays should either (i) narrow the ID comparator to BEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping the signed/unsigned compare tree) or (ii) accept that this pipeline's IPC-Fmax tradeoff curve for control-flow is near-saturated after r2s2's JAL predictor and pursue non-branch optimizations.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor ex_stage.sv to compute two shared combinational signals\\nonce and reference them from every consumer:\\n\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_imm;   // single adder for branch/jump target\\n  logic [31:0] pc_plus_4;     // single adder for linear-advance paths\\n  assign pc_plus_imm = in.pc + in.imm;\\n  assign pc_plus_4   = in.pc + 32'd4;\\n\\nThen rewrite:\\n  branch_target = pc_plus_imm;\\n  jump_target   = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0} : pc_plus_imm;\\n\\n  reg_q.pc_next <= misalign_fault ? pc_plus_4\\n                 : in.ctrl.is_jump  ? jump_target\\n                 : branch_taken     ? branch_target\\n                                    : pc_plus_4;\\n\\nThis is a pure structural refactor with zero functional change \\u2014\\nevery output bit is bit-identical to the current implementation for\\nevery input vector. Consequently:\\n\\n  - RVFI pc_wdata / pc_rdata taps are unchanged (same value, same\\n    cycle, same register).\\n  - No id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t payload bits added or removed\\n    (avoids the r5s2 / r6s2 payload-widening synthesis penalty).\\n  - No new formal state; SBY BMC depth unchanged (per the r1s2 and\\n    r3s1 lessons on symbolic-fetch coupling \\u2014 this change doesn't\\n    touch fetch or predictor state at all).\\n  - No change to the EX\\u2192MEM handshake, div_busy, or the JAL\\n    predictor in if_stage.sv.\\n\\nExpected effect on Tang Nano 20K synthesis:\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+imm (branch_target + jump_target\\n    sharing), saving ~32 LUT4 of carry chain duplication.\\n  - 1 adder collapsed for pc+4 (misalign-fault path + default\\n    pc_next sharing), saving another ~32 LUT4.\\n  - The pc_plus_imm wire is a single-source fanout to two mux legs\\n    (branch_target-select and jump_target-select) instead of two\\n    parallel adders racing to the same register input, shortening\\n    the critical-path slack on reg_q.pc_next.\\n\\nRisk profile:\\n  - Zero IPC impact (identical functional semantics).\\n  - Zero formal impact (same combinational output per input).\\n  - Zero invariant-1 (RVFI 2-channel) impact.\\n  - Only risk is that Yosys was already sharing these adders, in\\n    which case the RTL becomes cleaner but fitness is a wash. Even\\n    in that case the hypothesis strictly doesn't regress anything\\n    and documents the intent for future code readers. The LESSONS.md\\n    r6s0 note explicitly flags that Yosys sharing is NOT reliable\\n    for LUT-based datapaths across islands, which is the exact\\n    pattern here.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Introduce two shared combinational signals pc_plus_imm and\\npc_plus_4 at module scope, computed by a single `in.pc + in.imm`\\nand `in.pc + 32'd4` respectively. Replace all four existing\\nduplicate adder expressions (two `in.pc + in.imm` in the branch\\n/ jump-target blocks, two `in.pc + 32'd4` in the reg_q.pc_next\\nnext-state mux including the misalign_fault fallback) with\\nreferences to these shared wires. Preserve the existing\\njalr_sum = rs1 + imm computation for JALR (different operand,\\ndifferent adder). Preserve the (in.pc + 32'd4) expression used\\nfor the JAL rd_wdata path at reg_q.alu_result as a reference to\\npc_plus_4 as well. Verify bit-exact output equivalence by\\nrunning the full cocotb suite (test_alu, test_decoder,\\ntest_pipeline, test_rvfi) and the riscv-formal pc_fwd /\\nunique / liveness / insn_* checks \\u2014 no trace should change.\\n\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 364.26, \"delta_pct\": -3.17, \"vs_baseline\": 21.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 161.81, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5440, \"ff\": 1994, \"seeds\": [168.52, 158.33, 161.81], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:52:26.936440Z\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r7s0 (regression, -3.17%): Manually CSE'ing structurally-duplicated 32-bit adders (pc+imm across branch_target/jump_target; pc+4 across misalign-fault/default-pc_next/JAL-rd_wdata) in ex_stage.sv regressed fitness ~3% \\u2014 confirming that the r6s0 pattern generalizes beyond barrel shifters to ordinary adders on LUT4 fabrics: Yosys/nextpnr already share ripple-carry chains feeding a common mux cascade (the pc_next 4-way select was already collapsing in synthesis), so the hand-lifted `pc_plus_imm`/`pc_plus_4` wires introduce no new sharing but DO force a single-source high-fanout net feeding multiple mux legs across different always_comb blocks, which nextpnr routes with extra buffering/detour on Tang Nano 20K and lands worse on the EX critical path; the r3s0 DSP-consolidation heuristic is STRICTLY for hard primitives (DSP18, BSRAM, multipliers), and for LUT-only datapaths the empirical rule is \\\"don't manually CSE \\u2014 let the synth flow see the natural mux structure,\\\" with synth-report area diffs required before committing any structural-sharing refactor.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage BEQ/BNE-only early branch resolution (non-speculative, cheap comparator)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \\\"future\\nnon-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\\nBEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\\nthe signed/unsigned compare tree)\\\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\\ndominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\\nBEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture \\u224870-80% of conditional-branch cycles\\nat a fraction of the comparator cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \\\"future\\nnon-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\\nBEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\\nthe signed/unsigned compare tree)\\\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\\ndominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\\nBEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture \\u224870-80% of conditional-branch cycles\\nat a fraction of the comparator cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an ID-stage early-resolution path restricted to BEQ and BNE (funct3\\n\\u2208 {000, 001}), non-speculative: resolve the branch using forwarded rs1/rs2\\noperands at ID. The comparator is a single 32-bit equality (XOR-tree +\\nreduction-OR), dramatically cheaper than r6s2's 6-way signed/unsigned\\ncompare. When both operands are available at ID (not blocked behind an\\nin-flight LOAD in EX/MEM), compute taken = (rs1==rs2)^funct3[0], redirect\\nIF from ID to branch_target/pc+4, and mark the branch as already-resolved\\nin id_ex_t via a single 1-bit flag. At EX, a BEQ/BNE carrying\\nid_branch_resolved=1 bypasses the EX redirect (pc_next already correct,\\nRVFI pc_wdata wired from the pre-resolved target). Fallback: any BEQ/BNE\\nthat cannot be resolved at ID (operand behind an in-flight LOAD, or not\\nyet valid) falls through to the existing EX resolution path unchanged.\\nBLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU continue to resolve at EX (skipped by ID \\u2014 their\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree is what blew the timing budget in r6s2).\\n\\nFormal-tractability argument (addresses the r3s1/r3s2 trap): this change\\nis NON-speculative. ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2 values;\\nthere is no symbolic-fetch feedback loop where the predictor's redirect\\ntarget and the branch's resolved direction are both free variables.\\nrvfi_pc_wdata is always the resolved branch_target (whether resolved at\\nID or EX); rvfi_order / rvfi_trap are untouched. id_ex_t widens by 1 bit\\n(id_branch_resolved) plus a 32-bit pc_next field carried from ID \\u2014 BUT\\npc_next is already a 32-bit payload in ex_mem_t/mem_wb_t, so the extra\\nregister state is just 33 bits in id_ex_t, and the ID comparator is a\\nsingle narrow XOR-tree.\\n\\nWhy this is different from r6s2: r6s2 widened the ID comparator to cover\\nall 6 branch variants, which put a signed<, unsigned<, and == tree in\\nparallel on the ID combinational path. ID previously had slack vs EX but\\nnot enough for three wide comparators. BEQ/BNE alone is just a 32-bit XOR\\nreduction (\\u22485 LUT4 levels, same depth as a single operand-forward mux),\\nwhich should fit comfortably inside the existing ID slack. We explicitly\\nskip BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU to preserve ID-path timing.\\n\\nWhy this is different from r5s2: no 32-bit predicted_target threaded\\nthrough the pipeline, no new 4-way next_pc mux at IF. The 1-bit\\nid_branch_resolved flag and the 32-bit pc_next (already a downstream\\npayload field) are the only new id_ex_t state; EX muxes pc_next straight\\nthrough instead of recomputing it on resolved branches.\\n\\nExpected IPC win: CoreMark ~12-15% branch density, of which BEQ/BNE are\\n\\u224870-80%, taken rate ~60%. Saving 1 bubble cycle per taken BEQ/BNE where\\noperands are ID-available gives approx 0.12 \\u00d7 0.75 \\u00d7 0.60 = ~5.4% IPC\\nuplift. Fmax impact: neutral-to-slightly-negative (single narrow XOR tree\\n+ two 3:1 forwarding muxes on ID path). Net fitness: targeting +3-5%.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_resolved` (1-bit) and `pc_next` (32-bit) fields to id_ex_t so EX can bypass its redirect/target-mux for ID-resolved BEQ/BNE. pc_next defaults to pc+4 at ID for non-branches and non-resolved branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID-stage early-resolution logic restricted to funct3 \\u2208 {000 BEQ, 001 BNE}. Wire in rs1_val / rs2_val forwarding from EX/MEM.alu_result and MEM/WB write-mux data (drive via new input ports). Use a single 32-bit equality comparator (rs1_eff == rs2_eff), compute taken = eq ^ funct3[0]. Gate early resolution on: (a) instr is BEQ/BNE, (b) operand not waiting on an in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM, (c) if_id_w.valid. When resolved, set id_branch_resolved=1, set pc_next = taken ? (pc + B-imm) : (pc + 4), and drive an id_redirect pulse + id_redirect_target to if_stage via a new module output. Pass pc_next through id_ex_t.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_stage inputs (fwd_ex_mem, fwd_mem_wb, load_in_flight) from ex_mem_w and wb_stage outputs. Wire id_stage's new outputs (id_redirect, id_redirect_target) into if_stage alongside the existing EX redirect with ID having higher priority (the in-flight EX redirect cannot conflict since only one branch is in the resolution cone at a time). Add id_flush input to flush the branch shadow in IF/ID when ID redirects.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept new id_redirect / id_redirect_target inputs. PC reg update priority: reset > ex_redirect > id_redirect > static JAL predictor > pc+4. When id_redirect fires, emit NOP into the IF/ID combinational payload this cycle (same pattern as the existing flush logic) so the mis-speculated next sequential fetch is squashed.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"When id_ex_w.ctrl carries a BEQ/BNE AND id_branch_resolved=1, skip EX redirect (redirect output stays low for this instruction), and use id_ex_w.pc_next directly as the EX/MEM pc_next payload (don't recompute branch_target + branch_taken for RVFI). For non-resolved branches and BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, existing EX resolution path runs unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an id_redirect input mirroring the existing EX redirect's flush semantics: flush_if on id_redirect (so IF/ID next-cycle payload becomes NOP), and ensure the branch itself continues to ID/EX normally (the branch must retire with rvfi_valid=1 at WB \\u2014 only the wrong-path instruction behind it is squashed).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that exercises ID-stage early-resolution: a BEQ with rs1==rs2 and both operands ID-available should produce a taken redirect 1 cycle earlier than the current EX-resolution baseline (observe via fetch-PC sequence). A BEQ with operand blocked behind a LOAD falls through to EX resolution (baseline timing). Validate rvfi_pc_wdata matches the branch target on both paths.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `id_branch_resolved` (1-bit) and `pc_next` (32-bit) fields to id_ex_t so EX can bypass its redirect/target-mux for ID-resolved BEQ/BNE. pc_next defaults to pc+4 at ID for non-branches and non-resolved branches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add ID-stage early-resolution logic restricted to funct3 \\u2208 {000 BEQ, 001 BNE}. Wire in rs1_val / rs2_val forwarding from EX/MEM.alu_result and MEM/WB write-mux data (drive via new input ports). Use a single 32-bit equality comparator (rs1_eff == rs2_eff), compute taken = eq ^ funct3[0]. Gate early resolution on: (a) instr is BEQ/BNE, (b) operand not waiting on an in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM, (c) if_id_w.valid. When resolved, set id_branch_resolved=1, set pc_next = taken ? (pc + B-imm) : (pc + 4), and drive an id_redirect pulse + id_redirect_target to if_stage via a new module output. Pass pc_next through id_ex_t.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire new id_stage inputs (fwd_ex_mem, fwd_mem_wb, load_in_flight) from ex_mem_w and wb_stage outputs. Wire id_stage's new outputs (id_redirect, id_redirect_target) into if_stage alongside the existing EX redirect with ID having higher priority (the in-flight EX redirect cannot conflict since only one branch is in the resolution cone at a time). Add id_flush input to flush the branch shadow in IF/ID when ID redirects.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept new id_redirect / id_redirect_target inputs. PC reg update priority: reset > ex_redirect > id_redirect > static JAL predictor > pc+4. When id_redirect fires, emit NOP into the IF/ID combinational payload this cycle (same pattern as the existing flush logic) so the mis-speculated next sequential fetch is squashed.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"When id_ex_w.ctrl carries a BEQ/BNE AND id_branch_resolved=1, skip EX redirect (redirect output stays low for this instruction), and use id_ex_w.pc_next directly as the EX/MEM pc_next payload (don't recompute branch_target + branch_taken for RVFI). For non-resolved branches and BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, existing EX resolution path runs unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an id_redirect input mirroring the existing EX redirect's flush semantics: flush_if on id_redirect (so IF/ID next-cycle payload becomes NOP), and ensure the branch itself continues to ID/EX normally (the branch must retire with rvfi_valid=1 at WB \\u2014 only the wrong-path instruction behind it is squashed).\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a cocotb test that exercises ID-stage early-resolution: a BEQ with rs1==rs2 and both operands ID-available should produce a taken redirect 1 cycle earlier than the current EX-resolution baseline (observe via fetch-PC sequence). A BEQ with operand blocked behind a LOAD falls through to EX resolution (baseline timing). Validate rvfi_pc_wdata matches the branch target on both paths.\"}], \"outcome\": \"regression\", \"fitness\": 376.19, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 24.96, \"fmax_mhz\": 167.11, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442158, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 5469, \"ff\": 2016, \"seeds\": [169.98, 160.9, 167.11], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T01:54:21.381056Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 7, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r7s2 (regression, +0.00%): Following r6s2's post-mortem prescription to narrow ID-stage early branch resolution to BEQ/BNE-only (single 32-bit XOR-reduction equality, skipping the signed/unsigned compare tree) still lands at ~0% net fitness \\u2014 disproving the \\\"narrower comparator will fit in ID slack\\\" escape hatch and confirming the alternative branch of r6s2's dilemma: this pipeline's control-flow IPC-Fmax curve is structurally saturated after r2s2's JAL predictor because (a) BEQ/BNE-dependent-on-in-flight-LOAD cases cannot forward to ID (the LOAD's rdata doesn't exist yet at ID, forcing a new load-use stall that didn't exist when resolution was at EX) and those cases are common in CoreMark's pointer-walk / null-check idioms, (b) the 1-bit `id_branch_resolved` flag widening id_ex_t costs synthesis area on Tang Nano 20K regardless of comparator width (same mechanism as r5s2's RAS payload and r6s2's full-width variant), and (c) the BEQ/BNE \\u224870-80%-of-conditional-branches estimate ignores that the remaining BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU still pay the full 2-cycle bubble, capping the achievable IPC uplift below the fixed structural cost; future branch-bubble hypotheses on this microarchitecture should pivot away from ID-resolution entirely (the slot is now proven saturated across both wide-r6s2 and narrow-r7s2 variants) toward non-control-flow optimizations or accept the saturation.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Check if load-use forwarding was tried","truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/bonetto/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_deb954c5b001dh7e6xNxrZtU2M"},"title":"Check if load-use forwarding was tried","time":{"start":1777773923393,"end":1777773923424}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the formal verification failure for r2s0's approach—they tried the same pre-registration strategy at the MEM/WB boundary that I was considering, but hit a `reg_ch0` check failure marked as PREUNSAT with no traces. The lesson attributed it to an RVFI provenance mismatch, though the actual error output shows `reg_ch0` passing at 82s before being flagged as failed, so I need to dig deeper into what's actually happening there. The core issue is that `mem_rdata` (raw memory word for RVFI) and `read_data` (sign/zero-extended for register writes) are distinct fields, and r2s0 likely conflated them when adding `rd_wdata`. The fix is to keep `mem_rdata` untouched for RVFI, compute `rd_wdata` from the combinational load extension logic rather than the raw memory value, and either remove the now-dead `read_data` or leave it unused — the real problem is probably that `rvfi_rd_wdata` isn't being driven correctly, which is why `reg_ch0` failed.\n\nI'm exploring alternative structural approaches since the exact breakage is unclear: registering divider output won't help much since division is rare, separating the regfile read failed pipeline tests, replacing the regfile with BRAM failed, and pipelining the multiplier also failed. The EX stage's mux for `alu_result_eff` is fine as-is. For the IF stage, the PC computation chains together redirect logic, JAL target decode, and the default increment — all combinational — which might be worth examining for timing or correctness issues.\n\nA speculative JALR return address stack seems promising but complex: the post-mortem from r5s2 suggests reconstructing the predicted target at EX rather than threading it through the pipeline, but that defeats the purpose since JALR prediction needs to happen in IF to avoid bubbles. The pipeline bubble structure for JALR is two cycles (IF → ID → EX resolve → IF redirect), so a RAS-based prediction in IF could match JAL's behavior, but managing RAS state (push on JAL with x1/x5, pop on JALR with x1/x5) adds significant complexity.\n\nTrying other angles: splitting the ALU path, reducing fanout on the MEM/WB forward path, or restructuring the id_ex_t payload don't seem to yield real gains. The DIVIDER improvement worked well, so I'm looking at what else is hot in EX. Extracting the branch comparator into a dedicated module could shorten the path, but registering its inputs would add a pipeline stage. The real critical path in EX likely runs through the forwarding mux, ALU operand selection, the ALU itself (with multiplier DSP), then the div-override and pc_next muxes, or for branches it's forwarding → comparison → branch select → pc_next.\n\nThe multiplier DSP is probably the bottleneck, and the r3s0 optimization already addressed that. Most other structural improvements have been explored—pipelining EX further violates the depth constraint, and registering the forwarding muxes would break forwarding semantics. The one unexplored option is forwarding load data directly from the MEM stage combinationally to the EX forwarding muxes, which could eliminate the load-use stall by making dependent instructions see the loaded value one cycle earlier instead of waiting for it to reach WB.\n\nThe timing hinges on when the BRAM's read data arrives—in simulation it's combinational, but on the FPGA with registered BRAM reads, dmem_rdata won't be available until the end of the MEM cycle, which is too late to help the dependent instruction in EX that same cycle. I need to check how io_dmemRData is actually wired in the testbench to understand the real timing constraints. The new forwarding path from BRAM output through the shift/extend logic, forward mux, and into the ALU is significantly longer than the current critical path, which could drop Fmax even though it eliminates the load-use stall and improves IPC. I need to trace through the exact timing chain to see if this is feasible or if the critical path risk outweighs the performance gain.\n\nOne approach is to forward only word-aligned loads (LW) with raw BRAM data, bypassing the shift/extend logic entirely, but that still requires decoding the MEM instruction to know whether to forward, which brings back the full computation chain. I'm hitting a semantic and timing wall here — the idea is promising for CoreMark's pointer-heavy workload, but the structural cost might be prohibitive.\n\nLet me explore other pipeline modifications instead: a two-cycle IF stage would change depth and violate earlier constraints, and adding a branch prediction stage was already rejected. I need to think about what other structural changes could help without breaking timing or the existing design principles.\n\nWhat if I decouple regfile writes from WB entirely — for non-load instructions, write directly from MEM one cycle earlier? That would shrink the forwarding window, though it adds complexity by splitting writes across two stages. The existing forwarding paths from EX/MEM already exist, so that's not new. Maybe the better move is to focus on load-use forwarding with a tighter scope, or reconsider the rd_wdata consolidation despite the earlier failure.\n\nLet me examine the hazard detection logic more carefully to understand exactly when load-use stalls are triggered.\n\nThe load-use stall happens because the LOAD's data doesn't arrive until the MEM stage, but the dependent instruction is already in ID/EX and needs it immediately. I could add a forwarding path directly from the MEM-stage load data to the EX-stage operand mux, letting the dependent proceed without stalling. The critical path would be tight — dmem output through the load logic, into the forward mux, then into the ALU — but on an FPGA with registered BRAM reads, it might fit within the cycle. This could save a cycle on every load-dependent-load pattern, which shows up frequently in pointer chains and could yield a solid IPC improvement. The risk is that Fmax might suffer if this path becomes critical, making the net gain uncertain.\n\nLet me verify the timing more carefully. At cycle N+1, the LOAD is in MEM and the dependent is in EX, so I need to tap the MEM stage's combinational load_data output directly — not the registered version that feeds the writeback forwarding. I'd expose that combinational output as a new port, add it as a fourth input to the EX operand mux, and update the forward unit to detect when a LOAD in the EX/MEM register has its destination matching the dependent's source operand.\n\nActually, I can simplify this. Since both the ALU result and the LOAD data come from the same EX/MEM register, I can just multiplex them at the forward input itself — if the instruction is a LOAD, select the combinational load data; otherwise use the ALU result. That way I don't need new forward select logic, just a mux on the fwd_ex_mem wire. Then I can remove the load-use hazard stall entirely since the forwarding handles it. This should also work for dependent STOREs and BRANCHes that follow a LOAD, since they'll all use the same forwarded data path through the EX stage.\n\nThe real risk is timing. The critical path now runs from BRAM output through the MEM stage's shift/extend logic, then through the EX forward mux, ALU mux, ALU itself, and into the EX/MEM register. That's adding several LUT levels on top of what was already a tight combinational path. At 167 MHz this could easily fail to close. It's a novel structural idea with real potential, but the timing risk is genuine. Let me document this and set confidence to medium, then check if this has been explored before.\n\nLooking through the lessons, I don't see load-use forwarding elimination attempted yet, so this is fresh ground. Before committing to it, let me scan the remaining optimization categories: pipeline depth is saturated, stage work redistribution might have room, register and forwarding paths are where I'm focusing now, datapath sharing is mostly exhausted, and the predictor is near its limits. Load-use forwarding elimination stands out as genuinely novel and could be a significant win if timing holds. The control logic simplifies too—dropping the load_use_hazard condition from stall and flush signals keeps the other constraints intact. I'll write this up.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb954796001AdfXd4p3a5hJNt","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","messageID":"msg_deb93f00a001A1SOM7jAzaEaqO"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777773923429,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"id":"prt_deb95450c0017KnwNi3sYMd8wy","messageID":"msg_deb93f00a001A1SOM7jAzaEaqO","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons, the saturated paths are:\n- Branch prediction (formal trap or IF-timing)\n- DSP/divider sharing (already done)\n- Manual CSE on LUT4 adders (regresses)\n- Pipeline depth changes (breaks test_pipeline.py guardrail)\n- rd_wdata consolidation (r2s0 failed with `reg_ch0` break)\n\nOne genuine unexplored structural move: **eliminate the load-use 1-cycle bubble** via MEM→EX combinational forwarding. CoreMark's pointer-chase kernels (matrix, list, state) take this stall on nearly every dependent load. The forward source would be mem_stage's combinational `load_data` output, muxed into EX's existing `fwd_ex_mem` input when EX/MEM holds a LOAD.\n\nLet me check the critical-path contour once more, then write.","time":{"start":1777773921548,"end":1777773923429}}}
