{"type":"text","timestamp":1777773992495,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"id":"prt_deb958806001E7XP8gE1i7zAeI","messageID":"msg_deb954c9f001EbxzDH262AaJdO","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","type":"text","text":"Good — load-use forwarding elimination has not been tried. This is a genuine structural opportunity: CoreMark's pointer-chase kernels (list, matrix, state) pay a 1-cycle bubble on nearly every dependent load. Eliminating it requires a new combinational forward path from MEM-stage `load_data` to EX's operand muxes.\n\nThe concerns:\n- Critical path risk: dmem_rdata (BRAM q) → shift/extend → fwd mux → ALU could displace the existing EX path.\n- Lessons r5s2/r6s2 warn against widening pipeline payload. This hypothesis adds NO payload bits — just a new combinational forward source, and REMOVES the load-use hazard (net simplification of hazard_unit).\n\nLet me write it.","time":{"start":1777773938694,"end":1777773992494}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777773992502,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01PTjZbrBDFT4h7883vUa7vj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r8s1\ntitle: \"Eliminate load-use bubble via combinational MEM->EX load_data forwarding\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\n  r6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\n  comparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\n  or cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \"pursue\n  non-branch optimizations\". The largest remaining non-branch IPC loss\n  is the load-use hazard: a 1-cycle bubble inserted by hazard_unit\n  whenever an instruction in IF/ID consumes rd of a LOAD currently in\n  ID/EX. CoreMark is pointer-chase-heavy (core_list_find reverse walk,\n  core_bench_matrix row/column dereferences, core_state_transition's\n  character-class table lookup, crcu16/32 inner loops) — every dependent\n  load pays this stall. Empirically this is the single most common\n  non-branch pipeline bubble in CoreMark's dynamic trace.\n\n  Structural gap search: none of the prior iterations attempted this.\n  r5s1 (divider extraction, +8.79%) and r3s0 (DSP fold, +8.50%) both\n  succeeded by removing waste from the EX datapath; the symmetric move\n  on the DATA side is to make the LOAD-to-dependent path single-cycle\n  instead of 2-cycle. r2s0's rd_wdata consolidation tried to shorten\n  the MEM/WB forwarding path but broke the reg_ch0 formal check by\n  mis-plumbing the RVFI tap — that failure was a wiring bug, not a\n  structural impossibility. This hypothesis attacks a different path\n  (MEM combinational, not MEM/WB registered) and explicitly preserves\n  every RVFI field's provenance byte-for-byte.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a new combinational forwarding source that exposes the current\n  MEM-stage LOAD's extracted data to EX's rs1/rs2 operand muxes the\n  same cycle the load is in MEM. This collapses the existing 1-cycle\n  load-use stall to zero bubbles for the (common) case where the\n  dependent instruction follows the LOAD by exactly one pipeline slot.\n\n  Microarchitectural change:\n  1. mem_stage.sv exposes a new output port `load_data_comb [31:0]`\n     equal to the already-computed combinational `load_data` signal\n     (the sign/zero-extended, byte-shifted result). This is a pure\n     tap on existing combinational logic — no new gates.\n  2. ex_stage.sv accepts two new inputs: `fwd_mem_load_data [31:0]`\n     and `fwd_mem_is_load` (1-bit, = ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read &\n     ex_mem_w.valid, computed at top level). The existing\n     `fwd_ex_mem` input (= ex_mem_w.alu_result) is REPLACED by a\n     2:1 mux: `fwd_mem_is_load ? fwd_mem_load_data : ex_mem_w.alu_result`.\n     Forward select encoding 2'd1 continues to mean \"EX/MEM\n     instruction's writeback value\" — but now routes LOAD data when\n     the EX/MEM instruction is a LOAD, and ALU result otherwise.\n     No new select code (2'd1 is reused); forward_unit.sv is\n     unchanged.\n  3. hazard_unit.sv: DELETE the load_use_hazard computation and\n     remove it from stall_id / flush_id / stall_if.\n     stall_if = imem_stall || dmem_stall || div_busy.\n     stall_id = dmem_stall || div_busy.\n     flush_id = redirect && !dmem_stall && !div_busy.\n     The load-use hazard port inputs (id_ex_mem_read, id_ex_rd,\n     if_id_rs1, if_id_rs2) can be deleted — they are no longer\n     consumed.\n  4. core.sv: wire mem_stage.load_data_comb to ex_stage's new\n     fwd_mem_load_data input. Compute fwd_mem_is_load from ex_mem_w.\n     Remove the hazard_unit inputs that are no longer needed.\n\n  IPC gain: every dependent load retires 1 cycle earlier. On a\n  CoreMark trace where ~25% of instructions are LOADs and ~55% have\n  an immediately-dependent consumer (common pointer-chase pattern\n  in list/matrix/state kernels), that's ~14% of dynamic instructions\n  saving 1 cycle each. Against a baseline ~2.5 CPI, expected IPC\n  uplift is ~5-6%.\n\n  Fmax risk analysis (the core concern):\n    The new combinational chain for an EX instruction forwarding\n    from a MEM-stage LOAD is:\n      dmem_rdata (BRAM Q, clk-to-q)\n      -> mem_stage shift by addr[1:0]*8 (1-2 LUT levels)\n      -> mem_sext/mem_width mux (1 LUT level)\n      -> EX fwd mux (fwd_mem_is_load select, merges into existing\n         fwd_rs?_sel cascade — no added levels)\n      -> EX auipc mux (1 LUT level)\n      -> ALU operand mux (1 LUT level)\n      -> ALU (DSP18 multiplier dominates, ~3-4 LUT-equivalent levels)\n      -> div_result_eff mux (1 LUT level)\n      -> EX/MEM register\n\n    Compared to the BASELINE EX critical path:\n      ex_mem_reg Q (flop clk-to-q, faster than BRAM)\n      -> EX fwd mux ... (rest identical from fwd mux onward)\n\n    The new path front-end adds ~2-3 LUT levels PLUS swaps a flop\n    clk-to-q for a BRAM clk-to-q. On Gowin GW2A at 167 MHz with a\n    ~6 ns period, that's plausibly ~0.5-1 ns of extra pre-ALU\n    delay. The ALU-output side of the critical path is unchanged.\n    If the ALU/DSP was the existing bottleneck (likely, given\n    r3s0's DSP consolidation was the last Fmax-dominated win),\n    this new path may or may not become critical depending on\n    BRAM clk-to-q.\n\n    Mitigation if Fmax regresses: the fwd_mem_is_load signal\n    steers the mux only when the EX/MEM instruction is a LOAD\n    (~25% of cycles). Synthesis tools may timing-specialize the\n    path accordingly; the non-LOAD path is unchanged.\n\n  Why this avoids prior failure modes:\n    - r2s0 (broken): rd_wdata consolidation broke reg_ch0 because\n      the RVFI rd_wdata tap was mis-pointed. THIS hypothesis\n      touches neither mem_wb_t nor RVFI taps — only mem_stage's\n      combinational output and ex_stage's forward-input wiring.\n      rvfi_rd_wdata continues to come from wb_stage's w_data\n      unchanged. rvfi_mem_rdata still comes from mem_wb.mem_rdata\n      unchanged.\n    - r5s2 / r6s2 / r7s2 (all -60% to 0%): payload widening killed\n      Fmax. THIS hypothesis adds ZERO pipeline payload bits. id_ex_t,\n      ex_mem_t, mem_wb_t, ctrl_t are all bit-identical to baseline.\n    - r1s2 / r3s1 / r3s2 (formal broken): speculative state coupled\n      with symbolic fetch. THIS hypothesis introduces no speculation;\n      the forwarded LOAD data is the exact same value the LOAD will\n      commit next cycle (guaranteed by the pipeline contract that a\n      LOAD in MEM is on the retiring path if valid). No new formal\n      state. rvfi_order / rvfi_valid / retirement sequence identical\n      to baseline for every instruction.\n    - r7s0 (LUT CSE regression, -3.17%): hand-lifted shared wires\n      across always_comb islands hurt routing. THIS hypothesis adds\n      one cross-module wire (load_data_comb from mem_stage to\n      ex_stage), which is a natural module interface, not a forced\n      CSE. The synth flow will see the obvious structural sharing.\n\n  RVFI invariants (CLAUDE.md #1, #2, #4):\n    - rvfi_order still +1 per retirement. Zero-bubble load-use means\n      retirement rate increases (no holes), which is fine.\n    - rvfi_rd_wdata still matches regfile write. The dependent\n      instruction's rd_wdata is computed from the forwarded load\n      value — the SAME value that will be in mem_wb_w.read_data\n      one cycle later and will trigger the same regfile write.\n      Formal's `reg` check compares rvfi_rd_wdata to the actual\n      regfile write by rvfi_order, not by cycle — the order /\n      value pair is preserved.\n    - rvfi_trap unchanged: ill-check sees same trap pattern.\n    - Symbolic-fetch: every fetch path is the same as baseline\n      (IF-stage redirect priority, JAL predictor, etc. untouched).\n\n  Implementation notes for the agent:\n    - Do NOT rename any mem_wb_t field, ex_mem_t field, or ctrl_t\n      field. The r2s0 failure was an RVFI-tap mis-plumbing triggered\n      by a struct rename.\n    - Keep mem_stage's existing MEM/WB register-write logic\n      byte-for-byte identical — only ADD the combinational output\n      port.\n    - The forward-select priority stays EX/MEM > MEM/WB > ID/EX, so\n      forward_unit.sv need not change. The 2'd1 select code just\n      now routes load_data instead of alu_result when the EX/MEM\n      instruction is a LOAD.\n    - Double-check: for LOAD in EX/MEM + STORE in EX where STORE's\n      rs2 == LOAD's rd (forward write_data), the new mux must also\n      kick in on rs2. The fwd_rs2_sel = 2'd1 path goes through the\n      same EX mux, so this falls out naturally.\n    - hazard_unit still needs to stall on dmem_stall and div_busy.\n      Only load_use_hazard is removed.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Expose the existing combinational `load_data` signal as a new module output port `load_data_comb [31:0]`. This is a pure tap — no new logic. The signal is the sign/zero-extended, byte-shifted load result computed from dmem_rdata and in.alu_result[1:0] + in.ctrl.mem_width + in.ctrl.mem_sext. Keep the MEM/WB register-write logic byte-for-byte identical; this is ADDITIVE only.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Accept two new input ports: `fwd_mem_load_data [31:0]` and `fwd_mem_is_load` (1-bit). Replace the current `fwd_ex_mem` mux input with a 2:1 mux: `fwd_mem_is_load ? fwd_mem_load_data : fwd_ex_mem`. The existing forward-select cascade (fwd_rs1_sel / fwd_rs2_sel driven by forward_unit) is unchanged — 2'd1 now transparently routes LOAD data when EX/MEM holds a LOAD, ALU result otherwise. No changes to ALU, divider, branch resolve, EX/MEM register layout, or RVFI plumbing.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Delete the load_use_hazard computation and its contributions to stall_if / stall_id / flush_id. Delete the now-unused module inputs `id_ex_mem_read`, `id_ex_rd`, `if_id_rs1`, `if_id_rs2`. Resulting signals: stall_if = imem_stall || dmem_stall || div_busy; stall_id = dmem_stall || div_busy; flush_id = redirect && !dmem_stall && !div_busy; stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Add two new top-level combinational wires: `mem_load_data_comb` (from mem_stage's new output) and `fwd_mem_is_load` (= ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read && ex_mem_w.valid). Wire these into ex_stage's new input ports. Delete the hazard_unit connections for id_ex_mem_read / id_ex_rd / if_id_rs1 / if_id_rs2 (no longer inputs to hazard_unit). No RVFI port changes. No IO contract changes.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a directed cocotb test that exercises zero-bubble load-use: program `LW x5, 0(x6) ; ADDI x7, x5, 1 ; ADDI x8, x5, 2` and verify the ADDI at PC+4 retires exactly 1 cycle after the LW retires (not 2 cycles as in the baseline), observable via rvfi_order timing on mem_wb_w. Also add a regression test: a STORE whose rs2 depends on the immediately-preceding LOAD (LW x5,0(x6); SW x5,0(x7)) should retire with zero bubble and correctly write the LOAD's data to the STORE address. Keep existing probe names (dut.u_ex.reg_q.*, dut.u_mem.reg_q.*) to avoid the r4s1 rollback trap.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777773992485,"end":1777773992500}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm considering load-use forwarding as a structural improvement—CoreMark has many loads, and each dependent instruction currently incurs a bubble due to the load-use hazard. Adding a combinational forward path from the memory stage's load data directly to the execute stage's operand forwarding mux would eliminate this stall.\n\nNow I'm analyzing the critical path more carefully. The current bottleneck is the ALU multiplier through the DSP block, with the forward mux and subsequent stages before it being relatively short. My proposal is to extend the forwarding mux to include the load data combinationally computed from the BRAM output—this adds a shift and sign/zero-extend operation before the mux, but the timing impact depends on how many LUT levels this adds and whether it fits within the existing mux structure.\n\nThe key question is whether this new path (BRAM output → shift/extend → forwarding mux → ALU path) stays competitive with the current critical path, since the DSP multiply dominates either way. If the pre-DSP depth is similar, frequency shouldn't suffer. I'm estimating around 15% of instructions could benefit from this (loads with immediate use), which would give roughly a 6% IPC improvement, so I'm expecting a 5-8% fitness gain overall with medium confidence given the timing risk.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb958c1f001CxAlf1Fa5dBrcu","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","messageID":"msg_deb954c9f001EbxzDH262AaJdO"}}
