{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774002811,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","part":{"id":"prt_deb966229001dTY8KKQSf04aES","messageID":"msg_deb965a80001eNdO7fBKR1GRmh","sessionID":"ses_2146ce520ffegdvyQZvzOmSU1u","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written. Summary:\n\n**hyp-20260502-002-r8s1 — Eliminate load-use bubble via MEM→EX combinational load_data forwarding**\n\nThe unexplored structural gap: control-flow bubbles are saturated (r6s2/r7s2), but the load-use 1-cycle stall is still paid by every dependent load in CoreMark's pointer-chase kernels (list/matrix/state/crcu16/32). No prior hypothesis has attacked this.\n\nKey design choices to avoid known failure modes:\n- **Zero payload widening** (dodges r5s2/r6s2/r7s2 cost): no new bits in id_ex_t/ex_mem_t/ctrl_t.\n- **Zero speculation** (dodges r1s2/r3s1/r3s2 formal traps): forwarded value is the exact same word the LOAD would register next cycle; rvfi_order, rvfi_valid, retirement sequence all identical.\n- **Zero RVFI-tap mutation** (dodges r2s0 reg_ch0 break): mem_wb_t untouched, rvfi_rd_wdata still sourced from wb_stage.w_data.\n- **No forced cross-module CSE** (dodges r7s0 routing regression): single natural module-interface wire (mem_stage.load_data_comb → ex_stage).\n- Reuses existing 2'd1 forward-select code (fwd_mem_is_load swaps ALU-result for load_data at the same mux input) — forward_unit.sv unchanged.\n\nPrimary risk: the new pre-ALU path (BRAM clk-to-q → shift+extend → fwd mux → ALU) may become critical vs. the existing (flop clk-to-q → fwd mux → ALU) path, costing Fmax. Expected IPC uplift ~5-6% from zero-bubble dependent loads.","time":{"start":1777773994537,"end":1777774002808}}}
