{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777775105916,"sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","part":{"id":"prt_deba757770019U3GblGbtMnVQK","messageID":"msg_deba745ea0014ettneYh3nJvj6","sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","snapshot":"2393aff5fa4c3497571006e96f4063af2f4248c9","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777775254032,"sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","part":{"id":"prt_deba9042f001ZTHLGtOwkHhSEf","messageID":"msg_deba745ea0014ettneYh3nJvj6","sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, I need to find a structural change that:\n- Avoids IF-stage next_pc mux widening (r8s2, r5s2)\n- Avoids pipeline payload bloat (r5s2, r7s2)\n- Avoids manual CSE on LUT4 fabrics (r6s0, r7s0)\n- Avoids pipeline-depth changes (r4s1)\n- Targets an actual critical path\n\nThe most promising unexplored angle: the EX-stage forwarding fan-in includes the `wb_stage` 2:1 mux (`mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result`) feeding the 3:1 forward-select mux. This is an extra post-flop LUT4 level on the `fwd_mem_wb` path directly into the ALU input. Consolidating the WB-mux into `mem_stage` (so `mem_wb` stores a single pre-muxed `wb_data` field) shortens that post-flop path by one mux level while also narrowing `mem_wb_t` by 32 bits. r2s0's lesson flagged this class of refactor as requiring careful RVFI-tap re-pointing — that's exactly the mitigation I'll apply.","time":{"start":1777775215663,"end":1777775254031}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777775254044,"sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01X5ZoQWwPoT97A8YD8y3pAF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r9s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-002-r9s1\ntitle: \"Pre-register the WB-mux: collapse mem_wb.read_data + alu_result into a single pre-muxed wb_data field\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The EX-stage forwarding fan-in currently traverses, on the MEM/WB leg,\n  a registered mem_wb.read_data / mem_wb.alu_result pair → a combinational\n  2:1 mux in wb_stage (selecting on mem_to_reg) → the 3:1 forward-select\n  mux in ex_stage → ALU input. That post-flop 2:1 wb_stage mux is an\n  extra LUT4 level sitting directly in the rs1/rs2 → ALU critical path\n  for every instruction that depends on the instruction two ahead.\n\n  Per r5s1 + r7s1 / r8s1 lessons, the EX/MEM clk-to-q is not the binding\n  bottleneck on this fabric; the binding path is EX combinational depth.\n  The JAL-predictor algebraic win (r8s0, +6%) came from decoupling a\n  guard from a 32-bit adder — the same \"shave one LUT4 level from a hot\n  fan-in\" pattern. Shortening the MEM/WB forwarding leg is structurally\n  analogous and also saves 32 flops (one of the two 32-bit fields becomes\n  dead) plus a sliver of ex_mem_t width isn't touched.\n\n  r2s0 previously tripped on this refactor — the failure mode was losing\n  RVFI rd_wdata / mem_rdata tap provenance when fields were renamed. That\n  lesson is the specific mitigation playbook: keep mem_rdata (the raw\n  dmem word) as a separate RVFI-only field, re-point io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0\n  to the new mem_wb_w.wb_data signal in lockstep, and verify rd_wen\n  gating at the RVFI boundary still zeroes wb_data when reg_write=0.\nhypothesis: |\n  Fold the wb_stage 2:1 write-back mux (w_data = mem_to_reg ? read_data\n  : alu_result) into mem_stage so it is computed BEFORE the MEM/WB flop\n  rather than AFTER. Concretely:\n\n  1. rtl/core_pkg.sv — in mem_wb_t, replace the 32-bit `read_data` and\n     32-bit `alu_result` fields with a single 32-bit `wb_data` field.\n     Keep `mem_rdata` (raw dmem word for RVFI), `mem_wdata`, mem_addr,\n     and the rs?_val / pc / pc_next / instr / rd / rs?_addr / ctrl /\n     valid fields unchanged. Net payload change: -32 bits.\n\n  2. rtl/mem_stage.sv — compute `wb_data_comb = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ?\n     load_data : in.alu_result` combinationally and register it into\n     reg_q.wb_data on the non-hold_wb path. The hold_wb path retains\n     wb_data (same semantics as the old read_data / alu_result retain).\n\n  3. rtl/wb_stage.sv — becomes a trivial pass-through: w_en =\n     in.ctrl.reg_write && in.valid; w_addr = in.rd; w_data = in.wb_data.\n     The 2:1 mux is gone here (it now lives pre-flop in mem_stage).\n\n  4. rtl/core.sv — update the RVFI taps:\n       io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 = rd_wen ? mem_wb_w.wb_data : 32'b0;\n     (was: rd_wen ? wb_w_data : 32'b0, where wb_w_data was the wb_stage\n     mux output — semantically identical since wb_w_data === mem_wb_w.wb_data\n     after the refactor). io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0 continues to tap the raw\n     mem_wb_w.mem_rdata field — UNCHANGED.\n     The `fwd_mem_wb` input to ex_stage is re-pointed from `wb_w_data`\n     to `mem_wb_w.wb_data` directly (one wire re-name at the\n     instantiation site). forward_unit itself is unchanged.\n\n  5. rtl/ex_stage.sv — no logic change; the `.fwd_mem_wb` port receives\n     `mem_wb_w.wb_data` instead of `wb_w_data`. Both are registered,\n     same timing class; the difference is wb_data is now a direct flop\n     output with NO intervening mux.\n\n  Result: the rs1/rs2 → ALU path from a MEM/WB-forwarded operand drops\n  from (flop-q) → (wb_stage 2:1 mux) → (fwd 3:1 mux) → (alu_a/b 2:1\n  mux) → adder, to (flop-q) → (fwd 3:1 mux) → (alu_a/b 2:1 mux) →\n  adder. One LUT4 level saved on a hot post-flop path; ~0.3-0.5ns on\n  GW2A routing, plus the 2:1 mux's area and its detour from wb_stage to\n  ex_stage routing-wise.\n\n  Pre-flop in mem_stage: `load_data` computation (shift + sign-extend,\n  already on mem_stage's critical path) now feeds the 2:1 wb_mux before\n  the MEM/WB flop — but load_data comp is the dominant mem_stage path\n  anyway, so adding one 2:1 mux before the flop fits in the existing\n  slack (mem_stage is not the critical stage per the Fmax-177 profile;\n  EX is).\n\n  Formal/RVFI correctness: rd_wdata retirement value is identical — the\n  mux moved by one pipeline register, from post-flop combinational to\n  pre-flop combinational, but for any instruction the mem_to_reg signal\n  is stable across the EX→MEM→WB boundary so the mux inputs and output\n  are bit-exact the same at retirement. The RVFI reg check compares\n  rvfi_rd_wdata to the regfile write; both now read from the same\n  registered wb_data, preserving provenance (the r2s0 lesson\n  requirement). The mem_rdata tap is unchanged so ALIGNED_MEM /\n  mem_rdata / mem_rmask checks are untouched. hold_wb semantics are\n  unchanged — wb_data is retained exactly as read_data/alu_result were.\n\n  IPC unchanged (no stall or bubble behavior changed); this is purely\n  an Fmax + LUT4 + FF structural play. Expected: modest Fmax lift from\n  one-LUT4 shortening of a post-flop hot path, plus ~32 fewer flops and\n  a handful of LUT4s. Conservative because Yosys may already share the\n  wb mux into the fwd mux via cross-module flattening — but the\n  LESSONS-captured pattern (r8s0: \"isolate the mux SELECT from the\n  32-bit combinational chain\") suggests the explicit pre-register form\n  gives nextpnr a cleaner netlist to route.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"In mem_wb_t, replace read_data (32b) and alu_result (32b) with single wb_data (32b). Keep mem_rdata / mem_wdata / mem_addr / rs?_val / pc / pc_next / instr / rd / rs?_addr / ctrl / valid unchanged. Net -32 bits in mem_wb_t.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute wb_data_comb = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result combinationally. Register it into reg_q.wb_data on the non-hold_wb path. hold_wb retains wb_data (same semantics as old read_data/alu_result retain). Remove the reg_q.read_data and reg_q.alu_result assignments.\"\n  - file: rtl/wb_stage.sv\n    description: \"Simplify to pure pass-through: w_en = in.ctrl.reg_write && in.valid; w_addr = in.rd; w_data = in.wb_data. Delete the 2:1 mem_to_reg mux (it now lives pre-flop in mem_stage).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Re-point RVFI rd_wdata tap: io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 = rd_wen ? mem_wb_w.wb_data : 32'b0 (was wb_w_data). Re-point forward_unit/ex_stage fwd_mem_wb input: ex_stage u_ex .fwd_mem_wb(mem_wb_w.wb_data) (was wb_w_data). io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0 continues to tap mem_wb_w.mem_rdata — UNCHANGED. All other RVFI taps unchanged. Rationale follows r2s0 mitigation: keep mem_rdata separate from wb_data so mem_rdata RVFI provenance is preserved.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"No logic change — .fwd_mem_wb port now receives mem_wb_w.wb_data (re-named at the core.sv instantiation). The 2:1 wb_stage mux that used to sit in the MEM/WB → EX forwarding path is gone; the registered value is already the final w_data.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r9s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-002-r9s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777775254023,"end":1777775254041}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the key constraints from previous experiments: the IF-stage multiplexer for next_pc is expensive on this FPGA, combinational forwarding creates formal verification issues, and sequentializing the multiplier hurts performance since it's heavily used in CoreMark. Now I need to synthesize these lessons into a structural design that avoids these pitfalls.\n\nLooking at what's left to explore, I'm considering several angles: whether we can selectively pipeline only the MULH variants while keeping single-cycle MUL, if an instruction prefetch buffer could hide memory latency, whether fusing common pseudo-ops like AUIPC+ADDI would help, and if simplifying the memory stage logic could reduce area pressure. The challenge is finding improvements that don't trigger the known regressions—particularly avoiding pipeline depth changes that break the test suite or architectural modifications that conflict with formal verification.\n\nGiven that r3s0 succeeded with DSP consolidation and r7s1 failed trying to sequentialize MUL, I'm wondering if there's a way to leverage the DSP block's internal pipelining more effectively. The core insight is that the 33×33 multiplier already maps into the GW2A DSP18, and Yosys can infer its internal pipeline register when the surrounding logic allows it. The question is whether we can schedule MUL operations differently to take advantage of that without forcing a 2-cycle issue slot that breaks other patterns. Moving immediate generation out of the ID stage into IF might free up combinational slack in decode, though immediate generation is already quite fast. I need to think about what structural changes haven't been attempted yet that could actually improve fitness without hitting the known failure modes.\n\nLooking at the memory pipeline, I'm considering whether we can pre-compute load extraction combinationally from the EX stage using the byte offset and raw DMEM data, pushing that work earlier so the MEM stage doesn't become a bottleneck. Another angle is whether we can promote the mem-to-reg mux into the MEM stage itself, though WB is already a trivial pass-through so that might not help. Eliminating the EX/MEM register for non-memory operations would save a cycle but would break the pipeline depth contract. On the instruction fetch side, the BRAM already delivers instructions combinationally after address, so speculative prefetch of instr+4 wouldn't gain much since memory is already fast.\n\nThe real opportunity might be in the forwarding mux chain—currently we have three levels of muxing (the 2:1 WB mux feeding into the 3:1 forwarding mux) that sit in the EX critical path. I'm wondering if we can restructure this by pre-computing the forwarded value from each stage separately, then selecting between them, which could reduce the mux depth.\n\nLooking at the actual EX critical path more carefully: the rs1 value flows through the forwarding mux into the ALU, then through a 4:1 mux for jump/ALU result selection before hitting the EX/MEM register. That final mux is gated by is_jump which we know early, so pre-computing pc+4 in IF and threading it through would work but adds pipeline payload.\n\nFor structural improvements, I keep coming back to the IF-stage mux width being the bottleneck in the RAS failures. What if instead of adding to that mux, we predict the JALR target at the EX stage and use the existing redirect path?\n\nActually, a cleaner structural win might be moving the immediate generation into the IF stage and bundling it with the if_id_t register. Since if_id_t is already combinational, adding the immediate field doesn't cost an extra flop—it just shifts work from ID's critical path into IF's, which has more slack. The decoder could move there too, though that's riskier for the test probes.\n\nLet me explore other angles: collapsing the hazard and forward units into their respective stages as local logic, or eliminating redundant fields like rs1_val and rs2_val from ex_mem_t since they're only needed for RVFI and could be tapped directly from earlier pipeline stages.\n\nAnother option is separating the ALU's logic operations from the ADD/SUB carry chain so they don't serialize together. I could also try reducing EX/MEM register width by conditionally encoding pc_next with branch or jump targets.\n\nThe more interesting idea is instruction fusion—detecting LUI+ADDI or AUIPC+ADDI patterns and merging them into single operations, which would save cycles on common pseudo-instructions like `li` and `la`. This would need either dual-read BRAM with lookahead or a small fetch buffer, and the ID stage would have to suppress the next fetch by emitting a NOP.\n\nLooking at the forwarding path more carefully: the WB stage's data mux between memory read data and ALU result is already small and combinational, and the EX stage's 3:1 forwarding mux picks from the original register value or one of two forwarded sources. The real question is whether pre-computing the forwarding selection earlier would actually save a meaningful mux level, but both inputs to that mux are already registered, so the combinational path is already quite short.\n\nI'm reconsidering the prefetch queue approach instead. With random 22% instruction memory stalls, roughly one in five cycles the fetch stalls, which currently causes the IF/ID stage to emit NOPs that bubble through the pipeline. A small 2-entry prefetch queue could let the backend continue consuming instructions during those stall cycles, potentially recovering a significant portion of those stall-induced bubbles. The queue would naturally fill when the backend stalls and drain when it runs fast, so the control logic is straightforward.\n\nBut actually, this gets complicated quickly—it changes fetch semantics and requires reworking the hazard detection unit. A simpler alternative would be a single-entry instruction buffer to hold the last-fetched instruction through an imem stall, though I need to think through whether that actually helps or just repeats instructions incorrectly. The real win might be moving the forwarding muxes from the EX stage into the ID stage as a combinational path, shifting work from a saturated EX to a potentially slack ID stage—but the forwarding logic depends on values that don't exist until EX completes, so that won't work either.\n\nLet me focus on something concrete: merge the writeback stage's 2:1 mux into the MEM/WB register by storing the final `wb_data` directly instead of keeping separate `read_data` and `alu_result` fields. This shortens the forwarding path from two muxes down to just the EX-stage 3:1 mux, potentially saving a LUT4 level or two. The RVFI interface still works because `wb_w_data` just becomes the pre-muxed value from the MEM/WB register, and I'd still compute `load_data` in the mem stage for RVFI's mem_rdata field—the writeback stage becomes a trivial pass-through.\n\nThe key insight is that moving the mux before the flop rather than after it removes the mux from the critical path between the flop output and the ALU input. Right now the path is flop-q → wb_stage mux → forward mux → ALU, but if I pre-mux in mem_stage, it becomes flop-q → forward mux → ALU, cutting out one combinational layer in the forwarding fan-in.\n\nI'm checking that this doesn't break anything: RVFI still sees the correct write data through mem_wb.wb_data, the memory read data tap is separate, and the wb_stage just becomes a pass-through. This looks like a clean win for Fmax without any functional issues.\n\nWait, I need to be careful here—this is exactly what r2s0 warned about. That lesson said renaming or removing mem_wb_t fields fails the register check unless the RVFI taps are rewired in sync. But it also said it *can* work if done carefully. Let me verify the RVFI taps are correctly updated: io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 should point to mem_wb.wb_data instead, and I need to check the memory read data tap as well.\n\nThe key insight is that I'm consolidating the write-back mux (mem_to_reg ? read_data : alu_result) into the mem_stage, so wb_data becomes the unified result there. The RVFI field for rd_wdata stays correct since it's just reading this consolidated value. And alu_result is already available in mem_stage through ex_mem, so the forwarding path has what it needs.\n\nBut I'm wondering if this actually saves anything—Yosys might already flatten the mux across module boundaries, making this optimization neutral in terms of LUT depth.\n\nNow I'm considering moving the divider completion mux (is_div && done ? div_result : alu_result) from ex_stage to mem_stage instead. That would shift timing pressure away from EX, though it means div_result needs to be registered through ex_mem, adding 32 bits of pipeline width.\n\nLooking at the bigger picture though, the wins from r8s0 and r5s1 came from targeted, clean changes—algebraic simplification and divider extraction. I should focus on something similarly focused rather than broad restructuring. The multiplier is already fairly clean with its 66-bit combinational path and the signed/unsigned extension logic. And the parallel-arm approach with DSP pipeline registers already failed in r7s1.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether collapsing the write-back stage into MEM would help—that would make it effectively 4-stage for RVFI retirement. But r4s1 showed that pipeline-depth changes break test_pipeline.py, so that's risky.\n\nLet me commit to the wb_data consolidation idea instead. It's minimal, safe, and has a clear timing argument. But before I do, I want to understand what's actually bottlenecking the design. Since r5s1 and r7s1 showed the EX/MEM register clk-to-q isn't the constraint, the bottleneck is likely either the IF stage (given r8s2's complaints about next_pc mux width) or the EX ALU with forwarding logic. Let me examine the EX forwarding muxes more carefully.\n\nExamining the forwarding logic...\n\nThe critical path through EX is roughly: 3:1 forwarding mux → 2:1 ALU input mux → 32-bit adder → 2:1 result mux → 2:1 jump mux before the register, totaling around 13 LUT4 levels. At 177 MHz on GW2A that's about 5.5ns, which is likely the critical path. The 32-bit adder dominates, but I could shave cycles by predicting the forward decision and computing two ALU copies in parallel.\n\nAlternatively, I could add a 1-entry skid buffer between IF and ID to capture in-flight instructions during pipeline stalls and recover 5-10% IPC, but that adds mux complexity at IF which is already tight. A cleaner approach is consolidating the write-back mux into the MEM stage to narrow the forwarding path—replacing separate `read_data` and `alu_result` fields in the mem_wb struct with a single combined field.\n\nThis saves 32 flops and shortens the forwarding chain by removing the WB-stage mux from the critical path, though I need to be careful re-pointing the RVFI tap and ensuring any tests probing the old fields still work. The mux at RVFI level (rd_wen ? wb_data : 0) handles the non-write case correctly. Let me commit to this and write out the YAML changes.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deba91282001GnrLWlsdncK6QW","sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","messageID":"msg_deba745ea0014ettneYh3nJvj6"}}
