{"type":"text","timestamp":1777775263087,"sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","part":{"id":"prt_deba9aa78001mt1Sfto9d9uHqn","messageID":"msg_deba99a57001Vw32kMZlKJO8b4","sessionID":"ses_21458ba5effe0yEUCNCzEXJw7H","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260502-002-r9s1` — a structural refactor that collapses the wb_stage 2:1 write-back mux into `mem_stage` (pre-flop) rather than `wb_stage` (post-flop). Key points:\n\n- **Target**: the MEM/WB → EX forwarding leg currently traverses `flop-q → wb_stage 2:1 mux → fwd 3:1 mux → ALU input`. Moving the 2:1 mux pre-flop shaves one LUT4 level from a hot post-flop path, analogous to r8s0's algebraic-simplification win.\n- **Payload shrink**: mem_wb_t loses 32 bits (read_data + alu_result → single wb_data).\n- **r2s0 mitigation applied**: RVFI `rd_wdata` tap re-pointed to `mem_wb_w.wb_data` in lockstep; `mem_rdata` (raw dmem word) kept as a separate field so ALIGNED_MEM provenance is preserved.\n- **Avoids the traps from recent lessons**: no pipeline-depth change (r4s1-safe), no IF-stage mux widening (r5s2/r8s2-safe), no manual cross-expression CSE (r6s0/r7s0-safe), no payload threading through multiple registers (r5s2-safe).\n- **Expected impact**: +3% with medium confidence — modest Fmax lift from shortening a post-flop path by one LUT4 level, plus FF/LUT4 savings from the narrower mem_wb_t.","time":{"start":1777775258232,"end":1777775263084}}}
