{"type":"text","timestamp":1777776164808,"sessionID":"ses_2144c4d42ffeA7pwQt7LytZFCk","part":{"id":"prt_debb76d9c001NefG2k6hsPmSY2","messageID":"msg_debb76636001U2Yyng5x5yXyK0","sessionID":"ses_2144c4d42ffeA7pwQt7LytZFCk","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis `hyp-20260502-003-r10s2` — a formal-gated BTFN conditional branch predictor that sidesteps the three known predictor traps:\n\n1. **Formal symbolic-fetch coupling (r3s1/r3s2)**: BTFN logic wrapped in `!RISCV_FORMAL` ifdef so formal sees the unchanged r2s2 JAL-only predictor.\n2. **IF mux widening (r8s2)**: Overloads the existing `is_predicted` leg; next_pc stays 3-way.\n3. **Fresh B-imm adder (r4s2)**: Pre-adder 20-bit immediate mux shares the JAL pc+imm adder between J-imm and B-imm — only ~1 LUT4 level added before the existing adder.\n\nMispredict recovery at EX reconstructs `pred_taken_btfn` directly from `in.instr[31]` & `!in.instr[8]` — no id_ex_t widening (avoids r5s2/r6s2/r7s2 payload cost). Redirect narrowing to mispredicts only; new fallthrough leg reuses `in.pc + 4` already computed for misalign-fault.\n\nConfidence set to **low** because r4s2/r3s2 were repeated warnings this neighborhood is hostile; the novel angle is the formal-ifdef + shared-adder combination rather than the BTFN idea itself. Expected +4% IPC on CoreMark hot loops if Fmax holds.","time":{"start":1777776160156,"end":1777776164806}}}
