{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763508900,"sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01VHJTKQAK54DYRTdvxFFn8w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n\n\n(End of file - total 0 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/CORE_PHILOSOPHY.md","time":{"start":1777763508882,"end":1777763508898}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at this fresh tournament setup, I need to understand the pipeline architecture and how it handles branches. The processor uses a 5-stage in-order pipeline with branches resolved in the execute stage, which means a taken branch flushes both the fetch and decode stages and incurs a 2-cycle penalty. Since CoreMark is loop-heavy, branch prediction will be critical to performance.\n\nA BTB with static prediction for backward branches could eliminate most of that penalty. I could implement a small direct-mapped cache indexed by program counter that stores whether a branch was previously taken, allowing the fetch stage to predict loop branches without waiting for execution. Even a simple heuristic—predicting backward branches as taken based on the immediate sign during decode—would significantly reduce stalls on loop iterations.\n\nLet me calculate the impact: at roughly 450K cycles per iteration with about 15% of instructions being branches and 60% of those taken, that's around 40K taken branches per iteration, costing about 80K cycles in penalties—roughly 18% of total execution time. A working BTB predictor that correctly predicts taken branches would recover most of those 2-cycle penalties, potentially improving performance by 15-20%.\n\nThe challenge is fitting this into the fetch stage without hurting clock frequency. A 32-entry direct-mapped BTB indexed by low PC bits, storing the target address and a taken bit, could work if implemented as a small BRAM or LUT-based structure. On a BTB hit with the taken bit set, the fetch stage redirects to the target; on misprediction in execution, we flush and update the entry. This approach handles JAL correctly after the first execution and significantly reduces penalties on loops, though JALR remains problematic since the target depends on register values.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deaf662700015ZjSkjqzjhHaqc","sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","messageID":"msg_deaf61e80001bF86Iuy1g4FZ3B"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1777763508937,"sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","part":{"id":"prt_deaf662a4001EOQPFb212OHjQ4","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"97242038ebafea4a2baaaab32280042d085440b4","messageID":"msg_deaf61e80001bF86Iuy1g4FZ3B","sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":59132,"input":1,"output":861,"reasoning":464,"cache":{"write":404,"read":57402}},"cost":0.064356}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777763510692,"sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","part":{"id":"prt_deaf669a20013V6phdQo2V5dIj","messageID":"msg_deaf662df001pRunuL1iQ66AZC","sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","snapshot":"97242038ebafea4a2baaaab32280042d085440b4","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777763537298,"sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01X4z64pAYoMz42zSrNmq4bi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\ntitle: \"BTB with 1-bit hysteresis for taken branches and unconditional jumps\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX,\n  producing a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch and every\n  JAL/JALR (IF/ID is flushed to NOP and ID/EX is flushed to a bubble\n  before the redirected instruction reaches IF). CoreMark is dominated\n  by tight loops (core_list_find, crcu8/crcu16, core_bench_matrix inner\n  loops) — 10-20% of dynamic instructions are control-flow, and the\n  vast majority of those are backward loop-closing branches that are\n  almost always taken. Assuming ~15% branches+jumps at ~60% taken rate\n  and 2 cycles of penalty each, the lost IPC is on the order of 18%\n  of total CoreMark cycles. Removing even 70% of those bubbles is the\n  single biggest IPC lever this core has short of going superscalar,\n  and it does not touch the RVFI contract, the memory interface, or\n  the ALU path. No prior iteration has attempted this — the baseline\n  core has zero prediction, PC always fetches pc+4 until EX redirects.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a small direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer (BTB) in the IF stage\n  with 32 entries indexed by PC[6:2] (5 bits). Each entry holds\n  {valid, tag[24:0], target[31:1], taken_bit}. The taken_bit is a\n  1-bit hysteresis state (updated on every resolved branch/jump in\n  EX) — simpler than 2-bit counters but still captures loop\n  branches, which are what dominate CoreMark.\n\n  Fetch-side: in IF, combinationally look up BTB[PC[6:2]]. If\n  valid & tag-match & taken_bit, predict taken — the next PC is the\n  stored target instead of pc+4, and the IF/ID bundle carries a\n  \"predicted\" flag (packed into an unused bit of if_id_t or a new\n  field) so EX knows this instruction was speculatively redirected.\n\n  EX-side: when a branch or jump is resolved, compare the actual\n  outcome (taken & target) against the prediction carried with the\n  instruction:\n    - correctly-predicted taken branch / jump with matching target:\n      no redirect, no flush, 0-cycle penalty.\n    - mispredict (wrongly predicted taken, wrongly predicted\n      not-taken, or correct direction but wrong target for JALR):\n      redirect + flush as today, 2-cycle penalty.\n  Update the BTB entry in the same cycle with the resolved outcome\n  (write port driven from EX). JAL writes its immediate target.\n  JALR updates the stored target each time it resolves (single-target\n  approximation — good enough for monomorphic call/return sites\n  common in CoreMark's non-recursive call graph; polymorphic sites\n  fall back to the existing mispredict path at baseline cost).\n\n  Misalignment and illegal-instruction discipline are unaffected:\n  predictions only redirect PC; the instruction itself still decodes\n  and traps/retires exactly as before, because EX is the authoritative\n  resolver. RVFI fields remain driven by the MEM/WB retirement\n  register, unchanged.\n\n  Sizing rationale: 32 entries × (1+25+31+1) = ~58 bits per entry\n  = ~1860 bits. This fits comfortably in distributed LUT-RAM on the\n  Tang Nano 20K (no BRAM pressure), and the lookup is a single\n  LUT-indexed read with a small equality comparator — the critical\n  path stays under the existing IF-to-ID slack window. If the BTB\n  lookup+mux pushes Fmax down, the fallback is to pipeline the BTB\n  read one cycle (predict the taken target on the cycle AFTER the\n  branch is fetched, losing 1 cycle of the 2-cycle gain — still a\n  net win). The cocotb pipeline test and the existing riscv-formal\n  wrapper will catch any RVFI or liveness regression; the VexRiscv\n  cosim with ~22% random istall/dstall will catch any interaction\n  with the existing hazard/redirect priority logic.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 12\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/btb.sv\n    description: \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with {valid, tag, target, taken} per entry. Combinational read port for IF; synchronous write port for EX updates.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `predicted` (and optionally `pred_target`) field to if_id_t and propagate through id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can compare prediction vs. resolved outcome.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Instantiate the BTB. On BTB hit with taken_bit set, override next_pc with the BTB target (still subordinate to EX redirect priority). Emit `predicted` and `pred_target` on the IF/ID bundle.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Plumb `predicted` / `pred_target` from IF/ID through into the ID/EX register (no decode changes — purely pass-through metadata).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compare resolved (taken, target) against the incoming prediction. Suppress the redirect+flush when the prediction matches; issue redirect+flush on mispredict. Drive BTB update port with resolved outcome on every branch/jump.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"On correctly-predicted taken branch/jump, do not assert flush_if/flush_id — the IF stream already followed the predicted path. Mispredicts retain the current flush behavior.\"\n  - file: test/test_btb.py\n    description: \"New cocotb suite: unit tests for BTB lookup, update, tag mismatch, aliasing collisions, and a mini-loop trace asserting zero mispredicts after warmup on a 16-iteration backward-branch loop.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Augment with a fetch-redirect-during-prediction scenario: interleave a branch that aliases another in BTB, confirm rvfi_order stays monotonic and pc_wdata is correct on both mispredict and correct-predict cycles.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r1s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777763537281,"end":1777763537295}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deaf669a5001M1wXQP6NF2C2Nv","sessionID":"ses_21509ff27ffednDs1q55nk3GD7","messageID":"msg_deaf662df001pRunuL1iQ66AZC"}}
