{"type":"text","timestamp":1777766424321,"sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","part":{"id":"prt_deb22dd38001BwpnNlPMJF04xq","messageID":"msg_deb21de120019OtqRq6TA1difw","sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","type":"text","text":"Reading the lessons and recent outcomes to pick a predictor angle that won't repeat the BTB formal-blowup failure.","time":{"start":1777766423864,"end":1777766424320}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766424360,"sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01NECPmjHAMXQyGG2DbPAvSh","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/ 2>/dev/null; ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null","description":"List experiments directory"},"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","metadata":{"output":"hypotheses\nlog.jsonl\nprogress.png\n","exit":0,"description":"List experiments directory","truncated":false},"title":"List experiments directory","time":{"start":1777766424351,"end":1777766424358}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what went wrong with the previous predictor hypothesis—the formal verification hit a wall when adding prediction fields to the pipeline payload expanded the state space beyond what the solver could handle in the time budget.\n\nThe key insight is that predictor state needs to stay separate from the RVFI-observed pipeline structures, so I'm considering a design where the BTB operates as an independent module that only influences PC generation in the IF stage, while the pipeline continues using the existing redirect mechanism to handle mispredictions. The challenge is figuring out how to detect when a prediction was wrong without threading that information through the pipeline—I'm leaning toward a next-line predictor indexed by PC that compares predicted versus resolved addresses when the branch commits.\n\nRather than adding complex shadow state that still affects formal verification, I'm exploring whether a simpler static prediction scheme would work better—specifically predicting backward branches as taken and forward branches as not-taken, or even just handling unconditional JALs directly in IF by computing their targets from the instruction bits without any prediction state at all.\n\nFor JAL instructions specifically, the IF stage could decode the opcode and immediate combinationally to compute the target in the same cycle, eliminating the 2-cycle bubble entirely. The challenge is that the EX stage will still generate a redirect when it processes the JAL, so I need to either suppress that redundant redirect when it matches the predicted path, or handle the entire JAL in IF and prevent the EX redirect from flushing the already-correct path.\n\nThe core issue is that adding prediction tracking fields to the pipeline payload blows the formal verification budget, but I might be able to avoid new fields by having IF unconditionally predict JAL and letting EX verify the target matches—though this still requires some way to suppress the flush when prediction is correct.\n\nActually, if IF reliably detects JAL and predicts it, then by the time the instruction reaches EX, I know the prediction was correct (since any flush would have replaced it with a NOP). So I can suppress EX's redirect for JAL entirely by checking whether the instruction that reached EX was actually predicted by IF—which I can infer from whether it's a real JAL instruction versus a NOP that got flushed.\n\nThe key insight is that IF's JAL prediction is combinational and always correct: it sees the opcode, computes the target, and updates the PC. The only way this breaks is if a flush happens, but then the JAL gets replaced with a NOP anyway. So in EX, I can simply skip the redirect for JAL instructions, trusting that IF already handled it correctly.\n\nLet me verify this by checking the IF stage logic...\n\nExamining the IF stage code...\n\nSo when redirect fires, the PC jumps to redirect_target and a NOP is emitted downstream—no JAL propagates. In the normal case with no redirect, the JAL flows through to EX, and if EX fires its own redirect to the same target, it wastes cycles. The solution is to suppress EX's redirect for predicted JALs, either by adding a `predicted` bit to the pipeline or by having EX infer it from the instruction bits.\n\nLooking at the logic: EX can check `is_jump && !is_jalr` to identify JAL instructions. Since a JAL only reaches EX when IF successfully predicted it (any flush or stall would emit a NOP instead), EX can safely skip its redirect for JALs and only redirect on branches and JARLs.\n\nThis optimization eliminates 2 bubble cycles per JAL with minimal risk. CoreMark has frequent function calls, so I'm estimating roughly 2-4% overall IPC improvement. The main concern is timing—adding JAL detection and immediate extraction in IF creates combinational overhead, but merging the PC+4 and PC+JAL_imm adders into a single adder with a mux on the addend should keep it manageable. Current Fmax is 135 MHz with the critical path likely through the ALU, so this shouldn't become the bottleneck.\n\nFor the implementation, I'm suppressing the redirect signal for predicted JALs by changing the condition to only trigger on JALR and branches, not JAL. The RVFI pc_next field stays correct since it still captures the jump target. The redirect_target mux then only needs to choose between JALR and branch targets, which is cleaner. No pipeline structure changes or new state needed.\n\nOn misalignment: JAL targets are always aligned when the PC is aligned (since the immediate has bit 0 forced to 0 and RV32 keeps PC 4-byte aligned), so JAL won't trigger a misalignment trap. JALR can still be misaligned and uses the existing redirect path, so trap handling stays the same. I need to add JAL detection in the IF stage by checking the opcode bits and extracting the immediate the same way imm_gen does, then use that to compute the target for prediction.\n\nI'm going to skip branch prediction for now since it adds state and mispredict recovery complexity that could blow up the formal verification. Sticking with static JAL prediction only—it's safe, simple, and doesn't require any state tracking.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb22dd49001q58ZtdEbe045uj","sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","messageID":"msg_deb21de120019OtqRq6TA1difw"}}
