{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777766465301,"sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01GD5kp31JDrc6mcJpQziwKq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r2s2\ntitle: \"Stateless IF-stage static JAL-taken prediction (zero bubble on unconditional jumps)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The 5-stage baseline pays a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken\n  branch AND every unconditional jump. For JAL (opcode 0x6F) this\n  penalty is pure waste: JAL is unconditionally taken, and its target\n  is PC + a sign-extended immediate extracted directly from the\n  instruction word — IF can compute it as soon as imem_data arrives,\n  with no prior history. CoreMark is heavy on function calls (the\n  inner crcu8/crcu16/list_find loops all make indirect calls; the\n  harness is littered with JAL prologue/epilogue pairs), so even a\n  modest share of control-flow instructions being JAL (empirically\n  ~30–40% of taken branches in RV32 compiled code) translates to\n  ~1–3% of total CoreMark cycles wasted as JAL redirect bubbles.\n\n  Prior iter (hyp-20260502-003-r1s2) tried a full BTB and blew the\n  1800s formal budget because it threaded a `predicted` flag and\n  `pred_target` through if_id_t / id_ex_t, expanding the per-insn\n  state space seen by SBY. The lesson is: keep prediction OUT of the\n  RVFI-observed pipeline payload. A static JAL predictor needs no\n  state at all — the \"prediction\" is always correct by construction,\n  so no comparison or recovery logic is required downstream.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add combinational JAL-target computation inside if_stage.sv and use\n  it to redirect the PC register in the SAME cycle the JAL is fetched,\n  eliminating the normal 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble for every JAL.\n\n  Implementation details:\n\n    1. if_stage.sv decodes the currently-fetched imem_data for JAL\n       (opcode == 7'b1101111) combinationally. If JAL AND the fetch\n       is valid (no flush, no imem stall, no EX redirect this cycle),\n       compute jal_imm the same way imm_gen does:\n         jal_imm = {{11{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[19:12],\n                    instr[20], instr[30:21], 1'b0}\n       and set next_pc = pc + jal_imm instead of pc + 4. EX redirect\n       still has top priority over the JAL prediction (so a redirect\n       in flight this cycle correctly wins). The JAL instruction\n       itself is still emitted to ID normally so it decodes, writes\n       PC+4 to rd in EX, and retires via the usual RVFI path.\n\n    2. ex_stage.sv: narrow the redirect condition to exclude JAL.\n       Currently redirect fires on (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jump)\n       — change to (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jalr). JALR and taken\n       branches still redirect as today. JAL never does, because IF\n       has already fetched from the correct target. The misalignment\n       trap path stays unchanged (JAL immediates have bit0 forced to\n       0, and PC is 4-aligned, so JAL-misalign is impossible without\n       C-ext; the existing misalign check remains but is dead code\n       for JAL specifically).\n\n    3. reg_q.pc_next in EX is UNCHANGED — it still records the\n       jump_target for RVFI's pc_wdata. RVFI correctness is identical\n       to the baseline; only the externally-visible redirect signal\n       is suppressed.\n\n    4. No changes to if_id_t / id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t. No new\n       pipeline payload bits. No BTB, no counters, no tables. The\n       formal state space is unchanged — the IF combinational logic\n       just has one extra mux on next_pc, and EX has a narrower OR\n       condition on redirect. SBY should proof this as fast as the\n       baseline.\n\n  Why this is always safe without a prediction-correctness check:\n  a JAL can only reach EX when (a) it was fetched with flush=0 and\n  redirect=0, and (b) imem delivered the real instruction (not a\n  NOP). In both cases the IF-stage JAL predictor saw the same\n  opcode and computed the same target, so the EX-stage jump_target\n  provably matches the target IF already redirected to. When\n  flush=1 or redirect=1 at IF, the emitted instr is NOP (0x00000013),\n  so ctrl.is_jump is 0 when it reaches EX — nothing to redirect.\n  When imem_ready=0, flush_if is asserted upstream (via\n  hazard_unit), same story. So no \"was this predicted?\" bit is\n  ever needed.\n\n  Expected delta: saves exactly 2 cycles per dynamically-executed\n  JAL. Estimated JAL density in CoreMark ~2–4% of all retired\n  instructions; over 449k cycles this is ~2–4% IPC lift. Fmax\n  impact should be near-zero — the added IF path is a 32-bit adder\n  with a constant-pattern opcode compare in parallel with the\n  existing pc+4 adder, slotted into the same IF combinational\n  cone. Net fitness: +2 to +4%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add combinational JAL-target predictor: decode imem_data[6:0]==0x6F, extract JAL immediate, mux next_pc to pc+jal_imm when JAL is fetched (gated by !redirect and !flush, with EX redirect keeping top priority). No state, no new register.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Narrow redirect to (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jalr) && !misalign_fault — JAL no longer fires redirect because IF already handled it correctly. reg_q.pc_next still records jump_target for RVFI pc_wdata. jump_target/branch_target calculation unchanged.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add regressions: (1) a JAL at arbitrary PC with arbitrary sign-extended immediate retires with correct pc_wdata on channel 0 and the instruction fetched on the cycle after JAL is the one at the JAL target (not pc+4); (2) a JAL immediately after a taken branch still picks up the redirect target first, then the predicted JAL target on the next cycle; (3) JAL with imem_ready=0 in its fetch cycle correctly stalls PC and does NOT predict (NOP is emitted); (4) back-to-back JAL chain retires every cycle (no bubbles between JALs).\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r2s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777766465287,"end":1777766465299}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" So the previous approach failed because it tried to add new fields to the pipeline structs, which broke the formal verification. The key insight is to keep JAL prediction stateless and invisible to the formal model. My new approach is to handle JAL prediction combinationally in the IF stage—since the target is always computable directly from the instruction bits, I can detect JAL and redirect next_pc without adding any pipeline state or new fields.\n\nThen in the EX stage, I'll suppress the redundant jump redirect that would normally fire, since IF already handled it correctly. This keeps the state space unchanged for formal verification, adds no new pipeline payload fields, and just modifies the combinational logic in IF plus narrows the redirect condition in EX. The benefit is eliminating 2 bubbles per JAL, which matters for CoreMark since it has many function calls.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb230c8c001oJ52SRc75ibUnC","sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","messageID":"msg_deb22e9be001yzv37nrt4Pl42U"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777766465329,"sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","part":{"id":"prt_deb2307850019KwIcRG4y20msM","messageID":"msg_deb22e9be001yzv37nrt4Pl42U","sessionID":"ses_214de2280ffeyGR42V0T2BpcXU","type":"text","text":"I see a clear pattern: the BTB attempt broke formal by threading prediction metadata through `if_id_t` / `id_ex_t`. The lesson says keep prediction OUT of the RVFI-observed pipeline payload. The two M-extension attempts also yielded no improvement.\n\nMy angle: **static JAL-taken prediction in IF, stateless**. JAL is unconditional with a PC-relative immediate — IF can compute the target directly from the instruction bits and redirect next PC in the same cycle. Zero prediction state, zero new pipeline fields, always correct. EX suppresses its (now-redundant) redirect for JAL. This saves the 2-cycle redirect bubble on every JAL (function call prologues/epilogues, unconditional branches) without adding any formal state.","time":{"start":1777766434693,"end":1777766465328}}}
