{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777768186455,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"id":"prt_deb3dc254001GIGPj4fwLo1lAk","messageID":"msg_deb3db191001s74RIeMgj7dhdk","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","snapshot":"a3755d23ffda8fb42eea40904ecfe341789c0175","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768261045,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_016t9d9xE89ARdWrHSTWJtzn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check existing hypothesis files"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777768261004,"end":1777768261041}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Building on the stateless JAL predictor's success, I'm considering what predictor improvements could work next while respecting the constraints—specifically avoiding prediction state in the RVFI payload and preserving redirect semantics. The key is staying stateless and provably correct.\n\nLooking at what's left to predict: backward branches dominate loop iterations and are taken most of the time, but they require comparing register values to determine direction, which isn't feasible in the IF stage without adding recovery complexity. JALR prediction via a return address stack would help, but again requires mispredict recovery logic that bloats the formal model. Even a minimal RAS approach for x1-based returns runs into the same recovery problem—every speculative prediction needs a way to unwind when it's wrong, and that's where the formal verification starts to break down.\n\nThe real tension is that IF-stage prediction needs to redirect the PC early, but then EX has to validate it, and coordinating between them without embedding prediction state in the pipeline payload is tricky. If IF predicts a backward branch taken and redirects to the target, EX later sees the actual outcome—but if they match, does EX redirect anyway and create a spurious bubble? If EX doesn't redirect, how does IF know not to have already redirected? This circles back to needing some flag in the pipeline, which is exactly what caused the formal blowup before.\n\nThe cleanest remaining option is a purely static BTFN predictor at IF that detects backward branches by checking the sign bit of the immediate, redirects speculatively on backward branches, and lets EX's existing redirect logic handle mismatches—accepting that correct predictions still incur one bubble from the EX redirect, but at least avoiding the formal complexity of tracking prediction state through the pipeline.\n\nAlternatively, I could implement a small Return Address Stack as a side structure outside the pipeline: JAL with x1 pushes the return address at EX, and JALR with rs1=x1 and rd=x0 pops and predicts at IF, giving function return prediction without needing to thread predicted bits through the datapath.\n\nThe tricky part is handling mispredicts—if IF speculates with a wrong RAS pop, the stack gets corrupted. I could either track per-instruction state (which bloats the pipeline) or accept occasional RAS corruption and recover via a saved pointer, though that adds complexity. A simpler approach might be a 1-entry RAS that just remembers the last JAL-x1 return address, treating JALR-x1 as a return to that single saved PC. It's not perfect but avoids the recovery headache for most predictable code paths.\n\nBut the real constraint I'm hitting is that adding any new fields to the pipeline payload—like a predicted_target bit—blows up the formal verification state space past the time budget. So any predictor has to live in shadow state outside the main pipeline, gated only during formal checks. For a static backward-branch predictor, I can decode the B-immediate in IF and predict taken if the sign bit is set, then redirect speculatively. The problem is distinguishing in EX whether IF actually predicted taken or just fell through, since I can't add a predicted bit to the pipeline. There might be a trick using the PC of the instruction already in EX to infer what IF did, but I need to think through that more carefully. I'm considering whether to gate the predicted bit under `RISCV_FORMAL` to keep it out of the formal verification payload, which aligns with the lesson about tracking prediction state separately from the RVFI-observed pipeline. The alternative would be a shadow register indexed by instruction order, but gating under the formal flag is simpler and matches the recommended approach directly.\n\nMy concrete plan is to implement a static BTFN predictor that decodes branch opcodes in IF, predicts taken branches based on the sign bit of the immediate, and redirects the PC accordingly. I'll add the `predicted_taken` bit to the pipeline stages but gate it so formal verification doesn't see it, allowing EX to suppress redundant redirects on correct predictions while formal still validates the core redirect logic as it exists today.\n\nOn misprediction, EX fires its redirect normally. But I'm realizing this approach disables the predictor under formal verification, which defeats the purpose of proving it correct. The real issue is that the predictor state needs to cross the IF/EX boundary through the pipeline registers, which RVFI observes.\n\nLet me try a different angle: instead of storing the prediction in the pipeline, I'll have EX reconstruct what IF would have predicted by examining the branch instruction itself, then compare that reconstructed prediction against the actual branch outcome to determine if a redirect is needed.\n\nSo IF decodes the branch and predicts based on the immediate (backward branches taken, forward not taken), then EX receives the same instruction and recomputes that prediction from scratch. EX can then suppress the redirect when the prediction matches reality, and only fire it on misprediction or JALR. The XOR logic handles all four cases correctly: matching predictions produce no redirect, mismatches trigger redirects to the correct target.\n\nFor misaligned targets, IF's predictor just needs to gate on aligned addresses, same as the JAL predictor. This is stateless and provably correct since the reconstruction at EX is exact.\n\nNow I'm working through the implementation details. IF needs to decode the B-immediate and predict taken only when the opcode is a branch, the immediate's sign bit is 1, and the target is aligned. The priority in next_pc becomes: external redirect > JAL > branch prediction > pc+4. At EX, I reconstruct whether IF predicted taken by checking the same conditions—branch opcode, immediate sign bit, and target alignment—using the branch's PC and immediate that are already available. The tricky part is ensuring EX's guard conditions match IF's exactly, accounting for the fact that IF might have been flushed or redirected in the cycle the branch was there, but those external signals don't affect whether the branch instruction itself would have predicted. Refining the redirect logic for branches — I need to verify that IF's alignment guard prevents misaligned predictions, so if predicted_taken matches the actual branch outcome, no redirect is needed, but if they diverge, I redirect to the correct target.\n\nFor the case where prediction said taken but the branch isn't actually taken, I need to redirect back to pc+4 instead of always using branch_target. So the redirect target becomes conditional: jump_target for JALR, branch_target if the branch is taken, otherwise pc+4.\n\nThis feels like a solid approach. Now I'm writing up the YAML proposal with the file changes needed — IF stage gets the predictor, EX stage gets the narrowed redirect logic, and I'll add a test file to cover the branch prediction scenarios. I'm estimating this could yield around 5% improvement on CoreMark given the frequency of correctly-predicted backward branches.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3ee554001jOHTtbTfInFulT","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","messageID":"msg_deb3db191001s74RIeMgj7dhdk"}}
