{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768265666,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01XrcUZ6yLCh3mtH2Qc7NDqp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -i \"predictor\\|btb\\|branch.*predict\\|BTFN\\|backward\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl | head -20","description":"Find prior predictor attempts"},"output":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"BTB with 1-bit hysteresis for taken branches and unconditional jumps\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX,\\nproducing a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch and every\\nJAL/JALR (IF/ID is flushed to NOP and ID/EX is flushed to a bubble\\nbefore the redirected instruction reaches IF). CoreMark is dominated\\nby tight loops (core_list_find, crcu8/crcu16, core_bench_matrix inner\\nloops) \\u2014 10-20% of dynamic instructions are control-flow, and the\\nvast majority of those are backward loop-closing branches that are\\nalmost always taken. Assuming ~15% branches+jumps at ~60% taken rate\\nand 2 cycles of penalty each, the lost IPC is on the order of 18%\\nof total CoreMark cycles. Removing even 70% of those bubbles is the\\nsingle biggest IPC lever this core has short of going superscalar,\\nand it does not touch the RVFI contract, the memory interface, or\\nthe ALU path. No prior iteration has attempted this \\u2014 the baseline\\ncore has zero prediction, PC always fetches pc+4 until EX redirects.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 5-stage in-order pipeline resolves branches and jumps in EX,\\nproducing a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch and every\\nJAL/JALR (IF/ID is flushed to NOP and ID/EX is flushed to a bubble\\nbefore the redirected instruction reaches IF). CoreMark is dominated\\nby tight loops (core_list_find, crcu8/crcu16, core_bench_matrix inner\\nloops) \\u2014 10-20% of dynamic instructions are control-flow, and the\\nvast majority of those are backward loop-closing branches that are\\nalmost always taken. Assuming ~15% branches+jumps at ~60% taken rate\\nand 2 cycles of penalty each, the lost IPC is on the order of 18%\\nof total CoreMark cycles. Removing even 70% of those bubbles is the\\nsingle biggest IPC lever this core has short of going superscalar,\\nand it does not touch the RVFI contract, the memory interface, or\\nthe ALU path. No prior iteration has attempted this \\u2014 the baseline\\ncore has zero prediction, PC always fetches pc+4 until EX redirects.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped Branch Target Buffer (BTB) in the IF stage\\nwith 32 entries indexed by PC[6:2] (5 bits). Each entry holds\\n{valid, tag[24:0], target[31:1], taken_bit}. The taken_bit is a\\n1-bit hysteresis state (updated on every resolved branch/jump in\\nEX) \\u2014 simpler than 2-bit counters but still captures loop\\nbranches, which are what dominate CoreMark.\\n\\nFetch-side: in IF, combinationally look up BTB[PC[6:2]]. If\\nvalid & tag-match & taken_bit, predict taken \\u2014 the next PC is the\\nstored target instead of pc+4, and the IF/ID bundle carries a\\n\\\"predicted\\\" flag (packed into an unused bit of if_id_t or a new\\nfield) so EX knows this instruction was speculatively redirected.\\n\\nEX-side: when a branch or jump is resolved, compare the actual\\noutcome (taken & target) against the prediction carried with the\\ninstruction:\\n  - correctly-predicted taken branch / jump with matching target:\\n    no redirect, no flush, 0-cycle penalty.\\n  - mispredict (wrongly predicted taken, wrongly predicted\\n    not-taken, or correct direction but wrong target for JALR):\\n    redirect + flush as today, 2-cycle penalty.\\nUpdate the BTB entry in the same cycle with the resolved outcome\\n(write port driven from EX). JAL writes its immediate target.\\nJALR updates the stored target each time it resolves (single-target\\napproximation \\u2014 good enough for monomorphic call/return sites\\ncommon in CoreMark's non-recursive call graph; polymorphic sites\\nfall back to the existing mispredict path at baseline cost).\\n\\nMisalignment and illegal-instruction discipline are unaffected:\\npredictions only redirect PC; the instruction itself still decodes\\nand traps/retires exactly as before, because EX is the authoritative\\nresolver. RVFI fields remain driven by the MEM/WB retirement\\nregister, unchanged.\\n\\nSizing rationale: 32 entries \\u00d7 (1+25+31+1) = ~58 bits per entry\\n= ~1860 bits. This fits comfortably in distributed LUT-RAM on the\\nTang Nano 20K (no BRAM pressure), and the lookup is a single\\nLUT-indexed read with a small equality comparator \\u2014 the critical\\npath stays under the existing IF-to-ID slack window. If the BTB\\nlookup+mux pushes Fmax down, the fallback is to pipeline the BTB\\nread one cycle (predict the taken target on the cycle AFTER the\\nbranch is fetched, losing 1 cycle of the 2-cycle gain \\u2014 still a\\nnet win). The cocotb pipeline test and the existing riscv-formal\\nwrapper will catch any RVFI or liveness regression; the VexRiscv\\ncosim with ~22% random istall/dstall will catch any interaction\\nwith the existing hazard/redirect priority logic.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with {valid, tag, target, taken} per entry. Combinational read port for IF; synchronous write port for EX updates.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `predicted` (and optionally `pred_target`) field to if_id_t and propagate through id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can compare prediction vs. resolved outcome.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB. On BTB hit with taken_bit set, override next_pc with the BTB target (still subordinate to EX redirect priority). Emit `predicted` and `pred_target` on the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Plumb `predicted` / `pred_target` from IF/ID through into the ID/EX register (no decode changes \\u2014 purely pass-through metadata).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare resolved (taken, target) against the incoming prediction. Suppress the redirect+flush when the prediction matches; issue redirect+flush on mispredict. Drive BTB update port with resolved outcome on every branch/jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"On correctly-predicted taken branch/jump, do not assert flush_if/flush_id \\u2014 the IF stream already followed the predicted path. Mispredicts retain the current flush behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_btb.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: unit tests for BTB lookup, update, tag mismatch, aliasing collisions, and a mini-loop trace asserting zero mispredicts after warmup on a 16-iteration backward-branch loop.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Augment with a fetch-redirect-during-prediction scenario: interleave a branch that aliases another in BTB, confirm rvfi_order stays monotonic and pc_wdata is correct on both mispredict and correct-predict cycles.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 12, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/btb.sv\", \"description\": \"New module. 32-entry direct-mapped BTB with {valid, tag, target, taken} per entry. Combinational read port for IF; synchronous write port for EX updates.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add `predicted` (and optionally `pred_target`) field to if_id_t and propagate through id_ex_t / ex_mem_t so EX can compare prediction vs. resolved outcome.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Instantiate the BTB. On BTB hit with taken_bit set, override next_pc with the BTB target (still subordinate to EX redirect priority). Emit `predicted` and `pred_target` on the IF/ID bundle.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Plumb `predicted` / `pred_target` from IF/ID through into the ID/EX register (no decode changes \\u2014 purely pass-through metadata).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compare resolved (taken, target) against the incoming prediction. Suppress the redirect+flush when the prediction matches; issue redirect+flush on mispredict. Drive BTB update port with resolved outcome on every branch/jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"On correctly-predicted taken branch/jump, do not assert flush_if/flush_id \\u2014 the IF stream already followed the predicted path. Mispredicts retain the current flush behavior.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_btb.py\", \"description\": \"New cocotb suite: unit tests for BTB lookup, update, tag mismatch, aliasing collisions, and a mini-loop trace asserting zero mispredicts after warmup on a 16-iteration backward-branch loop.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Augment with a fetch-redirect-during-prediction scenario: interleave a branch that aliases another in BTB, confirm rvfi_order stays monotonic and pc_wdata is correct on both mispredict and correct-predict cycles.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: timeout\\nrun_all.sh exceeded 1800s wall-clock\\n--- partial output (tail) ---\\ne_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 16..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 14..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 17..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] prep: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] smt2: starting process \\\"cd insn_xori_ch0/model; yosys -ql design_smt2.log design_smt2.ys\\\"\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 18..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 15..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 16..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 19..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] smt2: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: starting process \\\"cd insn_xori_ch0; yosys-smtbmc -s bitwuzla --presat --unroll --noprogress -t 20:21  --append 0 --dump-vcd engine_0/trace.vcd --dump-yw engine_0/trace.yw --dump-vlogtb engine_0/trace_tb.v --dump-smtc engine_0/trace.smtc model/design_smt2.smt2\\\"\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 17..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assumptions in step 20..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 18..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 19..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assumptions in step 20..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Solver: bitwuzla\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Assumptions are unsatisfiable!\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: PREUNSAT\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 0..\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] engine_0: Status returned by engine: ERROR\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 20:30:07 [insn_xor_ch1] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 20:30:07 [\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 1, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r1s2 (broken, n/a): Adding a BTB with speculative IF-stage redirect and a new `predicted`/`pred_target` field threaded through if_id_t and id_ex_t expands the formal state space enough that per-instruction SBY checks blow past the 1800s wall-clock budget; predictor hypotheses should keep prediction state out of the RVFI-observed pipeline payload (e.g. track it in a side shadow indexed by rvfi_order or gate under `RISCV_FORMAL` to an empty struct) so formal proof time stays bounded.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Pre-register rd_wdata at MEM/WB boundary to shorten forward + regfile read paths\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\\nconsumers:\\n\\n  1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\\n     the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 fwd_rs?_sel mux \\u2192 is_auipc mux \\u2192\\n     ALU \\u2192 EX/MEM flop \\u2014 four mux levels before ALU input.\\n  2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\\n     ID-stage's regfile read path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 regfile bypass mux \\u2192 ID/EX flop\\n     \\u2014 two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\\n     rd matches.\\n\\nThat extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\\nplausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\\n1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\\ntransformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\\nconsumers:\\n\\n  1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\\n     the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 fwd_rs?_sel mux \\u2192 is_auipc mux \\u2192\\n     ALU \\u2192 EX/MEM flop \\u2014 four mux levels before ALU input.\\n  2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\\n     ID-stage's regfile read path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 regfile bypass mux \\u2192 ID/EX flop\\n     \\u2014 two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\\n     rd matches.\\n\\nThat extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\\nplausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\\n1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\\ntransformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Consolidate the WB-stage write-data mux into the MEM stage so the\\nselected rd_wdata is clocked into the MEM/WB register directly,\\nturning wb_stage into a trivial `w_data = in.rd_wdata` pass-through.\\n\\nConcretely:\\n - Extend `mem_wb_t` in core_pkg.sv with a new field\\n   `logic [31:0] rd_wdata;`  (can replace `read_data` since\\n   read_data is only consumed by wb_stage's mux anyway; keep\\n   read_data for the RVFI-accurate rmask path if needed).\\n - In mem_stage.sv, compute\\n   `rd_wdata = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? load_data : in.alu_result;`\\n   and assign it to `reg_q.rd_wdata`. This is a 32-bit 2:1 mux on\\n   already-combinational outputs of the same stage \\u2014 zero added\\n   delay in MEM (it fits behind the existing `load_data` combo\\n   without deepening that cone).\\n - In wb_stage.sv, set `w_data = in.rd_wdata;`\\n   \\u2014 one LUT level of mux gone from the forwarding + regfile\\n   read-bypass critical paths.\\n\\nThis is an IPC-neutral transformation (same retirement semantics,\\nsame forwarded values, same regfile writes) that purely shortens two\\ncombinational cones by one mux level each. It must stay IPC-neutral\\nbecause `load_data` was already computed combinationally in mem_stage\\nevery cycle; we just route its mux result through the existing\\nMEM/WB flop instead of re-doing the mux combinationally in WB.\\n\\nExpected Fmax lift: 3\\u20138% (one LUT-mux level out of a typical 7\\u201310\\nlevel path on GW2A). Zero IPC change. Zero formal-state expansion\\n(no new pipeline payload, same retirement sequence). RVFI contract\\npreserved: wb_stage still drives w_en/w_addr/w_data identically at\\nthe interface; only the internal provenance of w_data changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rd_wdata field to mem_wb_t (pre-muxed write-back value).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = mem_to_reg ? load_data : alu_result and register it into MEM/WB.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Simplify w_data to pass mem_wb.rd_wdata straight through; remove the combinational mem_to_reg mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Ensure fwd_mem_wb input to ex_stage remains wired to wb_stage's w_data output (now a pass-through of the registered rd_wdata) so the forwarding critical path shortens by one mux level.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add rd_wdata field to mem_wb_t (pre-muxed write-back value).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute rd_wdata = mem_to_reg ? load_data : alu_result and register it into MEM/WB.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/wb_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Simplify w_data to pass mem_wb.rd_wdata straight through; remove the combinational mem_to_reg mux.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Ensure fwd_mem_wb input to ex_stage remains wired to wb_stage's w_data output (now a pass-through of the registered rd_wdata) so the forwarding critical path shortens by one mux level.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: no_checks_generated\\nne_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assumptions in step 20..\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 18..\\nmake[1]: *** [insn_xor_ch1/status] Error 16\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Skipping step 19..\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Assumptions are unsatisfiable!\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assumptions in step 20..\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: PREUNSAT\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: Status returned by engine: ERROR\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned ERROR\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:04:44 [insn_xori_ch1] DONE (ERROR, rc=16)\\nmake[1]: *** [insn_xori_ch1/status] Error 16\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assertions in step 20..\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Checking assertions in step 20..\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\