 summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:05:27 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:01:01  waiting for solver (1 minute)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:01:21  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:01:22 (82)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:55 (55)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nmake[1]: *** [reg_ch0/status] Error 1\\nmake[1]: Target `all' not remade because of errors.\\n\\nFormal: 0 passed, 1 failed\\nFailed: no_checks_generated\\n\\nFull run log: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0/formal/last_run.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Renaming/removing a `mem_wb_t` field that the top-level RVFI wiring observes (here: replacing `read_data` with pre-muxed `rd_wdata`) fails the `reg` check unless the top-level `io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0` / `io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0` taps are re-pointed in lockstep \\u2014 the `reg` check compares rvfi_rd_wdata to the actual regfile write, so any provenance mismatch between wb_stage's `w_data` and the RVFI tap is caught; always audit every `mem_wb_q.<field>` reference at core.sv top-level when mutating the WB payload layout.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Decode JAL (opcode 0x6F) combinationally in if_stage.sv. When the\\nfetched word is JAL and the IF output is valid (not flushed by an EX\\nredirect, imem_stall, or reset), compute the J-type immediate and\\noverride next_pc with pc + imm_J instead of pc + 4. The JAL instruction\\nitself still flows normally through ID/EX/MEM/WB so its PC+4 writeback\\nretires and RVFI sees the canonical pc_wdata = target. EX must NOT\\nre-redirect for a JAL that IF already jumped, so a single-bit\\n`early_jumped` flag is added to `if_id_t` (propagated into `id_ex_t`\\nas a field separate from ctrl_t). `ex_stage` ANDs its redirect\\ncondition with `!in.early_jumped` for the JAL case (is_jump &&\\n!is_jalr). JALR is untouched (it needs rs1 + forwarding and has no\\npurely-IF-visible target).\\n\\nCost in logic:\\n  - A 32-bit J-imm extractor (existing pattern from imm_gen.sv) and\\n    a 2:1 mux on next_pc gated by `imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111`.\\n  - 1-bit `early_jumped` through 2 pipeline registers.\\nExpected Fmax impact: the added IF-stage adder is 32-bit pc + 32-bit\\nsign-extended imm, parallel with the existing pc+4 incrementer \\u2014 it\\nis unlikely to become the new critical path given EX currently owns\\nFmax via the ALU/multiplier mux. Worst case Fmax gives up ~2-3%;\\nIPC gain from eliminating ~2 bubbles on every dynamically-retired\\nJAL (CoreMark has thousands per iteration) should dominate.\\n\\nCorrectness hooks:\\n  - RVFI: pc_wdata of the JAL is always `pc + imm_J` whether IF\\n    early-jumped or EX did. rd_wdata stays PC+4. No change to any\\n    RVFI field \\u2192 riscv-formal `pc_fwd` / `unique` / `causal` checks\\n    remain closed with zero added state-space work.\\n  - Formal: the `early_jumped` flag is a pure function of decoded\\n    opcode + IF stall/flush signals \\u2014 not speculative, not predicted\\n    \\u2014 so SBY's BMC depth is unchanged.\\n  - Traps: a misaligned JAL target still traps in EX (its\\n    misalign_fault path fires there as before; we gate the EX redirect\\n    but not the misalign_fault computation, which also suppresses\\n    reg_write and leaves pc_next = pc + 4).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single-bit `early_jumped` field to if_id_t and id_ex_t (outside ctrl_t so decoder default-illegal semantics are unaffected).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect JAL (opcode 7'b1101111) on imem_data, extract the J-imm, and override next_pc = pc + imm_J when the IF output would otherwise be a valid instruction. Set out.early_jumped accordingly. Preserve reset/flush/stall priority so imem_stall and EX redirects still win over the early-jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate in.early_jumped into the ID/EX register as a standalone field (zero when reset/flush).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the redirect output for unconditional JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr) with !in.early_jumped so IF's in-flight target fetch is not flushed. Misalign_fault still asserts and still overrides via the existing trap path.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a JAL-latency cocotb test: two JALs back-to-back to verify zero bubble cycles in rvfi_order deltas, plus a branch-then-JAL interleaving test to confirm EX redirects still win when IF's JAL-prediction would race an older redirect, plus a misaligned-JAL test (imm with bit[1] set) to confirm trap semantics are preserved.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single-bit `early_jumped` field to if_id_t and id_ex_t (outside ctrl_t so decoder default-illegal semantics are unaffected).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect JAL (opcode 7'b1101111) on imem_data, extract the J-imm, and override next_pc = pc + imm_J when the IF output would otherwise be a valid instruction. Set out.early_jumped accordingly. Preserve reset/flush/stall priority so imem_stall and EX redirects still win over the early-jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate in.early_jumped into the ID/EX register as a standalone field (zero when reset/flush).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the redirect output for unconditional JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr) with !in.early_jumped so IF's in-flight target fetch is not flushed. Misalign_fault still asserts and still overrides via the existing trap path.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a JAL-latency cocotb test: two JALs back-to-back to verify zero bubble cycles in rvfi_order deltas, plus a branch-then-JAL interleaving test to confirm EX redirects still win when IF's JAL-prediction would race an older redirect, plus a misaligned-JAL test (imm with bit[1] set) to confirm trap semantics are preserved.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: no_checks_generated\\ns are unsatisfiable!\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:02  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: PREUNSAT\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:02 (2)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: Status returned by engine: ERROR\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned ERROR\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] DONE (ERROR, rc=16)\\nmake[1]: *** [insn_xori_ch1/status] Error 16\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:01  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:02 (2)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sw_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:01  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:01  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xor_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:19:00 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:01:01  waiting for solver (1 minute)\\nSBY 21:20:03 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:02:04  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:02:05 (125)\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:01:37 (97)\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:20:04 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nmake[1]: *** [reg_ch0/status] Error 1\\nmake[1]: Target `all' not remade because of errors.\\n\\nFormal: 0 passed, 1 failed\\nFailed: no_checks_generated\\n\\nFull run log: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1/formal/last_run.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-002-r2s1/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-002-r2s1 (broken, n/a): IF-stage early-redirect for JAL must still drive the EX-stage RVFI `pc_wdata` tap to the jump target \\u2014 gating `redirect` with `!early_jumped` silences the only signal that steers the EX rvfi_pc_wdata mux to `jump_target`, so the retiring JAL reports `pc_wdata = pc + 4` while the next fetched instruction's `pc_rdata` is the real target, breaking `pc_fwd` / `causal` transitively; any IF-side redirect optimization must either (a) compute pc_wdata from the decoded JAL target independently of the EX redirect gate, or (b) keep the EX redirect asserted (even if IF ignores it) purely for RVFI observability.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Stateless IF-stage static JAL-taken prediction (zero bubble on unconditional jumps)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage baseline pays a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken\\nbranch AND every unconditional jump. For JAL (opcode 0x6F) this\\npenalty is pure waste: JAL is unconditionally taken, and its target\\nis PC + a sign-extended immediate extracted directly from the\\ninstruction word \\u2014 IF can compute it as soon as imem_data arrives,\\nwith no prior history. CoreMark is heavy on function calls (the\\ninner crcu8/crcu16/list_find loops all make indirect calls; the\\nharness is littered with JAL prologue/epilogue pairs), so even a\\nmodest share of control-flow instructions being JAL (empirically\\n~30\\u201340% of taken branches in RV32 compiled code) translates to\\n~1\\u20133% of total CoreMark cycles wasted as JAL redirect bubbles.\\n\\nPrior iter (hyp-20260502-003-r1s2) tried a full BTB and blew the\\n1800s formal budget because it threaded a `predicted` flag and\\n`pred_target` through if_id_t / id_ex_t, expanding the per-insn\\nstate space seen by SBY. The lesson is: keep prediction OUT of the\\nRVFI-observed pipeline payload. A static JAL predictor needs no\\nstate at all \\u2014 the \\\"prediction\\\" is always correct by construction,\\nso no comparison or recovery logic is required downstream.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 5-stage baseline pays a 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken\\nbranch AND every unconditional jump. For JAL (opcode 0x6F) this\\npenalty is pure waste: JAL is unconditionally taken, and its target\\nis PC + a sign-extended immediate extracted directly from the\\ninstruction word \\u2014 IF can compute it as soon as imem_data arrives,\\nwith no prior history. CoreMark is heavy on function calls (the\\ninner crcu8/crcu16/list_find loops all make indirect calls; the\\nharness is littered with JAL prologue/epilogue pairs), so even a\\nmodest share of control-flow instructions being JAL (empirically\\n~30\\u201340% of taken branches in RV32 compiled code) translates to\\n~1\\u20133% of total CoreMark cycles wasted as JAL redirect bubbles.\\n\\nPrior iter (hyp-20260502-003-r1s2) tried a full BTB and blew the\\n1800s formal budget because it threaded a `predicted` flag and\\n`pred_target` through if_id_t / id_ex_t, expanding the per-insn\\nstate space seen by SBY. The lesson is: keep prediction OUT of the\\nRVFI-observed pipeline payload. A static JAL predictor needs no\\nstate at all \\u2014 the \\\"prediction\\\" is always correct by construction,\\nso no comparison or recovery logic is required downstream.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add combinational JAL-target computation inside if_stage.sv and use\\nit to redirect the PC register in the SAME cycle the JAL is fetched,\\neliminating the normal 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble for every JAL.\\n\\nImplementation details:\\n\\n  1. if_stage.sv decodes the currently-fetched imem_data for JAL\\n     (opcode == 7'b1101111) combinationally. If JAL AND the fetch\\n     is valid (no flush, no imem stall, no EX redirect this cycle),\\n     compute jal_imm the same way imm_gen does:\\n       jal_imm = {{11{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[19:12],\\n                  instr[20], instr[30:21], 1'b0}\\n     and set next_pc = pc + jal_imm instead of pc + 4. EX redirect\\n     still has top priority over the JAL prediction (so a redirect\\n     in flight this cycle correctly wins). The JAL instruction\\n     itself is still emitted to ID normally so it decodes, writes\\n     PC+4 to rd in EX, and retires via the usual RVFI path.\\n\\n  2. ex_stage.sv: narrow the redirect condition to exclude JAL.\\n     Currently redirect fires on (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jump)\\n     \\u2014 change to (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jalr). JALR and taken\\n     branches still redirect as today. JAL never does, because IF\\n     has already fetched from the correct target. The misalignment\\n     trap path stays unchanged (JAL immediates have bit0 forced to\\n     0, and PC is 4-aligned, so JAL-misalign is impossible without\\n     C-ext; the existing misalign check remains but is dead code\\n     for JAL specifically).\\n\\n  3. reg_q.pc_next in EX is UNCHANGED \\u2014 it still records the\\n     jump_target for RVFI's pc_wdata. RVFI correctness is identical\\n     to the baseline; only the externally-visible redirect signal\\n     is suppressed.\\n\\n  4. No changes to if_id_t / id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t. No new\\n     pipeline payload bits. No BTB, no counters, no tables. The\\n     formal state space is unchanged \\u2014 the IF combinational logic\\n     just has one extra mux on next_pc, and EX has a narrower OR\\n     condition on redirect. SBY should proof this as fast as the\\n     baseline.\\n\\nWhy this is always safe without a prediction-correctness check:\\na JAL can only reach EX when (a) it was fetched with flush=0 and\\nredirect=0, and (b) imem delivered the real instruction (not a\\nNOP). In both cases the IF-stage JAL predictor saw the same\\nopcode and computed the same target, so the EX-stage jump_target\\nprovably matches the target IF already redirected to. When\\nflush=1 or redirect=1 at IF, the emitted instr is NOP (0x00000013),\\nso ctrl.is_jump is 0 when it reaches EX \\u2014 nothing to redirect.\\nWhen imem_ready=0, flush_if is asserted upstream (via\\nhazard_unit), same story. So no \\\"was this predicted?\\\" bit is\\never needed.\\n\\nExpected delta: saves exactly 2 cycles per dynamically-executed\\nJAL. Estimated JAL density in CoreMark ~2\\u20134% of all retired\\ninstructions; over 449k cycles this is ~2\\u20134% IPC lift. Fmax\\nimpact should be near-zero \\u2014 the added IF path is a 32-bit adder\\nwith a constant-pattern opcode compare in parallel with the\\nexisting pc+4 adder, slotted into the same IF combinational\\ncone. Net fitness: +2 to +4%.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational JAL-target predictor: decode imem_data[6:0]==0x6F, extract JAL immediate, mux next_pc to pc+jal_imm when JAL is fetched (gated by !redirect and !flush, with EX redirect keeping top priority). No state, no new register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Narrow redirect to (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jalr) && !misalign_fault \\u2014 JAL no longer fires redirect because IF already handled it correctly. reg_q.pc_next still records jump_target for RVFI pc_wdata. jump_target/branch_target calculation unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add regressions: (1) a JAL at arbitrary PC with arbitrary sign-extended immediate retires with correct pc_wdata on channel 0 and the instruction fetched on the cycle after JAL is the one at the JAL target (not pc+4); (2) a JAL immediately after a taken branch still picks up the redirect target first, then the predicted JAL target on the next cycle; (3) JAL with imem_ready=0 in its fetch cycle correctly stalls PC and does NOT predict (NOP is emitted); (4) back-to-back JAL chain retires every cycle (no bubbles between JALs).\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add combinational JAL-target predictor: decode imem_data[6:0]==0x6F, extract JAL immediate, mux next_pc to pc+jal_imm when JAL is fetched (gated by !redirect and !flush, with EX redirect keeping top priority). No state, no new register.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Narrow redirect to (branch_taken || in.ctrl.is_jalr) && !misalign_fault \\u2014 JAL no longer fires redirect because IF already handled it correctly. reg_q.pc_next still records jump_target for RVFI pc_wdata. jump_target/branch_target calculation unchanged.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add regressions: (1) a JAL at arbitrary PC with arbitrary sign-extended immediate retires with correct pc_wdata on channel 0 and the instruction fetched on the cycle after JAL is the one at the JAL target (not pc+4); (2) a JAL immediately after a taken branch still picks up the redirect target first, then the predicted JAL target on the next cycle; (3) JAL with imem_ready=0 in its fetch cycle correctly stalls PC and does NOT predict (NOP is emitted); (4) back-to-back JAL chain retires every cycle (no bubbles between JALs).\"}], \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 318.71, \"delta_pct\": 5.87, \"vs_baseline\": 5.87, \"fmax_mhz\": 141.58, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4442217, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9860, \"ff\": 1869, \"seeds\": [141.58, 139.78, 142.13], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-03T00:28:15.263019Z\", \"slot\": 2, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-003-r2s2 (improvement, +5.87%): A stateless IF-stage JAL predictor \\u2014 combinationally decode opcode 0x6F, compute `pc + J-imm`, guard on `target[1:0]==0` to preserve misalign-trap semantics, and narrow EX redirect to `(branch_taken || is_jalr)` \\u2014 eliminates the 2-cycle JAL bubble without adding any pipeline payload bits or new formal state, confirming the r1s2 lesson: prediction that is *provably correct by construction* needs no `predicted` flag, no recovery logic, and leaves SBY proof time unchanged while still netting ~5-6% CoreMark fitness from JAL-heavy call/return sequences.\"}\n","exit":0,"description":"Find prior predictor attempts","truncated":false},"title":"Find prior predictor attempts","time":{"start":1777768265663,"end":1777768265665}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Now I'm checking what predictor-category hypotheses have already been explored.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3ef5ce001Ez3wq3s2W0ec5t","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","messageID":"msg_deb3eedb50010K2EDv2E4aNSKa"}}
