{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777768352690,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01CgGHZFWMfMRMyTLuGBNH58","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r3s2\ntitle: \"Stateless IF-stage BTFN conditional-branch predictor (reconstruct at EX)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The previous round's JAL predictor (hyp-20260502-003-r2s2, +5.87%)\n  confirmed the \"provably correct by construction\" pattern: decode the\n  instruction word at IF, redirect PC the same cycle, reconstruct the\n  prediction decision at EX from the same instruction bits, and narrow\n  the EX-stage redirect signal to mispredicts. Zero new pipeline\n  payload bits, zero new formal state — SBY proof time unchanged.\n\n  JAL is now zero-bubble, but conditional branches (opcode 0x63) still\n  pay the full 2-cycle redirect penalty on every taken branch. In\n  CoreMark the inner hot loops (crcu8 loop, core_list_find reverse\n  walk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k, core_state_transition's\n  big switch) are dominated by backward loop-closing conditional\n  branches that are taken ~90% of the time. Forward branches in\n  if/else-error paths are taken <20% of the time. Static BTFN\n  (Backward-Taken-Forward-Not-taken) captures both biases perfectly\n  and needs zero bits of history — the prediction is a pure function\n  of the B-immediate's sign bit (instr[31]).\n\n  Prior attempts and their lessons inform this design:\n    - r1s2 (BTB): blew formal budget by threading `predicted`+`pred_target`\n      through if_id_t/id_ex_t. AVOID payload fields.\n    - r2s1 (JAL early-redirect with `early_jumped` flag): broke\n      pc_fwd because gating EX `redirect` silenced the pc_wdata tap.\n      AVOID: keep pc_next computation independent of the redirect\n      assertion gate.\n    - r2s2 (stateless JAL predictor): succeeded because IF's decision\n      is a pure function of instruction bits, and EX reconstructs the\n      exact same decision to decide whether to redirect. ADOPT this\n      pattern verbatim, extended to branches.\n\n  With the JAL predictor already deployed, conditional branches are\n  the next-biggest source of control-flow bubbles. Estimated\n  density in CoreMark: ~12-15% of retired instructions are\n  conditional branches; ~55-65% are taken; ~75-85% of taken branches\n  are backward. BTFN nets ~80-90% accuracy overall. At 2 cycles saved\n  per correct prediction and ~10% of cycles going to branch bubbles\n  today, a +6 to +10% CoreMark IPC lift is realistic.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a stateless static BTFN conditional-branch predictor to\n  if_stage.sv, mirrored by EX-stage reconstruction that narrows the\n  redirect signal to actual mispredicts only. No new pipeline payload\n  bits, no new registers, no history tables.\n\n  IF-STAGE CHANGES (rtl/if_stage.sv):\n    1. Decode opcode 0x63 (BRANCH) from imem_data combinationally.\n    2. Extract the B-type immediate:\n         b_imm = {{19{imem_data[31]}}, imem_data[31], imem_data[7],\n                  imem_data[30:25], imem_data[11:8], 1'b0}\n    3. Compute br_target = pc + b_imm.\n    4. Predict taken iff all of:\n         - opcode == 7'b1100011 (BRANCH)\n         - imem_data[31] == 1     (negative immediate = backward)\n         - br_target[1:0] == 2'b00 (aligned; same guard as JAL\n           predictor to preserve misalign-trap semantics)\n         - funct3 is a valid branch (0,1,4,5,6,7 — exclude 2,3 which\n           are reserved/illegal and must retire with rvfi_trap)\n         - !flush && !redirect (same fetch-validity gate used for\n           JAL)\n    5. next_pc priority: redirect (EX) > jal_target > br_target >\n       pc+4. Update the existing next_pc mux.\n    6. The branch instruction itself is still emitted to ID normally\n       (no predicted flag, no NOP substitution) — it decodes and\n       flows through EX just like any other branch.\n\n  EX-STAGE CHANGES (rtl/ex_stage.sv):\n    1. Reconstruct IF's prediction decision from the same instruction\n       bits that are already carried through id_ex_t:\n         is_branch_opcode   = (in.instr[6:0] == 7'b1100011)\n         funct3_valid_br    = (in.instr[14:12] != 3'd2 &&\n                              in.instr[14:12] != 3'd3)\n         target_aligned     = (branch_target[1:0] == 2'b00)\n         if_predicted_taken = in.ctrl.is_branch\n                              && is_branch_opcode\n                              && in.instr[31]\n                              && funct3_valid_br\n                              && target_aligned\n    2. Detect mispredict:\n         branch_mispredict = in.ctrl.is_branch\n                             && (if_predicted_taken != branch_taken)\n    3. Narrow the redirect signal:\n         redirect = !misalign_fault\n                    && (in.ctrl.is_jalr || branch_mispredict)\n       (JAL is already excluded by r2s2; we keep that narrowing.)\n    4. Broaden the redirect_target mux to cover the \"predicted taken\n       but actually not taken\" case, which must redirect back to pc+4:\n         redirect_target = in.ctrl.is_jalr ? jump_target\n                         : branch_taken    ? branch_target\n                                           : (in.pc + 32'd4)\n    5. reg_q.pc_next is UNCHANGED. It already reads\n       `branch_taken ? branch_target : pc+4`, independent of the\n       redirect assertion — so RVFI's pc_wdata tap remains\n       authoritative regardless of whether EX physically redirects.\n       This is the fix the r2s1 lesson called out: keep pc_next\n       decoupled from the redirect gate.\n\n  WHY NO PAYLOAD BITS / NO FORMAL BLOWUP:\n    - IF's prediction is a pure combinational function of imem_data,\n      pc, flush, redirect. It writes nothing new into the IF/ID\n      bundle.\n    - EX reconstructs the prediction from in.instr (already in\n      id_ex_t for RVFI), in.ctrl.is_branch, and branch_target\n      (computed from in.pc + in.imm, also already present).\n    - SBY sees exactly the same id_ex_t / ex_mem_t / mem_wb_t as\n      baseline. The new logic is pure combinational at IF and EX.\n      BMC depth and state count are unchanged.\n\n  WHY THE PREDICTION IS SELF-CONSISTENT:\n    - If IF predicted taken for this branch (by the 5 conditions\n      above), the SAME branch reaches EX with the SAME instr bits\n      and the SAME branch_target (imm is derived from the same\n      instr), so EX's reconstruction produces if_predicted_taken=1.\n    - If flush=1 or redirect=1 when this branch was at IF, IF\n      emitted NOP (0x00000013) instead — ctrl.is_branch=0 at EX,\n      reconstruction is a no-op.\n    - If imem_stall at fetch, flush_if is asserted upstream — same\n      NOP outcome.\n    - The funct3_valid_br guard mirrors decoder.sv's branch-arm\n      acceptance: only funct3 ∈ {0,1,4,5,6,7} are legal branches.\n      Illegal-funct3 branches (funct3=2,3) don't have ctrl.is_branch\n      set, so reconstruction gracefully sees predicted=0.\n\n  RVFI FIELD IMPACT:\n    - rvfi_pc_wdata: still driven by reg_q.pc_next, unchanged.\n    - rvfi_trap: misalign_fault path untouched; IF's alignment guard\n      matches EX's misalign_branch guard, so a misaligned taken\n      branch is NEVER predicted and traps normally in EX.\n    - rvfi_pc_rdata of the next retirement: now physically equals\n      the predicted-target for correctly-predicted backward\n      branches, matching the prior pc_wdata. pc_fwd holds.\n    - All other RVFI fields unchanged (no decode, ALU, mem, or\n      regfile changes).\n\n  EXPECTED FITNESS:\n    - IPC lift: ~6-10% from eliminating taken-branch bubbles across\n      CoreMark's hot loops. Static BTFN on RV32 compiled code\n      typically achieves 80-88% accuracy.\n    - Fmax: one extra 32-bit adder in IF (parallel with pc+4 and\n      jal_target adders) + one 4-way mux. Fmax ceiling is currently\n      set by EX's ALU/multiplier cone, not IF. Expect ±1% Fmax\n      drift.\n    - LUT4 / FF: +30 to +80 LUTs for IF adder and EX reconstruction,\n      no new FFs. Well within the 10000 LUT budget.\n    - Net fitness: +5 to +8%, confidence medium.\n\n  FALLBACK IF EX RECONSTRUCTION CRITICAL PATH HURTS FMAX:\n    The reconstruction logic is ~5 LUT levels at worst\n    (instr[6:0]==0x63, instr[14:12] decode, branch_target[1:0]\n    check, AND-tree, XOR-with-branch_taken, OR into redirect).\n    It sits in parallel with the existing ALU-result cone and the\n    branch-comparator, which are both ~8-12 levels — reconstruction\n    should be well off the critical path. If Fmax regresses\n    unexpectedly, moving the `is_branch_opcode` and\n    `funct3_valid_br` evaluation into id_stage.sv and passing them\n    as a single `if_predicted_taken_mask` bit (1 bit, still no\n    payload widening of semantic fields) is the targeted escape\n    hatch.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add stateless BTFN conditional-branch predictor. Decode opcode 0x63, extract B-imm, compute br_target = pc + b_imm, predict taken iff imm[31]=1 AND target[1:0]=0 AND funct3 is legal branch AND !flush AND !redirect. Extend next_pc priority mux: redirect > jal_target > br_target > pc+4. No new state, no new output fields on if_id_t.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Reconstruct IF's prediction decision from in.instr bits (opcode==0x63, instr[31], funct3 validity, branch_target alignment). Detect branch_mispredict = is_branch && (if_predicted_taken != branch_taken). Narrow redirect to !misalign_fault && (is_jalr || branch_mispredict). Broaden redirect_target mux to route to pc+4 when actually-not-taken (after predicted-taken). Keep reg_q.pc_next = branch_taken ? branch_target : pc+4 unchanged so RVFI pc_wdata tap stays authoritative regardless of redirect gate (per the r2s1 lesson).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add regressions: (1) backward BEQ that is taken retires with zero bubble cycles between branch retirement and target retirement (rvfi_order deltas); (2) forward BEQ that is taken still costs 2 cycles (mispredict); (3) backward BEQ with taken=false must redirect back to pc+4 (mispredict-back) and the next retirement has correct pc_rdata=pc+4; (4) BEQ with misaligned backward target (imm with bit[1]=1) is NOT predicted (IF alignment guard) and traps normally via existing misalign_fault path; (5) branch with funct3=2 (reserved/illegal) is NOT predicted and retires with rvfi_trap=1; (6) back-to-back taken backward branches (tight loop body) retire every cycle after the first; (7) branch immediately after JAL: JAL predicts correctly, then the branch at the JAL target predicts according to BTFN — verify both rvfi_order monotonicity and correct pc_wdata on each retirement.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777768352668,"end":1777768352689}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm looking at how the successful JAL predictor achieved correctness through a \"provably correct by construction\" approach—decoding the opcode combinationally in the IF stage, redirecting immediately, then having the EX stage reconstruct the same computation from the instruction bits without adding pipeline payload. Now I'm thinking about extending this same pattern to BRANCH instructions, where the key insight is applying the BTFN heuristic (backward branches taken, forward branches not taken) in a way that maintains this verifiable correctness property.\n\nThe IF stage extracts the branch immediate from the instruction word, checks if it's a backward branch by examining the sign bit, computes the target address, validates alignment, and redirects the next cycle if the prediction is taken. Then in the EX stage, I reconstruct that exact same prediction logic from the instruction bits alone—checking the opcode, re-extracting the immediate, recomputing the target—and only trigger a redirect on a misprediction, comparing what IF predicted against the actual branch outcome.\n\nThe key insight from the r2s2 lesson is that `reg_q.pc_next` must be computed independently of whether the EX redirect signal fires, so that RVFI's pc_wdata stays correct regardless of redirect suppression. I'm already tracking `pc_next` as `branch_taken ? branch_target : pc+4`, which handles both taken and not-taken paths correctly without depending on the redirect assertion.\n\nFor the redirect logic itself, I need to narrow the condition so that branches only redirect when they're actually mispredicted—meaning I redirect to `branch_target` when `branch_taken=1`, and to `pc+4` when `branch_taken=0` (the mispredicted-not-taken case). I'm refactoring the redirect target assignment to cleanly separate JALR handling from branch handling.\n\nRefactoring redirect logic... The branch predictor and JAL predictor use different opcodes so there's no conflict there. I'm also checking that when a branch instruction reaches EX, it either went through IF's normal prediction path or was flushed to a NOP—either way, the reconstruction logic is safe. Stalls and flushes are handled correctly since they prevent the branch from reaching EX with `is_branch` asserted.\n\nFor misaligned targets, IF's guard prevents prediction and the EX reconstruction mirrors that check, so misaligned branches either trap or don't trigger a mispredict. The pc_next computation and RVFI correctness hold across all four cases of branch taken/predicted combinations. Now I'm verifying the sign-extension logic for branch_target in EX... ken branch saves 2 cycles.\n\nCoreMark has many loops. Very rough estimate:\n- 15% branches × 50% taken → 7.5% of instructions are taken branches\n- Of taken branches, ~80% are backward (loops) → IF predicts correctly for ~80% × taken → 6% \n- Each correct prediction saves 2 cycles → ~12% cycle reduction \n\nRealistic: maybe +6-10% IPC improvement. Let's estimate +6% conservatively.\n\n**Cost:**\nExtra IF combinational logic: 32-bit adder (parallel with pc+4 adder and JAL adder), opcode compare, alignment check, mux. Shouldn't dent Fmax much.\nExtra EX combinational: reconstruction logic (compare instr[6:0], instr[31]).\n\nLet me write the YAML now.\n\n---\n\nLooking at CoreMark's loop-heavy workload, I estimate backward branches (which BTFN handles well) make up roughly 6% of all instructions, and each correct prediction saves 2 cycles, so I'm targeting around 6% IPC improvement conservatively. The hardware cost is modest—just a parallel 32-bit adder in IF alongside the existing pc+4 and JAL adders, plus some opcode and alignment checks, and reconstruction logic in EX. This shouldn't significantly impact timing. Now I'll write up the YAML specification.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb3f9384001wqXinmIRnHs42f","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","messageID":"msg_deb3ef8410017gbpvB6vZHJARf"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768352692,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"id":"prt_deb3f92cc0018L5V3kiKaefajY","messageID":"msg_deb3ef8410017gbpvB6vZHJARf","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","type":"text","text":"Now I have full context. The successful r2s2 JAL predictor used the \"provably correct by construction\" pattern — IF decodes + predicts, EX reconstructs the same decision from instruction bits, no pipeline payload state added. I'll extend this pattern to conditional branches using a static BTFN (Backward-Taken, Forward-Not-taken) heuristic.\n\nKey insight: IF can't look at rs1/rs2 values, but it can look at the immediate sign bit. Backward branches (imm[31]=1) are almost always loop-closing and taken. Forward branches are frequently if-else and often not taken. Like JAL, EX can reconstruct what IF predicted from the SAME instruction word — no `predicted` flag in the pipeline payload needed.","time":{"start":1777768305356,"end":1777768352691}}}
