{"type":"text","timestamp":1777768359632,"sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","part":{"id":"prt_deb40533d0011EX9usQ2oeaZXH","messageID":"msg_deb404c17001sGPyVoUh53oV3d","sessionID":"ses_214c24f29ffeYrUHV0yx1krHN6","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r3s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Stateless static BTFN (Backward-Taken-Forward-Not-taken) conditional-branch predictor, built on the exact pattern that made r2s2's JAL predictor succeed:\n\n1. **IF-stage**: decode opcode 0x63, extract B-imm, redirect same cycle when `imm[31]==1` (backward) AND target aligned AND funct3 legal AND fetch is valid.\n2. **EX-stage**: reconstruct what IF would have predicted from the same `in.instr` bits already in `id_ex_t` for RVFI. Redirect only on mispredict, to `branch_target` (predicted-not/actually-taken) or `pc+4` (predicted-taken/actually-not-taken).\n3. **No payload bits added** → formal state space unchanged (avoids r1s2's BTB-payload blowup).\n4. **`reg_q.pc_next` stays decoupled from the redirect gate** → RVFI `pc_wdata` tap stays authoritative (avoids r2s1's pc_fwd break).\n5. **IF's alignment guard matches EX's misalign_branch check** → misalign trap semantics preserved (same trick as JAL predictor).\n\nExpected +6% fitness from eliminating the 2-cycle bubble on the ~80% of backward loop-branches that dominate CoreMark's hot inner loops.","time":{"start":1777768354621,"end":1777768359631}}}
