{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769772980,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"id":"prt_deb55ed5e0018F0WiB1ChXOw28","messageID":"msg_deb53624a0015uHSybc1yTwI7k","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","type":"text","text":"Looking at the situation carefully:\n\n**Recent outcomes in predictor space:**\n- r2s2 JAL predictor: +5.87% (stateless, provably correct by construction)\n- r3s1 and r3s2 BTFNT: both broken on formal (conditional-branch prediction couples direction + fetched opcode, breaks SBY induction under symbolic imem_data)\n- Lesson explicit: \"JAL sidestepped [formal] because its prediction/resolution equality is tautological (unconditional)\"\n\nThe winnable angle is extending the **provably tautological stateless IF-redirect** pattern from JAL to other always-taken encodings. Let me check the logs briefly and then write.","time":{"start":1777769770334,"end":1777769772979}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769772992,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01RFYspaAMqkng7smRxsdPdn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypothesis files"},"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r4s0.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r4s0.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777769772987,"end":1777769772990}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what worked and what didn't with the predictor approaches—the JAL predictor showed promise with a solid improvement, but the BTFNT conditional branch prediction ran into issues with symbolic memory creating infinite loops during formal verification. Since the current best result is at 8.50% after optimizing MUL variants, I'm now considering a Return Address Stack predictor as the next option to explore for the cores/bench category.\n\nThe challenge is that JALR instructions are data-dependent and harder to predict statically, though they're commonly used for returns. A RAS could help predict return targets, but adding state to the pipeline payload caused formal verification failures before. The real bottleneck seems to be that branches currently resolve at the EX stage, creating a 2-cycle bubble for taken branches—moving resolution earlier to the ID stage could cut that to 1 cycle, though it might increase combinational depth. The lesson from earlier attempts suggests I should focus either on reducing the EX-stage bubble or finding a provably correct approach like the JAL predictor was.\n\nI'm realizing a 1-entry Return Address Stack could work if I keep the state outside the RVFI pipeline payload—just a register tracking the last return address, indexed separately. When a JAL writes to x1, I cache its target; when a JALR reads from x1 with rd=x0, I predict that cached target. This avoids polluting the formal verification payload while still giving me a stateless-looking predictor for the common return pattern.\n\nThe misprediction path is already there—if the JALR target doesn't match my prediction, the EX stage redirects as usual. But I need to be careful: an uninitialized or garbage RAS value could cause out-of-bounds fetches that violate the formal memory bounds. So I should either initialize the RAS carefully or add a validity bit to gate predictions only when the RAS has been populated by an actual JAL.\n\nLet me step back and reconsider simpler approaches. A single-entry RAS that only pushes on JAL with rd=x1 and pops on JALR with rs1=x1 and rd=x0 matches the return pattern exactly, but in formal verification a symbolic stream might push without ever popping, leaving stale data. Other ideas like branch target buffers for backward branches or forward-taken static prediction don't help—they either fail the same way or add nothing new. The real bottleneck after JAL prediction is the 2-cycle bubble from taken conditional branches and JALR returns, which are everywhere in CoreMark due to function calls.\n\nA JALR predictor using the last link address written to x1 could work in principle—when JAL/JALR writes x1, capture PC+4, then predict that value on JALR reads of x1. The formal concern is the same as BTFNT: IF redirects to a predicted address whose imem_data is symbolically free, so SBY can't prove the fetched instruction is correct. But JAL was provably correct by construction because the target is encoded in the instruction itself, whereas JALR's target depends on register state that formal must track across the RAS flop.\n\nSince any JALR predictor needs EX-stage misprediction recovery anyway, the real risk is whether the pipeline can safely drain a mispredicted path back to correct execution—and given the prior formal verification struggles, that's a risky bet. So instead I'm leaning toward a more conservative approach: keep IF linear but move branch resolution earlier to ID, which could reduce the EX redirect penalty from 2 cycles down to 1.\n\nActually, that's a structural change and probably too complex. Let me refocus on something that clearly fits the \"predictor\" category. I'll go with a simple JALR predictor using a last-return-address register—essentially a minimal RAS that tracks the most recent link address from JAL or JALR instructions that write to x1 or x5. At IF time, if we see a JALR using one of those registers and the link_valid flag is set, we predict to that saved address. EX still computes the actual target and redirects if there's a mismatch, same as today. The key insight is that we can decode the opcode and register fields directly from the instruction memory, so we don't need any additional pipeline state to make the prediction decision. pipeline-threaded prediction bit if we handle misprediction at EX by comparing EX's jalr_sum to the RAS prediction that was used.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to not predict JALR at all and instead speed up JALR resolution itself—that's more structural.\n\nLet me try a different but safer predictor: a stateless PC+imm prefetch for JALR with x0 as rs1, though that's rare. Or better yet, branch resolution in the ID stage for earlier redirect, though that's borderline structural.\n\nGiven the constraints, I'm leaning toward a minimal side-channel single-entry RAS consulted only when profitable: push on JAL with rd=x1 at WB (committed only), predict at IF when we see JALR with rs1=x1 and rd=x0, and redirect the same cycle. But threading a predicted bit feels wrong after the r1s2 lesson.\n\nThe real problem is that at EX, the JALR computes its actual target and we need to know whether IF predicted for this specific instruction to avoid wasting the prediction with an unnecessary redirect. I could track a predicted_target field in ex_mem_t and suppress the redirect if it matches the actual target, though that might expand formal state. The main concern is whether adding ID-stage forwarding for the branch comparator will hurt Fmax, but with careful design it should be manageable. I'm realizing this is really about improving the implicit static predictor by reducing the misprediction penalty from 2 cycles to 1 cycle through early branch resolution—which counts as a predictor improvement even if it's structural in nature. The potential IPC gain is significant: conditional branches are roughly 10-15% of instructions with a 50-70% taken rate, so cutting the penalty in half could yield around 9% IPC improvement. I'll frame this as reducing the misprediction cost of the existing static \"predict not-taken\" strategy and move forward with the implementation. I'm circling back to what r3s2 actually said about the EX-stage bubble reduction path—resolving branches earlier to shrink the penalty without speculative IF redirects. ID-stage resolution does fit that constraint. I'd need to add branch comparison logic and forwarding muxes at ID, wire the redirect output, handle branch-dependent-on-load stalls, and extend the forward unit. But this feels too risky for a first attempt and could break formal verification. Let me look for something smaller and more predictor-focused instead.\n\nThe safe options like JALR prediction for x0 offsets are too narrow to matter. Software hints don't exist in RV32IM. Reviewing the full landscape: IF-stage speculation failed twice, RAS-1 has the same formal issues, multi-entry RAS is just more of the same problem. Early branch resolution at ID keeps IF linear and matches what the lesson called acceptable. That's the move—I'm going to commit to it and write it up carefully.\n\nActually, re-reading the lesson more closely: it's saying I can either pursue the EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear) or accept a formal wrapper-level assume about imem_data at the predicted target. If branch resolves at ID instead of EX, IF only fetches one wrong-path instruction instead of two, so the redirect happens one cycle earlier in the pipeline flow.\n\nLet me work through the concrete timing: currently a taken branch causes a 2-cycle bubble because the redirect fires at EX, but with ID-stage resolution I'd get down to 1 cycle. The tradeoff is handling forwarding from EX/MEM and MEM/WB to the comparator at ID, plus stalling when a branch depends on a load result that hasn't completed yet.\n\nThe real concern is ALU-to-branch dependencies—if the branch immediately follows a compare or arithmetic operation, I'd need to either forward combinationally from EX (which creates a long critical path through the ALU and comparator) or stall for 1 cycle. In typical code like a CMP followed by BEQ, that stall would eat into the savings, so I need to measure whether the net improvement actually materializes.\n\nFor load-dependent branches, the situation is even worse. A LOAD followed by BEQZ already incurs a 1-cycle stall today because the loaded data doesn't reach the branch comparator until the load completes. With ID-stage branch resolution, the branch would have to wait even longer—potentially 2 cycles—making it worse than the current design.\n\nLooking at CoreMark's actual patterns, there are pointer null checks and array traversals that depend on loads, plus ALU-based comparisons and unrelated register branches. The net performance impact of early resolution is genuinely unclear—it could be neutral or even negative overall.\n\nLet me step back and reconsider the real constraint. Fmax is 153.61 MHz versus a 135 MHz target, so we're actually ahead there. The real bottleneck is IPC—CoreMark/MHz needs to hit 2.2, and that's where the leverage is. Given how much trouble branch predictors have caused and how risky early resolution looks, maybe I should try something simpler.\n\nWhat if I prefetch speculatively from the branch target in parallel with the fall-through path? That would need dual-ported instruction memory though, which gets complicated. Or I could cache just JALR targets—keep a single-entry BTB specifically for the last resolved JALR, so on the next JALR we can predict its target immediately.\n\nLooking at what's actually worked: the JAL predictor gained 5.87%, DSP folding gained 8.5%, but the conditional branch IF-spec attempts failed twice. So maybe I should stick with what works. For the next predictor slot, I could recognize that BEQ x0, x0, offset is effectively an unconditional branch—x0 always equals x0, so this encoding is always taken. It's stateless and provably correct, just like the JAL predictor.\n\nCompilers do emit this pattern when JAL is out of range, though it's rare in CoreMark. I could also handle BEQ with the same register (like BEQ x1, x1), but that requires runtime comparison at fetch time and probably won't move the needle much. Given the constraints, I'll propose the stateless BEQ x0, x0 predictor—it's simple, proven-correct, and follows the same pattern as the successful JAL approach. The impact is probably too small to matter. Let me look for something with more potential—maybe predicting through JAL chains, or leveraging branch target alignment, but those either need extra hardware or don't pan out. I'm going to settle on extending the stateless predictor to handle BEQ and BNE when both operands are identical: BEQ rs, rs is always taken (since rs trivially equals itself), while BNE rs, rs is always not taken. This follows the same safety argument as JAL—it's provably correct by construction, requires no pipeline changes, and the target is deterministic from the instruction bits alone.\n\nThe expected impact is modest and uncertain—CoreMark might not even use this idiom much. But I could expand it to cover other tautological branches like BGE rs, rs and BGEU rs, rs, which are also always-taken regardless of register value. BLT rs, rs and BLTU rs, rs would be always-not-taken, which is already the default behavior.\n\nStill, real CoreMark branches are condition-dependent, not tautological, so this might not help much. The real opportunity I've been skirting is probably a careful RAS design for JALR returns—a shadow stack that's formal-invisible and tracks return addresses without speculating on symbolic data.\n\nThe core challenge is recovery: if the RAS prediction is wrong, I need to know whether the JALR was predicted at IF so I can suppress the redundant EX redirect. That requires threading a `predicted` bit through the pipeline, but I could gate it under a `RISCV_FORMAL` flag so formal verification sees the baseline behavior while simulation gets the prediction benefit.\n\nBut that's unsound — formal would never see the predictor's interaction with the pipeline, so bugs in redirect/flush priority could hide. The multiplier precedent (ALTOPS in formal) still exercises the pipeline structure; gating the predictor entirely doesn't. I need a better approach.\n\nLet me settle on stateless always-taken prediction for provably-tautological branch encodings: BEQ, BGE, and BGEU when both operands are the same register. This mirrors the proven JAL predictor pattern and is low-risk. The tautology is verifiable at fetch time from instruction bits alone — if rs1_addr == rs2_addr, the comparison is always true. Compilers rarely emit these, so impact might be negligible, but it's a safe experiment with no regression risk.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the delayed branch resolution approach by moving conditional branch resolution to the ID stage. I analyzed this before and found load-use hazard complications, so let me trace through the actual pipeline timing more carefully. Looking at the current datapath: a LOAD instruction produces data that gets latched into the MEM/WB register at the end of the cycle it's in MEM, then becomes available for forwarding in the next cycle when it reaches WB. A dependent instruction stalls in ID for one cycle while the LOAD is in MEM, then proceeds to EX where it can forward from MEM/WB. Moving branch resolution earlier would need to account for this forwarding delay, and the net benefit isn't clear.\n\nWith ID-stage branch resolution, a branch dependent on a LOAD would need to stall longer because the load data isn't available until later in the pipeline. I could create a long combinational path from the load's memory read through the shift/extend logic, into the ID stage's comparator, and back to the PC mux, but that would likely violate timing constraints. The safer approach would be to stall for two cycles instead of one, which defeats the purpose. For branches dependent on ALU results, I'd face a similar issue—the ALU result wouldn't be latched into EX/MEM yet when the branch reaches ID, so I'd either need a combinational forward from the ALU output or accept an extra stall cycle.\n\nThis means ID-stage resolution trades a one-cycle gain on taken branches against one-cycle losses on both LOAD-to-branch and ALU-to-branch dependencies. Since ALU-to-branch is likely common in typical code, the net effect would be negative. Adding the combinational forwarding paths to make it work would hurt Fmax, so this approach isn't worth pursuing.\n\nI'm going to stick with the tautological-always-taken predictor—it's low-impact but safe. I considered a few other ideas like tracking branch hints in the instruction or using a selective JALR return-address stack, but those either aren't part of the standard ISA or introduce too much risk. My final answer is to extend the JAL predictor to recognize BEQ and BGE patterns where both operands are the same register.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering the scope here. The tautological recognizer could catch more cases—BEQ x0, x0 and BGE x0, x0 are always taken, and some codegen paths emit BEQ x0, x0 for short forward jumps instead of JAL. Even if that's rare, a stateless recognizer that handles any same-register pair across these branch types is provably correct and could capture compiler idioms. The JAL predictor alone gave +5.87%, suggesting unconditional branches are common, so extending this pattern recognition might be worth the effort. I'm settling on the tautological always-taken branch predictor approach and need to write up the hypothesis now.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb55f46500142L8nX8yj34NlJ","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","messageID":"msg_deb53624a0015uHSybc1yTwI7k"}}
