{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777769785117,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"id":"prt_deb562718001Ha21xnCs4awvBM","messageID":"msg_deb5619cb002DIU8cywgfexleX","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","snapshot":"c0fc73655d84913c6c860a503c24846ae00274d4","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769836260,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"id":"prt_deb567d80001YaDTOWpxxR9FIN","messageID":"msg_deb5619cb002DIU8cywgfexleX","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","type":"text","text":"Good — novel angle. Now writing the hypothesis.\n\n**Rationale:** The only predictor approach that survived formal was JAL's \"provably-correct-by-construction\" stateless IF redirect (r2s2 lesson: tautological prediction/resolution equality). Conditional-branch predictors failed twice because direction + symbolic imem_data couples two free variables. But there's a class of conditional branches whose direction is tautologically forced by the **instruction bits themselves**, independent of register values:\n\n- `BEQ rs, rs` (rs1_addr == rs2_addr) → always taken (a == a)\n- `BGE rs, rs` → always taken (a ≥ a signed)\n- `BGEU rs, rs` → always taken (a ≥ a unsigned)\n\nThese are the compiler idioms that expand `j` / unconditional-branch short forms via the BRANCH opcode (e.g. `beq x0, x0, L`, sometimes emitted by assemblers when JAL range isn't needed). The tautology holds from instruction bits alone — same formal-safety argument as JAL (no free variable coupling).\n\nImplementation mirrors the JAL predictor: IF stage decodes the pattern combinationally, computes target, redirects same-cycle; EX redirect is narrowed to exclude the tautological-taken case (detectable at EX from `rs1_addr == rs2_addr` + branch_op, no pipeline-threaded state).","time":{"start":1777769807232,"end":1777769836260}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777769836265,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Pp4dHseo9qPaWEBXweWgWD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r4s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r4s2\ntitle: \"Stateless IF-stage prediction of tautologically-always-taken branches (BEQ/BGE/BGEU with rs1_addr == rs2_addr)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  After the r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%), the remaining control-flow\n  bubbles are (a) taken conditional branches and (b) JALR. Both\n  conventional IF-speculative approaches (r3s1 BTFNT, r3s2 BTFN) broke\n  formal identically: SBY's induction for the `reg` property could not\n  close a loop in which IF redirects onto an address whose imem_data is\n  a free symbolic variable AND the branch's resolved direction is also\n  free. JAL escaped that trap because its prediction/resolution\n  equality is tautological (unconditional). A parallel class of\n  conditional branches has the same tautological property: any BEQ /\n  BGE / BGEU whose rs1_addr == rs2_addr is ALWAYS taken regardless of\n  the register's runtime value (a == a, a >= a signed, a >= a unsigned\n  — all trivially true for any a). Compilers and assemblers sometimes\n  emit these idioms for short unconditional-jump sequences when the JAL\n  range is unnecessary, and link-editor fixups occasionally produce\n  them. Predicting this class at IF is provably-correct-by-construction\n  from instruction bits alone — no free variable coupling — and re-uses\n  the exact JAL predictor scaffolding that already proved formally\n  tractable.\nhypothesis: |\n  Extend if_stage.sv's stateless static predictor to recognize\n  tautologically-always-taken conditional branches and redirect PC to\n  pc+B-immediate the same cycle they are fetched, just as JAL does:\n\n    is_taut_taken_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1100011)        // BRANCH opcode\n                       && (imem_data[19:15] == imem_data[24:20]) // rs1 == rs2\n                       && (imem_data[14:12] inside {3'd0, 3'd5, 3'd7}) // BEQ, BGE, BGEU\n                       && !flush && !redirect\n                       && (b_target[1:0] == 2'b00)              // misalign guard\n\n  where b_target = pc + {{19{instr[31]}}, instr[31], instr[7],\n                         instr[30:25], instr[11:8], 1'b0}.\n\n  Priority in next_pc: redirect > is_jal_fetch > is_taut_taken_fetch >\n  pc+4. Flush path unchanged.\n\n  To avoid a redundant EX-stage re-redirect to the same address (which\n  would burn back the saved bubble), narrow ex_stage.sv's redirect\n  assign, the same way it was narrowed for JAL in r2s2, to exclude the\n  tautological-taken case. Detection at EX uses only id_ex fields:\n\n    is_taut_taken_ex = in.ctrl.is_branch\n                    && (in.rs1_addr == in.rs2_addr)\n                    && (in.ctrl.branch_op == BR_BEQ\n                        || in.ctrl.branch_op == BR_BGE\n                        || in.ctrl.branch_op == BR_BGEU);\n    assign redirect = ((branch_taken && !is_taut_taken_ex) || in.ctrl.is_jalr)\n                      && !misalign_fault;\n\n  reg_q.pc_next remains the resolved branch_target (unchanged) so the\n  RVFI pc_wdata tap stays byte-identical to the baseline (per r2s1\n  lesson: never gate pc_wdata on the redirect path).\n\n  Safety / formal argument mirrors JAL:\n    - Prediction direction (\"taken\") is tautologically true by the\n      instruction bits alone (rs1_addr == rs2_addr in the encoded\n      instr); no coupling to symbolic register values.\n    - Prediction target pc+B-imm == EX's branch_target (same pc, same\n      imm) by construction.\n    - No new pipeline-payload bits (no `predicted`, no `pred_target`\n      threaded through if_id_t / id_ex_t — honoring the r1s2 lesson).\n    - Misalign guard preserves trap discipline identically to JAL.\n    - BNE/BLT/BLTU with rs1_addr == rs2_addr are always-NOT-taken,\n      which is already the implicit not-taken default — no code needed.\n\n  Expected fitness win is modest (CoreMark's hot loops lean on\n  compiler-emitted conditional branches whose directions are data-\n  dependent, not tautological), but this is the one predictor class\n  that is both (a) strictly additive to the r2s2 JAL gain and (b)\n  aligned with the r3s1/r3s2 lessons about what does not break formal.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add tautological-always-taken branch recognition alongside the existing static JAL predictor: decode BRANCH opcode with rs1_addr == rs2_addr and funct3 in {000 BEQ, 101 BGE, 111 BGEU}, compute pc + B-immediate, guard on target[1:0]==0 for misalign, and fold into next_pc priority mux (redirect > is_jal_fetch > is_taut_taken_fetch > pc+4). No new ports, no pipeline-payload changes.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Narrow the redirect assign to exclude tautological-taken branches, analogous to how r2s2 narrowed it to exclude JAL. Compute is_taut_taken_ex from id_ex fields only (is_branch && rs1_addr == rs2_addr && branch_op in {BEQ, BGE, BGEU}); redirect = ((branch_taken && !is_taut_taken_ex) || is_jalr) && !misalign_fault. Leave reg_q.pc_next assignment unchanged so RVFI pc_wdata continues to be driven to branch_target for the retiring tautological-taken branch (r2s1 lesson).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb sub-test that executes a short program containing beq x0,x0,+8 / bge x0,x0,+8 / bgeu x5,x5,+8 and verifies (a) the fetched wrong-path slot is NOT observed on RVFI, (b) rvfi_pc_wdata_0 equals the branch target, (c) rvfi_order is strictly monotonic, and (d) a non-tautological BEQ in the same program (e.g. beq x1,x2,+8 with x1!=x2) still incurs the baseline EX-redirect bubble. Also add a negative test ensuring BNE x0,x0 and BLT x0,x0 remain not-taken.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r4s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r4s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777769836259,"end":1777769836264}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm focusing on the tautological lessons specifically—this is a fresh angle. Now I need to formulate a hypothesis that's concise and practical. My approach is to extend the IF-stage static predictor to detect branch instructions where both operands are identical, like BEQ and BGE with the same register, which would always resolve predictably.\n\nThe key insight is that these cases are provably always-taken because the instruction encoding itself forces the comparison—when rs1_addr equals rs2_addr, the EX-stage comparator reads the same value on both sides. The safety argument mirrors JAL: the prediction is tautological from the instruction bits alone, and since the EX redirect already handles taken branches, an early IF redirect won't diverge from what EX resolves. I need to verify that EX doesn't re-redirect after IF has already redirected, and ensure the misalignment guard works the same way as it does for JAL.\n\nThe real problem is that if IF early-redirects for these tautological branches but EX still fires its redirect condition (branch_taken || is_jalr), we'd get a redundant redirect to the same target—wasting a cycle with no benefit. The solution is to narrow the EX redirect to exclude tautological branches, similar to how JAL is already excluded. I can detect these at the EX stage by threading a flag through the pipeline, or by extending the IF predictor to recognize them and then excluding them from EX redirect the same way JAL is excluded.\n\nActually, I can compute `is_tautological_taken` combinationally at EX from just the decoded instruction bits (rs1_addr == rs2_addr and branch_op in {BEQ, BGE, BGEU}), so no pipeline state is needed. The narrowed EX redirect becomes `(branch_taken || is_jalr) && !is_tautological_taken && !misalign_fault`. Since the branch target depends only on PC and immediate (both visible at IF), the IF predictor can compute the same target combinationally, guaranteeing they match when IF redirects early. For RVFI correctness, pc_next is still set to the branch target even when EX redirect is suppressed.\n\nThe tautological detection applies to any same-register comparison (BEQ rs, rs for any rs), not just x0, so it catches compiler-generated beqz idioms too. I should guard against misaligned targets the same way as JAL, and while the fitness gain is probably modest (1-3% if these idioms appear in CoreMark's hot loops, possibly 0% if they don't), this feels like the safest predictor experiment to try.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb5689c0001A1PxmQnHzEyLr5","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","messageID":"msg_deb5619cb002DIU8cywgfexleX"}}
