{"type":"text","timestamp":1777769842377,"sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","part":{"id":"prt_deb56f88c001B8OhQucDfLvtHP","messageID":"msg_deb56ef1a001h7JRFAT7YHaosJ","sessionID":"ses_214ac9df6ffePsfeNbvRoEAiLi","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r4s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary:** Extend the stateless IF-stage predictor (which already handles JAL with +5.87% gain) to a second tautologically-correct class: conditional branches where the encoded `rs1_addr == rs2_addr` and the opcode is BEQ/BGE/BGEU — all three are always-taken for any register value because `a == a`, `a ≥ a`, `a ≥ᵤ a` are trivially true. This is the only conditional-branch angle that doesn't fall into the r3s1/r3s2 trap: direction is forced by instruction bits alone, not by a symbolic register value, so SBY induction has no new free-variable coupling to close. Scaffolding reuses the JAL pattern exactly (same misalign guard, same narrowed EX redirect, no pipeline-payload state). Low-confidence / +2% expected because the idiom is rare in CoreMark's hot path but strictly additive to the existing JAL gain and formally safe.","time":{"start":1777769838732,"end":1777769842376}}}
