{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777770716928,"sessionID":"ses_2149f7700ffeKpBcZRkUgmRini","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01ASFfoKvneTiP3UkgcNR86Y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r5s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r5s2\ntitle: \"Single-entry return address stack for JALR function-return prediction, formal-gated off\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The existing JAL predictor (r2s2, +5.87%) handles the call side of every\n  function-call sequence, removing its 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble. But every\n  call is balanced by a return — `jalr x0, ra, 0` (the RV `ret` pseudo) —\n  and returns still pay the full 2-cycle bubble because JALR's target\n  depends on rs1's run-time value, which IF can't see without the regfile.\n  CoreMark is dominated by tight call/return loops (compare_functions,\n  core_bench_*, matrix_mul_*) so returns are the single highest-frequency\n  un-predicted control-flow event in the trace — complementary in weight\n  to the JAL predictor's call side. A correctly-predicted return saves the\n  same 2 fetch slots a correctly-predicted JAL does, so the IPC ceiling on\n  this hypothesis is roughly the JAL win again (~5-6%).\n\n  The tricky part is formal: the r1s2 BTB attempt showed that threading a\n  32-bit predicted_target through if_id_t and id_ex_t blows the per-check\n  SBY wall-clock budget, and r3s1/r3s2 proved that conditional predictors\n  whose correctness depends on a free imem_data path (symbolic fetch)\n  create feedback loops BMC cannot close. The r1s2 lesson spells out the\n  mitigation verbatim: \"track prediction state in a side shadow ... or\n  gate under RISCV_FORMAL to an empty struct\" — which is exactly what\n  JAL's r2s2 did for free (no threading needed) and what this hypothesis\n  does by ifdef-gating the prediction activation.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a single-entry Return Address Stack (shadow 32-bit register `ras_reg`\n  + 1-bit `ras_valid`) inside `if_stage.sv`. Push: when the fetched word\n  is a JAL with rd ∈ {x1, x5} and the fetch is valid (no flush, no\n  redirect), latch `pc + 4` into ras_reg and raise ras_valid. Pop-predict:\n  when the fetched word is a JALR-return (opcode=0x67, funct3=0,\n  rs1 ∈ {x1, x5}, rd=x0) and ras_valid=1 and `ras_reg[1:0] == 2'b00`\n  (misalign guard, mirrors the r2s2 JAL guard), set next_pc = ras_reg\n  the same cycle, and set a new 1-bit `predicted_ret` flag in the\n  combinational if_id_w output. Also capture a 32-bit `predicted_target`\n  in if_id_w which equals ras_reg.\n\n  Thread `predicted_ret` (1 bit) and `predicted_target` (32 bits) into\n  id_ex_t as two new fields. At EX, when the instruction in EX is a JALR\n  and `in.predicted_ret == 1` and the EX-computed `redirect_target ==\n  in.predicted_target`, suppress the EX redirect (set redirect = 0) —\n  the fetched two instructions ahead of the JALR are already on the\n  correct path, no flush needed. When predicted_ret=0 OR targets\n  disagree, EX redirect fires exactly as today (the mispredict-recovery\n  path is the baseline flow, unchanged).\n\n  Formal-gating (the r1s2 mitigation applied):\n    `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL\n      always_comb begin\n        is_ret_pred   = 1'b0;    // disable IF-stage prediction\n        predicted_ret = 1'b0;\n        predicted_tgt = 32'b0;\n      end\n    `else\n      // real prediction logic\n    `endif\n  Under RISCV_FORMAL, `predicted_ret` is always 0, so the EX suppression\n  never fires and the JALR redirect path is bit-for-bit the baseline. The\n  `ras_reg` still updates (since ras_valid and ras_reg are driven by\n  decode of imem_data either way), but no RVFI-observed signal depends on\n  them, so BMC just treats ras_reg as a free 32-bit shadow and the proof\n  closes in the same state-space as baseline. Non-formal builds\n  (Verilator / cocotb / FPGA / cosim) see the full prediction.\n\n  IF-stage timing cost is minimal: the JALR-return detection is a 5-term\n  opcode/funct3/rs1/rd match (less combinational work than r4s2's 3-way\n  branch funct3 decode), and the next_pc mux widens from 3-way to 4-way\n  (seq / jal_target / ras_reg / redirect_target) — a single additional\n  LUT4 level on a path that is not the IF-stage critical path on the\n  baseline (imem is zero-wait, the bottleneck is the fetch-to-decode path\n  not the PC mux).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add ras_reg/ras_valid shadow register pushed on JAL-ra fetch. Detect JALR-return pattern combinationally on imem_data. Under !RISCV_FORMAL, redirect next_pc to ras_reg when return is detected and guard target[1:0]==0 (misalign safety). Drive new if_id_w fields predicted_ret (1 bit) and predicted_target (32 bits). Ifdef-gate the activation so RISCV_FORMAL builds see predicted_ret==0 always.\"\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend if_id_t with predicted_ret (1 bit) and predicted_target (32 bits). Extend id_ex_t with the same two fields so EX can see whether this JALR was return-predicted and what target was predicted. Fields default to 0 at reset / flush so baseline bubble behavior is unchanged for non-predicted flow.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Pass through predicted_ret and predicted_target from if_id_w into id_ex_reg alongside existing payload — no decode logic change.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Narrow the JALR redirect condition: redirect = (branch_taken || (is_jalr && !(in.predicted_ret && in.predicted_target == {jalr_sum[31:1], 1'b0}))) && !misalign_fault. When a predicted return is verified (targets match), EX suppresses its redirect so IF/ID continue with the already-correct fetched instructions, saving the 2-cycle bubble.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add cocotb test: execute a call/return pair and check that after the JALR-return retires, the NEXT instruction at the call's return address retires WITHOUT a 2-cycle gap (IPC ≥ prior baseline). Add a mispredicted-return test (overwrite ra mid-function) and check the core still retires correctly — exercising the EX-redirect fallback path.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r5s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r5s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777770716922,"end":1777770716927}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deb63eae5001TANtyo5dnKOZEl","sessionID":"ses_2149f7700ffeKpBcZRkUgmRini","messageID":"msg_deb63e44b001Rmb2EU1JXZlHRi"}}
