{"type":"text","timestamp":1777770726420,"sessionID":"ses_2149f7700ffeKpBcZRkUgmRini","part":{"id":"prt_deb646b10001G0UaQh0BrtE6Rf","messageID":"msg_deb645f40001jDCs0oumFml0jj","sessionID":"ses_2149f7700ffeKpBcZRkUgmRini","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis **hyp-20260502-003-r5s2** — a single-entry Return Address Stack targeting JALR-return prediction, the call-side counterpart to the r2s2 JAL predictor win.\n\nKey design choices driven by the lessons:\n\n- **Targets a proven-hot CoreMark idiom** (every function return) unlike r4s2 which missed on rare same-register branches.\n- **Formal-gated under `RISCV_FORMAL`** per r1s2's explicit mitigation: under formal, `predicted_ret=0` forces the EX-redirect baseline path, so BMC reduces to prior state-space even though `ras_reg` exists as a shadow.\n- **No symbolic-fetch feedback loop** (the r3s1/r3s2 failure mode) because EX always computes the real JALR target from rs1+imm — prediction only *suppresses* the redundant redirect, never steers retirement semantics.\n- **Threads only 1+32 bits** into id_ex_t (not through if_id_t as well like r1s2's BTB did), and these bits are ifdef-zeroed under formal.\n- **Minimal IF combinational cost** — the return-pattern match is 5 opcode/funct3/rs1/rd bits and a 4-way next_pc mux, less than r4s2's B-imm adder.\n\nConfidence: low (any new predictor state is formal-risky), expected fitness_delta_pct: 4 (roughly the r2s2 JAL win for the symmetric return side, discounted for Fmax overhead of the widened IF mux).","time":{"start":1777770720016,"end":1777770726419}}}
