{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777771656346,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","part":{"id":"prt_deb72b495001w9Logvq2ziZKC0","messageID":"msg_deb729fc8001Lf9goNwRwOE7ua","sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","snapshot":"127c54179551782ef9984e30ee038035adb2e21a","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777771824921,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","part":{"id":"prt_deb7535d00016ofCQVNEzmPY3L","messageID":"msg_deb729fc8001Lf9goNwRwOE7ua","sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons, predictor category has been a minefield:\n- JAL static predictor (r2s2) worked (+5.87%) — tautological, stateless\n- BTB/BTFN conditional attempts (r1s2, r3s1, r3s2) broke formal via symbolic fetch coupling\n- Tautological rs1==rs2 branches (r4s2) passed formal but regressed -7.92% (rare idiom)\n- RAS (r5s2) regressed -60% on synthesis cost even with ifdef-gating\n\nThe explicit guidance from r3s2: *\"future branch-prediction hypotheses should either target the EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear) or accept that a formal wrapper-level assume... is required\"*\n\nThis points directly at **compare-in-ID** — non-speculative, keeps IF linear. Let me verify this hasn't been tried.","time":{"start":1777771820496,"end":1777771824919}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777771824953,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_019Q6qx5GL8miKBtWymPgtNu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"rg -i \"compare.in.id|id.stage.*branch|branch.*id.stage|early.*resolve|compareinid\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check if compare-in-ID was tried"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check if compare-in-ID was tried","truncated":false},"title":"Check if compare-in-ID was tried","time":{"start":1777771824939,"end":1777771824950}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm examining the predictor category and need to form a hypothesis based on the lesson patterns. The JAL predictor succeeded with a simple stateless approach, while BTB and BTFN both failed when they tried threading prediction state through the pipeline or coupling symbolic fetch to conditional branches—suggesting that stateful prediction mechanisms break the formal requirements in this context.\n\nThe tautological BEQ check passed formal verification but regressed significantly due to rarity and timing overhead, while the RAS approach devastated performance by widening pipeline payloads and hurting maximum frequency. The current best result comes from a divider extraction optimization rather than prediction itself.\n\nThe core constraint is clear: any predictor must be stateless, reconstructible from instruction fields alone, and actually present in the CoreMark trace to matter. That leaves JALR and conditional branches as the remaining redirect sources. I'm wondering if an early branch resolution in the EX stage could eliminate bubbles without expanding the pipeline payload or formal state space.\n\nThe challenge with moving branch resolution to ID stage is that it requires forwarding rs1/rs2 data backward, which likely hurts frequency. But what if I could build a stateless JALR predictor that reconstructs the target at IF stage by tracking x1 (the return address register) through a shadow register?\n\nActually, reconsidering the RAS approach: I could keep it entirely within the IF stage as internal state without threading it through the pipeline, which might sidestep the formal verification issues. On JAL instructions that write x1, I'd push PC+4; on JALR with rs1=x1 and imm=0, I'd predict from the RAS top. The formal proof would need to verify the RAS target matches the actual JALR result at EX, but that's the same symbolic coupling problem that killed r5s2 when synthesis hit critical path limits on the Tang Nano 20K.\n\nLooking at what's actually on the critical path—the EX stage already has ALU, branch resolution, and forwarding—I'm wondering if I can avoid adding more logic there. Computing branch targets earlier in IF to precompute them for EX doesn't really help since it just shifts the adder delay rather than removing it. A 1-bit branch history predictor at IF stage would have the same fetch coupling problem. Even extending the static JAL predictor to handle AUIPC+JALR pairs wouldn't move the needle much for CoreMark since those patterns are rare there.\n\nBut rereading the design constraints, the real opportunity is reducing EX-stage redirect bubbles. If I move branch comparison to ID stage instead, I only flush 1 instruction instead of 2—that's a real win for loops and conditional branches which dominate CoreMark. The tradeoff is adding forwarding paths from EX/MEM back to ID and putting a comparator on the ID critical path, which could hurt Fmax. Still, it's worth exploring whether the bubble reduction outweighs the timing cost.\n\nFor the predictor itself, I'm realizing most CoreMark branches fall into predictable patterns: loop-back branches that are almost always taken, comparison branches in conditionals, and JAL calls which are already handled. Rather than trying to build something formally verifiable, I should gate a simple IF-stage BHT predictor behind RISCV_FORMAL so it's disabled during formal verification but available for simulation. The key is reconstructing the prediction at EX from the branch's PC via shadow indexing, keeping the pipeline payload clean.\n\nBut there's a fundamental issue: if the predictor redirects IF on a predicted-taken branch, I need to squash wrong-path instructions when the prediction fails, which adds complexity. Maybe the simpler approach is to move branch resolution earlier—if I can resolve conditionals in the first half of EX instead of the full cycle, I reduce the flush penalty from 2 cycles to 1 cycle.\n\nActually, I can do better by resolving in ID itself. I'd need to forward rs1 and rs2 values from EX and WB stages to the ID comparator, then assert a redirect when a branch resolves taken. This cuts the penalty to just 1 cycle and avoids speculation entirely. The main concern is whether adding a comparator to ID hurts timing, but the critical path is probably in EX with the ALU and forwarding logic, not in ID's decoder and immediate generation.\n\nLooking at the misalignment trap issue though—if the branch target is misaligned, the current design catches it at EX, but with compare-in-ID I'd need to handle that earlier or defer the redirect. That complicates things.\n\nLet me step back and try something simpler: use a stateless IF-stage predictor for the return address stack pattern, specifically the `jalr x0, 0(x1)` idiom. I'd keep a 1-entry RAS purely inside IF without threading it through the pipeline, since the r5s2 experiment showed that threading hurts. On JAL with rd==x1 I push pc+4, and on JALR with rs1==x1 and rd==x0 I pop and predict the target. The EX stage still verifies the prediction, and if it's wrong we flush and use the normal redirect.\n\nThe key is that the RAS state stays local to IF—the pipeline payload doesn't change, and redirect still fires for JALR as before. Under formal verification with symbolic execution, the RAS prediction would rarely match since rs1 is free, so redirect would almost always fire to correct the path, but that's fine because correctness still holds: redirect asserts, wrong-path fetches get flushed, and rvfi_pc_wdata comes from the EX redirect target unchanged. The synthesis cost is just the RAS SRAM and comparator at IF, not widening the whole payload.\n\nCoreMark has enough function calls that return prediction could save roughly 2 cycles per return, which is meaningful. But the real bottleneck is the 4-way next_pc mux at IF—adding JALR-RAS would make it even worse on the critical path, which was already a problem on the Tang Nano 20K. So instead of pursuing that, I'm going to focus on something simpler: extending the stateless IF-stage predictor or taking a completely different angle like resolving branches earlier in the pipeline. Moving the branch comparator logically earlier so redirect fires a cycle sooner would cut the bubble from 2 cycles down to 1, which is the high-impact move worth pursuing.\n\nThe cleaner approach is ID-stage branch resolution for conditional branches—add a comparator to ID that resolves them one cycle earlier than EX, with forwarding from EX/MEM and MEM/WB to feed the branch inputs, plus a new load_use_branch hazard to stall when a branch depends on an in-flight load. JALR still resolves at EX since it needs the computed register value. The tricky part is that id_ex_t doesn't currently have pc_next, so if branch resolves at ID, I'd need to compute and propagate the target through the pipeline earlier than the current design does. EX still computes branch_taken for RVFI correctness, but suppresses its redirect since ID already resolved it—this avoids the symbolic coupling issue because ID uses real forwarded register values rather than speculation. The simpler path is adding a BTB at IF gated under ifdef for formal verification, keeping it empty in formal mode while allowing synthesis to use it for prediction recovery, with no pipeline payload changes needed since prediction info can be reconstructed at EX like before.\n\nBut this was already tried in r3s2 and failed—the real problem is that narrowing EX redirect to only fire on mispredicts creates a correlation between redirect and branch_taken under symbolic fetch, letting the IF predictor \"redirect\" to addresses whose instruction memory is also free. If redirect always fires instead, every branch gets flushed and the prediction provides no benefit, so narrowing is essential for performance. What if I separate the signals—add a distinct mispredict signal to EX that kills wrong-path fetches while redirect always fires for RVFI, decoupling the formal hazard from the performance optimization?\n\nActually, that's exactly what r3s2 attempted and it still failed. So conditional branch prediction is fundamentally risky; the only viable options are unconditional branches (JAL, already working), tautological predictors (BEQ with rs1==rs2, passes formal but poor performance), non-speculative compare-in-ID, or JALR-RAS entirely in the IF stage without payload threading. I'll try the JALR-RAS approach with a 4-entry internal stack—state inside IF is fine as long as it doesn't thread through the payload. But r5s2 showed that even without threading, the mux and EX comparator hit the critical path, so I need to avoid adding an EX comparator. If IF predicts correctly, the target flows naturally through the fetched path; if wrong, EX redirect corrects it. The real question is whether I can avoid the hit detection logic entirely or if I'm forced back into the same trap.\n\nActually, I think the cleaner path is compare-in-ID—moving the branch comparator from EX to ID stage to resolve conditional branches one cycle earlier, reducing taken-branch bubbles from 2 to 1. This keeps IF linear and non-speculative, which aligns with what the lessons suggest. I'll implement branch comparators for all the conditional types (BEQ, BNE, BLT, BGE, BLTU, BGEU) in the ID stage with proper forwarding logic.\n\nThe tricky part is handling pc_next for RVFI reporting—if ID resolves the branch, I need to either compute pc_next at ID and thread it through the pipeline, or just store a 1-bit branch_taken signal in the control word and let EX compute pc_next from that. The latter is cleaner since it's minimal payload growth.\n\nI'm concerned about adding forwarding logic to the ID stage, which could impact Fmax, but the fitness gain from eliminating 1 cycle per taken branch (roughly 10-15% of instructions in CoreMark) should outweigh a small clock penalty. The implementation requires adding a branch comparator and forwarding mux to ID, updating the control packet to carry branch_taken, and modifying the redirect logic to feed back to IF.\n\nUpdating the module interfaces... Maybe add branch_taken field to id_ex_t (1 bit), wire ID-stage redirect to IF, and extend forwarding sources to include EX/MEM and WB results. This is a large restructuring with moderate risk of subtle interactions. Alternatively, I could pre-compute branch targets at IF to reduce EX delay, but the adder there is already simple. Let me commit to compare-in-ID and estimate the fitness gain.\n\nGiven the current best is 376.19 with branch density around 15% and 50% taken rate, I'm looking at roughly 7.5% of cycles potentially saved. Fmax impact is uncertain and aggressive predictor moves historically have low success rates, so I'll target +4% with medium confidence.\n\nI'm concerned that widening id_ex_t could break test_pipeline.py like the stage renaming did before, but adding a field shouldn't affect stage names themselves. The real question is whether ID and EX could disagree on branch resolution if forwarding sources differ—but if a LOAD-use hazard stalls the BRANCH at ID, by the time it reaches ID the LOAD has already progressed through the pipeline, so both stages should see the same forwarded value.\n\nI'll go with a parallel compare-in-ID approach: add a branch comparator and forwarding logic to ID, fire id_redirect when the branch resolves taken, and keep EX's resolve unchanged for RVFI. This avoids payload widening and lets ID redirect IF one cycle earlier, reducing the bubble from two cycles to one. EX's redirect becomes redundant but harmless since IF and ID are already on the correct path.\n\nBut there's a catch—if ID redirects correctly and EX fires its redirect to the same target, EX would flush the now-valid instruction in IF/ID, creating an unwanted bubble. To avoid this, I need to suppress EX's redirect when ID already handled it, which requires tracking whether ID redirected for this branch. The cleanest way is to add a 1-bit `id_redirected` flag to the id_ex pipeline register so EX can gate its redirect signal accordingly. The pc_next computation stays the same at EX, but now I need to ensure ID and EX agree on branch_taken—they forward from slightly different pipeline stages, so there's a risk of disagreement that could cause pc_wdata mismatches.\n\nLooking at the forwarding sources more carefully: when the branch is in ID, it forwards from EX/MEM and WB; when that same branch reaches EX the next cycle, those registers hold different instructions. However, in an in-order pipeline the forwarded values should still match because they reflect the same regfile update history. The tricky case is a load-use hazard on the branch—if a load is in EX and the branch in ID needs that value, ID stalls, and by the time the branch reaches EX, the load data is being computed combinationally in the MEM stage.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to keep the branch's ID-stage comparison using only the standard forwarding sources (EX/MEM.alu_result and WB data). The existing load-use stall already handles the load-to-branch dependency: after one stall cycle, the load moves to MEM and the branch can forward from there, or we add another stall to let the load reach WB. I'm realizing the forwarding and stall logic for branch-on-load is getting too tangled. Let me step back and focus on a simpler, more practical predictor improvement: adding a tiny return address stack in the IF stage to predict JALR returns, keeping it isolated with an ifdef so it doesn't complicate the formal verification. The catch is that EX will still redirect unconditionally, so the prediction doesn't actually save a cycle unless I can narrow EX's redirect for JALR by checking if the prediction was correct—but that loops back to needing an EX comparator, which is the original problem.\n\nLooking at what the core currently doesn't predict: conditional branches have failed multiple times, JALR returns hit synthesis issues with the RAS approach, and tautological branch comparisons didn't work either. The compare-in-ID approach is different because it's not speculative—it just resolves branches early when both operands are available from the regfile without forwarding. I'll propose a minimal version: add BEQ/BNE resolution at ID stage only when both rs1 and rs2 are ready, falling back to EX-stage resolution when forwarding is needed.\n\nThe trade-off is that many loop-back branches like `BNE x_cnt, x_loopend` have rs1 produced recently, so forwarding would be needed and the benefit would be missed. I should go with full compare-in-ID including forwarding support, though I'm now wondering if the r3s1 symbolic coupling issue could still apply even to non-speculative resolution—I need to think through whether ID reading from IF/ID and computing the branch condition creates the same kind of problematic coupling.\n\nActually, on closer inspection, the key difference is that compare-in-ID uses real register values (forwarded concretely), not speculation. The instruction encoding and branch target come from the symbolic imem_data, but that's just normal execution under BMC—there's no prediction happening, so formal verification should pass. I'm going to commit to this approach: BEQ/BNE only initially, with forwarding from EX/MEM and WB, load-use stalls for branch-on-load cases, ID-stage redirect, and a flag in the pipeline to suppress EX's redirect once ID has already fired. Let me write this up in YAML with a modest +3% expected impact. So the key insight is that EX's `pc_next` computation stays the same regardless of whether ID already resolved the branch—it just needs to compute the correct target. I'll gate EX's redirect signal with the new `branch_id_resolved` flag so it doesn't fire redundantly, and add that 1-bit field to the pipeline register. Now I'm laying out the full implementation across the affected modules.\n\nThe fitness gain comes from eliminating roughly one cycle per taken branch in tight loops, though there's a tradeoff with Fmax from the added ID-stage logic and some formal verification complexity. Adding the new field to `id_ex_t` shouldn't break the test harness since it accesses named fields rather than checking exact struct widths. Writing up the YAML spec now.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb7542f9001K4lisBvtYlebx0","sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","messageID":"msg_deb729fc8001Lf9goNwRwOE7ua"}}
