{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777771881420,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Et3ujGKnf9pJPkoPbSSduE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r6s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r6s2\ntitle: \"Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution (halve taken-branch bubble to 1 cycle)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  After r2s2's JAL predictor (+5.87%), the dominant remaining control-flow\n  penalty is the 2-cycle redirect bubble on every taken conditional branch\n  (opcode 0x63). Five prior IF-stage *speculative* attempts to attack this\n  bubble all failed:\n    - r1s2 (BTB) blew the formal budget by threading predicted/pred_target\n      through if_id_t/id_ex_t.\n    - r3s1 (BTFNT) / r3s2 (BTFN) triggered the symbolic-fetch coupling\n      trap: narrowing EX `redirect` to `mispredict` correlates the gate\n      with `branch_taken`, and SBY's induction for the `reg` property\n      cannot close the loop where IF redirects onto an address whose\n      `imem_data` is itself a free symbolic variable AND the branch's\n      resolved direction is also free.\n    - r4s2 (tautological rs1==rs2) passed formal but the idiom is ~zero\n      in compiler-emitted code, and the extra B-imm adder / 3-way mux\n      cost Fmax. Net -7.92%.\n    - r5s2 (RAS for JALR returns, formal-gated) passed formal but the\n      4-way next_pc mux and EX ret_pred_hit comparator blew Fmax on the\n      Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths. Net -60.03%.\n\n  The r3s2 lesson distills the explicit mitigation direction:\n    \"future branch-prediction hypotheses should either target the\n     EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear)\n     or accept that a formal wrapper-level assume ... is required\"\n\n  This hypothesis takes the non-speculative path. It has NOT been tried.\n  All five prior predictor attempts were IF-stage speculation — none\n  moved the resolution itself earlier in the pipeline.\n\n  CoreMark's dynamic trace is dominated by tight loops (crcu8 inner,\n  core_list_find reverse walk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k,\n  core_state_transition dispatch). Assuming ~12% of dynamic instructions\n  are conditional branches with ~55% taken rate, cutting the taken-branch\n  penalty from 2 cycles to 1 cycle is ~6.6% of total cycles reclaimed\n  before any Fmax adjustment. JALR stays at EX (needs register-computed\n  target — unchanged, as r5s2 proved the IF-side JALR predictor is\n  synthesis-toxic on this FPGA).\nhypothesis: |\n  Move conditional-branch resolution from EX to ID (non-speculative).\n  ID reads rs1_data/rs2_data combinationally from the regfile and can\n  evaluate BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU one cycle earlier than EX. On a\n  resolved taken branch, ID asserts `id_redirect` with target =\n  id.pc + id.imm, redirecting IF the same cycle the BRANCH is in ID.\n\n  Bubble accounting:\n    baseline: BRANCH in EX fires redirect → IF and ID squashed → 2 bubbles\n    new:      BRANCH in ID fires redirect → IF squashed, BRANCH moves to\n              EX → 1 bubble (the squashed IF)\n\n  To keep RVFI pc_wdata and the `reg` / `pc_fwd` formal properties intact,\n  EX still computes branch_taken / branch_target / pc_next as before, and\n  stores them in ex_mem_t. The only change at EX is that its `redirect`\n  output is gated off for conditional BRANCH when ID already redirected.\n  This is tracked via a single new 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` in\n  id_ex_t (so ex_stage knows which instruction ID already took care of).\n\n  Formal tractability — why this is safe:\n    - No speculation. ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2 values.\n      When ID says \"taken\", it's the SAME answer EX would compute next\n      cycle (subject to forwarding equality, which is a pipeline\n      invariant), not a guess.\n    - No symbolic-fetch coupling. The r3s1/r3s2 failure mode was a\n      feedback loop between free imem_data at the redirect target and a\n      free branch direction. Here ID's redirect target and direction are\n      both determined by already-fetched concrete values (instr bits +\n      forwarded register values), exactly like the JAL predictor's\n      `pc+imm` — provably-correct-by-construction.\n    - pc_wdata tap unchanged: RVFI still reads mem_wb.pc_next, which still\n      comes from ex_mem.pc_next, which EX still computes from its own\n      (redundant) branch_taken path. The r2s1 \"gate silences the\n      pc_wdata tap\" trap is avoided because pc_next computation is\n      decoupled from the redirect-assertion gate.\n    - riscv-formal's `causal` / `pc_fwd` checks see the same retirement\n      sequence as baseline — only the IF PC trajectory shifts earlier\n      on taken branches.\n\n  ID-stage forwarding (new, scoped to branch comparator only):\n    Two 3:1 muxes select rs1_cmp / rs2_cmp from:\n      - in.rs1_data / rs2_data (regfile, default)\n      - ex_mem_w.alu_result (when ex_mem_w.rd matches and ex_mem_w is a\n        register-write, non-LOAD)\n      - wb w_data (when mem_wb_w.rd matches)\n    LOAD-in-EX cannot forward to ID (its rdata doesn't exist yet), so\n    hazard_unit grows one case: if BRANCH in IF/ID has rs1/rs2 matching\n    a LOAD's rd in ID/EX, stall ID one extra cycle (in addition to the\n    existing load-use stall). The BRANCH falls back to the standard\n    EX-stage resolution in that case — no speculation, just no IPC win\n    for LOAD→BRANCH adjacency (rare; compilers schedule around it).\n\n  Load-use handling:\n    The existing load-use hazard (LOAD in EX with dep in IF/ID) already\n    stalls 1 cycle. With compare-in-ID active, a BRANCH immediately\n    after a LOAD still gets the 1-cycle stall; after the stall, LOAD is\n    in MEM/WB, BRANCH is in ID, and the WB-result forward path lets ID\n    resolve normally. No new hazard interactions; just an additional\n    forward source at ID.\n\n  Fmax risk mitigation:\n    ID stage currently only drives decoder + imm_gen + regfile read —\n    significant slack vs. the EX critical path (ALU + divider + fwd mux).\n    Adding a 6-way funct3-driven comparator and two 3:1 forwarding muxes\n    at ID should land well under the EX path's delay. If Fmax regresses\n    materially, the comparator scope can be narrowed to BEQ/BNE only\n    (the two fastest / most common) via a subsequent micro-opt iteration.\n\n  Scope exclusions (keep the change bounded):\n    - JALR resolution stays at EX (needs rs1+imm; r5s2 showed IF-side\n      JALR prediction is synthesis-toxic).\n    - JAL handling unchanged (r2s2's static IF predictor).\n    - Misalign-branch trap stays at EX (it must be a synchronous\n      rvfi_trap with the exact retiring insn; ID lacks the retirement\n      context and the 2-cycle EX path already catches it).\n    - test/test_pipeline.py probes access named struct fields\n      (dut.u_id.reg_q.ctrl.*, etc.); adding id_ex_t.id_branch_resolved\n      is an append-only field change, not a stage rename, so the r4s1\n      test_pipeline.py trap does not apply.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add a single 1-bit field `id_branch_resolved` to id_ex_t, indicating the ID stage already asserted redirect for this instruction's conditional branch. No other payload changes; zero new RVFI-visible bits.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add a conditional-branch comparator at ID: funct3-driven BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU on rs1_cmp/rs2_cmp (post ID-stage forwarding). Drive id_redirect and id_redirect_target outputs. Set id_branch_resolved=1 in the ID/EX register when a conditional BRANCH is resolved at ID with no forwarding hazard. When ID cannot resolve (LOAD producer in ID/EX), fall back to baseline (EX-stage resolves as before, id_branch_resolved=0).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new ID-stage forwarding sources (ex_mem_w.alu_result + ex_mem_w.ctrl.reg_write + ex_mem_w.ctrl.mem_read to skip LOAD; wb w_data + wb w_en). Wire id_redirect/id_redirect_target into if_stage. Add load-use-at-ID detection to hazard_unit inputs (LOAD in ID/EX with BRANCH in IF/ID whose rs1/rs2 matches).\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Extend PC update priority: redirect_ex > id_redirect > jal_pred > pc+4. Both redirects flush IF; id_redirect does not flush ID because the BRANCH itself is what's moving from ID to EX (not being squashed). Keep the existing misalign guard on jal_pred; ID-side conditional branches cannot produce misaligned targets under RV32I (B-imm bit0 is implicit 0).\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Gate the BRANCH portion of the `redirect` output on `!in.id_branch_resolved`. JALR and misalign-trap redirect paths are unchanged. pc_next computation in the EX/MEM register is unchanged (still branch_taken ? target : pc+4) so RVFI pc_wdata is byte-for-byte identical to baseline on all retirements.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add `id_branch_needs_load` input from top-level (BRANCH in IF/ID with rs matching a LOAD's rd in ID/EX). When asserted, force stall_id / stall_if for one extra cycle so the LOAD advances to MEM/WB and its result becomes forwardable to ID; otherwise ID's forward muxes would select stale data for the BRANCH compare.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a directed test for the compare-in-ID path: program a sequence `ADDI x5,x0,3 ; ADDI x5,x5,-1 ; BNE x5,x0,-4 ; ADDI x6,x0,42` and verify (a) rvfi_order increments by exactly the expected number of retirements, (b) only 1 bubble per taken BNE (vs. 2 in baseline) by counting cycles between PC=BNE and PC=BNE-target across the loop, and (c) the load-use-BRANCH fallback path still resolves correctly with an extra stall. Also add a regression probe that id_ex.id_branch_resolved is 0 whenever the instr is not a conditional BRANCH.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r6s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r6s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777771881404,"end":1777771881418}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" So none of the previous predictor attempts actually tried compare-in-ID—they were all speculative approaches at the IF stage. The key insight from r3s2 is pointing toward an EX-stage bubble reduction strategy that doesn't rely on speculation and keeps the IF pipeline linear. That's exactly what compare-in-ID would do. Let me formalize this as a hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb7566ab001grAMCAQUHdHtQL","sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","messageID":"msg_deb755810001FEsV1jvrIRjlwA"}}
