{"type":"text","timestamp":1777771888553,"sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","part":{"id":"prt_deb762912001N16eOtYG8KyaU9","messageID":"msg_deb76240f001TEF9H8tDzpxHVt","sessionID":"ses_2148d6070ffeg5NzhrML3lJp2A","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r6s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution. Move conditional-branch resolve from EX to ID to cut taken-branch bubble from 2 cycles → 1 cycle.\n\n**Why this angle is novel**: All 5 prior predictor attempts (r1s2 BTB, r3s1 BTFNT, r3s2 BTFN, r4s2 tautological, r5s2 RAS) were IF-stage *speculative*. The r3s2 lesson explicitly called out the \"EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear)\" as the remaining safe direction — compare-in-ID is exactly that, and it's unexplored.\n\n**Why formal should pass**: No speculation means no symbolic-fetch coupling (the r3s1/r3s2 trap). ID resolves from concrete forwarded register values using the same instruction bits JAL's r2s2 predictor uses — provably-correct-by-construction. EX still computes pc_next/branch_taken for RVFI, so the `pc_fwd` / `reg` / `causal` properties see identical retirement traces; only IF's PC trajectory shifts earlier. A single 1-bit `id_branch_resolved` payload addition gates EX's redundant redirect (avoiding the double-flush bug). +4% / medium confidence.","time":{"start":1777771882770,"end":1777771888550}}}
