{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777772579504,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","part":{"id":"prt_deb80caaa001ONZ1f3o6idl4Ip","messageID":"msg_deb80b7f40011ILwl9yIfT4mkb","sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","snapshot":"69b88b11c12e6cae66e34131946901e1979f6cce","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777772660826,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","part":{"id":"prt_deb81fc210012HS5qO4mNtqyLN","messageID":"msg_deb80b7f40011ILwl9yIfT4mkb","sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, the predictor category is heavily explored. Key takeaways:\n\n- **r2s2** (+5.87%): stateless JAL predictor — already shipped\n- **r3s1/r3s2** (broken): BTFN breaks formal via symbolic-fetch coupling\n- **r4s2** (-7.92%): tautological rs1==rs2 branches — idiom absent in CoreMark\n- **r5s2** (-60%): RAS threading 33 bits through pipeline payload destroyed Fmax\n- **r6s2** (0%): non-speculative ID-early resolution with all 6 funct3 variants — timing wash\n\nThe r6s2 lesson explicitly recommends: *\"narrow the ID comparator to BEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping the signed/unsigned compare tree)\"*. CoreMark's hot loops are BNE-to-counter, so BEQ/BNE-only captures most of the dynamic branch mix.","time":{"start":1777772657697,"end":1777772660825}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772660863,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_0152FbJFRCZ1MsTRhgyTfoih","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5","description":"Check hypotheses directory"},"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses directory","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses directory","time":{"start":1777772660858,"end":1777772660861}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at what worked and what failed in previous predictor attempts—the JAL predictor succeeded by staying stateless, while the BTFN approach broke formal verification and the tautological branch check ran into issues—I need to find a similar lightweight approach for the cores/bench/ predictor that avoids those pitfalls.\n\nThe RAS attempt taught me that threading predicted targets through the pipeline is too costly; the real bottleneck is the fetch bubble after JALR, which happens at IF before we even have the return address from the regfile. An IF-stage JALR predictor using the ra register heuristic won't work since we can't read the regfile that early, but a stateless predictor for JALR with rs1==x0 (where the target is just the immediate, computable from the instruction alone) might be viable—though it's admittedly a narrow case.\n\nA better angle: use a tiny shadow-state RAS in IF only, without threading any bits through the pipeline payload. IF redirects speculatively to the RAS prediction, and EX independently resolves the JALR and redirects if needed; if they match, those 2 cycles of speculative fetch were productive, and if they don't, EX corrects it. The win is those 2 cycles of useful work on correct predictions, with the cost being just the IF PC mux and the RAS lookup logic.\n\nThe tricky part is avoiding a spurious flush when EX redirects to the same target that IF already predicted correctly—we need EX to know whether the prediction was right. The cleanest solution is to push just a 1-bit \"predicted JALR\" flag into the pipeline, much cheaper than threading the full predicted target through like r5s2 did.\n\nAt EX, I can compare the resolved target against the PC of the instruction that followed the JALR in the pipeline—if they match, the prediction was correct and we suppress the redirect. This works because that next instruction's PC is already available in the pipeline stages.\n\nI'm exploring simpler predictor ideas now: a BEQ-zero predictor for backward loops, a branch history table with direct-mapped indexing, or zero-latency BEQ resolution in ID for register-zero comparisons, but each runs into the same BTFN trap or regresses performance like r4s2 did. Given r6s2's findings that this pipeline's control-flow tradeoff is already near saturation, I'm hitting diminishing returns on further speculation improvements.\n\nThe cleanest remaining option is a stateless JALR return-address predictor: a single-entry RAS in IF that only stores a 32-bit register, pushed by JAL with rd==x1 and popped by JALR with rs1==x1 and rd==x0. This adds no pipeline payload width. At EX, I just need to check if the resolved target matches the PC of the instruction currently in the IF/ID stage—that comparison tells me whether the prediction succeeded. there was a stall or flush, so we can't rely on if_id_w.pc being the instruction right after the JALR. The core insight is that we must suppress the EX redirect on correct prediction to avoid wasting cycles, which means threading a 1-bit predicted flag through id_ex_t so EX can compare the resolved target against what was predicted in IF—but the challenge is that the predicted value becomes stale by the time it reaches EX, so we need a way to capture and validate it at the right moment.\n\nThe r5s2 approach tried staging a 32-bit predicted target register in IF, but that regressed performance by 60% because the extra mux and comparator landed on the critical path between IF and EX. Given that the design is already saturated, I'm exploring alternatives like a formal-gated BTB that only activates outside of formal verification, or a small direct-mapped 8-entry BTB that stays hidden from the formal model to avoid state explosion.\n\nThe core tension is that any IF-only BTB needs EX-side feedback to suppress incorrect redirects, which either requires threading the prediction through the pipeline (killing Fmax) or reconstructing it statefully at EX (which works for JAL but not for conditional branches or JALR). I'm now considering a minimal JALR-return predictor using the formal gating pattern—a single-entry RAS in the IF stage as shadow state that formal verification can ignore.\n\nThe proposal is to push return addresses when IF fetches JAL with rd=x1/x5, pop when IF fetches JALR with rs1=x1/x5, and add just one bit to the pipeline to mark RAS predictions. At EX, I'd use a pending prediction register that holds the speculated target for up to two cycles (since only one JALR can be in flight due to stalls), then compare the resolved target against it—if they match, suppress the redirect; if they mismatch, redirect normally.\n\nThis avoids threading the full 32-bit target through the pipeline like r5s2 did, keeping it in a shadow register instead. But I'm still facing a 32-bit comparator at EX, which contributed to r5s2's Fmax issues. Let me explore a simpler direction: maybe a non-speculative branch predictor at ID stage using just a cheap equality check for BEQ instructions, leveraging forwarded operand values rather than speculating ahead.\n\nActually, r6s2 already suggested this exact approach—restricting to BEQ/BNE-only at ID with a simple xor-tree comparator instead of a full signed compare tree. If operands are available through forwarding, I can resolve these branches early at ID and redirect before reaching EX, saving a bubble cycle. For branches that can't resolve yet (operands still pending), they just fall through to the existing EX resolution path. Since it's deterministic and non-speculative, the `rvfi_pc_wdata` tap always captures the correct resolved target regardless of where resolution happens, keeping symbolic tractability intact.\n\nThe synthesis is straightforward: add a 32-bit xor-tree equality check at ID plus forwarding muxes for rs1/rs2 from EX/MEM and MEM/WB stages. ID already has timing slack per the lesson, so this narrow comparator and mux logic should fit without hurting Fmax—much cheaper than r6s2's full 6-way funct3 tree. CoreMark's loops are mostly BNE iteration tests, so resolving these early should yield roughly 5-7% IPC gain, assuming load-use stalls don't dominate.\n\nNow I'm sketching the implementation: detect BEQ/BNE in ID, forward operands from downstream stages, check if either operand is blocked by an in-flight load, and if resolvable, compute the branch outcome and redirect the PC immediately while flushing the IF/ID stage. The tricky part is RVFI compliance—the branch instruction still needs to retire with the correct pc_wdata, so I'd need to thread a resolved-flag and target down through the pipeline, but that adds width to id_ex_t which could hurt Fmax per the earlier lesson. I'm wondering if I can reuse existing fields instead of widening.\n\nActually, a single bit flag in id_ex_t to mark \"already resolved\" seems like the right trade-off—it's minimal overhead and lets EX know not to redirect again. Let me go with that approach and write it up in YAML.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb8205a4001pYIZUQ0GUksW93","sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","messageID":"msg_deb80b7f40011ILwl9yIfT4mkb"}}
