{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777772695986,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01VKQmgXJWH2DBKpgbYEN4pb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r7s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r7s2\ntitle: \"ID-stage BEQ/BNE-only early branch resolution (non-speculative, cheap comparator)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\n  stateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\n  branch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\n  idiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\n  killed Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\n  r6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\n  six BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\n  signed/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% — the Fmax hit\n  from the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\n  taken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \"future\n  non-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\n  BEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\n  the signed/unsigned compare tree)\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\n  dominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\n  BEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture ≈70-80% of conditional-branch cycles\n  at a fraction of the comparator cost.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add an ID-stage early-resolution path restricted to BEQ and BNE (funct3\n  ∈ {000, 001}), non-speculative: resolve the branch using forwarded rs1/rs2\n  operands at ID. The comparator is a single 32-bit equality (XOR-tree +\n  reduction-OR), dramatically cheaper than r6s2's 6-way signed/unsigned\n  compare. When both operands are available at ID (not blocked behind an\n  in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM), compute taken = (rs1==rs2)^funct3[0], redirect\n  IF from ID to branch_target/pc+4, and mark the branch as already-resolved\n  in id_ex_t via a single 1-bit flag. At EX, a BEQ/BNE carrying\n  id_branch_resolved=1 bypasses the EX redirect (pc_next already correct,\n  RVFI pc_wdata wired from the pre-resolved target). Fallback: any BEQ/BNE\n  that cannot be resolved at ID (operand behind an in-flight LOAD, or not\n  yet valid) falls through to the existing EX resolution path unchanged.\n  BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU continue to resolve at EX (skipped by ID — their\n  signed/unsigned compare tree is what blew the timing budget in r6s2).\n\n  Formal-tractability argument (addresses the r3s1/r3s2 trap): this change\n  is NON-speculative. ID's compare uses concrete forwarded rs1/rs2 values;\n  there is no symbolic-fetch feedback loop where the predictor's redirect\n  target and the branch's resolved direction are both free variables.\n  rvfi_pc_wdata is always the resolved branch_target (whether resolved at\n  ID or EX); rvfi_order / rvfi_trap are untouched. id_ex_t widens by 1 bit\n  (id_branch_resolved) plus a 32-bit pc_next field carried from ID — BUT\n  pc_next is already a 32-bit payload in ex_mem_t/mem_wb_t, so the extra\n  register state is just 33 bits in id_ex_t, and the ID comparator is a\n  single narrow XOR-tree.\n\n  Why this is different from r6s2: r6s2 widened the ID comparator to cover\n  all 6 branch variants, which put a signed<, unsigned<, and == tree in\n  parallel on the ID combinational path. ID previously had slack vs EX but\n  not enough for three wide comparators. BEQ/BNE alone is just a 32-bit XOR\n  reduction (≈5 LUT4 levels, same depth as a single operand-forward mux),\n  which should fit comfortably inside the existing ID slack. We explicitly\n  skip BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU to preserve ID-path timing.\n\n  Why this is different from r5s2: no 32-bit predicted_target threaded\n  through the pipeline, no new 4-way next_pc mux at IF. The 1-bit\n  id_branch_resolved flag and the 32-bit pc_next (already a downstream\n  payload field) are the only new id_ex_t state; EX muxes pc_next straight\n  through instead of recomputing it on resolved branches.\n\n  Expected IPC win: CoreMark ~12-15% branch density, of which BEQ/BNE are\n  ≈70-80%, taken rate ~60%. Saving 1 bubble cycle per taken BEQ/BNE where\n  operands are ID-available gives approx 0.12 × 0.75 × 0.60 = ~5.4% IPC\n  uplift. Fmax impact: neutral-to-slightly-negative (single narrow XOR tree\n  + two 3:1 forwarding muxes on ID path). Net fitness: targeting +3-5%.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `id_branch_resolved` (1-bit) and `pc_next` (32-bit) fields to id_ex_t so EX can bypass its redirect/target-mux for ID-resolved BEQ/BNE. pc_next defaults to pc+4 at ID for non-branches and non-resolved branches.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add ID-stage early-resolution logic restricted to funct3 ∈ {000 BEQ, 001 BNE}. Wire in rs1_val / rs2_val forwarding from EX/MEM.alu_result and MEM/WB write-mux data (drive via new input ports). Use a single 32-bit equality comparator (rs1_eff == rs2_eff), compute taken = eq ^ funct3[0]. Gate early resolution on: (a) instr is BEQ/BNE, (b) operand not waiting on an in-flight LOAD in EX/MEM, (c) if_id_w.valid. When resolved, set id_branch_resolved=1, set pc_next = taken ? (pc + B-imm) : (pc + 4), and drive an id_redirect pulse + id_redirect_target to if_stage via a new module output. Pass pc_next through id_ex_t.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire new id_stage inputs (fwd_ex_mem, fwd_mem_wb, load_in_flight) from ex_mem_w and wb_stage outputs. Wire id_stage's new outputs (id_redirect, id_redirect_target) into if_stage alongside the existing EX redirect with ID having higher priority (the in-flight EX redirect cannot conflict since only one branch is in the resolution cone at a time). Add id_flush input to flush the branch shadow in IF/ID when ID redirects.\"\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Accept new id_redirect / id_redirect_target inputs. PC reg update priority: reset > ex_redirect > id_redirect > static JAL predictor > pc+4. When id_redirect fires, emit NOP into the IF/ID combinational payload this cycle (same pattern as the existing flush logic) so the mis-speculated next sequential fetch is squashed.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"When id_ex_w.ctrl carries a BEQ/BNE AND id_branch_resolved=1, skip EX redirect (redirect output stays low for this instruction), and use id_ex_w.pc_next directly as the EX/MEM pc_next payload (don't recompute branch_target + branch_taken for RVFI). For non-resolved branches and BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU, existing EX resolution path runs unchanged.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add an id_redirect input mirroring the existing EX redirect's flush semantics: flush_if on id_redirect (so IF/ID next-cycle payload becomes NOP), and ensure the branch itself continues to ID/EX normally (the branch must retire with rvfi_valid=1 at WB — only the wrong-path instruction behind it is squashed).\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test that exercises ID-stage early-resolution: a BEQ with rs1==rs2 and both operands ID-available should produce a taken redirect 1 cycle earlier than the current EX-resolution baseline (observe via fetch-PC sequence). A BEQ with operand blocked behind a LOAD falls through to EX resolution (baseline timing). Validate rvfi_pc_wdata matches the branch target on both paths.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r7s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r7s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777772695970,"end":1777772695984}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deb820df50014OP8eTvwqqNGGq","sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","messageID":"msg_deb8208b1001gAjHi54UoVP5Np"}}
