{"type":"text","timestamp":1777772702806,"sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","part":{"id":"prt_deb8296ff0015fpH65SAkHkVaq","messageID":"msg_deb8291f9001U7coyWxX0r0FAo","sessionID":"ses_2147f4851ffeePE0XXyGs1GFXc","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis. Summary of the proposal:\n\n**ID-stage BEQ/BNE-only early branch resolution** — follows the explicit r6s2 post-mortem recommendation to narrow the ID comparator to just equality (cheapest tree) instead of r6s2's full 6-way signed/unsigned compare.\n\nKey design choices:\n- **Non-speculative** (sidesteps r3s1/r3s2 symbolic-fetch coupling that broke formal)\n- **Single 32-bit XOR equality comparator** at ID (vs r6s2's wide signed+unsigned compare bank that consumed all ID slack)\n- **BEQ/BNE only** — captures ~75% of CoreMark conditional branches (loop-exit BNE, null-check BEQ) at a fraction of r6s2's timing cost\n- **Pipeline payload widening: 1 bit + 32-bit `pc_next`** — smaller than r5s2's 33-bit RAS payload that killed -60%\n- **Fallback to EX resolution** when operands are blocked behind an in-flight LOAD (preserves baseline correctness for the load-use case r6s2 cited as IPC-eating)\n- **BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU skip ID resolution entirely** — their compare trees are what blew r6s2's timing\n\nExpected net: ~4% fitness gain (0.12 branch density × 0.75 BEQ/BNE fraction × 0.60 taken rate = ~5.4% IPC, minus minor Fmax).","time":{"start":1777772697343,"end":1777772702804}}}
