{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774021463,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01KjrSmdwX1Q1ydCoULou68j","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -l \"r5s2\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -1; grep \"r5s2\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null | head -c 3000","description":"Look up r5s2 details"},"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry return address stack for JALR function-return prediction, formal-gated off\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing JAL predictor (r2s2, +5.87%) handles the call side of every\\nfunction-call sequence, removing its 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble. But every\\ncall is balanced by a return \\u2014 `jalr x0, ra, 0` (the RV `ret` pseudo) \\u2014\\nand returns still pay the full 2-cycle bubble because JALR's target\\ndepends on rs1's run-time value, which IF can't see without the regfile.\\nCoreMark is dominated by tight call/return loops (compare_functions,\\ncore_bench_*, matrix_mul_*) so returns are the single highest-frequency\\nun-predicted control-flow event in the trace \\u2014 complementary in weight\\nto the JAL predictor's call side. A correctly-predicted return saves the\\nsame 2 fetch slots a correctly-predicted JAL does, so the IPC ceiling on\\nthis hypothesis is roughly the JAL win again (~5-6%).\\n\\nThe tricky part is formal: the r1s2 BTB attempt showed that threading a\\n32-bit predicted_target through if_id_t and id_ex_t blows the per-check\\nSBY wall-clock budget, and r3s1/r3s2 proved that conditional predictors\\nwhose correctness depends on a free imem_data path (symbolic fetch)\\ncreate feedback loops BMC cannot close. The r1s2 lesson spells out the\\nmitigation verbatim: \\\"track prediction state in a side shadow ... or\\ngate under RISCV_FORMAL to an empty struct\\\" \\u2014 which is exactly what\\nJAL's r2s2 did for free (no threading needed) and what this hypothesis\\ndoes by ifdef-gating the prediction activation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing JAL predictor (r2s2, +5.87%) handles the call side of every\\nfunction-call sequence, removing its 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble. But every\\ncall is balanced by a return \\u2014 `jalr x0, ra, 0` (the RV `ret` pseudo) \\u2014\\nand returns still pay the full 2-cycle bubble because JALR's target\\ndepends on rs1's run-time value, which IF can't see without the regfile.\\nCoreMark is dominated by tight call/return loops (compare_functions,\\ncore_bench_*, matrix_mul_*) so returns are the single highest-frequency\\nun-predicted control-flow event in the trace \\u2014 complementary in weight\\nto the JAL predictor's call side. A correctly-predicted return saves the\\nsame 2 fetch slots a correctly-predicted JAL does, so the IPC ceiling on\\nthis hypothesis is roughly the JAL win again (~5-6%).\\n\\nThe tricky part is formal: the r1s2 BTB attempt showed that threading a\\n32-bit predicted_target through if_id_t and id_ex_t blows the per-check\\nSBY wall-clock budget, and r3s1/r3s2 proved that conditional predictors\\nwhose correctness depends on a free imem_data path (symbolic fetch)\\ncreate feedback loops BMC cannot close. The r1s2 lesson spells out the\\nmitigation verbatim: \\\"track prediction state in a side shadow ... or\\ngate under RISCV_FORMAL to an empty struct\\\" \\u2014 which is exactly what\\nJAL's r2s2 did for free (no threading needed) and what this ","metadata":{"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry return address stack for JALR function-return prediction, formal-gated off\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The existing JAL predictor (r2s2, +5.87%) handles the call side of every\\nfunction-call sequence, removing its 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble. But every\\ncall is balanced by a return \\u2014 `jalr x0, ra, 0` (the RV `ret` pseudo) \\u2014\\nand returns still pay the full 2-cycle bubble because JALR's target\\ndepends on rs1's run-time value, which IF can't see without the regfile.\\nCoreMark is dominated by tight call/return loops (compare_functions,\\ncore_bench_*, matrix_mul_*) so returns are the single highest-frequency\\nun-predicted control-flow event in the trace \\u2014 complementary in weight\\nto the JAL predictor's call side. A correctly-predicted return saves the\\nsame 2 fetch slots a correctly-predicted JAL does, so the IPC ceiling on\\nthis hypothesis is roughly the JAL win again (~5-6%).\\n\\nThe tricky part is formal: the r1s2 BTB attempt showed that threading a\\n32-bit predicted_target through if_id_t and id_ex_t blows the per-check\\nSBY wall-clock budget, and r3s1/r3s2 proved that conditional predictors\\nwhose correctness depends on a free imem_data path (symbolic fetch)\\ncreate feedback loops BMC cannot close. The r1s2 lesson spells out the\\nmitigation verbatim: \\\"track prediction state in a side shadow ... or\\ngate under RISCV_FORMAL to an empty struct\\\" \\u2014 which is exactly what\\nJAL's r2s2 did for free (no threading needed) and what this hypothesis\\ndoes by ifdef-gating the prediction activation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The existing JAL predictor (r2s2, +5.87%) handles the call side of every\\nfunction-call sequence, removing its 2-cycle EX-redirect bubble. But every\\ncall is balanced by a return \\u2014 `jalr x0, ra, 0` (the RV `ret` pseudo) \\u2014\\nand returns still pay the full 2-cycle bubble because JALR's target\\ndepends on rs1's run-time value, which IF can't see without the regfile.\\nCoreMark is dominated by tight call/return loops (compare_functions,\\ncore_bench_*, matrix_mul_*) so returns are the single highest-frequency\\nun-predicted control-flow event in the trace \\u2014 complementary in weight\\nto the JAL predictor's call side. A correctly-predicted return saves the\\nsame 2 fetch slots a correctly-predicted JAL does, so the IPC ceiling on\\nthis hypothesis is roughly the JAL win again (~5-6%).\\n\\nThe tricky part is formal: the r1s2 BTB attempt showed that threading a\\n32-bit predicted_target through if_id_t and id_ex_t blows the per-check\\nSBY wall-clock budget, and r3s1/r3s2 proved that conditional predictors\\nwhose correctness depends on a free imem_data path (symbolic fetch)\\ncreate feedback loops BMC cannot close. The r1s2 lesson spells out the\\nmitigation verbatim: \\\"track prediction state in a side shadow ... or\\ngate under RISCV_FORMAL to an empty struct\\\" \\u2014 which is exactly what\\nJAL's r2s2 did for free (no threading needed) and what this ","exit":0,"description":"Look up r5s2 details","truncated":false},"title":"Look up r5s2 details","time":{"start":1777774021460,"end":1777774021462}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_deb96c657001gk6RHLb2bVwSGZ","sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","messageID":"msg_deb96bcdc001wUyQjxr9rZwrdG"}}
