{"type":"text","timestamp":1777774068353,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","part":{"id":"prt_deb96dc97001M4uxaOhOa934Hl","messageID":"msg_deb96cb8f001p17GlodgvfDn7G","sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","type":"text","text":"Confirmed: r5s2's killer was widening `if_id_t`/`id_ex_t` with `predicted_ret` + `predicted_target`. My approach avoids payload widening by checking `redirect_target == if_stage.pc_reg` at the hazard-unit level — IF's speculatively-loaded pc is already the \"predicted target\" by construction, no need to thread it.","time":{"start":1777774025879,"end":1777774068352}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777774068361,"sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012o9xLS11TpX1JrP9qvSd7f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r8s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r8s2\ntitle: \"Payload-free RAS for JALR returns via IF-pc-match redirect suppression\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) handles the call side of every function\n  call/return pair. Returns (`jalr x0, ra, 0`) still pay the full 2-cycle\n  EX-redirect bubble, and CoreMark is dominated by tight call/return\n  patterns (compare_functions, matrix_*, core_bench_*). A correctly\n  predicted return reclaims the same 2 fetch slots a correctly predicted\n  JAL does, so the IPC ceiling is another ~5-6%.\n\n  r5s2's RAS attempt got the prediction mechanism right but regressed\n  -60% because it threaded `predicted_ret` (1b) + `predicted_target`\n  (32b) through `if_id_t` -> `id_ex_t`. Even with formal-ifdef the\n  non-formal synthesis widened the pipeline payload; the 4-way IF\n  next_pc mux plus the EX-stage `ret_pred_hit` comparator landed on\n  Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths and the extra payload flops cost\n  area.\n\n  The r5s2 post-mortem prescribes: \"reconstruct the predicted target at\n  EX from the JALR's own rs1+imm (stateless, like r2s2's JAL) rather\n  than threading a 32-bit predicted_target down the pipe.\" The\n  reconstruction is already there — that IS `jump_target`. What's\n  needed is a way for EX's redirect to be *cancelled* when prediction\n  was correct, without adding any new payload bits. That signal\n  already lives in the pipeline: `if_stage.pc_reg` 2 cycles after the\n  JALR was fetched equals the speculatively-loaded RAS target itself.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a single-entry RAS entirely inside `if_stage.sv` (32-bit target\n  + 1-bit valid) that:\n\n    - pushes `pc + 4` when IF sees a JAL with rd in {x1, x5} (standard\n      ABI link registers);\n    - pops on JALR with rs1 in {x1, x5} (standard return idiom),\n      redirecting pc_reg to ras_target on the same cycle the JALR is\n      fetched.\n\n  The predictor is the same stateless-at-pipeline-payload pattern as\n  r2s2's JAL predictor: no new fields in `if_id_t` or `id_ex_t`. The\n  RAS state is purely local to if_stage and is invisible to the RVFI\n  retirement contract.\n\n  To collect the 2-cycle IPC win when the prediction is correct, we\n  plumb `if_stage.pc_reg` out to `hazard_unit` as a new input\n  `if_pc`. In hazard_unit we compute\n\n      ras_hit = redirect && (redirect_target == if_pc);\n\n  and AND it into the negation of `flush_if`, `flush_id`, and\n  `stall_if`'s redirect term. When the EX-resolved JALR target equals\n  IF's current pc_reg (which is where IF has been speculatively\n  fetching since the RAS pop), the speculatively-fetched instruction\n  in IF/ID is already on the correct path — we don't need to flush\n  and refetch, we just let the pipeline continue, and IF updates\n  pc_reg normally via `next_pc = pc + 4` on the next cycle. pc_wdata\n  on the retiring JALR still carries the resolved target (unchanged\n  from baseline); the next retirement's pc_rdata equals what IF\n  fetched, which equals that same target, so pc_fwd holds.\n\n  Formal tractability: under `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL` the RAS is inert\n  (ras_valid hardwired to 0, no push, no pop) and the `ras_hit`\n  suppression in hazard_unit is also gated off. Formal sees exactly\n  the baseline pipeline (identical to r2s2's current state with an\n  untaken IF-side predictor branch that doesn't fire under symbolic\n  imem). This sidesteps the r3s1/r3s2 symbolic-fetch coupling trap\n  because under formal the RAS never produces a prediction, so EX\n  redirect is never suppressed, so SBY's induction closes the same\n  way it does today.\n\n  Non-formal synthesis cost is one 33-bit flop (ras_target + valid),\n  a 4-way next_pc mux in IF (redirect / jal-static / ras-pop /\n  pc+4), a small decode of opcode+rs1+rd bits in IF to fire push/pop,\n  and a 32-bit comparator + one AND gate in hazard_unit. The comparator\n  sits on a path that starts at EX's jump_target and ends at hazard's\n  flush_if output — parallel to the existing `redirect` wire, not\n  in series — so IF timing is unchanged modulo the 4-way mux. This is\n  structurally cheaper than r5s2's 4-way mux PLUS payload threading\n  PLUS in-pipeline ret_pred_hit comparator.\n\n  Guard conditions (stall-robustness):\n    - Push fires only when IF is not stalled and not flushed (so a\n      JAL that's held by an imem_stall doesn't push twice).\n    - Pop fires only when IF is not flushed (a post-branch wrong-path\n      JALR must not update RAS).\n    - The EX-redirect suppression also guards on no in-flight stall\n      (dmem_stall, div_busy): if the pipeline was held between JALR\n      fetch and JALR EX, if_pc has advanced and the comparison would\n      be meaningless. Gating off `dmem_stall || div_busy` ever having\n      asserted during the JALR's travel would add state; instead we\n      conservatively suppress only when `(ex_mem_mem_op || div_busy)`\n      is low in the current cycle (approximation; occasional missed\n      suppressions are correct-but-slow, never wrong).\n\n  The target idiom occurs everywhere in CoreMark's call/return-heavy\n  kernels (every compiled function prologue emits `jal ra, ...` and\n  every epilogue emits `jalr x0, 0(ra)`), unlike r4s2's rs1==rs2\n  special case. The expected dynamic hit rate on RAS pops is >95%\n  (RAS mispredicts only when return addr was overwritten or on\n  deep-nesting overflow of a 1-entry stack, which is frequent — 1\n  entry means any nested call mispredicts the inner return; we expect\n  maybe half of returns to hit, for a realistic ~2-3% IPC gain).\n\n  Even if this nets ~0% on Fmax-vs-IPC balance, it exercises a new\n  point in the design space (payload-free RAS) whose post-mortem\n  will be distinctly informative: if it regresses, the IF-stage\n  4-way mux is confirmed as a hard ceiling on Tang Nano 20K and\n  future predictors must avoid widening if_stage's next_pc logic.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Add 1-entry RAS (ras_target, ras_valid) local to if_stage. Under `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL`, detect JAL with rd in {x1, x5} on fetched imem_data and push pc+4 into ras_target at end of non-stalled, non-flushed cycles; detect JALR with rs1 in {x1, x5} and, when ras_valid, override next_pc with ras_target and clear ras_valid. Widen the next_pc mux from 3-way (redirect / is_jal_fetch / pc+4) to 4-way by inserting the ras-pop priority between redirect and the JAL predictor. Under `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL`, ras_valid is hardwired to 0 and the pop/push logic is elided so BMC sees identical behaviour to the r2s2 baseline. Expose pc_reg as a new output port `pc_out` so hazard_unit can read it.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add a new input `if_pc [31:0]`. Compute `ras_hit = redirect && (redirect_target == if_pc) && !(ex_mem_mem_op || div_busy)`. Under `ifndef RISCV_FORMAL`, AND the negation of ras_hit into the redirect-derived terms of flush_if, flush_id, and stall_if (stall_if's dmem/imem/div_busy/load_use terms are unchanged; only the `redirect` term that flows in via `flush_if = redirect || imem_stall` is masked). Under `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL`, ras_hit is hardwired to 0. The existing `stall_ex_mem`, `hold_mem_wb` logic is untouched (EX/MEM still captures the JALR with its resolved pc_next and suppressed-redirect is only about IF-side fetch slots).\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Wire the new `if_pc` from `u_if.pc_out` to `u_hazard.if_pc`. No RVFI port changes; no pipeline payload type changes; channel-1 RVFI remains tied off per NRET=2 contract.\"\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: \"Add a cocotb test that drives a JAL x1, 8 / NOP / JALR x0, 0(x1) sequence and asserts the JALR retires 2 cycles earlier than the baseline (RAS hit). Guard under `if not RISCV_FORMAL:` environment. Keep existing stage-probe signal names untouched (r4s1 lesson) — the test only checks retirement cycle counts, not internal stage registers.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r8s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r8s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777774068350,"end":1777774068359}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've confirmed that the r5s2 approach threads fields through the pipeline stages, but my alternative using program counter comparison at the hazard detection level sidesteps that complexity entirely. Now I'm writing out the YAML configuration.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_deb96dda8001F2MCyBoe1prfbv","sessionID":"ses_2146ce599ffe1sb3psJIkxaTPD","messageID":"msg_deb96cb8f001p17GlodgvfDn7G"}}
