{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777775389617,"sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01VoB9fR2jugqSiSw2LcHHGQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check existing hypothesis files"},"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.yaml\nhyp-20260502-002-r9s1.yaml\n","metadata":{"output":"hyp-20260502-001-r9s0.yaml\nhyp-20260502-002-r9s1.yaml\n","exit":0,"description":"Check existing hypothesis files","truncated":false},"title":"Check existing hypothesis files","time":{"start":1777775389612,"end":1777775389615}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor category results, the JAL predictor showed solid gains while the BTB/BTFN approach failed due to symbolic fetch coupling issues. The RAS attempts both underperformed significantly—one with threading payload problems and another with IF-stage mux bottlenecks—so the key takeaway is avoiding widening the IF-stage's next_pc mux and not threading the payload through it.\n\nNow I'm exploring what predictor approaches haven't been tested yet. I could try a JALR target predictor with stateless reconstruction at the EX stage, though the payload threading issue from r5s2 rules that out. There's also the idea of a delayed predictor that keeps IF linear while reducing the EX bubble, or a branch direction predictor that stays completely out of the IF path. The r8s2 failure with the 4-way next_pc mux suggests I could try folding a RAS into the existing JAL-static predictor mux instead of adding a separate one, but that still requires another mux leg. A last-taken-branch predictor that reuses the existing redirect path is tempting, but that's essentially what BTB does and it's already ruled out. The pattern-based delayed resolution approach from r6s2/r7s2 also didn't work out. Given that the JAL predictor is the proven working pattern and r4s2 showed stateless BEQ prediction lost Fmax despite passing formal verification, I'm wondering if I should focus on statically predicting conditional branches that are always-taken by construction.\n\nLooking at what's actually frequent in CoreMark—conditional branches are saturated from prior attempts, JALR returns have the payload and mux cost problem, and indirect JALR calls are hard to predict without state. The key constraint is that JALR returns at IF time don't have access to the rs1 value without a stateful RAS, which r8s2 showed regresses performance by 18% even with a clean design. An alternative would be detecting returns at the ID stage and flushing only the single wrong-path instruction to cut the bubble from 2 cycles to 1, but that requires ID-stage forwarding of rs1 which prior attempts priced out.\n\nThe real bottlenecks are the 4-way IF next_pc mux, the 32-bit equality comparator in the hazard unit, and the 1-entry RAS being too shallow for CoreMark. Rather than expanding the predictor, I should target Fmax through simplification. The design constraint is that any solution should be non-speculative to avoid the IF-stage linear fetch issue—the branch resolves at EX with a 2-cycle bubble from wrong-path instructions in IF and ID. I'm exploring whether a stateless taken-branch repeat predictor could work at IF without the formal verification issues that plague other speculative approaches.\n\nMoving to EX-stage resolution would cut the bubble structurally rather than through prediction, but that's a different lever. The real insight from the lessons is that JAL works because prediction and resolution are tautological—so for JALR returns, if I can reconstruct the target from forwarded register state at ID or EX, I might cut redirect latency without adding a deep predictor. But ID-stage resolution is already saturated. The other prediction categories—memory disambiguation, way prediction, load-value prediction—don't apply here. So I'm circling back to strengthening the existing JAL predictor with minimal area cost.\n\nThe JAL predictor already delivers +6%, so the question is whether I can extend it further. The IF mux (redirect / jal-pred / pc+4) is probably already merged by synthesis since redirect and jal-pred never fire together. Pre-computing the JAL target one cycle earlier won't help because imem_data arrives combinationally. A BEQ-zero predictor for loop termination hits the same symbolic-fetch wall. The RAS idea keeps failing due to mux expansion in IF, but what if instead of adding a mux leg, the RAS suppresses the EX redirect when the target matches the RAS prediction—letting EX check the RAS before deciding to redirect?\n\nThat would require IF to make an earlier decision before fetching wrong-path, but that still needs an IF-stage mux. Let me try a different approach: maybe a simple local predictor targeting something specific, or a return-value predictor via rd_wdata shadow—a stateless pipeline predictor that caches last taken direction by PC. But that runs into the same symbolic-fetch formal issue.\n\nThe real constraint is that stateless predictors at IF are mostly exhausted, and formal-gated shadow state keeps hitting synthesis costs even when ifdef'd—r5s2 had 33-bit payload in synthesis despite being zero-bits in formal, and r8s2 still paid the IF-mux and comparator cost. The fundamental blocker appears to be...\n\nThe IF-stage 4-way next_pc mux itself. What if instead of a dedicated JAL predictor, we had a general \"unconditional fetch redirect\" handling both JAL and JALR-return from the same mux leg via ordinary decoding? For JALR returns we can't predict the target at fetch anyway. Or maybe relative JAL target caching—speculatively fetch a JAL's target, then predict the return point controls the next fetch—but that's just RAS again. Looking back at what actually worked: the JAL algebraic simplification gave +6%, so what similar simplifications are left? JALR with zero offset is pure return, but the target is rs1_val which isn't available at IF—that needs RAS. Speculative execution with no IF redirect wouldn't help, and a single-entry BTB caching only JAL targets is redundant since the JAL predictor already handles that statically. I need to find a genuinely novel angle here.\n\nWhat if we move the JALR-return redirect to the ID stage instead? We'd detect the canonical return pattern (JALR x0, x1, 0) at ID using the already-forwarded rs1 value from the regfile read port plus WB bypass, cutting the JALR-return bubble from 2 cycles to 1. This avoids expanding the IF mux since the detection happens downstream, and the canonical return is very common in CoreMark. The concern is the combinational path from ID regfile read back to IF's PC mux—but wait, that still requires a fourth mux leg for the ID-predicted target alongside EX redirect, JAL-predicted, and pc+4. Unless we propagate the ID-stage predicted return through the existing EX redirect path one cycle earlier, but that still adds a mux. I'm hitting the same bottleneck.\n\nActually, let me reconsider: the earlier analysis showed that ID-stage conditional branch resolution was saturated, but JALR-return is fundamentally different—it's unconditional, and the \"prediction\" is just a target prediction based on rs1 value, which is deterministic modulo forwarding. So I could do a non-speculative JALR-return early redirect at ID: when ID decodes JALR and has rs1 available via regfile plus forwarding, compute the target as rs1+imm and assert a redirect one cycle earlier than EX would, reusing the existing EX redirect wire. This cuts the bubble from 2 to 1 cycle without a new IF-mux leg. The risk is that rs1 might not be available if it's waiting on a load, so I'd gate the redirect on rs1 being available through existing forward paths. Essentially I'm moving JALR resolution from EX to ID—same ID-stage criticality concerns as conditional branches, but JALR only needs rs1 (not a compare), is unconditional, and the path is just rs1 forward plus imm add plus PC mux. The ID stage already has an adder for decode and immediate generation, so I'd need to check if adding the rs1+imm path creates a timing bottleneck.\n\nBut looking back at the design history, r6s2 explicitly noted that the IPC-Fmax tradeoff for control-flow is near-saturated after r2s2's JAL predictor, and future improvements should focus on non-branch optimizations. Plus, every RAS-style approach (r5s2, r8s2) has regressed. The only successful predictor improvements were r2s2 (the JAL predictor itself) and r8s0 (an algebraic simplification of it). So a safer bet would be to look for another algebraic or structural simplification of the existing JAL predictor rather than adding new logic. Let me examine the current JAL predictor implementation to see if there's room to optimize it.\n\nExamining the JAL predictor code...\n\nThe core operation is computing `pc + jal_imm` combinationally to feed the mux. I'm wondering if we could pre-compute this or split it into low and high-order parts to reduce the critical path, but I'm not seeing an obvious algebraic win there. Let me try a different angle: what if we use a static prediction scheme based on instruction patterns, like predicting backward branches as taken? But that runs into the same symbolic-fetch coupling issue that broke r3s1/r3s2. The real insight is that r2s2's JAL predictor works because it's tautologically correct—JAL is unconditional, so there's no misprediction possible. Are there any other RISC-V instructions that are tautologically predictable at the IF stage with no state? BEQ x0, x0 would always be taken, but compilers don't emit that. Beyond JAL, there's almost nothing else that fits this pattern.\n\nI'm exploring other angles now: a conditional move pattern detector that could squash single-instruction branches entirely, or specializing the pc+4 adder since pc[1:0] is always 00, but Yosys probably already optimizes that. I also considered pre-computing pc + jal_imm at the PC flop, but we can't know which instruction is there until we fetch it, so the adder is inherently dependent on imem_data. A local branch history table stored in distributed BRAM could work, but using it at IF would just recreate the mux bottleneck, and using it at EX doesn't help with prediction.\n\nActually, the key insight is that non-taken branches are already optimal with zero penalty, so there's nothing to gain there—the real problem is taken branches needing earlier redirects, and r2s2 is the only stateless approach that works. Everything else I've tried hits failure modes. I'm considering whether to make the JAL predictor more aggressive in a narrow way without triggering those failures, or to simplify its redirect priority logic instead of expanding it. Let me examine the current JAL predictor structure more carefully to find structural optimizations.\n\nLooking at the condition gates on is_jal_fetch—the `!redirect` check is actually redundant since the outer mux already prioritizes redirect, but `!flush` matters because flush doesn't fire the redirect mux leg, so we need to suppress speculative prediction when the fetch isn't real to avoid bad PC updates.\n\nNow I'm examining whether there's a worthwhile predictor improvement. The JAL predictor could theoretically be narrowed or enhanced, but most obvious angles either duplicate existing behavior or add too much complexity—like pre-computing targets for JAL-after-JAL or caching last-seen JALs. The safest move is probably to focus on the core predictor without over-engineering it.\n\nLooking at the actual performance data, the jump from r2s2 to r8s0 came from an algebraic simplification that moved the misalignment guard earlier in the pipeline. The question is whether a similar optimization exists in the current opcode checking logic.\n\nI'm examining whether we can narrow the 7-bit opcode comparison by finding a shorter bit pattern that uniquely identifies JAL. Checking the RV32I instruction set, I notice that bits [4:0] = 01111 appears in multiple opcodes like MISC-MEM, AMO, and JAL itself, so that's not unique. Testing other bit combinations like [6:5] and [3:2] together — JAL has 11/11 while JALR has 11/01 and BRANCH has 11/00 — but this still doesn't isolate JAL cleanly enough to be a meaningful simplification.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the implications of mis-predicting JAL on an invalid opcode. If we incorrectly identify an illegal instruction as JAL and redirect to pc+jal_imm, the instruction would still trap at retirement, but the pipeline would have already fetched from the wrong address. The question is whether the trap handling properly discards the mispredicted fetch or if it causes issues with the PC state during exception handling.\n\nLooking at the core logic, an illegal decode trap doesn't trigger a redirect like a misalign fault does — it just sets rvfi_trap=1 and lets the instruction retire. This means the next instruction fetched would be from pc+jal_imm instead of pc+4, breaking the pc_fwd invariant where the illegal instruction's pc_wdata should match the next instruction's pc_rdata. So the opcode check has to be exact, which means sticking with the 7-bit comparison even though it costs a few LUT4s.\n\nGiven that constraint, let me focus on something more practical: moving JALR resolution for returns (rs1==x1, imm==0) from the EX stage to the ID stage using the existing regfile read and write-back bypass logic. This would eliminate one cycle of the two-cycle JALR bubble by redirecting the PC earlier, similar to how conditional branches resolve at ID, but without needing a compare tree since we're just using the rs1 data directly as the target.\n\nThe trick is to avoid adding another mux leg in the IF stage by ORing the ID redirect signal with the existing EX redirect path — both drive the same redirect wire, but ID fires one cycle earlier, so the PC update happens sooner and fewer wrong-path instructions get fetched. The main concern is forwarding when x1 is being written by an in-flight instruction, but that's manageable since writes to x1 are almost always JAL or return-address stores, not loads.\n\nStill working through the forwarding logic at ID... The key insight is that JALR-return targets depend on x1's value from prior writes, not on fetched instruction data, so there's no circular dependency like with conditional branches. This could work formally, though it's complex. The performance upside is modest—maybe 5% IPC improvement from eliminating the 2-cycle bubble on returns—but the critical path risk at ID is real. The solution is to specialize the predictor to just canonical `ret` (JALR with x1, x0, 0), which avoids the 32-bit adder entirely since the immediate is zero.\n\nBut implementing this requires detecting the exact pattern at ID, gating on no in-flight writes to x1, and carefully handling the redirect logic to avoid conflicts with EX-stage redirects—it's getting complex enough that formal verification becomes questionable. Given the budget constraints, I'm reconsidering whether to pursue this or look for simpler wins instead. The alternative of predicting misaligned JAL targets doesn't help because those already trap correctly, so there's no gain there either. Let me just commit to the ID-stage RET predictor approach. It targets a real CoreMark workload (returns), uses stateless reconstruction, and avoids the r8s2 IF-mux expansion by reusing the existing redirect wire.\n\nActually wait, re-reading r5s2: \"the 4-way next_pc mux and EX `ret_pred_hit` comparator land on the Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths and cost enough Fmax/LUTs to dwarf the ~5% CoreMark IPC ceiling returns could deliver\"\n\nThe \"5% CoreMark IPC ceiling returns could deliver\" confirms the IPC upper bound. And r5s2 failed because of IF/EX synthesis cost. The ID-stage approach I'm proposing might have IF cost too (the id_early_redirect OR gate + mux between id_target and ex_target in the existing \"redirect\" wire).\n\nActually just reusing the redirect wire: `redirect = ex_redirect | id_early_redirect`, `redirect_target = id_early_redirect ? id_target : ex_redirect_target`. The IF mux is still 3-way: redirect, jal-pred, pc+4. No NEW leg. Just a 2-way mux on the redirect_target source.\n\nBut the id_early_redirect gating logic (pattern match + no-in-flight-writer check) adds a combinational path from ID stage decode + regfile read state back into the IF PC mux, via the EX-stage redirect_target mux. This probably lengthens the critical path, and the gate check itself adds logic.\n\nI'll commit to this anyway—it's a real hypothesis with merit and addresses a gap not previously tried. But given how consistently RAS/RET prediction regresses (r5s2 -60%, r8s2 -18%), maybe I should pivot to a predictor that doesn't target returns at all. Let me explore a different angle: a minimal JAL predictor refinement that doesn't try to cover new instruction types, focusing instead on splitting the JAL predictor's opcode check for better efficiency. That approach won't work either—r4s2 already showed that expanding the IF-mux regresses performance. Let me try a different angle: collapsing the existing 3-way next_pc selector into a simpler 2-way structure by pre-combining the redirect and JAL paths. But even after working through the logic, this still produces the same LUT structure synthesis would generate anyway, so there's no real gain. And since redirect and is_jal_fetch are mutually exclusive, I can't exploit that for meaningful optimization either.\n\nI keep circling back to predictor ideas, but they've all hit diminishing returns or failed outright. The ID-stage RET predictor is clean and testable, but I'm skeptical it'll help. And orthogonal approaches like load value prediction or bypass prediction don't offer real wins either—the forwarding logic is already combinational, and predicting load values is too rare to matter.\n\nLet me commit to a concrete proposal: a stateless JALR-return predictor that detects the canonical `ret` pattern (JALR x0, x1, 0) in ID and reuses the existing EX-redirect wire via an OR-gate, flushing only IF rather than IF+ID. No new mux leg, no RAS, just a regfile read of x1 as the target. The synth cost is minimal—just pattern matching and an OR-gate—and I'd expect maybe 2–4% improvement if it works, though confidence is low since predictors are saturated. Now I need to verify the control flow: when ID fires an early redirect at cycle N, the JALR instruction still enters the ID/EX register and reaches EX at N+1, where its own redirect shouldn't fire again since it would target the same address.\n\nThe tricky part is avoiding a double-redirect or wasting a cycle. I could add an \"already_redirected\" flag in the pipeline register, but that widens the payload like r5s2 warned against. Or I could suppress EX's redirect if it detects the target matches the current PC, but that requires an equality compare at IF—the same pitfall r8s2 flagged. Another option is to flush both IF and the ID/EX register on the early redirect, killing the JALR outright so it never reaches EX.\n\nBut that breaks RVFI because the JALR never retires. The core issue is that the predicted instruction has to retire even though we're redirecting early. Let me step back and try a simpler approach: pre-compute the JALR target at ID instead of EX to reduce the critical path delay. The problem is ID doesn't have the forwarded rs1 value yet—forwarding happens at EX—so the pre-computed sum would be wrong if rs1 is being forwarded from a prior instruction. I'd need to extend forwarding to ID as well, but r6s2 showed that's expensive.\n\nLet me just work through the RET-at-ID hypothesis with a clean design: detect `ret` at ID, and when there's no in-flight writer to x1, fire an early redirect signal that feeds into the top-level redirect mux alongside the EX redirect. Mark the JALR with a `pre_redirected` bit so EX suppresses its own redirect, and let the JALR continue through the pipeline normally to retire properly. I'm tracing through the timing to make sure this works without creating bubbles or breaking retirement.\n\nNow I'm walking through the cycle-by-cycle behavior: at cycle N-1 the JALR is in the IF/ID combinational stage, we detect it and fire the redirect, so the PC flops to the return target by end of cycle N-1. Then at cycle N, IF fetches from the correct return address while the JALR moves into EX with the `pre_redirected` bit set to suppress any duplicate redirect.\n\nThe core issue is that EX would normally fire its own redirect when it computes the JALR target, but since we've already redirected at ID stage, firing again would flush the correct in-flight fetch—so we need to carry a suppression flag through the pipeline or check that the computed target matches the current PC.\n\nI'm leaning toward the simplest approach: just add a one-bit flag that travels with the JALR through ID/EX to tell EX \"don't redirect, we already did this at ID stage.\" The suppression approach requires carrying a pred_ret flag through the pipeline, which risks hurting timing like r5s2 experienced. Alternatively, I could avoid the compare entirely by making matching redirects harmless—but that still needs comparison logic somewhere. I'm going to step back and commit to a simpler hypothesis instead: a static conditional-branch predictor targeting \"BEQ rs1, x0\" patterns with backward targets, sidestepping the RAS complexity and prior failure modes altogether. I'm settling on a simpler approach: narrowing the JAL predictor's opcode check from a full 7-bit comparison down to just three specific bits, since that bit pattern is unique to JAL among all valid RV32I opcodes.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a problem—if the predictor fires on an illegal opcode that happens to match this narrow pattern, it creates a pc_fwd mismatch during retirement. The illegal instruction would retire with pc+4, but the next instruction (fetched from the mispredicted target) would have a different pc_rdata, breaking the forward-progress check.\n\nLooking back at recent results, the only proven win in this space is algebraic simplification of the existing JAL predictor. Any widening of the IF stage's next_pc selection tends to hurt fitness. So I need to examine the PC flop logic more carefully—there's a 3-way priority mux where redirect takes precedence, then the JAL prediction, then default pc+4. Maybe there's a simpler algebraic transformation I'm missing rather than trying to add new prediction patterns. Removing the `!flush && !redirect` conditions from the JAL predictor gate saves a few LUTs by shortening the logic chain, though the instruction mux still needs to emit NOPs on flush or redirect. I notice that `flush` already encompasses `redirect`, so the output logic can collapse to just checking `flush` directly. These are all small algebraic simplifications, but they align with the pattern from the previous optimization. I'll go with simplifying `is_jal_fetch` and cleaning up the output gating.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there's a bigger opportunity: the IF-stage JAL predictor could use a narrower adder instead of a full 32-bit one by exploiting the structure of how PC and immediate values combine.\n\nSimplifying the adder width...\n\nActually, let me step back and commit to a concrete ID-stage return predictor that reuses the existing redirect mux without adding new paths. The idea is to detect the canonical `ret` instruction (JALR x0, x1, 0) at ID, read x1 early via the regfile and bypass logic, and drive a redirect one cycle sooner—but only when x1 is immediately available and there's no in-flight writer to it. The JALR still retires normally through the pipeline; the EX stage just suppresses its own redirect if it matches what ID already predicted.\n\nBut there's a timing concern I need to think through: the ID-stage regfile read plus the redirect mux at the top level creates a new combinational path from regfile output all the way to the IF stage's PC, which might be tighter than the existing EX-stage path.\n\nLet me compare the two paths. The EX redirect goes through ID/EX registers, then EX forwarding muxes, the full JALR adder, and finally the redirect mux—that's roughly 19 LUT levels of depth. The ID path would be regfile read (about 5 LUT levels for a 32:1 mux plus WB bypass) plus a top-level mux (2 more levels), totaling around 7 LUT levels. So the ID path is actually shorter, which is good—it won't become the new critical path as long as the EX redirect path isn't already the Fmax bottleneck.\n\nThe real problem is handling the suppression logic. If I let the JALR retire normally and mark its predicted target in EX/MEM, then EX computes the correct pc_next from forwarded rs1. When EX's redirect fires with the same target that IF already predicted, the flush_if kills the correctly-fetched instruction—that's the bug. I need either a 32-bit compare to suppress the redirect when targets match (which cost r8s2 18% performance), or carry an \"already_predicted\" bit through the pipeline (which widens the payload). Neither option is cheap. I'm wondering if there's a third way: suppress the flush but let the redirect fire anyway, so the PC updates to the same target without killing the next instruction.\n\nBut tracing through the cycles, that doesn't work either. The flush at cycle N+1 squashes the correctly-fetched target instruction, and since the PC doesn't change (it's already at target), IF just re-fetches the same address at cycle N+2. That wastes the cycle I was trying to save, making the whole scheme neutral. Without suppression, this approach is a wash. The bit-in-id_ex approach seems unavoidable, but r5s2 showed payload widening is costly. So the ID-stage RET predictor is a net loss.\n\nI'm abandoning the search for a new predictor and going with a safe, minimal refinement of the existing JAL predictor—the only winning move since r2s2. I'll drop the redundant `!redirect` gate from the is_jal_fetch check since the PC mux already prioritizes redirect, then retie the computation through a pre-stalled adder split. Better yet, I can move the JAL opcode detection into a more efficient \"valid-JAL-opcode\" signal using just two bits from the instruction. Let me verify which opcodes have both bits set to distinguish JAL from similar instructions like JALR and BRANCH.\n\nAfter checking the RV32I instruction set, I found that only JAL has both bits set to 1, while JALR, BRANCH, and SYSTEM have the second bit as 0, and all other instructions have the first bit as 0. This two-bit check would be unique for JAL among valid opcodes, but invalid opcodes could also match, which would break the pc_fwd logic unless the decoder treats those invalid patterns as JAL too—but that violates the decoder's safety invariant. So I can't narrow the opcode check without compromising correctness.\n\nI'm settling on a simpler algebraic fix: remove the `!redirect` term entirely from is_jal_fetch since it's redundant with the flush logic, saving one AND gate on the critical path.\n\nNow I'm looking at the EX stage's redirect path to see if there's a more substantial optimization there...\n\n`branch_taken` feeds into the redirect signal and depends on a complex compare tree, which sits on the critical path to the IF PC flop—but decoupling that would be out of scope. I could pre-compute `branch_target` at the ID stage since both `pc` and the immediate are available there, moving the adder earlier and saving it from the EX critical path. The tradeoff is that `id_ex` would widen by 32 bits since the immediate is still needed for other instruction types like OP-IMM, STORE, and LOAD, so `branch_target` becomes additional payload rather than a replacement. That's the kind of widening that hurts area.\n\nI notice in the EX stage that `jump_target` for JAL instructions recomputes `pc + imm`, which is identical to `branch_target`—so a structural CSE pass could theoretically merge these two adders into one. But I think I should stick with the conservative JAL predictor optimization for now.\n\nLooking at the actual implementation, I can simplify the JAL predictor's fetch gate by removing all the guards and relying on the outer PC mux to handle invalid cases. The redirect signal has priority in the mux, so when a redirect fires, the `is_jal_fetch` computation is harmless. Similarly, when memory stalls, the PC holds and `is_jal_fetch` firing doesn't matter. Only when both redirect and stall are inactive does the predictor actually drive the next PC, which is exactly when it should be operating normally.\n\nThe redundant `!flush && !redirect` guards can be stripped, cutting the opcode check from a 5-input AND down to 3 inputs—maybe saving a LUT4 depth on the IF path. But there's a deeper issue: even if I narrow the JAL opcode check, an invalid instruction that matches the pattern could misdirect the PC, and since the decoder still retires it as invalid with `pc_wdata = pc+4`, the next fetch uses the predicted target instead, causing a mismatch that breaks `pc_fwd`.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debabab7c0012qQAswo4X3Yltn","sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","messageID":"msg_deba7464d0019Aob0ZKzc7wGDJ"}}
