{"type":"text","timestamp":1777775455993,"sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","part":{"id":"prt_debac5689001gvMivw9GKU5AIu","messageID":"msg_debababe9001zyDuBbX0ormcUr","sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","type":"text","text":"Based on LESSONS.md analysis, the predictor slot is heavily saturated — only two wins exist (r2s2 JAL predictor +5.87%, r8s0 algebraic simplification +5.99%), and both were *stateless* with *no new IF-mux legs* and *no pipeline payload widening*. Every RAS/BTB/BTFN/ID-resolve attempt has regressed (-18% to -60%). The safe play following the r8s0 pattern is further algebraic/structural simplification of the existing JAL predictor.\n\nLooking at `if_stage.sv`, I can see `is_jal_fetch` has redundant guards. The outer PC-flop mux:\n```\nif (redirect) pc <= redirect_target;\nelse if (!stall) pc <= next_pc;\n```\nalready handles both redirect priority (target wins regardless of next_pc) and stall hold (`imem_stall → stall_if=1 → PC holds`). So the `!flush && !redirect` conjunction inside `is_jal_fetch` is dead logic on the IF combinational critical path.","time":{"start":1777775433353,"end":1777775455986}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777775456026,"sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EAWnTxyrM3oysSKbtf7VR4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r9s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260502-003-r9s2\ntitle: \"Prune redundant !flush/!redirect guards from JAL-predictor is_jal_fetch — IF critical-path algebraic simplification\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The predictor slot on this Tang Nano 20K flow is structurally saturated per\n  LESSONS.md: every non-JAL predictor attempt (BTB/BTFN r3s1/r3s2, rs1==rs2\n  r4s2, RAS r5s2 at -60%, RET-fast r8s2 at -18%, ID-stage branch-resolve\n  r6s2/r7s2) has regressed or broken formal. The only two predictor-category\n  *improvements* in the log are (a) r2s2 — the stateless JAL predictor itself\n  — and (b) r8s0 (+5.99%) which was a pure *algebraic* rewrite of the JAL\n  predictor's misalign guard from a post-adder 2-bit compare into a pre-adder\n  single-bit slice of imem_data, decoupling the mux SELECT from the 32-bit\n  adder carry chain. Both of those kept IF's next_pc mux at 3 ways, added\n  zero pipeline payload, and required zero formal-state expansion.\n\n  Given the demonstrated Pareto ceiling, the only remaining \"predictor\" lever\n  with positive expected value is *further structural refinement of the same\n  JAL predictor's IF-stage combinational gating*, looking for expressions\n  that are functionally dead after accounting for the outer PC-flop priority\n  mux. Such refinements match the r8s0 pattern exactly and carry near-zero\n  regression risk — no new state, no mux legs, no formal-proof impact.\nhypothesis: |\n  Observation: inside if_stage.sv, the JAL-predictor gate is\n\n    is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)\n                   && !flush && !redirect\n                   && (imem_data[21] == 1'b0);\n\n    next_pc = redirect     ? redirect_target\n            : is_jal_fetch ? jal_target\n                           : (pc + 32'd4);\n\n  and the outer PC-flop priority mux is\n\n    if      (reset)    pc <= RESET_PC;\n    else if (redirect) pc <= redirect_target;\n    else if (!stall)   pc <= next_pc;\n\n  Claim: the `!flush && !redirect` conjunction in is_jal_fetch is DEAD\n  LOGIC after the outer mux's priority is accounted for.\n\n    - When redirect=1: the outer mux writes redirect_target regardless of\n      what next_pc evaluates to. is_jal_fetch firing is harmless.\n    - When imem_stall=1 (the only other source of flush beyond redirect,\n      per hazard_unit: `flush_if = redirect || imem_stall`): stall_if=1\n      fires on imem_stall, the outer mux holds PC, next_pc is discarded.\n      is_jal_fetch firing is harmless.\n    - When redirect=0 and imem_stall=0: is_jal_fetch correctly predicts.\n      Normal operation unchanged.\n\n  So is_jal_fetch can be simplified to\n\n    is_jal_fetch = (imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111) && (imem_data[21] == 1'b0);\n\n  and the redundant `redirect ? redirect_target` leg inside next_pc can be\n  dropped (outer mux already dominates it):\n\n    next_pc = is_jal_fetch ? jal_target : (pc + 32'd4);\n\n  This shortens the is_jal_fetch gate from a 5-input AND tree (7-bit\n  opcode compare + misalign guard + !flush + !redirect) to a 3-input AND\n  (opcode + misalign guard), removing ~1 LUT4 level from the IF-stage\n  combinational path that feeds next_pc. The next_pc mux itself drops\n  from 3-way to 2-way, which synthesis may collapse into a single LUT4\n  per output bit (vs. the current 2-level select).\n\n  RVFI semantics are bit-exact identical. Formal proof time is unchanged\n  (no new state, no new free variables, same pc_fwd / unique / ill /\n  reg / liveness properties). The change is a pure combinational\n  simplification of the existing r2s2+r8s0 predictor gate — the r8s0\n  rule-of-thumb in action: \"look for post-mux guards that are covered\n  by a dominating outer-mux priority\".\n\n  The misalign guard (imem_data[21]==0) stays — without it, a misaligned\n  JAL would be predicted to a misaligned target, breaking pc_fwd\n  (predictor jumps, then EX's misalign_jump trap fires, pc_wdata\n  defaults to pc+4, mismatch vs. next retirement's pc_rdata). The\n  opcode check stays exact (no narrowing) because false-positive\n  prediction on an illegal opcode would similarly break pc_fwd (illegal\n  traps with pc_wdata=pc+4, next retirement's pc_rdata = mispredicted\n  target). These guards are the *non-redundant* part of the gate.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Simplify is_jal_fetch to drop the redundant `!flush && !redirect` conjunction (dead logic after outer PC-flop priority-mux analysis). Simplify next_pc to drop the redundant `redirect ? redirect_target` inner leg (dominated by the outer mux). Keep the opcode compare and imem_data[21] misalign guard exactly as-is; both are load-bearing for pc_fwd on the illegal-opcode and misaligned-target paths.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r9s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260502-003-r9s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777775455983,"end":1777775456006}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the predictor category, it's clear the field is oversaturated—only two approaches have actually worked: the original stateless JAL predictor and its algebraic simplification variant, both yielding modest gains around 6%. I should avoid repeating the failed patterns and focus on what made those two winners distinct.\n\nThe safest path forward is another algebraic refinement of the existing JAL predictor, similar to what worked with r8s0. I'm noticing redundant conditional gates in the is_jal_fetch logic that the outer PC-flop mux and stall gate already handle, so removing this dead logic should trim unnecessary LUT4 levels from the IF combinational path without changing behavior.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debac5d05001tsQJHV1G0IaTcw","sessionID":"ses_21458b9f9ffe9NXVCVvLDmd70H","messageID":"msg_debababe9001zyDuBbX0ormcUr"}}
