{"type":"text","timestamp":1777778015983,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef91ffeS7Emr0lEdRj3ks","part":{"id":"prt_debd34115001uNmEIEvf0jmFCU","messageID":"msg_debd010dc0015y5Hhe5spmSCMG","sessionID":"ses_2142fef91ffeS7Emr0lEdRj3ks","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons carefully:\n- EX-path optimizations are hot (r5s1 divider seq +8.79%, r3s0 DSP consolidation +8.50%, r8s0 algebraic pre-adder +5.99%)\n- Forwarding-path widening is fatal (r5s1/r7s1/r8s1/r9s1/r10s1/r11s1 all regressions)\n- Boolean AND/OR rewrites don't help (r9s2, r11s0) — only arithmetic-dependency shortenings pay\n- Pipeline payload widening is fatal regardless of formal cost (r5s2, r6s2, r7s2, r10s2, r8s2)\n- IF next_pc mux widening is fatal (r4s2, r8s2, r10s2)\n\nLet me examine the EX-stage output flop critical path:\n```\nrs_forward_mux → operand_mux → ALU(19-way case) → alu_result_eff(2:1 w/ div_result) → flop_input_mux(2:1 w/ pc+4)\n```\n\nThe `alu_result_eff` mux between `alu.out` and `div_result_eff` is a 32-bit 2:1 mux sitting OUTSIDE the ALU that duplicates work the ALU's case mux could absorb. Under non-ALTOPS, the ALU's DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case arms return constant 0 — a pure waste, since the real value is muxed in AFTER. If we route `div_result` INTO the ALU and put it in those case arms, the external mux disappears — saving 1 LUT4 level on the binding EX→flop arc without touching any pipeline payload struct.\n\nThis is structurally analogous to r3s0 (consolidate duplicate arithmetic) but targets the output mux, not the input DSP. No new pipeline fields, no IF-path widening, no forwarding-path change, no formal-state growth. ALTOPS branch keeps its XOR stand-ins (preserves formal BMC depth).","time":{"start":1777777983765,"end":1777778015982}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777778015994,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef91ffeS7Emr0lEdRj3ks","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01T26azHRkfPzmYwY4a84qPD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r12s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r12s0\ntitle: \"Absorb div_result into ALU case, eliminating the external alu_result_eff 32b 2:1 mux on the EX flop arc\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The EX-stage output flop's binding combinational arc is:\n    rs_forward_mux → operand_mux → ALU(19-way case) → alu_result_eff(2:1)\n    → flop_input_mux(is_jump ? pc+4 : _) → EX/MEM.alu_result\n  The alu_result_eff mux (`(is_div_op && div_done) ? div_result : alu.out`)\n  is a 32-bit 2:1 mux living OUTSIDE the ALU, gating the ALU's DIV/DIVU/\n  REM/REMU case-arm outputs (currently forced to 32'b0 under non-ALTOPS\n  as a don't-care placeholder). This external mux adds ~1 LUT4 level of\n  combinational depth on a path that fitness history (r5s1 +8.79%, r3s0\n  +8.50%, r8s0 +5.99%) shows is sensitive to Fmax — and it duplicates\n  selection work the ALU's own case mux could absorb for free. The\n  r8s0 meta-rule (\"rewrites pay when they eliminate an ARITHMETIC\n  dependency or shorten the critical path by a structurally-guaranteed\n  LUT level, never merely boolean AND/OR\") applies here: this is a\n  structural mux-depth reduction, not a boolean simplification, so it\n  escapes the r9s2/r11s0 \"synth already found it\" trap.\nhypothesis: |\n  Route the divider's `div_result` (and a `div_done` qualifier for the\n  DONE-cycle select) into alu.sv as new inputs. In the ALU's case\n  statement, replace the current non-ALTOPS `ALU_DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU:\n  out = 32'b0` arms with `out = div_result` (the arm is only selected\n  when EX is holding a DIV/REM op anyway, and under the existing\n  div_busy stall the EX/MEM flop only captures on the DONE cycle where\n  div_result is stable). Delete the `alu_result_eff` wire in ex_stage\n  and drive `reg_q.alu_result` directly from `is_jump ? (pc+4) :\n  alu_result`. The ALTOPS branch in alu.sv is unchanged — its XOR\n  stand-ins already live in those case arms, so riscv-formal's BMC\n  depth and RVFI semantics are byte-identical to baseline.\n\n  Why this is expected to help on Tang Nano 20K / GW2A:\n  1. One less LUT4 level on the EX→flop arc (the external 2:1 mux is\n     gone — the 19-way ALU case mux absorbs the select for free because\n     case-arm outputs are already a mux tree at the output port).\n  2. No new pipeline payload fields (the r5s2/r6s2/r8s2/r10s2 payload-\n     cost lesson doesn't apply — div_result is module-to-module wiring,\n     not a flopped field).\n  3. No change to the forwarding cone (r5s1-r11s1 MEM→EX and WB→EX\n     forwarding lessons unaffected — div_result fans INTO the ALU\n     input, not OUT of its alu_result).\n  4. No change to IF-stage next_pc mux (r4s2/r8s2/r10s2 IF-widening\n     lesson unaffected).\n  5. Formal proof time unchanged: under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS the divider\n     module is not instantiated and the ALU's ALTOPS arms still hit\n     (div_result is a dangling 32'b0 tie under ifdef in that mode).\n\n  Risk triage against historical failure modes:\n  - r9s1 (mem_wb_t pre-muxed wb_data → PREUNSAT): this hypothesis does\n    NOT remove any RVFI-observable field or rename mem_wb_t — the ALU\n    output path is pre-flop internal, and rvfi_rd_wdata's provenance\n    (wb_stage.w_data) is unchanged.\n  - r7s0/r11s0 (manual CSE / boolean collapse → regress): this is not\n    a CSE — it's a structural mux-elimination that removes an ACTUAL\n    separate 2:1 mux from the netlist. The reduction is visible to the\n    synth flow as \"one fewer case-mux level on the EX output cone,\"\n    which is r8s0-class (shortens combinational depth), not r11s0-class\n    (reshuffles AND/OR terms).\n  - r10s0 (DSP split → regress): not applicable — we aren't splitting\n    the DSP's outputs, we're consolidating a downstream mux into the\n    ALU's existing output case.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n    description: |\n      Add two new inputs: `input logic [31:0] div_result` and\n      `input logic div_done`. Under `\\`ifndef RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS`,\n      change the ALU_DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU case arms from `out = 32'b0`\n      to `out = div_result`. The ALTOPS branch (XOR stand-ins)\n      remains unchanged. div_done is reserved for a future gate but\n      wired in now so ex_stage doesn't need to mux externally.\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Connect the divider instance's `result` and `done` outputs to\n      the ALU's new `div_result` / `div_done` inputs. Remove the\n      `alu_result_eff` wire and its combinational mux; drive\n      `reg_q.alu_result <= in.ctrl.is_jump ? (in.pc + 32'd4) :\n      alu_result;` directly (where `alu_result` is now the ALU's\n      absorbed output). Under RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, tie div_result\n      and div_done to 32'b0 / 1'b0 (the divider isn't instantiated\n      in that mode and the ALU's ALTOPS arms still hit).\n  - file: test/test_alu.py\n    description: |\n      Update the ALU testbench's DUT port map to supply the new\n      `div_result` / `div_done` inputs (tie both to 0 for all\n      existing vectors — the non-ALTOPS DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU vectors\n      now expect `out = div_result = 0` which matches the previous\n      \"tie to zero\" semantics for the ALU's combinational DIV path).\n      Add one vector per DIV op that drives div_result to a non-zero\n      value and checks that alu.out forwards it through the case arm.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r12s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r12s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777778015969,"end":1777778015989}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the key patterns from previous optimizations, I'm noticing that targeted simplifications in specific pipeline stages tend to yield the biggest wins—algebraic pre-adder tricks, DSP consolidation, and divider sequentialization all worked well. The IF-stage path seems particularly constrained, so I should avoid widening next_pc there and instead focus on other bottlenecks for this micro_opt hypothesis.\n\nThe MEM→EX forwarding leg is hostile to timing, and manual CSE on LUT4s doesn't help since synthesis already handles it. Boolean rewrites are similarly redundant, so I should focus only on arithmetic-dependency optimizations. Looking at the ALU, the barrel shifter regressed before, and DSP is already consolidated. The auipc mux sitting in front of the ALU adds unnecessary depth on the input path, and while the multiplier computes unconditionally each cycle, synthesis should optimize that away. The real opportunity seems to be in the regfile bypass logic—the write-first path from wb_stage through mem_wb_q creates a long combinational chain that's likely impacting timing.\n\nRemoving the bypass would shorten the regfile's critical path, but I need to think through the forwarding implications carefully. The forwarding unit already handles MEM/WB cases, so the bypass is somewhat redundant, though it does allow same-cycle reads at ID to see freshly-written values. The timing trade-off is whether accepting one cycle of stale data at ID is worth cutting that long combinational path. ctness without compensating forwarding — that's a fundamental blocker. Let me explore other optimization angles instead. The load data bypass through the MEM stage looks promising since the byte shifting and sign extension happen combinationally from the BRAM output, but moving that across the pipeline register boundary creates issues like what r11s1 showed. For the multiplier path, the sign-extension controls are just a few bit comparisons feeding into the DSP, so there's probably not much to gain there without affecting inference. The variable shift for load alignment uses a 2-bit control to select byte offsets, but it's already fairly tight since the BRAM output is late and feeds through multiple mux levels.\n\nLooking at the MEM/WB register itself, it's carrying a lot of RVFI-only signals like memory addresses and masks that aren't on the critical path, though they're needed for verification. The forwarding unit's priority logic produces a 2-bit select for a 3:1 mux, but that sits in a chain with the AUIPC mux and ALU source mux before reaching the ALU itself — the immediate value for AUIPC and the register operand for ordinary instructions both feed through these muxes in sequence.\n\nI could potentially fold the AUIPC path into the forwarding logic since rs1 isn't actually read for AUIPC instructions, or precompute PC+immediate earlier in the pipeline, though that adds another adder. The PC+4 computation for jumps is already in the EX stage and doesn't seem to be a bottleneck based on earlier analysis.\n\nThe real constraint now is area — we're at 5446 LUT4s out of a 10000 target, and Fmax is already comfortably above 135 MHz at 177 MHz. The focus should shift to reducing LUT usage to improve placement and routing.\n\nLooking at the EX stage more carefully, there's a cascade of multiplexers stacked before the flop: the forwarding mux feeds into the AUIPC/ALU source mux, then the ALU output, then a divide-result mux, then finally a jump-PC mux — that's potentially three or more LUT4 levels just for the ALU result path. I could potentially bypass the ALU for JAL/JALR by treating them as ADD operations with PC and 4 as operands, eliminating one of those post-ALU muxes.\n\nAlternatively, merging the jump and divide muxes into a single 4:1 selector would be structurally cleaner, though synthesis probably already does this optimization.\n\nLet me think about what could actually move the needle. For the multiply operations, the `a_signed` signal is a 5-bit inequality check against ALU_MULHU, combined with `a[31]` via AND to feed the DSP's sign-extension input. Looking at the opcode assignments — MULHU is 13, MULH is 12, MULHSU is 14, MUL is 11 — I'm wondering if there's a simpler bit pattern that would let me extract the sign-extension control more directly without the full comparison.\n\nThe constraint is that `a_signed` should be 1 for MUL, MULH, and MULHSU, but 0 only for MULHU. Examining the binary representations, I'm trying to find a single-bit or simple logic expression that separates MULHU from the others, but the bit patterns don't align cleanly enough to avoid a multi-input decoder.\n\nReassigning the opcode for MULHU to something like `10000` could make the logic simpler, but that would require updating the decoder mapping throughout the design, which is probably not worth the effort for this one signal.\n\nThe multiply product itself is computed unconditionally every cycle as a combinational operation that likely maps to a DSP block, which does consume power but isn't a critical path or area concern. LUI is straightforward—it just passes the immediate through the ALU with minimal cost. I'm also noticing that the regfile already handles zeroing x0, so there's no fast-path optimization there. Looking at the mem_wb_t struct, some RVFI signals like `rs1_val` might be unused and could be candidates for removal.\n\nActually, those register values are needed at writeback for RVFI output, so carrying them through the pipeline is necessary. The DSP block gets instantiated regardless of whether we use it conditionally, so gating won't help with power. And from the r10s0 experience, adding explicit pipeline registers around the DSP tends to backfire since Yosys already infers internal DSP pipeline stages.\n\nLet me look at the immediate generator logic...\n\nGenerating immediate decoder... I'm realizing the ALU for JAL doesn't actually need special handling—it just computes garbage that gets overridden by the `is_jump` mux anyway. The real question is whether I could eliminate that mux layer by encoding the `pc+4` computation into the ALU itself, but that would require changing how immediates and operands are routed, and it's not clear it saves anything since the mux is already at the flop boundary and not on the critical path.\n\nLet me pivot to a different optimization: simplifying how the divider operations are decoded...\n\nDefining divider operation codes...\n\nIf I renumber the ALU opcodes so the four division operations occupy the top bits (111xx), I can replace the multi-bit comparator with a simple 3-bit equality check and extract the operation type directly from the lower 2 bits instead of using a mux. This trades decoder and ALU updates across multiple files for cleaner hardware, though the scope of changes is substantial.\n\nBut actually, div_busy feeds into the hazard unit's stall logic which gates the pipeline flops — if this path were critical I could optimize it, but the algebraic collapse from earlier runs suggests it's not the bottleneck. Let me focus elsewhere.\n\nThe real issue is the MEM→EX forwarding path. The writeback stage muxes between load data and ALU result, then that output feeds back to EX as a forward signal. This path chains through multiple muxes in the ALU pipeline. I could move that mux computation into the memory stage itself, shortening what the EX stage sees.\n\nBut an earlier attempt to collapse the read_data and alu_result fields into a single wb_data field failed formal verification. The issue was that trap handling needs access to the original alu_result as a sidecar — when a load instruction traps, the formal solver needs to distinguish between what gets written to the regfile versus what the RVFI interface reports, and removing alu_result from the MEM/WB payload eliminated a degree of freedom the solver was using to verify this behavior.\n\nNow I'm working through whether pre-muxing the data in the MEM stage would actually solve this. The key question is whether the mux should happen before or after trap gating — if it happens before, a trapped load would still compute the load_data path, but reg_write=0 would prevent it from being written, which should be equivalent to the current behavior where read_data and alu_result are kept separate and muxed later in WB.\n\nThe formal failure with r9s1 suggests there's some subtle implementation issue I'm not catching, so I should probably avoid retrying that exact approach.\n\nLet me shift focus to other optimizations. The hazard unit's stall and flush signals are already pretty tightly coupled with shared OR chains, so there's probably not much room to simplify there. But looking at the ALU itself — it handles 19 operations total: the 11 base RV32I instructions plus 8 M-extension ops, where the division operations just return 0 and defer to the divider unit. That's a 19-way mux which takes several LUT levels. I could try collapsing the DIV, DIVU, REM, and REMU cases since they all produce the same output.\n\nActually, wait — those cases are already redundant with the default case that returns 0, so removing them wouldn't change functionality and Yosys probably optimizes this away anyway. The multiplier width is also already trimmed by synthesis. I'm running low on promising micro-optimizations that haven't been explored already.\n\nLet me think about whether there's anything else worth trying — early redirect from EX to IF was already saturated in previous runs, and the memory address path is just a direct register output with no combinational logic to tighten. The register file inference might be worth examining though.\n\nThe read-first behavior is needed for write-first bypass to support same-cycle ID→WB forwarding, but if I added a pipeline stage to delay the read output, that would require architectural changes that previous runs flagged as violating test constraints. For the PC-relative computations, I notice branch_target and jump_target both compute pc+imm, and AUIPC also does pc+imm through the ALU — these should already be sharing the same adder through Yosys's common subexpression elimination, though a prior attempt at manual CSE actually regressed performance.\n\nI'm thinking about a few concrete micro-optimizations: consolidating the alu_result selection logic in the EX-stage output flop into a cleaner 3-way mux, though synthesis probably already infers this; pre-muxing the mem_to_reg selection at the MEM stage instead of waiting until WB, but that was attempted before and failed; and sharing the multiplier result between MUL and MULH operations since they both use the same product computation.\n\nLooking at the multiplier more closely, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU all output the upper 32 bits of the product, just with different sign handling in the inputs. The output mux itself is trivial—just a 2:1 selector between the lower and upper halves—and Yosys already handles this efficiently, so there's no obvious savings there.\n\nI'm also considering whether we could shorten the ID→EX path by pre-decoding the opcode in the IF stage and passing hints through the IF/ID boundary, but that would widen the pipeline payload, which r5s2 showed is costly. Another angle is rethinking the decoder logic itself—maybe computing it via functional groups rather than a giant case statement could reduce gate count, though I'm not sure how much that would actually help.\n\nLooking at the ctrl_t output fields, most of them are already implicitly optimized by Yosys. For instance, reg_write is 1 for most instruction types and could be expressed as a 6-way OR, but that's already what the case statement encodes. Same with alu_src and other control signals.\n\nI'm thinking the real win might be reordering the ALU operation encoding so that checking for division operations becomes a single bit test rather than multiple comparisons.\n\nIf I move the division operations (DIV, DIVU, REM, REMU) to occupy a contiguous range in the upper bits of alu_op—say positions 28-31 where the top 2 bits are both 1—then is_div_op becomes just a 2-input AND gate checking those high bits. That's one LUT4 instead of a 4-way decoder. The changes would be localized: renumbering the cases in alu.sv, updating the localparams in core_pkg.sv, remapping the decoder output, and simplifying the ex_stage logic.\n\nBut I'm realizing this might not actually help with the critical path since the div_busy chain wasn't shown to be timing-critical. And with LUT count at 5446 out of 10000, area pressure isn't really the binding constraint either.\n\nLet me think about this from a different angle.\n\nActually, looking at the alu_b selection chain in ex_stage—when alu_src is 1 (for I-type, LOAD, STORE, etc.), alu_b gets the immediate directly, so the forwarding mux output for rs2 isn't even used on the ALU's alu_b input. But that same forwarded rs2 value still feeds other paths like branch condition and store write data, so the forward mux itself is still on the critical path regardless.\n\nThe key insight is that when alu_src=1, we get a short path from the immediate flop to the ALU, but when alu_src=0 (R-type and BRANCH), we're stuck with the longer rs2-forward-mux path. The critical path is whichever is slower.\n\nI'm wondering if we could move the rs2 forwarding decision earlier—compute it at ID stage instead of EX stage, so the mux result is ready before the flop. But that's tricky because at ID, we'd need to predict which instruction will be in EX/MEM next cycle to know if forwarding is needed, and the pipeline timing gets complicated.\n\nActually, the forwarding sources at ID are one cycle too early compared to what we'd need at EX, so precomputing doesn't work without speculation and correction. A simpler approach is what we already have: the regfile includes a write-first bypass so that when WB writes back, the ID stage can immediately read the new value combinationally, and then EX stage has additional forwarding paths from EX/MEM and MEM/WB for cases where the producer is still in flight.\n\nNow I'm clarifying which forwarding path catches which producer-consumer gap: the write-first bypass at ID handles the case where the producer is at WB during the same cycle the consumer reads, the EX/MEM→EX forward handles a 1-cycle gap, and the MEM/WB→EX forward handles a 2-cycle gap. Let me trace through the timing more carefully to make sure each path is actually needed. The producer instruction is long gone from the pipeline by then, so there's no source to forward from—removing the bypass would require restructuring the pipeline itself.\n\nLet me consider a different angle. One option is to fast-path the JAL/JALR return address through a precomputed pc+4 value passed down the pipeline, but that adds payload overhead which prior experiments showed hurts fitness. Another thought: the wb_stage mux selecting between memory data and ALU result sits on the critical path to both the forwarding network and regfile, so eliminating it by pre-muxing in mem_stage would help—but formal verification failed on that approach.\n\nI could also try narrowing the forward unit's encoding or removing unused ALU operations, though the synthesizer probably already handles those. Let me focus on what's actually blocking the critical path: the EX stage's register update has three mux layers stacked together—the ALU's internal case statement, then the jump-vs-ALU mux, then the div-vs-ALU mux—which chains through multiple LUT levels.\n\nI'm considering whether I can eliminate the jump mux by routing JAL and JALR through the ALU itself, computing PC+4 as an ALU operation. But that would require either feeding the PC into the ALU or overriding the immediate generator, both of which add complexity without clear benefit. I'll skip that approach.\n\nNow I'm exploring a different angle: decoupling the divider FSM from the EX pipeline stall using a rendezvous mechanism instead of the current blocking approach.\n\nActually, divisions barely show up in CoreMark, so optimizing that path won't help throughput. Not worth the effort.\n\nI could try widening the ALU operand mux to forward load data in the same cycle when it's safe, but that's a critical path killer for Fmax. Skipping that too.\n\nHere's something cleaner: the multiplier's signedness derivation is unnecessarily deep. Currently I'm computing `a_signed` and `b_signed` through multiple comparisons and logic gates, but if I re-encode the MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU opcodes strategically, I can extract the signedness directly from a single bit, cutting the combinational depth and letting Yosys map it more efficiently to the DSP's built-in mode pins. I'm working through a cleaner encoding scheme where the signedness flags map directly to single bits—`a_signed = !op[0]` and `b_signed = !op[1]` within mul operations—which would reduce the decode logic from multiple LUT4s down to just one. The tradeoff is that this requires renumbering the ALU opcodes across several files (core_pkg, alu, decoder, ex_stage), though each change is fairly localized and shouldn't affect formal verification since the behavior stays the same. I'm questioning whether this actually helps Fmax though, since the DSP itself is typically fast and the real bottleneck is probably the output mux selecting which slice of the multiplier result to use.\n\nThere's a stronger case for the renumbering if it lets me replace the `is_div_op` and `div_op_code` decodes with simple bit slices instead of a 4-way case statement—that saves a couple of LUT4s per signal. But `is_div_op` feeds the hazard chain (not critical) and `div_op_code` goes to the divider FSM, so the net win might still be small.\n\nI'm now exploring a different angle: absorbing the divider result directly into the ALU's output path by routing `div_result` as an input to the ALU and having the DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU cases output it directly, which would eliminate the `alu_result_eff` mux in ex_stage. The timing works because `div_result` is only valid on the DONE cycle, and the ALU output is only flopped when `stall_ex_mem` is released—which is gated by `div_busy` and only happens at DONE anyway.\n\nThis costs routing 32 bits into the ALU and changes its interface, but that's acceptable since alu.sv isn't in the don't-touch list. Under ALTOPS the ALU already has the XOR stand-in for division, so I'd need to preserve that branch while adding the `div_result` input for the non-ALTOPS case.\n\nThe real question is whether the mux depth reduction is worth it. Currently the EX output path chains through forward mux, operand mux, the 19-way ALU case, then the alu_result_eff mux with div_result, then the final flop input mux with pc+4. Collapsing div_result into the ALU eliminates one level, saving roughly 11% of the critical path on this 177 MHz fabric—though Yosys might already fold this away. The case statement ensures div_result only drives the output when op is actually a division operation, so there's no risk of accidentally routing it through on other instructions. This looks like a clean win worth proposing.\n\nBut I need to handle the ALTOPS mode carefully—when formal verification runs with ALTOPS enabled, the ALU computes an XOR stand-in instead of instantiating the divider, so I'll need conditional compilation to switch between outputting the XOR result and the actual div_result depending on the mode. The divider's output is stable by the DONE cycle anyway, so moving it into the ALU's case mux structure shouldn't hurt timing—I'm just removing that external 2:1 mux layer. This should give a modest boost, maybe 2-5% improvement in fitness.\n\nYosys might already be collapsing these muxes together through optimization, but it's a small enough change that it's worth attempting. I'll estimate around 3% gain with medium confidence.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debd3578f001025AOnIK13be7Q","sessionID":"ses_2142fef91ffeS7Emr0lEdRj3ks","messageID":"msg_debd010dc0015y5Hhe5spmSCMG"}}
