bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX c...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Pre-register rd_wdata at MEM/WB boundary to shorten forward + regfile read paths\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\\nconsumers:\\n\\n  1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\\n     the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 fwd_rs?_sel mux \\u2192 is_auipc mux \\u2192\\n     ALU \\u2192 EX/MEM flop \\u2014 four mux levels before ALU input.\\n  2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\\n     ID-stage's regfile read path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 regfile bypass mux \\u2192 ID/EX flop\\n     \\u2014 two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\\n     rd matches.\\n\\nThat extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\\nplausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\\n1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\\ntransformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Fold MUL variants into single 33x33 signed multiplier with sign-ext mux\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\\non every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\\nmul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\\nmultiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\\ndedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes three separate 64-bit products unconditionally\\non every EX cycle: mul_ss (signed*signed), mul_uu (unsigned*unsigned), and\\nmul_su (signed*unsigned). Yosys synthesises each as a distinct 33x33 signed\\nmultiplier, and on Tang Nano 20K (GW2A) each multiplier instantiates a\\ndedicated DSP18 (or LUT-cascade) block. Running three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su with a single 33-bit signed multiplier\\nwhose operand sign bits are muxed from op: MUL / MULH use signed*signed\\n(sign-extend both), MULHU uses unsigned*unsig...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Stateless IF-stage backward-taken branch prediction (BTFNT)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) eliminated the 2-cycle redirect\\nbubble for unconditional jumps. The next structural lever on the same\\naxis is conditional branches \\u2014 still paying a 2-cycle EX-redirect penalty\\nevery time a branch is taken. In CoreMark's hot loops (core_list_find,\\ncrcu8/crcu16 bit loops, core_bench_matrix nested loops, core_state state\\nmachines) the dominant control flow is loop-closing backward branches\\nthat are taken on every iteration except the last. A 5-iteration loop\\npays 2 bubbles \\u00d7 4 = 8 cycles of taken-branch redirect and 0 cycles on\\nthe exit-fallthrough; a 50-iteration loop pays 98 cycles of bubbles.\\n\\nStatic backwards-taken / forwards-not-taken (BTFNT) is the classic\\nprediction heuristic that captures this without any history: a BRANCH\\ninstruction whose sign-extended B-immediate is negative is almost\\ncertainly a loop edge. The r1s2 BTB lesson (broken, formal timeout)\\nwas that threading speculative state through the RVFI-observed payload\\nblows the per-insn BMC budget. The r2s2 lesson was the exact opposite\\npattern succeeds: a *stateless* predictor whose decision is a pure\\nfunction of the already-observed (PC, instr) pair costs zero formal\\nstate because EX can re-derive the IF-side decision from the same bits\\nit already has in ID/EX.\\n\\nOn CoreMark (~15% branch frequency, ~70% backward-taken), eliminating\\nthe 2-cycle bubble on backward-taken branches while paying a 2-cycle\\nbubble on the ~30% of backward branches that fall through (loop\\nexits, rare) is net-positive IPC. Rough estimate: 0.15 \\u00d7 0.70 \\u00d7 2 =\\n0.21 cycle savings per dynamic instr, offset by 0.15 \\u00d7 0.30 \\u00d7 2 = 0.09\\nnew mispredict cost \\u2248 0.12 cycle/instr net, i.e. ~8\\u201310% IPC win on\\ntop of the JAL baseline. Fmax impact is expected to be minimal:\\nthe IF-stage critical path...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"(slot 1 hypothesis-gen failed)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"hypothesis_gen_failed: Hypothesis agent modified off-limits paths and was rolled back: ['cores/bench/test/test_pipeline.py']\", \"slot\": 1, \"round_id\": 4, \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Fitness history shows Fmax is the dominant lever: JAL predictor (r2s2)\\nand DSP fold (r3s0) both won primarily via Fmax (135.21 -> 141.58 ->\\n153.61 MHz, tracking 1:1 with fitness). Conversely r1s0/r1s1 (divider,\\nmulti-cycle M-unit) regressed despite targeting EX-stage arithmetic,\\nproving the EX LUT path (now DSP-consolidated) is NOT the current\\nceiling. The remaining deepest combinational window is the IF->ID\\npath: in today's 5-stage the only register between the FPGA BRAM's\\noutput flop (imem_data) and id_ex_reg is a full cycle containing\\n(a) the decoder's ~20-arm case statement producing 15 control bits,\\n(b) the 32-bit imm_gen, (c) the 32x32 regfile distributed-LUT read\\nwith write-first bypass mux, and (d) the ctrl_t packing into\\nid_ex_reg. That is easily 10-15 LUT4 levels on Gowin GW2A, which at\\n~0.35 ns/LUT plus routing is right at the 6.5 ns period of 153 MHz.\\nUntil this path is split, neither JAL-nor-DSP-class optimizations\\ncan unlock the next Fmax tier; both r3s1 and r3s2 already confirmed\\nthat speculative branch prediction cannot close under SBY, so the\\nremaining structural move is pipeline-depth rebalance.\\n\\nAt LUT4=9865/target 10000 we also have routing-pressure evidence\\n(seed-to-seed Fmax variance was ~15 MHz before r3s0 settled it),\\nwhich a shallower per-stage logic depth directly relieves.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the 5-stage IF->ID->EX->MEM->WB pipeline to a 6-stage\\nIF->IFD->ID->EX->MEM->WB by inserting a new IFD pipeline register\\nwhose payload is ALREADY-DECODED control. Specifically:\\n\\n1. Move the decoder, imm_gen, and the JAL-target pre-computation into\\n   the IF stage. I...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative 32-cycle sequential divider module\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in\\nthe EX stage (32-bit restoring division fanning into the ALU\\noutput mux, which then feeds EX/MEM's alu_result register plus\\nthe forwarding path to the next cycle's EX operand muxes).\\n\\nMeanwhile CoreMark is an integer benchmark dominated by list\\ntraversal, matrix multiply, and CRC/state transitions; its\\ndynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM ops.\\nSo whatever Fmax and LUT budget is being spent on the\\ncombinational divider is pure waste for this fitness function.\\n\\nThe successful r3s0 hypothesis (+8.50% from folding 3 DSP18\\nmultipliers into 1) established the pattern: identify EX-stage\\narithmetic structures whose current implementation over-spends\\nFPGA resources, and consolidate/sequentialize them. The divider\\nis the most egregious remaining instance \\u2014 a single 32-bit\\ncombinational divide is worth more LUT4s than the rest of the\\nALU combined and sits on the EX critical path.\\n\\nCurrent fitness 345.80 at 153.61 MHz; Fmax target is 135 MHz\\n(we're already over) but Gowin timing closure on GW2A tightens\\nsharply above 150 MHz \\u2014 removing the combinational divider\\nshould push Fmax materially further.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Non-speculative compare-in-ID early branch resolution (halve taken-branch bubble to 1 cycle)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"After r2s2's JAL predictor (+5.87%), the dominant remaining control-flow\\npenalty is the 2-cycle redirect bubble on every taken conditional branch\\n(opcode 0x63). Five prior IF-stage *speculative* attempts to attack this\\nbubble all failed:\\n  - r1s2 (BTB) blew the formal budget by threading predicted/pred_target\\n    through if_id_t/id_ex_t.\\n  - r3s1 (BTFNT) / r3s2 (BTFN) triggered the symbolic-fetch coupling\\n    trap: narrowing EX `redirect` to `mispredict` correlates the gate\\n    with `branch_taken`, and SBY's induction for the `reg` property\\n    cannot close the loop where IF redirects onto an address whose\\n    `imem_data` is itself a free symbolic variable AND the branch's\\n    resolved direction is also free.\\n  - r4s2 (tautological rs1==rs2) passed formal but the idiom is ~zero\\n    in compiler-emitted code, and the extra B-imm adder / 3-way mux\\n    cost Fmax. Net -7.92%.\\n  - r5s2 (RAS for JALR returns, formal-gated) passed formal but the\\n    4-way next_pc mux and EX ret_pred_hit comparator blew Fmax on the\\n    Tang Nano 20K IF/EX critical paths. Net -60.03%.\\n\\nThe r3s2 lesson distills the explicit mitigation direction:\\n  \\\"future branch-prediction hypotheses should either target the\\n   EX-stage bubble reduction path (non-speculative, keeps IF linear)\\n   or accept that a formal wrapper-level assume ... is required\\\"\\n\\nThis hypothesis takes the non-speculative path. It has NOT been tried.\\nAll five prior predictor attempts were IF-stage speculation \\u2014 none\\nmoved the resolution itself earlier in the pipeline.\\n\\nCoreMark's dynamic trace is dominated by tight loops (crcu8 inner,\\ncore_list_find reverse walk, core_bench_matrix triple-nested i/j/k,\\ncore_state_transition dispatch). Assuming ~12% of dynamic instructions\\nare conditional branches with ~55% taken rate, cutti...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate redundant PC+imm and PC+4 adders on the EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.imm            (branch-resolve block)\\n  (2) jump_target   = (in.pc + in.imm) | jalr   (jump-target block)\\n  (3) reg_q.pc_next <= misalign ? (in.pc + 4)\\n                     : is_jump   ? jump_target\\n                     : taken     ? branch_target\\n                                 : (in.pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.i...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Sequentialize MUL/MULH* into a 2-cycle pipelined DSP multiplier (r5s1 pattern for multiply)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"r5s1 netted +8.79% by extracting DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU into a\\n32-cycle iterative FSM \\u2014 rare-in-workload but LUT-hungry arithmetic was\\nsitting on the EX critical path and paying Fmax for every cycle. The same\\nargument applies verbatim to MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU: CoreMark's dynamic\\ninstruction mix contains very few multiplies (the core loops are list/matrix\\npointer chase + ALU ops, not MAC-dense), but the 33x33 signed multiplier\\nconsolidated in r3s0 is still a COMBINATIONAL path that feeds mul_prod[63:0]\\ninto the EX-stage alu_result mux every cycle. On GW2A the DSP18 block\\nsupports an internal pipeline register that Yosys/himbaechel will only\\ninfer if we register the product \\u2014 leaving it combinational forces a\\nsame-cycle 33x33 multiply + sign-ext mux + 2:1 alu_result mux all before\\nthe EX/MEM flop, which is almost certainly the current Fmax-limiting\\nchain after r5s1 removed the divider from it.\\n\\nCurrent core: Fmax 167.11 MHz, LUT4 5469, fitness 376.19. The EX ALU's\\nmul_prod is the tallest remaining combinational tree (r6s0 confirmed the\\nbarrel shifter is already opportunistically shared and not a fat tree).\\nOne-cycle multiply sequentialization is the lowest-risk Fmax play left.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r5s1 netted +8.79% by extracting DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU into a\\n32-cycle iterative FSM \\u2014 rare-in-workload but LUT-hungry arithmetic was\\nsitting on the EX critical path and paying Fmax for every cycle. The same\\nargument applies verbatim to MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU: CoreMark's dynamic\\ninstruction mix contains very few multiplies (the core loops are list/matrix\\npointer chase + ALU ops, not MAC-dense), but the 33x33 signed multiplier\\nconsolidated in r3s0 is still a COMBINATIONAL path that feeds mul_prod[63:0]\\ninto the EX-stage alu...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Eliminate load-use bubble via combinational MEM->EX load_data forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-branch IPC loss\\nis the load-use hazard: a 1-cycle bubble inserted by hazard_unit\\nwhenever an instruction in IF/ID consumes rd of a LOAD currently in\\nID/EX. CoreMark is pointer-chase-heavy (core_list_find reverse walk,\\ncore_bench_matrix row/column dereferences, core_state_transition's\\ncharacter-class table lookup, crcu16/32 inner loops) \\u2014 every dependent\\nload pays this stall. Empirically this is the single most common\\nnon-branch pipeline bubble in CoreMark's dynamic trace.\\n\\nStructural gap search: none of the prior iterations attempted this.\\nr5s1 (divider extraction, +8.79%) and r3s0 (DSP fold, +8.50%) both\\nsucceeded by removing waste from the EX datapath; the symmetric move\\non the DATA side is to make the LOAD-to-dependent path single-cycle\\ninstead of 2-cycle. r2s0's rd_wdata consolidation tried to shorten\\nthe MEM/WB forwarding path but broke the reg_ch0 formal check by\\nmis-plumbing the RVFI tap \\u2014 that failure was a wiring bug, not a\\nstructural impossibility. This hypothesis attacks a different path\\n(MEM combinational, not MEM/WB registered) and explicitly preserves\\nevery RVFI field's provenance byte-for-byte.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-b...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Pipeline MULH/MULHU/MULHSU high-32 output via registered DSP tap, leaving MUL combinational\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After r3s0 consolidated MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU onto a single 33x33 signed DSP,\\nthe shared 66-bit product sits on the EX combinational chain from a/b \\u2192 DSP \\u2192\\nmul_prod \\u2192 case mux \\u2192 alu_result \\u2192 alu_result_eff mux \\u2192 is_jump mux \\u2192 EX/MEM\\nflop. Of the four MUL-class ops, only MUL reads mul_prod[31:0] (cheap low\\ncarry chain); MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read mul_prod[63:32], the longest carry chain\\nin the EX datapath. r5s1 (+8.79%) established that cold-in-workload /\\nhot-in-ISA arithmetic is free real estate for sequentialization on this\\nTang Nano 20K flow (the combinational LUT tree sat on the critical path but\\nthe dynamic op frequency in CoreMark was near-zero). r7s1 (-7.56%) is the\\nsharp caveat: the DIV\\u2192FSM pattern does NOT transfer to MUL because CoreMark's\\nmatrix/state/CRC kernels multiply constantly, so per-MUL latency cost\\ndominates any Fmax win. MULH* falls squarely on r5s1's side of that line \\u2014\\nthese ops appear almost exclusively in high-precision-arithmetic idioms\\nCoreMark doesn't exercise (32\\u00d732\\u219264 extraction is rare in CRC/matrix/state),\\nso paying a 1-cycle stall per MULH* while keeping MUL combinational should\\nnet mostly Fmax upside with negligible IPC downside.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After r3s0 consolidated MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU onto a single 33x33 signed DSP,\\nthe shared 66-bit product sits on the EX combinational chain from a/b \\u2192 DSP \\u2192\\nmul_prod \\u2192 case mux \\u2192 alu_result \\u2192 alu_result_eff mux \\u2192 is_jump mux \\u2192 EX/MEM\\nflop. Of the four MUL-class ops, only MUL reads mul_prod[31:0] (cheap low\\ncarry chain); MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read mul_prod[63:32], the longest carry chain\\nin the EX datapath. r5s1 (+8.79%) established that cold-in-workload /\\nhot-in-ISA arithmetic is free real estate for ...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Algebraically collapse div_busy to is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The ex_stage.sv divider handshake feeds the hazard_unit's stall_if /\\nstall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb outputs, which drive the clock\\nenables of every pipeline register in the core. Any LUT4 depth on\\nthat fanout path translates directly into Fmax pressure on Tang Nano\\n20K, where r5s1's +8.79% win already confirmed that touching the\\ndivider-to-hazard path moves the fitness needle.\\n\\nCurrently:\\n  div_start_pulse = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_busy_int && !div_done_int;\\n  div_busy        = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\\n                    && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse);\\n\\nLet X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int. Substituting:\\n  div_busy = X && (div_busy_int || (X && !div_busy_int))\\n- X=0: div_busy=0.\\n- X=1: div_busy = (div_busy_int || !div_busy_int) = 1.\\nSo div_busy is bit-exact equivalent to X \\u2014 the ORed div_start_pulse\\nterm is algebraically redundant against the outer AND gate. This is\\nexactly the r8s0 pattern: a module-local algebraic simplification\\nusing only signals already driven in ex_stage (no pipelined-operand\\ninvariants like r9s0's doomed EX-side pc/rs1 rewrite, which is the\\ntrap that breaks BMC reachability).\\n\\nCritically, this is NOT the r9s2 failure mode: r9s2 removed boolean\\nguards (!flush, !redirect) that were already being absorbed into the\\nupstream priority-mux flattening for the PC flop, so the claimed\\nLUT4 reduction was imaginary and the removal only perturbed placement\\nfor the worse. The div_busy rewrite attacks a genuine redundant AND/OR\\nchain that feeds a NON-priority-mux consumer (hazard_unit's stall\\noutputs are simple OR-reductions across stall reasons, not priority\\nmuxes), so Yosys's priority-mux absorption does not already cover it.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ex_stage.sv divider handshake feeds the hazard_unit's stall_...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260503-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Absorb div_result into ALU case, eliminating the external alu_result_eff 32b 2:1 mux on the EX flop arc\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage output flop's binding combinational arc is:\\n  rs_forward_mux \\u2192 operand_mux \\u2192 ALU(19-way case) \\u2192 alu_result_eff(2:1)\\n  \\u2192 flop_input_mux(is_jump ? pc+4 : _) \\u2192 EX/MEM.alu_result\\nThe alu_result_eff mux (`(is_div_op && div_done) ? div_result : alu.out`)\\nis a 32-bit 2:1 mux living OUTSIDE the ALU, gating the ALU's DIV/DIVU/\\nREM/REMU case-arm outputs (currently forced to 32'b0 under non-ALTOPS\\nas a don't-care placeholder). This external mux adds ~1 LUT4 level of\\ncombinational depth on a path that fitness history (r5s1 +8.79%, r3s0\\n+8.50%, r8s0 +5.99%) shows is sensitive to Fmax \\u2014 and it duplicates\\nselection work the ALU's own case mux could absorb for free. The\\nr8s0 meta-rule (\\\"rewrites pay when they eliminate an ARITHMETIC\\ndependency or shorten the critical path by a structurally-guaranteed\\nLUT level, never merely boolean AND/OR\\\") applies here: this is a\\nstructural mux-depth reduction, not a boolean simplification, so it\\nescapes the r9s2/r11s0 \\\"synth already found it\\\" trap.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage output flop's binding combinational arc is:\\n  rs_forward_mux \\u2192 operand_mux \\u2192 ALU(19-way case) \\u2192 alu_result_eff(2:1)\\n  \\u2192 flop_input_mux(is_jump ? pc+4 : _) \\u2192 EX/MEM.alu_result\\nThe alu_result_eff mux (`(is_div_op && div_done) ? div_result : alu.out`)\\nis a 32-bit 2:1 mux living OUTSIDE the ALU, gating the ALU's DIV/DIVU/\\nREM/REMU case-arm outputs (currently forced to 32'b0 under non-ALTOPS\\nas a don't-care placeholder). This external mux adds ~1 LUT4 level of\\ncombinational depth on a path that fitness history (r5s1 +8.79%, r3s0\\n+8.50%, r8s0 +5.99%) shows is sensitive to Fmax \\u2014 and it duplicates\\nselection work the ALU's own case mux could absorb for free. The\\nr8s0 meta-rule (\\...","metadata":{"matches":15,"truncated":false},"title":"divider|counter_q|S_DONE","time":{"start":1777779296462,"end":1777779296491}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_debe74749001C2Cm3J5RengUkT","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","messageID":"msg_debe74193001wJ9dlW4P5S2TT3"}}
