{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777779361083,"sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Sbn4CUhVS1yftAxHNsKQBx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"path":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","pattern":"byte.?val|shifted|load.?data|mem_width.*1|load.?extract"},"output":"Found 6 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Pre-register rd_wdata at MEM/WB boundary to shorten forward + regfile read paths\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational, and its output fans out to TWO critical-path\\nconsumers:\\n\\n  1. `fwd_mem_wb` into ex_stage's rs1/rs2 forwarding muxes, meaning\\n     the EX-stage ALU's operand path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 fwd_rs?_sel mux \\u2192 is_auipc mux \\u2192\\n     ALU \\u2192 EX/MEM flop \\u2014 four mux levels before ALU input.\\n  2. `w_data` into reg_file's write-first read bypass, meaning the\\n     ID-stage's regfile read path is\\n     (MEM/WB flop) \\u2192 wb_stage mux \\u2192 regfile bypass mux \\u2192 ID/EX flop\\n     \\u2014 two mux levels on every register read the WB instruction's\\n     rd matches.\\n\\nThat extra mux level lives on both sides of the pipeline and is a\\nplausible candidate for the actual Fmax cap. Fmax gains translate\\n1:1 to fitness since CoreMark iter/cycle is unaffected by this\\ntransformation (the functional mux just moves one pipe stage earlier).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior round's two M-extension latency splits (hyp-001 divider, hyp-002\\nM-unit) both returned fitness delta = 0.00%, which means the EX-stage\\ndivider was NOT actually the Fmax-limiting combinational path \\u2014 Yosys\\nwas already factoring it well or another path dominates. The BTB\\nattempt (hyp-003) broke formal.\\n\\nRe-reading the RTL with fresh eyes: the WB-stage mux\\n`w_data = in.ctrl.mem_to_reg ? in.read_data : in.alu_result`\\nis purely combinational...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate SLL/SRL/SRA onto a single shared right-barrel-shifter via bit-reversal\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesises three independent 32-bit barrel shifters\\nin alu.sv's case arms:\\n  ALU_SLL: a << shamt\\n  ALU_SRL: a >> shamt\\n  ALU_SRA: $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)\\nEach 32-bit variable barrel shifter is a 5-level 32-wide mux cascade\\n(~80 LUT4 on GW2A). Three of them consume ~240 LUT4 even though at\\nmost one result is selected per cycle. Yosys CSE does NOT fold these\\nbecause the shift directions differ and the `>>>` arithmetic variant\\nhas a different fill-bit discipline than `>>`.\\n\\nThe prior big micro_opt win (r3s0, +8.50%) established the dominant\\npattern on Tang Nano 20K: the EX path is area/routing-bound, not\\nlogic-depth-bound, so explicitly collapsing redundant datapath trees\\ninto shared hardware pays off even when every sub-expression was\\nalready single-cycle. Folding three MUL variants onto one 33x33\\nmultiplier freed DSP routing; folding three 32-bit barrel shifters\\nonto one right-shifter with bit-reversal should free the analogous\\nLUT4 routing channel around the ALU output mux.\\n\\nZero IPC impact (purely combinational restructuring with identical\\nbit-level semantics), formal-invariant (SLL/SRL/SRA are base I ops\\nfully proven by the per-instruction BMC), and the saving is a pure\\narea/routing gain that tends to translate into Fmax uplift on this\\ndevice.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesises three independent 32-bit barrel shifters\\nin alu.sv's case arms:\\n  ALU_SLL: a << shamt\\n  ALU_SRL: a >> shamt\\n  ALU_SRA: $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)\\nEach 32-bit variable barrel shifter is a 5-level 32-wide mux cascade\\n(~80 LUT4 on GW2A). Three of them consume ~240 LUT4 even though at\\nmost one result is selected per cycle. Yosys CSE does NOT fold these\\nbecause the shift directions differ and the `>>>` arithmetic variant\\nhas a different fi...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Eliminate load-use bubble via combinational MEM->EX load_data forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-branch IPC loss\\nis the load-use hazard: a 1-cycle bubble inserted by hazard_unit\\nwhenever an instruction in IF/ID consumes rd of a LOAD currently in\\nID/EX. CoreMark is pointer-chase-heavy (core_list_find reverse walk,\\ncore_bench_matrix row/column dereferences, core_state_transition's\\ncharacter-class table lookup, crcu16/32 inner loops) \\u2014 every dependent\\nload pays this stall. Empirically this is the single most common\\nnon-branch pipeline bubble in CoreMark's dynamic trace.\\n\\nStructural gap search: none of the prior iterations attempted this.\\nr5s1 (divider extraction, +8.79%) and r3s0 (DSP fold, +8.50%) both\\nsucceeded by removing waste from the EX datapath; the symmetric move\\non the DATA side is to make the LOAD-to-dependent path single-cycle\\ninstead of 2-cycle. r2s0's rd_wdata consolidation tried to shorten\\nthe MEM/WB forwarding path but broke the reg_ch0 formal check by\\nmis-plumbing the RVFI tap \\u2014 that failure was a wiring bug, not a\\nstructural impossibility. This hypothesis attacks a different path\\n(MEM combinational, not MEM/WB registered) and explicitly preserves\\nevery RVFI field's provenance byte-for-byte.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-b...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Pre-register the WB-mux: collapse mem_wb.read_data + alu_result into a single pre-muxed wb_data field\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage forwarding fan-in currently traverses, on the MEM/WB leg,\\na registered mem_wb.read_data / mem_wb.alu_result pair \\u2192 a combinational\\n2:1 mux in wb_stage (selecting on mem_to_reg) \\u2192 the 3:1 forward-select\\nmux in ex_stage \\u2192 ALU input. That post-flop 2:1 wb_stage mux is an\\nextra LUT4 level sitting directly in the rs1/rs2 \\u2192 ALU critical path\\nfor every instruction that depends on the instruction two ahead.\\n\\nPer r5s1 + r7s1 / r8s1 lessons, the EX/MEM clk-to-q is not the binding\\nbottleneck on this fabric; the binding path is EX combinational depth.\\nThe JAL-predictor algebraic win (r8s0, +6%) came from decoupling a\\nguard from a 32-bit adder \\u2014 the same \\\"shave one LUT4 level from a hot\\nfan-in\\\" pattern. Shortening the MEM/WB forwarding leg is structurally\\nanalogous and also saves 32 flops (one of the two 32-bit fields becomes\\ndead) plus a sliver of ex_mem_t width isn't touched.\\n\\nr2s0 previously tripped on this refactor \\u2014 the failure mode was losing\\nRVFI rd_wdata / mem_rdata tap provenance when fields were renamed. That\\nlesson is the specific mitigation playbook: keep mem_rdata (the raw\\ndmem word) as a separate RVFI-only field, re-point io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0\\nto the new mem_wb_w.wb_data signal in lockstep, and verify rd_wen\\ngating at the RVFI boundary still zeroes wb_data when reg_write=0.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage forwarding fan-in currently traverses, on the MEM/WB leg,\\na registered mem_wb.read_data / mem_wb.alu_result pair \\u2192 a combinational\\n2:1 mux in wb_stage (selecting on mem_to_reg) \\u2192 the 3:1 forward-select\\nmux in ex_stage \\u2192 ALU input. That post-flop 2:1 wb_stage mux is an\\nextra LUT4 level sitting directly in the rs1/rs2 \\u2192 ALU critical path\\nfor every instruction that depends on the ins...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble load-use via MEM->EX combinational forward with bit-exact misalign-trap replication\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The load-use bubble remains the largest untapped structural IPC opportunity\\non this microarchitecture. CoreMark's pointer-walk, matrix, and CRC kernels\\nall execute dependent LW->ALU/BRANCH sequences where the consumer must wait\\none cycle for the LOAD to clear MEM/WB before MEM/WB->EX forwarding can\\nfire. Branch-prediction IPC is saturated (r2s2 JAL predictor + r6s2/r7s2\\nproved ID-resolution is a dead end), and Fmax is 177 MHz vs a 135 MHz target\\nso there's also headroom to trade a little combinational depth for an IPC\\nwin. The r8s1 post-mortem prescribed the exact fix: \\\"replicate mem_stage's\\nCOMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\\\"\\nr8s1 went broken (not regression) - formal broke due to a trap-surface\\nmismatch between the forward-mux gate and mem_stage's actual reg_write\\nsuppression, NOT due to any inherent incompatibility with the microarch.\\nOoB is sim-enforced, not RTL - so the complete trap surface on the load-\\nresult path is just the compact mem_misalign predicate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The load-use bubble remains the largest untapped structural IPC opportunity\\non this microarchitecture. CoreMark's pointer-walk, matrix, and CRC kernels\\nall execute dependent LW->ALU/BRANCH sequences where the consumer must wait\\none cycle for the LOAD to clear MEM/WB before MEM/WB->EX forwarding can\\nfire. Branch-prediction IPC is saturated (r2s2 JAL predictor + r6s2/r7s2\\nproved ID-resolution is a dead end), and Fmax is 177 MHz vs a 135 MHz target\\nso there's also headroom to trade a little combinational depth for an IPC\\nwin. The r8s1 post-mortem prescribed the exact fix: \\\"replicate mem_stage's\\nCOMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\\\"\\nr8s1 went broken (not regression) - formal broke due to a trap-sur...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Retime load-extract from pre-MEM-flop to post-MEM-flop (WB-stage combinational)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Lesson r10s1 established that BRAM synchronous read data (dmem_rdata)\\narrives LATE in the cycle on Tang Nano 20K, and any combinational\\nconsumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\\nremaining slack. The current mem_stage does exactly that competition\\n*before* the MEM/WB flop: dmem_rdata -> byte-shift by alu_result[1:0]\\n-> sign/zero-extend per (mem_width, mem_sext) -> flop into\\nmem_wb.read_data. That is ~4 LUT4 levels of extract logic sitting on\\nthe binding late-arriving dmem_rdata path, eating MEM-stage slack\\nthat then reports up as the global Fmax ceiling.\\n\\nMeanwhile wb_stage is currently a trivial 2:1 mux (mem_to_reg ?\\nread_data : alu_result) feeding the regfile write port and the RVFI\\nrd_wdata tap. It has substantial combinational slack \\u2014 both\\nmem_wb.read_data and mem_wb.alu_result arrive at the start of the\\ncycle (clean flop outputs), and the fanout is shallow.\\n\\nThis is the exact retiming pattern the \\\"move combinational logic\\nfrom a tight stage to a loose stage, across an existing flop\\nboundary\\\" heuristic applies to. It is NOT the r10s1 pattern (which\\ncrossed a stage boundary the wrong way \\u2014 late BRAM data into an EX\\nforwarding path that then had to feed the ALU cone); this retimes\\nFORWARD by zero stages (same flop boundary, logic just moves from\\nbefore to after it).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Lesson r10s1 established that BRAM synchronous read data (dmem_rdata)\\narrives LATE in the cycle on Tang Nano 20K, and any combinational\\nconsumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\\nremaining slack. The current mem_stage does exactly that competition\\n*before* the MEM/WB flop: dmem_rdata -> byte-shift by alu_result[1:0]\\n-> sign/zero-extend per (mem_width, mem_sext) -> flop into\\nmem_wb.read_data. That is ~4 LUT4 levels of extract lo...","metadata":{"matches":6,"truncated":false},"title":"byte.?val|shifted|load.?data|mem_width.*1|load.?extract","time":{"start":1777779361058,"end":1777779361080}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm narrowing down what a viable micro-optimization would need to avoid based on previous failures—it has to stay within a single module, skip any EX→MEM/WB forwarding changes, and steer clear of priority mux widening or reorganization.\n\nThe forward_unit check for `ex_mem_rd != 5'b0` initially looked redundant since the regfile already prevents writes to x0, but it's actually a correctness safeguard—without it, instructions reading x0 would get stale forwarded data instead of the guaranteed zero value. So that's not the angle.\n\nNow I'm looking at the division operation detection logic in ex_stage.sv...\n\nExamining division detection logic... I'm exploring a cleaner encoding scheme where the division operations occupy a contiguous range with a recognizable bit pattern. If I reassign ALU_DIV through ALU_REMU to values 16-19, their lower two bits naturally map to the div_op_code, and I can detect division operations with a simple bit-field check on bits [4:2] rather than a multi-way equality comparison.\n\nThe tradeoff is that this renumbering spans three files—core_pkg.sv, alu.sv, and decoder.sv—but it's just relabeling constants, not merging modules or restructuring logic. The real benefit is simplifying the is_div_op decode path, which feeds into div_busy and propagates through the hazard unit to all pipeline control signals. However, I'm cautious because r11s0 flagged that touching div_busy fanout is risky, though that was about boolean simplifications rather than structural re-encoding.\n\nThere's also a simpler fallback: since the current division ops are already contiguous at 15-18, I could just use a range check instead of equality detection.\n\nBut the cleaner approach is to shift the DIV block up by one—leaving op=15 unused—so DIV becomes 16, DIVU becomes 17, REM becomes 18, and REMU becomes 19. This leaves a hole at 15, which Yosys treats as a don't-care default, and the decoder never emits that value anyway. Updating the decoder assignments...\n\nUpdating the ALU case labels to match, and in ex_stage I can simplify the is_div_op check to a 3-bit equality on bits [4:2], which saves logic depth on a critical path that feeds div_busy and all pipeline control enables. The div_op_code extraction becomes a direct bit slice with no decode overhead. This is really just enforcing a structural property of the encoding across modules—they're staying independent, just agreeing on the numeric convention that's already defined in core_pkg.sv.\n\nBut I'm second-guessing whether this actually helps. The current case-based is_div_op probably synthesizes to four 5-bit equality checks ORed together, which is around 4 LUT4s. The new bit-slice version would be 1 LUT4 or less, so maybe 2–3 LUT4s saved on the critical path. However, r11s0 showed that even algebraically-redundant edits to high-fanout signals like div_busy can hurt Fmax when they share routing resources with the EX critical path. Re-encoding to shorten is_div_op might hit the same problem.\n\nThis fabric is incredibly sensitive to placement changes. Let me try a safer approach that doesn't touch high-fanout signals.\n\nI'm thinking about replacing the full 32-bit variable shifter in mem_stage with explicit byte and half-word muxes instead. Currently the code does a variable right-shift by 0/8/16/24 bits, but only the low 8 or 16 bits are actually used. Yosys might not fully collapse the shifter since the shifted value is used twice. I can rewrite this with explicit case statements that directly select the right byte or half-word based on the address alignment bits, avoiding the variable shifter altogether.\n\nThe concern is whether Yosys already optimizes this away. Looking at the math, a 16-bit slice of a variable shift gets messy—at shift 24, for instance, you'd get zero-padded bits mixed with data bits. The explicit muxes are unambiguously simpler, but I'm not sure this optimization will actually improve Fmax enough to matter.\n\nThe load-use path is already pipelined and not the bottleneck anyway. Let me pivot to something safer: the divider-counter simplification is module-local and low-risk. Or I could tackle the mem_misalign check—I can rewrite it using bit-level encoding of mem_width to eliminate the equality comparisons and make it more compact.\n\nLooking at the mem_width encoding, I can express the misalignment logic as a combination of bit tests rather than full comparisons. Since mem_width[1] maps to width==2 and mem_width[0] maps to width==1 (width==3 never happens), I can collapse the logic down to checking individual bits of the ALU result against the corresponding width bits. This saves a couple of LUT levels, though it's not on a critical path since the memory stage is already post-flop and feeds external FPGA memory.\n\nI'm tempted to bundle multiple micro-optimizations together, but that increases risk. Better to commit to a single, well-scoped change: refactoring the mem_stage load-extract logic to use explicit byte and half-word muxes instead of a variable shifter. It's confined to one module, happens before the MEM/WB register, doesn't alter the pipeline payload, and leaves forwarding paths untouched.\n\nWait—I need to reconsider the wb_stage.w_data cone. The r11s1 failure was about moving the extract across the flop, which regressed timing by 49%. But I'm not moving it; I'm keeping it pre-flop and just restructuring it to be simpler. The key insight is that my change shouldn't lengthen the combinational cone feeding w_data—it should actually shorten it by replacing a variable shifter with direct muxing.\n\nSo the refactor is safe: I'm simplifying mem_stage's load-data extraction using explicit byte and half-word muxes instead of a full 32-bit shifter, keeping everything pre-flop and preserving the pipeline. It's a small structural optimization targeting area with low confidence but defensible reasoning.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debe84423001nHW9PJ7SL1jGjg","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","messageID":"msg_debe74929001tmFOln6WfRCpcV"}}
