{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777779364265,"sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","part":{"id":"prt_debe851a8001zYTxKmNvU4ZxIO","messageID":"msg_debe8458c001bXPDORkGfikMw3","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","snapshot":"eec0d667c6483b53e3a43f67908d5d51d76dca37","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777779409355,"sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_012BGvPC2C9pHHYVudqP6Hoz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r13s0\ntitle: \"Narrow mem_stage load-extract: replace 32-bit variable barrel shift with direct byte/half muxes on the late dmem_rdata cone\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  Lesson r11s1 established that on Tang Nano 20K, \"BRAM synchronous read\n  data (dmem_rdata) arrives LATE in the cycle, and any combinational\n  consumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\n  remaining slack.\" r11s1's specific failure was moving load-extract\n  ACROSS the MEM/WB flop (into wb_stage), which lengthened the\n  wb_stage.w_data -> fwd_mem_wb -> EX-ALU post-flop cone — the OTHER\n  binding arc. So retiming the extract is out, but r11s1's lesson\n  also implies the symmetric play that has NOT been tried: shorten\n  the pre-flop load-extract cone IN PLACE, leaving the flop boundary\n  where it is.\n\n  The current mem_stage.sv load-extract uses a 32-bit variable barrel\n  shifter:\n\n      shifted   = dmem_rdata >> (in.alu_result[1:0] * 8);\n      byte_val  = shifted[7:0];\n      hword_val = shifted[15:0];\n\n  Yosys lowers `a >> (k * 8)` on a 2-bit select to a 32-bit-wide 4:1\n  mux cascade (~2 LUT4 levels across all 32 bits). The high 16 bits\n  of `shifted` are consumed by `hword_val = shifted[15:0]` only via\n  the shift-direction dependency — opt_clean cannot prune them\n  because `shifted[15:0]` at shift-amount 16 reads `dmem_rdata[31:16]`\n  and at shift-amount 24 reads {8'b0, dmem_rdata[31:24]}, so the\n  full width of the shifter must be synthesized. This sits directly\n  on the dmem_rdata -> MEM/WB-flop arc that r11s1 identified as\n  binding Fmax-relevant late in the cycle.\n\n  The structurally-equivalent narrow form is a 4:1 byte mux (1 LUT4\n  level on 8 bits) plus a 2:1 half mux (1 LUT4 level on 16 bits),\n  followed by the same width+sext mux. That removes ~1 LUT4 level\n  from the 32-bit barrel cascade on the 16 upper shifter bits, and\n  critically replaces the full-width variable shift with narrower\n  per-width extraction trees.\n\n  This is the r8s0-class structural simplification pattern (shorten\n  an arithmetic cone, source of invariant is module-local) applied\n  to the load-extract path instead of the jal-target path. It does\n  NOT:\n   - move logic across a flop (r11s1's exact failure mode)\n   - lengthen wb_stage.w_data's post-flop cone (r11s1 warning)\n   - widen any pipeline payload (r5s2/r8s2 trap)\n   - touch high-fanout CE nets like div_busy (r11s0 warning)\n   - cross module boundaries (r12s1 trap)\n   - consolidate across separate always_comb islands (r7s0 trap)\n\n  The rewrite is confined to mem_stage.sv's load-extract always_comb\n  block and is bit-exact in output — same byte_val and hword_val per\n  any (dmem_rdata, addr[1:0]) input, same load_data through the\n  width/sext mux. RVFI mem_rdata/rd_wdata taps unchanged, mem_wb_t\n  field layout unchanged, flop boundary unchanged.\nhypothesis: |\n  In cores/bench/rtl/mem_stage.sv's load-extract always_comb, replace\n  the variable barrel shifter:\n\n      shifted   = dmem_rdata >> (in.alu_result[1:0] * 8);\n      byte_val  = shifted[7:0];\n      hword_val = shifted[15:0];\n\n  with explicit narrow muxes:\n\n      // 4:1 on 8 bits — 1 LUT4 level per output bit (2-bit select\n      // fits inside one LUT4 input)\n      case (in.alu_result[1:0])\n        2'b00: byte_val = dmem_rdata[7:0];\n        2'b01: byte_val = dmem_rdata[15:8];\n        2'b10: byte_val = dmem_rdata[23:16];\n        2'b11: byte_val = dmem_rdata[31:24];\n      endcase\n\n      // 2:1 on 16 bits — 1 LUT4 level per output bit. Halfword loads\n      // are half-aligned (bit 0 invariantly zero when not trapped),\n      // so only bit 1 of the address selects the half.\n      case (in.alu_result[1])\n        1'b0: hword_val = dmem_rdata[15:0];\n        1'b1: hword_val = dmem_rdata[31:16];\n      endcase\n\n  The downstream load_data mux over (mem_width, mem_sext) stays\n  identical — it consumes byte_val and hword_val exactly as before.\n  The `shifted` intermediate wire is removed entirely (with its\n  verilator lint_off/on pragma), saving a 32-bit combinational\n  intermediate and the implicit 32-bit barrel shifter Yosys was\n  inferring behind it.\n\n  Expected mechanism for Fmax uplift: the dmem_rdata -> load_data ->\n  mem_wb_q.read_data flop arc loses ~1 LUT4 level on the bit-[15:0]\n  half (the full barrel's upper 16 bits were contributing to bits\n  [15:0] of `shifted` via the shift-by-16/24 arms), which is exactly\n  the late-arriving path r11s1 identified. Narrower extraction trees\n  also pack better in GW2A slices.\n\n  Misalign-trap semantics and byte-lane store mask (wdata_rep,\n  byte_mask) paths are untouched. RVFI mem_rdata tap still reports\n  the raw dmem word (mem_wb_q.mem_rdata <- dmem_rdata unchanged).\n  Every retirement's rd_wdata via the mem_to_reg WB mux is bit-exact\n  identical to the current behavior for every (dmem_rdata, addr,\n  width, sext) input combination.\n\n  Formal impact: zero. The load-extract value for any retiring LOAD\n  is functionally identical, so riscv-formal's insn_lb/lh/lw/lbu/lhu\n  checks see the same rd_wdata as before. No new pipeline state, no\n  RVFI wiring changes, no new hazard logic, no new ctrl bits.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the `shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)` variable barrel shifter with explicit 4:1 byte mux on `byte_val` and 2:1 half mux on `hword_val`, remove the `shifted` intermediate and its verilator lint pragmas. Width+sext mux over byte_val/hword_val/dmem_rdata stays structurally identical. All other mem_stage logic (wdata_rep, byte_mask, misalign trap, dmem gating, MEM/WB register capture) untouched.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777779409346,"end":1777779409354}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm realizing the real bottleneck: BRAM read data arrives late in the cycle, and the current pipeline chains it through byte-shifting, sign-extension, and a flop before it reaches the memory-writeback stage—all competing on the critical path. This is what caused the regression in r11s1, and I need to rethink how to pipeline this data flow.\n\nThe key insight is that I don't need to move the extraction across the flop like r11s1 did; instead, I should make the extraction logic itself shallower by replacing the variable barrel shifter with explicit per-width muxes. The current `shifted >> (alu_result[1:0] * 8)` approach creates a deep combinational cone—essentially a 32-bit 4-way mux plus sign-extension logic—that all happens before the flop. By switching to a case statement that directly selects the right bytes for each load width, I can reduce the LUT depth and improve timing without restructuring the pipeline. Writing the mux logic...","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debe89819001FYrUNiq9MbyKqv","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","messageID":"msg_debe8458c001bXPDORkGfikMw3"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779409371,"sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","part":{"id":"prt_debe88b61001kSlTl3KIqpCljj","messageID":"msg_debe8458c001bXPDORkGfikMw3","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","type":"text","text":"Now I have a clear target. Let me examine r11s1's lesson carefully — it said \"BRAM dmem_rdata arrives LATE in the cycle, any combinational consumer competes\" and warned against *moving* logic across the flop. But it never tried *shortening* the pre-flop cone in place. The current code uses a full 32-bit variable barrel shifter (`dmem_rdata >> (addr[1:0]*8)`) which is deeper than the minimal byte/half extraction actually needed.\n\nKey observations:\n- Confined to `mem_stage.sv` (single module — avoids r12s1 cross-module trap)\n- Pre-flop cone only — does NOT move across flop (avoids r11s1 trap)\n- Does NOT touch `wb_stage.w_data` post-flop cone (avoids r11s1 warning)\n- Shortens the LATE-arriving `dmem_rdata` path per r11s1's own lesson\n- No pipeline payload changes (avoids r5s2/r8s2 mux-widening trap)\n- Purely structural — r8s0-class narrow-mux-depth reduction on an arithmetic-shift chain\n\nThe `>> (alu_result[1:0] * 8)` generates a full 32-bit 4:1 barrel shifter (~2 LUT4 levels), but only `shifted[7:0]` (for byte) or `shifted[15:0]` (for half) is ever used. A 4:1 mux on 8 bits or 2:1 mux on 16 bits is structurally shallower than a 32-bit variable shift.","time":{"start":1777779379041,"end":1777779409370}}}
