{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779415333,"sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","part":{"id":"prt_debe90903002WSwnkWVEvySohP","messageID":"msg_debe90209001txPK0CwMzqsItY","sessionID":"ses_2141be0f9ffeXB22nZwgsAH7vW","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r13s0.yaml`.\n\nSummary: An r8s0-class structural narrowing of the mem_stage load-extract. The current `shifted = dmem_rdata >> (alu_result[1:0]*8)` synthesizes a full 32-bit variable barrel shifter, but only `shifted[7:0]` and `shifted[15:0]` are consumed. Replacing it with an explicit 4:1 byte mux (8 bits) and 2:1 half mux (16 bits) shaves ~1 LUT4 level off the dmem_rdata → MEM/WB-flop arc that r11s1 identified as late-arriving and Fmax-sensitive.\n\nThe change threads between all documented failure modes:\n- Does NOT move logic across a flop (r11s1's exact regression)\n- Does NOT lengthen `wb_stage.w_data` post-flop cone (r11s1 warning)\n- Does NOT widen pipeline payload (r5s2/r8s2)\n- Does NOT touch high-fanout CE nets like div_busy (r11s0)\n- Does NOT cross module boundaries (r12s1)\n- Does NOT manually CSE across always_comb islands (r7s0)\n\nConfined to mem_stage.sv, bit-exact output, zero formal impact. Confidence: low (+2%), because Yosys may already partially collapse this during opt_muxtree, but the upper 16 bits of the barrel shifter are hard to prune structurally and this is a genuine depth reduction on the binding cone.","time":{"start":1777779411203,"end":1777779415332}}}
