{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777780312033,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfe47ffeXzMnBiCl655KRX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01KphqWo8BS2FxzTy1gRKiCo","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -l \"pc30\\|pc\\[31:2\\]\\|pc.*narrow\" cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl 2>/dev/null || echo \"no prior pc-narrow attempts\"","description":"Check for prior pc-narrowing hypothesis attempts"},"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","metadata":{"output":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl\n","exit":0,"description":"Check for prior pc-narrowing hypothesis attempts","truncated":false},"title":"Check for prior pc-narrowing hypothesis attempts","time":{"start":1777780312029,"end":1777780312031}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what's worked in previous optimizations—the DSP consolidation, the stateless prediction approach, and the divider sequentialization all showed solid gains—to figure out what kind of micro_opt hypothesis might move the needle on the bench core.\n\nLooking at what's already been applied to the current RTL, the major wins are already in place: the DSP is consolidated for multiply, the divider's been FSM'd, the JAL predictor is live, and the IF-stage alignment is optimized. Now I need to figure out what's still left on the table, particularly around MULHSU operations.\n\nChecking the ALU implementation, MULHSU is already routed through the shared DSP path, so that's covered. I'm working through the remaining micro-optimization candidates: JALR target guard simplification doesn't work because rs1 is symbolic at EX, shift operand narrowing is already at 5-bit width, shared adder lifting regressed before, register file write-port gating looks solid, immediate generation isn't a carry-chain opportunity, divider early-termination would complicate the FSM for minimal CoreMark benefit, and the comparison logic for BEQ/BNE is already using XOR-reduction for equality checks. The last thing to examine is whether LUI and AUIPC operations can be consolidated in the ALU.\n\nAUIPC feeds the PC and immediate into ALU_ADD, while LUI just passes the immediate through as output—this is already efficient. Branch target adder sharing with the ALU regressed in testing, and collapsing hazard unit boolean logic also caused regressions. Now I'm looking at the redirect logic in ex_stage more carefully. The jump_target for JALR is constructed from the sum of rs1 and immediate with the low bit cleared, while branch_target is PC plus immediate. The redirect_target mux currently selects between these two based on whether it's a jump instruction, but both paths involve adder operations—I'm wondering if there's a way to consolidate this into a single adder path.\n\nThe pc_next mux already has two instances of PC plus 4, but the synthesizer should handle that sharing. For the misalign_fault check, I'm noticing that branch_target's lower bits depend on the B-immediate encoding, where bit 0 is always zero and bit 1 comes directly from instruction bit 8, similar to the pattern I found with JAL earlier.\n\nSo the misalign check could simplify to just checking if instr[8] is nonzero. But I ran into this exact issue in r9s0 when I tried a similar rewrite at the EX stage — the pipelined PC became symbolic during formal verification and broke the proof. Retiming to IF-stage where PC is local would require threading more information through the pipeline, which isn't clean.\n\nLet me look at other optimization angles instead. The immediate generator has seven arms plus a default case with overlapping patterns, particularly I-type appearing multiple times. The register file is straightforward with write-first bypass. I considered using a dual-read BRAM primitive, but r5s0 showed that approach failed because the SSRAM needs a clocked read while the bypass needs combinational access — adding a registered port would introduce an extra cycle. Now I'm examining the ALU sign-extension muxing...\n\nExamining sign-extension logic... I don't think branch_target is actually read anywhere—it's probably just for debug or RVFI, so I'll leave it alone since payload reduction has failed formal checks before. Let me dig into the IF stage more carefully. The next_pc mux and the PC flop both reference redirect_target, which is redundant but likely collapsed by synthesis anyway. The pc+4 adder is used in multiple places (next_pc, pc_next in EX, and jump_target for JAL), but they're naturally separate adders so there's no obvious win there. I've already ruled out static BTFNT with guarded rewrites since that failed formal. Now I'm wondering if I can hoist the DIV result mux past the EX/MEM flop—currently the alu_result_eff selection happens combinationally in EX before the flop.\n\nRegistering the divider result separately and routing it directly to the flop seems too complex without a clear benefit. Load-extract optimization in the mem stage has been tried multiple times and regressed each time. The shift amount decode isn't expensive anyway. Let me focus on the ex_stage misalign_fault computation—it checks the low 2 bits of branch_target and jump_target, which are minimal 2-bit additions, but r9s0 showed that even the JALR version regresses formally because the pipelined in.pc breaks the algebraic pre-adder pattern that worked in IF stage.\n\nEX-stage arithmetic chain shortening is clearly a minefield for formal verification. The branch comparator chain has parallel comparators for different operations—BEQ, BNE, BLT, BGE, BLTU, BGEU—and while I could theoretically rewrite them to share a subtractor (since BLT is the sign bit of rs1 - rs2, BGE is its negation, and so on), r12s0 and r13s1 already showed that hand-lowering like this is net-negative when synthesis already handles it. Let me look at the divider start_pulse logic instead.\n\nThe divider control signals are already pretty compact—start_pulse fires when it's a div operation, input is valid, and the divider isn't busy or done, while the busy signal itself combines the operation type with validity and completion state. The real constraint is the alu_result_eff mux sitting before the EX/MEM flop, which multiplexes between the ALU result and the divider result based on whether division is done. This looks like it could be on the critical path, but r12s0 showed that moving it into the ALU actually regressed timing—the current placement lets nextpnr pack the 2:1 mux directly into the flop's input mux slot, which is free on GW2A slices. So the structure is already optimal. Let me try a different angle and look at simplifying something in a module-local way, like the immediate generation sign-extension logic.\n\nExamining sign-extension patterns...\n\nThe forward unit comparators are already minimal—just four 5-bit equality checks across two register sources and two write-back stages. But I'm wondering if pre-computing a regwrite-effective enable signal could help...\n\nactually, the synthesizer already handles that naturally. And the register file write logic with its `w_addr != 5'b0` check is just a 5-bit OR reduction, which is already optimal. The ALU's shift amount is just a slice, nothing to optimize there either.\n\nI'm hitting diminishing returns on obvious improvements. Let me reconsider what made the previous optimizations work—they all exploited either structural duplication, cold-path sequentialization, provable correctness by construction, or architectural invariants. For micro_opt, I need to find what arithmetic chain still has a module-local invariant I can leverage.\n\nThe JALR misalignment check is interesting—it's currently at EX, but the actual rs1 value isn't available until then. The target address is computed as `(rs1 + imm)[31:1], 1'b0`, so bit 0 is always forced to zero. For JAL, bit 0 is also zero since both pc and imm start at zero. That means the misalignment check `jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00` is really just checking `jump_target[1]`, which should already be optimized away by synthesis.\n\nThe real question is whether this is worth pursuing—the fitness gap is 398.73 versus a baseline of 301.04, and I need a high-risk play to push higher. CoreMark's hot loops involve matrix multiply, CRC operations, and linked list traversal with load-use chains, so the MEM-to-EX pipeline leg is likely the bottleneck. The core is already at 177 MHz Fmax against a 135 MHz target, so there's headroom there, but the CoreMark iteration count seems off in the current metrics.\n\nLooking at what's been tried: branch handling is nearly saturated—JAL works but JALR returns and conditional branches keep failing. Multiply and divide are mostly handled. The pc+4 adder duplication across modules didn't help when manually lifted. Now I'm examining the ALU more closely to see if there's another consolidation opportunity, particularly around the add/subtract and comparison operations.\n\nThe SLT and SLTU comparisons can theoretically be derived from the same subtractor used for SUB, pulling the sign bit and overflow information. But the synthesizer probably already does this, and past attempts at hand-lifting have regressed. Shifts were tried too without success.\n\nI'm now looking at the JAL predictor's target calculation—there's an adder computing pc plus the immediate, and since both pc and the result have known low bits, maybe there's algebraic simplification possible in the upper bits. The mux feeding into the EX/MEM flop has `pc + jal_imm` and `pc + 4` sharing the same PC input, so synthesis might already be combining their adder logic. The real question is whether IF-stage PC update is still the critical path after r8s0's improvements, or if the bottleneck has shifted downstream to EX—the recent regressions suggest IF is still tight. Looking at the EX stage, I'm noticing the `alu_result_eff` mux that selects between divider output and ALU result uses a late `div_done_eff` signal, but the divider's DONE state is actually predictable from the counter reaching 32, so there might be an opportunity to register the divider result earlier and decouple it from the mux's critical path.\n\nActually, the divider result is already on flop outputs, so it arrives early—the late path is the combinational ALU result, and the mux can handle that efficiently with a pass-through leg. Moving past that, I'm examining the hazard unit's control logic, which has several OR chains like `dmem_stall || div_busy` repeated multiple times and `load_use_hazard || redirect` appearing once. Synthesis should already be factoring out these common subexpressions, but there's an interesting structural pattern emerging in how the stall and flush signals are composed.\n\nLet me step back and think about what's genuinely unexplored. I've hit saturation on most of the major paths—the EX→MEM flop cone, the IF→PC cone, the register file, decoder, divider, multiplier, and several other components have all been tried or are fundamentally limited. One thing I haven't fully explored is pre-computing immediates at the IF stage instead of ID. The immediate generation is purely combinational from the instruction bits, so moving it earlier would save a cycle by threading the immediate through the IF/ID flop. But the instruction already carries those bits, so I'd need to add the decoded immediate to the if_id_t structure, which trades off adding flop width against saving the combinational decode delay in ID.\n\nActually, that doesn't work—if_id_t is combinational with no flop between IF and ID, so moving the computation just shifts where it happens without saving a cycle. Probably synthesis-neutral, so I'll skip it.\n\nThe divider could theoretically save a cycle by fusing the IDLE→BUSY transition with the first iteration, bringing it down from 34 to 33 cycles, but that's only a gain for division operations and CoreMark has essentially no dividers, so the overall impact is negligible.\n\nLooking at the stall logic for consecutive divisions, the timing works out fine—when one DIV completes on the DONE cycle, the next DIV can start immediately in the following cycle, giving a 34-cycle latency between back-to-back divisions. But again, CoreMark doesn't stress this case.\n\nI'm really struggling to find a novel micro-optimization at this point.\n\nOkay, let me try something concrete. What if I narrow the PC register in the IF stage to just 30 bits (pc[31:2]) and explicitly concatenate 2'b00 when forming the full 32-bit address? This would let me use a 30-bit adder for pc+4 instead of a 32-bit one. The tricky part is handling jumps—jal_imm has bit 1 that can be set (instr[21]), which would create a misaligned target that gets caught by is_jal_fetch anyway. Let me work through the bit arithmetic to see if this actually saves anything. So the key insight is that storing only the upper 30 bits internally while reconstructing the full 32-bit pc for downstream stages and RVFI keeps the optimization transparent to the rest of the pipeline. The main question is whether the 2-bit adder savings actually improves timing on the target FPGA, and whether this local optimization in the IF-stage avoids the formal verification issues that plagued previous attempts at pc rewriting in later pipeline stages. The RVFI interface will still report the correct full 32-bit pc values since the pipeline carries the expanded form through to retirement. This optimization fits the r8s0 pattern by making the pc[1:0]=0 invariant explicit to synthesis, which should shrink the adder. The formal correctness hinges on whether the EX-stage's misalign gate truly guarantees redirect_target[1:0]=0 whenever redirect fires—if that invariant holds, then storing only the upper 30 bits is lossless and should pass formal verification. The main risk is that synthesis may have already optimized this away, but removing gates from the critical path should be safe or beneficial rather than harmful. I'm verifying that narrowing the pc register to 30 bits is safe because the misalignment fault gate ensures redirect_target[1:0] always equals 0 when a redirect occurs, making the implicit zero-padding bit-exact to the full 32-bit version. The riscv-formal checks should still pass since both pc_rdata and pc_wdata would consistently have [1:0]=0, preserving the pc_fwd property. I'm going to commit to this IF-stage pc narrowing approach rather than trying to narrow pc_next in the EX stage, which would be riskier across pipeline flops.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the IF-stage pc adder is actually the timing bottleneck—the current Fmax is 177 MHz with a comfortable margin to the 135 MHz target, but recent runs show IF-stage modifications have consistently moved the needle (r8s0 gained 5.99%, while widening it regressed timing), so it's definitely near-binding. Narrowing the adder by 2 bits might yield 1-3% improvement. But I'm second-guessing whether narrowing the branch-target adder in EX could work instead—both pc and B-imm have bit 0 = 0, so branch_target[0] is always 0 and could be dropped. However, r9s0 showed that exploiting the pc[1:0]=0 invariant in EX breaks formal verification because the pipelined in.pc is symbolic under BMC, even though the invariant should hold after reset.\n\nLooking back at r9s0's failure, it combined two rewrites—one for JALR using rs1 (which isn't invariant-constrained and is symbolic at EX) and one for B-imm. The JALR rewrite was probably the culprit, so maybe the B-imm optimization alone would've been safe, but EX-stage rewrites are flagged as risky anyway. I should stick with IF-stage optimizations. My plan is to narrow the IF-stage PC register to 30 bits and exploit the pc[1:0]=0 invariant to shorten the JAL-target and pc+4 adders. Though I'm realizing the RVFI wrapper reconstructs pc as 32-bit for formal visibility, and Yosys might already be optimizing out bit 0 in the existing design anyway.\n\nWhen I trace through pc+4, bits 1:0 are just pass-throughs since pc[0]+0=pc[0] and pc[1]+0=pc[1], while bit 2 is where the actual addition happens. Without the invariant, synthesis has to keep bits 1:0 as copies of the original pc bits, but by narrowing the register to [31:2], I force those bits to constant 0 in synthesis's view, letting the adder drop them entirely. That's roughly 4 LUTs saved across the two IF-stage adders, maybe 1-3% improvement if we're lucky—not particularly promising. I should look for something with bigger impact.\n\nMoving the forwarding mux from EX to ID is tricky because the mux would need to see the current cycle's ex/mem and mem/wb results, but those values would be captured into the id_ex flop before they're actually available. The timing works out differently than I initially thought—the data sources are the same, just at different pipeline stages.\n\nAdding forwarding logic to ID would deepen the combinational path there, and ID is already packed with decode, regfile reads, and immediate generation. The lessons from r6s2/r7s2 suggest this would likely cause timing issues.\n\nI could try combining the branch target adder in IF with the JAL predictor target adder in EX, but they operate on different PC values across flop boundaries, so that won't work.\n\nFor the branch compare logic, I'm noticing all six comparison operations can be reduced to just the equality flag and the subtraction result—BEQ checks equality, BNE inverts it, BLT uses the sign bit XORed with overflow, BGE is the inverse, and the unsigned variants use the carry flag. This could compress the comparison significantly.\n\nBut I'm hesitant to hand-lower this into a unified subtractor. The r12s0 lesson warns that restating mux structures the synthesizer already optimizes can actually regress performance. The synthesizer likely already shares subtractors across the signed and unsigned compare paths, so manually extracting this probably won't help.\n\nI think I should commit to the IF-stage PC register narrowing. Though before I do, let me check if there's a way to consolidate the multiplier further—the current implementation has separate sign-extension logic for different multiply operations that might be compressible.\n\nLooking at the multiplier, the sign-extension computations are already minimal—just a couple of AND gates. And the r3s0 consolidation already got us to a single DSP18, with r7s1 failing to pipeline it further.\n\nReviewing the biggest wins from past attempts, they're all in the 5-9% range: IF-stage adder guard simplification, DSP consolidation, divider sequentialization, and the JAL predictor. The unexplored path that seems most promising is further simplifying the IF-stage PC path by exploiting the pc[1:0]=0 invariant.\n\nI'm cycling through other ideas—carry-save for ALU add/sub (synth probably handles this already), shift amount optimization (too trivial), integrating the result mux into the EX/MEM flop with clock-enable logic (ultimately the same), radix-4 divider (CoreMark has too few DIVs), BSRAM for the regfile (read is registered, adds a cycle), and precomputing the forwarding select one cycle earlier. That last one is interesting—if I move forwarding comparison to the ID stage, I'd be comparing the current IF/ID register's rs* addresses against the upcoming ex_mem.rd and mem_wb.rd values, but I need to think through whether that actually saves a cycle or just shifts the logic around. The forwarding select isn't directly visible to RVFI—it's internal, and what matters is the final rs1/rs2 values that reach the ALU and get stored in ex_mem. But the formal verification concern is trickier: if I pre-register fwd_sel, the solver needs to prove that this registered select correctly reflects the forwarding logic based on the previous cycle's register file state, which is more complex than just checking RVFI outputs match. I'm getting tangled up in the timing details of when each register captures its values—the forwarding logic depends on comparing register addresses across pipeline stages, but I keep second-guessing whether I'm looking at the right cycle's data. Rather than risk making an error here, I'll pivot to a simpler approach: narrow the PC register to 30 bits by exploiting the architectural invariant that pc[1:0] is always zero, then expand those bits back when needed for the adders.\n\nBut I need to handle the redirect path carefully—when a redirect fires, I have to ensure redirect_target[1:0] gets treated as zero even though the synthesizer won't automatically know they're guaranteed to be zero by the EX-stage misalignment fault. Let me think through the arithmetic more carefully. Since pc[1:0]=0 and jal_imm[0]=0 always, the pc+jal_imm computation simplifies: bit 0 stays zero with no carry, and bit 1 becomes just instr[21] (which is zero when is_jal_fetch guards the instruction). The pc+4 adder always produces 2'b00 in the lower bits, and redirect_target[1:0] is guaranteed zero by the EX-stage. So next_pc[1:0] is always 2'b00 regardless of which path we take.\n\nThis means I can drop bits [1:0] from the pc register entirely and save a tile or two of carry-chain delay on both the pc+4 and pc+jal_imm adders. I need to be careful with formal verification though—the key invariant is that pc[1:0] starts at zero after reset and stays zero inductively.\n\nThe tricky part is that riscv-formal runs bounded model checking from a symbolic initial state rather than from reset, so narrowing the register removes certain misaligned-pc states from consideration. But since the formal checks care about the retirement stream properties, and the core must produce correct results regardless of initial state, I need to verify that restricting to aligned pc doesn't break the correctness guarantees.\n\nLooking at the actual checks — the register file comparison doesn't depend on pc[1:0], and instruction encoding semantics are independent of those bits too. So this should be safe; we're just ensuring that unreachable misaligned states stay unreachable.\n\nActually, there's a cleaner approach: instead of narrowing the register itself, I can explicitly assert pc[1:0] = 0 at the imem_addr assignment and in the adders to structurally expose to synthesis that those bits are always zero. This keeps the register width the same but lets the tool optimize away the unnecessary bits.\n\nWriting up the hypothesis now with a note that this change is localized to the IF-stage module.\n\nThe core idea is to store PC internally as 30 bits (pc[31:2]) and reconstruct the full 32-bit address only at the module boundary, which lets the pc+4 and pc+jal_imm adders shrink from 32-bit ripple chains to 30-bit increments since the low two bits are architecturally guaranteed zero by RV32I alignment rules. Verifying the safety of dropping the low bits — when the PC flop captures a jal_target value, the is_jal_fetch guard ensures instr[21]=0, which means jal_target[1:0] is always 2'b00 in that path, so it's safe to narrow the register and reconstruct the full address on output.\n\nThe narrowed version avoids constructing the illegal wide value altogether by only computing the pc30-width paths, which is cleaner than relying on gating. This is a data-path optimization similar to r8s0 but in reverse — it removes gates without adding any, so worst case it's neutral if synthesis was already doing this implicitly. Expecting 1-4% improvement with low-medium confidence given the sensitivity of IF-stage changes and the need for RVFI reconstruction to match exactly.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debf6c3ad001qEbfNrRiP1Eci3","sessionID":"ses_2140cfe47ffeXzMnBiCl655KRX","messageID":"msg_debf30203001PACuCGt2ZdTknW"}}
