S (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xori_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_xori_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:02  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:02 (2)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:04:45 [insn_sub_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:05:27 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:01:01  waiting for solver (1 minute)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:01:21  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:01:22 (82)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:55 (55)\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:05:47 [reg_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nmake[1]: *** [reg_ch0/status] Error 1\\nmake[1]: Target `all' not remade because of errors.\\n\\nFormal: 0 passed, 1 failed\\nFailed: no_checks_generated\\n\\nFull run log: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0/formal/last_run.log\\nPer-check logs in: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/worktrees/hyp-20260502-001-r2s0/formal/riscv-formal/cores/bench/checks/<check>/logfile.txt\", \"slot\": 0, \"round_id\": 2, \"lesson\": \"- 2026-05-02 hyp-20260502-001-r2s0 (broken, n/a): Renaming/removing a `mem_wb_t` field that the top-level RVFI wiring observes (here: replacing `read_data` with pre-muxed `rd_wdata`) fails the `reg` check unless the top-level `io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0` / `io_rvfi_mem_rdata_0` taps are re-pointed in lockstep \\u2014 the `reg` check compares rvfi_rd_wdata to the actual regfile write, so any provenance mismatch between wb_stage's `w_data` and the RVFI tap is caught; always audit every `mem_wb_q.<field>` reference at core.sv top-level when mutating the WB payload layout.\"}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesis avoids\\nboth failure modes: JAL redirect is deterministic (never mispredicted),\\nintroduces no speculative wrong-path state, and doesn't touch the ALU.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Decode JAL (opcode 0x6F) combinationally in if_stage.sv. When the\\nfetched word is JAL and the IF output is valid (not flushed by an EX\\nredirect, imem_stall, or reset), compute the J-type immediate and\\noverride next_pc with pc + imm_J instead of pc + 4. The JAL instruction\\nitself still flows normally through ID/EX/MEM/WB so its PC+4 writeback\\nretires and RVFI sees the canonical pc_wdata = target. EX must NOT\\nre-redirect for a JAL that IF already jumped, so a single-bit\\n`early_jumped` flag is added to `if_id_t` (propagated into `id_ex_t`\\nas a field separate from ctrl_t). `ex_stage` ANDs its redirect\\ncondition with `!in.early_jumped` for the JAL case (is_jump &&\\n!is_jalr). JALR is untouched (it needs rs1 + forwarding and has no\\npurely-IF-visible target).\\n\\nCost in logic:\\n  - A 32-bit J-imm extractor (existing pattern from imm_gen.sv) and\\n    a 2:1 mux on next_pc gated by `imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111`.\\n  - 1-bit `early_jumped` through 2 pipeline registers.\\nExpected Fmax impact: the added IF-stage adder is 32-bit pc + 32-bit\\nsign-extended imm, parallel with the existing pc+4 incrementer \\u2014 it\\nis unlikely to become the new critical path given EX currently owns\\nFmax via the ALU/multiplier mux. Worst case Fmax gives up ~2-3%;\\nIPC gain from eliminating ~2 bubbles on every dynamically-retired\\nJAL (CoreMark has thousands per iteration) should dominate.\\n\\nCorrectness hooks:\\n  - RVFI: pc_wdata of the JAL is always `pc + imm_J` whether IF\\n    early-jumped or EX did. rd_wdata stays PC+4. No change to any\\n    RVFI field \\u2192 riscv-formal `pc_fwd` / `unique` / `causal` checks\\n    remain closed with zero added state-space work.\\n  - Formal: the `early_jumped` flag is a pure function of decoded\\n    opcode + IF stall/flush signals \\u2014 not speculative, not predicted\\n    \\u2014 so SBY's BMC depth is unchanged.\\n  - Traps: a misaligned JAL target still traps in EX (its\\n    misalign_fault path fires there as before; we gate the EX redirect\\n    but not the misalign_fault computation, which also suppresses\\n    reg_write and leaves pc_next = pc + 4).\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single-bit `early_jumped` field to if_id_t and id_ex_t (outside ctrl_t so decoder default-illegal semantics are unaffected).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect JAL (opcode 7'b1101111) on imem_data, extract the J-imm, and override next_pc = pc + imm_J when the IF output would otherwise be a valid instruction. Set out.early_jumped accordingly. Preserve reset/flush/stall priority so imem_stall and EX redirects still win over the early-jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate in.early_jumped into the ID/EX register as a standalone field (zero when reset/flush).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the redirect output for unconditional JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr) with !in.early_jumped so IF's in-flight target fetch is not flushed. Misalign_fault still asserts and still overrides via the existing trap path.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a JAL-latency cocotb test: two JALs back-to-back to verify zero bubble cycles in rvfi_order deltas, plus a branch-then-JAL interleaving test to confirm EX redirects still win when IF's JAL-prediction would race an older redirect, plus a misaligned-JAL test (imm with bit[1] set) to confirm trap semantics are preserved.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a single-bit `early_jumped` field to if_id_t and id_ex_t (outside ctrl_t so decoder default-illegal semantics are unaffected).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect JAL (opcode 7'b1101111) on imem_data, extract the J-imm, and override next_pc = pc + imm_J when the IF output would otherwise be a valid instruction. Set out.early_jumped accordingly. Preserve reset/flush/stall priority so imem_stall and EX redirects still win over the early-jump.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Propagate in.early_jumped into the ID/EX register as a standalone field (zero when reset/flush).\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Gate the redirect output for unconditional JAL (is_jump && !is_jalr) with !in.early_jumped so IF's in-flight target fetch is not flushed. Misalign_fault still asserts and still overrides via the existing trap path.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_pipeline.py\", \"description\": \"Add a JAL-latency cocotb test: two JALs back-to-back to verify zero bubble cycles in rvfi_order deltas, plus a branch-then-JAL interleaving test to confirm EX redirects still win when IF's JAL-prediction would race an older redirect, plus a misaligned-JAL test (imm with bit[1] set) to confirm trap semantics are preserved.\"}], \"outcome\": \"broken\", \"formal_passed\": false, \"cosim_passed\": false, \"error\": \"formal_failed: no_checks_generated\\ns are unsatisfiable!\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: ##   0:00:02  Status: passed\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: ##   0:00:00  Status: PREUNSAT\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: finished (returncode=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] engine_0: Status returned by engine: pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:02 (2)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:01 (1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned pass\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_sub_ch0] DONE (PASS, rc=0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: finished (returncode=1)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] engine_0: Status returned by engine: ERROR\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed clock time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: Elapsed process time [H:MM:SS (secs)]: 0:00:00 (0)\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 (smtbmc bitwuzla) returned ERROR\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] summary: engine_0 did not produce any traces\\nSBY 21:18:22 [insn_xori_ch1] DONE (ERROR, rc=16)\\nmake[1]: *** [insn