{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777781212733,"sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01151itPyW6ux1aqhQsfyNay","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r15s0.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-001-r15s0\ntitle: \"Retime AUIPC result (pc+imm) from EX to ID via id_ex.auipc_result\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  r14s1 netted +4.22% by retiming JAL/JALR's link-address (pc+4) from EX to\n  ID via a new id_ex.link_addr field. The post-mortem identified the\n  exact safety envelope: a pipelined-across-a-flop arithmetic copy is\n  formal-safe and Fmax-positive iff (a) the retimed quantity does not\n  feed the redirect/trap-generation cone (r13s2's trap), (b) it has a\n  single registered fanout (r7s0's trap), and (c) ID has measurable\n  slack vs the binding EX cone.\n\n  AUIPC is the ONLY remaining ALU op in this pipeline where BOTH\n  operands are fully known at ID — alu_a = pc (module-local, no\n  forwarding), alu_b = imm (already registered in id_ex). Every other\n  ALU op has at least one operand (rs1 or rs2) that depends on\n  EX-stage forwarding and cannot be resolved at ID. That uniquely\n  makes AUIPC a drop-in candidate for the r14s1 retime pattern.\n\n  Currently at EX: alu_a = is_auipc ? pc : rs1_fwd. This 2:1 mux sits\n  at the ALU input and adds one LUT4 level to the binding EX cone\n  (ALU input → case-mux → alu_result → EX/MEM flop). The mux is there\n  for AUIPC (which writes pc+imm to rd), but the rs1_fwd path is the\n  dominant one (all ADD/SUB/SLT/AND/OR/XOR/SHIFT/MUL/STORE-addr/LOAD-addr\n  ops). Eliminating the pc-leg of alu_a shortens the input cone for\n  every common ALU op.\nhypothesis: |\n  Pre-compute AUIPC's result at ID and retime it across the ID/EX\n  flop, matching r14s1 verbatim:\n\n  1. Add `auipc_result` (32-bit) to id_ex_t in rtl/core_pkg.sv.\n  2. In rtl/id_stage.sv, compute `reg_q.auipc_result <= in.pc + imm`\n     at the same posedge that captures pc/imm/link_addr. The adder\n     is a new 32-bit add at ID but imm_gen's case output is\n     post-registered so the ID cone has measurable slack (r14s1\n     demonstrated this on link_addr = pc + 4, which shares the same\n     pc fanout).\n  3. In rtl/ex_stage.sv, remove the pc leg from alu_a:\n       before: alu_a = in.ctrl.is_auipc ? in.pc : rs1;\n       after:  alu_a = rs1;\n     Then at the EX/MEM reg write, add an is_auipc leg to the\n     alu_result-latch mux (currently 2:1 between is_jump ? link_addr\n     and alu_result_eff):\n       reg_q.alu_result <= in.ctrl.is_jump  ? in.link_addr\n                         : in.ctrl.is_auipc ? in.auipc_result\n                                            : alu_result_eff;\n\n  Expected effect on timing:\n  - EX ALU input cone loses one 2:1 mux (the pc leg of alu_a) that\n    sat at the rs1_fwd-to-ALU boundary. This is the binding arc on\n    Tang Nano 20K per r10s1's post-mortem (BRAM-output-to-flop is\n    the other arc; ALU-input-to-flop is this one).\n  - EX/MEM reg_q.alu_result mux widens from 2:1 to 3:1. In LUT4\n    both synthesize to one LUT level (2-bit select fits a single\n    LUT4), so output-side depth is unchanged; only LUT count grows\n    by ~32 LUT4s (one per bit) for the extra leg.\n  - Net: -1 LUT4 level on the EX input cone for the common-case\n    rs1→ALU path, 0 LUT4 level change on the output cone. Should\n    translate to a small Fmax uplift without IPC change.\n\n  Formal safety (r13s2 / r14s1 analysis):\n  - auipc_result feeds ONLY the rd_wdata path (via EX/MEM reg_q.alu_result\n    for AUIPC instructions, then mem_wb.alu_result, then wb_stage.w_data,\n    then io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0). It does NOT feed redirect_target, does\n    NOT feed branch_target, does NOT feed any misalign-trap guard,\n    does NOT feed dmem_addr. This matches r14s1's link_addr envelope\n    exactly.\n  - auipc_result is captured at ID as `in.pc + imm` from the same\n    if_id payload that sources pc. Single registered fanout (consumed\n    only at ex_stage's reg_q write mux). No combinational CSE across\n    always_comb blocks (r7s0 trap avoided).\n  - No payload struct widening that the solver reads inductively beyond\n    what it already does for pc/imm — auipc_result is a pure arithmetic\n    function of two existing registered quantities, so the `reg` check's\n    rd_wdata↔regfile-write equality remains structurally provable (the\n    solver can verify auipc_result === pc + imm at ID-flop-capture and\n    propagate inductively, same as it does for link_addr === pc + 4 post-r14s1).\n  - ALTOPS formal mode: unaffected — AUIPC uses ALU_ADD (not an M-ext\n    op), so the RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS XOR substitutions are orthogonal\n    to this retime.\n\n  Expected CoreMark dynamic hit rate: AUIPC is not the hottest op\n  (ADD/LOAD/BRANCH dominate) but it appears in every pc-relative\n  address materialization (e.g. la pseudo-op expansions for globals\n  and function tables in CoreMark's list_init/matrix_test/state_init).\n  The Fmax win comes from the common-case rs1→ALU path shortening,\n  not from AUIPC's own latency (which is unchanged), so fitness is\n  gated by synth Fmax delta not IPC.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `logic [31:0] auipc_result;` field to the id_ex_t struct alongside link_addr. No other struct changes; width/order of existing fields preserved to avoid downstream probe/tap drift.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"In the ID/EX register always_ff arm, add `reg_q.auipc_result <= in.pc + imm;` alongside the existing `reg_q.link_addr <= in.pc + 32'd4;` line. Reset arm clears auipc_result to 0 via the existing `reg_q <= '0` sweep — no separate reset statement needed.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Two changes. (1) In the alu_a mux, remove the is_auipc leg: replace `alu_a = in.ctrl.is_auipc ? in.pc : rs1;` with `alu_a = rs1;`. (2) In the EX/MEM register always_ff block's non-stall arm, widen the alu_result-latch mux from 2:1 to 3:1 to add the AUIPC pre-computed leg: `reg_q.alu_result <= in.ctrl.is_jump ? in.link_addr : in.ctrl.is_auipc ? in.auipc_result : alu_result_eff;`. No change to redirect / redirect_target / branch_target / jump_target / misalign_fault paths — AUIPC never participates in control flow so those cones are unaffected.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r15s0.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r15s0.yaml","time":{"start":1777781212709,"end":1777781212731}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the recent performance gains, I'm noticing that the r14s1 optimization worked well by moving the link-address calculation earlier in the pipeline—specifically registering it in the ID stage to avoid feeding into the redirect logic. I'm also seeing a pattern with the algebraic pre-adder approach that showed promise in the IF stage, and I want to build on these insights to develop a solid hypothesis for the next micro-optimization.\n\nThe failures are telling too: any attempt to touch the MEM/WB forwarding path, widen the IF next_pc mux, or mess with branch prediction has regressed. Even structural changes like splitting modules or narrowing the PC have backfired. This suggests the current design is already well-tuned in those areas, so I should focus on finding other EX computations that could be safely retimed to ID without hitting the redirect or trap cone—similar to what worked with the link-address.\n\nAUIPC looks promising here since it computes pc + imm at the EX stage, but that result only feeds the write-data path, not the redirect logic. I'm wondering if I can pre-compute this at ID and store it in the id_ex pipeline register, though I need to be careful since an earlier attempt with pc+imm for branch targets failed because those DO feed the redirect cone.\n\nThe memory-stage optimizations seem exhausted based on prior regressions, so the real opportunity is probably on the ID side—finding more operations that can be safely moved earlier without creating a critical path or breaking the redirect/trap dependencies.\n\nLooking at the EX cone structure, I'm considering whether pre-computing AUIPC at ID (pc + imm stored as a registered field) would help, since it only feeds writeback and doesn't touch the redirect logic. The savings would be skipping the alu_a mux for the pc case and the ALU adder itself, but that's probably marginal since the mux is shallow and the ALU is already the main path. A more general approach might be pre-computing pc+imm at ID as a shared field for both AUIPC and JAL, which could feed multiple consumers downstream.\n\nHowever, there's a complication: branch_target is in the redirect cone, so pre-computing pc+imm there would violate the formal constraints like r13s2. For AUIPC alone, the registered fanout pattern matches r14s1 cleanly, but adding it to the alu_result mux at the latch would make it 3-way instead of the current 2-way (jump ? link_addr : alu_result), which might actually regress timing. The core issue is that eliminating the pc → alu_a path requires the pre-compute, but keeping the ALU doing pc+imm for AUIPC doesn't actually shorten the critical path much.\n\nNow I'm looking at other potential optimizations: the imm_gen is already combinational at ID before the id_ex flop, so that's registered. The store write_data replication at MEM is trivial. But the branch misalignment check in EX is interesting—for B-type instructions, branch_target[1:0] reduces to just instr[8] due to the ISA invariants, which is the r9s0 trap. That's pipelined and broke formal. The cleaner approach might be the MEM-stage mem_misalign check instead...\n\nChecking memory alignment conditions...\n\nActually, I'm thinking about a different optimization: pre-computing the ALU's control path selection at ID rather than doing the full decode at EX. Instead of the case mux on the 5-bit op having 19 arms, I could emit pre-decoded signals like is_add_sub, is_sub, is_shift_left, logical_op_code, and is_slt_u at ID, then at EX the ALU just muxes based on those simpler signals instead of re-decoding the operation.\n\nBut that approach widens the id_ex_t payload, which has synthesis costs. Looking at the actual ALU op encoding in core_pkg.sv, the 19 operations are fairly dense with no obvious structure to exploit. I'm also considering whether I can pre-compute the STORE byte-mask at ID, but that depends on alu_result[1:0] which isn't available until EX, so that won't work. Same issue with the aligned_addr computation in mem_stage — it gates on mem_misalign which is combinational from alu_result, so I can't move that earlier either.\n\nLet me trace the actual critical paths on Tang Nano 20K more carefully. The binding paths are the EX ALU cone feeding into the EX/MEM flop, the BRAM load data feeding into MEM/WB, and the PC+JAL computation feeding back to the PC flop. After the recent r14s1 timing fix, the EX mux that selects between jump link address and alu_result_eff is feeding the register. I could try pre-computing pc_next_branch_target at ID, but that's already been tried and broke the redirect cone. Another angle: pre-computing the LUI result at ID since LUI just outputs the immediate directly, then special-casing it at the EX→MEM register write to bypass the ALU case-mux entirely. But LUI is rare and the ALU output is still the dominant path, so this won't help much.\n\nActually, I'm realizing I could handle LUI and AUIPC directly in the EX register assignment by adding them to the mux alongside the jump case, which would eliminate the ALU's handling of these operations. But that's just moving the work around since the ALU case-mux already handles them. The real opportunity is pre-computing AUIPC's pc+imm addition at ID stage—it's a single registered fanout into the alu_result mux at EX, doesn't feed into any redirect or trap logic, and follows the same pattern as r14s1. This would shorten the EX path by removing AUIPC from the ALU's case-mux.\n\nLooking at the actual ex_stage code, alu_a is a 2:1 mux selecting between pc and rs1 based on is_auipc, and rs1 itself comes from a 3:1 forwarding mux. If I pre-compute AUIPC at ID, alu_a becomes just rs1, eliminating one mux level on the ALU input side. But the trade-off is adding a 3-way mux to the alu_result latch instead of the current 2-way, which adds area on the output side. Since both the input and output muxes sit on the critical path, it's unclear whether moving the mux from input to output actually improves timing.\n\nLet me step back and look for a clearer pattern. The link_addr pre-compute worked because it had slack in ID and only fed a single registered fanout. Looking at what else could move to ID, most of the remaining EX computations either feed the redirect logic (branch_target, jump_target, jalr_sum) or trap detection, which can't be retimed. The only candidates without those constraints are the ALU inputs and the register write mux itself.\n\nFor AUIPC specifically, I could pre-compute it at ID since pc is available then, but the alu_a mux still depends on rs1_fwd which isn't known until EX. The real question is whether there's enough slack in ID to absorb this work without hurting cycle time, and whether the savings in EX depth justify the added complexity. I'm realizing the alu_a mux for AUIPC is actually upstream of the ALU, so for the common case (non-AUIPC), it just passes rs1 through—the synthesizer might fold this into the rs1 forwarding mux to create a wider selector. Pre-computing AUIPC's result at ID and muxing it in at the register write stage would eliminate that pc→alu_a path entirely, cleaning up the ALU input cone for everything else.\n\nNow I need to verify this doesn't break the formal verification: since id_ex.auipc_result is combinationally equivalent to pc + imm and both values are already in the pipeline payload, the solver should be able to prove equivalence at the flop boundary. The key difference from the failed r13s2 attempt is that I'm not decoupling redirect logic—AUIPC's result only affects regfile writes, which the `reg` check validates against rvfi_rd_wdata.\n\nI'm going to write this up as a proposal. Performance-wise, AUIPC is less frequent than JAL/JALR, so I'm expecting a more modest gain around +2% rather than the +4.22% from r14s1. But before committing to this, I should think about whether there are higher-impact optimizations on the common path—like ADD operations—that might be worth pursuing instead. AUIPC and LUI are the only ALU ops where both operands are known at ID—AUIPC because pc and imm are both available, and LUI because its result is just the immediate itself. I'll pre-compute `auipc_result = pc + imm` at ID and route it directly to the result mux at EX, while LUI just uses the immediate combinationally. This means removing AUIPC from the ALU's ADD path entirely and simplifying alu_a to always be rs1.\n\nThe output mux at EX becomes a 4:1 selector handling jumps, AUIPC, LUI, and the normal ALU result, but since a 4:1 mux is still one LUT level like the original 2:1, the depth stays the same—just more logic in the output path instead of the input path.\n\nOn the input side, removing the alu_a 2:1 mux saves one LUT level on the critical path to the ALU. The tradeoff is worth it: I gain a cycle on the ALU input while the output mux doesn't degrade. Area-wise, I'm adding a 32-bit adder and flop at ID for the precomputed result, plus widening the output mux, but the formal risk is low since it follows the same pattern as other registered fanouts. Actually, I'll keep it simpler and only precompute AUIPC—LUI already runs through the ALU efficiently as a passthrough, so there's no win there. The 3:1 output mux is still one LUT level and removes the alu_a mux entirely.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec040d69001YQNJ7z83XtRt2c","sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","messageID":"msg_dec017a2600144aBFCf4SjEQvT"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777781212736,"sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","part":{"id":"prt_dec04089c001Y3Sb7yccwJP8im","messageID":"msg_dec017a2600144aBFCf4SjEQvT","sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","type":"text","text":"Looking at the recent outcomes and lessons, I need to find a micro_opt that follows the r14s1 winning pattern (+4.22%): retime EX-stage arithmetic to ID via a single-registered-fanout field that does NOT feed the redirect/trap cone.\n\nKey constraints from lessons:\n- r13s2 broke formal: retiming `pc+imm` for branch_target breaks `reg_ch0` because it feeds redirect cone\n- r14s1 succeeded: `link_addr = pc+4` pre-compute worked because it feeds only rd_wdata / misalign-fallback, NOT redirect\n- r7s0: don't CSE into multiple combinational fanouts\n- AUIPC is the only remaining ALU op where BOTH operands (`pc` and `imm`) are fully known at ID (no rs forwarding needed) — making it a perfect r14s1-analog target","time":{"start":1777781180573,"end":1777781212734}}}
