{"type":"text","timestamp":1777781218007,"sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","part":{"id":"prt_dec048e29001clx8prY8ariXcH","messageID":"msg_dec04868a001KGABw1dsGk9qtL","sessionID":"ses_213fe8612ffep3FhKN035E7hrv","type":"text","text":"Wrote hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-001-r15s0.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Apply the r14s1 winning pattern (+4.22%) to AUIPC. AUIPC is the only remaining ALU op where both operands (pc, imm) are fully known at ID — no forwarding dependency. Pre-compute `auipc_result = pc + imm` at ID alongside `link_addr`, then at EX:\n- Remove the `is_auipc ? pc : rs1` mux from alu_a (saves one LUT4 level on the common rs1→ALU cone, which is the binding EX arc per r10s1)\n- Widen the alu_result latch mux from 2:1 to 3:1 (same LUT4 depth, just more area)\n\nFormal safety matches r14s1 exactly: single registered fanout, feeds only rd_wdata (never redirect/trap cone, sidestepping r13s2's trap), bit-exact equivalent at flop capture.","time":{"start":1777781214761,"end":1777781218005}}}
