{"type":"text","timestamp":1777777974853,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"id":"prt_debd318e5001NLY6uFxClCFBJ3","messageID":"msg_debd0114100131KmdrsGLKB7gV","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","type":"text","text":"Looking at the lessons and recent outcomes, I need to find a structural play that avoids the well-documented pitfalls:\n\n- IF-stage next_pc mux widening is Fmax-fatal (r4s2, r5s2, r8s2, r10s2)\n- MEM→EX/WB forwarding widening is Fmax-fatal (r8s1, r10s1, r11s1)\n- Pipeline payload widening costs synthesis area (r5s2, r6s2, r7s2)\n- Splitting DSP output consumers breaks DSP18 register inference (r10s0)\n- 2-cycle MUL regresses (r7s1: MUL is hot in CoreMark matrix kernels)\n- Manual CSE on LUT4 datapaths regresses (r6s0, r7s0, r9s2, r11s0)\n\nLet me check the log for similar past refactoring attempts.","time":{"start":1777777973477,"end":1777777974852}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777777974897,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01SshhFiabYmb7JZwphH3B3N","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypotheses","time":{"start":1777777974876,"end":1777777974894}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the key constraints from previous design iterations—the memory-to-execute/writeback forwarding path and the instruction fetch stage multiplexer both created critical timing violations, while branch prediction also presented challenges. Now I need to develop a structural hypothesis for the bench core that avoids these bottlenecks.\n\nLooking at what's worked: divider sequentialization gained 8.79%, DSP consolidation 8.50%, and a stateless JAL predictor added 5.87%. The current best configuration sits at 398.73 MHz versus the baseline 301.04 MHz. I'm thinking about what structural changes haven't already failed—avoiding wider IF-path muxes, keeping the MEM-to-EX forwarding cone narrow, and not threading new fields through the pipeline. The ALU's case statement for M-extension operations might be a candidate, though previous attempts at manual operator sharing backfired. I'm also wondering if the register file itself could be optimized.\n\nThe 32x32 dual-read-port regfile doesn't benefit from LUTRAM inference on this architecture. Divider speed improvements like radix-4 won't help much since DIV/REM are cold in CoreMark. The real opportunity might be in how the ALU operand mux is structured—currently forwarding happens before the AUIPC/immediate selection, but I'm not sure reordering that helps. What's interesting is that AUIPC results could theoretically be precomputed at the ID stage since the PC is already known there.\n\nLUI is another angle—it just passes the immediate through the ALU, so bypassing the ALU entirely for LUI could save a cycle since it's a common constant-loading instruction. The EX/MEM bypass is already optimized with the registered ALU result feeding forward combinationally. Now I'm looking at the hazard unit's stall and flush logic to see if there's redundancy or unnecessary serialization happening there.\n\nThe flush signal takes priority over stall in the ID stage flop, and flush is only asserted when there's no dmem or divider stall, so the semantics are consistent. One structural approach would be clock-gating unused fields in the ID/EX register during stalls, but that's synthesis-dependent. A more promising idea is pipelining the divider to start in the ID stage with forwarded operands, saving a cycle on the critical path. Alternatively, a radix-4 divider could halve the iteration count from 32 cycles to 16.\n\nLooking at other structural improvements: moving MULH computation to a second pipeline stage regressed performance, and manually sharing adders for PC+4 computation also hurt results. Simplifying the 64-bit RVFI order counter is tempting but risky for correctness. Most other changes like combining forwarding logic or adding an early commit path for pure ALU ops are either cosmetic or require careful trade-off analysis.\n\nThe wins that actually stuck were DSP consolidation, divider sequentialization, the stateless predictor, and algebraic rewrites — mostly structural changes that reduced critical path or pipeline stalls. Now I'm wondering if we can start the divider one cycle earlier by initiating it combinationally from the ID/EX register instead of waiting for it to reach the EX stage, though the operands might not be ready yet.\n\nLooking at the actual timing: the divider sits idle for one cycle after the op enters EX, then runs 32 iterations, then signals done — that's roughly 34 cycles of stall total. Starting it combinationally could save a cycle or two, but that's more of a micro-optimization than a structural win.\n\nFor a real structural change, I'm considering whether we could bypass the MEM stage entirely for non-memory, non-branch ALU ops so they retire directly from EX to WB one cycle earlier. The problem is this violates the retirement ordering contract where channel 0 must always be older than channel 1 — if an ALU result retires the same cycle as a load in MEM, the load is technically older and should take priority. A simpler approach might be a dual-issue static ALU+LOAD slot instead.\n\nI'm also exploring whether a radix-4 divider could cut the latency to 16 cycles, though for a cold operation the IPC gain is marginal against the added area cost. Another angle: the instruction field is 32 bits replicated across three pipeline registers just for RVFI observability — in production synthesis without formal verification, we could gate that storage away entirely and save 96 flops.\n\nBut the RVFI ports are always instantiated, so that won't work. Let me look at the hazard detection logic instead. The load-use comparator is on the critical path, checking if the destination of a load matches either source operand of the next instruction. I could pre-compute which sources are actually used during decode, or alternatively replicate the register file into two banks to reduce read-port fanout — though that would double the flop count from 1024 to 2048, likely a net area loss despite potential Fmax gains.\n\nThe divider result mux with its corner cases for division-by-zero and overflow is done combinationally but probably isn't the bottleneck anyway. What I really need to focus on is what the synthesis flow can't optimize on its own. The multiplier drives both the lower and upper halves of the result, and while Yosys might not recognize that only one is used per cycle, splitting those drives made things worse before. The more ambitious option would be restructuring to dual-issue LOAD and ALU operations in parallel — the NRET=2 contract actually permits this — but that's a significant refactor requiring formal validation and forwarding restructure.\n\nSplitting the EX stage into separate ALU and divider lanes won't help since the divider stalls the whole pipeline anyway. The RVFI counter arithmetic is a 64-bit adder that's not critical path but required by spec. The reset assign of zeros to the large ex_stage struct is wasteful. The real opportunity might be registering the dmem_rdata inside mem_stage before the byte-extract logic runs, so the load extraction operates on a registered value rather than the async BRAM output — but r11s1 showed that moving extraction into wb_stage regressed performance because it feeds the forwarding path.\n\nIf I latch dmem_rdata early and delay extraction by a cycle, that adds a stage and hurts load latency. A decoder-output cache indexed by PC could help straight-line loops but that's adding state, not optimizing existing logic. The divider replacement with radix-2 non-restoring is a minor win on a cold op. The more interesting angle is moving immediate generation to the IF stage and pre-computing it through if_id_t, but the instruction bits are still needed for other decoding. Looking at imm_gen more closely, it decodes the immediate based on opcode in the ID stage combinationally, which is unusual since opcode decode happens twice.\n\nMerging imm_gen into decoder.sv would let Yosys share the opcode decode LUTs, though it probably already does that automatically. A better micro-optimization might be pre-encoding the immediate type as part of ctrl_t (one of four values: I/S/B/U/J) and using a small mux in id_stage instead of a full opcode decoder, replacing a 7-bit decode with a 3-bit select. For a concrete structural play, I could pipeline the multiplier for MULH variants with DSP register retention, but that regressed before. The safest bet is something small—maybe replacing the 32-cycle restoring divider with an 18-cycle radix-2 non-restoring divider with early-exit on trailing zeros, though that's still a cold operation. I need to settle on something concrete and low-risk.\n\nLooking at the EX-stage more carefully, I notice the is_jump mux selects between pc+4 and the ALU result for the register write. What if I routed JAL/JALR through the ALU itself to compute pc+4 as the ALU output, eliminating that 32-bit mux entirely? The decoder would set alu_op=ADD with pc routed into alu_a and 4 into alu_b, removing the special-case logic at the EX/MEM boundary.\n\nBut there's a tension: JAL needs both pc+4 (the return address to write) and pc+imm (the jump target). Currently the ALU doesn't meaningfully compute anything for jumps since alu_b gets rs2 garbage, while EX separately computes the jump target with its own adder. So I'm looking at two pc-adder instances in EX—one for pc+4 in the is_jump mux and one for pc+imm—and wondering if consolidating them through the ALU is actually worth the decoder complexity, or if the current split is cleaner.\n\nI could propagate pc+4 through the pipeline registers from IF, but that widens the payload. Or I could try early-exit optimizations on the divider—detecting when divisor > dividend to skip iterations—but CoreMark has almost no divisions anyway, so that won't help. Looking at the overall design, the core is already reasonably optimized and there's probably not much structural low-hanging fruit left. Let me explore sequentializing the multiplier high bits instead.\n\nThe GW2A DSP18 has optional input/output registers that Yosys can infer, but only with the right coding pattern—typically a direct flop on the multiplier output. The issue in r10s0 was that splitting the output between two consumers broke this inference. The solution would be to register both the low-32 and high-32 multiplier outputs, making multiply 2-cycle and letting Yosys infer the DSP18's output register for both halves. But that costs IPC on MUL, which CoreMark uses heavily, and r7s1 showed even small MUL IPC losses are expensive. I could also try making the entire ALU a 2-stage pipeline so MUL gets the register essentially for free from DSP inference while LUT4 adds get explicit registers, but that's a pipeline-depth change that touches forbidden territory per r4s1. Let me consider retiming the EX-stage pc+4 generation instead.\n\nActually, moving pc+4 to ID stage would add a 32-bit field to id_ex_t, widening the payload—another regression risk. Splitting the forwarding mux across cycles adds a pipeline stage with the same problem. Moving the ALU_LUI path to pre-flop in ID doesn't help Fmax since the ALU already handles LUI. I could try early-starting the divider by tapping operands from the ID/EX transition, but the operands needed are post-forward, which happen in EX, so that won't work without wrong operands. What if I dedicate a separate EX-lane flop path for DIV/REM so the pipeline doesn't globally stall during the 32-cycle iteration?\n\n—but that requires out-of-order retirement and touches the NRET=2 contract, too complex.\n\nLet me try something more conservative: an early-exit divider with leading-zero count on dividend and divisor to reduce average latency from 32 to ~8 cycles on typical operands. But wait—r5s1 succeeded because it removed the combinational divider from the EX critical path for an Fmax win, not because divides got faster. Making divides faster probably won't help fitness.\n\nWhat about registering the multiplier inputs so Yosys can infer DSP18 input pipeline registers, keeping the output combinational? This adds 1 cycle to multiply latency but relaxes timing on the multiplier's input path.\n\nActually, DSP18 has both input and output registers. If I add a pipeline register, Yosys should infer it as part of the DSP block itself. The real question is whether I should register just the output uniformly instead—making all MUL/MULH* take 2 cycles to cut the combinational path and help Fmax. But r7s1 showed that multi-cycle MUL regressed by 7.56% due to IPC cost, and CoreMark has matrix multiplies in the hot path.\n\nLooking at other structural angles: I could change the register file reset from parallel 32-flop clear to a sequential counter-based clear over 32 cycles, removing the huge simultaneous reset net and potentially helping routing and Fmax. Though GW2A's reset network is usually a global net, so it might be \"free\" anyway.\n\nI could also try consolidating the hazard_unit and forward_unit to share rd comparators, but past lessons show that manual sharing of small LUT4 groups typically regresses. Or I could pipeline the divider's shift-subtract datapath into 2 LUT4 levels per iteration by splitting the 33-bit subtract into two halves with a carry propagation register—but I'm not even sure the divider's combinational path is actually binding Fmax. The 33-bit subtractor plus comparator is probably 8-9 LUT4 levels, comparable to the ALU's adder, so it might not be the bottleneck.\n\nLet me settle on something conservative and structural: I'll relocate the divider's shift-subtract logic to run at half rate, splitting the 33-bit subtract across two cycles with a carry-save intermediate register. This doubles the iteration count from 32 to 64 cycles but halves the per-iteration logic depth, which should help if the divider was binding. More likely though, the multiplier's 33x33 combinational path is the real bottleneck—the DSP18 is fast but the surrounding mux logic is long. So instead, I'll propose extracting the multiplier into a dedicated module instantiated from ex_stage, keeping it combinational but giving Yosys better isolation to reason about DSP primitives, though I need to be careful not to break DSP inference.\n\nActually, that's probably a zero-delta refactor structurally. Let me think about area reduction instead—the regfile is huge at 1024 flops, and the pipeline registers carry a lot of baggage. I notice the instruction word rides through multiple pipeline stages but is only really needed in ID for decoding and immediate generation; after that it's just carried along for RVFI. If I drop the intermediate copies and only keep it at the MEM/WB boundary, I could trim some register width.\n\nBut then I'd need to reconstruct the instruction somehow, or buffer it separately—both messy. The simpler approach would be to gate the intermediate instruction copies behind an ifdef for formal verification, except the FPGA benchmark always exposes the RVFI outputs, so the synthesis tool might not actually strip them even if they're unused. Let me check what CoreBench actually does with those signals.\n\nLooking at CoreBench, it probably ignores RVFI entirely, which means Yosys's optimization pass would clean up the instruction propagation automatically during FPGA synthesis anyway—so there's no real win here.\n\nLet me refocus on what could actually improve Fmax: I need shorter critical paths without widening the pipeline payload, the IF mux, or the MEM-to-EX forwarding. I'm considering splitting the ALU into parallel smaller units, but that likely increases area and doesn't help the mux overhead. Early branch detection in EX regressed before. Eliminating one forwarding mux level would break N-2 dependency forwarding. The ALU's case statement...\n\nActually, I'm going to propose extracting the multiplier into its own module—mirroring how the divider was extracted in r5s1. Keeping it combinational and 1-cycle avoids the 2-cycle regressions I saw before. It's a safe refactor that should help Yosys and nextpnr with placement without touching IPC.\n\nNow stepping back: CoreMark score is iter/cycle times Fmax. I've already squeezed most of the Fmax gains, and the JAL predictor is in place. The real bottleneck is IPC—branch prediction and load-use forwarding don't work, and dual-issue is too complex. Let me think about whether I can flatten the decode path somehow. Currently the decoder runs combinationally in ID, but if I moved it earlier to IF... except we don't have an IF/ID flop, so that doesn't actually save a cycle. What if I trim unused fields from the pipeline registers instead—rs1_val, rs2_val, branch_taken, and branch_target are only needed for RVFI observability after EX, so I could strip them out in non-formal builds to reduce register width.\n\nActually, checking the code flow: rs1_val and rs2_val propagate from ex_mem_t through mem_wb_t just to feed the RVFI outputs, but in FPGA synthesis those unused RVFI signals get eliminated anyway, so there's no real win there. I think the best move is to extract the multiplier into its own dedicated module like we did with the divider—keeps it single-cycle and focused, lets the ALU stay lean with just base RV32I operations.\n\nBut there's another angle: the JAL predictor in IF already redirects, so the EX stage's redundant pc+imm computation for JAL is wasted work. If we make the EX-stage jump_target path JALR-only and handle JAL's pc_next differently, we could simplify that logic.\n\nThe catch is RVFI needs pc_wdata reported correctly—we still need the next PC value when the JAL retires. Tracking a predicted-pc field through the pipeline would widen payloads and likely regress performance. Since the IF-predicted target becomes the new PC within a couple cycles and propagates through the pipeline, we could theoretically look ahead, but that's messy. Keeping the redundant adder in EX is probably the cleaner call—synthesis likely optimizes it anyway.\n\nSo I'm settling on the multiplier extraction as my structural hypothesis: mirroring the divider split pattern into a dedicated multiplier module should give cleaner DSP18 recognition by Yosys, with low risk and maybe a marginal Fmax boost.\n\nActually, let me reconsider one more structural angle: rewriting the mem_stage's byte-lane logic with a rotating shifter instead of the current right-shift approach. I'm reconsidering the pc_plus_4 hoisting idea — widening the pipeline payload would regress fitness per earlier lessons about the IF/EX critical path, so that's off the table. Instead, I'm settling on consolidating trap detection into a single unified module that combines decoder-illegal, branch-misalign, mem-misalign, and out-of-bounds checks at the end of EX stage, which should simplify is_illegal propagation even if it introduces a new module, though there are tradeoffs to weigh.\n\nActually, I'm going to commit to extracting the multiplier into its own module with registered outputs to make multiply uniformly 2-cycle — though I'm aware this is risky territory. But wait, I need to reconsider the shape here: I could register just the inputs via a transparent flop to let Yosys infer a DSP input register, or keep the multiplier combinational but relocate it upstream of the ALU case statement as a sideband to the output mux, but that's already what r3s0 does so moving it physically won't help.\n\nI'm going to commit to the multiplier extraction as a low-risk, low-expected-delta play. Though actually, splitting the regfile into two separate sub-regfiles — one per read port, each a 32×32 bank with replicated write ports — could really work by decoupling the two rs read muxes and eliminating one of the cross-port fanout paths.\n\nThe dual-port approach would give cleaner routing and shorter per-port combinational paths, but it doubles the flop count from 1024 to 2048, which is manageable within the Tang Nano 20K budget. The 32-to-1 read mux is about 5 LUT4 levels, and having fanout-1 per port instead of shared could simplify placement and improve Fmax. But I'm worried Yosys will see the identical data in both banks and merge them back together — I'd need some attribute or structural separation to prevent that, which makes it risky.\n\nSo I'm going with the cleaner play: extract the combinational multiplier into a dedicated module following the divider extraction pattern from r5s1, reducing the ALU to base RV32I ops with ALTOPS stand-ins for modest Fmax improvement.\n\nActually, looking at the critical paths more carefully — the EX stage is the real bottleneck with the ALU's mult and shift paths, followed by the 32-bit mux feeding the flop. The current fitness is in the 301–398 range, and the best gains came from DSP consolidation and divider sequentialization. I could try separating the slow ops (MULH*, MUL) into a 2-stage pipeline lane without making base MUL 2-cycle, but MUL is hot in CoreMark so that hurts. Or I could pre-compute the multiplier result starting in the ID stage if the decoder identifies an MUL* instruction early.\n\nBut honestly, the safest move is a clean structural refactor: extract the combinational multiplier into its own dedicated module like I did with the divider in r5s1. The ALU shrinks to focus on base RV32I ops, and the multiplier module handles MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU with a single output port, keeping the single-DSP18 pattern from r3s0 intact. It's a pure refactor — probably Fmax-neutral with potential small gains from cleaner synthesis boundaries. I considered adding a tiny explicit register at the multiplier boundary for the high 32 bits gated on is_mulh*, hoping Yosys would map it into the DSP18's output register, but r10s0 showed that split broke DSP inference anyway, so I'll stick with the pure refactor approach.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debd31a91001dSA1LJoyymjX3g","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","messageID":"msg_debd0114100131KmdrsGLKB7gV"}}
