{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777777982518,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"toolu_bdrk_014YizJr9M9uVknvteW864Wu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"structural","path":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 26 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative shift-subtract divider to shorten EX-stage critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier path (which lands on\\nDSP blocks) and the adder/shift paths, and is almost certainly what\\ncaps Fmax at 135 MHz \\u2014 well below the 150\\u2013170 MHz that a well-floor-\\nplanned 5-stage core reaches on Tang Nano 20K when divide is iterative.\\nCoreMark itself issues essentially zero divide ops in its hot loops\\n(matrix, list, state machines use MUL/shifts/compares, not DIV/REM),\\nso the IPC cost of making divide multi-cycle is negligible \\u2014 a few\\ndozen cycles per 449,148-cycle iteration at most, i.e. <0.01% IPC\\nregression against an 8\\u201315% Fmax gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Current fitness is 301.04 iter/s with Fmax=135.21 MHz on Tang Nano 20K.\\nFitness = Fmax \\u00d7 CoreMark iter/cycle, so raising Fmax lifts fitness\\none-for-one. Profiling by inspection points to a single dominant\\ncombinational critical path in the EX stage: alu.sv maps DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU\\nto SystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. GOWIN LUT4\\nfabric has no division primitives, so Yosys must synthesize a ~30-level\\nLUT cascade of restoring-division compare/subtract/mux stages for each\\nof the four divide ops, feeding a mux that selects between them and\\nthe other 15 ALU ops. This dwarfs the multiplier pa...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Split M-extension into multi-cycle unit off EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX critical\\npath and lower LUT count is strictly fitness-positive for this workload.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv computes, every cycle, three parallel 64-bit multipliers\\n(mul_ss signed*signed, mul_uu unsigned*unsigned, mul_su signed*unsigned)\\nand a combinational 32-bit divider (`/` and `%`), then muxes one into `out`\\nvia the ALU_* case. On Tang Nano 20K (GW2AR-18C) this path is almost\\ncertainly the Fmax bottleneck and a substantial share of the 9880 LUT\\nbudget (target 10000 \\u2014 only 120 LUTs of headroom). The baseline Fmax\\nseeds span 121..136 MHz, indicating P&R is pressure-sensitive \\u2014 exactly\\nthe signature of an overly wide combinational datapath in EX.\\n\\nCoreMark's hot loop is dominated by ADD / SHIFT / LOAD / STORE / BRANCH;\\nMUL/DIV/REM occur only sporadically (CRC updates, the matrix/list code\\nuses a handful per iteration). So trading a multi-cycle M-unit (with a\\nsmall IPC hit on those few instructions) for a much shorter EX c...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble JAL via IF-stage early redirect\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The 5-stage pipeline resolves all control flow in EX. Because JAL/JALR\\nset reg_write, they are always routed through EX to compute rd=PC+4 and\\nsignal redirect. For an unconditional JAL this is wasteful: the target\\nis purely a function of the in-flight instruction bits (PC + sign-extended\\nJ-imm), fully available the same cycle the word leaves imem. The current\\npenalty is 2 bubbles per JAL (IF/ID-fetch-of-PC+4 becomes NOP via flush_if\\nwhen EX redirects, and the next cycle's IF also delivers no useful work\\nuntil pc<=target takes effect). CoreMark's hot loops are riddled with\\nfunction-call JALs (core_bench_list/matrix/state all call helpers in\\ntheir per-iteration critical path, plus all crcu* calls, plus epilogue\\nJALR returns). Eliminating just the JAL bubbles (not JALR, which needs\\nrs1) is worth a conservative 3-6% IPC on CoreMark.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts failed on different axes: r1s0/r1s1 targeted\\nthe M-extension datapath and regressed (likely Fmax didn't move because\\nthe divider is DSP-muxed, not LUT-dominated, once Yosys maps it; or LUT\\ncount grew). r1s2 (BTB) broke formal by threading speculative state\\n(`predicted`, `pred_target`) through the RVFI-observed payload, which\\nblew the per-instruction BMC wall-clock budget. This hypothesi