ning three DSPs in parallel for\\nevery EX cycle costs LUT4/FF for operand replication and congests the DSP\\nrouting channel, contributing to Fmax ceiling at 141.58 MHz. The prior\\n\\\"split M-extension into multi-cycle unit\\\" attempt (r1s1) regressed because\\nmoving MUL off the EX critical path hurt IPC more than it helped Fmax \\u2014\\nevidence that the multiplier is timing-tolerable when kept single-cycle\\nbut has free area/routing headroom to give up.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace mul_ss / mul_uu / mul_su with a single 33-bit signed multiplier\\nwhose operand sign bits are muxed from op: MUL / MULH use signed*signed\\n(sign-extend both), MULHU uses unsigned*unsig...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Stateless IF-stage backward-taken branch prediction (BTFNT)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) eliminated the 2-cycle redirect\\nbubble for unconditional jumps. The next structural lever on the same\\naxis is conditional branches \\u2014 still paying a 2-cycle EX-redirect penalty\\nevery time a branch is taken. In CoreMark's hot loops (core_list_find,\\ncrcu8/crcu16 bit loops, core_bench_matrix nested loops, core_state state\\nmachines) the dominant control flow is loop-closing backward branches\\nthat are taken on every iteration except the last. A 5-iteration loop\\npays 2 bubbles \\u00d7 4 = 8 cycles of taken-branch redirect and 0 cycles on\\nthe exit-fallthrough; a 50-iteration loop pays 98 cycles of bubbles.\\n\\nStatic backwards-taken / forwards-not-taken (BTFNT) is the classic\\nprediction heuristic that captures this without any history: a BRANCH\\ninstruction whose sign-extended B-immediate is negative is almost\\ncertainly a loop edge. The r1s2 BTB lesson (broken, formal timeout)\\nwas that threading speculative state through the RVFI-observed payload\\nblows the per-insn BMC budget. The r2s2 lesson was the exact opposite\\npattern succeeds: a *stateless* predictor