ers and assemblers sometimes\\nemit these idioms for short unconditional-jump sequences when the JAL\\nrange is unnecessary, and link-editor fixups occasionally produce\\nthem. Predicting this class at IF is provably-correct-by-construction\\nfrom instruction bits alone \\u2014 no free variable coupling \\u2014 and re-uses\\nthe exact JAL predictor scaffolding that already proved formally\\ntractable.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After the r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%), the remaining control-flow\\nbubbles are (a) taken conditional branches and (b) JALR. Both\\nconventional IF-speculative approaches (r3s1 BTFNT, r3s2 BTFN) broke\\nformal identically: SBY's induction for the `reg` property could not\\nclose a loop in which IF redirects onto an address whose imem_data is\\na free symbolic variable AND the branch's resolved direction is also\\nfree. JAL escaped that trap because its prediction/resolution\\nequality is tautological (unconditional). A parallel class of\\nconditional branches has the same tautological pr...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Extract DIV/REM into iterative 32-cycle sequential divider module\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in\\nthe EX stage (32-bit restoring division fanning into the ALU\\noutput mux, which then feeds EX/MEM's alu_result register plus\\nthe forwarding path to the next cycle's EX operand muxes).\\n\\nMeanwhile CoreMark is an integer benchmark dominated by list\\ntraversal, matrix multiply, and CRC/state transitions; its\\ndynamic instruction mix contains essentially zero DIV/REM ops.\\nSo whatever Fmax and LUT budget is being spent on the\\ncombinational divider is pure waste for this fitness function.\\n\\nThe successful r3s0 hypothesis (+8.50% from folding 3 DSP18\\nmultipliers into 1) established the pattern: identify EX-stage\\narithmetic structures whose current implementation over-spends\\nFPGA resources, and consolidate/sequentialize them. The divider\\nis the most egregious remaining instance \\u2014 a single 32-bit\\ncombinational divide is worth more LUT4s than the rest of the\\nALU combined and sits on the EX critical path.\\n\\nCurrent fitness 345.80 at 153.61 MHz; Fmax target is 135 MHz\\n(we're already over) but Gowin timing closure on GW2A tightens\\nsharply above 150 MHz \\u2014 removing the combinational divider\\nshould push Fmax materially further.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current alu.sv performs DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU combinationally with\\nSystemVerilog `/` and `%` operators on 32-bit operands. Yosys maps\\nthese to `$div`/`$mod` cells that synthesize into a very wide,\\ndeep subtract-compare LUT chain on GW2A \\u2014 both a large LUT4\\nconsumer AND almost certainly the longest combinational path in...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Consolidate SLL/SRL/SRA onto a single shared right-barrel-shifter via bit-reversal\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesises three independent 32-bit barrel shifters\\nin alu.sv's case arms:\\n  ALU_SLL: a << shamt\\n  ALU_SRL: a >> shamt\\n  ALU_SRA: $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)\\nEach 32-bit variable barrel shifter is a 5-level 32-wide mux cascade\\n(~80 LUT4 on GW2A). Three of them consume ~240 LUT4 even though at\\nmost one result is selected per cycle. Yosys CSE does NOT fold these\\nbecause the shift directions differ and the `>>>` arithmetic variant\\nhas a different fill-bit discipline than `>>`.\\n\\nThe prior big micro_opt win (r3s0, +8.50%) established the dominant\\npattern on Tang Nano 20K: the EX path is area/routing-bound, not\\nlogic-depth-bound, so explicitly collapsing redundant datapath trees\\ninto shared hardware pays off even when every sub-expression was\\nalready single-cycle. Folding three MUL variants onto one 33x33\\nmultiplier freed DSP routing; folding three 32-bit barrel shifters\\nonto one right-shifter with bit-reversal should free the analogous\\nLUT4 routing channel around the ALU output mux.\\n\\nZero IPC impact (purely combinational restructuring with identical\\nbit-level semantics), formal-invariant (SLL/SRL/SRA are base I ops\\nfully proven by the per-instruction BMC), and the saving is a pure\\narea/routing gain that tends to translate into Fmax uplift on this\\ndevice.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ALU currently synthesises three independent 32-bit barrel shifters\\nin alu.sv's case arms:\\n  ALU_SLL: a << shamt\\n  ALU_SRL: a >> shamt\\n  ALU_SRA: $unsigned($signed(a) >>> shamt)\\nEach 32-bit variable barrel shifter is a 5-level 32-wide mux cascade\\n(~80 LUT4 on GW2A). Three of them consume ~240 LUT4 even though at\\nmost one result is selected per cycle. Yosys CSE does NOT fold these\\nbecause the shift directions differ and the `>>>` arithmetic variant\\nhas a different fi...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Unified bidirectional barrel shifter in ALU via bit-reversal for SLL\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The ALU currently instantiates three independent 32-bit variable shifters\\nfor SLL, SRL, and SRA (alu.sv:70-72). On GW2A fabric this is the same\\nkind of structural duplication that r3s0 eliminated for the MUL/MULH/\\nMULHU/MULHSU triplet (3 DSP18 -> 1 DSP18, +8.5% fitness) and r5s1\\neliminated by sequentializing DIV/REM. Each 32-bit barrel shifter costs\\nroughly 150-200 LUT4 plus routing, and three separate shifters feed a\\n19-way case-mux at the ALU output \\u2014 a known EX-stage area/routing hot\\nspot on the Tang Nano 20K. CoreMark's dynamic instruction mix makes\\nheavy use of SLL/SRL/SRA (array indexing, bit-pack