pc + 4)   (two distinct pc+4 adders)\\n\\nYosys CSE across separate always_comb islands with distinct\\ndownstream consumers is unreliable \\u2014 each `+` expression typically\\nlowers to its own carry chain even when the operand sources are\\nidentical. The r6s0 LUT-shifter regression confirmed Yosys DOES\\nopportunistically share mux cascades within a single case statement,\\nbut the r3s0 DSP-consolidation win confirmed that structurally\\nduplicated primitives across blocks require EXPLICIT RTL sharing to\\nbe collapsed. 32-bit adders are the latter: each replicated instance\\ncosts ~32 LUT4 of carry chain plus routing, and the longest-slack\\nsuch adder (pc+imm feeding branch_target, which in turn feeds\\nbranch_taken?branch_target mux into reg_q.pc_next) lives on the\\nEX-stage critical path alongside the forward-mux\\u2192ALU chain.\\n\\nThis fits the explicit guidance from r6s2's lesson (\\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\") and follows the successful structural\\nconsolidation pattern of r3s0 (DSP18) and r5s1 (divider extraction)\\nwithout touching IPC, pipeline depth, RVFI semantics, or pipeline\\npayload struct widths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX stage (ex_stage.sv) currently contains multiple 32-bit adders\\ncomputing identical operand patterns across structurally disjoint\\nalways_comb blocks:\\n\\n  (1) branch_target = in.pc + in.i...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Sequentialize MUL/MULH* into a 2-cycle pipelined DSP multiplier (r5s1 pattern for multiply)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"r5s1 netted +8.79% by extracting DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU into a\\n32-cycle iterative FSM \\u2014 rare-in-workload but LUT-hungry arithmetic was\\nsitting on the EX critical path and paying Fmax for every cycle. The same\\nargument applies verbatim to MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU: CoreMark's dynamic\\ninstruction mix contains very few multiplies (the core loops are list/matrix\\npointer chase + ALU ops, not MAC-dense), but the 33x33 signed multiplier\\nconsolidated in r3s0 is still a COMBINATIONAL path that feeds mul_prod[63:0]\\ninto the EX-stage alu_result mux every cycle. On GW2A the DSP18 block\\nsupports an internal pipeline register that Yosys/himbaechel will only\\ninfer if we register the product \\u2014 leaving it combinational forces a\\nsame-cycle 33x33 multiply + sign-ext mux + 2:1 alu_result mux all before\\nthe EX/MEM flop, which is almost certainly the current Fmax-limiting\\nchain after r5s1 removed the divider from it.\\n\\nCurrent core: Fmax 167.11 MHz, LUT4 5469, fitness 376.19. The EX ALU's\\nmul_prod is the tallest remaining combinational tree (r6s0 confirmed the\\nbarrel shifter is already opportunistically shared and not a fat tree).\\nOne-cycle multiply sequentialization is the lowest-risk Fmax play left.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r5s1 netted +8.79% by extracting DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU into a\\n32-cycle iterative FSM \\u2014 rare-in-workload but LUT-hungry arithmetic was\\nsitting on the EX critical path and paying Fmax for every cycle. The same\\nargument applies verbatim to MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU: CoreMark's dynamic\\ninstruction mix contains very few multiplies (the core loops are list/matrix\\npointer chase + ALU ops, not MAC-dense), but the 33x33 signed multiplier\\nconsolidated in r3s0 is still a COMBINATIONAL path that feeds mul_prod[63:0]\\ninto the EX-stage alu...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage BEQ/BNE-only early branch resolution (non-speculative, cheap comparator)\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken-branch bubble. The r6s2 post-mortem lesson is explicit: \\\"future\\nnon-speculative branch-bubble plays should narrow the ID comparator to\\nBEQ/BNE-only from the start (the two fastest and most common, skipping\\nthe signed/unsigned compare tree)\\\". CoreMark's dynamic branch mix is\\ndominated by BNE loop-exits (decrement counter, branch-if-not-zero) and\\nBEQ null-checks, so BEQ/BNE capture \\u224870-80% of conditional-branch cycles\\nat a fraction of the comparator cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor slot for this pipeline is near-saturated: r2s2 shipped a\\nstateless JAL predictor (+5.87%), r3s1/r3s2 proved BTFN-class speculative\\nbranch predictors break formal via symbolic-fetch coupling, r4s2 showed\\nidiom-specific tautological branches don't occur in CoreMark, and r5s2\\nkilled Fmax by threading 33 bits of RAS payload through the pipeline.\\nr6s2 came closest to a win (non-speculative compare-in-ID) but pushed all\\nsix BRANCH funct3 variants (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) plus a full\\nsigned/unsigned compare tree onto the ID path, netting ~0% \\u2014 the Fmax hit\\nfrom the wide comparator exactly cancelled the IPC win from halving the\\ntaken...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Eliminate load-use bubble via combinational MEM->EX load_data forwarding\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-branch IPC loss\\nis the load-use hazard: a 1-cycle bubble inserted by hazard_unit\\nwhenever an instruction in IF/ID consumes rd of a LOAD currently in\\nID/EX. CoreMark is pointer-chase-heavy (core_list_find reverse walk,\\ncore_bench_matrix row/column dereferences, core_state_transition's\\ncharacter-class table lookup, crcu16/32 inner loops) \\u2014 every dependent\\nload pays this stall. Empirically this is the single most common\\nnon-branch pipeline bubble in CoreMark's dynamic trace.\\n\\nStructural gap search: none of the prior iterations attempted this.\\nr5s1 (divider extraction, +8.79%) and r3s0 (DSP fold, +8.50%) both\\nsucceeded by removing waste from the EX datapath; the symmetric move\\non the DATA side is to make the LOAD-to-dependent path single-cycle\\ninstead of 2-cycle. r2s0's rd_wdata consolidation tried to shorten\\nthe MEM/WB forwarding path but broke the reg_ch0 formal check by\\nmis-plumbing the RVFI tap \\u2014 that failure was a wiring bug, not a\\nstructural impossibility. This hypothesis attacks a different path\\n(MEM combinational, not MEM/WB registered) and explicitly preserves\\nevery RVFI field's provenance byte-for-byte.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Control-flow IPC wins are saturated on this microarchitecture (per\\nr6s2 / r7s2 lessons: all branch-resolution moves net ~0% after\\ncomparator/payload costs; all speculative IF-predictors break formal\\nor cost Fmax). The r6s2 post-mortem explicitly redirects to \\\"pursue\\nnon-branch optimizations\\\". The largest remaining non-b...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Payload-free RAS for JALR returns via IF-pc-match redirect suppression\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The r2s2 JAL predictor (+5.87%) handles the call side of every function\\ncall/return pair. Returns (`jalr x0, ra, 0`) still pay the full 2-cycle\\nEX-redirect bubble, and CoreMark is dominated by tight call/return