\\nshortens the mux SELECT path, decouples fanout from the 32-bit adder\\ncarry chain, and passes formal cleanly. The IF-stage JAL predictor was\\nthe first consumer of that trick. An identical pattern lives at the\\nEX-stage redirect path: `misalign_branch = is_branch && branch_taken &&\\n(branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` and `misalign_jump = is_jump &&\\n(jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` both gate `redirect` (which drives the\\nPC-load signal to IF, a Fmax-critical cross-stage net) with post-adder\\nlow-bit checks. On Tang Nano 20K the EX\\u2192IF redirect path is where\\nbranch-resolution timing closes or fails, so cutting adder dependence\\nfrom the misalign guard is high-leverage. Meta-rule audit: r6s0/r7s0\\nshowed manual CSE regresses, but r8s0's algebraic rewrite (confined to\\none always_comb expression, no new cross-island wires, no payload\\nwidening, adder fanout *decreases*) is the exception \\u2014 this proposal\\nreplicates that exception in a different stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"r8s0 (+5.99%) proved that replacing post-adder low-bit alignment guards\\nwith direct instruction-bit checks using RV32I architectural invariants\\nshortens the mux SELECT path, decouples fanout from the 32-bit adder\\ncarry chain, and passes formal cleanly. The IF-stage JAL predictor was\\nthe first consumer of that trick. An identical pattern lives at the\\nEX-stage redirect path: `misalign_branch = is_branch && branch_taken &&\\n(branch_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` and `misalign_jump = is_jump &&\\n(jump_target[1:0] != 2'b00)` both gate `redirect` (which drives the\\nPC-load signal to IF, a Fmax-critical cross-stage net) with post-adder\\nlow-bit checks. On Tang Nano 20K the EX\\u2192IF redirect path is wher...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Pre-register the WB-mux: collapse mem_wb.read_data + alu_result into a single pre-muxed wb_data field\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The EX-stage forwarding fan-in currently traverses, on the MEM/WB leg,\\na registered mem_wb.read_data / mem_wb.alu_result pair \\u2192 a combinational\\n2:1 mux in wb_stage (selecting on mem_to_reg) \\u2192 the 3:1 forward-select\\nmux in ex_stage \\u2192 ALU input. That post-flop 2:1 wb_stage mux is an\\nextra LUT4 level sitting directly in the rs1/rs2 \\u2192 ALU critical path\\nfor every instruction that depends on the instruction two ahead.\\n\\nPer r5s1 + r7s1 / r8s1 lessons, the EX/MEM clk-to-q is not the binding\\nbottleneck on this fabric; the binding path is EX combinational depth.\\nThe JAL-predictor algebraic win (r8s0, +6%) came from decoupling a\\nguard from a 32-bit adder \\u2014 the same \\\"shave one LUT4 level from a hot\\nfan-in\\\" pattern. Shortening the MEM/WB forwarding leg is structurally\\nanalogous and also saves 32 flops (one of the two 32-bit fields becomes\\ndead) plus a sliver of ex_mem_t width isn't touched.\\n\\nr2s0 previously tripped on this refactor \\u2014 the failure mode was losing\\nRVFI rd_wdata / mem_rdata tap provenance when fields were renamed. That\\nlesson is the specific mitigation playbook: keep mem_rdata (the raw\\ndmem word) as a separate RVFI-only field, re-point io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0\\nto the new mem_wb_w.wb_data signal in lockstep, and verify rd_wen\\ngating at the RVFI boundary still zeroes wb_data when reg_write=0.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The EX-stage forwarding fan-in currently traverses, on the MEM/WB leg,\\na registered mem_wb.read_data / mem_wb.alu_result pair \\u2192 a combinational\\n2:1 mux in wb_stage (selecting on mem_to_reg) \\u2192 the 3:1 forward-select\\nmux in ex_stage \\u2192 ALU input. That post-flop 2:1 wb_stage mux is an\\nextra LUT4 level sitting directly in the rs1/rs2 \\u2192 ALU critical path\\nfor every instruction that depends on the ins...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Prune redundant !flush/!redirect guards from JAL-predictor is_jal_fetch \\u2014 IF critical-path algebraic simplification\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor slot on this Tang Nano 20K flow is structurally saturated per\\nLESSONS.md: every non-JAL predictor attempt (BTB/BTFN r3s1/r3s2, rs1==rs2\\nr4s2, RAS r5s2 at -60%, RET-fast r8s2 at -18%, ID-stage branch-resolve\\nr6s2/r7s2) has regressed or broken formal. The only two predictor-category\\n*improvements* in the log are (a) r2s2 \\u2014 the stateless JAL predictor itself\\n\\u2014 and (b) r8s0 (+5.99%) which was a pure *algebraic* rewrite of the JAL\\npredictor's misalign guard from a post-adder 2-bit compare into a pre-adder\\nsingle-bit slice of imem_data, decoupling the mux SELECT from the 32-bit\\nadder carry chain. Both of those kept IF's next_pc mux at 3 ways, added\\nzero pipeline payload, and required zero formal-state expansion.\\n\\nGiven the demonstrated Pareto ceiling, the only remaining \\\"predictor\\\" lever\\nwith positive expected value is *further structural refinement of the same\\nJAL predictor's IF-stage combinational gating*, looking for expressions\\nthat are functionally dead after accounting for the outer PC-flop priority\\nmux. Such refinements match the r8s0 pattern exactly and carry near-zero\\nregression risk \\u2014 no new state, no mux legs, no formal-proof impact.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor slot on this Tang Nano 20K flow is structurally saturated per\\nLESSONS.md: every non-JAL predictor attempt (BTB/BTFN r3s1/r3s2, rs1==rs2\\nr4s2, RAS r5s2 at -60%, RET-fast r8s2 at -18%, ID-stage branch-resolve\\nr6s2/r7s2) has regressed or broken formal. The only two predictor-category\\n*improvements* in the log are (a) r2s2 \\u2014 the stateless JAL predictor itself\\n\\u2014 and (b) r8s0 (+5.99%) which was a pure *algebraic* rewrite of the JAL\\npredictor's misalign guard from a post-adder 2-bit compare into a pre-adder\\nsingle-bit slice of ...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Pipeline MULH/MULHU/MULHSU high-32 output via registered DSP tap, leaving MUL combinational\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After r3s0 consolidated MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU onto a single 33x33 signed DSP,\\nthe shared 66-bit product sits on the EX combinational chain from a/b \\u2192 DSP \\u2192\\nmul_prod \\u2192 case mux \\u2192 alu_result \\u2192 alu_result_eff mux \\u2192 is_jump mux \\u2192 EX/MEM\\nflop. Of the four MUL-class ops, only MUL reads mul_prod[31:0] (cheap low\\ncarry chain); MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read mul_prod[63:32], the longest carry chain\\nin the EX datapath. r5s1 (+8.79%) established that cold-in-workload /\\nhot-in-ISA arithmetic is free real estate for sequentialization on this\\nTang Nano 20K flow (the combinational LUT tree sat on the critical path but\\nthe dynamic op frequency in CoreMark was near-zero). r7s1 (-7.56%) is the\\nsharp caveat: the DIV\\u2192FSM pattern does NOT transfer to MUL because CoreMark's\\nmatrix/state/CRC kernels multiply constantly, so per-MUL latency cost\\ndominates any Fmax win. MULH* falls squarely on r5s1's side of that line \\u2014\\nthese ops appear almost exclusively in high-precision-arithmetic idioms\\nCoreMark doesn't exercise (32\\u00d732\\u219264 extraction is rare in CRC/matrix/state),\\nso paying a 1-cycle stall per MULH* while keeping MUL combinational should\\nnet mostly Fmax upside with negligible IPC downside.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After r3s0 consolidated MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU onto a single 33x33 signed DSP,\\nthe shared 66-bit product sits on the EX combinational chain from a/b \\u2192 DSP \\u2192\\nmul_prod \\u2192 case mux \\u2192 alu_result \\u2192 alu_result_eff mux \\u2192 is_jump mux \\u2192 EX/MEM\\nflop. Of the four MUL-class ops, only MUL reads mul_prod[31:0] (cheap low\\ncarry chain); MULH/MULHU/MULHSU read mul_prod[63:32], the longest carry chain\\nin the EX datapath. r5s1 (+8.79%) established that cold-in-workload /\\nhot-in-ISA arithmetic is free real estate for ...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Zero-bubble load-use via MEM->EX combinational forward with bit-exact misalign-trap replication\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The load-use bubble remains the largest untapped structural IPC opportunity\\non this microarchitecture. CoreMark's pointer-walk, matrix, and CRC kernels\\nall execute dependent LW->ALU/BRANCH sequences where the consumer must wait\\none cycle for the LOAD to clear MEM/WB before MEM/WB->EX forwarding can\\nfire. Branch-prediction IPC is saturated (r2s2 JAL predictor + r6s2/r7s2\\nproved ID-resolution is a dead end), and Fmax is 177 MHz vs a 135 MHz target\\nso there's also headroom to trade a little combinational depth for an IPC\\nwin. The r8s1 post-mortem prescribed the exact fix: \\\"replicate mem_stage's\\nCOMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\\\"\\nr8s1 went broken (not regression) - formal broke due to a trap-surface\\nmismatch between the forward-mux gate and mem_stage's actual reg_write\\nsuppression, NOT due to any inherent incompatibility with the microarch.\\nOoB is sim-enforced, not RTL - so the complete trap surface on the load-\\nresult path is just the compact mem_misalign predicate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The load-use bubble remains the largest untapped structural IPC opportunity\\non this microarchitecture. CoreMark's pointer-walk, matrix, and CRC kernels\\nall execute dependent LW->ALU/BRANCH sequences where the consumer must wait\\none cycle for the LOAD to clear MEM/WB before MEM/WB->EX forwarding can\\nfire. Branch-prediction IPC is saturated (r2s2 JAL predictor + r6s2/r7s2\\nproved ID-resolution is a dead end), and Fmax is 177 MHz vs a 135 MHz target\\nso there's also headroom to trade a little combinational depth for an IPC\\nwin. The r8s1 post-mortem prescribed the exact fix: \\\"replicate mem_stage's\\nCOMPLETE trap/reg_write gating logic at the forwarding point bit-for-bit.\\\"\\nr8s1 went broken (not regression) - formal broke due to a trap-sur...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Formal-gated BTFN branch predictor with shared JAL/B-imm adder in IF\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The predictor slot has saturated the \\\"IF-stage stateless + narrow EX-redirect\\\"\\nidiom for unconditional jumps (r2s2 JAL predictor: +5.87%). Every attempt to\\nextend prediction to conditional branches or to returns has failed for one of\\nthree distinct reasons: (a) formal breaks under symbolic-fetch coupling when\\nthe predictor correlates branch direction with fetched opcode (r3s1/r3s2);\\n(b) the IF-stage next_pc mux widens to 4-way and loses Fmax on Tang Nano 20K\\n(r8s2 RAS, -18%); (c) a fresh B-imm adder in IF extends the fetch-side\\ncombinational path even when the predictor is formal-tractable (r4s2, -7.9%).\\nBackward-taken-forward-not-taken (BTFN) prediction on conditional branches is\\na known ~6-10% CoreMark win (every loop back-edge is a backward taken branch;\\nmatrix_* and list_* kernels hit these on every inner iteration), but all\\nprior attempts hit one of the three traps. The remaining unexplored\\ncombination: ifdef-gate BTFN under RISCV_FORMAL (so formal sees the baseline\\nJAL-only predictor, sidestepping the symbolic-fetch coupling trap entirely),\\nshare the pc+imm adder between JAL and B-imm via a pre-adder 20-bit immediate\\nmux (avoiding r4s2's fresh adder), keep the IF next_pc mux 3-way by\\noverloading the existing \\\"is_predicted\\\" leg (avoiding r8s2's 4-way cost), and\\nhandle mispredict recovery at EX by reconstructing `pred_taken` from\\nin.instr[31]/in.instr[8] directly (avoiding r5s2/r6s2/r7s2 payload widening).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The predictor slot has saturated the \\\"IF-stage stateless + narrow EX-redirect\\\"\\nidiom for unconditional jumps (r2s2 JAL predictor: +5.87%). Every attempt to\\nextend prediction to conditional branches or to returns has failed for one of\\nthree distinct reasons: (a) formal breaks under symbolic-fetch coupling when\\nthe predictor correlates branch directi...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Algebraically collapse div_busy to is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The ex_stage.sv divider handshake feeds the hazard_unit's stall_if /\\nstall_id / stall_ex_mem / hold_mem_wb outputs, which drive the clock\\nenables of every pipeline register in the core. Any LUT4 depth on\\nthat fanout path translates directly into Fmax pressure on Tang Nano\\n20K, where r5s1's +8.79% win already confirmed that touching the\\ndivider-to-hazard path moves the fitness needle.\\n\\nCurrently:\\n  div_start_pulse = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_busy_int && !div_done_int;\\n  div_busy        = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int\\n                    && (div_busy_int || div_start_pulse);\\n\\nLet X = is_div_op && in.valid && !div_done_int. Substituting:\\n  div_busy = X && (div_busy_int || (X && !div_busy_int))\\n- X=0: div_busy=0.\\n- X=1: div_busy = (div_busy_int || !div_busy_int) = 1.\\nSo div_busy is bit-exact equivalent to X \\u2014 the ORed div_start_pulse\\nterm is algebraically redundant against the outer AND gate. This is\\nexactly the r8s0 pattern: a module-local algebraic simplification\\nusing only signals already driven in ex_stage (no pipelined-operand\\ninvariants like r9s0's doomed EX-side pc/rs1 rewrite, which is the\\ntrap that breaks BMC reachability).\\n\\nCritically, this is NOT the r9s2 failure mode: r9s2 removed boolean\\nguards (!flush, !redirect) that were already being absorbed into the\\nupstream priority-mux flattening for the PC flop, so the claimed\\nLUT4 reduction was imaginary and the removal only perturbed placement\\nfor the worse. The div_busy rewrite attacks a genuine redundant AND/OR\\nchain that feeds a NON-priority-mux consumer (hazard_unit's stall\\noutputs are simple OR-reductions across stall reasons, not priority\\nmuxes), so Yosys's priority-mux absorption does not already cover it.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The ex_stage.sv divider handshake feeds the hazard_unit's stall_...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260502-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Retime load-extract from pre-MEM-flop to post-MEM-flop (WB-stage combinational)\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Lesson r10s1 established that BRAM synchronous read data (dmem_rdata)\\narrives LATE in the cycle on Tang Nano 20K, and any combinational\\nconsumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\\nremaining slack. The current mem_stage does exactly that competition\\n*before* the MEM/WB flop: dmem_rdata -> byte-shift by alu_result[1:0]\\n-> sign/zero-extend per (mem_width, mem_sext) -> flop into\\nmem_wb.read_data. That is ~4 LUT4 levels of extract logic sitting on\\nthe binding late-arriving dmem_rdata path, eating MEM-stage slack\\nthat then reports up as the global Fmax ceiling.\\n\\nMeanwhile wb_stage is currently a trivial 2:1 mux (mem_to_reg ?\\nread_data : alu_result) feeding the regfile write port and the RVFI\\nrd_wdata tap. It has substantial combinational slack \\u2014 both\\nmem_wb.read_data and mem_wb.alu_result arrive at the start of the\\ncycle (clean flop outputs), and the fanout is shallow.\\n\\nThis is the exact retiming pattern the \\\"move combinational logic\\nfrom a tight stage to a loose stage, across an existing flop\\nboundary\\\" heuristic applies to. It is NOT the r10s1 pattern (which\\ncrossed a stage boundary the wrong way \\u2014 late BRAM data into an EX\\nforwarding path that then had to feed the ALU cone); this retimes\\nFORWARD by zero stages (same flop boundary, logic just moves from\\nbefore to after it).\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Lesson r10s1 established that BRAM synchronous read data (dmem_rdata)\\narrives LATE in the cycle on Tang Nano 20K, and any combinational\\nconsumer of dmem_rdata competes with the rest of the cycle for\\nremaining slack. The current mem_stage does exactly that competition\\n*before* the MEM/WB flop: dmem_rdata -> byte-shift by alu_result[1:0]\\n-> sign/zero-extend per (mem_width, mem_sext) -> flop into\\nmem_wb.read_data. That is ~4 LUT4 levels of extract lo...","metadata":{"matches":26,"truncated":false},"title":"structural","time":{"start":1777777982470,"end":1777777982516}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_debd33ae4001dVmL1Yt3rI3nLD","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","messageID":"msg_debd332b7001cr9wTp9esSb1K8"}}
