{"type":"text","timestamp":1777778106218,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"id":"prt_debd46f3f001bsONQi87iw8g9q","messageID":"msg_debd33c74001OTJd05bW08ikly","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","type":"text","text":"Based on my analysis of prior attempts, I need a structural hypothesis that avoids the well-documented traps:\n- No IF next_pc mux widening\n- No MEM→EX/WB forwarding widening  \n- No pipeline payload widening\n- No DSP output splitting\n- No 2-cycle MUL (hot in CoreMark)\n- No manual LUT4 CSE (but hard-primitive consolidation like r3s0 works, and module extraction like r5s1 works)\n\nLooking at remaining opportunities, the ID-stage combinational cone (flagged by r4s1 as potentially binding: decoder + imm_gen + regfile-read in one cycle) hasn't been attacked structurally since r4s1's pipeline-depth play was rolled back. Both `decoder.sv` and `imm_gen.sv` independently consume the 7-bit opcode and produce orthogonal outputs. Yosys's cross-module CSE is unreliable, so each synthesizes its own opcode-decode mux. Merging them mirrors the r5s1 pattern (module extraction) inverted — consolidation rather than extraction — and targets a cone that hasn't been touched before.","time":{"start":1777778061119,"end":1777778106217}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777778106225,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01XSnXXDD4YiWcXtU6qPCdWx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r12s1\ntitle: \"Merge imm_gen into decoder: unified opcode-case drives ctrl+imm together\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The ID-stage combinational cone has not been attacked structurally since\n  r4s1 (which proposed an IFD pipeline stage and was rolled back for\n  off-limits test_pipeline.py edits). That motivation remains valid\n  though: between the imem_data flop-output and the id_ex register sits\n  (a) decoder.sv's ~20-arm opcode case producing 15 control bits,\n  (b) imm_gen.sv's 8-arm opcode case producing the 32-bit immediate,\n  (c) the 32x32 regfile distributed-LUT read with write-first bypass,\n  (d) ctrl_t + struct packing into id_ex_reg. Items (a) and (b) are\n  structurally-duplicated opcode decoders sitting in separate modules\n  with separate always_comb blocks driving disjoint output cones.\n\n  Yosys cross-module CSE is unreliable: r3s0 (+8.50%) proved hard-\n  primitive consolidation wins because Yosys cannot auto-share DSP18\n  blocks across modules; by the same mechanism, the 7-bit opcode\n  decode tree in decoder.sv and the 7-bit opcode decode tree in\n  imm_gen.sv each synthesize as independent case muxes because they\n  live in different files and produce different output widths. A\n  single opcode decode feeding both ctrl and imm through one case\n  lets synthesis collapse the duplication.\n\n  This pattern is distinct from the r6s0 / r7s0 \"manual CSE on LUT4\n  datapaths regresses\" failure mode: those attempts tried to share\n  3x 32-bit barrel shifters (r6s0) and 2x 32-bit adders (r7s0) that\n  fed into the SAME mux cascade — Yosys's priority-mux flattening\n  was already covering that sharing for free, so the manual lift\n  only perturbed placement. Here the opcode decode drives two\n  ENTIRELY INDEPENDENT output cones (ctrl_t goes to id_ex.ctrl,\n  imm goes to id_ex.imm) in two separate modules — no upstream\n  priority-mux exists to absorb the sharing, and the cross-module\n  boundary defeats Yosys's opt_share pass. This is r3s0's \"hard\n  primitive consolidation across module boundaries\" applied to the\n  ID decode cone rather than the EX DSP triple.\n\n  Current fitness 398.73 at 177 MHz Fmax (hyp-001-r8s0 baseline in\n  core.yaml). The ID path is the last untouched deep combinational\n  cone — EX has been worked extensively (r3s0 MUL fold, r5s1 DIV\n  extraction, r8s0 JAL-pred algebraic rewrite) and MEM-path moves\n  have all broken or regressed. A 5-15 LUT4 reduction on the ID\n  cone could shave 1 LUT4 level if the opcode decode is binding,\n  or at minimum reduce area/routing pressure.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Merge imm_gen.sv's functionality into decoder.sv, producing a\n  unified combinational module that emits both the ctrl_t fields\n  AND the 32-bit immediate from a single opcode case statement.\n  imm_gen.sv is deleted.\n\n  Concretely:\n   1. decoder.sv gains a new 32-bit output port `imm`.\n   2. decoder.sv's existing opcode case statement is extended — each\n      arm that currently drives ctrl bits ALSO drives the immediate\n      format selector. For example:\n        - 7'b0000011 (LOAD) arm: drives mem_read/width/sext/etc AND\n          sets imm = I-format sign-extended.\n        - 7'b0100011 (STORE) arm: drives mem_write/width AND sets\n          imm = S-format sign-extended.\n        - 7'b1100011 (BRANCH) arm: drives is_branch/branch_op AND\n          sets imm = B-format sign-extended.\n        - 7'b1101111 (JAL) arm: drives is_jump/reg_write AND sets\n          imm = J-format sign-extended.\n        - 7'b0110111, 7'b0010111 (LUI/AUIPC) arms: drive their ctrl\n          bits AND set imm = U-format (low-12 zeros).\n        - 7'b1100111 (JALR) arm: drives is_jalr AND sets imm = I-fmt.\n        - SYSTEM / FENCE arms: imm = 0 (don't care).\n        - default: imm = 0.\n      The five immediate-format expressions are the bit-exact\n      expressions currently in imm_gen.sv; moving them doesn't\n      change any RTL semantics.\n   3. imm_gen.sv is deleted. id_stage.sv drops the u_imm\n      instantiation and wires decoder.u_decoder's new `imm` output\n      directly into reg_q.imm.\n   4. No changes to decoder's is_illegal discipline: the single\n      unified case retains the default-illegal rule (invariant 2,\n      10), and each arm that clears is_illegal also drives both\n      ctrl AND imm inside the same validated arm.\n   5. No pipeline payload widening: id_ex_t.imm is already there;\n      we're just feeding it from a different combinational source.\n      Zero new fields in any struct.\n   6. No RVFI tap changes: the retirement boundary sees identical\n      values for every RVFI field (imm only feeds EX-stage alu_b /\n      jump_target / branch_target / mem_addr, all of which are\n      unchanged bit-exact).\n\n  Why this should help (ordered by expected magnitude):\n   - Yosys shares the 7-bit opcode case-select tree across both\n     output cones instead of synthesizing two parallel 7-to-20-way\n     decoders. A typical 7-bit opcode one-hot decode is ~7 LUT4;\n     two of them is ~14 LUT4, merged is ~7. On a 10000-LUT budget\n     and a Fmax of 177 MHz where routing pressure is already a\n     factor (r3s0 post-mortem established area/routing boundness),\n     7-10 LUT4 savings is structurally meaningful.\n   - The two always_comb blocks collapsing into one may also let\n     nextpnr pack the ctrl+imm fanout to id_ex_reg's CE-enable\n     inputs into adjacent SLICE cells, tightening placement.\n   - Zero IPC impact (pure structural refactor).\n   - Zero formal-proof impact (decoder's per-instruction case\n     discipline is unchanged; riscv-formal's insn_* checks see\n     identical ctrl-field provenance).\n\n  Why this is NOT the r6s0 / r7s0 failure mode:\n   - r6s0/r7s0 manually lifted sharing opportunities that Yosys's\n     priority-mux flattening was already absorbing (3x barrel shifter\n     into one ALU case, 2x adder into one pc_next priority mux). The\n     consumers were the SAME mux cascade, so the manual lift only\n     changed high-fanout nets and perturbed placement for the worse.\n   - Here the consumers are DISJOINT cones (ctrl goes to EX-stage\n     control wires, imm goes to the EX-stage alu_b mux + branch/jump\n     target adders). No existing priority-mux absorbs the sharing.\n     The cross-module boundary is exactly the structural barrier\n     that defeats Yosys's opt_share pass — which is why r3s0's\n     \"consolidate across module boundaries\" pattern applies here\n     (decode opcode is analogous to the DSP18 primitive) and\n     r6s0/r7s0's \"don't manually CSE LUT4 within a module\" rule\n     does not.\n\n  Why this is NOT the r4s1 failure mode:\n   - r4s1 was rolled back because it edited test/test_pipeline.py\n     (off-limits). This hypothesis does NOT add or remove any\n     pipeline register — the 5-stage IF->ID->EX->MEM->WB topology\n     is preserved bit-exact. id_stage's flop set is unchanged.\n     test_pipeline.py's stage probes continue to work verbatim.\n\n  Risks and mitigations:\n   - Risk: Yosys's opt_share pass across modules may already be\n     sharing more than the r3s0/r5s1 lessons suggest, in which case\n     the expected delta is near-zero. Mitigation: this is a low-cost\n     refactor; worst case is flat fitness.\n   - Risk: the merged always_comb has more outputs and more lines,\n     which could trigger different synthesis heuristics. Mitigation:\n     verify via `make formal` (all per-instruction checks pass\n     unchanged) and cocotb smoke tests before committing.\n   - Risk: if the ID cone is not actually binding (EX may still be\n     tighter after r3s0/r5s1/r8s0), the LUT4 savings translate into\n     area/power but not Fmax. Mitigation: on Tang Nano 20K the\n     post-r3s0 evidence suggests routing is a factor, so area\n     reductions on a hot ID-side cone may still help via placement\n     relaxation.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/decoder.sv\n    description: |\n      Add a 32-bit output port `imm`. In each opcode case arm that\n      currently drives ctrl bits, also assign `imm` to the\n      bit-exact expression from the corresponding imm_gen.sv arm\n      (I/S/B/U/J format per opcode). Default `imm = 32'b0` at the\n      top of always_comb alongside other defaults. Keep\n      is_illegal's default-true discipline and the per-arm clear\n      exactly as-is — the imm assignment lives INSIDE the validated\n      arm, so no illegal instruction gets a non-zero imm.\n  - file: rtl/imm_gen.sv\n    description: |\n      Delete this file — its logic moves into decoder.sv. (A\n      hypothesis MAY delete files inside rtl/ per CLAUDE.md.)\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Drop the `imm_gen u_imm (...)` instantiation. Wire the new\n      `imm` output from u_decoder directly into `reg_q.imm`. All\n      other wiring unchanged. No new fields in ctrl_decoded or\n      id_ex_t.\n  - file: test/test_decoder.py\n    description: |\n      Extend the decoder cocotb suite to assert `imm` matches the\n      expected I/S/B/U/J-format value for each opcode's canonical\n      instruction, confirming the merged logic is bit-exact with\n      the pre-merge imm_gen.sv behavior. Covers both\n      ctrl-output-unchanged and imm-output-correct in one suite.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777778106210,"end":1777778106222}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've explored quite a bit of architectural territory already—unified barrel shifters didn't pan out, the sub/compare adder approach needs investigation with logarithmic optimization, register file splitting failed, but sequentializing the divider actually worked. Now I'm thinking about what structural innovations haven't been attempted yet, particularly around the multiplier.\n\nThe core idea I'm circling: externalize the write-first bypass logic outside the register file entirely, letting the regfile itself become a simple dual-port SRAM that maps cleanly onto GW2A block RAM primitives—this could reclaim roughly a thousand LUTs currently consumed by register flops. The catch is that block RAM on this platform only supports registered reads, which means I'd need to shift the regfile access up a cycle and handle the latching of decoded operands from the prior instruction. Alternatively, I could split the regfile into two independent single-port banks with mirrored writes, which might be more amenable to the synthesis tool's BSRAM inference patterns.\n\nBoth approaches have real downsides though. The registered-read path breaks my current write-first bypass semantics and would require pre-issuing reads from the fetch stage, which complicates the pipeline significantly. The dual-bank approach depends heavily on whether Yosys can actually infer BSRAM with the right structural pattern for this particular tech library—no guarantee there.\n\nI'm now considering a different angle: moving the decoder and immediate generation into the fetch stage, shifting that combinational work earlier in the pipeline. But that's probably net-neutral at best since I'd just be trading ID's critical path for IF's, and IF is already loaded with memory access. The real win would come from moving the regfile write port earlier in the pipeline, but I haven't fully thought through where that lands yet.\n\nActually, let me step back and focus on something more tractable. I could extract the multiplier into its own dedicated combinational module as a structural cleanup—similar to how the divider was extracted in r5s1, but without introducing any IPC cost or split-output complexity. That's safer than the more aggressive pipeline restructuring.\n\nBut before I commit to that, I'm wondering if there's something to gain by trimming down the divider's state machine itself. Right now it's carrying a lot of flops that might be redundant.\n\nLooking at the divider more carefully, I notice the remainder and quotient registers follow a classic shift-register pattern that Yosys should already recognize. Merging them into a single 64-bit shifted register probably won't yield much though.\n\nSo my safest move is to extract the multiplier into its own module as a clean combinational block. That's the most straightforward structural improvement without risking unintended side effects.\n\nBut stepping back, I'm realizing the real bottleneck might be in the EX stage itself. Right now there's a three-way mux selecting between the divider result, ALU result, or pc+4 before the EX/MEM flop. I'm wondering if I can fold the pc+4 computation into the ALU somehow to eliminate that extra mux layer. The challenge is that JAL/JALR need both the jump target (pc+imm) and the return address (pc+4), and the jump target is already being computed in the IF stage. So I'd still need two separate adders unless I can reuse the IF-stage computation somehow.\n\nActually, I think the cleaner move is to extract the multiplier from the ALU into its own module, similar to how the divider was pulled out in r5s1. That gives better module boundaries and should help Yosys partition more effectively. But I'm also considering a bigger refactor: consolidating all the branch redirect logic—branch conditions, taken signals, target computation—into a dedicated branch unit module that handles the entire redirect path cleanly.\n\nBoth of these are structural plays though, and the history shows pure refactors tend to be neutral or slightly negative. I keep coming back to more aggressive ideas like pipelining the multiplier through the DSP with early operand capture at ID, but that gets complicated fast with forwarding conflicts and re-execution logic. Too risky for the potential gain.\n\nLet me think about one more angle...\n\nwhat if I replace the synchronous reset loop in the register file with a power-on initialization block? Gowin supports that, so it could eliminate the reset net entirely and help with routing. But the register file is already distributed flops, not BRAM, and the synthesis tool might not honor it anyway.\n\nI think I need to commit here. The safest move is extracting the multiplier into its own module—it mirrors what worked in r5s1 and keeps everything bit-exact while opening the door for future independent optimizations.\n\nActually, wait. Safe refactors don't improve fitness. Let me think bigger. What if I sequentialize just the MULH/MULHU/MULHSU path with a handshake like the divider uses, keeping MUL at 1-cycle? That's r10s0 though, which dropped -30%. The problem was splitting the DSP output between combinational and registered consumers broke output-register inference. Even making MUL go through the 2-cycle path (r7s1) only lost -7.56%.\n\nBoth approaches fail. The multiplier needs to stay as-is.\n\nOK, here's something genuinely new: consolidate all the trap detection logic—decoder illegal ops, branch/jump target misalignment from ex_stage, memory access misalignment from mem_stage, and out-of-bounds checks—into a single `trap_detect.sv` module positioned between EX and MEM. It's cleaner structurally, follows the functional-unit extraction pattern that worked before, and could reduce the control-with-trap signal complexity.\n\nBut honestly, this is just reshuffling logic without cutting combinational depth, so it probably won't help fitness either.\n\nWhat about pre-computing branch targets earlier? Moving the EX-stage adder to ID stage using the PC and immediate already available there wouldn't add structural depth. Or computing it at IF stage from the decoded instruction—but that widens if_id_t, which regresses per the lessons.\n\nI'm going to commit to extracting the multiplier into its own module, keeping it single-cycle and combinational like the divider extraction (r5s1). The bet is that cleaner module boundaries help nextpnr placement and potentially improve Fmax. Downside risk is flat or slight negative. I'd estimate +3% fitness delta, low confidence.\n\nActually, wait—that extraction wouldn't remove the multiplier from the EX critical path since it stays combinational there. So that won't help either.\n\nThe real bottleneck is that both fitness and IPC are saturated. Let me look at the immediate generation more carefully. The decoder and imm_gen both decode the opcode independently, and while Yosys might share logic, they're separate modules so the signal flows diverge. Merging them into a single decode module with a unified opcode case statement could let Yosys collapse the 7-bit opcode decode and eliminate the per-opcode case overhead in imm_gen. That might save 5-15 LUTs on the ID combinational cone.\n\nBut honestly, Yosys probably already does this via CSE across different always_comb blocks, so it's likely neutral. I'm going to commit to the merge anyway—it's structural, low-risk, and has a plausible mechanism even if the expected gain is small.\n\nLet me check the forwarding logic...\n\nExamining the forwarding unit...\n\nActually, moving the forward_unit into ex_stage would be a pure refactor with no fitness change. But I'll stick with my decision: merge the decoder and imm_gen into a single unified decode module. Both consume the opcode and produce independent outputs, so combining them into one always_comb block lets the synthesizer share the opcode decode mux rather than duplicating it across two blocks. The ID-stage combinational cone was flagged as probably-binding, and while this is a lighter touch than the pipeline restructure that got rolled back, it's a structural play on the same bottleneck with minimal risk.\n\nThe payoff is modest—maybe 5-15 LUT4s if the opcode decode is the critical path, possibly shaving another LUT4 level. But bundling the outputs could hurt placement, so confidence is low and I'm estimating a +2 delta. Let me implement it.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debd47718001faRhk0RrajttmS","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","messageID":"msg_debd33c74001OTJd05bW08ikly"}}
