{"type":"text","timestamp":1777778114472,"sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","part":{"id":"prt_debd52aec0016dMgi1B452Dakf","messageID":"msg_debd51fec001BG56M4Ft5acz8z","sessionID":"ses_2142fef26ffeQ7VqYPu2Kz0VjD","type":"text","text":"I've written the hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r12s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: The hypothesis proposes a structural consolidation of `imm_gen.sv` into `decoder.sv`, creating a unified opcode-case that drives both ctrl bits and the 32-bit immediate. \n\n**Key rationale**:\n- The ID combinational cone (decoder + imm_gen + regfile-read) was flagged by r4s1 as potentially binding but hasn't been attacked since (r4s1 was rolled back for off-limits edits, not bad hypothesis).\n- Both modules independently decode the 7-bit opcode — Yosys's cross-module CSE is unreliable, so each synthesizes its own opcode-decode tree.\n- This is the r3s0 \"consolidate across module boundaries\" pattern (opcode decode analogous to DSP18 primitive Yosys can't auto-share), NOT the r6s0/r7s0 failure mode (those sharing targets fed the SAME priority-mux which Yosys was already absorbing).\n- Zero pipeline payload widening, zero RVFI tap changes, zero IPC impact, zero pipeline-depth change → sidesteps r5s2/r4s1/r6s2/r7s2/r8s2 failure modes.\n\n**Expected delta**: +2% (low confidence) — conservative given refactor plays tend to be neutral, but plausible Fmax uplift if the opcode decode tree is on a binding LUT chain in ID.","time":{"start":1777778109164,"end":1777778114471}}}
