{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777779294061,"sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01UNChxKc6qoiKcKy5GM4DxX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -5; ls cores/bench/test/ 2>/dev/null","description":"Check hypotheses dir and test files"},"output":"_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_divider.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","metadata":{"output":"_helpers.py\nconftest.py\ntest_alu.py\ntest_decoder.py\ntest_divider.py\ntest_imm_gen.py\ntest_pipeline.py\ntest_reg_file.py\n","exit":0,"description":"Check hypotheses dir and test files","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypotheses dir and test files","time":{"start":1777779294056,"end":1777779294059}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" Looking at the LESSONS.md file to understand what optimizations have been successful so far—the algebraic pre-adder simplification, DSP consolidation, divider sequentialization, and JAL static predictor all showed meaningful gains ranging from 5% to 8.8%, so I need to identify what similar structural improvements might work for the cores/bench/ target.\n\nI'm noticing a clear pattern of failures: branch predictors consistently don't help, ID-stage early resolution doesn't work, MEM→EX forwarding is a dead end with five failures, and cross-module consolidation keeps hitting walls. The IF-stage next_pc mux and manual CSE on LUT paths are also saturated. Given the constraint that I must pick a structural approach, I'm exploring what hasn't been attempted yet—like an early-out mechanism for the divider to handle common small divisions faster, or extracting a dedicated shifter module, though I need to be careful not to repeat the pipeline depth issues that broke test_pipeline.py before.\n\nThe divider FSM could potentially skip leading zeros or bypass trivial cases like division by one instantly, but CoreMark barely exercises divides so the payoff is questionable. For branching, the JAL predictor works but the EX redirect still costs two cycles, and ID-stage resolution keeps failing due to fanout. I'm now considering whether I can decouple regfile reads from ID's combinational decode—moving the regfile read earlier into the IF stage by using raw instruction bits directly from imem_data, so rs1_addr comes from imem_data[19:15] and the read overlaps with decode in the next cycle.\n\nLooking at the actual id_stage.sv, the regfile is already accessed combinationally with rs1/rs2 addresses from the IF/ID payload, so that's already parallel with decode. For the divider, I could add an early-exit condition when the quotient and remainder are both zero, cutting cycles on trivial cases.\n\nI'm considering splitting EX into EX1/EX2 to separate forwarding from ALU execution, but that increases pipeline depth and would break existing tests. The decoder-splitting idea mirrors the failed r12s1 approach. The JAL misalign check is already handled in IF via the predictor guard.\n\nWhat's actually working—r2s2's targeted JAL prediction and r8s0's algebraic rewrites—suggests I should try applying that same algebraic approach to JALR target computation in EX. The current path computes `rs1 + imm` then masks the low bit; I could potentially shorten the adder carry chain...\n\nOptimizing JALR target computation... The current design has two separate adders running in parallel—one for `pc + jal_imm` and another for `pc + 4`—feeding into a multiplexer. Merging them into a single adder with the immediate selection happening on the B input could save area, but the mux select signal would need to propagate through the operand mux before the carry chain starts, potentially adding a LUT level to the critical path and offsetting any timing benefit.\n\nActually, the `pc + 4` operation is much simpler than a full 32-bit addition—it's really just incrementing bit 2 with minimal carry propagation, so it synthesizes to logarithmic depth. Merging it with the arbitrary immediate addition would force the simpler path to take the longer route, making things worse overall.\n\nI should look for a different structural improvement. The ALU's combinational M-extension operations are already optimized, and the multiplier through the DSP is hot—sequentializing it would hurt. Maybe I'm overthinking this and should focus on something more targeted like refactoring the branch comparison logic, though that's just code organization and won't change the synthesis result.\n\nThe divider's output path is a wide mux feeding through `alu_result_eff`, and registering it would push computation across the divider-to-EX flop boundary, which r11s1 showed is counterproductive. But what if I split the redirect path differently—precompute a `redirect_will_fire` flag registered in the EX/MEM stage to drive IF's next cycle, replacing the current 0-cycle combinational redirect?\n\nThat trades off IPC though, since redirect now takes 2 cycles instead of 1. Let me look at algebraic rewrites on the IF-stage adders instead. The `pc + jal_imm` adder might have slack if I exploit the invariants: pc[1:0] is always 0, and jal_imm[0] is always 0, so bits 0 and 1 are determined without a full carry chain. But the carry chain still dominates bits 2 through 31, and I'm not seeing another invariant to break that dependency.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if I can restructure the branch comparison logic itself—move the BEQ/BNE equality checks into a dedicated parallel path that feeds redirect faster, since those are just XOR-reductions and don't need the full subtractor depth of the signed comparisons. But on second thought, synthesis probably already optimizes this, and all branch types feed redirect equally anyway, so splitting them doesn't help.\n\nLet me reconsider: the ALU already computes signed and unsigned less-than for SLT/SLTU instructions. When a branch executes, the ALU is just doing a throwaway ADD operation. Could I reuse those comparison results for branch conditions instead? The issue is the ALU operates on different operands for non-branch instructions, so this doesn't actually save anything. \n\nA cleaner approach might be to compute branch targets earlier in the pipeline—push the target address calculation into the IF stage so EX only needs to decide whether to take the branch, cutting down the combinational depth on the critical path. But that's essentially what I'm already doing.\n\nLet me try a different angle entirely. The divider runs for ~34 cycles unconditionally, but most real divisions finish faster. I could optimize it to a non-restoring divider or extract multiple quotient bits per cycle, though CoreMark doesn't divide much so this probably won't help fitness. I could also add a dedicated address generation unit running in parallel with the ALU for loads and stores, but that increases area without fixing the actual Fmax bottleneck. Banking the register file or adding pre-decode in IF would either break inference or increase pipeline depth and break existing tests.\n\nLooking more carefully at the divider, I notice that early termination is possible when the quotient becomes zero or when leading zeros in the dividend could skip iterations—real savings for small values, but CoreMark rarely divides anyway. Let me focus on something concrete: the EX stage has a mux chain where the divider result feeds into another mux for jump addresses. I could optimize this mux cascade...\n\nCollapsing the mux chain in the EX/MEM register path...\n\nActually, I keep circling back to ideas that either failed before or won't help much. The pipelined multiplier approach didn't work because splitting the DSP routing breaks inference. Flattening the decoder's 10-bit case is probably what the synthesizer already does. What I should try is separating the M-extension operations into a parallel decode path instead of keeping them in the main ALU's 19-way case statement—this could reduce LUT depth on the critical path.\n\nBut the most promising angle is extracting branch evaluation into its own module. Moving branch computation out of ex_stage.sv gives the place-and-route tool independent placement opportunities for the branch logic versus the rest of the pipeline stage. The branch unit would take rs1, rs2, pc, imm, and branch_op as inputs and produce branch_cond and branch_target, forcing Yosys to see these as module boundaries rather than one monolithic stage.\n\nHowever, Yosys tends to inline trivial modules anyway, so this might just be reorganization without real structural benefit. The real constraint is that I've already tried sequentializing the multiplier (r7s1 failed), splitting MUL routing at the DSP output (r10s0 failed because dual consumers defeat the DSP's internal pipeline inference), and the baseline fitness is stuck around 398 with marginal improvements. Let me explore early-terminating the divider when the remaining quotient bits are guaranteed zero—adding a skip condition when the committed remainder is already smaller than the divisor and no more quotient bits can be set.\n\nActually, that's minor since CoreMark rarely divides. Instead, I'm considering a more structural approach: removing the redundant `divider_int` vs `divider_eff` aliasing layer in ex_stage.sv and using the signals directly, or extracting load-extract and store-pack logic into separate modules for potential placement wins. But the real opportunity might be adding a dedicated Branch Target Pre-adder in the ID stage that computes pc+imm combinationally for branches and JAL/AUIPC, then registers it into ID/EX to let the EX stage skip that adder entirely and shorten the critical path.\n\nHowever, widening the id_ex_t pipeline register with a 32-bit field has real cost, and ID stage already has less slack than EX, so that's likely net-negative. I'm exploring other unexplored structural ideas: a carry-bypass adder for pc+4 in IF, though Yosys probably already optimizes constant adds; splitting MEM into separate address-compute and load-extract cycles, but that breaks the test pipeline; or consolidating the three stall detection OR-reductions into a single hazard vector, though that likely hits the same fanout wall. Given nothing's worked recently and this slot is for diversity, I need to commit to something genuinely structural with no direct counterexample.\n\nI'm considering replacing the 32-cycle restoring divider with a radix-4 non-restoring divider that completes in 16 cycles. It halves latency and is a real structural change, but looking back at the lessons, the divider was added because arithmetic sequentialization was free real estate—yet CoreMark doesn't divide often, so halving divide latency gives almost no IPC gain, and the divider's critical path isn't binding anyway, so Fmax doesn't improve either. That's probably net-neutral, so it's a bad choice. Let me look at the memory stage instead.\n\nThe aligned_addr mux is straightforward and should synthesize cleanly. Extracting RVFI into a separate module might give nextpnr two independent placement opportunities, but RVFI isn't observable in FPGA synthesis anyway since the top-level bench ties it off, so that's not worth pursuing. I'm going to focus on something genuinely under-explored: moving the branch comparator into a dedicated module and potentially sharing logic with the ALU's SLT/SLTU operations, since both compute similar subtract-and-sign-analysis patterns.\n\nThe ALU already has SLT and SLTU that could theoretically feed branch conditions if we routed BRANCH instructions through those operations, but BEQ/BNE need equality checks and BGE/BGEU need negation, so it's not a clean fit. Most RISC cores do combine comparators, but Yosys usually handles common-subexpression elimination within the EX stage anyway, and routing through the ALU would lengthen an already-long cone. I considered inlining the divider into ex_stage to give Yosys a flat view for optimizing the negation patterns, but module merging proved fatal in the r12s1 lesson. So instead I'll extract the branch comparator and JAL/JALR target computation into a separate branch_unit module—splitting the cone gives nextpnr two independent placement opportunities, which is the real win here.\n\nThe branch_unit would handle the 6-way branch condition logic, target address computation with alignment, and misalignment detection. By isolating the deep signed/unsigned comparator tree from the main ALU and forwarding logic, nextpnr gets explicit placement freedom, though there's risk that Yosys inlines it anyway during flattening, making this a no-op. I'm skeptical this yields real gains—probably net zero—but it's the safest structural hypothesis given what failed before. Now I'm considering a more concrete angle: pre-computing the JALR target using forwarded operands in parallel and registering it earlier in the pipeline.\n\nActually, that would add a redirect bubble since EX already computes JALR combinationally. Moving it to ID would require ID-stage forwarding to handle in-flight writes to rs1, which adds fanout and costs Fmax. Let me just commit to the branch_unit extraction as the most defensible move. But wait—I'm noticing the redirect signal depends on all six comparison results, creating a wide combinational cone. What if I could short-circuit the cheaper comparisons like BEQ/BNE through a faster path while the expensive BLT/BGE operations take the longer route?\n\nThat's probably a dead-end too. Let me try something bolder instead: decouple the divider's result mux from the ALU output by running the divider result directly into the EX/MEM register, bypassing the current mux that selects between ALU and divider results. This separates the data paths structurally and might help timing.\n\nLooking back at what's actually worked — DSP consolidation and divider extraction were both structural wins. The question is what else could be consolidated. I'm scanning for redundant hardware: multiple subtractors in the execute stage, multiple adders scattered across IF/EX, sign-extend operations that are just wire permutations. None of those seem promising. But I notice both the hazard unit and forward unit are checking `rd != 5'b0 && rd == rs1/rs2` — there might be redundant comparators there worth consolidating.\n\nActually, that won't work either. The forwarding and hazard detection are looking at different pipeline stage pairs, so there's no real sharing opportunity even if I could merge the modules.\n\nLet me pivot to something concrete: the EX/MEM register is carrying `branch_taken` and `branch_target` fields that don't appear to be consumed downstream. If I can verify they're truly unused, dropping them would shrink the register by 33 flops and potentially ease routing congestion.\n\nScanning through mem_stage and the top-level hazard/forward logic, I don't see these fields being read anywhere — they're just dead state. Since `pc_next` already captures the redirect target anyway, removing them is a straightforward structural optimization.\n\nBut I should double-check whether test_pipeline.py probes these fields directly, since the orchestrator's rollback set might have explicit references to `branch_taken` or `branch_target` in the pipeline registers. If tests are checking those signals, removing them would break the test harness.\n\nLet me reconsider: maybe a different structural optimization is safer than risking test breakage on a field removal I can't fully validate.\n\nI could extract the divider's operation detection logic into the divider module itself rather than duplicating it in the execute stage — that's a clean refactor with minimal risk. But that's just code tidying, not a real performance win.\n\nActually, I think the better move is splitting the EX/MEM register into separate control and data bundles. A single 300+ bit flop can create routing congestion in the placer, and splitting it gives nextpnr two independent placement opportunities — control flops can sit near the memory stage's decode logic while data flops stay near the ALU. It's a medium-confidence play with maybe 2-5% upside, but the risk is the synthesizer might treat it as redundant or force long routing between the clusters.\n\nWait, that doesn't actually work — the flops for individual bits can already be placed independently regardless of HDL grouping. Nextpnr doesn't care about struct-level organization.\n\nLet me just commit to something concrete: extracting the branch condition evaluation logic into its own module. The 6-way comparator with signed/unsigned handling is a significant combinational cone in the execute stage, and giving it a module boundary creates another independent placement opportunity for nextpnr. Low confidence, but it's the right kind of structural change and hasn't been tried yet.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is extracting a dedicated Address Generation Unit from the execute stage. Right now the ALU handles LOAD/STORE addressing via ALU_ADD with a source mux, but a separate AGU taking the forwarded rs1 and immediate would let the main ALU shrink its case statement and give the AGU its own shorter critical path.\n\nThe risk is that Yosys might already be resource-sharing the adder through the ALU's case mux, so duplicating it could increase area without helping placement — similar to the r7s0 lessons where independent placement sometimes works and sometimes doesn't.\n\nMoving the pc+imm and pc+4 adders to the ID stage to pipeline resolved targets would help, but widening the id_ex register by 32 bits costs synthesis area and likely isn't worth it based on earlier lessons.\n\nI'm going with the branch_cmp extraction as my final answer. One more thought though: what if I sequentialize just the MULH operations by registering the DSP's high 32 bits outside the internal pipeline?\n\nActually, r10s0 already ruled that out. Let me consider other angles — maybe a bypass-capable EX/MEM register that fuses the stages combinationally when there's no hazard, but that breaks the rvfi_order contract. Or a hybrid ALU where simple ops finish in 0 cycles and complex ones in 1, though that's too invasive.\n\nWhat I'm actually trying now is registering the shifter output separately to pipeline shifts independently and stall only on shift ops. The barrel shifter's combinational path is deep, so if shifts are the binding constraint in EX, sequentializing them could unlock Fmax. Shifts are maybe 10-15% of CoreMark's dynamic instructions, so a 2-cycle shift would cost around 10% IPC — but if Fmax gains 10% or more, it's a net win.\n\nI'm going to commit to a pipelined shifter with a dedicated FSM for SLL/SRL/SRA gated by the existing stall mechanism. Let me verify the critical path math: a 32-bit barrel shifter is roughly 5 LUT4 levels, the ALU's case mux with 19 arms adds another 5 levels, so total EX is around 11 LUT4 levels. If I pipeline the shifter, the new bottleneck becomes the deepest non-shift arm — the adder is also 5-6 carry chain levels plus the case mux, so still around 11 levels. No Fmax win unless the shifter is actually deeper than I think. And DSP18 MUL is already single-cycle from r3s0, so MULH/MULHU/MULHSU taking the high 32 bits of the result...\n\nActually, the DSP output path to the high bits through the case mux is probably the real Fmax bottleneck. DSP delay on GW2A is substantial — likely 6-8 ns for a 33x33 signed multiply — so MULH* is probably binding. Consolidating to one DSP in r3s0 helped (+8.5%), but splitting the output in r10s0 broke pipeline register inference and tanked performance (-30%). If I register just the DSP output for MULH* while keeping MUL combinational, that could help Fmax, but r10s0 showed multi-consumer taps defeat inference anyway. Registering all DSP outputs makes MUL 2-cycle like r7s1, which regressed CoreMark's MUL-heavy kernels. The real question is whether CoreMark's MULH* usage is negligible enough that pipelining only MULH* — accepting the DSP inference break — nets positive if the Fmax gain outweighs the IPC loss.\n\nThat's a dead end though, since the DSP break costs Fmax directly.\n\nI'm going to commit to extracting the branch comparator into its own module — it's a clean structural change that gives Yosys a boundary to work with, low risk, and should give +1 to +3%. But actually, I think there's a better angle: moving dmem address computation out of the execute stage into a dedicated pre-register in the memory stage, so the address generation doesn't contend with the ALU result path. Wait, that doesn't actually change anything. What about widening the regfile write port to dual-issue-ready with a speculative second channel for MULH* delayed by one cycle? That's too complex and breaks RVFI ordering. So branch_cmp extraction it is — though I'm realizing there might be an even better optimization I haven't fully explored yet.\n\nActually, the real opportunity is replacing the six-way branch comparator with a dedicated adder-subtractor that shares operands with the ALU's subtractor, since both ALU_SUB and branch comparisons need subtractors internally. But if the synthesizer is already sharing these, there's no gain, and manual CSE on LUT4 paths is risky based on past runs. I'm going to stick with the safe choice: extracting branch comparison logic into a dedicated module. It's conservative, structural, and follows what worked before.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debe73b29001TbLLKlTLde6PzO","sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","messageID":"msg_debe41e8b001HRu5I1cLGIySJ7"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779294512,"sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","part":{"id":"prt_debe7372c0018jsOK8BpXseKrP","messageID":"msg_debe41e8b001HRu5I1cLGIySJ7","sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","type":"text","text":"Looking at the history, this is a tough slot — most structural plays have been tried. Let me analyze what's left:\n\n- **Failed patterns:** IF next_pc mux widening, MEM→EX forwarding, manual CSE on LUT4 adders, cross-module merging (r12s1), absorbing muxes into upstream case blocks (r12s0), splitting DSP output paths (r10s0), sequentializing hot MUL (r7s1).\n- **Winning patterns:** DSP consolidation (r3s0 +8.5%), cold-op sequentialization (r5s1 +8.8%), stateless JAL predictor (r2s2 +5.9%), algebraic IF-guard rewrite (r8s0 +6%).\n- **r12s1 inverse lesson:** \"two smaller modules give nextpnr two independent placement opportunities, one merged module gives it one harder one.\"\n\nThe EX stage currently bundles a large combinational cone: forwarding muxes, ALU (19-way case), branch 6-way comparator (with signed/unsigned subtractor), JALR target, misalign trap — all in one monolithic `ex_stage.sv`. The branch comparator has distinct structure (subtractor-based signed/unsigned compare) that doesn't overlap naturally with the ALU's case mux tree. Extracting it gives nextpnr an independent placement opportunity per r12s1's converse.\n\nLet me check the current test file structure before writing:","time":{"start":1777779291948,"end":1777779294509}}}
