{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779328083,"sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","part":{"id":"prt_debe7b2e6001VL2ICRQ1Iiqg2o","messageID":"msg_debe7ae74001evAyHlxDTWuLJK","sessionID":"ses_2141be1c8ffeUEVAm02sy4gvQG","type":"text","text":"Wrote the hypothesis YAML to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r13s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary of proposal:** Extract the 6-way branch comparator (BEQ/BNE/BLT/BGE/BLTU/BGEU) from the monolithic `ex_stage.sv` into a new `branch_cmp.sv` module. \n\n**Rationale applied from LESSONS.md:**\n- Follows r12s1's *converse* lesson: splitting orthogonal cones gives nextpnr independent placement opportunities (the signed/unsigned subtractor tree is structurally distinct from the ALU's case-mux).\n- Matches the winning direction of r3s0 (DSP consolidation) and r5s1 (divider extraction) — both won by separating a non-overlapping sub-cone from the main EX flow.\n- **Explicitly avoids** the r6s0/r7s0/r11s0/r12s0 failure modes: no structural sharing, no manual CSE, no mux absorption, no cross-module merging.\n- Keeps pipeline payload unchanged (no id_ex_t/ex_mem_t widening per r5s2/r6s2/r8s2).\n- Keeps the pc+imm adder inline (sharing pc input with pc+4) to avoid r11s0-style net-fanout regressions.\n\nLow confidence — this is a conservative structural split with limited upside, but it's the safest untried structural angle given the saturated failure landscape in the recent outcomes.","time":{"start":1777779323622,"end":1777779328081}}}
