{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777780068936,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","part":{"id":"prt_debf312430013Vhcr0SG2mQa85","messageID":"msg_debf30196001xWCYi7KkoM761Z","sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","snapshot":"3526a81fa8a9e75f52f93e7eda4f3c3a712f6c85","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777780108041,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01X2H3P8s6qigmqxoEPBTyGE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"List existing hypotheses"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"List existing hypotheses","truncated":false},"title":"List existing hypotheses","time":{"start":1777780107999,"end":1777780108039}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing the performance gains from each optimization to understand what's working. The DSP consolidation for multiplication gave us 8.5%, the DIV sequentialization behind the ALTOPS gate yielded 8.79%, the stateless JAL predictor contributed 5.87%, and there's an algebraic optimization that added about 6% — these are the key architectural improvements I need to synthesize into a coherent bench core structure.\n\nNow I'm looking at what structural refactors actually pay off: consolidating operations onto hard primitives that synthesis can't share, sequentializing cold operations behind pipeline boundaries, and eliminating arithmetic carry chains. We're at 398.73 fitness versus the 301.04 baseline, so there's real progress.\n\nI'm examining what hasn't been explored yet in the structural space. The recent attempts — extracting branch comparison modules, merging immediate generation into the decoder, retiming the branch adder, rewriting load extraction, absorbing division results — all failed or regressed, so those directions are exhausted. Looking at the sequentialization pattern from r5s1, I'm wondering what other cold operations could be pipelined, but most ALU operations are hot in CoreMark workloads. Shifts and branch compares are heavily used, and the multiply extension consolidation already saturated from previous attempts. BRAM-based regfile was tried before too, so I need to find a different structural angle.\n\nI'm considering several possibilities: adding a dedicated pipeline register just for the load path without touching the ALU path, though that increases depth; putting the multiplier behind its own pipeline stage while keeping the single DSP block, but earlier attempts showed the IPC cost outweighs gains; using BSRAM dual-port explicitly with registered reads, but that breaks write-first bypass logic; pipelining the divider to reduce FSM overhead, though the divider isn't the binding constraint for CoreMark; or splitting the EX stage into multiple cycles for better Fmax, though that's a more aggressive restructuring.\n\nI'm also wondering about retiming the PC+4 adder from IF to ID, or pre-decoding DIV instructions in ID to start them one cycle earlier in EX—but neither addresses the real bottleneck. The critical paths I'm seeing are the late BRAM output feeding through shift/extend logic into the MEM/WB register, the forwarding mux and ALU path in EX, and the PC+JAL adder in IF—and the BRAM output arc is what keeps saturating across multiple attempts.\n\nNow I'm looking at the regfile write path and wondering if I can pre-compute the mux that selects between read_data and alu_result before it crosses the MEM/WB flop boundary. The catch is r9s1 already tried collapsing that payload and it broke formal verification. A safer approach would be to keep both fields in mem_wb for RVFI compliance but add a pre-muxed field that the forwarding logic consumes directly—except that adds flop width and the mux is already absorbed into the flop input timing anyway. The real issue is that wb_stage's mux is combinational *after* the flop, so retiming it across would save maybe one LUT4 of depth, but I'm not sure that's the actual bottleneck.\n\nActually, I could add a `pre_w_data` field (32 flops) driven by the mux at the MEM flop input, which is free per the GW2A architecture, then have forwarding read directly from that without post-flop logic. I'd still need to keep alu_result and read_data for RVFI taps, so it's a 32-bit flop width trade-off for zero depth on the forwarding path. But this is getting risky with the added complexity.\n\nLet me consider a different angle—what if I pipeline the divider to radix-4 instead?  That would cut iterations from 32 down to ~16-17, but CoreMark barely uses division so it won't improve fitness. Not worth pursuing.\n\nRegistering the multiplier product once and having all four ALU arms consume it would add a cycle of latency to every multiply, which is net-negative. Fusing the divider FSM's IDLE→BUSY transition saves only one cycle. Splitting mem_stage into separate request and register modules is the same combinational split that already failed. I need to think about what \"structural\" really means here—maybe the forward_unit's two separate always_comb blocks are the real bottleneck.\n\nPrecomputing forwarding selects at ID-stage won't work because the hazard model shifts as instructions move through the pipeline. Optimizing the register file reset loop via synthesis pragmas is risky given past flop inference issues. Let me check the log for what structural attempts have already been tried.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debf3aaa0001Bi9O5g6Na4IJhx","sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","messageID":"msg_debf30196001xWCYi7KkoM761Z"}}
