{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777780299625,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01C7sFKn1x7eFGTb42AC74US","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/fpga/CoreBench.sv","offset":1,"limit":50},"error":"File not found: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/fpga/CoreBench.sv","time":{"start":1777780299607,"end":1777780299623}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I've tried various structural approaches—pipeline reorganization, forwarding tweaks, ALU consolidation—but most haven't panned out except for division sequentialization. Now I'm exploring what structural changes haven't been attempted yet, particularly looking at how the binding paths work through the execute stage.\n\nThe EX critical path runs through the forwarding mux into the ALU operand muxes, through the 19-way ALU case statement, and into the EX/MEM flop. I'm noticing the ALU output actually feeds through two sequential muxes before being registered—one selecting between the division result and normal ALU output, then another choosing between jump PC+4 and that result. The division mux couldn't be folded into the ALU itself based on earlier attempts, so I'm wondering if I could instead register the jump PC+4 value earlier in the ID stage to break up that second mux chain.\n\nThe idea is to compute PC+4 in the IF stage (which already happens as a candidate for the next PC), then propagate it through the ID/EX flop as a dedicated field rather than recomputing it in EX. That way the EX stage only needs to select between this pre-computed link address and the ALU result, removing one 32-bit adder from the critical path before the EX/MEM flop. The risk is this resembles a previous retiming attempt that broke formal verification, but that failure was because the retimed value got used in the trap/redirect cone—here the link address would only feed the jump return path, so the redirect logic should stay clean. The retiring instruction writes rd_wdata traced back through the pipeline stages to id_ex.pc + 4, which is exactly what the register check expects, so the solver can close induction without needing a combinational pc+4 path. Retiming just the link address avoids the redirect path problem, but adding a 32-bit field to id_ex_t carries a real cost in terms of flop count and LUT utilization. The pc+4 adder already fires every cycle in IF as part of the next_pc computation, so tapping that wire and latching it through id_ex gains nothing in terms of hardware efficiency. I'm tracing through the formal verification to check if the invariant holds: at each pipeline stage, the link address should equal the PC plus 4. At reset everything's zero, so after one fetch cycle the ID stage has PC=0 and link_addr=4, which checks out. But I need to verify this holds consistently through the pipeline without the solver getting stuck on the reset state mismatch.\n\nThe register check fires only when the instruction is valid, so invalid entries after reset don't cause spurious failures. I think the formal approach should work, but the payload widening adds significant overhead per instruction, so I'm reconsidering the approach.\n\nI'm exploring structural optimizations instead: sequentializing the shifter won't help since that was already attempted, and pushing the EX/MEM register later doesn't gain anything since memory address generation is already combinational from the ALU result. Converting the regfile to dual-port synchronous reads targeting block RAM would free up LUTs, but adding read latency is too invasive and previous attempts with LUT RAM failed anyway. Reducing the divider from 34 to 18 cycles via radix-4 is structurally sound but won't meaningfully improve CoreMark since division is rare. Now I'm looking back at the writeback stage—the forwarding path from mem_wb feeds the EX operand mux combinationally, selecting either the memory read data or ALU result depending on the mem_to_reg control signal.\n\nI'm considering pre-muxing this selection at the MEM stage flop input so the result is already latched, eliminating the LUT depth after the flop on the ALU input path. The challenge is that both the ALU result and read data are still needed for RVFI outputs, but they're separate fields from the write data. Looking at the core, the RVFI write data comes from wb_w_data, which is also used for the forwarding path, so I need to check whether pre-muxing would require duplicating this logic or if I can add a latent field while keeping the original signals for RVFI. b + regfile write.\n\nIf we add a NEW mem_wb field `pre_w_data` that's computed at MEM/WB flop input and replaces wb_w_data everywhere, we still need the 2:1 mux — just move it across the flop. The r12s0 lesson said flop-adjacent 2:1 mux is \"free\" because GW2A slice has it. So moving a 2:1 across the flop might not help.\n\nActually r12s0 said: the post-flop 2:1 feeding EX/MEM flop input was packed for free. Here we're talking about the wb_stage 2:1 which is NOT flop-adjacent — wb_stage is pure combinational with no flop. Its output feeds the regfile write port (synchronous, captured next cycle) AND the fwd_mem_wb path (combinational into EX).\n\nIf we pre-mux at MEM flop input, fwd_mem_wb has 0 LUT4 depth instead of 1. The MEM flop input gains a 2:1 mux (free if slice has it, otherwise +1 LUT4). Net benefit: save 1 LUT4 on the fwd_mem_wb→EX forward mux→ALU→EX/MEM flop path.\n\nBut r9s1 tried this and broke formal due to RVFI tap provenance. The solution: keep alu_result and read_data fields for RVFI io_rvfi_rd_wdata_0 derivation BUT route fwd_mem_wb through the new pre_w_data field. That way RVFI stays on the old combinational wb_stage output, and only the forwarding path uses pre_w_data.\n\nThe key insight is that pre_w_data and wb_w_data compute the same value—both select between load_data and alu_result based on mem_to_reg—just at different pipeline stages, so they're bit-exact and forwarding stays consistent with the regfile write. The r9s1 failure happened because collapsing alu_result entirely removed a degree of freedom at the RVFI boundary, but here we're keeping those fields intact while just routing the forwarding path separately. I'm cycling through structural optimizations—fusing IF+ID stages, moving misalign-trap logic, adding a BTB—but each hits constraints from prior lessons or formal verification. The ALU's 19-way mux is already optimized by synthesis. Now I'm reconsidering the divider: instead of the current IDLE→BUSY→DONE sequence taking 34 cycles, I could overlap the capture phase with the first iteration, starting computation immediately on the IDLE+start signal and transitioning to BUSY with the first result already in flight.\n\nThe divider is instantiated inside ex_stage, and while moving it to top-level might improve placement, Yosys flattens module boundaries anyway, so that's a wash. The real opportunity is replacing the 32-cycle restoring divider with a CLZ-based approach that skips leading zeros by shifting the divisor up to match the dividend's MSB before iterating—cutting iterations significantly.\n\nBut CoreMark barely uses division, so this won't move the needle. Looking back at what actually worked: DSP consolidation (+8.5%), DIV sequentialization (+8.8%), and the JAL predictor (+5.9%). The regfile reset loop creates a 32-way mux on the write port that might prevent efficient inference, but r5s0 already tried dropping synchronous reset and failed. I'm circling back to explore whether there's an unexplored structural angle here.\n\nActually, I could move the `is_div_op` computation from a 4-way case in the EX stage into a single bit field set during decode—saves a couple LUTs in the combinational path by eliminating the mux, though it costs one extra bit in the control signal. It's a minor refactor but probably not impactful enough. The bigger moves like a parallel BRAM regfile with write-through caching or a skid buffer at the memory boundary either add too much complexity or introduce cycle penalties. I'm wondering if there's room for a pipelined multiplier inside the DSP itself.\n\nThe DSP has optional internal pipeline registers that Yosys-himbaechel might infer automatically, but earlier attempts to make MUL 2-cycle with external registers actually regressed—the tool couldn't infer the DSP's internal register when there were multiple external consumers of the result. So the current single-cycle combinational multiplier is probably already the best fit for this fabric. I should focus on structural changes that are actually safe and haven't been explored yet.\n\nExtracting the multiplier into a separate module would just get flattened back. Sequentializing it inside the DSP path already failed. Combining div and mul into a shared MDU would sequentialize the hot MUL path, which is bad. Using a Booth-4 multiplier doesn't help since the DSP is already being used. The divider is a single restoring divider with no other large-width subtractor to share with. But the MEM stage's variable barrel shift for load extraction is actually quite wide—it takes the 32-bit memory data, shifts by 0/8/16/24 bits based on address, then sign/zero-extends to 8 or 16 bits. That's worth examining more closely.\n\nMoving load-extract entirely to WB regressed before because it put depth on the forwarding path. Splitting it—shifting at MEM and sign-extending at WB—might not help much since the byte-shift is the heavy part. Let me look at the pipeline structs themselves. The `ex_mem_t` and `mem_wb_t` carry a lot of redundant fields that only exist for RVFI output: rs1_val, rs2_val, rs1_addr, rs2_addr, instr. These flow through just to be emitted at WB, adding flops and area without being on the critical path. I could gate the RVFI-only payload under a conditional compilation flag and build it in a shadow structure in the RVFI wrapper instead, keeping the main pipeline structs lean.\n\nThe forwarding path needs mem_wb.alu_result, mem_wb.read_data, and mem_wb.rd, so those stay. But the RVFI fields—rs1_addr, rs1_val, rs2_addr, rs2_val, instr—are only consumed by formal verification. In synthesis mode they'd be optimized away anyway since nothing uses them, so gating them saves flops and frees up LUT4s for nextpnr to improve placement of the remaining logic.\n\nThough actually, Yosys won't prune output ports even if they're unused, so I need to check how the RVFI outputs are wired in the actual synthesis target to see if they get eliminated there.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debf69616001nimTV6iT87USrq","sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","messageID":"msg_debf4e684001jdOFUjwgsZw3hx"}}
