{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777780528362,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01YDY3FoMYk4jggbBjNAvEKA","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-002-r14s1\ntitle: \"Retime JAL/JALR link-address (pc+4) from EX to ID via id_ex.link_addr field (non-redirect-path)\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The EX-stage flop-input to `reg_q.alu_result` currently pays a 32-bit\n  ripple-add `(in.pc + 32'd4)` whenever `ctrl.is_jump` selects the link\n  address leg. With JAL/JALR being hot in CoreMark call/return sequences\n  (JAL itself already benefits from the r2s2 IF-stage static predictor\n  for the fetch redirect, but the link-address add is still done in EX),\n  this adder sits on the EX binding critical path alongside the ALU cone\n  — the `is_jump ? (pc + 4) : alu_result_eff` mux feeds directly into\n  the EX/MEM flop input.\n\n  The r5s1 + r3s0 positive-structural template says: move combinational\n  work off the binding cone when it can be precomputed earlier without\n  widening the redirect/trap cone that the formal solver's retirement\n  reachability depends on. The ID stage has abundant slack (regfile-read\n  + decode + imm_gen is the ID cone, which runs in parallel to the\n  fetched-instruction-latch path and is not binding on Tang Nano 20K),\n  making it a natural home for a pc+4 computation that EX only needs at\n  flop capture time.\n\n  r13s2's failure was retiming `pc + imm` (the branch/jump target) which\n  feeds the redirect cone — the solver's inductive `reg`/`pc_fwd` checks\n  lost the combinational dependency that closed retirement reachability.\n  The `pc + 4` link-address is materially different: it feeds ONLY the\n  rd_wdata leg of `reg_q.alu_result` (for JAL/JALR) and the misalign-\n  fault / default-fall-through legs of `reg_q.pc_next`. Neither is part\n  of the redirect/trap generation cone (`redirect = (branch_taken ||\n  is_jalr) && !misalign_fault`; `redirect_target = is_jump ? jump_target\n  : branch_target`) — so the BMC retirement-reachability chain stays\n  intact.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a single new 32-bit field `link_addr` to `id_ex_t` (in\n  `rtl/core_pkg.sv`) and precompute `link_addr = in.pc + 32'd4` in\n  `rtl/id_stage.sv` at the ID/EX flop input. Replace the three textual\n  occurrences of `in.pc + 32'd4` in `rtl/ex_stage.sv` (lines 212, 222,\n  225 — the `alu_result` JAL-link leg and the two `pc_next` fallback\n  legs) with `in.link_addr`.\n\n  This hoists one 32-bit ripple-adder off EX's binding `flop-input`\n  combinational cone into ID's slack cone. In synthesis, nextpnr sees\n  the jump-link / misalign-fallback mux legs sourced from a registered\n  input (`in.link_addr`) instead of requiring a 32-bit carry chain to\n  resolve within the EX clock period alongside the ALU case-tree and\n  forwarding mux. Expected Fmax uplift of 2-4 MHz (~1.5-3%) on Tang\n  Nano 20K based on the ripple-add depth saved.\n\n  Correctness (bit-exact under all conditions):\n    id_ex.link_addr (at cycle T+1) === id_ex.pc (at cycle T+1) + 4\n    because both are captured from the same if_id payload at ID's\n    posedge.  All three use-sites compute the same value as before.\n\n  Formal tractability:\n    - Under BMC, the solver traces concrete values. At reset id_ex\n      is all-zero (valid=0, no retirement). First valid fetch at pc=X:\n      id_ex.pc=X, id_ex.link_addr=X+4. Propagates bit-exact.\n    - The redirect cone in EX continues to consume combinational\n      `in.pc + in.imm` for jump_target / branch_target / misalign-\n      fault checks — UNCHANGED. This is the specific r13s2 escape\n      hatch: the retimed quantity does not feed redirect/trap\n      generation, only rd_wdata and pc_next fallback muxes.\n    - `rvfi_pc_wdata` is mem_wb.pc_next — for JAL retirements it\n      equals jump_target (still combinational from `in.pc + in.imm`\n      in EX); for misalign-fault / default-fall-through it equals\n      pc_next = in.link_addr = pc+4 bit-exact. rvfi_rd_wdata for\n      JAL/JALR retirements equals ex_mem.alu_result = in.link_addr\n      = pc+4 bit-exact. `reg_ch0` and `pc_fwd` both see the same\n      concrete values they saw before retime.\n    - Under `RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS` the divider is gated off, so\n      division-retire cases are unaffected.\n  \n  Payload cost: +32 flops in the id_ex_t register, zero-cost\n  downstream (no widening of ex_mem_t or mem_wb_t — link_addr is\n  consumed only in EX to drive the is_jump mux leg and the misalign\n  fallback). Per the r5s2/r6s2/r7s2 lesson on payload cost, 32 flops\n  is a real area line item, but the expected Fmax gain from removing\n  a 32-bit ripple-add from the EX binding cone is the dominant term.\n  \n  Distinction from r7s0 (manual CSE of pc+4 across multiple EX-stage\n  always_comb blocks regressed): r7s0 created a high-fanout wire\n  `pc_plus_4` feeding several EX-internal muxes, which nextpnr routed\n  with extra buffering. This retime moves the add entirely to ID and\n  creates a SINGLE registered consumer (id_ex.link_addr → EX's one\n  is_jump-or-misalign mux), so fanout is NOT increased — in fact it\n  DECREASES (the old combinational `pc+4` served the is_jump mux and\n  two pc_next fallback legs; the new link_addr serves the same three\n  consumers from a flop output, which nextpnr treats as a single\n  fanout from a placed register — much cleaner routing topology than\n  three combinational adder-output taps). This is the r8s0 pattern:\n  remove an arithmetic carry-chain dependency from the binding cone\n  by restating the same value through a module-local invariant\n  (here: id_ex.link_addr === id_ex.pc + 4, invariant by construction\n  since both capture from if_id.pc at the same posedge).\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `logic [31:0] link_addr;` field to `id_ex_t` struct (placed adjacent to `pc` for natural packing).\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"In the id/ex register always_ff, assign `reg_q.link_addr <= in.pc + 32'd4;` alongside the existing `reg_q.pc <= in.pc;` line. The adder here runs in parallel to regfile-read / decode / imm_gen and is not binding at ID.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace three instances of `(in.pc + 32'd4)` (in the `reg_q.alu_result` JAL/JALR link-address assignment and in the `reg_q.pc_next` misalign-fault and default-fall-through legs) with `in.link_addr`. No other change — redirect cone, branch_target / jump_target / misalign_fault all still use combinational `in.pc + in.imm` unchanged.\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml","time":{"start":1777780528352,"end":1777780528361}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm noticing that the `pc + 4` computation appears three times in the EX stage—once for the link address on JAL/JALR instructions and twice as fallback values for pc_next—all feeding into flop inputs through multiplexers. Yosys should automatically consolidate these into a single adder that feeds all three mux inputs, though pre-computing this value at the ID stage could potentially improve timing.\n\nThe key insight is that if I pass a pre-computed `link_addr = pc + 4` through the ID/EX pipeline, the EX stage can use this registered value instead of computing it again, which removes the adder from the critical path. This differs from the earlier branch_target retiming that broke formal verification—the link address doesn't feed into redirect_target logic, only into the ALU result for jump-and-link instructions and the pc_next fallback for misaligned faults or default execution flow.\n\nThe concern is whether the formal verification can still prove that `link_addr` remains equivalent to `pc + 4` when it's registered through the pipeline, especially for the pc_fwd inductive check that validates pc progression. The real optimization benefit comes from Yosys recognizing `link_addr` as a registered value rather than forcing it to compute `pc + 4` combinationally each cycle—the retiming pass might already be capturing this, but either way, I should just commit to testing the hypothesis.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debf99fc2001ZlDuTdAVTQAWUo","sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","messageID":"msg_debf8634c001jEvZZmeA97sVl4"}}
