{"type":"text","timestamp":1777780601198,"sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","part":{"id":"prt_debfb1f27001bPZ3jS082cL0rK","messageID":"msg_debfa1534001xdLyDtTo4q9jp4","sessionID":"ses_2140cfebcffeMMFyIxL1VvDCN1","type":"text","text":"I've written the structural hypothesis to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r14s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Retime the JAL/JALR link-address `(pc+4)` computation from EX to ID via a new `id_ex_t.link_addr` field.\n\n**Why this might work where r13s2's similar retime failed**:\n- r13s2 retimed `pc+imm` (branch_target), which feeds the **redirect/trap cone** — breaking the solver's retirement-reachability dependencies.\n- `pc+4` link-address feeds ONLY `reg_q.alu_result` (JAL/JALR rd_wdata) and two `reg_q.pc_next` fallback legs — **not** redirect generation. The redirect path continues to use combinational `in.pc + in.imm` unchanged.\n\n**Why it might help Fmax**:\n- Removes a 32-bit ripple adder from the EX binding flop-input cone, relocating it to ID where the cone has slack (ID only does regfile-read + decode + imm_gen).\n- Creates a single registered consumer (unlike r7s0's high-fanout `pc_plus_4` wire that regressed).\n\n**Confidence: low** — given the recent run of regressions and the saturated landscape, I've set delta to +3%. The formal-tractability argument is sound but the r13s2 retiming failure is a cautionary adjacent data point.","time":{"start":1777780596519,"end":1777780601197}}}
