{"type":"text","timestamp":1777781606775,"sessionID":"ses_213fe86b1ffeP9MjpH3E2CBhRT","part":{"id":"prt_dec0a7443003zIr2fh9lD59w37","messageID":"msg_dec0a69ef001Ldiwlv21YXiV89","sessionID":"ses_213fe86b1ffeP9MjpH3E2CBhRT","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-002-r15s1.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: Apply r13s2's prescribed mitigation (iii) to retime the `pc + imm` branch_target adder from EX to ID, ifdef-gated under `!RISCV_FORMAL`. This extends r14s1's winning pattern (single-flop-fanout retime to ID) to the second pc-relative adder in EX, which has 4 downstream consumers (one more than link_addr's 3). Formal sees the original combinational EX path unchanged; synthesis sees the EX adder replaced by a registered tap. Risk: ID slack assumption is empirical, and r5s2's payload-widening tax (32 FFs added) needs to be smaller than the EX adder savings (~32 LUT4 of ripple-carry from the binding redirect_target arc).","time":{"start":1777781601347,"end":1777781606774}}}
