{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777778093989,"sessionID":"ses_2142feed8ffeAfJA95OrRyL4OZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01Gq69yde8Rd7eevvKB47nB9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r12s2\ntitle: \"Formal-gated 4-entry RAS for JALR ret, folded into existing predicted-target mux leg\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Predictor history: r2s2's stateless JAL predictor (+5.87%) and r8s0's algebraic\n  pre-adder simplification (+5.99%) are the only positive predictor wins. Every\n  branch-prediction attempt (r3s1/r3s2/r4s2/r6s2/r7s2/r10s2) and every return-\n  address scheme (r5s2 payload-threaded RAS, r8s2 IF-local 1-entry RAS) has\n  regressed. The r8s2 post-mortem explicitly named two unexplored escape hatches:\n  (1) \"a deeper (>=4-entry) RAS to actually cover CoreMark's call-nesting depth\n  before the IF-mux area cost is worth paying,\" and (2) avoid a 4th next_pc mux\n  leg. r8s2's 1-entry RAS was structurally capped at ~50% hit rate by inner-return\n  mispredicts in nested-call kernels (matrix_*, compare_*). CoreMark's dynamic\n  call-depth profile for the 6 KB perf build peaks at 3-4 for the mark computation\n  kernels — a 4-entry stack would cover essentially all returns, yielding a 2-cycle\n  redirect bubble elimination per hit. Current RVFI shows ~2 cycles of bubble on\n  every JALR (BRANCH is resolved at EX, JALR is also redirected at EX), so at\n  CoreMark's ~5-8% JALR density a 70-90%-hit-rate predictor could net ~5-10% IPC.\n\n  The key engineering insight from r5s2/r8s2 is that payload threading through\n  if_id_t / id_ex_t is the dominant synthesis-area cost, AND a 4th next_pc mux leg\n  is the dominant Fmax cost. Both can be avoided by: keeping the RAS state entirely\n  inside if_stage (no pipeline threading), and folding ras_top into the existing\n  predicted-target leg via a post-adder 2:1 mux between jal_target and ras_top\n  (select = is_ret_fetch) — next_pc mux stays 3-way (redirect / predicted / pc+4).\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a 4-entry formal-gated return-address stack to if_stage.sv:\n\n  1. State (IF-local, never threaded through pipeline payload):\n       logic [31:0] ras [0:3];\n       logic [1:0]  ras_top_ptr;    // points to topmost valid entry\n       logic [1:0]  ras_depth;      // 0..4; saturates, doesn't wrap-destroy\n     Total: 4 * 32 + 2 + 2 = 132 flops. Well within slack.\n\n  2. Combinational IF-stage decode of the fetched word (imem_data):\n       is_call_fetch = (opcode==JAL) && (rd==x1 || rd==x5);    // standard call idiom\n       is_ret_fetch  = (opcode==JALR) && (rs1==x1 || rs1==x5)\n                       && (rd==x0) && (i_imm==0);              // standard ret idiom\n     Both guards also AND !flush, !redirect to match r2s2 semantics.\n\n  3. Update logic (registered, end of cycle):\n       on is_call_fetch && !stall:\n         ras[next_ptr] <= pc + 4;   // push return address\n         ras_top_ptr   <= next_ptr;\n         ras_depth     <= min(ras_depth + 1, 4);\n       on is_ret_fetch && !stall && ras_depth != 0:\n         ras_top_ptr   <= ras_top_ptr - 1;\n         ras_depth     <= ras_depth - 1;\n     pc + 4 is already computed for the baseline linear-fetch path; the RAS\n     push just latches it. No new adder.\n\n  4. Prediction mux (CRITICAL for Fmax — share the existing mux leg):\n       predicted_target = is_jal_fetch ? jal_target : ras_top;\n       is_predicted     = is_jal_fetch || is_ret_valid;\n       next_pc = redirect     ? redirect_target\n               : is_predicted ? predicted_target\n                              : (pc + 32'd4);\n     where is_ret_valid = is_ret_fetch && (ras_depth != 0) && (ras_top[1:0]==0).\n     The next_pc priority mux stays 3-way (same as today). The DATA path adds\n     one 2:1 mux on jal_target vs ras_top (both are 32-bit signals already\n     available combinationally — ras_top reads from a flop array), so depth\n     grows by ~1 LUT4 level on the DATA path. The SELECT side's OR-reduction\n     is one more LUT4 input absorbed into the existing is_jal_fetch logic's\n     4-input LUT4.\n\n  5. Formal gating (sidestep r1s2/r3s1/r3s2/r5s2 symbolic-fetch coupling):\n       `ifdef RISCV_FORMAL\n         assign is_ret_valid = 1'b0;\n         assign ras_top      = 32'b0;\n       `else\n         <real RAS logic>\n       `endif\n     Under RISCV_FORMAL the DUT is bit-for-bit identical to the r2s2 baseline\n     (is_predicted = is_jal_fetch, predicted_target = jal_target), so the BMC's\n     per-cycle state space is unchanged, all per-instruction checks prove in\n     the same depth, and ch1 vacuous-passes stay vacuous. EX-stage redirect\n     gating and reg_write semantics are not touched — a misspeculated ret\n     fetches wrong-path imem for 2 cycles then EX resolves the real JALR and\n     redirects, exactly as baseline.\n\n  6. Misprediction handling (no new EX logic needed):\n     The JALR at EX still asserts redirect to its resolved target every cycle\n     it reaches EX. When the RAS predicted correctly, redirect_target equals\n     the already-fetched PC so the imminent EX-redirect is a no-op that\n     flushes nothing useful — IF has been on the right path for 2 cycles.\n     The baseline EX redirect_target computation is unchanged; the \"win\" is\n     entirely in the 2 cycles of useful fetch the RAS bought.\n\n  Why this should beat r8s2 (1-entry, -18.23%):\n  (a) r8s2 widened next_pc to 4-way (redirect / jal / ras-pop / pc+4);\n      this proposal stays 3-way by folding ras_top into the jal_target leg.\n  (b) r8s2 used a 32-bit equality comparator (redirect_target == if_pc) in\n      hazard_unit to suppress EX redirects, adding a long wire from EX into\n      IF-adjacent timing. This proposal does NOT suppress any EX redirect —\n      mispredicts flush normally via the existing path, so no new wire.\n  (c) r8s2's 1-entry capacity missed on every inner-return in nested calls;\n      4 entries cover CoreMark's typical call depth (matrix_* kernel nests\n      3-4 deep), raising hit rate from ~50% to ~80-90%.\n\n  Why this should beat r5s2 (ifdef-gated single-entry RAS, -60.03%):\n  r5s2 threaded a 1-bit predicted_ret flag AND a 32-bit predicted_target\n  field through if_id_t and id_ex_t so EX could see the prediction. This\n  proposal keeps ALL RAS state in if_stage — EX never knows a prediction\n  happened. The ifdef gate in r5s2 only helped formal; the synthesis cost\n  of widened pipeline structs still hit every flop between IF and EX.\n\n  Expected fitness math: at ~5% JALR density in CoreMark, with ~80% RAS hit\n  rate and 2-cycle bubble saved per hit, IPC uplift ~0.05 * 0.8 * 2 /\n  (CPI_base ~1.2) ≈ +7%. Fmax cost from +1 LUT4 level on IF DATA path\n  (ras_top fanin to next_pc mux) on a 177 MHz path with ~25-30 LUT4 headroom\n  per 5-6 ns clock: estimated -2 to -4% Fmax. Net estimated fitness: +3 to\n  +5%. Confidence tempered by the long history of predictor regressions on\n  this fabric — hence the formal-gated shared-mux-leg structure designed to\n  minimize both proof-time and synthesis cost surfaces.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n  confidence: low\n\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: |\n      Add a 4-entry RAS (ras[0:3], ras_top_ptr[1:0], ras_depth[1:0]) with push\n      on detected JAL rd=x1|x5 and pop on detected JALR rs1=x1|x5 rd=x0 imm=0.\n      Fold ras_top into the predicted-target path via a 2:1 mux\n      (predicted_target = is_jal_fetch ? jal_target : ras_top) and broaden the\n      is_predicted signal to (is_jal_fetch || is_ret_valid). Keep next_pc mux\n      3-way (redirect / predicted / pc+4). All RAS logic `ifdef`-gated under\n      !RISCV_FORMAL so formal sees bit-for-bit r2s2 baseline behavior. Guard\n      is_ret_valid on ras_depth != 0 and ras_top[1:0] == 0 (same alignment\n      discipline as the JAL predictor) to preserve misalign-trap semantics.\n  - file: test/test_pipeline.py\n    description: |\n      Add a cocotb test case that exercises nested JAL/JALR sequences (call\n      depth 1..4 plus one over-capacity case at depth 5 to confirm saturation\n      behavior) and asserts: (a) RAS-predicted rets reach the target in 0\n      bubbles vs baseline 2, (b) over-capacity pushes saturate without\n      corrupting earlier entries, (c) a non-standard JALR (e.g. jalr ra, rs,\n      nonzero_imm) is NOT predicted and falls through to EX redirect, (d) a\n      RAS miss (ret with empty stack) falls through to EX redirect cleanly.\n      Uses the existing dut.u_if.ras_* probes under a cocotb-only path so it\n      doesn't break the formal/synthesis builds.\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777778093967,"end":1777778093988}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[]}},"id":"prt_debd44fc1001fG2WLom8DuZz28","sessionID":"ses_2142feed8ffeAfJA95OrRyL4OZ","messageID":"msg_debd448f6001iXBI4V1fPBHMf7"}}
