{"type":"text","timestamp":1777778099640,"sessionID":"ses_2142feed8ffeAfJA95OrRyL4OZ","part":{"id":"prt_debd4f542001K6obfIL2XB6aot","messageID":"msg_debd4f006001M2lN72CD1QApoy","sessionID":"ses_2142feed8ffeAfJA95OrRyL4OZ","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r12s2.yaml`.\n\n**Summary**: A formal-gated 4-entry RAS for JALR ret prediction, designed to sidestep both prior RAS-failure modes:\n- **vs r8s2's -18% (1-entry, 4-way mux)**: keeps next_pc 3-way by folding `ras_top` into the existing `jal_target` leg via a post-adder 2:1 mux; no EX-redirect-suppression comparator\n- **vs r5s2's -60% (ifdef-gated 1-entry with payload threading)**: ALL RAS state lives in `if_stage` — zero pipeline-payload widening; ifdef gate makes the DUT bit-identical to r2s2 baseline under `RISCV_FORMAL`\n- **Depth=4** targets CoreMark's actual call-nesting depth (matrix_*/compare_* kernels nest 3-4), per the r8s2 post-mortem's explicit hint\n\nConfidence marked `low` given predictor saturation evidence across 11 iterations — but this is the single unexplored cell in the matrix (deeper RAS × shared mux leg × no payload threading × formal gating).","time":{"start":1777778095426,"end":1777778099639}}}
