{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779299062,"sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","part":{"id":"prt_debe6cd3d001EwqlwOeoOFdJPY","messageID":"msg_debe6bc6c001uDWA8r8xsc7H1E","sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","type":"text","text":"Confirmed: retiming the pc+imm branch-target adder from EX to ID (keeping the comparator at EX) is distinct from r6s2/r7s2 (which moved the comparator) and r7s0 (which CSE'd within EX). Writing the hypothesis.","time":{"start":1777779264829,"end":1777779299061}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777779299077,"sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01DBkvYz6Q8cZXQkvt3gACYn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","content":"id: hyp-20260503-003-r13s2\ntitle: \"Retime branch-target adder from EX to ID (pre-compute pc+imm one stage early)\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The predictor slot has saturated for IF-side redirection: r2s2's stateless\n  JAL predictor (+5.87%) and r8s0's algebraic alignment guard (+5.99%) are\n  the only surviving wins. Every subsequent extension has hit one of three\n  distinct failure modes catalogued in LESSONS:\n    (a) IF next_pc mux widening (r5s2, r8s2, r12s2 RAS variants; r4s2)\n    (b) IF pc-adder chain lengthening (r10s2 B-imm shared adder, r12s2 DATA\n        cone stretch — r8s2 meta-rule sharpened in r12s2 to \"don't lengthen\n        predicted-target DATA cone either\")\n    (c) formal symbolic-fetch coupling (r3s1/r3s2 BTFN, r9s0 EX-side rewrite)\n\n  r6s2 (-0%) and r7s2 (-0%) moved the full branch compare + adder to ID\n  and showed the IPC uplift is EXACTLY cancelled by the Fmax hit of a\n  widened ID comparator PLUS a new load-use stall case (BEQ/BNE consuming\n  an in-flight LOAD can't forward to ID).\n\n  What has NOT been tried: retiming ONLY the 32-bit branch-target ADDER\n  (pc+imm) from EX to ID, while keeping the comparator at EX. The key\n  distinction vs r6s2/r7s2 is that this retime does NOT introduce a new\n  load-use hazard (the comparator still consumes forwarded rs1/rs2 at EX\n  where forward paths already exist), and it does NOT widen the IF\n  next_pc mux or lengthen the IF adder chain (both saturated-failure\n  paths per r8s2/r10s2/r12s2). The retime targets the OTHER Fmax-binding\n  cross-stage arc: EX→IF redirect_target.\n\n  The current EX redirect_target path is:\n    branch_target = in.pc + in.imm         // 32-bit ripple-carry add\n    redirect_target = is_jump ? jump_target : branch_target\n    -> fanout into if_stage.pc flop (across-stage combinational net)\n\n  This adder sits on a cross-stage path that competes with the existing\n  IF-local JAL-adder critical path for worst-case slack. Moving pc+imm\n  upstream across the ID/EX flop converts it from a live combinational\n  arc feeding IF's PC flop into a flop-output mux source.\n\nhypothesis: |\n  Pre-compute branch_target = if_id_w.pc + imm_gen.imm combinationally\n  inside id_stage.sv, register it into a new 32-bit id_ex_t.branch_target\n  field, and re-point ex_stage.sv's branch_target to use in.branch_target\n  directly (no new add at EX). The branch comparator, JALR sum, and all\n  redirect logic stay at EX — only the target ADDER for direct branches\n  and JAL moves.\n\n  Concretely:\n    - core_pkg.sv: add `logic [31:0] branch_target;` to id_ex_t (one\n      new 32-bit field, ~1% of id_ex_t total width).\n    - id_stage.sv: add `branch_target_comb = in.pc + imm;` in the\n      combinational block; register it into reg_q.branch_target under\n      the existing stall/flush gating.\n    - ex_stage.sv: replace local `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm;` with\n      `branch_target = in.branch_target;`. jump_target for JAL keeps\n      using in.branch_target too (since jump_target = pc+imm for JAL,\n      pre-computed value matches bit-exact). JALR's jalr_sum = rs1 +\n      in.imm stays unchanged (needs post-forward rs1, cannot retime).\n    - misalign guard rewrites accordingly: branch_target[1:0] check\n      becomes in.branch_target[1:0] (bit-exact, no algebraic change).\n    - No change to if_stage.sv, no change to hazard_unit.sv, no change\n      to RVFI field provenance (in.pc + in.imm still uniquely determines\n      the same value; regfile/memory taps untouched).\n\n  Bit-exact equivalence proof: id_ex.branch_target registered at cycle\n  N+1 captures if_id_w.pc + imm at cycle N's posedge. id_ex.pc and\n  id_ex.imm also capture their respective sources at the same posedge.\n  Therefore id_ex.branch_target === id_ex.pc + id_ex.imm at every cycle\n  after the first valid id_ex capture — identical to the current EX-\n  stage combinational computation. Formal should pass unchanged (no new\n  observable state, no symbolic-fetch coupling, no reg_write gate\n  changes — same failure mode that sank r9s1, but here no WB-side\n  layout change).\n\n  Expected Fmax effect: EX-stage's redirect_target cone shortens by one\n  32-bit ripple-carry adder (~5 LUT4 levels). ID-stage adds the same\n  adder, but ID's existing combinational cone (decoder + imm_gen + 32x32\n  regfile read with write-first bypass) is already settled well before\n  EX's combined (ALU cone + forward mux + compare + adder) path hits the\n  EX/MEM flop — r6s2's lesson explicitly notes that ID \"previously had\n  slack vs EX\" for the comparator; the same slack exists for the adder,\n  and the adder is lighter than the 6-funct3 compare tree r6s2 moved.\n  The 32-bit id_ex_t widening is the one clear area cost, but it is\n  smaller than r5s2's 33-bit RAS payload (which regressed -60%) because\n  (i) no new mux leg at IF, (ii) no new comparator at EX, (iii) no new\n  stall reason in hazard_unit, (iv) no formal state expansion. Net\n  expected: +2-4% if the EX redirect_target path is currently binding,\n  ~0% if not.\n\n  Risk audit vs LESSONS:\n    - r5s2/r8s2/r12s2 (payload widening): yes, 32-bit widening here, but\n      mitigations above. Cost estimate: ~32 flops + routing, no\n      comparator/mux.\n    - r6s2/r7s2 (ID early resolve, ~0%): distinct — those moved the\n      COMPARATOR and introduced a new load-use stall. This moves only\n      the ADDER; comparator stays at EX with existing forward paths.\n    - r7s0 (manual CSE across islands, -3%): distinct — this is a cross-\n      stage retime across an existing flop, not intra-stage CSE. The\n      pc+imm adder is CONSUMED combinationally at EX today; we move the\n      consumption site to a registered source, which is structurally\n      different from duplicating it.\n    - r12s0 (absorb flop-adjacent 2:1 into case, -3%): distinct — no\n      flop-adjacent mux is being absorbed; we're retiming pure\n      arithmetic.\n    - r9s1 (MEM/WB payload rename, broken formal): mitigated by keeping\n      EX's existing branch_target signal name and just re-sourcing it\n      from in.branch_target. All RVFI taps observe id_ex/ex_mem/mem_wb\n      fields whose semantics are unchanged.\n\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: low\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Add `logic [31:0] branch_target;` field to id_ex_t struct so the pre-computed pc+imm value can flow from ID to EX.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"Compute branch_target_comb = in.pc + imm combinationally; latch into reg_q.branch_target under the same stall/flush gating as other id_ex fields.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace local `branch_target = in.pc + in.imm;` with `branch_target = in.branch_target;`. Update jump_target for non-JALR jumps to reuse in.branch_target (bit-exact for JAL since JAL target = pc+imm). Update misalign_branch/jump guards to reference in.branch_target[1:0].\"\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/opus-4_7-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml","time":{"start":1777779299056,"end":1777779299075}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" So the key insight is that no one's actually tried moving just the adder to ID while keeping the comparator at EX — previous attempts either optimized within EX or moved both components together. This hybrid approach might be the breakthrough. Let me draft the proposal now.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_debe6cd5d001Z4nQ4WiNSqUVkm","sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","messageID":"msg_debe6bc6c001uDWA8r8xsc7H1E"}}
