{"type":"text","timestamp":1777779304959,"sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","part":{"id":"prt_debe759e50012f24z01Iha6VMy","messageID":"msg_debe75348001NbYRHaQ7YZ2ntE","sessionID":"ses_2141be16cffeuFPb2NzIY2rLf2","type":"text","text":"Hypothesis written to `cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260503-003-r13s2.yaml`.\n\n**Proposal summary:** Retime the 32-bit branch-target adder (`pc + imm`) from EX to ID while keeping the branch comparator at EX. This is distinct from all prior predictor/structural failures:\n\n- Not r6s2/r7s2 (which moved the comparator and introduced a new load-use hazard)\n- Not r8s2/r12s2 (no IF next_pc mux widening or DATA cone stretch)\n- Not r3s1/r3s2 (no symbolic-fetch coupling — pure arithmetic retime)\n- Not r7s0 (cross-stage retime across an existing flop, not intra-stage CSE)\n\nThe retime targets the EX→IF `redirect_target` cross-stage arc, shortening it by one 32-bit ripple-carry adder. Cost: 32-bit widening of `id_ex_t` (smaller than r5s2's failed 33-bit RAS payload, and without the mux/comparator/stall additions that killed r5s2). Framed as low confidence (+3%) given the saturated predictor landscape — the EX redirect path may or may not currently be binding vs the ALU cone.","time":{"start":1777779300837,"end":1777779304957}}}
