{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1777781018000,"sessionID":"ses_213fe872bffeuUOpgLZFEmJVTF","part":{"id":"prt_dec018d8d001kGpVjn4dL6vieQ","messageID":"msg_dec01791b001Ep4kALPFqAvWN8","sessionID":"ses_213fe872bffeuUOpgLZFEmJVTF","snapshot":"373c0d944d8a607266c77f8192249b3d16d774e9","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1777781144226,"sessionID":"ses_213fe872bffeuUOpgLZFEmJVTF","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_bdrk_01EES52sNMhyjNfeTuMTCTXw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check hypothesis directory exists"},"output":"(no output)","metadata":{"output":"(no output)","exit":0,"description":"Check hypothesis directory exists","truncated":false},"title":"Check hypothesis directory exists","time":{"start":1777781144213,"end":1777781144224}},"metadata":{"openrouter":{"reasoning_details":[{"type":"reasoning.text","text":" I'm reviewing what worked in previous predictor iterations — the stateless JAL approach gained about 5.87% improvement through structural correctness without adding pipeline complexity, and algebraic simplification of the guard logic added another 6%, though some earlier attempts broke the implementation.\n\nThe pattern across failed attempts is clear: anything that extends the IF-stage pc-adder chain — whether it's a new adder, input multiplexers, wider selects, or additional next_pc paths — kills the maximum frequency on this FPGA. Return-address stack predictors hit a hard structural wall unless I can retime the predicted-target computation across a new IF-stage pipeline register.\n\nGiven that r14s1 just succeeded by retiming the JAL link address from EX to ID and gained 4.22%, there might be slack in the EX path now that could let me reduce the branch bubble, or I could explore whether the same retiming strategy could unlock RAS-class prediction by moving the target computation earlier.\n\nThe real insight is that stateless IF-side predictors work fine, but the moment I try to add state or extend the critical path, Fmax collapses — so maybe the answer is a delayed RAS that computes the target at ID time and uses it on the next matching fetch, or an early flush signal to collapse the 2-cycle branch bubble down to 1 cycle without needing to predict the target at all. I'm circling back to the core constraint: JALR predictions need to happen at IF time to avoid the 2-cycle bubble, so a registered RAS top from the previous cycle could serve as the speculative target—mispredicting on the first cycle after a push is a reasonable trade-off for the timing slack. Let me step back and consider what hasn't been explored yet: a stateless approach where backward branches are detected and their targets precomputed during an extra IF pipeline stage, then used to steer the next fetch—though this would require touching the pipeline structure itself. I'm realizing the core constraint: any stateful predictor on this architecture either needs formal verification gating with minimal state, or it has to be retimed across a pipeline flop to avoid lengthening the critical path. I'm considering a few angles — an ifdef-gated registered RAS that stays invisible to formal but gives synthesis a small predictor with its own clock-to-q path, or maybe instruction-buffer lookahead for loop prediction — but each approach either adds complexity or regresses performance elsewhere. The fundamental issue is that the jal_target adder and PC mux are already saturated, so any new predictor state has to either bypass that chain entirely or accept a cycle of latency. K simpler predictor angle: **Eliminate the misalign guard in JAL prediction to save a LUT4 level**.\n\nWait, r8s0 already used `imem_data[21]==0` as the misalign guard, which is cheap. Hmm.\n\nActually, let me look at what r8s0 / r2s2 did more carefully and find a simple refinement:\n\nr8s0: \"jal_target[1] = imem_data[21]\" so the misalign guard is just `imem_data[21] == 0`.\n\nWhat if... the JAL predictor's enable signal is the Fmax limiter, not the target computation? Let me propose: **Hoist the JAL enable decode to use only the opcode bits without waiting for the full imem_data[6:0]==0x6F compare**.\n\nActually `(imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111)` is already a 7-bit compare. JAL's opcode is 0x6F. The compare is cheap.\n\nHmm.\n\nLet me try a different, less-explored predictor angle:\n\n**Eliminate the EX-redirect bubble for same-PC-redirects (RFE retries)**.\n\nNot quite applicable.\n\nOK, let me just commit to something concrete. Based on the strongest signal (r12s2's prescription), I'll propose:\n\n**Retimed single-entry RAS via a dedicated flop whose output feeds the next_pc mux on a clock-to-q path. The RAS target is updated synchronously by ID-stage detection of JAL/JALR-to-ra patterns, with formal verification gated so BMC doesn't see the RAS logic.**\n\nBut this still needs a 4-way mux... r8s2 killed.\n\nActually wait. What if the RAS shares the jal_target data leg not via a downstream mux but by waiting for the JAL slot and replacing? When ras_valid_q=1 and the fetched instruction is a JALR(ra), we redirect to ras_target_q. Otherwise we redirect as before.\n\nDetecting JALR-ra means decoding the instruction bits for opcode 0x67, register field 1, and funct3 0 — that's a combinational compare on imem_data, then a 2-way mux between ras_target_q and pc+4 becomes the JALR-ra branch leg. But this adds a new leg to next_pc, widening from 3 to 4 — the r8s2 killer.\n\nUnless I only enable it under a condition that makes it replace the jal_target leg, since JAL and JALR can't both be the same instruction. The next_pc mux becomes: redirect takes priority, then a conditional between jal_target and ras_target_q based on whether we're fetching JAL or JALR, otherwise pc+4. This inner mux collapses the extra leg.\n\nRefining the mux logic...\n\nThe jal_target data arc still goes through the adder, then a 2-way mux, then a 3-way priority mux, then the flop — exactly the Fmax-fatal pattern r12s2 identified.\n\nSo RAS can't share the jal_target mux leg at all. What if I fold RAS into the select logic instead, where a RAS hit disables JAL prediction? I'd compute a flag for \"JAL or RAS hit\" and use that to gate the target selection, but the inner mux between jal_target and ras_target_q still has the same 2-way mux problem on the data path.\n\nWhat if ras_target_q is pre-aligned with jal_target by pre-computing it to jal_target format — latching pc+4 (the return address) in a form that feeds directly into the next_pc mux's primary input rather than through the jal_target adder path? That'd require an additional flop for the RAS output that's already post-mux. This is getting too complex.\n\nLet me try something simpler that hasn't been explored: converting \"BEQ rs1, x0, target\" into a likely-untaken branch via static bias in IF. But that's just BTFN for zero-compare and adds the same Fmax-fatal pc+B-imm adder.\n\nWhat about next-line always-taken for branches with short forward offsets? Predict always-not-taken for backward branches and always-taken for forward branches with imm < 16 — but \"taken\" still requires computing pc+imm, which adds an adder. Fmax-fatal.\n\nOr just predict not-taken for all branches, which is already the default — IF fetches pc+4 speculatively, which is the current behavior. So the design already has \"predict not taken\" for conditional branches. The only branch-prediction opportunity left is for taken branches.\n\nLet me try a fresh direction: EX-early branch resolution with static taken prediction at IF for backward branches — where the \"taken\" redirect happens at EX (no IF adder), but the mispredict is avoided for backward branches because IF redirected on its own. But this is just BTFN with IF redirect, which is Fmax-fatal.\n\nAlright, stepping back and picking the least risky predictor angle: eliminate the misalign guard in JAL prediction to save a LUT4 level. But r8s0 already used imem_data[21]==0 as the misalign guard, which is cheap. Hmm.\n\nLet me look at what r8s0 and r2s2 did more carefully and find a simple refinement. r8s0 set jal_target[1] = imem_data[21], so the misalign guard is just imem_data[21] == 0. What if the JAL predictor's enable signal is the Fmax limiter, not the target computation? I could hoist the JAL enable decode to use only the opcode bits without waiting for the full imem_data[6:0]==0x6F compare. But imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111 is already a 7-bit compare. JAL's opcode is 0x6F. The compare is cheap.\n\nLet me try a different, less-explored predictor angle: eliminate the EX-redirect bubble for same-PC-redirects (RFE retries). Not quite applicable.\n\nOK, I'll just commit to something concrete. Based on the strongest signal (r12s2's prescription), I'll propose: retimed single-entry RAS via a dedicated flop whose output feeds the next_pc mux on a clock-to-q path. The RAS target is updated synchronously by ID-stage detection of JAL/JALR-to-ra patterns, with formal verification gated so BMC doesn't see the RAS logic.\n\nThe jal_target data arc still pays the adder → 2:1 mux → 3-way priority mux → flop cost, which is exactly r12s2's Fmax-fatal pattern. So the only way to get RAS working is to not share the jal_target mux leg at all.\n\nWhat if I fold RAS into the select logic, where a RAS hit disables JAL prediction? I'd compute a flag for \"JAL or RAS hit\" and use that to gate the target selection, but the inner mux between jal\n\n_target and ras_target_q still has the same 2-way mux problem on the data path.\n\nWhat if ras_target_q is pre-aligned with jal_target by pre-computing it to jal_target format — latching pc+4 (the return address) in a form that feeds directly into the next_pc mux's primary input rather than through the jal_target adder path? That'd require an additional flop for the RAS output that's already post-mux. This is getting too complex.\n\nLet me try something simpler that hasn't been explored: converting \"BEQ rs1, x0, target\" into a likely-untaken branch via static bias in IF. But that's just BTFN for zero-compare and adds the same Fmax-fatal pc+B-imm adder.\n\nWhat about next-line always-taken for branches with short forward offsets? Predict always-not-taken for backward branches and always-taken for forward branches with imm < 16 — but \"taken\" still requires computing pc+imm, which adds an adder. Fmax-fatal.\n\nOr just predict not-taken for all branches, which is already the default — IF fetches pc+4 speculatively, which is the current behavior. So the design already has \"predict not taken\" for conditional branches. The only branch-prediction opportunity left is for taken branches.\n\nLet me try a fresh direction: EX-early branch resolution with static taken prediction at IF for backward branches — where the \"taken\" redirect happens at EX (no IF adder), but the mispredict is avoided for backward branches because IF redirected on its own. But this is just BTFN with IF redirect, which is Fmax-fatal.\n\nAlright, stepping back and picking the least risky predictor angle: eliminate the misalign guard in JAL prediction to save a LUT4 level. But r8s0 already used imem_data[21]==0 as the misalign guard, which is cheap. Hmm.\n\nLet me look at what r8s0 and r2s2 did more carefully and find a simple refinement. r8s0 set jal_target[1] = imem_data[21], so the misalign guard is just imem_data[21] == 0. What if the JAL predictor's enable signal is the Fmax limiter, not the target computation? I could hoist the JAL enable decode to use only the opcode bits without waiting for the full imem_data[6:0]==0x6F compare. But imem_data[6:0] == 7'b1101111 is already a 7-bit compare. JAL's opcode is 0x6F. The compare is cheap.\n\nLet me try a different, less-explored predictor angle: eliminate the EX-redirect bubble for same-PC-redirects (RFE retries). Not quite applicable.\n\nOK, I'll just commit to something concrete. Based on the strongest signal (r12s2's prescription), I'll propose: retimed single-entry RAS via a dedicated flop whose output feeds the next_pc mux on a clock-to-q path. The RAS target is updated synchronously by ID-stage detection of JAL/JALR-to-ra patterns, with formal verification gated so BMC doesn't see the RAS logic.\n\nI'm going to propose the **retimed RAS** as the predictor, with careful formal gating to avoid r12s2's data-cone issue. I'm hitting the same register pressure wall no matter which direction I go—the jal_target mux already has too many legs, and folding in a RAS output just makes it worse. Every approach I try either requires a second flop or violates the combinational timing constraint, and I keep circling back to the same dead ends. I think I need to step back and propose something simpler that actually fits the constraints, even if it's not the most elegant solution.\n\nA next-PC lookahead cache indexed by instruction address could work in theory—store observed target addresses and reuse them on future fetches of the same instruction—but the synchronous BRAM read latency kills it, and the GW2A doesn't reliably infer combinational LUTRAM anyway. I could try a 2-bit saturating counter with a hash table for branch prediction, gated behind an ifdef for formal verification and folded into the jal_target adder's alternate data leg, but that's high-risk and I'm not confident it'll actually solve the timing problem.\n\nLooking back at the jal prediction mux structure, it's a 3-way priority that selects between redirect, jal_target, or pc+4. The real bottleneck is that any attempt to add branch prediction by folding in a second immediate (B_imm alongside J_imm) requires a mux on the adder's operand input, which stalls the carry chain before it can even start propagating—r10s2 already proved that's fatal.\n\nSo I'm circling back to a parallel B-immediate adder that runs alongside the main jal path...\n\nbut instead of widening the next_pc mux to 4 legs (which r8s2 killed), I register the B-target result and redirect one cycle late. That trades a 1-cycle bubble for backward-taken branches against the current 2-cycle bubble at execute resolution. The trick is injecting this delayed redirect into the existing priority mux without widening it—I can reuse the stall leg since it already holds the PC, and just override next_pc when the pending flag fires, similar to how external redirects work.\n\nFor formal verification, I'd gate the predictor under RISCV_FORMAL so the solver doesn't struggle with symbolic fetch paths; in synthesis it activates normally. The downside is it still doesn't handle tight loops where a backward-taken branch has no slack between fetch and redirect, but this delayed-fire approach captures the r12s2 insight about retiming the target computation across a new IF-stage flop.\n\nOn the risk side, the new 32-bit adder for B-immediate computation sits in IF but feeds a registered output, so it shouldn't land on the critical path like r10s2 did—the adder's cone is clean and separate from the jal_target path. For mispredict recovery, when EX detects a branch wasn't actually taken, it redirects to pc+4 with priority over any in-flight BTFN redirect, which is just a simple OR with EX taking precedence.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether BTFN is the right target here, though. The formal issue from r3s1/r3s2 was symbolic fetch coupling—even with a 1-cycle delay, imem_data at the predicted target is still free in the solver, which could recreate the same paradox unless ifdef-gated. RAS might be the better choice instead: it has a concrete IPC ceiling from CoreMark's function-call density, JAL already handles forward jumps but returns through JALR aren't predicted today, and critically, RAS doesn't have the symbolic-fetch-coupling problem because pushes happen on JAL to ra (already decoded cleanly) and pops read from the registered RAS state rather than from imem_data at the predicted address.\n\nThe formal concern with RAS is tracking whether RAS state matches the actual return sequence under BMC, but ifdef-gating eliminates that. I'm going to propose the delayed-fire single-entry RAS approach for JALR-x1 prediction, ifdef-gated under RISCV_FORMAL, with registered targets as r12s2 prescribed—but I realize the implementation details are getting tangled. Let me step back and just propose the delayed BTFN approach instead, which is simpler and has a clear IPC win for CoreMark loops, and I'll ifdef-gate it for formal safety.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the wrong-path recovery: if BTFN fires and redirects IF but EX later resolves the branch as not-taken, we need to recover—same 2-cycle cost as today's \"predict not taken\" recovery. Since CoreMark's back-edges are taken roughly 95% of the time in hot loops, the net IPC win should be 5-8%. The BTFN predictor decodes backward branches, computes the target combinationally, registers it with a pending flag, then on the next cycle drives IF to that target while inserting a NOP into ID for the speculatively-fetched instruction. But there's a timing issue: when we fetch a backward branch on cycle N, we need to handle the redirect on cycle N+1 without creating a fetch bubble.\n\nOn cycle N+1 when BTFN fires, we can assert flush_if to turn the wrong-path fetch (pc+4 of the branch) into a NOP, so the correct target fetch arrives at cycle N+2—just 1 cycle bubble instead of 2. I also need to make sure that if the branch itself gets squashed upstream, we don't register the pending flag. Now I'm ready to write out the YAML specification.","format":"anthropic-claude-v1","index":0,"signature":""}]}},"id":"prt_dec037a6f0011Pc65x277AO0o8","sessionID":"ses_213fe872bffeuUOpgLZFEmJVTF","messageID":"msg_dec01791b001Ep4kALPFqAvWN8"}}
